('Anatomy of the Esophagus and the Gastroesophageal Reflux Barrier', 'shackelford-9th-ed-1-anatomy-of-the-esophagus-and-the-gastroesophageal-reflux-barrier', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Anatomy of the Esophagus and the Gastroesophageal Reflux Barrier\n\nJules Lin\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 1, 1-13\n\n## Introduction\n\nThe primary purpose of the esophagus is to transport food from the mouth to the stomach, and the esophagus has no digestive or absorptive function. The esophagus is a muscular tube that starts at the inferior border of the cricoid cartilage in the neck and traverses the chest, ending as it enters the stomach in the upper abdomen. Esophageal surgeons need to be familiar with the anatomy and clinical importance of the relationship of the esophagus to surrounding structures in all three areas of the body.\n\nThe esophagus is anchored superiorly to the cricoid cartilage and inferiorly to the diaphragm. Its length from the cricoid cartilage at C6 to the gastroesophageal junction at T11 ranges from 22 to 28 cm ( Fig. 1.1 ). The length of the esophagus varies with the height of the patient. The esophageal bed lies in the posterior mediastinum along the ventral surface of the spine. This is the shortest distance for reconstruction after esophagectomy and measures approximately 30 cm. When the orthotopic route is not available due to previous surgery, the retrosternal (32 cm) or subcutaneous (34 cm) routes are alternatives. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nA diagram presents the labeled anatomy of the esophagus and displays the esophageal segments. The diagram depicts the esophagus of 39 to 48 centimeters in length. The esophagus begins at the cricoid cartilage 15 centimeters below the incisors. The esophagus portion between cricoid cartilage and incisura jugularis sterni is labeled 1. The esophagus portion between incisura jugularis sterni and T h 1 to 10 is labeled 2 and measures between 18 and 22 centimeters. The diaphragm T h 10 to 12 reaches the gastric orifice labeled 3 and measures 3 to 6 centimeters in length. The denomination of the esophageal segments based on Anatomy shows the cervical region as 1, the thoracic region as 2, and the abdominal region as 3. The esophagus is subdivided based on function and includes the upper esophageal sphincter in the proximal cervical region, the tubular esophagus functioning in the cervical and the abdominal region, and the lower esophageal sphincters functioning in the abdominal region. On the Surgery basis, the cervical and thoracic proximal regions lie in the cervical and thoracic region, while the thoracic distal and abdominal region lie in the lower esophagus. The diagram and labels help differentiate the various segments of the esophagus.\n\nFig. 1.1\n\nOn endoscopy, the upper esophageal sphincter is approximately 15 cm from the incisors, the carina is at 25 cm, and the lower esophageal sphincter (LES) is at 38\u201340 cm in men and 36\u201338 cm in women. When planning the surgical approach to the esophagus, it is useful to consider the location of the tumor relative to the carina at 25 cm in deciding whether to perform a left or a right thoracotomy in order to avoid the aortic arch, which blocks access to the upper thoracic esophagus on the left.\n\nWhile the cervical esophagus is flattened by surrounding structures, the thoracic esophagus is more round due to negative intrathoracic pressure. Once the esophagus enters the abdomen, it becomes more flattened again as a result of positive intraabdominal pressure. The overall diameter of the esophagus is approximately 2.5 cm. There are three anatomic narrowings of the esophagus ( Fig. 1.2 ). The narrowest part of the gastrointestinal tract is at the cricopharyngeal constriction at the upper esophageal sphincter where the esophagus is 1.5 cm in diameter. In the superior mediastinum, the aortic arch, left atrium, and left mainstem bronchus compress the left anterolateral aspect of the esophagus around 22 cm from the incisors. The third area of narrowing is at the LES. Recognizing these natural areas of narrowing can be clinically important as swallowed foreign bodies often lodge in these areas.\n\nA radiological scan shows the shape, structure, and strictures in the esophagus prominent due to the presence of Barium. The radiological scan shows the cross-sectional view of the esophagus with cricopharyngeal muscle in the upper region, the aortic impression in the middle region, and the lower esophageal sphincter in the lower region of the esophagus. An arrowhead, arrow, and asterisk indicate the respective positions.\n\nFig. 1.2\n\nThe esophageal wall is composed of four layers including an inner squamous mucosal layer, submucosa, muscularis propria, and adventitia. The mucosal layer consists of the squamous epithelium, lamina propria, and muscularis mucosa, whereas the muscularis propria consists of an inner circular and outer longitudinal layer of muscle ( Fig. 1.3 ). The longitudinal layer originates from the cricoid cartilage as two muscle bundles that converge 3 cm distal to the cricopharyngeus muscle, leaving a V-shaped weakened area posteriorly covered only with circular muscle fibers, known as Laimer\u2019s triangle ( Fig. 1.4 ). The cricopharyngeal muscle and up to 2 cm of the cervical esophagus are composed mostly of striated muscle. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> There is a gradual transition from striated muscle, which is only present in the upper 40% of the esophagus, to smooth muscle ( Fig. 1.5 ). As a result, most dysmotility disorders, which involve smooth muscle, predominantly affect the distal two-thirds of the esophagus.\n\nA diagram presents a micro histological cross section of the esophagus labeled with different muscle layers. The diagram shows a circular structure with layers, which include the outer layer labeled epithelium with cellular details. The submucosa layer beneath is less distinct, while the next layer is muscularis mucosae. The circular muscle has a broader band and is found around the central lumen. The longitudinal muscle lies on the perimeter that spreads over the circular muscular layers.\n\nFig. 1.3\n\nA diagram of the anatomy of the pharyngoesophageal junction from a posterior view. The diagram shows the inferior constrictor muscle with overlapping ends at the top, followed by the cricoid cartilage, the cricopharyngeal muscle, the longitudinal muscle of the esophagus, the trachea, and the longitudinal muscles of the esophagus forming a layer on the trachea. The weak points include two triangular portions from the exposed part of the esophagus labeled ''Triangle of Killian'' and ''Triangle of Laimer'' on both sides of the cricopharyngeal muscle.\n\nFig. 1.4\n\nTwo microscopic sections of muscle tissue with different muscle fibers and a diagram that depicts the features of striated and smooth muscle types. The two microscopic views of muscle tissue in the upper sections are labeled A and B. Section A displays elongated striated muscle cells. Section B offers a closer view of the relaxed and smooth muscle fiber arrangement. Below these sections, a diagram contrasts striated and smooth muscle, with a graphical representation. A flipped triangle indicates the Striated muscles, while an upright triangular region extending downwards represents 100 percent smooth muscles in the esophagus.\n\nFig. 1.5\n\n## Cervical Esophagus\n\nThe cervical esophagus shifts to the left at the base of the neck, so the best approach to the cervical esophagus, for example, during the cervical anastomosis for a transhiatal esophagectomy or resection of a Zenker\u2019s diverticulum, is through a left neck incision. The cervical esophagus is 5 cm in length and extends from the cricoid cartilage at the C6 vertebra to the suprasternal notch anteriorly and the T1\u2013T2 interspace posteriorly. The esophagus is surrounded by loose fibroareolar tissue, and unlike the remainder of the gastrointestinal tract, there is no serosal lining or mesentery.\n\nThe pretracheal fascia anteriorly, prevertebral fascia posteriorly, and carotid sheaths laterally create two cervical compartments, the paraesophageal space anteriorly and the retroesophageal space posteriorly. The pretracheal fascia extends to the pericardium, whereas the prevertebral fascia extends to the diaphragm, connecting compartments in the neck and chest allowing infections from tonsillar or dental abscesses to quickly spread into the mediastinum. A descending infection can rapidly lead to potentially fatal necrotizing mediastinitis emphasizing the importance of early surgical drainage. Iatrogenic perforations most commonly occur above the narrowing of the cricopharyngeal muscle resulting in a posterior pharyngeal perforation ( Fig. 1.4 ).\n\nThe arterial blood supply for the cervical esophagus originates from the right and left superior and inferior thyroid arteries ( Fig. 1.6 ). There are also smaller branches from the common carotid and subclavian arteries. Venous drainage is through the inferior thyroid vein. The middle thyroid vein crosses from the internal jugular vein to the thyroid gland and is often divided to improve exposure of the cervical esophagus. Innervation of the cervical esophagus is from the recurrent laryngeal nerves and the sympathetic chains.\n\nA diagram depicts the macrovascular blood supply to the esophagus. The schematic illustrates the macrovascular blood supply from the thyroid arteries to the esophagus. Blood from the two interior sources marked right and left inferior thyroid artery, flows from the neck labeled 1. From the thorax labeled 2, tracheobronchial arteries marked regions 2 and 3 supply the blood. The dorsal splenic artery marked 4 supplies the blood from the left gastric artery formed by lateral and ventral. All the arteries coexist in a network to supply blood to the esophagus walls through blood capillaries. The azygos vein in the thorax section is responsible for venous drainage through the collateral pathway.\n\nFig. 1.6\n\n### Upper Esophageal Sphincter\n\nThe posterior pharynx consists of three bilateral constrictor muscles originating from the base of the skull, the hyoid bone, and the thyroid and cricoid cartilages. These constrictor muscles converge in the midline posteriorly to form a median raphe. The cricopharyngeus forms a continuous band of muscle originating from the cricoid cartilage without a raphe and blends with the oblique fibers of the inferior pharyngeal constrictor and the circular muscles of the esophagus. Between the inferior constrictor muscle and the cricopharyngeal muscle is a relatively weak area known as Killian\u2019s triangle ( Fig. 1.4 ). A pulsion pharyngoesophageal, or Zenker\u2019s, diverticulum can form in Killian\u2019s triangle due to hypertrophy of the cricopharyngeus muscle or underlying dysmotility. There is a 2- to 4-cm high-pressure zone between the pharynx and the cervical esophagus corresponding to the semicircular cricopharyngeal muscle. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The upper esophageal sphincter is composed of the cricoid cartilage, the hyoid bone, and the cricopharyngeal and inferior pharyngeal constrictor muscles. The cricopharyngeus muscle includes a mixture of fast- and slow-twitch striated muscle fibers allowing a basal tone but also permitting rapid changes for swallowing. The upper esophageal sphincter relaxes as intrapharyngeal pressure increases during a swallow, allowing the food bolus to enter the cervical esophagus.\n\n### Trachea and Spine\n\nThe esophagus is closely related to the membranous trachea, and care must be taken during dissection of the cervical esophagus to avoid injury to the trachea ( Fig. 1.7 ). A tracheoesophageal fistula can also result from direct invasion, radiation of tumors in this area, or dilation of proximal radiation-associated or anastomotic strictures. Laterally, the esophagus is adjacent to the common carotid arteries and the thyroid gland.\n\nA computed tomographic cross sectional scan of the neck is on the left and a schematic is on the right. The computed tomographic cross sectional of the neck shows the positions of the esophagus, trachea, common carotid artery, jugular veins, and thyroid gland close to the first thoracic vertebra. Numeric lines extend to these structures for clear identification. The schematic illustrates the same structures. A key on the right of the schematic enumerates the structures and organs numbered from 1 to 8, with T 1 indicating the first thoracic vertebra. The thyroid artery, phrenic nerve, and recurrent nerve are additional structures indicated in the schematic.\n\nFig. 1.7\n\nThe cervical esophagus is directly anterior to the vertebra. A cervical esophageal perforation or anastomotic leak can lead to a spinal abscess and should be drained by opening the neck to help prevent this complication. Anterior spinal procedures can also result in inadvertent esophageal injury. In addition, esophageal surgeons should be aware of previous anterior cervical spinal operations that could lead to adhesions to the esophagus and potential infection of spinal hardware.\n\n### Recurrent Laryngeal Nerves\n\nThe recurrent laryngeal nerves originate from the vagus nerves ( Fig. 1.8 ). The right nerve recurs posteriorly around the right subclavian artery, whereas the left nerve recurs around the aortic arch. Both recurrent nerves ascend in the tracheoesophageal groove, although the left nerve comes closer to the esophagus as the cervical esophagus deviates to the left, whereas the right nerve recurs around the subclavian more laterally. A nonrecurrent nerve occurs rarely on the right, with Toniato et al. reporting an incidence of 0.1% (31/6000) of patients on the right and none on the left. The recurrent laryngeal nerves also innervate the cricopharyngeal muscle and the cervical esophagus. Care must be taken to protect the left recurrent laryngeal nerve when dissecting out the cervical esophagus during a transhiatal esophagectomy or Zenker\u2019s diverticulectomy. The fat in the tracheoesophageal groove containing the nerve should be sharply dissected from the wall of the esophagus, and care should be taken to gently retract the trachea medially with a finger to expose the esophagus, avoiding the use of any metal retractors on the nerve. With experience and these precautions, the incidence of recurrent laryngeal injury should be approximately 1%. Injury to the recurrent laryngeal nerve not only results in hoarseness but also affects mobility of the cervical esophagus and function of the cricopharyngeal muscle with impaired swallowing and increased risk of aspiration. Injury to both the recurrent nerves can result in bilateral vocal cord paralysis with airway obstruction and the need for a tracheostomy.\n\nA diagram illustrates the esophagogastric innervation. The diagram presents a labeled anatomical diagram of the esophagogastric innervation. Central to the diagram is the sympathetic chain, with connections to the splanchnic nerve and both anterior and posterior vagal trunks. The right and left vagus nerves branch out from the cervical region. The key structures include the sympathetic cervical ganglion, ganglion nodosum, recurrent laryngeal nerves, and parasympathetic cervical nerves.\n\nFig. 1.8\n\n## Thoracic Esophagus\n\nThe thoracic esophagus is 20 cm in length and extends from the thoracic inlet to the diaphragmatic hiatus ( Fig. 1.1 ). The esophagus passes through the middle mediastinum and shifts to the right at the level of the seventh thoracic vertebra, so the best approach to the mid-esophagus is through a right thoracotomy or thoracoscopy, for example, during an Ivor Lewis or minimally invasive three-hole esophagectomy. However, the esophagus angulates to the left after passing through the diaphragmatic crura and along with the location of the liver on the right, the best approach to the distal thoracic esophagus is from the left for a transthoracic hiatal hernia repair or resection of an epiphrenic diverticulum, even when the hernia or diverticulum extends into the right chest.\n\nThe arterial blood supply originates from the bronchial arteries, and the majority of patients have one right-sided branch and one to two left-sided branches. There are usually two esophageal branches from the descending aorta between the sixth and ninth thoracic vertebra. There is a vast network of collateral vessels within the wall of the esophagus allowing the esophagus to receive blood supply from larger vessels perfusing other organs such as the thyroid, trachea, and stomach ( Fig. 1.6 ). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Because of this rich intramural network of small vessels, the esophagus can be completely mobilized from the stomach to the aortic arch yet continue to be well perfused ( Fig. 1.9 ). However, care should be taken if the inferior thyroid artery has been ligated during a previous thyroidectomy. The arterial vessels supplying the esophagus branch into small, fine vessels at a distance from the esophageal wall, and bleeding can be controlled by packing the mediastinum, allowing for blunt dissection during a transhiatal esophagectomy. Venous drainage is through the azygos vein with some drainage through the hemiazygos and bronchial veins.\n\nA diagram labeled Cast of Esophageal Blood Supply represents a detailed representation of the esophagus and its blood supply. The diagram splits into two sections, where the left represents a line diagram of the esophageal blood supply with labeled structures like the aorta and arteria gastrica sinistra, and cardiac branches. The right side features the same anatomical structures with a 10 centimeter scale bar for reference. Key anatomical structures are annotated, that indicate the arteria esophagea propria, bronchial artery, cardiac bronchi of arteria gastrica sinistra, and previous site of the diaphragm in the esophagus. The diagram illustrates the overall vascular connections in the esophagus.\n\nFig. 1.9\n\nThe thoracic esophagus is bordered by the mediastinal pleura on either side. The esophagus is surrounded by loose fibroareolar tissue. This loose investing tissue, with no dense fibrous attachments in the chest, allows the esophagus to be bluntly dissected during a transhiatal esophagectomy. During transhiatal or laparoscopic dissection of the esophagus, it is important to recognize entry into either pleural space. A chest tube is placed for drainage of blood during an esophagectomy, and a tension pneumothorax must be recognized during laparoscopy. In the upper thorax, the trachea is anterior, the azygos is on the right ( Fig. 1.10 ), and the left subclavian artery and aortic arch are to the left of the esophagus ( Fig. 1.11 ). The descending aorta turns posteriorly and continues to the left of the esophagus until T8 where the esophagus moves anterior to the aorta.\n\nAn anatomical diagram of the azygos vein from a lateral perspective. The anatomical diagram shows the azygos vein connections from the esophagus, lungs, and spine. The superior caval vein is located at the top, with the right bronchus and lung below. The thoracic esophagus, spine, and intercostal vein are clearly labeled, along with the dorsal-lateral aspect. The azygos vein runs in a vertical direction, flanked by the right vagus nerve and paratracheal lymph nodes in a detailed anatomical layout.\n\nFig. 1.10\n\nA cross-section of the computed tomography of the thorax and another diagram on the right represent the same part labeled with all the structures. The left side features a transverse computed tomography of the thorax at the T 4 vertebra level with a circular section with the trachea centrally located, flanked by the lungs. The nearby structures are marked with numbers that connect to the anatomical labels. The right side presents a diagram of the esophagus, trachea, and various vessels and nerves, also annotated with respective numbers for clear identification.\n\nFig. 1.11\n\nIn the lower thorax, the pericardium and left atrium lie anterior to the esophagus ( Fig. 1.12 ). Locally advanced esophageal cancer invading the heart or the aorta is unresectable and can be evaluated on a chest CT with contrast or endoscopic ultrasound. Direct invasion of the aorta can also lead to an aortoesophageal fistula. Hematemesis in a patient with esophageal cancer can represent sentinel bleeding from an aortoesophageal fistula which must be recognized early to prevent fatal exsanguinating hemorrhage. However, if the tumor just abuts these structures, often there is no invasion at intraoperative exploration. Posteriorly, the esophagus is adjacent to the spine from the thoracic inlet to T8 where the esophagus moves anteriorly to enter the esophageal hiatus. The left lateral distal esophagus is covered only with mediastinal pleura. As a result of the relative weakness in this area, spontaneous Boerhaave\u2019s perforation occurs most commonly along the left lateral aspect of the distal esophagus.\n\nA computed tomographic scan of the thorax and its detailed anatomical structures with numbered structures and organs on the right side. The transverse computed tomography of the thorax on the left represents various anatomical structures, including the esophagus, lungs, aorta, inferior vena cava, azygos vein, lefty ventricle in the heart, and ninth thoracic vertebra. The right side contains a labeled diagram that corresponds with the scan that consists of the structures and their relationships, with an additional reference to the coronary artery, hemiazygos vein, phrenic nerve, vagus nerve, and diaphragmatic pleura.\n\nFig. 1.12\n\n### Vagus Nerves\n\nThe recurrent laryngeal nerves recur around the subclavian artery on the right and the aortic arch on the left ( Fig. 1.8 ). The nerves may be injured when dissecting the esophagus or lymph nodes in these areas resulting in hoarseness, difficulty swallowing, and possible aspiration. Care should be taken to avoid the use of cautery in these areas.\n\nThe vagus nerves provide parasympathetic innervation to the esophageal musculature. Branches from the vagus nerves and the sympathetic chain enter the wall of the esophagus and form a myenteric (Auerbach\u2019s) plexus between the longitudinal and circular muscle layers which control contraction of the esophageal musculature. The submucosal (Meissner\u2019s) plexus regulates contraction of the muscularis mucosae and secretions. Achalasia results from degeneration of the ganglion in Auerbach\u2019s plexus leading to aperistalsis of the esophagus with impaired relaxation of the LES.\n\nAt the tracheal bifurcation, the right and left vagus nerves form pulmonary and esophageal plexuses. Along the distal esophagus, the anterior fibers from the left vagus coalesce into the anterior vagus, and the posterior fibers from the right vagus form the posterior vagal trunk, although both vagal trunks can contain nerve fibers originating from the left or right vagal nerves. The vagal trunks pass through the esophageal hiatus along with the esophagus.\n\n### Trachea\n\nThe esophagus is closely related to the membranous trachea anteriorly. Care must be taken during dissection of the esophagus, especially with energy devices, to avoid injury to the membranous trachea, which if not recognized can lead to a delayed tracheoesophageal fistula. The carina is located at 25 cm from the incisors, and patients with esophageal tumors proximal to this point should undergo a bronchoscopy to evaluate for any tracheal invasion. Below the carina, the esophagus is in contact initially with the left mainstem bronchus, and tumor invasion can result in a bronchoesophageal fistula.\n\n### Azygos Vein\n\nThe azygos vein is adjacent and to the right of the upper thoracic esophagus ( Fig. 1.10 ). It can be involved by direct invasion by mid-esophageal tumors. Care must be taken during the mediastinal dissection for a transhiatal esophagectomy not to avulse the azygos vein. The vein is often divided during an Ivor Lewis esophagectomy to improve exposure of the upper thoracic esophagus.\n\n### Lymphatic Drainage and Thoracic Duct\n\nUnderstanding esophageal lymphatic drainage is important in tumor staging and treatment planning. A rich submucosal lymphatic network transports lymph to subadventitial lymphatics. The vast network of lymphatics not only drains fluid, debris, and bacteria but also allows the spread of tumor cells. While there are few lymphatics in the superficial mucosa, once tumors invade the submucosa, the submucosal lymphatic plexus allows tumor cells to spread widely ( Fig. 1.13 ). Sakata first noted that the esophageal lymphatic drainage was longitudinal and intramural. These longitudinal lymphatic channels within the submucosa allow lymph to flow most easily up and down the esophagus, which is consistent with the longitudinal spread of esophageal cancer sometimes far away from the primary tumor.\n\nA diagram consists of two sections that represent the lymphatic drainage system in the esophageal wall, and another section highlights the tumor''s impact on it. The diagram is divided into two horizontal sections, which illustrate the local lymphatic drainage of the esophageal wall. The top section details the lymphatic anatomy, which includes the lamina mucosa, submucosa, and muscularis layers, with linear lymph channels and circular lymph collectors that have featured valves. The bottom section displays a tumor within the submucosa and the abnormal cell accumulation in lymph collectors, indicative of the disrupted drainage patterns. Arrows denote lymph flow direction.\n\nFig. 1.13\n\nWhile lymph from the esophagus above the tracheal bifurcation drains superiorly to paratracheal, subcarinal, and paraesophageal lymph nodes, lymph below the carina drains inferiorly toward the lower mediastinal, celiac, and left gastric lymph nodes ( Fig. 1.14 ). However, the direction of lymphatic flow may change when the lymphatics become blocked by tumor, and the pattern of metastatic spread may not follow normal lymphatic drainage, allowing cephalad spread of distal tumors. Collecting lymphatic ducts also originate intermittently from the submucosal network. These collecting ducts connect directly to the thoracic duct in 40% of patients.\n\nA diagram of the human esophagus that represents the flow direction of the path from the neck down through the thorax and into the abdomen. The diagram features a simplified anatomical representation of the human esophagus, which is divided into three main compartments: the cervical, thoracic, and terminal. It includes a vertical arrow indicative of the flow direction from the neck to the abdomen, with a partition line that separates the cervical from thoracic sections. Labeled anatomical features, which include celiac lymph nodes and cisterna chyli, are presented at the base of the esophagus.\n\nFig. 1.14\n\nThe importance of the submucosal lymphatic network in nodal metastases is highlighted by the association of the depth of tumor invasion (T stage) with the incidence of nodal disease. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> T1a tumors localized to the mucosa with limited lymphatics have a low incidence of nodal spread of 2.6%, whereas T1b tumors crossing the muscularis mucosa into the submucosa have a 22.2% incidence. Nodal involvement increases to 43.2% in T2, 77.2% in T3, and 66.7% in T4 esophageal tumors.\n\nThe main lymphatic vessel is the thoracic duct, which begins in the abdomen as the cisterna chyli at T12 and passes through the aortic hiatus along with the aorta and the azygos and hemiazygos veins. The duct lies on the anterior surface of the vertebra and is posterior to the esophagus between the azygos on the right and the descending aorta on the left. To perform a mass ligation for a chylothorax, the tissue between the azygos vein and aorta is ligated just above the diaphragm. In greater than 50% of patients, the duct turns behind the left mainstem bronchus, at the level of the fifth and sixth thoracic vertebra, to eventually empty into the junction of the left subclavian and jugular veins. There are also a number of possible anatomic variations. The thoracic duct is adjacent to the thoracic esophagus and is damaged in 1%\u20132% of esophagectomies resulting in a chylothorax. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> If there is suspicion for a thoracic duct injury postoperatively with high pink, clear chest tube output which becomes milky once fat is added to the patient\u2019s diet, the thoracic duct should either be surgically ligated or embolized by interventional radiology to prevent complications associated with the loss of the protein and leukocyte-rich lymph.\n\nThe thoracic esophagus is in contact with lymph nodes from several stations allowing endoscopic ultrasound imaging and fine-needle aspiration of stations 2 (upper paratracheal), 3P (posterior mediastinal), 4 (lower paratracheal), 7 (subcarinal), 8 (paraesophageal), and 9 (inferior pulmonary ligament) lymph nodes in the staging of lung and esophageal cancer. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The proximity of the esophagus to the left atrium also allows optimal transesophageal echocardiographic imaging of the mitral valve.\n\n## Abdominal Esophagus\n\nThe abdominal esophagus and proximal stomach are approached through a laparotomy or laparoscopy. Normally, the abdominal esophagus is 3\u20136 cm in length. The abdominal esophagus angulates to the left after passing through the diaphragmatic hiatus, and care must be taken to guide an esophageal bougie during a Nissen fundoplication or a rigid esophagoscope through this area to avoid perforation ( Fig. 1.1 ). The distal esophagus is the second most common site of perforation after the pharynx just proximal to the cricopharyngeus. The esophagus ends as it enters the cardia along the lesser curvature of the stomach. The abdominal esophagus receives blood supply from small arteries derived from the left gastric artery and the inferior phrenic artery ( Fig. 1.6 ). Venous drainage is through the left gastric vein. Intraesophageal veins are located in a subepithelial plexus located in the lamina propria. In the distal esophagus, this venous plexus connects with the portal system leading to esophageal varices with elevated portal vein pressures. Regional lymph nodes in the abdomen include stations 15 (diaphragmatic), 16 (paracardial), 17 (left gastric), 18 (common hepatic), 19 (splenic), and 20 (celiac).\n\nThe esophagus passes through the esophageal hiatus at the level of the 10th thoracic vertebra ( Fig. 1.15 ). Distal esophageal tumors can directly invade the crura, which can be resected *en bloc* with the esophageal tumor. The crura originate from the anterior aspect of the first three to four lumbar vertebrae. As the esophagus passes through the hiatus, the left lobe of the liver lies anteriorly, and the triangular ligament can be divided to help expose the hiatus ( Fig. 1.16 ). The aorta is posterior to the esophagus and passes through its own hiatus in the diaphragm. The aortic hiatus is bordered by the median arcuate ligament anteriorly which is used to anchor sutures in performing a Hill repair for gastroesophageal reflux. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The inferior vena cava lies lateral and inferior to the right crus.\n\nAn anatomical diagram of the diaphragm indicates various hernia locations. The anatomical diagram represents a cross-section of the diaphragm. The diagram is circular, with the central tendon at the top center. Various labeled areas indicate the sites of Morgagni hernia, traumatic laceration, Bochdalek hernia, and esophageal hiatus hernia. Additional labels include the vena cava foramen and aortic hiatus, with arrows pointing to each.\n\nFig. 1.15\n\nA cross sectional computed tomography of the abdominal esophagus on the left shows various internal structures and organs along with a diagram on the right indicates the same. The axial computed tomography of the thorax represents internal structures and organs at the thoracic 10 vertebra level. Structures are labeled numerically from 1 to 11 that identify the esophagus, lungs, heart, and blood vessels like the aorta and inferior vena cava. The right side presents an illustrated anatomical diagram with respective labels.\n\nFig. 1.16\n\n### Vagus Nerves\n\nThe anterior and posterior vagal nerves run along the distal esophagus through the esophageal hiatus ( Fig. 1.8 ). The anterior nerve is usually located adjacent to the esophageal wall, whereas the poster nerve can be further away. The anterior nerve should be carefully identified after the phrenoesophageal membrane is opened and preserved during a Heller myotomy, continuing the myotomy underneath the nerve when necessary. Both nerves should be identified during a Nissen fundoplication, especially with a hiatal hernia repair where the nerves can become involved in the hernia sac and inadvertently divided. If the nerves are injured, approximately 15% of patients will develop delayed gastric emptying.\n\n### Diaphragm\n\nThe left and right edges of the esophageal hiatus most commonly originate from the deep and superficial layers of the right crus, while the left crus forms one edge of the aortic hiatus. The phrenoesophageal membrane, also known as Laimer\u2019s or Allison\u2019s membrane, arises from the subdiaphragmatic fascia and attaches the esophagus to the diaphragm ( Fig. 1.17 ). The phrenoesophageal membrane is composed of two sheaths. One sheath passes superior from the diaphragm for 2\u20134 cm along the distal esophagus, and its fibers insert into the submucosa of the esophagus. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The other sheath extends inferiorly across the cardia and blends into the gastric serosa, muscle, dorsal mesentery, and the gastrohepatic ligament. The phrenoesophageal membrane allows the esophagus to move dynamically relative to the diaphragm.\n\nA diagram illustrates the attachment fibers of the phrenoesophageal membrane. The diagram represents the attachment fibers of the phrenoesophageal membrane. It features cross-sectional views that include relevant structures, with the pleura shown in the upper left and the diaphragm and peritoneum labeled. The Z line, lower esophageal sphincter, and gastric folds are also annotated.\n\nFig. 1.17\n\n### Gastroesophageal Reflux Barrier\n\nThe pathogenesis of gastroesophageal reflux disease is complex and involves a combination of a compromised antireflux barrier and decreased esophageal clearance. Proper function of the antireflux barrier depends on an intact intrinsic LES and the extrinsic sphincter function of the diaphragmatic crura and supporting structures which normally comprise a high-pressure zone at the gastroesophageal junction. The pressure gradient between the abdomen and the chest also plays a role in overcoming the antireflux barrier leading to gastroesophageal reflux. Intragastric pressure is higher with obesity, pregnancy, or gastric emptying disorders, and losing weight can decrease reflux. Antireflux surgery reduces reflux by reinforcing the barrier function at the gastroesophageal junction.\n\nThe location of the gastroesophageal junction remains controversial and can vary depending on the criteria used, which can be based on histologic, endoscopic, or surgical findings. Histologically, the gastroesophageal junction has been defined as the point where there are no longer any submucosal esophageal glands or the proximal extent of the gastric oxyntic glands. Endoscopically, the junction has been defined as the squamocolumnar junction, or Z-line, and the proximal extent of the gastric mucosal folds. Surgically, the gastroesophageal junction has been identified as the peritoneal reflection on the stomach and the junction of the tubular esophagus and the stomach. It is important to remove the gastric fat pad to accurately identify the gastroesophageal junction during a Nissen fundoplication or a Heller myotomy.\n\n#### Lower Esophageal Sphincter\n\nApproximately 3 cm proximal to the gastroesophageal junction, the circular muscle layer increases in thickness. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Although there is no palpable circular sphincter at the gastroesophageal junction, the circular fibers become short muscular clasps along the lesser curvature ( Figs. 1.18 and 1.19 ). Along the greater curvature and the angle of His, the circular fibers become oblique gastric sling fibers. This muscular arrangement extends 3\u20134 cm above the gastroesophageal junction and 1\u20132 cm onto the stomach forming a high-pressure zone allowing the LES to be identified on manometry. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In healthy patients, the LES resting pressure is approximately 10\u201330 mmHg.\n\nA photo with two sections, where the left side indicates an anatomical model of the esophagus, diaphragm, fundus, and stomach, and a closer view of the stomach musculature. The photo is divided into two parts. The left side features a three-dimensional anatomical model of the esophagus and stomach, with clear labels for the esophagus, diaphragm, fundus, and stomach. The right side displays a detailed diagram of the stomach musculature, focused on the gastric sling and the labels identified as the gastroesophageal junction and clasps of the lower esophageal sphincter.\n\nFig. 1.18\n\nA diagram of the closure mechanisms of the upper esophageal sphincter, the lower esophageal sphincter, and gastric sling fibers. The diagram represents the closure mechanisms associated with the pharynx, esophagus, and stomach. On the left, the upper part includes the constrictor muscle, upper esophageal sphincter, and longitudinal esophageal muscle, arranged vertically. The lower section illustrates the diaphragm and stomach, with curved and wavy lines of the muscle fibers. The right side shows the lower esophageal sphincter, circular gastric muscle, and gastric sling fibers, with arrows indicative of functional aspects.\n\nFig. 1.19\n\nThe LES provides a barrier to gastroesophageal reflux and relaxes 3 seconds after swallowing is initiated, allowing the food bolus to enter the stomach. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Some have suggested that an esophagomyotomy for achalasia should be performed between the short clasp fibers and the oblique gastric sling fibers to maintain the strength of the sling mechanism. Reflux usually occurs with transient LES relaxation, low LES pressure, swallow-associated LES relaxation, and straining. The basal LES pressure is important in preventing reflux when lying down or after eating, and a hypotensive LES can lead to nocturnal or postprandial reflux. Distension of the gastric cardia results in transient relaxation of the LES, and cooling the vagus nerves prevents the sphincter relaxation suggesting that this is a vagally mediated response.\n\nThe muscle is thicker along the greater curvature, and three-dimensional manometry findings have shown that the pressure measurements are also asymmetric, which is thought to contribute to the antireflux mechanism of the LES ( Fig. 1.20 ). Using CT imaging and three-dimensional gastroesophageal pressure recordings, Mittal et al. found circular and axial pressure asymmetry of the functional morphology of the LES with the highest pressure and shortest length toward the greater curvature.\n\nA diagram with two sections illustrates the correlation of muscular structures and a 3 dimensional mesh representation of manometric pressure measurement. The diagram consists of two sections. On the left, a diagram of muscular structures includes labeled components, which include the pyramid, glenoid cavity, lower cavity, and anterior wall, with vertical and horizontal measurement scales in millimeters. The right side presents a wireframe model that illustrates the correlation to manometric pressure measurements, with pressure levels marked from 0 to 30.\n\nFig. 1.20\n\n#### Diaphragmatic Crura\n\nThe phrenoesophageal ligament normally anchors the distal esophagus to the diaphragm. The angle of His between the lower esophagus and the gastric fundus along with the attachments of the phrenoesophageal membrane to the diaphragmatic hiatus contribute to the antireflux mechanism at the gastroesophageal junction. The diaphragmatic crura play a crucial role in preventing reflux during episodes of increased intraabdominal pressure and straining. Pressure at the diaphragmatic crura also varies with respiratory movement.\n\n#### Hiatal Hernia\n\nAbnormalities in the phrenoesophageal membrane may lead to hiatal hernia formation. The elastic fibers of the phrenoesophageal membrane are replaced by inelastic fibers with aging. Eliska et al. believe that abnormal anchorage of the phrenoesophageal membrane along with increasing adipose tissue between the membrane and the cardia may lead to the development of a hiatal hernia. Mittal et al. reported that the phrenoesophageal membrane and its esophageal attachments may also contribute to the function of the LES, although hiatal hernia experiments in cats found no effect on the LES function with complete disruption of the phrenoesophageal membrane and positioning the cardia in the chest.\n\nA hiatal hernia disrupts the extrinsic sphincter function of the diaphragmatic crura and displaces the intrinsic LES away from the crura. Reflux can occur in the setting of low LES pressure, straining, and LES relaxation with swallowing. Gastric fluid can become entrapped above the hiatus, and pH probe and scintigraphy studies demonstrate re-reflux of fluid from the herniated stomach during swallowing which impairs normal reflux clearance with peristalsis. Hiatal hernias are classified into four types: type I, sliding hiatal hernia ( Fig. 1.21A ); type II, pure paraesophageal hernia with the gastroesophageal junction fixed at the hiatus; type III, combined hiatal hernia with the cardia above the diaphragm and the fundus herniated along the esophagus ( Fig. 1.21B ); and type IV, with herniation of the stomach along with the colon, small bowel, or spleen ( Fig. 1.21C ). Patients with larger hiatal hernias have more frequent episodes of acid reflux on pH probe studies, lower LES pressures, and weaker peristalsis on high-resolution manometry, and more severe esophagitis on endoscopy.\n\nThree radiograms labeled A, B, and C represent the lateral view of the gastrointestinal tract. Panel A is a lateral radiograph of the esophagus and stomach with abnormalities visible as disrupted contours. Panel B shows a detailed view of the gastrointestinal tract, the lumen, and the irregularities. Panel C presents a coronal C T scan of the abdomen, which represents soft tissue structures, an arrow indicates a notable lesion in the region of the kidneys.\n\nFig. 1.21\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe esophagus is a muscular tube that starts at the cricoid cartilage in the neck and traverses the chest before ending in the stomach in the upper abdomen. The primary purpose of the esophagus is to transport food from the mouth to the stomach, while the LES and the diaphragmatic crura play key roles in serving as an antireflux barrier. Although the esophagus seems like a simple organ at first glance, esophageal surgeons must be familiar with the complex anatomy and function of the upper and lower esophageal sphincters, the extensive lymphatic and vascular submucosal networks, and the clinical importance of the relationship of the esophagus to surrounding structures in all three areas of the body for effective surgical planning and the prevention of potential complications.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Liebermann-Meffert D.: Anatomy, embryology, and histology . In Pearson F.G., Cooper J.D., Delauriers J., et al. (eds): Esophageal Surgery . 2000. WB Saunders , Philadelphia\n\nVi