.: Code C.F., Fyke F.E., Schlegel J.F.: The gastroesophageal sphincter in healthy human beings . Gastroenterologia 1956; 86 (3): pp. 135-150.\n\nView In Article\n\n34.: Winans C.S.: Manometric asymmetry of the lower-esophageal high-pressure zone . Am J Dig Dis 1977; 22 (4): pp. 348-354.\n\nView In Article\n\n35.: Friedland G.W., Melcher D.H., Berridge F.R., et al.: Debatable points in the anatomy of the lower oesophagus . Thorax 1966; 21 (6): pp. 487-498.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n36.: Pope C.E.: 2nd. The esophagus: 1967 to 1969. I . Gastroenterology 1970; 59 (3): pp. 460-476.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference33747-3)\n\n37.: Bombeck C.T., Nyhus L.M., Donahue P.E.: How far should the myotomy extend on the stomach? . In Giuli R., McCallum R.W., Skinner D.B. (eds): Primary Motility Disorders of the Esophagus . 1991. Libbey Eurotext , Paris pp. 455.\n\nView In Article\n\n38.: Korn O., Stein H.J., Richter T.H., Liebermann-Meffert D.: Gastroesophageal sphincter: a model . Dis Esophagus 1997; 10 (2): pp. 105-109.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n39.: Preiksaitis H.G., Tremblay L., Diamant N.E.: Regional differences in the in vitro behaviour of muscle fibers from the human lower esophageal sphincter . J Gastrointest Motility 1991; 3: pp. 195.\n\nView In Article\n\n40.: Mittal R.K., Zifan A., Kumar D., et al.: Functional morphology of the lower esophageal sphincter and crural diaphragm determined by three-dimensional high-resolution esophago-gastric junction pressure profile and CT imaging . Am J Physiol Gastrointest Liver Physiol 2017; 313 (3): pp. G212-G219.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n41.: Mittal R.K.: Current concepts of the antireflux barrier . Gastroenterol Clin North Am 1990; 19 (3): pp. 501-516.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference00653-1)\n\n42.: Liebermann-Meffert D., Heberer M., Allg\u00f6wer M.: The muscular counterpart of the lower esophageal sphincter . In DeMeester T.R., Skinner D.B. (eds): Esophageal Disorders: Pathology and Therapy . 1985. Raven Press , New York\n\nView In Article\n\n43.: Mittal R.K., Lange R.C., McCallum R.W.: Identification and mechanism of delayed esophageal acid clearance in subjects with hiatus hernia . Gastroenterology 1987; 92 (1): pp. 130-135.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference90849-3)\n\n44.: Schlottmann F., Andolfi C., Herbella F.A., et al.: GERD: presence and size of hiatal hernia influence clinical presentation, esophageal function, reflux profile, and degree of mucosal injury . Am Surg 2018; 84 (6): pp. 978-982.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Next:** [[2. Esophageal Motility: Techniques Used for the Diagnosis of Esophageal Motility Disorders and for Surgical Decision Making - ClinicalKey|2. Esophageal Motility: Techniques Used for the Diagnosis of Esophageal Motility Disorders and for Surgical Decision Making]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "1. Anatomy of the Esophagus and the Gastroesophageal Reflux Barrier - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Anatomy of the Esophagus and the Gastroesophageal Reflux Barrier', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Esophageal Anatomy', 'Gastroesophageal Reflux', 'Upper Esophageal Sphincter', 'Hiatal Hernia', 'Vagus Nerves', 'Esophageal Anatomy / Gastroesophageal Reflux', 'Esophageal Anatomy / Upper Esophageal Sphincter', 'Esophageal Anatomy / Hiatal Hernia', 'Esophageal Anatomy / Vagus Nerves'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '1', NULL, 2, 40, FALSE, TRUE),
('Magnetic Sphincter Augmentation for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease', 'shackelford-9th-ed-10-magnetic-sphincter-augmentation-for-gastroesophageal-reflux-disease', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Magnetic Sphincter Augmentation for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease\n\nSteven G. Leeds; Marc A. Ward\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 10, 129-138\n\n## Background\n\nTreatment of gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) involves medical and surgical management. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Historically, fundoplication has been the only surgical option and has been shown to provide exceptional reflux control, improvement in quality of life, and is more cost effective than medical management. Despite these benefits, there are side effects associated with fundoplication that can be bothersome to patients. These include dysphagia, diarrhea, recurrent heartburn, and gas bloat syndrome. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Partial fundoplications are often performed to decrease the frequency of these negative side effects, but these symptoms can still persist. Fundoplications are still the most common antireflux operation done today, but other options have emerged to effectively manage GERD symptoms while minimizing the postoperative effects of a fundoplication.\n\nMagnetic sphincter augmentation (MSA) was created to fill a treatment gap between medical management and patients not ready for fundoplication. The device consists of a bracelet of magnetic beads held together with titanium wires that were engineered to be placed around the lower esophageal sphincter (LES). This was designed to provide enough strength to keep the LES closed but could be opened with normal esophageal peristalsis. In addition, the device will partially open in order to vent the stomach should the patient need to belch or vomit. The device also can be tailored to the patient\u2019s esophageal size with a variable number of beads in the bracelet that allowed for different apertures. Characteristics of the device are seen in Figs. 10.1 and 10.2 .\n\nA set of two diagrams of a magnetic ring with titanium wires in open and closed configurations. The magnetic ring expands in the open configuration, while shrinks in the closed configuration. Panel A shows the device in its open state and its components fabricated from titanium wires and titanium cases. Panel B shows the device closed, with the magnetic cores in closer positions. The titanium wires are movable inside the titanium cases and are responsible for the functionality of the device.\n\nFig. 10.1\n\nAn illustration shows the mechanism of the magnetic sphincter augmentation supporting the lower esophageal sphincter while functioning. The illustration consists of two diagrams that depict the normal function and adjustments in the herniated sphincter supported with magnetic sphincter augmentation. Diagram A illustrates magnetic sphincter augmentation in a closed position that prevents the backflow from the stomach. Panel B illustrates magnetic sphincter augmentation in an open configuration allowing the passage through the herniated sphincter. Arrows annotate the directions in the stomach and herniated sphincter.\n\nFig. 10.2\n\n## Premodern Procedure for MSA Implantation\n\nThe original indication for MSA implantation was to augment a failing LES to improve the barrier function in patients with a hiatal hernia less than 2 cm. The technique included preservation of the hiatal anatomy, which included sparing the hepatic branch of the vagus nerve and creating a retroesophageal window between the posterior surface of the esophagus and the posterior vagus nerve. This window was used as a fixation point to prevent migration of the device. There was no dissection into the mediastinum, mobilization of the mediastinal esophagus, transection of the short gastric vessels, or takedown of the phrenoesophageal membrane ( Fig. 10.3 ). A sizing tool was developed to adjust the MSA device to wrap around the esophagus without pressure. This original technique, referred to as the minimal dissection technique, is not currently recommended.\n\nA photo of a magnetic sphincter augmentation implantation with hiatal anatomy and hepatic branches of the vagus nerve. #REF!\n\nFig. 10.3\n\n## Early Uses and Emergence\n\nMinimal dissection and MSA implantation were first published in 2008 by Ganz et al. for feasibility in a porcine model and then published later that year in humans by Bonavina et al. The initial clinical trial followed 41 patients with GERD for a mean of 209 days. Of these, 89% of patients were free from proton pump inhibitor (PPI) therapy and 79% had normalization of acid. There was mild dysphagia in 46% and most importantly, no erosions or migrations. These patients and a few additional patients that had MSA implantation were followed for 1- and 2-year intervals. Similar results were reported with greater than 86% of patients off PPI therapy and 90% of patients with normalization of esophageal acid exposure at 2 years. Additionally, there was 86% satisfaction rate at 2 years, and once again, no erosions or migrations. The concerning early dysphagia rate of 43% showed complete resolution by 90 days. In 2013 the *New England Journal of Medicine* published the results of a pivotal trial that included 100 patients prospectively followed with a 64% normalization of esophageal acid exposure and documented six serious adverse events (four explants for dysphagia and two hospital admissions for nausea and vomiting). The appeal of a new procedure to compete with a fundoplication spread to advanced centers that continued to demonstrate its effectiveness, leading to Food and Drug Administration approval in March 2012. A postapproval study verified the effectiveness, safety, and feasibility in 67 patients where there were no complications, and it worked to alleviate the symptoms of GERD. Centers began adopting the technology as an alternative to fundoplication but gained significant traction after the completion of a 5-year follow-up study that showed preserved control of reflux symptoms long term. This study showed a decrease in GERD Health-Related Quality of Life (GERD-HRQL) scores from 27 to 4 and 85% were free from PPI therapy. Satisfaction was at 93%, regurgitation decreased to 1.2%, and persistent dysphagia was 6% at 5 years ( Fig. 10.4 ).\n\nA graph that represents patient percentages for heartburn, regurgitation, proton pump inhibitor dependence, and dissatisfaction over five years. The graph denotes the years on the horizontal axis increasing from the baseline to the fifth year. The number of patients receiving the treatment continuously decreases from 100 in the baseline to 85 in the fifth year. The vertical axis denotes the number of patients reporting heartburn, regurgitation, proton pump inhibitor dependence, and dissatisfaction with rhombus, square, triangular, and cross-shaped points. The line graphs drastically dip from the baseline year to the first year and then remain stable with minimal fluctuations. A table below the horizontal axis lists the number of patients reporting heartburn, regurgitation, proton pump inhibitor dependence, and dissatisfaction referring to the line graphs. A text below the table states, \"P is less than.001 for comparison between baseline and follow-ups\".\n\nFig. 10.4\n\n## Evolution of the Procedure\n\nExpanding device criteria to include larger hiatal hernias, modern technique includes full mediastinal dissection, repair of the diaphragm with a cruroplasty, and then implantation the device as the final step. This technique was incorporated in subsequent studies. This involved mobilization of the intrathoracic esophagus and taking down the phrenoesophageal membrane ( Fig. 10.5 ). The first publication using this technique was in 2016 with 162 patients followed for 20 months; two groups were separated by hiatal hernia size less or greater than 3 cm. Of these, 52 patients had hernias greater than 3 cm. Better outcomes were reported in the cohort that had the hiatal hernia repaired ( Fig. 10.6A and B ). PPI freedom was better in this group (9.6% vs. 26.6%, *P* \\=.011), and there was better improvement in GERD-HRQL scores with a reduction to 3.6 versus 5.6 ( *P* \\=.027). Dysphagia and symptom resolution rates were statistically similar between the two groups. In 2018 another publication by Buckley et al. showed similar results in a cohort of 200 patients with 78% of them having hiatal hernias greater than or equal to 5 cm. Outcomes improved with a full hiatal dissection and cruroplasty with no change in rates of dysphagia. The authors concluded that the success of the MSA device was independent of the hiatal hernia size.\n\nA closer view of a magnetic sphincter augmentation implant with a larger incision. #REF!\n\nFig. 10.5\n\nA set of two bar graphs that compare outcomes in patients with different size hiatal hernias. The bar graphs illustrate data related to esophageal disorders and hiatal hernia. The first bar chart represents the percentage of patients with various outcomes after hiatal hernia repair, which includes postoperative proton pump inhibitor use, symptom improvement or resolution, and dysphagia requiring dilation for patients with hiatal hernia less than or equal to 3 centimeters and hiatal hernia greater than 3 centimeters. The second bar graphs compare mean preoperative and postoperative Gastroesophageal reflux disease Health-Related Quality of Life scores for patients with hiatal hernia less than or equal to 3 centimeters and hiatal hernia greater than 3 centimeters.\n\nFig. 10.6\n\nAnother study compared outcomes of patients who underwent full mediastinal dissection versus minimal dissection. This included 182 patients, of whom 47% had an obligatory hiatal dissection regardless of hiatal hernia size. At 1-year follow-up, this cohort had 82.2% freedom from PPI therapy where the minimal dissection resulted in 76.6% ( *P* \\=.48). The hiatal hernia recurrence rate was lower in the obligatory dissection group (2.4% vs. 19%, *P* \\=.01), whereas dysphagia rates, explant rates, and need for dilation remained the same. Other data emerged showing similar results that procedures involving a cruroplasty had superior outcomes. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nA subsequent multi-institutional publication looked at the components of the reflux barrier that included the intraabdominal esophagus and LES, the angle of His, crural diaphragm, and phrenoesophageal membrane. Four cohorts were created from 197 patients that had MSA implanted including a minimal dissection (41%), crural closure only (20%), formal crural closure (22%), and an extensive dissection with no hiatal closure (17%) to demonstrate the worthiness of each component. The outcomes showed that the formal crural closure was the most likely to normalize esophageal acid exposure. Furthermore, the investigators went on to describe the characteristics of a patient with GERD that would most likely not normalize esophageal acid exposure. This included the presence of a hiatal hernia, a defective LES, and higher DeMeester scores in the preoperative phase of workup. This study supports the idea that both the crura and LES must be addressed to maximize the outcomes of MSA implantation.\n\nA large group of high-volume MSA implanters were surveyed to determine if this evolution in procedure recommendations was being followed. The study was designed for consensus on several aspects of MSA implantation. Consensus was obtained with 87% of surgeons agreeing that a hiatal hernia was not a contraindication to MSA implantation. When asking surgeons about a mediastinal esophageal mobilization before MSA implantation, 67% agreed to do it all the time and the other 33% only do it sometimes. This did not reach consensus, but the majority supported routine mediastinal. As a result, Ayazi et al. recommended abandoning the minimal dissection completely. Out of 350 patients examined, patients with minimal dissection were more likely to develop a hiatal hernia in follow-up ( *P* \\=.033), and those patients were more likely to need a redo surgery ( *P* \\=.0133).\n\n## Comparison Studies\n\nWhen MSA surged and gained popularity, studies of comparison with other GERD treatments were necessary in order to find out where MSA fit in the spectrum of therapy. There have been a few studies comparing MSA with Nissen fundoplication, including a meta-analysis in 2017 of three studies ( Fig. 10.7 ). This meta-analysis compared 273 patients with MSA with 415 patients with Nissen fundoplication. MSA was superior in preservation of belching and ability to vomit, but no difference was observed in gas bloating, dysphagia, or freedom from PPI therapy. A follow-up meta-analysis was performed that included 1211 patients and again demonstrated that MSA was associated with less gas/bloating with similar rates of PPI freedom and postoperative dysphagia ( Fig. 10.8A and B ).\n\nA table compares the preoperative and postoperative outcomes for magnetic sphincter augmentation and laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication based on the systematic review and meta-analysis. The table presents outcomes from a systematic review and meta-analysis comparing magnetic sphincter augmentation and laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication to treat gastroesophageal reflux disease. Measures are listed with the corresponding numerical values. Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease Health-Related Quality of Life scores improved postoperatively in both groups. DeMeester scores decreased significantly after surgery. The ability to belch was retained more often in M S A patients. The Ability to vomit (emesis) was also significantly higher in M S A patients. Gas or bloating symptoms were reported less in the M S A group. Dysphagia due to difficulty in swallowing is observed. The Proton pump inhibitor independence postoperatively. Endoscopic dilation is conducted in only 50 percent of M S A patients. Satisfaction with the procedure was slightly higher in LNF patients. Willingness to undergo the procedure again was similar in both. Operative time is shorter for M S A. The texts below the table read, W M percent presented as weight means or percent, minutes, n equals 1 for some measures, and Meta-analysis is completed in some measures.\n\nFig. 10.7\n\nA set of two forest plots with results from studies on magnetic sphincter augmentation for gas and bloat symptoms. The two forest plots depict the results of studies that examine the effects of magnetic sphincter augmentation on gas and bloat symptoms. Part A represents the results of six studies that analyze gas symptoms. For each study, it lists the number of events in the magnetic sphincter augmentation and control groups, the odds ratio, and the 95 percent confidence interval. It also displays the odds ratios for the fixed-effect and random-effects models. Part B represents the results of five studies that analyze bloat symptoms, presented in the same format as Part A.\n\nFig. 10.8\n\nAsti et al. compared 199 with Toupet fundoplication with 130 patients with MSA. It is unclear whether the patients had a mediastinal dissection, but the hernia sizes were matched at 2 cm. Postoperative dysphagia was much higher in the MSA group (7.7% vs. 35.5%, *P* \\=.0009) and freedom from PPIs was lower in the MSA group (47.1% vs. 37.9%, *P* \\=.0441). Operative time (110 mins vs. 65 mins, *P* <.001) and length of stay (2 days vs. 0\u20132 days, *P* <.001) favored MSA group. Similar outcomes in operative time and length of stay have been reported in a similar study by Callahan et al. Severe gas bloat, postoperative esophagitis, and digression of Barrett\u2019s esophagus were equal in both groups.\n\nMore data will continue to emerge as MSA implantation is compared with other nontraditional fundoplication antireflux procedures, such as transoral incisionless fundoplication (TIF) and antireflux mucosectomy (ARM). The largest study available compared all surgical procedures with medical therapy and endoscopic procedures. This study showed superiority of MSA implantation to surgical fundoplication, PPI therapy, TIF and radiofrequency ablation of the LES (Stretta). This was done using the four most common endpoints in the literature for antireflux surgery: percent of patients off PPI therapy, change in GERD-HRQL score, DeMeester score, and percent time with pH less than 4. Despite MSA showing superiority, the data presented in this paper include an overwhelming cohort of minimal dissection MSA implantation, which is not extrapolated to the current implantation recommendations with a mediastinal dissection and cruroplasty. A systematic review comparing MSA implantation with TIF demonstrated that MSA was superior in resolution of regurgitation (91.1% vs. 73.1%, *P* \\=.002) and freedom from PPI (86.5% vs. 64.4%, *P* \\=.001). MSA and TIF were equivalent in improvement of GERD-HRQL scores (80.4% vs. 77.7%, *P* \\=.8), patient satisfaction (86.3% vs. 72.5%, *P* \\= 0.06), and technical success (98.8% vs. 98.5%, *P* \\= 0.5). MSA was inferior to TIF in postoperative dysphagia (9.1% vs. 3.6%, *P* \\=.05) ( Fig. 10.9 ).\n\nA table compares the pooled outcome rates of magnetic sphincter augmentation and transoral incisionless fundoplication in the treatment of gastroesophageal reflux disease. The table lists comparison parameters with the corresponding numerical values. The clinical success based on gastroesophageal reflux disease health-related quality of life scores was 80.4 percent for M S A and 77.7 percent for T I F 2. Patient satisfaction was higher in the M S A group (86.3 percent) compared to T I F 2 (72.5 percent). Absence of regurgitation was more common with M S A (91.1 percent) than T I F 2 (73.6 percent). The percentage of patients off proton pump inhibitors at follow-up was higher in M S A (86.5 percent) than in T I F 2 (64.4 percent). Technical success in M S A is 98.8 percent, and T I F 2: 95.8 percent. Postoperative dysphagia occurred in 9.1 percent of patients in M S A versus 3.6 percent of T I F 2 patients. Confidence intervals, prediction intervals, and heterogeneity indices are provided for each outcome.\n\nFig. 10.9\n\nIn 2018 a randomized clinical trial emerged comparing PPI therapy with MSA implantation. This study focused on relief of regurgitation showing the MSA at 89% and PPI therapy at 10% ( *P* \\=<.001). Drastic improvement in GERD-HRQL scores were reported with MSA over PPI therapy and 91% of the MSA cohort were free from PPI therapy. This study would help substantiate the referral for surgical evaluation instead of increasing PPI dosing or continuing to rely on medical therapy to alleviate regurgitation symptoms.\n\n## Indications Expanded\n\nOnce a full mediastinal dissection was implemented into MSA implantation, more indications continued to be investigated for MSA use. There have been a few areas of interest that include bariatric surgery patient with postoperative GERD and patients with atypical GERD symptoms such as laryngopharyngeal reflux (LPR). The patients with prior bariatric surgery have shown significant promise given the inability to use a fundoplication, especially in those with a sleeve gastrectomy.\n\nThe first use of MSA implantation in patients with bariatric surgery that included sleeve gastrectomy and gastric bypass showed safety and feasibility. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Further evaluation included larger patient cohorts that all show promising outcomes. Postoperative length of stay is reasonable from 1 to 2 days in a combination of patients with sleeve gastrectomy and those with gastric bypass pooled together. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Leeds et al. showed an improvement in GERD-HRQL score from 32 to 2. This improvement was also seen in other studies such as Patel et al. (from 46.9 to 16.7) and Khaitan et al. (from 35.6 to 8.1).\n\nLPR is also an area of significant interest where the implantation of the device has been shown to improve atypical GERD symptoms based on the Reflux Symptom Index questionnaire (RSI). Ward et al. found that patients proven to have typical symptoms of GERD also showed a remarkable improvement in atypical symptoms ( Fig. 10.10A and B ). All symptoms showed significant improvement following MSA implantation such as hoarseness, throat clearing, postnasal drip, and coughing. Furthermore, Smoot et al. demonstrated evidence that an MSA implant helped remission of a laryngeal cancer by stopping all gastric regurgitation.\n\nA table and graph compare the symptoms before and after the magnetic sphincter augmentation implantation. The table and graph present the data from a study on respiratory symptoms before and after an operation. The table lists six typical respiratory symptom index symptoms and their respective p-values based on paired t-tests after computing the mean and standard deviation for pre-operative and post-operative conditions along with the differences in means and standard deviation. The symptoms listed are hoarseness or voice problems, throat clearance, excess throat mucus or postnasal drip, cough after feed or in sleep, and inhalation and exhalation difficulties or episodes of being choked. The graph consists of six lines distinguished by color and structure that represent reduced atypical symptoms over time. The horizontal axis indicates the time-lapse from preoperative and postoperative. The vertical axis indexes the symptoms from the scores of 0 to 4. The six lines represent each of the six symptoms listed in the previous table. The lines drop drastically from the scores between 3 to 4 in preoperative to the scores around 0 point 5 to 1 in post-operative.\n\nFig. 10.10\n\n## Long-Term Outcomes\n\nThere have been questions regarding long-term durability of fundoplication, implicating its shortcomings in long-term follow-up. Fundoplication failure is most commonly due to the hiatal hernia recurrence with reported 10-year failure rates of 27%. The first long-term data for MSA implantation by Bonavina et al. in 2013 followed 100 patients for a median of 3 years. GERD-HRQL scores reduced from a baseline of 24 to 2 at long-term follow-up. The DeMeester scores improved from 30 to 11 over the 3 years with 85% cessation of PPI therapy. In 2015 Saino et al. followed 33 patients for 5 years and the GERD-HRQL scores decreased from 26 to 3. The DeMeester scores also improved from 42.3 to 16.1 at 5 years ( *P* \\=.001). The following year, in 2016 Ganz et al. published regarding 85 patients in 5-year follow-up with GERD-HRQL scores improved from 27 to 4, with 85% patients with PPI cessation. The total number of devices being implanted increased from 1600 implants in 2014 to almost 6500 implants in 2016 to 12,000 in 2018. By 2020 the longest follow-up was published with long-term outcomes from 6 to 12 years by Ferrari et al. for 124 patients. This study showed similar improvements in GERD-HRQL scores from 21 to 3 and DeMeester score improvement from 41 to 16 out to 12 years. Also, at 12 years, there were 32 patients remaining with a 91% cessation of PPI therapy. In 2021 two more 3-year studies were published with similar GERD-HRQL score outcomes and PPI cessation. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nThe long-term results continue to demonstrate very similar results across institutions worldwide showing the reproducibility of the procedure ( Fig. 10.11 ).\n\nA set of pre and postoperative graphs that compare gastroesophageal reflux disease and reflux severity scores. The two graphs depict the preoperative and postoperative scores for esophageal and hiatal hernia surgeries rated in various studies. Graph A displays the Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease Health-Related Quality of Life score on the vertical axis, with the horizontal axis denoting the time lapse for pre and post-operation. Graph A consists of six declining lines of different colors, originating from between the scores of 20 and 30 preoperation and ending between the scores of 2 and 5 postoperation. A table below the horizontal axis lists the scores given in different studies referring to the graph. The horizontal axis denotes the time-lapse and the vertical axis denotes the DeMeester score ranging from 0 to 45. Graph B consists of four declining lines of different colors, originating between the scores of 30 and 40 preoperation and ending between the scores of 5 and 10 postoperation. A table below the horizontal axis lists the scores given in different studies referring to the graph.\n\nFig. 10.11\n\n## Dysphagia, Erosion, and Explantation Rates\n\nDue to previous failed foreign bodies implanted at the LES (e.g., Angelchik device), postoperative dysphagia and erosion were significant concerns when MSA was developed. There is both early and late dysphagia reported in the literature. The difference between the two is that early dysphagia is related to the immediate inflammatory response to the implant, whereas late dysphagia relates to the inability of the esophagus to tolerate the device. Early dysphagia rates can be reported as high as 19% to 39%. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Early dysphagia is typically treated conservatively or with antiinflammatory medical therapy and will resolve in most patients. Late dysphagia is the most common reason for explantation. Explantation rates vary from 3% to 9% worldwide. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> A rare cause of explantation is erosion, with the erosion rates ranging from 0 to 0.5%. When this occurs, eroded devices can be removed using organ-preserving endoscopic approaches, reserving laparoscopy only if this option fails.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nMSA has proven to be a viable option in patients diagnosed with GERD. The implant procedure has evolved to accommodate all sizes of hiatal hernias. The use of MSA is slowly expanding to include patients with bariatric surgery and those with LPR. MSA appears to have a high rate of PPI cessation and low rate of adverse events, including dysphagia and explantation. The most feared complication of device erosion appears to be very low and can be managed using endoscopic techniques.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Katz P.O., Dunbar K.B., Schnoll-Sussman F.H., Greer K.B., Yadlapati R., Spechler S.J.: ACG clinical guideline for the diagnosis and management of gastroesophageal reflux disease . Am J Gastroenterol 2022; 117 (1): pp. 27-56.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Slater B.J., Dirks R.C., McKinley S.K., et al.: SAGES guidelines for the surgical treatment of gastroesophageal reflux (GERD) . Surg Endosc 2021; 35 (9): pp. 4903-4917.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: Robinson B., Dunst C.M., Cassera M.A., Reavis K.M., Sharata A., Swanstrom L.L.: 20 years later: laparoscopic fundoplication durability . Surg Endosc 2015; 29 (9): pp. 2520-2524.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Csendes A., Orellana O., Cuneo N., Mart\u00ednez G., Figueroa M.: Long-term (15-year) objective evaluation of 150 patients after laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication . Surgery 2019; 166 (5): pp. 886-894.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: Aye R.W., Baison G.N., Ahmed H., et al.: The Nissen-Hill Hybrid repair: experience with the first 500 . Ann Surg 2022; 276 (4): pp. 626-634.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n6.: Kappaz G.T., Sallum R.A., Szachnowicz S., Rocha J.R., Cecconello I.: Improvement in quality-of-life after laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication . Arq Gastroenterol 2014; 51 (3): pp. 212-216.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n7.: Sgromo B., Irvine L.A., Cuschieri A., Shimi S.M.: Long-term comparative outcome between laparoscopic total Nissen and Toupet fundoplication: symptomatic relief, patient satisfaction and quality of life . Surg Endosc 2008; 22 (4): pp. 1048-1053.\n\n