('Endoscopic Approach to Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease', 'shackelford-9th-ed-11-endoscopic-approach-to-gastroesophageal-reflux-disease', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Endoscopic Approach to Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease\n\nShaun C. Daly; Ninh T. Nguyen; Kenneth J. Chang\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 11, 139-143\n\n## Introduction\n\nGastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) is a spectrum of disease with an estimated prevalence of 18.1% to 27.8% in North America. There are several mechanisms that contribute to GERD, including esophageal hypersensitivity, delayed gastric emptying, genetic variability, obesity, and poor esophageal clearance. However, one of the main factors in GERD is a defective antireflux barrier (ARB). First-line treatment for GERD consists of lifestyle modifications and medical therapy with proton pump inhibitors (PPIs). Despite optimal medical management, 30% to 40% of patients have breakthrough heartburn or regurgitation symptoms. Laparoscopic fundoplication has been shown to be superior to medical therapy in the treatment of GERD refractory to medical therapy and is considered the gold standard treatment in this patient population. The Society of American Gastrointestinal and Endoscopic Surgeons (SAGES) published data in the society\u2019s guidelines demonstrating that surgery has benefit over medical therapy with regard to short-term and long-term quality of life. Despite the failures in PPI therapy and endorsement by SAGES, only 30,000 antireflux operations are done annually. The small number of laparoscopic fundoplications performed can be attributed to gastroenterologist and patient hesitancy secondary to the side effects associated with the procedure, mainly dysphagia and gas bloat syndrome. Transoral incisionless fundoplication (TIF) alone or in combination with hiatal hernia repair (cTIF) provides an alternative option for restoration of the ARB with potentially lower risk of side effects.\n\n## Background of TIF and cTIF\n\nTIF is an endoscopic procedure in the management of GERD that reestablishes the gastroesophageal flap valve (GEFV). Introduced in 2006, three developmental steps of the EsophyX device have been described; the original EsophyX device, EsophyX2, and EsophyX Z device (EndoGastric Solutions, Inc. Redmond, WA, USA) resulting in four described procedures. These procedures, in order of adoption, include the endoluminal fundoplication, TIF 1.0, TIF 2.0, and cTIF. Eligible candidates for the former three include patients with refractory symptoms and objective abnormal acid exposure, but without esophagitis or hiatal hernia.\n\nHowever, since a majority of patients are found to have a hiatal hernia, the cTIF procedure has evolved to address both the compromised crural integrity and the fundoplication. The importance of the crural repair cannot be underestimated in the control of gastric reflux. The cTIF is now the most commonly performed endoscopic-assisted GERD procedure. The cTIF procedure is commonly performed as a collaborative effort between an interventional gastroenterologist and foregut surgeon, or by surgeons who perform significant endoscopy and will be described below.\n\n## Patient Indications and Contraindications\n\nIndications for TIF include patients with chronic refractory heartburn, patients with partial response to acid-suppression medications, patients wishing to stop acid-suppression medications secondary to side effects, or patients unable to tolerate acid-suppression medications. As stated earlier, candidates must have objective evidence of increased acid exposure on pH testing.\n\nRelative contraindications include patients with a BMI greater than 35 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> , hiatal hernia greater than 2 cm, paraesophageal hernias, bleeding disorders, severe esophagitis, esophageal diverticula, esophageal varices, esophageal infections or fungal disease, esophageal stenosis, strictures, limited neck mobility, or any other anatomy that precludes the insertion of the EsophyX device.\n\nIndications and contraindications are the same between TIF and cTIF except that inclusion of hiatal defect repair in cTIF liberalizes eligibility to include patients with hiatal hernia.\n\n## Technique for TIF 2.0\n\nThe TIF 2.0 procedure is performed under general anesthesia with muscle relaxation and positive pressure ventilation. The patient is typically positioned in the left lateral position, although the supine position may be preferred by some providers. A diagnostic esophagogastroduodenoscopy (EGD) is performed to exclude previously unrecognized contraindications. Empiric dilation of the upper esophageal sphincter is accomplished with a 57-French (18-mm) Savary-Gilliard dilator (Cook Medical, Bloomington, IN) over guidewire placed at the time of EGD.\n\nTo prepare the device, open the package and use the included sizer (11.4 mm) to ensure the endoscope will pass though the EsophyX device. Retract the fastener pusher back until the single black line is visualized. Load the fastener cartridge into the device and deploy the first set of fasteners by pulling the cartridge tabs outward until you hear an audible clicking sound. Advance the fastener pusher to the double black line to visualize and confirm fastener placement on the delivery wire through the clear plastic portion of the device. Continue to advance the fastener pusher until the blue holder locks into the device. Using mineral oil or Endo Lube (Covidien, Fridley, MN), lubricate the endoscope channel in the device, the stylet port, and the helical retractor. Advance the endoscope through the EsophyX device, clean the camera lens of the scope with an alcohol wipe. Finally, lubricant is applied to the tissue mold and chassis ( Fig. 11.1 ).\n\nA representation of the Esophy X device with its components and functions. The labeled representation depicts the Esophy X device, which treats esophageal and hernia conditions. The device includes a serosa fuse fastener cartridge, a tissue mold with closed and open indicators, a fastener pusher knob, and a tissue mold control. The shaft contains a clear nose cone and style ports. Other components include a helical retractor, an invaginator vacuum stopcock, and a fastener delivery trigger. The diagram also highlights an endoscope compatibility tool and the internal layout with styles and the chassis.\n\nFig. 11.1\n\nThe scope and EsophyX device are passed under direct visualization into the patient\u2019s stomach. A jaw thrust can be used if necessary. If the device is not passing with ease, the endotracheal balloon cuff can be temporality deflated to allow passage. The stomach is insufflated using a CO <sub>2 </sub> insufflator set to 15 to 18 mmHg (air insufflation is contraindicated) connected though the working channel of the endoscope. The endoscope is retroflexed and under direct visualization the device is advanced until the second blue mold of the chassis is visualized. The endoscope is withdrawn into the device until the first blue mold is in view. The tissue mold is then articulated, and the scope is advanced back into the stomach. The endoscope is retroflexed, and the device is positioned for use.\n\nThe procedure begins by engaging the EsophyX helical retractor to the tissue just inferior to the gastroesophageal junction (GEJ) at the 11 o\u2019clock position by rotating the retractor until the tissue is firmly engaged ( Fig. 11.2 ). The tissue mold is opened to allow the helical retractor to free up from the tissue mold. The tissue mold is partially closed to allow for tissue retraction and optimizing rotation of the device. The device is set by withdrawing the entire device until the first blue mold is no longer visualized. The stomach is partially desufflated while the tissue is drawn into the tissue mold by retracting the helical retractor and locked. The stomach is fully desufflated while the tissue mold is rotated counterclockwise to the lesser curvature. Once maximal rotation has been achieved, the tissue mold is closed. The invaginator is turned on and the esophagus is opposed to the device with suction. The device is advanced approximately 0.5 to 1 cm into the stomach to ensure the fasteners will not be deployed though the crura. The safety is released and the device is fired, deploying two full-thickness fasteners. The invaginator is turned off, the helical retractor is unlocked, the device is returned to neutral, and the tissue hold is opened. The device is reloaded. This step is repeated two additional times in the 11 o\u2019clock position and three times in the 1 o\u2019clock position. Additional fasteners are deployed in the 5 o\u2019clock and 7 o\u2019clock positions without wrapping the tissue to garner more length of the valve. The final GEFV should measure 270 to 300 degrees in circumference and 3 to 4 cm in length ( Fig. 11.3 ).\n\nAn endoscopic view depicts the gastroesophageal junction with clock positions for orientation. The endoscopic view represents the gastro-esophageal junction with clock positions marked for orientation. The lesser curve is at the twelve-clock position in the retroflex view, with three-clock, six-clock, and nine-clock positions identified around the junction. This view helps to understand the anatomical layout amid endoscopic procedures.\n\nFig. 11.2\n\nA representation of engages tissue to form a fundoplication shape under endoscopic guidance. The Esophy X device engages tissue to form a fundoplication shape under direct endoscopic guidance. The device closes and rolls the tissue near completion. The surrounding tissue folds into the required fundoplication shape, which supports the treatment of gastroesophageal reflux disease. This process involves precise manipulation of tissue.\n\nFig. 11.3\n\nThe endoscope is again withdrawn into the device until the first blue mold is in view. The tissue mold is then disarticulated and the scope is advanced back into the stomach. The helical retractor is seated back in the tissue mold and locked. The endoscopic is withdrawn. A completion EGD is performed to assess the GEFV.\n\n## Technique for cTIF\n\nIn this procedure, the hiatal hernia repair and restoration of crural integrity is approached using a minimally invasive (laparoscopic or robotic) approach. This approach has several benefits, including less postoperative pain, reduced morbidity, and shorter lengths of stay, compared with open surgery. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Surgical repairs of hiatal hernias should be performed based on each surgeon\u2019s preference and experience. Universal principles of hiatal hernia repair should be adhered to including high mediastinal dissection and return of adequate, tensionless intraabdominal esophageal length (recommended 3 cm). Closure of the crural defect should be performed according to the standard practice of the surgeon with careful consideration to allow enough room for passage of the EsophyX device. The choice to use a biologic or biosynthetic mesh should be that of the preference of the surgeon and is not contraindicated in performing a cTIF. Once the hiatal hernia is repaired and crural closure complete, the TIF can be performed in the same manner as described earlier in this chapter ( Fig. 11.4 ).\n\nThree sequential endoscopic views of the esophagus and stomach show a hiatal hernia before and after surgical repair, with tissue manipulation visible in the final stage of the procedure. The sequential endoscopic views of the esophagus and stomach display different stages of a hiatal hernia repair. The first view shows the esophageal opening with a hiatal hernia, where the stomach lining appears displaced above the diaphragm. The second view captures the esophagus and stomach after surgical correction, showing a restructured esophageal opening. The third view depicts tissue manipulation during transoral incisionless fundoplication, with visible sutures and signs of surgical intervention.\n\nFig. 11.4\n\n## Outcomes of TIF 2.0 and cTIF\n\nSeveral randomized controlled trials (RCTs) have been published supporting the efficacy and safety of the TIF 2.0 procedure and has led to growing adoption of the endoscopic management of GERD. The RESPECT trial in 2015 was an RCT performed at eight centers in the United States and included 129 patients with regurgitation. Patients were randomized to TIF plus 6 months of placebo (87) or sham procedure and 6 months of antireflux medications (42). At 6 months, 67% of patients in the TIF group reported elimination of regurgitation versus 47% of patients in the antireflux medication group. At 18 months, 71% of patients in the antireflux medication group crossed over to the TIF group.\n\nThe TEMPO trial in 2015 was an RCT performed at seven centers in the United States and included 63 patients with GERD and partial response to PPIs. Patients were randomized to TIF (40) or maximum dose PPI treatment (23). At 6 months, 62% of patients had elimination of troublesome GERD symptoms compared with 5% in the PPI treatment group. Patient satisfaction was significantly improved in the TIF group (72%) compared with the PPI treatment group (3%). In the TIF group, 90% of patients were PPI free. Three-year follow-up data was published in 2017, which demonstrated that all patients from the original trial had crossed over to the TIF arm. TIF continued to demonstrate elimination of troublesome regurgitation and atypical symptoms in 83% of patients. In addition, 71% of patients remained off PPI treatment. Patient satisfaction remained high at 81%. Five-year follow-up data was published in 2018, which demonstrated stable elimination of troublesome regurgitation and atypical symptoms in 80% of patients. Patient satisfaction remained high at 70% of patients. The number of patients off PPI at 5 years was significantly lower at 46%. Additional RCTs comparing the TIF 2.0 procedure with medical management of GERD are summarized in Table 11.1 . <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nTable 11.1\n\nAdditional Published RCTs of TIF 2.0 in the Management of GERD\n\n| Study | Type | Intervention | Symptoms | GERD Questionnaires | PPI | AET% | Adverse Events | Follow-Up |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| H\u00e5kansson et al. RCT: TIF vs. sham intervention to control GERD | RCT | *N* \\= 44 TIF (22 pts) Sham (22 pts) | Remission time TIF 197 days vs. sham 107 days ( *P* <.001) | QOLRAD in TIF 4.9\u20136.4 ( *P* \\=.005) QOLRAD in sham 4.8\u20135.2 ( *P* \\=.34) | NA | Normalized TIF 69% vs. sham 20% ( *P* \\=.04) | No significant differences | 6 months |\n| Trad et al. RCT: TIF vs. high-dose PPI | RCT | *N* \\= 63 TIF (39 pts) High-dose PPI (21 pts) | Resolution TIF 6 months: 65% 12 months: 77% 67% crossover | TIF Improvement in all | 12 months: 82% off PPI | Normalized 12 months: 45% | None | 6 months |\n\n*AET,* Acid exposure time; *GERD,* gastroesophageal reflux disease; *PPI,* proton pump inhibitor; *pts,* patients; *QOLRAD,* Quality Of Life in Reflux and Dyspepsia; *RCT,* randomized controlled trial; *TIF,* transoral incisionless fundoplication.\n\nSeveral prospective studies have evaluated the TIF 2.0 and cTIF procedure. The first study was published by Janu et al. and was performed at two centers in the United States. Ninety-nine patients were enrolled with moderate to severe GERD symptoms and a hiatal hernia measuring between 2 and 5 cm. Patients demonstrated an improvement in heartburn scores, regurgitation scores, dysphagia scores, and in gas bloat symptoms. Furthermore, 74% of patients were off PPI treatment at 12 months and 70% of patients were satisfied with the results. A second prospective study was published by Choi et al., which included 60 patients at one center in the United States. Patients enrolled had clinically significant GERD and a hiatal hernia measuring greater than 2 cm. Mean GERD and regurgitation scores were decreased at 6 and 12 months, and dysphagia scores did not increase above baseline. Furthermore, 29% of patients were on PPI at 6 months, 14% at 12 months compared with 68% at baseline. A third prospective study performed by Gisi et al. evaluated 33 patients with GERD refractory to PPI and hiatal hernia greater than 2 cm or severe GERD symptoms with hiatal hernia less than 2 cm at one center in the United States. The study demonstrated significant decreases in heartburn scores and atypical symptom scores. Further, 81% of patients were off PPI and 75% of patients were satisfied with the procedure with follow-up between 11 and 29 months. In addition, a retrospective study published by Ihde et al. including 29 matched patients with GERD and a hiatal hernia greater than 3 cm demonstrated significantly decreased heartburn and atypical symptom scores with 10% on PPI therapy at 6 months.\n\n## Perioperative Adverse Events\n\nThe TIF 2.0 and cTIF procedure is regarded as a safe option for the treatment of GERD. All risks of general anesthesia apply. As with all procedures, bleeding can be encountered. Bleeding can occur at the time of device passage, making the diagnostic EGD prior to insertion important for assessing anatomic abnormalities that may increase this risk. Bleeding may be encountered with placement of the fasteners. If bleeding occurs at this time, the tissue mold may be utilized to hold pressure. The bleeding is most commonly self-limiting. Continued bleeding may require more advanced endoscopic maneuvers to control and those performing the TIF 2.0 or cTIF procedure should be familiar with these.\n\nPerforation of the esophagus is a potential complication and most commonly occurs during device placement. This complication is rare. To avoid this complication, upper esophageal sphincter dilation prior to insertion is suggested, a jaw thrust maneuver may be useful for insertion, and deflating the cuff of the endotracheal tube can decrease resistance to insertion. Do not force the device if resistance is encountered and the device should be placed under direct visualization at all times. A less common site of perforation may occur at the site of the fundoplication should multiple fasteners be deployed in the same area.\n\nAbscess or infection at the GEJ may occur. The fasteners are deployed full thickness through the esophageal and gastric wall and can lead to translocation of bacteria in a small set of patients. Perioperative antibiotics are administered. Common pathogens that should be covered for include enteric gram-negative bacteria, anaerobes, and enterococci. Additional complications associated with hiatal hernia repair apply to the cTIF procedure.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nA significant proportion of the population experiences GERD. First-line treatment has historically been diet modification and antireflux medications such as PPIs. Surgical interventions for GERD have remained low. The TIF 2.0 procedure has demonstrated significant improvement in heartburn and regurgitation symptoms while decreasing the potential side effects of a surgical fundoplication. More recently, with more understanding of the importance of the crural integrity on GERD control and the increasing proportion of patients presenting with measurable hiatal hernias, a combined surgical hiatal hernia repair and TIF 2.0 procedure has been described with encouraging results. Patients presenting for GERD should be counseled on all approaches for treatment including the growing TIF 2.0 and cTIF procedure.\n\n## References\n\n1.: El-Serag H.B., Sweet S., Winchester C.C., et al.: Update on the epidemiology of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease: a systematic review . Gut 2014; 63 (6): pp. 871-880.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Toghanian S., Johnson D.A., Stalhammar N.-O., Zerbib F., et al.: Burden of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease in patients with persistent and intense symptoms despite proton pump inhibitor therapy . Clin Drug Investig 2011; 31 (10): pp. 703-715.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: Castell D.O., Kahrilas P.J., Richter J.E., et al.: Esomeprazole (40 mg) compared with lansoprazole (30 mg) in the treatment of erosive esophagitis . Am J Gastroenterol 2002; 97 (3): pp. 575-583.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Labenz J., Malfertheiner P.: Treatment of uncomplicated reflux disease . World J Gastroenterol 2005; 11 (28): pp. 4291-4299.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: Lundell L., Miettinen P., Myrvold H.E., et al.: Comparison of outcomes twelve years after antireflux surgery or omeprazole maintenance therapy for reflux esophagitis . Clin Gastroenterol Hepatol Off Clin Pract J Am Gastroenterol Assoc. 2009; 7 (12): pp. 1292-1298.\n\nView In Article\n\n6.: McKinley SK, Dirks RC, Walsh D, et al. Surgical treatment of GERD: systematic review and meta-analysis. 2024. Available at: .\n\nView In Article\n\n7.: Yates R.B., Oelschlager B.K.: Surgical treatment of gastroesophageal reflux disease . Surg Clin N Am 2015; 95 (3): pp. 527-553.\n\nView In Article\n\n8.: Ihde G.M.: The evolution of TIF: transoral incisionless fundoplication . Therap Adv Gastroenterol 2020; 13:\n\nView In Article\n\n9.: Chang K.J.: Endoscopic foregut surgery and interventions: the future is now. The state-of-the-art and my personal journey . World J Gastroenterol 2019; 25 (1): pp. 1-41.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n10.: Bazerbachi F., Krishnan K., Abu Dayyeh B.K.: Endoscopic GERD therapy: a primer for the transoral incisionless fundoplication procedure . Gastrointest Endosc 2019; 90 (3): pp. 370-383.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n11.: Wayman J., Myers J.C., Jamieson G.G.: Preoperative gastric emptying and patterns of reflux as predictors of outcome after laparoscopic fundoplication . Br J Surg 2007; 94 (5): pp. 592-598.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n12.: Hunter J.G., Kahrilas P.J., Bell R.C., et al.: Efficacy of transoral fundoplication vs omeprazole for treatment of regurgitation in a randomized controlled trial . Gastroenterol 2015; 148 (2): pp. 324-333.e5.\n\nView In Article\n\n13.: Trad K.S., Barnes W.E., Simoni G., et al.: Transoral incisionless fundoplication effective in eliminating GERD symptoms in partial responders to proton pump inhibitor therapy at 6 months: the TEMPO Randomized Clinical Trial . Surg Innov 2015; 22 (1): pp. 26-40.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n14.: Trad K.S., Fox M.A., Simoni G., et al.: Transoral fundoplication offers durable symptom control for chronic GERD: 3-year report from the TEMPO randomized trial with a crossover arm . Surg Endosc 2017; 31 (6): pp. 2498-2508.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n15.: Trad K.S., Barnes W.E., Prevou E.R., et al.: The TEMPO trial at 5 Years: transoral fundoplication (TIF 2.0) is safe, durable, and cost-effective . Surg Innov 2018; 25 (2): pp. 149-157.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n16.: Trad K.S., Simoni G., Barnes W.E., et al.: Efficacy of transoral fundoplication for treatment of chronic gastroesophageal reflux disease incompletely controlled with high-dose proton-pump inhibitors therapy: a randomized, multicenter, open label, crossover study . BMC Gastroenterol 2014; 14: pp. 174.\n\nView In Article\n\n17.: Hakansson B., Montgomery M., Cadiere G.B., et al.: Randomised clinical trial: transoral incisionless fundoplication vs. sham intervention to control chronic GERD . Aliment Pharmacol Ther 2015; 42 (11\u201312): pp. 1261-1270.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n18.: Janu P., Shughoury A.B., Venkat K., et al.: Laparoscopic hiatal hernia repair followed by transoral incisionless fundoplication with EsophyX device (HH + TIF): efficacy and safety in two community hospitals . Surg Innov 2019; 26 (6): pp. 675-686.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n19.: Choi A.Y., Roccato M.K., Samarasena J.B., et al.: Novel interdisciplinary approach to GERD: concomitant laparoscopic hiatal hernia repair with transoral incisionless fundoplication . J Am Coll Surg 2021; 232 (3): pp. 309-318.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n20.: Gisi C., Wang K., Khan F., et al.: Efficacy and patient satisfaction of single-session transoral incisionless fundoplication and laparoscopic hernia repair . Surg Endosc 2021; 35 (2): pp. 921-927.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n21.: Ihde G.M., Pena C., Scitern C., Brewer S.: pH scores in hiatal repair with transoral incisionless fundoplication . J Soc Laparoendosc Surg 2019; 23 (1): e2018.00087 .\n\nView In Article\n\n22.: Bratzler D.W., Dellinger E.P., Olsen K.M., et al.: Clinical practice guidelines for antimicrobial prophylaxis in surgery . Surg Infect (Larchmt). 2013; 14 (1): pp. 73-156.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\nPrevious ChapterGo to the previous chapter\n\nNext ChapterGo to the next chapter\n\n\n\n## Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract\n\nNinth Edition\n\nCopyright \u00a9 2026 by Elsevier Inc. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies.\n\n## Get rights and content\u00a0\n\n##\n\n281240\n\n  - Google Play - Go to our Google Play page\n  - Apple App Store - Go to our Apple App Store page\n  - Facebook - Go to our Facebook page\n  - LinkedIn - Go to our LinkedIn page\n  - X - Go to our X page\n\nElsevier (opens in a new window)\n\n  - Contact Us (opens in a new window)\n  - Resource Center (opens in a new window)\n  - Registered User Agreement (opens in a new window)\n  - Help (opens in a new window)\n  - Terms & Conditions (opens in a new window)\n  - Privacy Policy (opens in a new window)\n  - Accessibility (opens in a new window)\n\nWe use cookies to help provide and enhance our service and tailor content. By continuing you agree to the .\n\nAll content on this site: Copyright \u00a9 2025 Elsevier Inc. or its licensors and contributors. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies. For all open access content, the relevant licensing terms apply.\n\n RELX''%20d=''M20.