ll=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n\n\nNeed help? Chat with AI Buddy!\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[10. Magnetic Sphincter Augmentation for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease - ClinicalKey|10. Magnetic Sphincter Augmentation for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease]]\n**Next:** [[12. Delayed Gastric Emptying in Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease - ClinicalKey|12. Delayed Gastric Emptying in Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "11. Endoscopic Approach to Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Endoscopic Approach to Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Endoscopic Approach to Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease', 'Background of TIF and cTIF', 'Patient Indications and Contraindications', 'Technique for TIF 2.0', 'Technique for cTIF', 'Outcomes of TIF 2.0 and cTIF', 'Endoscopic Approach to Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease / Background of TIF and cTIF', 'Endoscopic Approach to Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease / Patient Indications and Contraindications', 'Endoscopic Approach to Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease / Technique for TIF 2.0'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '11', '139-143', 2, 20, FALSE, TRUE),
('Delayed Gastric Emptying in Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease', 'shackelford-9th-ed-12-delayed-gastric-emptying-in-gastroesophageal-reflux-disease', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Delayed Gastric Emptying in Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease\n\nAmber Shada\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 12, 144-147\n\n## Gastric Motility\n\nGastroparesis is present in 16 per 100,000 people in the United States. Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) results in 9 million medical visits annually. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> These two diseases can coexist, and symptoms of gastroparesis can be present in as many as 40% of patients with GERD. This can create confusion in diagnosis and workup for surgical treatment of symptoms of both diseases. Hallmark symptoms of gastroparesis include nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and bloating. This is due to food remaining in the stomach for a prolonged period of time but can be present on an empty stomach when severe.\n\nWorkup for gastroparesis should include an upper endoscopy and gastric emptying study. Endoscopy is important to rule out mechanical causes for obstruction of the distal stomach. This can include peptic ulcer disease, gastroduodenal cancers, or large hiatal hernias with volvulus. Endoscopy in the setting of gastroparesis will typically be unremarkable. Presence of food in the stomach during endoscopy, when done fasting, can be suggestive of gastroparesis but is not diagnostic. Gastric emptying scintigraphy should be performed to confirm the diagnosis of gastroparesis. While the quality of gastric emptying scintigraphy can vary among locations, standardization of measurements at timepoints of 0, 1, 2, and 4 hours is the best way to assure validity of results with the current testing available. Typically, greater than 10% of an ingested meal remaining in the stomach at 4 hours is indicative of a diagnosis of gastroparesis. Suggestive results include greater than 90% retained at 1 hour or greater than 60% retained at 2 hours, but the diagnosis should ideally be confirmed with a 4-hour study.\n\nKnown etiologies of gastroparesis includes diabetes (more often type 1) or postoperative (after esophagogastric or other surgery). The remainder of patients with gastroparesis are characterized as \u201cidiopathic\u201d etiology. This is likely a label given to various types of gastroparesis for which the underlying cause is less well understood. For example, there are a myriad of other autonomic disorders that have gastroparesis as part of their symptomatology. In addition to these causes of gastroparesis, several medications can slow emptying of the stomach. The most well-known of these include narcotics, as well as GLP-1 agonists like semaglutide.\n\nThe first-line treatment for gastroparesis includes dietary modifications (small, frequent, easily digestible meals) and medical therapy. Prokinetics such as metoclopramide or domperidone, as well as antiemetics can improve nausea and bloating. Stopping medications that slow gastric emptying should be strongly considered. Patients with diabetes who have poor glycemic control should focus on improvement of this as well.\n\n## Gastric Motility in the Setting of GERD\n\nPatients with gastroparesis who have concomitant lower esophageal sphincter (LES) dysfunction often report symptoms of GERD including epigastric discomfort, heartburn, and regurgitation. Abdominal bloating is common in both disorders. Symptom overlap can make distinguishing between gastroparesis and GERD challenging in some circumstances. GERD and gastroparesis can coexist. Gastroparesis can also lead to GERD. Progressive distension of the stomach with food can efface the LES rendering it incompetent. This can lead to reflux of stomach contents into the esophagus. Also, presence of food within the stomach can increase gastric acid production, and static gastric contents can ferment and create secondary acidification. It is less common for GERD to cause gastroparesis, but there are disorders where esophageal function and stomach function are both impaired and these can also create symptomatic GERD that coexists with gastroparesis.\n\n## The Impact of Gastroparesis When Planning Antireflux Surgery\n\nWhen meeting a patient in clinic to discuss foregut symptomatology, it is important to discuss symptoms related to both GERD and gastroparesis. Use of a validated symptom questionnaire such as the GERD-Health Related Quality of Life (HRQL) plus the Gastroparesis Cardinal Symptom Index (GCSI) can help direct clinical conversation and decide upon appropriate workup. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The most critical part of history-taking is to understand what symptoms trouble patients most and what they hope to accomplish with surgery. Foregut symptoms can be complex and multifactorial, and foregut operations can improve some symptoms (regurgitation) at the expense of creating/worsening others (bloating). Thus, it is important to know what a patient values and hopes to see improved with surgery.\n\nPerforming an antireflux operation like a fundoplication in a setting of unaddressed delayed gastric emptying can create poor outcomes. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Gastroparesis, with its concomitant bloating, vomiting, and nausea, is often exacerbated by antireflux surgery. Although heartburn and regurgitation can be improved reliably with fundoplication, if this is not the most troubling symptom a patient has, they will be dissatisfied after antireflux surgery if their gastroparesis symptoms are unchanged or even worsened.\n\nImportantly, even the best constructed wrap will have difficulty standing up to the pressures of retching and vomiting. Any patient with known history of vomiting, rumination, or retching deserves careful consideration prior to embarking on antireflux surgery. Any reversible causes for these symptoms should be aggressively treated prior to offering antireflux surgery.\n\nBloating and flatulence are known side effects of antireflux surgery. These are typically time-limited, but sometimes persist. The patient who is not educated on this possibility will be dissatisfied no matter how well their reflux is controlled. Patients with gastroparesis have more bloating at baseline, and without the ability to expel air through their LES a patient with gastroparesis may experience a significant worsening of bloating after fundoplication. Again, the most important consideration here is preoperative counseling and setting expectations. Additionally, tailoring antireflux surgery to match the patient\u2019s symptoms is reasonable. Many surgeons consider a partial fundoplication superior to complete fundoplication for lower incidence of postoperative bloating and dysphagia. However, the durability of a partial fundoplication is perhaps lower than a complete fundoplication, and the LES pressure is higher after Nissen than after Toupet. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Thus, shared decision-making is critical when discussing antireflux options in the setting of gastroparesis.\n\nSurgical history is a critical part of decision-making surrounding foregut surgery. Patients with a history of thoracic surgery (lung transplant, prior lobectomy, esophagectomy, prior mediastinal surgery) as well as patients with a history of radiation to the chest can be at elevated risk for gastroparesis. This is likely related to neuropraxia or division of the vagus nerve during surgery. Patients who have had a prior antireflux operation (fundoplication, paraesophageal hernia repair) can also have delayed gastric emptying.\n\nFor patients who present to clinic with symptoms of both gastroparesis and GERD and have objective testing confirmatory for gastroparesis and GERD, both diseases can be addressed concurrently with surgery. The most common surgical option in this case is a fundoplication and pyloric procedure (endoscopic pyloromyotomy or pyloroplasty). Alternatively, it is reasonable to treat the gastroparesis first and re-evaluate symptoms of gastroparesis and GERD in patients without significant hiatal disruption. If GERD symptoms persist, these can be addressed with delayed fundoplication.\n\nFor patients who present to clinic with GERD confirmed with objective testing but also have symptoms of gastroparesis, a gastric emptying study should be performed. If this is abnormal, it is recommended that the patient have both GERD and gastroparesis addressed concurrently with surgery. The most common surgical option in this case is a fundoplication and pyloric procedure. Surgical treatment for gastroparesis is focused on symptom improvement. Therapies directed at the pylorus include endoscopic pyloromyotomy or pyloroplasty. Gastric neural stimulation implantation can improve symptoms, though it does not always lead to an improvement in gastric emptying. If nutrition support is needed, enteral feeding with a gastrojejunal tube or a jejunostomy tube can be considered. This may be especially important in patients with diabetes who have poor blood sugar control plus highly refractory nausea and vomiting, which exacerbates their symptoms.\n\nPyloric procedures in the setting of delayed gastric emptying are a reasonable consideration. It stands to reason that patient with GERD and gastroparesis on objective testing will have better outcomes if both diseases are treated concurrently. Patients with symptomatic untreated gastroparesis who are offered fundoplication as an antireflux operation are likely to see worsening symptoms of their gastroparesis, though there is no primary literature addressing this scenario. There is likely some undiagnosed gastroparesis being mistakenly treated with antireflux surgery and creating subpar outcomes, including expected bloating and nausea. Endoscopic pyloromyotomy (termed as per-oral pyloromyotomy \\[POP\\] or alternatively a gastric per-oral endoscopic myotomy \\[G-POEM\\]) has gained favor since its first published use in gastroparesis in 2014 as a minimally invasive approach to gastroparesis. This can be done in the setting of fundoplication or on its own to address refractory gastroparesis. Laparoscopic pyloroplasty improves gastric emptying in 86% of patients. Rates of improvement after pyloroplasty and POP are similar.\n\nLaparoscopic pyloroplasty is often performed in the Heineke\u2013Mikulicz fashion, which is very feasible in a pylorus that is structurally normal ( Fig. 12.1 ). A Kocher maneuver can be used to mobilize the pylorus if needed, and the pylorus can be identified laparoscopically or with the help of an endoscope. A full-thickness gastrotomy is made just proximal to the pylorus and carried across the pylorus onto the duodenum. A 5-cm full-thickness pyloromyotomy is thus made and closed transversely with absorbable suture. Placement of an endoscope across the pylorus during closure can avoid incorporating the back wall of the pylorus in the closure. Intraoperative endoscopic air leak test can be used to confirm complete closure. Omentoplasty atop the closure is a reasonable adjunct. A percutaneous drain can also be used along the suture line for early leak detection, though this is not mandatory. Most patients with gastroparesis have some baseline nausea that can be exacerbated by anesthesia and should be managed perioperatively aggressively with antiemetics, consideration for total intravenous anesthesia, and proton pump inhibitor to help healing of the suture line. The risks of this procedure are bleeding and leak, which are often manageable endoscopically but may require reoperation in the perioperative period. Dumping syndrome is a rare complication that can occur as a result of rapid emptying and may require dietary modifications or medications such as bile binders.\n\nA closer view of a laparoscopic pyloroplasty includes medical instruments operating the damaged pylorus. The raptured outermost connective tissue layers are being closed with stitches. Ch12\n\nFig. 12.1\n\nEndoscopic treatment of the pylorus can be considered. This includes pyloric dilation, stenting, Botox injections, or pyloromyotomy. There is little evidence that pyloric dilation, stenting and Botox have any long-term efficacy. Pyloromyotomy, which has been performed endoscopically (POP) does have demonstrable long-term efficacy in improving symptoms of gastroparesis in the setting of GERD. POP uses the principles of \u201cthird space endoscopy\u201d or submucosal dissection and myotomy techniques that have long been used in esophageal motility disorders. Using a standard upper endoscope fitted with a cap, the mucosa proximal to the pylorus is lifted with a solution of saline containing methylene blue. The mucosa is incised and the endoscope inserted into the submucosal space, where it is tunneled down to the pylorus. The pylorus is then cut with electrosurgery, and the mucosal incision closed with endoscopic clips or suture. This approach to the pylorus provides an incisionless, outpatient option for treatment of gastroparesis ( Fig. 12.2 ). The approximate length of procedure varies, but once the learning curve is complete it can be done in under 30 minutes and is a reasonable alternative to traditional laparoscopic pyloroplasty.\n\nFour photos labeled A to D depict different stages of a pyloric surgical procedure. Photo A captures the exposed pylorus, mucosa, duodenal mucosa, and muscle wall beneath a mucosal layer due to myotomy. Photo B presents the pylorus incision. Photo C shows transected pylorus with pyloric congestion. Photo D captures the closure of incision linings with clips with pyloric atrophy. Arrows point to the surgical sites in photos A, B, and C.\n\nFig. 12.2\n\nPatients with GERD and gastroparesis who are morbidly obese are a challenging subset of patients. Traditional fundoplication is considered to be less durable in these patients. Many believe that the default surgical option in this setting should be Roux-en-Y gastric bypass (RYGB). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> There is debate about whether the stomach should be removed either subtotal or completely instead of routine RYGB for gastroparesis. This does create more morbidity and does not allow for enteral access via gastrojejunal tube in the future. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> It does, however, decrease the need for future surgery (presumably remnant gastrectomy in patients who remain symptomatic).\n\n## Postoperative Gastroparesis After Foregut Surgery\n\nGastroparesis can occur after foregut surgery. This can be an early or a late complication of surgery. If early, it can often be temporary. This is more common for patients undergoing paraesophageal hernia repair in the setting of intrathoracic stomach, and also those who are undergoing reoperative foregut surgery. Because mitigating side effects of gastroparesis is a priority for complex redo foregut surgery, our practice is to get preoperative gastric emptying studies for all patients who are getting workup for consideration of reoperative foregut surgery.\n\nIn cases of gastroparesis that are early postoperative, supportive care with dietary modifications and prokinetics should be considered. If nutrition support is needed, a temporary gastrojejunal tube can be placed endoscopically or radiologically or surgical jejunostomy tube can be placed. For gastroparesis that lasts beyond 3\u20136 months, surgical treatment of gastroparesis should be considered. Early intervention for gastroparesis (prior to 48 weeks) can improve clinical outcomes.\n\n### Refractory Gastroparesis After Foregut Surgery\n\nThere are patients whose symptoms do not suitably improve after pyloromyotomy or pyloroplasty. This can be for several reasons. A subset of patients will not have improved emptying despite pyloric procedure, and a repeat procedure is sometimes indicated. There is a subset of patients with a sump-like problem inhibiting emptying of their stomach (the reservoir is too dilated to overcome transit from the dependent body of the stomach to the pylorus). These patients may benefit from a partial or total gastrectomy. There is data in support of sleeve gastrectomy for gastroparesis, but total gastrectomy with Roux-en-Y gastrojejunostomy is the standard operation in these cases. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In general, the literature on this is sparse and careful patient counseling and expectation setting is critical.\n\n## Conclusions\n\nDelayed gastric emptying can impact both GERD and antireflux surgery, and careful consideration of stomach function is critical for successful outcomes after antireflux surgery. Delayed gastric emptying can also be a temporary or permanent outcome after antireflux surgery, and early diagnosis and treatment is crucial to minimize the impact of delayed gastric emptying on patient\u2019s quality of life.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Chen Y.J., et al.: Health-care resource use and costs associated with diabetic and idiopathic gastroparesis: a claims analysis of the first 3 years following the diagnosis of gastroparesis . Neuro Gastroenterol Motil 2022; 34 (9):\n\nView In Article\n\n2.: Richter J.E., Rubenstein J.H.: Presentation and epidemiology of gastroesophageal reflux disease . Gastroenterology 2018; 154 (2): pp. 267-276.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: Khajanchee Y.S., Dunst C.M., Swanstrom L.L.: Outcomes of Nissen fundoplication in patients with gastroesophageal reflux disease and delayed gastric emptying . Arch Surg 2009; 144 (9): pp. 823-828.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Velanovich V.: 25 Years of the GERD-HRQL symptom severity instrument: an assessment of published applications . Surg Endosc 2023; 37 (1): pp. 255-265.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: Revicki D.A., et al.: Gastroparesis Cardinal Symptom Index (GCSI): development and validation of a patient reported assessment of severity of gastroparesis symptoms . Qual Life Res 2004; 13 