', 'The Impact of Gastroparesis When Planning Antireflux Surgery', 'Postoperative Gastroparesis After Foregut Surgery', 'Refractory Gastroparesis After Foregut Surgery', 'Delayed Gastric Emptying in Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease / Gastric Motility', 'Delayed Gastric Emptying in Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease / Gastric Motility in the Setting of GERD', 'Delayed Gastric Emptying in Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease / The Impact of Gastroparesis When Planning Antireflux Surgery'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '12', '144-147', 2, 17, FALSE, TRUE),
('Patient Selection for Antireflux Surgery', 'shackelford-9th-ed-13-patient-selection-for-antireflux-surgery', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Patient Selection for Antireflux Surgery\n\nMarie L. Fefferman; Yalini Vigneswaran\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 13, 148-152\n\n## Introduction\n\nGastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) is a chronic disease, and without surgical intervention, lifelong medical therapy is required. Patients diagnosed with GERD may be candidates for antireflux surgery (ARS) as a long-term treatment option. However, appropriate patient selection is critical to optimizing clinical outcomes and aligning patient expectations with surgical treatment plans. In this chapter, we will discuss optimal patient selection for ARS by reviewing the clinical presentation of GERD and the necessary diagnostic tests before pursuing ARS. In this context, we will discuss the predictors of a favorable or poor postoperative response as well as potential cautions when identifying surgical candidates.\n\n## Diagnostic Testing\n\nSurgical success relies heavily on appropriate patient selection. Most importantly, patients should undergo diagnostic testing to obtain an objective GERD diagnosis given the ambiguity of a clinical diagnosis. While a thorough history and physical exam is necessary to understand clinical impact, diagnostic testing for GERD is required before determining candidacy for ARS. These tests are described in detail in Chapter 2 , Chapter 3 , Chapter 4 , Chapter 5 , Chapter 6 and will not be belabored here, but it is important to understand these tests in the context of patient selection. A suggested algorithm for preoperative diagnostic testing is briefly described here and shown in Fig. 13.1 .\n\nA flowchart showing the diagnostic process for gastroesophageal reflux disease. This flowchart guides the decision-making steps and diagnostic processes in blocks. Patients presenting with gastroesophageal reflux disease symptoms or suspected gastroesophageal reflux disease undergo gold standard diagnostic tests, which include pH testing off Proton Pump Inhibitor therapy using either a wireless pH monitoring system for a duration of 48 to 96 hours or a catheter based pH monitoring system for 24 hours. Alternatively, they may undergo upper endoscopy with biopsy to provide objective evidence of gastroesophageal reflux disease, identifying conditions like erosive esophagitis or long segment Barrett''s esophagus. The results are categorized based on the DeMeester score. If the DeMeester score is less than 14 point 7, alternative diagnostic testing should be considered if gastroesophageal reflux disease remains a strong concern. If the score is greater than 14 point 7, further evaluation is necessary to rule out other esophageal pathologies before considering surgery. If no dysphagia symptoms are present, an Esophageal is performed. If the Esophagram indicates dysmotility, manometry should be pursued. However, if the Esophagram is normal, all antireflux surgery options may be considered. Manometry results further guide treatment decisions. If manometry is normal, all antireflux surgery options remain available. If inefficient esophageal motility or nonspecific dysmotility disorder is detected, not all antireflux surgery options are available, and careful consideration is needed to determine the best approach for the patient.\n\nFig. 13.1\n\nFirst, preoperative testing is necessary to confirm the diagnosis of GERD with objective measures of pathologic acid exposure in the distal esophagus. Ambulatory pH testing is the gold standard for confirming GERD prior to ARS. This testing can be performed either via pH catheter or wireless capsule monitoring as described in Chapter 4 but should be conducted with patients off all acid suppression therapy during a preoperative evaluation. Up to 93% of patients with typical symptoms and 99% of patients with atypical symptoms will have a false-negative result on pH testing when taking twice-daily proton pump inhibitors (PPIs). Unsurprisingly, the odds of a normal pH value are 11 times higher for patients taking PPIs. Thus, for a patient with high suspicion for GERD and a negative pH test performed on acid suppression, pH testing should be repeated off all acid suppression therapy for at least 1\u20132 weeks before testing. Preoperative ambulatory pH testing may not be necessary if there is other sufficient evidence of GERD or lower esophageal sphincter (LES) dysfunction, such as erosive esophagitis, which will be discussed later.\n\nSecond, preoperative testing can identify other underlying esophageal pathologies that may mimic GERD symptoms but require different treatment. For example, eosinophilic esophagitis may present with similar symptoms to GERD but will not be improved with ARS and in fact may result in worsening of symptoms if ARS is performed. Patients should have endoscopic evaluation prior to ARS to rule out these other pathologies in addition to a thorough clinical history to guide further workup.\n\nThird, preoperative testing can influence the type of reflux procedure performed by evaluating for any underlying esophageal motility disorders that could affect the success of ARS. Many surgeons require high-resolution manometry (HRM) before proceeding with ARS to evaluate for any major motility disorder, specifically achalasia, that would respond poorly to ARS or be better treated with other therapies (see Chapter 2 , Chapter 6 ). In the absence of dysphagia symptoms, an esophagram may be used to rule out major motility disorders and negate the need for preoperative HRM. However, the quality and utility of an esophagram is highly dependent on the protocol used and the radiologist performing the study. Therefore, the use of esophagram for preoperative testing is still debated, and the diagnostic value of this test largely depends on the radiologist\u2019s skill set and familiarity with using esophagram for this indication (see Chapter 5 ). If there is evidence of dysmotility on barium esophagram, patients should subsequently undergo HRM prior to ARS. Specific findings on HRM may alter antireflux procedure choice.\n\n## Optimal Surgical Candidates\n\nAll patients with an objective diagnosis of GERD without surgical contraindications are candidates for ARS. In 1999, Campos et al. examined patient variables that best predicted clinical outcomes of laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication. They found that with a median follow-up of 15 months postoperatively, three variables were predictive of a successful outcome: an abnormal 24-hour pH score, the presence of typical symptoms of GERD, and a response to PPI therapy. Since then, multiple studies have similarly concluded that the outcome of ARS is based on a variety of patient factors. Therefore, once the diagnosis of GERD is objectively confirmed, surgeons must understand the patient\u2019s specific clinical syndrome, review the anticipated clinical outcome with the patient, and discuss postoperative expectations. Here we will review the intricacies of the objective test results, the clinical spectrum of GERD, and how these impact clinical outcomes and patient selection for ARS.\n\n### Objective Findings\n\nWhile we discussed the key diagnostic components to proceed with ARS, the details of the results of these diagnostic tests can help predict success after surgery and guide patient expectations postoperatively. The fundamental goal of preoperative testing is to confirm that the patient has objective evidence of abnormal reflux. This section will review the available literature and various scenarios to help guide these discussions.\n\n#### Ambulatory pH Testing\n\nAs discussed earlier, patients with pathologic GERD seen on ambulatory pH testing are great candidates for ARS. Pathologic GERD, defined as a DeMeester score greater than 14.7 (see Chapter 4 ), is predictive of a successful outcome after ARS. However, the challenge arises when there is high suspicion for GERD but normal, nonpathologic findings on pH testing when performed off PPI therapy. The largest challenge with this subset of patients is that most studies evaluating ARS outcomes are conducted in patient populations with pathologic pH findings. Thus, caution should be used when proceeding with ARS in patients with normal pH results.\n\nIn the setting of normal pH findings off PPI therapy with high suspicion for GERD, several other adjuvants have been proposed to better understand if patients\u2019 symptoms are due to (1) biliary or nonacid reflux events or (2) hypersensitivity to lower levels of acid exposure. In order to evaluate for these events, impedance, symptom association, and medication response have been investigated as adjuvant measures. Impedance is discussed in Chapter 4 , but its ability to independently predict the success of ARS in the absence of positive pH findings is not well defined. While impedance should measure nonacid events such as biliary reflux, little data is available to advocate for its independent use in preoperative planning for ARS. Similarly, positive symptom association and positive response to acid suppression should not be used as independent predictors of ARS success. While some studies suggest that there may be a benefit to performing ARS in reflux hypersensitive patients with typical symptoms, pure acid sensitivity has also been shown to be a negative predictor of success with ARS. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Thus, in the absence of other objective evidence of GERD, such as esophagitis or hiatal hernia, patients with negative pH testing off PPI therapy are not considered good candidates for ARS.\n\n#### Erosive Esophagitis\n\nPatients with GERD can be designated as those with nonerosive reflux disease (NERD) or erosive reflux disease (ERD) as seen on endoscopy. ERD, evident with mucosal breaks and classified as Los Angeles grade B or higher, demonstrates the progression of pathologic reflux. In these cases, treatment with surgery is superior to medical treatment. Furthermore, satisfaction is seen in over 85% of these patients after ARS. Although patients with NERD may also benefit from ARS, diligent investigation with pH testing should be conducted.\n\n#### Presence of Hiatal Hernia\n\nPatients with a hiatal hernia and GERD symptoms are optimal surgical candidates as medication alone may not overcome the anatomic disruption. The presence of a hiatal hernia is associated with worsening disease, higher risk of Barrett\u2019s esophagus, and decreased efficacy of PPI. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In fact, the severity of esophagitis can be predicted by the size of the hiatal hernia. Few multivariate studies have failed to demonstrate the influence of hiatal hernia on the success of ARS. Yet as discussed in previous chapters, a hiatal hernia disrupts LES competency, making it an important component of GERD pathophysiology and subsequently diagnostic of LES dysfunction. Still, the presence of a small hiatal hernia alone is not a sufficient indication for ARS surgery.\n\n#### Manometry Findings\n\nMajor motility disorders such as achalasia, diffuse esophageal spasm, or absent contractility are general contraindications for ARS. However, other minor dysmotilities may be discovered with preoperative HRM. The most common finding in this context is ineffective esophageal motility (IEM) and can be seen in over 20% of patients undergoing preoperative workup with HRM. IEM is often associated with GERD and is secondary to low peristaltic contractions. While the exact etiology is unclear, this dysmotility is thought to be secondary to neuronal damage or inflammation of underlying GERD. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Such findings should not discourage the use of ARS but may require some consideration as to the type of procedure that is performed. While the literature is controversial as to whether 360-degree fundoplication should be avoided in patients with IEM, long-term outcomes are favorable with overall satisfaction similar to patients with normal preoperative HRM. Furthermore, the latest Chicago Classification of Esophageal Motility Disorders now requires >70% ineffective swallows for the diagnosis of IEM (opposed to >50%), which will likely reduce the incidence of this finding on preoperative HRM. Thus, in patients with findings of IEM, ARS is still an optimal treatment for GERD, but patients should be carefully counseled on postoperative expectations.\n\n### Clinical GERD Spectrum\n\nAs discussed in previous chapters, GERD symptoms can vary significantly, making a clear causal path between symptoms and GERD challenging. In patients with a confirmed GERD diagnosis, only 49% report typical symptoms of heartburn or regurgitation as their primary symptom. Yet in patients without GERD, 26% also identify heartburn or regurgitation as their primary complaint. Furthermore, many symptoms associated with GERD are not unique to GERD and can be attributed to respiratory, otolaryngologic, cardiac, or other esophageal and gastric pathologies. These GERD symptoms can be divided into two categories: (1) typical symptoms (esophageal) and (2) atypical (extraesophageal). Understanding these two categories is particularly important when discussing patient selection and expectations for symptom resolution after ARS.\n\n  - 1.\n\tTypical GERD symptoms\n  - \u2022\n\t\theartburn\n  - \u2022\n\t\tregurgitation\n  - \u2022\n\t\tdysphagia\n  - 2.\n\tAtypical GERD symptoms\n  - \u2022\n\t\tchest pain\n  - \u2022\n\t\tcough\n  - \u2022\n\t\twheezing\n  - \u2022\n\t\tsore throat\n  - \u2022\n\t\tsleep alterations\n  - \u2022\n\t\tpostnasal drip\n  - \u2022\n\t\tdental erosion\n  - \u2022\n\t\thoarseness\n  - \u2022\n\t\tasthma\n  - \u2022\n\t\taspiration\n\nWhen symptoms are suspicious for GERD, a typical practice is monitoring patients\u2019 symptom response to acid suppression therapy. In fact, most patients receive a diagnosis of GERD without any objective testing and are instead started on acid suppression therapy. PPIs are the class of medications most commonly used, and patients with GERD can be further designated based on their response to PPIs. PPI-responsive GERD refers to patients who experience significant improvement, not necessarily resolution, in their symptoms with PPI use. Patients who do not respond to PPI therapy with symptom improvement are defined as PPI-unresponsive or PPI-refractory. Often some symptoms will improve, whereas others, such as regurgitation, do not respond to acid suppression. These designations are important when we evaluate the treatment options including ARS.\n\n#### Typical Symptoms\n\nPatients with heartburn as a primary symptom with a complete or partial response to PPI therapy are favorable candidates for ARS. These are also the patients who are receiving satisfactory symptom relief on a PPI and are less likely to seek surgical treatment. However, up to 80% of patients with PPI-controlled GERD have recurrent symptoms within 6 to 12 months of discontinuing medical therapy. Thus, while PPIs are largely well-tolerated and have a low risk of potential adverse effects, these therapies are lifelong. Many patients do not want to be on medication for their entire life. For these patients, ARS may allow them to discontinue medical therapy entirely with high satisfaction rates. At a mean follow-up of 8 years, up to 85% of patients remained off of PPI therapy after ARS.\n\nCompared with heartburn, regurgitation as a main symptom of GERD is difficult to treat medically. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In patients with regurgitation symptoms who are refractory to PPI therapy, ARS is a good option. This is especially true for patients with provocative or positional regurgitation that interferes with activities they enjoy. ARS appears to be superior to PPIs in alleviating regurgitation symptoms; however, a careful workup must be performed to rule out underlying motility disorders. While ARS is superior to PPI therapy for these patients, postoperative expectations must be adjusted from the above subset of PPI-responsive patients who experience heartburn as a primary symptom.\n\n#### Atypical Symptoms\n\nPatients with atypical symptoms make up a special subset for several reasons. First, linking these patients\u2019 symptoms to GERD is extremely difficult. Second, atypical symptoms, even if secondary to GERD, are less likely to respond to medical therapy. Therefore, these patients are often referred for surgical treatment. Although patients with atypical GERD symptoms may not be as satisfied as patients with typical symptoms after ARS, their chance for successful treatment is still higher with ARS than if they were maintained on medical therapy. However, this only remains true if objective testing confirms the presence of GERD. When patients present with atypical symptoms and have objective evidence of GERD, ARS may not completely resolve all atypical symptoms, but patients may still achieve clinically relevant improvement in symptoms. Therefore, with confirmatory objective testing and upfront communication about postoperative expectations, these patients may still be good candidates for ARS. It is important for patients to understand that the cause of atypical symptoms is often multifactorial and therefore correcting GERD alone may not completely eliminate their symptoms. It is helpful if patients also have typical symptoms they would like to have resolved. ARS for patients with only atypical symptoms, even in the presence of objective confirmation of abnormal esophageal acid exposure, should be performed with exceeding caution.\n\n#### PPI-Refractory GERD\n\nWhile medical therapy may be successful in treating many patients\u2019 symptoms of GERD, acid suppression therapy itself does not repair the incompetent antireflux barrier responsible for GERD. PPIs reduce acid production in the stomach, but medical treatment does not stop reflux from occurring, allowing weak acid, food, and bile to continue refluxing and causing symptoms of GERD. This explains why up to 40% of patients partially or completely fail to respond to PPIs. These patients can be classified as PPI-refractory once providers confirm that patients are taking their PPIs appropriately. The inappropriate use of PPIs is not uncommon, and patients can only be considered PPI-refractory if it is verified that the medication is taken 20 to 30 minutes before meals. Once genuinely refractory disease is identified and diagnostic testing has confirmed GERD, these patients may be good candidates for ARS. Schwameis et al. studied 75 patients with PPI-refractory heartburn and found that all patients were satisfied with their symptom relief after laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication, including the 26 patients who had a poor response to PPI therapy. A randomized control trial in 2019 demonstrated that, in truly refractory disease, 67% of patients had symptomatic success after ARS. Since medical therapy is inadequate, patients with PPI-refractory confirmed GERD will have the highest chance of successful treatment with ARS. However, expectations should be set preoperatively, and patients should be informed that the outcomes are not as good as they are in patients with PPI-responsive disease.\n\n## Special GERD Patient Populations\n\nAfter confirming a GERD diagnosis, certain groups of patients should be excluded from ARS candidacy and be considered for alternative treatments. Here we will discuss those patients.\n\n### Obesity\n\nAs the obesity epidemic continues to grow, many patients suffer from both GERD and obesity. This clinical metabolic syndrome must be considered when discussing treatment options for GERD. While BMI between 30 and 35 remains controversial, patients with GERD and a BMI greater than 35 may be best served with a metabolic surgery such as a gastric bypass. This allows for the treatment of their greater clinical disease (metabolic syndrome) rather than treating their GERD in isolation. Additionally, offering ARS without treating obesity may result in poor outcomes. Refer to Chapter 17 , which specifically addresses the topic of obesity and GERD.\n\n### Scleroderma\n\nPatients with scleroderma suffer from a systemic severe smooth muscle disease that can affect esophageal motility. While there are small series studies suggesting the success of ARS in these patients with partial fundoplication, postoperative dysphagia is a large concern. Although the esophagus may not always be affected, careful evaluation of these patients must be performed prior to proceeding with ARS. Additionally, postoperative expectations should be clear to patients. Overall, these patients are likely poor candidates for ARS but should be considered on a case-by-case basis. Alternative options such as gastric bypass may be more favorable with scleroderma and reflux disease.\n\n### Functional Gastrointestinal Disorders\n\nIn patients who suffer from functional disorders such as irritable bowel syndrome or dyspepsia, caution must be taken when offering ARS. Objective testing must clearly demonstrate a diagnosis of GERD with correlation of symptoms. While these gastrointestinal disorders are not a contraindication to ARS, postoperative expectations must be clear. These include the possibility of persistent functional gastrointestinal symptoms as well as the risk of increased gas-bloat and flatulence symptoms after ARS.\n\n## Conclusions\n\nARS significantly improves the quality of life of patients suffering from GERD. However, patient selection is key to achieving optimal outcomes after ARS. There are many intricacies to patient selection, but providers should always start with an objective diagnosis of GERD. Every patient case is different, and the surgeon should be mindful of the individual clinical scenario to provide the patient with clear expectations for symptom relief and side effects after ARS. If appropriate workup and discussions are performed in a thoughtful and thorough manner, ARS is associated with very good outcomes and high patient satisfaction.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Charbel S., Khandwala F., Vaezi M.F.: The role of esophageal pH monitoring in symptomatic patients on PPI therapy . Am J Gastroenterol 2005; 100 (2): pp. 283-289.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Richter J.E.: Current diagnosis and management of suspected reflux symptoms refractory to proton pump inhibitor therapy . Gastroenterol Hepatol (N Y) 2014; 10 (9): pp. 547-555.\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: Campos G.M., Peters J.H., DeMeester T.R., et al.: Multivariate analysis of factors predicting outcome after laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication . J Gastrointest Surg 1999; 3 (3): pp. 292-300.\n\nView In Article\n\n4.: Tolone S., Gualtieri G., Savarino E., et al.: Pre-operative clinical and instrumental factors as antireflux surgery outcome predictors . World J Gastrointest Surg 2016; 8 (11): pp. 719-728.\n\nView In Article\n\n5.: Patel A., Sayuk G.S., Gyawali C.P.: Prevalence, characteristics, and treatment outcomes of reflux hypersensitivity detected on pH-impedance monitoring . Neuro Gastroenterol Motil 2016; 28 (9): pp. 1382-1390.\n\nView In Article\n\n6.: del Genio G., Tolone S., del Genio F., et al.: Prospective assessment of patient selection for antireflux surgery by combined multichannel intraluminal impedance pH monitoring . J Gastrointest Surg 2008; 12 (9): pp. 1491-1496.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n7.: Isolauri J., Luostarinen M., Isolauri E., Reinikainen P., Viljakka M., Keyril\u00e4inen O.: Natural course of gastroesophageal reflux disease: 17-22 year follow-up of 60 patients . Am J Gastroenterol 1997; 92 (1): pp. 37-41.\n\nView In Article\n\n8.: Laine S., Rantala A., Gullichsen R., Ovaska J.: Laparoscopic vs conventional Nissen fundoplication. A prospective randomized study . Surg Endosc 1997; 11 (5): pp. 441-444.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\