ule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[12. Delayed Gastric Emptying in Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease - ClinicalKey|12. Delayed Gastric Emptying in Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease]]\n**Next:** [[14. Management of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease With Esophageal Dysmotility, Scleroderma, and End-Stage Reflux - ClinicalKey|14. Management of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease With Esophageal Dysmotility, Scleroderma, and End-Stage Reflux]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "13. Patient Selection for Antireflux Surgery - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Patient Selection for Antireflux Surgery', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Patient Selection for Antireflux Surgery', 'Diagnostic Testing', 'Optimal Surgical Candidates', 'Special GERD Patient Populations', 'Objective Findings', 'Ambulatory pH Testing', 'Patient Selection for Antireflux Surgery / Diagnostic Testing', 'Patient Selection for Antireflux Surgery / Optimal Surgical Candidates', 'Patient Selection for Antireflux Surgery / Special GERD Patient Populations'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '13', '148-152', 2, 24, FALSE, TRUE),
('Management of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease With Esophageal Dysmotility, Scleroderma, and End-Stage Reflux', 'shackelford-9th-ed-14-management-of-gastroesophageal-reflux-disease-with-esophageal-dysmotility-scle', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Management of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease With Esophageal Dysmotility, Scleroderma, and End-Stage Reflux\n\nTheresa N. Wang; Kelly R. Haisley\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 14, 153-158\n\n## Introduction\n\nEsophageal dysmotility may be present in as many as 8.3% of patients with gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) and may present a significant challenge to surgeons. In the setting of reflux, years of increased acid and enzyme exposure in the esophagus, obstruction from hernias and strictures, or even a failed prior fundoplication can greatly deteriorate the peristaltic function of the esophageal body. A clear understanding of the pathophysiology of esophageal dysmotility and its effects on surgical outcomes is key in ruling out alternate diagnoses and planning an appropriate fundoplication to maximize reflux control while minimizing the risks of postoperative complications such as dysphagia. For patients with GERD with undiagnosed ineffective motility, or more severe disorders of motility such as scleroderma or \u201cend-stage\u201d esophagus, the implications of constructing an inappropriately tight flap valve can have devastating long-term effects. As such, properly assessing and accounting for esophageal dysmotility is key to assuring the best possible quality of life for patients undergoing antireflux surgery for GERD.\n\n## Esophageal Dysmotility in Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease\n\n### Clinical Presentation\n\nIn patients with GERD, by far the most common clinical symptom of an underlying motility disorder is the presence of clinical dysphagia (trouble swallowing or a sensation of food sticking). Patients may also present with less typical symptoms, such as throat clearing, halitosis, and globus sensation, or may simply complain of more traditional symptoms, such as severe heartburn and regurgitation as a result of their inability to clear refluxate from the esophagus once it occurs. Clinicians should carefully assess the symptom\u2019s progression over time, severity, and associated alarm signs (weight loss, progressive dysphagia) as part of initial information gathering. However, it is also important to recognize that dysphagia may be present in the setting of normal motility due to anatomic obstructions (hernias or strictures) and that some patients may have no clinical dysphagia despite underlying dysmotility. Given the wide array of possible clinical presentations, objective evaluation is very important in preoperative planning and symptoms alone are inadequate to diagnose a disorder of esophageal motility.\n\n### Causes of Esophageal Dysmotility in Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease\n\nIn the absence of a clear major disorder of peristalsis such as achalasia or scleroderma, the exact cause of impaired esophageal motility is not always clear. Importantly, dysphagia is considered a typical symptom of GERD that often responds to appropriate treatment. It is postulated that in the setting of longstanding GERD, chronic inflammation from increased acid exposure in the esophagus may lead to transmural inflammation that can affect both the contractile function of the smooth muscle of the esophagus and propagation of the peristaltic signal. It has been shown that motor abnormalities such as esophagogastric junction (EGJ) impairment and ineffective esophageal motility (IEM) are increasingly prevalent with increasing GERD severity (nonerosive-> erosive-> Barrett\u2019s) and with increased esophageal acid exposure duration and frequency on pH testing. As mucosal damage from GERD progresses, there is a decrease in the lower esophageal sphincter (LES) pressure, lower distal esophageal amplitude, and increase in the number and duration of reflux episodes.\n\nIn addition to direct damage from acid exposure, gastroduodenal contents (acid, pepsin, bile acids, trypsin) likely further damage the esophageal epithelium resulting in additional inflammatory-mediated injury in the submucosal layer. Furthermore, any process causing functional esophagogastric outflow obstruction (inflammation from esophagitis, strictures, Barrett\u2019s, hiatal hernias, previous fundoplication, etc.) can induce stasis-mediated inflammation or cause enough of resistance to flow to cause burnout of the esophagus over time as esophageal function deteriorates further or entirely.\n\n### Workup of Esophageal Motility in Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease\n\nWith the high prevalence and significant impact of dysmotility in GERD, all patients being considered for antireflux surgery should receive an appropriate motility assessment ahead of any planned operation. Although tests such as a barium radiograph can hint at a motility disorder by showing disorganized peristalsis, esophageal dilation, or delayed emptying, the gold standard for evaluation of esophageal function is through high-resolution manometry (HRM) with motility classification through the Chicago 4.0 schema. This exam uses catheter-based pressure and impedance measurements to provide information on peristaltic function, dynamic wave formation, sphincter relaxation, and bolus clearance, among other parameters. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Please see Chapter 2 , Chapter 4 for more information.\n\nUsing data collected from HRM, the Chicago 4.0 classification system divides esophageal dysmotility into categories based broadly on disorders of EGJ function (achalasia and EGJ outflow obstruction \\[EGJOO\\]) and disorders of esophageal body peristalsis (IEM/absent esophageal motility, distal esophageal spasm, hypercontractile/Jackhammer esophagus). Each of these clinical entities has specific implications for surgeons, and it is important to rule out one of these major disorders of peristalsis in the workup for GERD.\n\nIn addition to HRM, it is important to fully rule out any alternate diagnoses that might be causing symptoms or signs of esophageal dysfunction and a standard comprehensive reflux workup should be completed. In addition to objective pH testing to confirm the diagnosis of GERD, a barium esophagram is helpful to assess for bolus clearance, reflux, hiatal hernia, mechanical obstruction, and esophageal size and shape. Upper endoscopy is utilized to assess for stricture, mass, hiatal hernia, and mucosal changes such as Barrett\u2019s esophagus or esophagitis. Once a full understanding of a patient\u2019s particular combination of disease-specific metrics is clarified, an appropriate treatment plan can be constructed.\n\n## Management of GERD in the Setting of Esophageal Dysmotility\n\nIt is important to understand that GERD may coexist with a disorder of esophageal body peristalsis, but that each is a distinct clinical entity and the diagnosis of one does not necessarily confirm or preclude the other and both must be considered in making a therapeutic plan.\n\nIt is valuable to stress here that achalasia is a distinct clinical entity from GERD and their diagnoses are mutually exclusive. Due to the presence of similar symptoms such as chest pain and regurgitation, achalasia is frequently clinically mistaken for GERD. Objective testing with HRM and pH studies can easily differentiate these two issues, and achalasia should always be ruled out before proceeding with a traditional antireflux intervention, particularly when dysmotility is suspected.\n\n### GERD and Hypercontractile Esophagus (Diffuse Esophageal Spasm and Jackhammer)\n\nHypercontractile disorders of the esophagus are less common in the setting of GERD; however, it is possible to see these motility patterns emerge in the setting of reflux as a result of the esophagus attempting to overcome a functional or anatomic obstruction from inflammation, stricture, or a hernia. Although both jackhammer esophagus (a hypercontractile, peristaltic contraction) and diffuse esophageal spasm (a hypercontractile, spastic contraction) are often first managed through medical therapy, there are scenarios in which surgery may be necessary to consider, particularly when uncontrolled GERD is also present or the disease is refractory to medical therapy.\n\nIf the patient does have objectively documented GERD and they have a hyperperistaltic esophagus (jackhammer), it is reasonable to consider traditional fundoplication as the esophageal body has both preserved strength and coordination. In these patients, Nissen fundoplication has still been associated with improvement in both GERD symptoms and normalization of the esophageal motility parameters.\n\nIn the case of diffuse or distal esophageal spasm, careful counseling is important, as the disordered peristalsis that is characteristic of esophageal spasm may predispose the patient to a higher risk of postoperative dysphagia, and any pain related to esophageal spasticity may persist despite antireflux surgery, making medication management the first line of therapy. When refractory, some authors have supported an extended esophageal myotomy (endoscopic or laparoscopic) through the spastic segment of the distal esophagus paired with a partial fundoplication. The major drawback of this approach is that it increases the chance of postoperative GERD through destruction of the LES and is associated with high rates of dysphagia as the myotomized portion of the esophagus becomes permanently aperistaltic, which may lead to worse quality of life outcomes overall.\n\n### Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and Esophagogastric Junction Outflow Obstruction\n\nEGJOO involves impaired relaxation of the EGJ with a characteristic finding of an elevated integrated relaxation pressure (IRP) on HRM, but with preserved esophageal peristalsis. There is mixed data on the clinical significance of a manometric finding of EGJOO in the setting of GERD. Impaired relaxation in the LES leading to an increase in the IRP can occur as a result of inflammation at or near the LES from esophagitis due to reflux. Whether this represents a transient phenomenon from inflammation alone that will resolve with fundoplication alone, or if it is more of a reflection of EGJ permanent dysfunction related to fibrosis or denervation is not entirely clear.\n\nEndoscopic dilation, botulinum toxin injection, per-oral endoscopic myotomy (POEM), and Heller myotomy have all been utilized in the management of EGJOO, though this must be balanced with the risk of worsening reflux if GERD is in fact the primary diagnosis. In the setting of EGJOO, some authors have shown good outcomes with a myotomy with fundoplication. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Others have advocated that a simple fundoplication without any myotomy is safe and adequate. Current data suggest that either approach is acceptable barring any other clear explanation for the EGJOO apart from reflux. Again, it must be considered that the risk of a myotomy in the setting of GERD may predispose to increased rates of recurrent reflux and thus surgical decision-making should be targeted by the patient\u2019s primary symptoms and therapeutic goals.\n\n### Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and Ineffective Esophageal Motility\n\nThe most common pattern of dysmotility seen in patients with GERD is IEM. This is defined as either a decreased distal contractile integral (<450 mmHg) or a high rate of failed peristalsis (>50%). While several studies have shown that manometric findings are not perfectly predictive of postoperative dysphagia, it is important to understand the contribution, if any, that impaired peristalsis plays in symptom generation. Ultimately, tailoring a fundoplication to manometric and clinical data would ideally strike the balance between reflux control and postoperative side effects, allowing for optimal patient outcomes.\n\nThere is mixed data on whether fundoplication type needs to be tailored (partial vs. complete) based on the presence of IEM, particularly as the exact degree of motility impairment may vary between patients (minor to near aperistaltic) and measurements may be affected by the patient\u2019s ability to tolerate the test or the degree of active inflammation at the time of the exam. There is no strong data showing that any single measurement on HRM, including distal contractile integral, percent peristalsis, or overall classification, is directly correlated with postoperative dysphagia or that this outcome can be actively prevented with partial fundoplication.\n\nMultiple retrospective studies do support performing a partial fundoplication in patients with esophageal motility disorders and GERD, with data suggesting that partial fundoplication (Toupet) has better outcomes than complete fundoplication (Nissen) regardless of esophageal motility. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The largest randomized control trials of Toupet versus Nissen fundoplication both generally and in the setting of esophageal dysmotility have noted excellent outcomes with both procedures but fewer unwanted functional symptoms such as dysphagia or gas bloat in Toupet fundoplication in the early postoperative period.\n\nOther data have shown that Toupet and Nissen fundoplication achieve similar results regardless of esophageal manometry <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> and that patients with persistent heartburn despite medical therapy have high treatment success with either approach. There are comparable rates of postoperative dysphagia overall, and no differences have been found in postoperative esophagitis between types of fundoplication so far. Furthermore, a slight preference has been shown for Nissen for better reflux control.\n\nThe mixed data regarding partial versus complete fundoplication in the setting of esophageal dysmotility precludes consensus over firm indications for tailoring operations based on HRM alone. Ultimately, rather than relying solely on manometric parameters, tailoring a partial versus complete fundoplication should involve a clear discussion of the patients\u2019 specific preoperative symptoms and their goals of therapy, with a discussion of the potential trade-off of recurrent reflux symptoms versus risk of dysphagia. This decision remains at the discretion of the operating surgeon but overall favors partial fundoplication in cases of ineffective motility.\n\n## Scleroderma Esophagus\n\n### Pathophysiology\n\nSystemic sclerosis is a chronic autoimmune disease involving proliferative vascular lesions which cause fibrosis of the skin and multiple organs, including the gastrointestinal tract. It most frequently presents in women aged between 35 and 65 with an incidence of 0.3\u20132.8 per 100,000 per year. Systemic sclerosis can occur in the absence of cutaneous involvement and may include esophageal dysmotility, inflammatory polyarthritis, interstitial lung disease, renal insufficiency, myocardial fibrosis, and other gastrointestinal manifestations. The most common systemic visceral manifestations are esophageal involvement, followed by pulmonary involvement. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The pathophysiology of gastrointestinal tract sclerosis, and specifically esophageal sclerosis, is hypothesized to be due to recurrent vasoconstriction\u2013reperfusion episodes resulting in ischemia and fibrosis. Up to 70% of patients with scleroderma have involvement of the esophagus, with the replacement of muscles by fibrous tissue and dysfunction of cholinergic nerves. The esophagus frequently becomes shortened due to fibrosis, resulting in a hiatal hernia.\n\n### Clinical Presentation\n\nEsophageal involvement in scleroderma can present with debilitating GERD symptoms, dysphagia, and reflux esophagitis. Symptoms are exacerbated by autonomic nerve dysfunction, gastroparesis and other gastrointestinal dysmotility, and the frequent coexistence of sicca syndrome (characterized by absent or ineffective saliva production).\n\n### Diagnosis\n\nOn manometry, scleroderma esophagus has a dysmotility pattern with hypotensive LES and entirely absent esophageal contractions ( Fig. 14.1 ). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Complications of GERD are common in scleroderma, such as erosive esophagitis, peptic strictures, and Barrett\u2019s esophagus due to both the severely weakened LES leading to high levels of reflux, as well as the esophageal aperistalsis creating an inability to clear any caustic substances trapped within the esophagus.\n\nA manometry graph displays pressure measurements along the esophagus. The manometry graph displays an esophageal manometry graph, which measures the pressure along the Esophagus throughout a gulp test. The left side of the graph features a color scale that ranges from negative 10 millimeters of mercury to 150 millimeters of mercury, with higher pressures and lower pressures marked in different colors. On the right side, the Esophagus is marked with specific anatomical regions and pressure values. The Pharynx is labeled at 19 point 0 centimeters with a pressure of 22 point 0 millimeters of mercury, followed by the Esophagus at 46 point 3 centimeters with a pressure of 46 point 3 millimeters. The Lower Esophageal Sphincter is labeled at 48 point 8 centimeters with a pressure of 49 point 3 millimeters of mercury. Just below that, the Gastric area is labeled at 53 point 5 centimeters with a pressure of 53 point 5 millimeters of mercury.\n\nFig. 14.1\n\nThe formal diagnosis of systemic sclerosis is made through a combination of physical exam (modified Rodnan skin score) and laboratory markers (antinuclear antibodies \\[ANAs\\], and specific antigens in systemic sclerosis: centromere, topoisomerase-1, RNA polymerase III, exosomal ribonuclear protein \\[PM/Scl\\], and uridine-rich small nuclear ribonuclear protein \\[U1-snRNP\\]). Patients with esophageal dysmotility patterns suspicious for scleroderma esophagus should be referred to rheumatology for further evaluation and management prior to moving ahead with any antireflux interventions.\n\n### Treatment of Scleroderma\n\nThe treatment of esophageal dysfunction in patients with scleroderma is typically medical. Proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) and other acid-suppressing medications in combination with lifestyle modification to reduce GERD symptoms can be relatively effective with minimal adverse effects. The symptoms of dysphagia may be more difficult to manage. Promotility agents, laxatives, and antibiotics to reduce bacterial overgrowth have been used with variable efficacy. Unfortunately, although systemic treatment of scleroderma may delay progression of the disease, it does not reverse the end-organ dysfunction.\n\n### Surgical Considerations in Scleroderma\n\nIn most cases, surgery should be avoided in patients with scleroderma because of the poor prospects for functional improvement and high risk of impaired wound healing and poor functional outcomes. Patients with severe symptoms refractory to medical therapy and those with severe complications of GERD (such as undilatable stricture, recurrent aspiration from regurgitation, or esophageal erosion) may benefit from carefully planned surgery. Options in these unique cases include partial fundoplication, gastric resection with Roux-en-Y reconstruction, and esophageal replacement.\n\nIt is important to note that the few series that have looked at the outcome of antireflux surgery in patients with scleroderma have shown variable results and that complete fundoplication is contraindicated in these cases. Patients with scleroderma esophagus who underwent even partial fundoplication have been reported to have return of reflux symptoms in 50%\u201370% of cases, <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> postoperative dysphagia in 30%\u201370% of patients, and frequent recurrence of reflux esophagitis despite antireflux operations. There are small case series with Dor and Toupet fundoplication in patients with scleroderma esophagus with symptomatic improvement, though further evidence is necessary to determine efficacy and side effects. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Another very important consideration is the difficulty in achieving an adequate length of intraabdominal esophagus in the setting of severe fibrosis, which may be impossible. If this is the case, a Collis gastroplasty may need to be performed which creates an additional length of aperistaltic neo-esophagus that contributes to high rates of postoperative dysphagia. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nIn advanced cases where fundoplication is expected to cause prohibitive dysphagia, Roux-en-Y gastric bypass (RYGB) can be performed as an antireflux procedure in scleroderma esophagus if nutritional status is otherwise appropriate. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The benefit of this approach is that there is little to no resistance at the gastroesophageal junction, reducing the risk of postoperative dysphagia. This approach also does significantly reduce rates of acid reflux, but recurrent reflux symptoms still occur in up to 30% of patients. Small series have shown superiority in the RYGB as the operation of choice for scleroderma compared with traditional fundoplication given improvement in reflux symptoms, dysphagia, and overall quality of life in patients undergoing Roux-en-Y reconstruction as opposed to traditional fundoplication with slightly decreased rates of bloating and diarrhea.\n\n## \u201cEnd-Stage\u201d Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease\n\nEnd-stage GERD is the result of longstanding medically refractory GERD or extreme dysmotility (including late stage scleroderma) over a long duration, resulting in progressive severe esophageal dysmotility, loss of function, anatomic distortion (tortuous \u201csigmoid\u201d esophagus \\[Fig. 14.2 \\], or megaesophagus \\[>6 cm\\]), and persistent symptoms. Since the 1990s, the widespread application of PPIs has decreased the number of patients presenting with this degree of damage from primary GERD alone. However, in rare cases, previously failed fundoplication, intractable esophagitis, long-segment or undilatable strictures, ulceration, or fistula may ultimately create a situation in which the disease is so severe that it is unlikely to respond to traditional interventions. In these unique scenarios, esophageal replacement (esophagectomy) may need to be considered. Esophagectomy is a last resort in the setting of benign disease when the esophagus has become non-functional and causes persistent symptoms; it should be reserved for only those situations in which no other options exist, as morbidity and mortality of the procedure can be high.\n\nA medical radiography view of the human chest and upper abdomen, with some visible areas of the esophagus and other structures. #REF!\n\nFig. 14.2\n\n## Conclusion\n\nEsophageal motility should be carefully assessed prior to consideration of operative intervention in GERD. GERD and other systemic diseases such as scleroderma can cause primary dysmotility, or a cycle of inflammation and progressive dysfunction ultimately leading to end-stage esophagus. Understanding the pathophysiology of this process and important effects of esophageal motility is a critical component in operative planning and preoperative patient counseling.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Galindo G., Vassalle J., Marcus S.N., Triadafilopoulos G.: Multimodality evaluation of patients with gastroesophageal reflux disease symptoms who have failed empiric proton pump inhibitor therapy . Dis Esophagus Off J Int Soc Dis Esophagus 2013; 26 (5): pp. 443-450.\n\nView In Article\n\n2.: Meneghetti A.T., Tedesco P., Damani T., Patti M.G.: Esophageal mucosal damage may promote dysmotility and worsen esophageal acid exposure . J Gastrointest Surg Off J Soc Surg Aliment Tract 2005; 9 (9): pp. 1313-1317.\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: Savarino E., Giacchino M., Savarino V.: Dysmotility and reflux disease . Curr Opin Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg 2013; 21 (6): pp. 548-556.\n\nView In Article\n\n4.: Jiang L.Q., Ye B.X., Wang M.F., Lin L.: Acid exposure in patients with gastroesophageal reflux disease is associated with esophageal dysmotility . J Dig Dis 2019; 20 (2): pp. 73-77.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: Mittal R., Vaezi M.F.: Esophageal motility disorders and gastroesophageal reflux disease. Longo DL, ed . N Engl J Med 2020; 383 (20): pp. 1961-1972.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n6.: Yadlapati R., Kahrilas P.J., Fox M.R., et al.: Esophageal motility disorders on high-resolution manometry: Chicago classification version 4.0 . Neurogastroenterol Motil 2021; 33 (1):\n\nView In Article\n\n7.: Gyawali C.P.: High resolution manometry: the Ray Clouse legacy . Neurogastroenterol Motil 2012; 24 (s1): pp. 2-4.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n8.: Castell D.O.: Emerging technologies for esophageal manometry and pH monitoring . Gastroenterol Hepatol 2008; 4 (6): pp. 404-406.\n\nView In Article\n\n9.: Crespin O.M., Tatum R.P., Yates R.B., et al.: Esophageal hypermotility: cause or effect? . Dis Esophagus Off J Int Soc Dis Esophagus 2016; 29 (5): pp. 497-502.\n\nView In Article\n\n10.: Henderson R.D., Ryder D., Marryatt G.: Extended esophageal myotomy and short total fundoplication hernia repair in diffuse esophageal spasm: five-year review in 34 patients . Ann Thorac Surg 1987; 43 (1): pp. 25-31.\n\nView In Article\n\n11.: Achem S.R., Gerson L.B.: Distal esophageal spasm: an update . Curr Gastroenterol Rep 2013; 15 (9): pp. 325.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n12.: Liu-Burdowski J., Duarte-Chavez R., Kahaleh M.: Per-oral endoscopic myotomy: State of the art . J Clin Gastroenterol 2022; 56 (1): pp. 16-22.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n13.: Khan M.A., Kumbhari V., Ngamruengphong S., et al.: Is POEM the answer for management of spastic esophagea