-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n\n\nNeed help? Chat with AI Buddy!\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[14. Management of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease With Esophageal Dysmotility, Scleroderma, and End-Stage Reflux - ClinicalKey|14. Management of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease With Esophageal Dysmotility, Scleroderma, and End-Stage Reflux]]\n**Next:** [[16. Management of Failed Antireflux Procedures - ClinicalKey|16. Management of Failed Antireflux Procedures]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "15. The Role of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease in Pulmonary Disease - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'The Role of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease in Pulmonary Disease', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'The Role of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease in Pulmonary Disease', 'Role of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease in Chronic Cough', 'Laryngopharyngeal Reflux', 'Role of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease in Asthma and Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease', 'Role of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease in Bronchiectasis', 'Role of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease in Interstitial Lung Disease', 'The Role of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease in Pulmonary Disease / Role of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease in Chronic Cough', 'The Role of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease in Pulmonary Disease / Laryngopharyngeal Reflux', 'The Role of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease in Pulmonary Disease / Role of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease in Asthma and Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '15', '159-165', 2, 39, FALSE, TRUE),
('Management of Failed Antireflux Procedures', 'shackelford-9th-ed-16-management-of-failed-antireflux-procedures', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Management of Failed Antireflux Procedures\n\nLuigi Bonavina\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 16, 166-171\n\nRevisional surgery for gastroesophageal reflux or de novo postfundoplication symptoms represents a technical challenge and is associated with the risk of operative complications and further recurrence. Therefore patient care must be personalized based on symptoms and objective anatomical and physiological assessment.\n\nLaparoscopic Nissen fundoplication was introduced in 1991 and has since then become the standard approach for surgical therapy of gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) and hiatal hernia (HH). Variations of the 360-degree fundoplication, including the 270-degree posterior Toupet fundoplication and the 180-degree anterior Dor fundoplication, are also commonly performed. Although it is claimed that 90% of patients have durable symptom relief after primary laparoscopic fundoplication, real-world data show that up to 30% experience persistent, recurrent, or de novo symptoms that can be managed medically, and up to 10% to 17% of patients will ultimately require reoperation. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Failures of primary fundoplication increase in incidence over time, usually a decade or more later. In two-thirds of patients presenting for reoperation, the major complaints are recurrent heartburn or regurgitation. Other symptoms, alone or in combination, include dysphagia, gas bloat, epigastric/chest pain, laryngopharyngeal complaints, chronic cough, and asthma.\n\nHH is the most common cause of failure of the index fundoplication. This explains why more emphasis has recently been placed on concomitant crural repair. In fact, both the fundoplication and the cruroplasty are implicated in the restoration of the antireflux barrier and have a role in preventing surgical failures. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n## Reasons for Failure of Antireflux Repairs\n\nTo minimize failures of primary antireflux surgery and to improve the outcomes of revisional procedures, deep understanding of pathophysiology, standardization of surgical techniques, and ability to adapt to the complexity of individual clinical and anatomical presentations are necessary. Failure of laparoscopic antireflux surgery can be defined as a spectrum of postoperative conditions characterized by lack of reflux symptom control or de novo symptoms such as dysphagia and bloating. All these symptoms may have a significant negative impact on the patient\u2019s quality of life. Symptom persistence or recurrence does not always reflect failure of the index operation and thus requires both subjective and objective testing. Understanding the reasons for failure is important to put the symptoms and signs of recurrent GERD/HH into context and to determine the most appropriate therapeutic strategy. In fact, the majority of anatomical recurrences after paraesophageal hernia repair are rather small and minimally symptomatic or asymptomatic and do not require reoperation.\n\nAntireflux operations may fail because of inadequate preoperative assessment, poor judgment in planning a personalized surgical treatment, technical errors that lead to a malfunctioning wrap, and/or defective crural repair. Early failures can also occur as a result of sentinel events such as postoperative coughing or retching, heavy lifting, abdominal straining or trauma, all causing abrupt rises in intraabdominal pressure. The ideal candidate for a primary antireflux repair is a nonobese individual with typical GERD symptoms at least partially responsive to proton pump inhibitors (PPIs), documented abnormal esophageal acid exposure with positive correlation between symptoms and reflux episodes on prolonged pH monitoring, and relatively preserved esophageal peristalsis. Patients with atypical presentations, such as chest pain, chronic cough, asthma, and pharyngoesophageal complaints, and concomitant esophageal motility disorders and/or nonacid reflux, have inferior outcomes following fundoplication. Advanced age, female gender, and the presence of a large HH have also been identified as potential risk factors for failure. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n## Prevention of Surgical Failures\n\nIntrathoracic slippage, usually attributed to the presence of axial or radial tension, accounts for more than half of the fundoplication failures. Foreshortening of the esophagus causes axial tension, and the combination of both axial and radial forces leads to diaphragmatic breakdown and reherniation. In the immediate postoperative period, this creates an iatrogenic incarcerated HH with risk of acute gastric ischemia and necrosis. To reduce recurrence rates, tension along these force vectors must be minimized, and a 3-cm tension-free segment of distal esophagus should be reduced in the abdominal cavity to prevent mediastinal migration of the esophagogastric junction and the fundoplication. During dissection, both vagal nerves should be respected to prevent delayed gastric emptying that may contribute to postoperative symptoms of postprandial epigastric fullness, gas bloat syndrome, or diarrhea.\n\nThe diaphragmatic crura should be approximated with permanent sutures, and a tension-free and symmetric \u201cfloppy\u201d fundoplication wrap should then be constructed and secured to the esophagus. Technical variations exist with regard to the type of fundoplication performed, the need for division of the short gastric vessels, and the use of a bioprosthetic mesh to augment the hiatus. Migration of fundoplication wrap is the most common anatomic defect encountered at the time of reoperation, occurring in approximately two-thirds of patients. Several patterns of wrap migration can be identified, including transhiatal herniation of an intact wrap into the mediastinum or herniation of the proximal stomach through the wrap into a supra- or infra-diaphragmatic position (\u201cslipped\u201d Nissen). Other technical problems encountered at reoperation include a tight crural closure or a wrap that is too tight or too long, a malpositioned or twisted wrap, or a complete wrap disruption.\n\nUpfront mediastinal dissection and restoration of the intraabdominal esophagus remain key factors for the success of antireflux surgery, and failure to recognize or address a shortened esophagus can cause recurrent transhiatal hernia. Inability to create sufficient intraabdominal esophagus despite an extensive mediastinal dissection should be addressed with a Collis gastroplasty.\n\n## Approach to Patients With Failed Antireflux Surgery\n\nPatients with recurrent or new symptoms after antireflux surgery may present after years of marginally beneficial medical therapy when symptoms and secondary sequelae of previous surgery may be quite advanced. When available, patient\u2019s preoperative studies and the operative report should be carefully reviewed, and attention should be paid to differences between the patient\u2019s previous symptoms and their current symptom complex. For example, dysphagia that was present prior to the index operation and still persists may indicate a different etiology of failure than dysphagia that developed after fundoplication, persists after 3 months, and does not resolve with pneumatic dilation.\n\nThe standard preoperative workup includes medical history with disease-specific questionnaires. Somatoform disorders should be ruled out, and it is mandatory to obtain objective data before proceeding with a reoperation. Although symptoms and objective findings are imperfectly correlated, upper gastrointestinal contrast imaging, endoscopy, high-resolution manometry, and pH-metry/multichannel intraluminal impedance (MII) testing guide surgical decision making and provide a baseline against which the outcome of reoperation may be measured.\n\nContrast imaging, traditionally a dynamic barium swallowing study, should be the first-line investigation in all patients with persistent or de novo symptoms after previous antireflux surgery. An intact and well-situated fundoplication appears as a filling defect of the gastric fundus that is smooth in contour. A barium swallow in a patient with recurrent symptoms may demonstrate HH, slipped Nissen with \u201chour-glass\u201d stomach, gastroesophageal reflux, or delayed esophageal/gastric emptying ( Fig. 16.1 ). It may also show that the wrap is too tight, too long, or disrupted, or that the distal esophagus is angulated by a too tight posterior crural repair.\n\nA photo of wrap identification in the esophagogram. The photo captures the closer view of the wrap when it is exposed by surgical instruments. The wrap in the left inferior phrenic artery is similar to the hour glass pattern.\n\nFig. 16.1\n\nUpper gastrointestinal endoscopy is necessary to assess the degree of esophagitis and patency of the esophageal lumen, and exclude Barrett\u2019s esophagus or adenocarcinoma. The presence of erosive esophagitis when off PPI therapy may be sufficient to establish a diagnosis of recurrent GERD without the need for pH monitoring. Endoscopy is also important to assess the axial extent of HH (distance between the Z-line and crura impression) and the morphology of the gastroesophageal flap valve according to the American Foregut Society classification.\n\nThe main role of esophageal manometry prior to revisional antireflux surgery is to exclude achalasia. While several studies have shown that ineffective esophageal motility is not predictive of postoperative dysphagia, it is important to understand the contribution, if any, that impaired peristalsis may play in symptom generation.\n\nEsophageal pH testing may be done with a transnasal catheter or a wireless implantable system (Bravo). Establishing the presence of abnormal esophageal acid exposure and symptom correlation clarifies that recurrent reflux is at least part of the patient\u2019s problem. In patients whose sole postfundoplication complaint is dysphagia and who have a slipped fundoplication identified on barium swallow, esophageal pH monitoring is unnecessary.\n\nMII can document both acid and nonacid reflux, as well as bolus transit in the esophagus. Coupled with manometry, MII can establish the presence of ineffective peristalsis and is indicated for patients in whom symptoms strongly suggest reflux or dysmotility, but objective findings on pH studies or manometry are discordant.\n\nScintigraphic gastric emptying studies are indicated in patients whose predominant symptoms are epigastric fullness and bloating. Delayed gastric emptying may confound a diagnosis of failed fundoplication and change the reoperative strategy. Computed tomography scans may have a role in patients with recurrent large paraesophageal hernias or when permanent prosthetic material has been used at index operation. In complex revisional operations, in which esophagectomy with colon interposition is considered, colonoscopy and mesenteric angiography are an important part of the preoperative evaluation to exclude pathology of the large bowel and to confirm continuity of the marginal artery and the presence of a late-branching middle colic artery.\n\n## Choice of the Remedial Surgical Procedure\n\nThe threshold to perform reoperative surgery should be somewhat higher than for primary operations. Patients whose original fundoplication has loosened over time and who complain primarily of heartburn that can be effectively managed with intermittent and low-dose PPI therapy should avoid the risks associated with a reoperation. Some of these patients, however, may ultimately opt to have a redo fundoplication because they felt better with a functional fundoplication than they do on medical therapy, especially if the predominant symptom is regurgitation. If they are not obese and their esophageal motility is reasonably well preserved, they should be offered surgery. Also, patients with a slipped fundoplication rarely achieve symptom relief with medical therapy alone because the fundus becomes a reservoir of acid and reflux occurs through the incompetent sphincter. Even if acid is suppressed by PPI, duodenogastroesophageal reflux may cause severe symptoms and complications especially in the setting of a prior cholecystectomy.\n\nThe choice of which operation to perform is dictated by the patient\u2019s symptoms and objective findings, body mass index (BMI), number of prior operations, and anatomy. The majority of patients can be helped by laparoscopic revision of the prior fundoplication. However, patients with BMI \u226535 and those who have had multiple prior fundoplications with severe dysmotility or with iatrogenic gastroparesis are more likely to be helped by Roux-en-Y gastric bypass or a subtotal gastrectomy. Esophagojejunostomy or esophageal resection with conduit replacement may be required in patients who had previous implant of permanent mesh at the hiatus.\n\n## Redo Crural Repair and Fundoplication\n\nBased on compelling evidence that both the diaphragmatic crura and the fundoplication equally contribute to the esophagogastric junction competency, the current standard of care in patients with symptomatic recurrence after failed antireflux surgery consists of redo cruroplasty and revisional fundoplication. Reported outcomes vary widely and have been traditionally considered less satisfactory compared to primary surgery. Reoperative surgery can be technically demanding and associated with longer operative times and more frequent conversions to an open approach. More recent data show that laparoscopic revisional surgery for recurrent HH is safe, feasible, and effective when performed in experienced centers. A meta-analysis suggests that laparoscopic revisional surgery can be performed with low conversion rates, acceptable morbidity, 78.5% symptom and quality of life improvement, and 10.7% recurrence rate. Large series have demonstrated that patient satisfaction and objective measures of acid reduction in patients undergoing a first revision fundoplication are similar to those obtained after primary antireflux surgery. Dysphagia, esophageal dysmotility, HH, obesity, and short esophagus have been identified as risk factors for failure after first-time redo fundoplication. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The ideal patient for revisional fundoplication is one who has had a single attempt at an antireflux procedure and now presents with recurrent reflux that can be attributed to a technical failure associated with the index operation. Patients presenting after two or more failed fundoplications may have worse outcomes after redo fundoplication. The risk associated with the operation is also substantially increased, and damage incurred by the stomach and esophagus limits attempts at redo fundoplication.\n\nRevisional fundoplication should follow the same technical principles and steps as a primary fundoplication: restoration of intraabdominal esophagus, approximation of the diaphragmatic hiatus, and proper construction of a partial or complete fundoplication. Occasionally, depending on the overall anatomical status at reoperation, a normal appearing fundoplication can be repositioned in the abdomen and left intact after performing an appropriate crural repair. Generally, the pneumoperitoneum is induced with a Veress needle in an area remote from previous incisions and a 12-mm optical trocar is used to enter the abdominal cavity. Correctly identifying the anatomy during redo fundoplication is challenging because scar and distortion from prior surgery can be misleading ( Figs. 16.2 and 16.3 ). The initial part of the operation consists of adhesiolysis and routine takedown of the original wrap when necessary. Extensive mediastinal dissection is required to achieve a 3-cm tension-free segment of distal esophagus. The angle of His is identified and cleaned from lipoma and residual hernia sac. Care is taken to recognize and preserve at a minimum the posterior vagus nerve. A posterior or combined left-lateral cruroplasty is routinely performed using interrupted nonabsorbable stitches. Lowering the pneumoperitoneum to 8 mmHg may help to reduce tension on the hiatus and assist in the recruitment of the left crus. For patients with significant dysmotility, a Toupet rather than a complete fundoplication is recommended.\n\nA photo shows a caudate lobe of a liver. The photo presents the caudal view of the liver, with labels pointing to the caudate lobe and right crus. The liver specimen has been sectioned to reveal the internal anatomy, with labels indicating the caudate lobe and right crus. These views help illustrate the structure of the liver and its key anatomical components.\n\nFig. 16.2\n\nA computed tomography scan of a hiatal hernia with altered anatomy. The computed tomography scan depicts a diaphragmatic hernia. Arrows point to an hourglass-shaped herniation through the hiatus of the diaphragm, a herniated wrap, the hernia''s location, and an hourglass pattern through the hiatus.\n\nFig. 16.3\n\nAdvances in laparoscopy have largely overcome the need for a thoracotomy to achieve adequate exposure to the mid- and distal esophagus during first-time redo operations. The utility of Collis gastroplasty, hiatal mesh augmentation, diaphragm relaxing incisions, and gastropexy remain controversial, and only a limited number of studies have analyzed the indications and outcomes of these procedures at the time of revisional surgery. Due to the unknown prevalence and the lack of a universally accepted definition of short esophagus, the Collis gastroplasty is largely underused, though it has been revisited and simplified with the development of laparoscopic surgery. In some circumstances, when the length of the intraabdominal esophagus is judged inadequate (<2.5 cm with desufflated pneumoperitoneum) despite extensive mediastinal dissection, a stapled Collis gastroplasty with wedge fundectomy is performed to create a 3-cm neoesophagus. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> To reduce tension at the hiatus, special attention should be paid to approximate not only the posterior but also the anterior and left-lateral crura, which is the most frequent site of reherniation. A biosynthetic mesh implanted over the approximated crura and fixed with a few nonabsorbable sutures can provide a temporary scaffold for ingrowth of native tissue and collagen deposition, being completely reabsorbed in 6 to 18 months, and may reduce early recurrences.\n\n### Reoperation After Failure of the Magnetic Sphincter Augmentation (MSA) Procedure (LINX)\n\nExplantation of the Linx device may be required in up 9% of patients due to recurrent reflux/HH, persistent dysphagia, or endoluminal erosion. MSA generates inflammation and fibrosis around the esophagogastric junction that may decrease tissue compliance and lead to persistent dysphagia in up to 15% of the patients. Reoperation in MSA patients can be done laparoscopically and appears to be a safe procedure. Once the fibrous band corresponding to the site of the Linx implant is identified, a monopolar electrocautery hook is used to cut through the fibrotic capsule and to expose the anterior titanium beads. The wire connecting the beads is cut with ultrasonic scissors, and the device is grasped and retracted upward. This allows step by step cutting of the fibrous tissue overlying each bead and pulling out of the device. Once the total bead count in the explanted device is confirmed, the Linx is removed through the port site. Intraoperative endoscopic assistance helps to check the integrity of the esophageal mucosa during and after removal and/or to assist during retrieval of the beads migrated into the esophageal lumen. A concurrent partial fundoplication is performed when the Linx is removed for ongoing reflux, but may not be necessary when no recurrent HH is found.\n\n### Reoperation After Failure of Transoral Incisionless Fundoplication\n\nFailures of transoral incisionless fundoplication (TIF) are secondary to technical or anatomical factors and are commonly associated with iatrogenic bleeding/perforation or untreated/recurrent HH. Disrupted fasteners and a poorly constructed gastroesophageal valve are often reported as the primary mechanism of technical failure. Recommended laparoscopic revisional surgery for a failed TIF is a crural repair combined with fundoplication. Often, the left crus is included in the T-fasteners, which should be cut and left to fall in the visceral lumen rather than pulled out to avoid transmural injury. In case the fundus is fused with the esophageal wall, it is wise to roll the gastric wall over and perform a Toupet fundoplication instead of a Nissen to prevent twisting of the wrap and possible postoperative dysphagia.\n\n## Roux-en-Y Gastric Bypass or Gastrectomy\n\nRoux-en-Y reconstruction has been recommended as the preferred approach to the patient with morbid obesity and/or failure of multiple prior fundoplications. It is well established that Roux-en-Y gastric bypass is the optimal primary antireflux operation for patients with GERD and severe obesity. A Roux limb of at least 100 cm prevents reflux of biliopancreatic secretions into the small gastric pouch and into the esophagus and facilitates weight loss, which in turn decreases intraabdominal pressure and reflux. In patients with obesity and a prior failed fundoplication, Roux-en-Y gastrojejunostomy has proven superior to revision fundoplication for reflux suppression. About 80% of these patients are pleased with the result of their operation, despite a higher incidence of postoperative complications and a 5% HH rate. These results have led surgeons to extend the indications of Roux-en-Y gastric bypass to patients with BMI 30 to 35 and a prior failed fundoplication. However, this enthusiasm should be tempered by the fact that an unbuffered layer of acid distal to the esophagogastric junction (\u201cacid pocket\u201d) may persist in 20% of these patients and that dysmotility of the jejunal limb may cause weakly acidic reflux. Lengthening the Roux limb to 150 cm may provide some benefit in these cases.\n\nThe potential advantage of Roux-en-Y reconstruction in patients who are otherwise candidates for revisional fundoplication remains debatable due to the lack of comparative studies and inadequate long-term follow-up. Roux-en-Y reconstruction deprives the patient of the reservoir function of the stomach, which may be an advantage in patients with delayed gastric emptying, but in others it may lead to poor oral intake and early satiety particularly when an esophagojejunostomy is required. Roux-en-Y gastric bypass is also known to expose patients to the life-long consequences of malabsorption and nutritional deficiencies. Lastly, Roux-en-Y reconstruction can create the conditions for future complications including internal hernia, intussusception, and marginal ulcers.\n\nIn some reoperative cases in which the fundus is damaged from prior operations and cannot be salvaged, the Roux limb can be brought to the distal esophagus and an esophagojejunostomy constructed. For normal-weight patients, a short (60 cm) retrocolic retrogastric Roux limb should be constructed to prevent malabsorption. Gastrectomy of the remnant stomach is necessary only in selected patients with severe dysmotility and delayed gastric emptying.\n\n## Esophageal Replacement\n\nResection and reconstruction of the esophagus entails major physiological changes and most patients will experience some degree of reflux, dysphagia, or poor conduit emptying. Therefore, indications for esophageal replacement in patients with previously failed fundoplication are restrictive and mainly include severe esophagitis/dysplastic Barrett esophagus, nondilatable esophageal stricture, dysmotility of the esophageal body, and multiple failed antireflux operations with persistent and disabling symptoms. Results of esophageal replacement show that 88% of patients were ultimately satisfied with their operation despite a 24% complication rate. Subsequent series of esophagectomy and gastric conduit reconstruction after antireflux surgery have confirmed the satisfactory results <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> and the feasibility of a minimally invasive approach.\n\nIn selected patients, short-segment resection of the distal esophagus and intrathoracic esophagojejunal anastomosis is possible given the theoretical advantage of preserving as much normal esophagus as possible.\n\nSince the main outcome measure of interest in these patients is functional performance over a presumably normal life span, a colon interposition graft may provide superior quality of life compared to gastric pull-up by preserving the reservoir function of the stomach. However, the colon is not always available as a conduit due to intrinsic pathology. Despite the inherent technical challenges of reconstruction with additional anastomoses, long-term quality of life and alimentary satisfaction after colon interposition are excellent, with most patients being free of dysphagia and few requiring surgical revision for colon redundancy.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nRevisional surgery after fundoplication is complex, requiring good surgeon judgment and expertise, but it is generally feasible through a laparoscopic approach. Accurate preoperative and intraoperative assessment is necessary to identify the cause of failure of the previous antireflux surgery and to tailor the revisional procedure to the individual patient. With the rising epidemic of GERD, reoperative hiatus surgery remains a challenge whose complexity and volume are expected to remain stable or even to increase in the future.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Maret-Ouda J., Wahlin K., El-Serag H.B., Lagergren J.: Association between laparoscopic antireflux surgery and recurrence of gastroesophageal reflux . JAMA 2017; 318 (10): pp. 939-946.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Markar S.R., Arhi C., Wiggins T., et al.: Reintervention after antireflux surgery for gastroesophageal reflux disease in England . Ann Surg 2020; 271 (4): pp. 709-715.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: Suppiah A., Sirimanna P., Vivian S.J., et al.: Temporal patterns of hiatus hernia recurrence and hiatal failure: quality of life and recurrence after revision surgery . Dis Esophagus 2017; 30 (4): pp. 1-8.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Louie B.E., Kapur S., Blitz M., et al.: Length and pressure of the reconstructed lower esophageal sphincter is determined by both crural closure and Nissen fundoplication . J Gastrointest Surg 2013; 17 (2): pp. 236-243.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: Siboni S., Bonavina L., Rogers B.D., et al.: Effect of increased intra-abdominal pressure on the esophagogastric junction. A systematic review . J Clin Gastroenterol 2022; 56 (10): pp. 821-830.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n6.: Gerdes S., Schoppmann S.F., Bonavina L., et al.: Management of paraesophageal hiatus hernia: recommendations following a European expert Delphi consensus . Surg Endosc 2023; 37 (6): pp. 4555-4565.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n7.: Lamb P.J., Myers J.C., Jamieson G.G., et al.: Long-term outcomes of revisional surgery following laparoscopic fundoplication . Br J Surg 2009; 96: pp. 391-397.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n8.: Campos G.M., Peters J.H., DeMeester T.R., et al.: Multivariate analysis of factors predicting outcome after laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication . J Gastrointest Surg 1999; 3 (3): pp. 292-300.\n\nView In Article\n\n9.: Oelschlager B.K., Quiroga E., Parra G.D., Cahill M., Polissar N., Pellegrini C.A.: Long-term outcomes after laparoscopic antireflux surgery . Am J Gastroenterol 2008; 103 (2): pp. 280-287.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n10.: Furn\u00e9e E.J., Draaisma W.A., Broeders I.A., Smout A.J., Vlek A.L., Gooszen H.G.: Predictors of symptomatic and objective outcomes after surgical reintervention for failed antireflux surgery . Br J Surg 2008; 95 (11): pp. 1369-1374.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n11.: Bradley D.D., Louie B.E., Farivar A.S., Wilshire C.L., Baik P.U., Aye R.W.: Assessment and reduction of diaphragmatic tension during hiatal hernia repair . Surg Endosc 2015; 29: pp. 796-804.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n12.: Khajanchee Y.S., O\u2019Rourke R., Cassera M.A., Gatta P., Hansen P.D., Swanstr\u00f6m L.L.: Laparoscopic reintervention for failed antireflux surgery: subjective and objective outcomes in 176 consecutive patients . Arch Surg 2007; 142 (8): pp. 785-791.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n13.: Furn\u00e9e E.J., Draaisma W.A., Broeders I.A., Smout A.J., Gooszen H.G.: Surgical reintervention after antireflux surgery for gastroesophageal reflux disease: a prospective cohort study in 130 patients . Arch Surg 2008; 143 (3): pp. 267-274.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n14.: Awais O., Luketich J.D., Schuchert M.J., et al.: Reoperative antireflux surgery for failed fundoplication: an analysis of outcomes in 275 patients . Ann Thorac Surg 2011; 92 (3): pp. 1083-1089.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n15.: Dallemagne B., Arenas Sanchez M., Francart D., et al.: Long-term results after laparoscopic reoperation for failed antireflux procedures . Br J Surg 2011; 98 (11): 1581\u2013158 .\n\nView In Article\n\n16.: Grover B.T., Kothari S.N.: Reoperative antireflux surgery . Surg Clin North Am 2015; 95 (3): pp. 629-640.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n17.: Velanovich V.: Comparison of generic (SF-36) vs disease specific quality of life (GERD-HRQL) scales for gastroesophageal reflux disease . J Gastrointest Surg 1998; 2 (2): pp. 141-145.\n\nView In Article\n\n18.: Nguyen N.T., Thosani N.C., Canto M.I., et al.: The American Foregut Society white paper on endoscopic classification of esophagogastric junction integrity . Foregut 2022; pp. l-10.\n\nView In Article\n\n19.: Jobe B.A., Richter J.E., Hoppo T., et al.: Preoperative diagnostic workup before antireflux surgery: an evidence and experience-based consensus of the Esophageal Diagnostic Advisory Panel . J Am Coll Surg 2013; 217 (4): pp. 586-597.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n20.: Kivela A.J., Kauppi J., Rasanen J., et al.: Long-term health-related quality of life (HRQoL) after redo-fundoplication . World J Surg 2021; 45 (5): pp. 1495-1502.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n21.: Schlottmann F., Laxague F., Angeramo C.A., et al.: Outcomes of laparoscopic redo fundoplication in patients with failed antireflux surgery: a systematic review and meta-analysis . Ann Surg 2021; 274 (1): pp. 78-85.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n22.: van Beek D.B., Auyang E.D., Soper N.J.: A comprehensive review of laparoscopic redo fundoplication . Surg Endosc 2011; 25 (3): pp. 706-771.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n23.: Symons N.R., Purkayastha S., Dillemans B., et al.: Laparoscopic revision of failed antireflux surgery: a systematic review . Am J Surg 2011; 202 (3): pp. 336-343.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n24.: Antiporda M., Jackson C., Smith C.D., et al.: Strategies for surgical remediation of the multi-fundoplication failure patient . Surg Endosc 2019; 33 (5): pp. 1474-1481.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n25.: Nguyen R., Dunn C.P., Putnam L., et al.: Less is more: cruroplasty alone is sufficient for revisional hiatal hernia surgery . Surg Endosc 2020; 35 (8): pp. 4661-4666.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n26.: Markar S., Andreou A., Bonavina L., et al.: UEG and EAES rapid guideline: update systematic review, network meta-analysis, CINeMA and GRADE assessment, and evidence-informed European recommendations on surgical management of GERD . United European Gastroenterology J 2022; 10: pp. 983-998.\n\nView In Article\n\n27.: Zehetner J., DeMeester S., Ayazi S., et al.: Laparos