('Obesity and GERD', 'shackelford-9th-ed-17-obesity-and-gerd', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Obesity and GERD\n\nDavid Leenen; Melissa L. Desouza\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 17, 172-179\n\n## Introduction\n\nGastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) is considered a well-known comorbidity of obesity and its prevalence increases with increasing body mass index (BMI). As a consequence of this relationship, there has been an unsurprising increase in GERD within the US population as the prevalence of obesity continues to rise. Estimates by the US Preventive Services Task Force suggest that over 42% of the US population is obese, with 9.2% having severe obesity (BMI >40 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> ). Managing this influx of GERD is economically burdensome, with treatment costing the US healthcare system $15 billion annually.\n\nHowever, the ideal management strategy of reflux disease in patients with obesity is under debate, and the mainstay of treatment for many has been pharmacologic. Over-the-counter access to proton pump inhibitor (PPI) therapy may actually lead to underreporting of GERD symptoms, particularly in patients who have been discouraged from pursuing other elective surgeries due to BMI. Symptoms of heartburn and acid regurgitation have been shown to increase even in normal-weight individuals as BMI rises, and weight loss alone has been shown to improve GERD symptoms, following this BMI trend. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Patients with BMI over 35 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> are six times more likely to have GERD symptoms than their normal-weight counterparts.\n\nThe mechanism by which GERD develops in the obese patient is multifactorial, with increased intraabdominal pressure (IAP) contributing to both failure of the mechanical components of the antireflux barrier and delaying esophageal clearance and resulting in more intrusive reflux events. Waist circumference (WC) has an even stronger correlation to GERD than BMI alone, further supporting that visceral adiposity is a key component in obesity-related GERD. Beyond reflux itself, the systemic effects of morbid obesity have profound impact on the cardiopulmonary and neurohormonal systems, with significant reduction in life expectancy often as a result from complications of cardiovascular disease, diabetes, or cancer.\n\n## Physiologic Effects of Obesity on the Antireflux Barrier\n\nWhile the link between GERD and obesity is widely recognized, the specific pathway by which GERD develops in this population is poorly understood. This is in part related to limited objective evidence and lack of longitudinal assessments that explore the direct effects of weight on the diaphragmatic crura, function of the lower esophageal sphincter (LES), and esophagogastric motility. The fact that GERD can occur in normal-weight individuals further contributes to the complexity of the pathogenesis. An overview of the currently proposed mechanisms for development of reflux in obesity is presented below, as well as summarized in Table 17.1 .\n\nTable 17.1\n\nProposed Mechanisms for Development of GERD in Obesity\n\n| Mechanism | Proven Objective Changes | Clinical Sequelae |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Anatomic disruption | - \u2022 \tIncreased risk of hiatal hernia - \u2022 \tHigher risk for hiatal hernia recurrence | - \u2022 \tIndependently associated with delayed acid clearance - \u2022 \tRefractory reflux control |\n| Mechanical LES failure | - \u2022 \tIncreased frequency of TLESR - \u2022 \tGastric overdistension leading to LES shortening | - \u2022 \tMore symptomatic reflux events - \u2022 \tProximal migration of pH transition point |\n| Abnormal pressurization | - \u2022 \tIncreased intragastric pressure - \u2022 \tIncreased perihiatal adipose tissue | - \u2022 \tPotential for larger volume reflux - \u2022 \tPotentiates anatomic disruption of the hiatus |\n| Impaired acid clearance | - \u2022 \tDelayed esophageal clearance - \u2022 \tAcid trapping in hernia sac | - \u2022 \tProlonged acid exposure and stasis in the distal esophagus |\n| Biochemical changes | - \u2022 \tIncreased adipocytokines including IL-6 and TNF-\u03b1 - \u2022 \tIncreased leptin | - \u2022 \tPromotes carcinogenesis - \u2022 \tPotentiates progressive weight gain |\n\n*GERD,* Gastroesophageal reflux disease; *IL-6,* interleukin-6; *LES,* lower esophageal sphincter; *TLESR,* transient lower esophageal sphincter relaxation; *TNF-\u03b1,* tumor necrosis factor-alpha.\n\nThere are several proposed mechanisms as to how obesity may lead to GERD. Among the most common suggested mechanisms in the obesity\u2013GERD pathway are increased intragastric pressure, anatomic disruption of the gastroesophageal junction, increased prevalence of hiatal hernia, increased frequency of transient relaxation of the LES, and relative hypotension of the LES. Increased intragastric pressure due to extrinsic compression by visceral adipose tissue has the strongest mechanistic evidence. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> There is much weaker evidence regarding the specific mechanism of anatomic disruption of the reflux barrier in obesity, though some of this is thought to be related to increased prevalence of hiatal hernia with weight gain. Although not all patients with obesity and GERD have hiatal hernia, disruption of the crural diaphragm leads to failure of one of the components of the native antireflux barrier. Several studies have shown an increased prevalence of hiatal hernia at higher BMI, as increased IAP is thought to weaken fascial integrity and impact a variety of hernia types. In patients with morbid obesity undergoing bariatric surgery, 40% have been found to have radiographic evidence of hiatal hernia.\n\nThere has been discussion as to whether generalized obesity is as impactful as abdominal obesity in relation to GERD and its sequelae, particularly the development of Barrett\u2019s esophagus (BE) and esophageal adenocarcinoma (EAC). WC has been found to be a risk factor for BE that is independent of BMI, and patients with visceral adiposity are 1.5 times more likely to have BE than their control counterparts. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> This has been supported by several other studies, and in meta-analysis of the data, central adiposity has been shown to be a risk factor for erosive esophagitis, BE, and EAC independent of BMI. Furthermore, increased hip circumference alone (as a marker for non-abdominal obesity) has been shown to be inversely correlated with development of BE.\n\nOne potential cause of failure of the LES is thought to be related to altered pressure gradient across the esophagogastric junction, specifically that the relative increase in intragastric pressure may lead to reversal of flow and promote gastroesophageal reflux. Patients with obesity have higher IAP than patients with a normal BMI, with studies of bladder pressures demonstrating baseline IAP in morbid obesity as nearly double (9\u201314 mmHg) that of normal-weight populations (5\u20137 mmHg). This would suggest that baseline intragastric pressures should also be commensurately increased in morbid obesity; however, this has not been explored in detail within the motility literature. What has been shown is that the pH transition point is more proximal in patients with larger WC, and gastric overdistension may contribute to development of reflux. Manometric assessment in asymptomatic volunteers found distension and distal shortening of the LES associated with increased WC and intragastric pressure >7 mmHg, which allowed the gastric acid pocket to enter the distal esophagus. The result of this increased intrasphincteric acid exposure was lengthening of the cardiac mucosa (thought to be a precursor to development of intestinal metaplasia), and the effects were more pronounced postprandially with gastric overdistension. This effect of overeating and gastric distension on the LES suggests that behaviors that lead to development of obesity may also concurrently lead to development of GERD.\n\nFailure of the reflux barrier in obesity has been proven through objective pH studies. Obesity (specifically BMI \u226530 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> ) has been shown to be associated with both increased number and duration of reflux episodes on pH testing in the postprandial period, and this finding appears to be most strongly associated with increased central adiposity. In meta-analyses, obesity has been shown to be associated with a 1.5- to 2-fold increased risk of GERD and erosive esophagitis, and a 2- to 2.5-fold risk or EAC as compared with individuals with a normal BMI. Regarding the risk for malignancy in obesity, visceral fat has been shown to be more metabolically active than subcutaneous fat, with increased release of proinflammatory cytokines such as TNF-\u03b1 and IL-6. In particular, increased levels of leptin and insulin resistance are associated with progression to EAC in patients with BE. Serum adiponectin is decreased in the presence of visceral adiposity. This cytokine has an antiproliferative effect on various cancer cell types and suppresses tumor-associated angiogenesis, so the relative decrease in circulating levels is thought to contribute to increased risk of malignant transformation in patients with obesity. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nAnother key component for the development of reflux disease is thought to be an increase in the number of transient lower esophageal sphincter relaxation (TLESR) episodes. TLESR is defined as LES relaxation outside of normal swallowing, and TLESR events are typically longer than a swallow-induced relaxation event. The primary driver of TLESR events is thought to be gastric distension.\n\nPatients with obesity reportedly have increased rate of TLESR events in the postprandial period compared with patients with a normal BMI, as well as increased proportion of TLESR events associated with gastroesophageal reflux on pH studies. This was correlated to both BMI and WC in a dose\u2013effect relationship.\n\nSeveral studies also link delayed esophageal clearance with exacerbation of reflux disease. Patients with prolonged esophageal clearance times have higher rates of erosive esophagitis. Esophageal dysmotility disorders are not uncommon in patients with morbid obesity. In manometry studies of 338 patients with a BMI >35 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> , Vigo et al. found that 22.7% of patients had esophageal dysmotility, and 38.5% had hypotensive LES. Additionally, the presence of hiatal hernia also plays a role in delayed esophageal acid clearance. Mittal et al. found that hiatal hernias were independently associated with delayed acid clearance due to trapping of acid in the hernia sac, with ruminatory reflux episodes during TLESR.\n\nIt is the combination of these multiple mechanistic factors that poses the greatest challenge to the treatment of GERD in obesity. Acid-suppressive medications alone do not address the mechanical failures of the antireflux complex or the neurohormonal effects of obesity, and targeted weight loss therapies are ineffective at restoring a defective LES. Treatment of GERD in the patient with obesity therefore requires its own multidisciplinary approach.\n\n## Management of GERD in Obesity\n\nFor most patients presenting with GERD, the initial approach to disease management includes antacid medications and behavioral modifications. Dietary modifications and weight loss have both been shown to reduce GERD-related symptoms. Specific dietary changes, such as increasing dietary fiber and reducing saturated fat and cholesterol consumption, lead to reduced symptoms in patients with a high BMI. Weight loss alone has been demonstrated to reduce symptoms of GERD. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> A medically supervised weight loss program may help patients to lose 5%\u201315% of excess body weight; however, weight regain is common once these physician-supervised programs complete. A meta-analysis by Anderson et al. of 29 long-term weight loss studies highlighted that in patients who lost weight on low-calorie and balanced diets, more than half of weight lost was regained within 2 years, and more than 80% of weight lost was regained by 5 years. The addition of medications such as phentermine, topiramate, naltrexone\u2013buprenorphine, orlistat, and liraglutide may lead to a further loss of 5%\u201310% of total body weight. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> More novel applications of glucagon-like peptide 1 receptor agonists have demonstrated up to 15% of total body weight loss in randomized trials. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> As with physician-supervised weight loss programs, these medications appear to require consistent adherence in order to maintain weight loss over time.\n\nStandard antacid medication therapy including PPIs and histamine type-2 receptor blockers may only provide partial management of symptoms in patients with obesity. Several studies suggest that an increased dose of PPI is required for sustained control of symptoms and esophagitis. High BMI has also been shown to be a risk factor for long-term antacid medication use due to persistent and troublesome symptoms of reflux. These patients may benefit from surgical management of reflux disease when medical and lifestyle management has failed.\n\n## Perioperative Considerations\n\nThere are many challenges to safely performing surgery in the patient with obesity. These patients are high risk for perioperative morbidity. From an anesthesia standpoint, a large tongue and redundant oropharyngeal tissues can obstruct the airway, leading to difficulties in mask ventilation and intubation. Decreased chest wall compliance due to excess adipose tissue and reduced lung volumes result in impaired ability to ventilate sedated patients. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> This, in addition to requiring increased ventilation pressures intraoperatively has the effect of prolonging atelectasis in the postoperative period. Patients with obesity are at high risk for obstructive sleep apnea (OSA), which leads to several cardiopulmonary changes including increased pulmonary pressures, and predisposes patients to hypoxemia. When respiratory drive is further impaired by concomitant use of opiate medications or benzodiazepines during anesthesia, the result can be postoperative respiratory failure from hypoxia and hypoventilation. This has led the American Society of Anesthesiologists to recommend an additional 3-hour observation period post anesthesia for patients suspected of OSA, and at least 7 hours after the last hypoxic or obstructing event before discharge.\n\nIncrease in total body weight and metabolic demands in obesity result in an increased circulating blood volume, with resulting cardiac hypertrophy that predisposes these patients to left ventricular dysfunction. This effect predisposes patients with obesity to cardiac compromise in the perioperative period, and thorough preoperative assessment of function is recommended. These patients additionally have impaired clearance of several medications used in anesthesia, including certain inhalational agents which may accumulate in adipose tissue, delaying emergence. Obesity has also been reported as an independent risk factor for perioperative venous thromboembolic events, and a risk factor for increased wound infection. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nFrom an operative perspective, the patient with obesity presents additional challenges. Due to body habitus, the morbidly obese patient may not fit on a standard operating room bed. A typical standard maximum hospital bed weight limit is 450 lbs. Extra care must be taken to position these patients to prevent fall or positioning injury. Prolonged operative time has been shown to be a risk factor for rhabdomyolysis at high BMI with a functional crush injury from the weight of excess tissue without ability to routinely offload pressure during certain procedures. Ulnar neuropathies from positional injury also occur at higher frequency in patients with obesity than in non-obese individuals. There is an estimated 50%\u201390% prevalence of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease in patients with obesity compared with 15%\u201330% prevalence in the overall population. An enlarged left lobe of the liver impairs visualization of the hiatus and gastroesophageal junction. In the setting of bariatric surgery, low-calorie diets targeted at reducing liver size have been shown to reduce the left lobe of the liver by up to 27%, and in randomized trials has been shown to reduce postoperative complications. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In a prospective study by Childs et al., even a week of a low-calorie diet was effective in reducing liver volumes in 47% of patients prior to antireflux surgery, with a goal of ease of operation.\n\nSpecialty instrumentation may be required to complete a case laparoscopically in an obese patient. Standard ports may not reach the peritoneum in patients with increased subcutaneous adipose tissue. Bariatric length ports and instruments should be available before the start of the case. While analysis of upper extremity muscle group activation and mental workload did not show any difference in laparoscopic ergonomics in patients above and below BMI of 30 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> , other studies report longer operative times for antireflux surgery in patients who are obese, which is often used as a surrogate for technical complexity. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Compared with standard laparoscopy, robotic-assisted surgery may reduce physical stressors on the surgeon when operating on patients with obesity. The use of the robotic platform has therefore gained notable traction in the area of surgeon ergonomics. However, increased abdominal wall thickness limits trocar range of motion in both laparoscopic and robotic-assisted surgery, and no study to date has shown direct benefit to the patient in the use of the robotic platform in reflux disease over standard laparoscopy.\n\n## Surgical Options and Outcomes\n\nThe coincidence of GERD and obesity should prompt the surgeon to consider concurrent treatment of both diseases. All patients with obesity presenting with GERD should undergo a thorough preoperative workup with pH testing, manometry, contrast esophagram, and upper endoscopy.\n\n### Antireflux Surgery\n\nStandard surgical approaches to reflux disease aim to restore the reflux barrier through structural augmentation of the LES and gastroesophageal flap valve, often in conjunction with repair of concomitant hiatal disruption. The most common antireflux procedure is fundoplication, either partial (Toupet, Dor, or other) or complete (Nissen). Nissen and Toupet both have proven efficacy in the treatment of GERD long-term with comparable palliation of symptoms and cessation of antacid medication use. However, there is concern about the efficacy and durability of fundoplication in patients with obesity. Patients with a BMI >30 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> are at higher risk for recurrence of reflux following fundoplication. Perez et al. found that risk of recurrent GERD 3 years postoperatively was 4.5% in normal-weight patients, 8.0% in overweight patients (BMI 25\u201330 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> , *P* not significant vs. normal), but 31% in obese patients (BMI \u226530 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> , *P* <.001 vs. normal, *P* <.001 vs. overweight). In a long-term follow-up study (11\u201322 years) by Schietroma et al. of 201 patients, obese patients (BMI >30 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> ) had significantly higher rates of non-esophagitis reflux disease, esophagitis, reflux recurrence, and reoperation than the normal-weight and overweight patients who underwent laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication. In particular, patients with obesity have higher risk of recurrence of hiatal hernia following antireflux surgery than both normal-weight and overweight patients. Herniation of the fundoplication is considered to be the most common reason for failure of Nissen to control reflux disease. Obesity is a known independent risk factor for recurrence of many abdominal hernia subtypes, including ventral and incisional hernias. Increased baseline IAP is thought to be a contributing factor to hernia recurrence, as this results in continuous stressor on the fascia and musculature. In the case of the diaphragm, this continuous pressure translates to increased radial tension on the hiatus and any associated crural repair. In paraesophageal hernia repair, Parker et al. demonstrated that the odds of hernia recurrence are 2.92 times higher for individuals with a BMI >25 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> , demonstrating that even overweight patients carrier higher recurrence risks than normal-weight individuals. Bashir et al. performed a meta-analysis of 12 studies with 932 patients in the obese group and 2423 patients in the non-obese group; they reported that the overall risk ratio for GERD recurrence after laparoscopic antireflux surgery in obese group was 1.36 (95% CI 1.08\u20131.72, *P* <.009) versus non-obese group. This was confirmed with studies that reported objective recurrence (RR 1.53, 95% CI 1.01\u20132.32, *P* <.05) showing up to 53% increased risk of recurrence for obese patients.\n\nDespite these concerns, many studies argue that obesity itself is not a contraindication to antireflux surgery. Within the first 2 postoperative years, several authors found that reflux control was equivocal between normal-weight and obese individuals, with similar rates of recurrence. In a classic multivariate analysis predicting success after Nissen fundoplication, Campos et al. reported that BMI was not predictive of failure at a median of 15 months follow-up. A study by Luketina et al. involving a small cohort of 80 patients showed that of the 6 patients who required reoperation, 2 (5%) were in the obese group and 4 (10%) were in the normal-weight group. Similarly, Fraser et al. showed no correlation between increasing BMI and poorer overall outcome in the first 2 years of follow-up of 194 patients who underwent laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication. Data from Winslow et al. also showed no difference in symptoms, overall improvement, or patient satisfaction, with similar rates of anatomic failure between normal-weight, overweight, and obese patients. A study by Ng et al. followed 366 patients, and both the obese and non-obese patient groups had similar Visick scores up to 1 year postoperatively. Another study comparing 481 patients (normal weight, overweight, obese, and morbidly obese) showed that the requirement for revision surgery was not influenced by preoperative weight after 7.5-year follow-up. A meta-analysis by Abdelrahman et al. suggested that while the risk of recurrent GERD was significantly higher in patients with obesity, the actual demonstrated odds ratio was only 0.28 across 13 studies comparing 6246 patients (95% CI 0.13\u20130.61, *P* \\=.001). In these patients, there were no significant differences in rates of revisional surgery (OR 0.94, 0.51\u20131.72, *P* \\=.84) or endoscopic dilation (OR 0.98, 0.45\u20132.17, *P* \\=.97). Patients with obesity who undergo Nissen fundoplication experience similar improvement in quality of life as do normal-weight patients, and there is no evidence to suggest that fundoplication should not be offered to patients with obesity.\n\nOther commercially available solutions currently used to augment the LES include magnetic sphincter augmentation (\\[MSA\\] LINX implantable device, Ethicon, Raritan, New Jersey) and trans-oral incisionless fundoplication (\\[TIF\\] Endogastric Solutions, Redmond, Washington). MSA was initially approved by the FDA in 2012 as an alternative to fundoplication in patients with no prior foregut surgery, small type I hiatal hernias, and BMI <35 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> . A BMI >35 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> was found to be a negative predictor of a good to excellent outcome after MSA placement. Since the early 2020s, surgeons have expanded the application of MSA to include larger hiatal hernias and patients with higher BMI. However, Vivek et al. found that there have only been five studies that specifically assessed MSA outcomes in patients who were overweight or obese. These studies presented contradictory evidence with three reporting no difference in outcomes, and two reporting poorer reflux control with MSA patients with higher BMI. Of the reviewed studies, only one specifically included patients with a BMI >35 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> and did not report differences in recurrence of GERD between normal-weight, overweight, and obese groups by symptoms or endoscopy at 15 months. TIF is an endoscopic procedure, increasingly combined with laparoscopic cruroplasty, where a series of permanent fasteners are used to reconstruct gastroesophageal flap valve. Exclusion criteria for TIF includes BMI >35 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> , which has been maintained across most studies. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> One of the arguments for exclusion of patients with a high BMI is that an enlarged anterior fat pad and perihiatal adiposity may impair plication and satisfactory placement of the fasteners. However, there are insufficient studies to confirm poorer outcomes of TIF in patients with obesity.\n\n### Bariatric Surgery\n\nIn contrast to surgical approaches that restore the antireflux barrier, bariatric procedures seek to reduce acid reflux by other mechanisms ( Table 17.2 ). Most notable approaches are through reducing the volume of gastric refluxate by surgically decreasing gastric volume, and significant weight loss. Patients with class II and III obesity (BMI \u226535 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> ) are candidates for bariatric surgery as a strategy to manage multiple obesity-related comorbidities. When specifically considering GERD, Roux-en-Y gastric bypass (RYGB) has been demonstrated to have the most significant benefit. As described elsewhere in this text (see Chapter 69 ), RYGB achieves weight loss through both the restrictive creation of a gastric pouch as well as the malabsorptive bypass of the proximal small bowel and remnant stomach. This has multiple effects on reflux. The small gastric pouch contains mostly cardia tissue, which is largely devoid of parietal and chief cells. This results in low acid production and exposure to the adjacent esophagus. Gastric acid produced in the remnant stomach is neutralized through standard bicarbonate production in the duodenum, and the antegrade flow of bile from the biliopancreatic limb to the common channel typically results in prevention of bile refluxate, which has itself been shown to play a notable role in the pathogenesis of BE. These mechanisms make RYGB particularly desirable as an antireflux operation. For weight loss, the length of Roux and biliopancreatic limbs are typically exaggerated to be between 75 and 150 cm each. This significant diversion induces weight loss in these populations. The Roux-en-Y reconstruction is also used in multiple other applications with shorter limbs, and RYGB was recommended by Mittal et al. as a superior alternative to revision fundoplication in patients who had failed multiple prior antireflux surgeries who risked progressive esophagogastric dysmotility. When comparing between RYGB to fundoplication as an index procedure to treat GERD, Varela et al. found that morbidly obese patients undergoing bypass had significantly lower in-hospital mortality than fundoplication patients in spite of higher illness severity scores. The vast majority of patients with morbid obesity undergoing RYGB with concomitant GERD have improvement or resolution in their symptoms, ranging from 89% to 96%, with concurrent normalization of esophageal acid exposure. While some surgeons will opt for concurrent repair of hiatal hernia at the time of RYGB, it has been suggested that smaller type I hernias may be left unrepaired at the time of bypass without adversely affecting GERD-health-related quality of life (HRQL) scores. However, Bonavina et al. caution against omitting a thorough crural assessment and repair due to the substantial role that crural integrity plays in the antireflux barrier. Development of GERD post bariatric surgery remains a topic of technical complexity and controversy.\n\nTable 17.2\n\nOptions for Management of GERD in Obesity\n\n| Intervention | Decreased Acid Secretion | Restores LES | Decreased Volumetric Expansion | Bile Diversion | Weight Loss |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Antacid medication (PPI/H2B) | Yes | No | No | No | No |\n| Fundoplication | No | Yes | No | No | No |\n| Magnetic sphincter augmentation | No | Yes | No | No | No |\n| Transoral incisionless fundoplication <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">a</sup> | No | Yes | No | No | No |\n| Roux-en-Y gastric bypass | Yes | No | Yes | Yes | Yes |\n| Sleeve gastrectomy | Yes <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">b</sup> | No | Yes | No | Yes |\n| Endoscopic sleeve gastroplasty | No | No | Yes | No | Yes |\n\n*BMI,* Body mass index; *GERD,* gastroesophageal reflux disease; *H2B,* histamine-2 receptor blocker; *PPI,* proton pump inhibitor.\n\nWhile RYGB is considered an optimal treatment for coincident GERD and obesity, laparoscopic sleeve gastrectomy (LSG) is not. As a surgical treatment of morbid obesity, LSG induces weight loss through gastric restriction without bypass or diversion of the nutrient flow. Lateral resection of the gastric body and fundus does reduce overall parietal cell volume, but flow and pressure changes within the tubularized gastric body may exacerbate underlying esophageal emptying disorders or promote retrograde flow across the LES. A systematic review by Bolckmans et al. disclosed a 25.3% rate of *de novo* erosive esophagitis in 1004 patients who underwent LSG. Preoperative GERD has been shown to be the strongest risk factor for postoperative GERD in patients undergoing LSG, but *de novo* GERD has been reported to be as high as 67.9% after LSG. Similarly, the laparoscopic adjustable gastric band (LAGB) has largely fallen out of favor as both a standalone treatment of obesity as well as a strategy to manage concomitant GERD. Reflux disease, as both symptoms and erosive esophagitis, is considered the most common complication after LAGB that requires reoperation and removal. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nEndoscopic sleeve gastroplasty (ESG, see Chapter 68 ) has been gaining traction as a novel weight loss option, where endoscopic suture plication narrows the lumen of the stomach to provide restrictive weight loss without requiring general anesthesia or gastric resection. Regarding weight loss, studies are mixed, with ESG reaching equivalent weight loss outcomes compared with LSG in well-monitored physician-supervised programs, but poorer weight loss in others. However, there is some evidence to suggest that ESG may be less likely to result in reflux symptoms. Fayad et al. found that in matched patients undergoing ESG versus LSG, *de novo* GERD was significantly lower in the ESG group (1.9% vs. 14.5%, *P* <.05). In these patients, the fundus was not plicated during the endoluminal procedure. This is a method commonly practiced in Europe, and there has been discussion that sparing the fundus may be protective against GERD; although that mechanism is not well understood, it is theorized that it may maintain an intact LES. A meta-analysis by Mohan et al. found that across 3994 patients, the rate of post-procedure GERD was 5.8% with LSG, but only 0.4% after ESG ( *P* \\=.001). There has also been some evidence that poor durability of sutures allowing the stomach to return to native anatomy may explain the lower risk for post-ESG GERD than after LSG, but this has not been proven. Overall, ESG is not a suitable standalone procedure to treat reflux, but it may aid in weight loss to improve symptoms.\n\nMazzini and Campos detail their recommendations for management of GERD in patients with BMI >35 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> , recommending RYGB as a primary surgical treatment unless technical risks of the procedure outweigh the risk of GERD after LSG. With newer guidelines from national and international societies, these BMI thresholds may be at least 5 points lower. The primary barrier that surgeons face in managing concomitant GERD and morbid obesity is often not which procedure to choose, but what patient insurance will approve. Many insurance programs have exclusions for RYGB, either through non-coverage of bariatric procedures or through non-coverage of RYGB as a treatment modality for GERD. Barriers set by insurance companies that contradict current evidence-based practices is a challenge across multiple surgical specialties and will only be improved through greater advocacy moving forward.\n\n## Conclusions\n\nGERD is a common comorbidity of obesity that develops through a multifactorial loss of the native antireflux barrier. As obesity rates continue to rise in the United States, increasing numbers of patients who present for surgical management of reflux will also require consideration in management of their obesity. Although several surgical options exist to manage reflux in the obese patient, the decision to pursue fundoplication versus RYGB or alternate procedures requires a thorough workup of reflux symptoms and an attentive surgeon with clinical expertise in managing the patient with obesity. All patients require workup with appropriate objective pH testing, manometry, contrast esophagram, and endoscopy, as well as assessment of comorbid conditions. For the patient with multiple comorbidities of obesity, bariatric procedures should be discussed and offered, as surgical weight loss may provide significant benefits in health beyond reflux control alone. The patient and surgeon should also both be aware that antireflux surgery in the setting of obesity may be more technically challenging and may have higher risk for complications. Surgeons who wish to offer bariatric options to their obese patients with reflux should undergo the necessary training or refer patients to another qualified surgeon in a high-volume center. Thorough preoperative assessment should be performed with involvement of anesthesiology, and appropriate hospital and operating room equipment should be obtained to maintain safe practices in managing complications that may arise in the obese patient. The modern surgeon must be prepared to manage the obese patient with GERD and understand the strengths and limitations of our current treatment strategies.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Nirwan J.S., Hasan S.S., Babar Z.U., Conway B.R., Ghori M.U.: Global prevalence and risk factors of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD): systematic review with meta-analysis . Sci Rep 2020; 10 (1): pp. 5814.\n\nView In Article\n\n2.: Stierman B., et al.: National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey 2017\u2013March 2020 Prepandemic Data Files Development of Files and Prevalence Estimates for Selected Health Outcomes. National Health Statistic Reports . 2021 .\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: El-Serag H.B., Sweet S., Winchester C.C., Dent J.: Update on the epidemiology of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease: a systematic review . Gut 2014; 63 (6): pp. 871-880.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Greer K.B.: Management of GERD in patients with obesity . Foregut 2021; 1 (4): pp. 321-327.\n\nView In Article\n\n5.: Jacobson B.C., Somers S.C., Fuchs C.S., Kelly C.P., Camargo C.A.: Body-mass index and symptoms of gastroesophageal reflux in women . N Engl J Med 2006; 354 (22): pp. 2340-2348.\n\nView In Article\n\n6.: Singh M., Lee J., Gupta N., et al.: Weight loss can lead to resolution of gastroesophageal reflux disease symptoms: a prospective intervention trial . Obesity (Silver Spring) 2013; 21 (2): pp. 284-290.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n7.: Eslick G.D.: Gastrointestinal symptoms and obesity: a meta-analysis . Obes Rev 2012; 13 (5): pp. 469-479.\n\nView In Article\n\n8.: Tai C.M., Lee Y.C., Tu H.P., et al.: The relationship between visceral adiposity and the risk of erosive esophagitis in severely obese Chinese patients . Obesity (Silver Spring) 2010; 18 (11): pp. 2165-2169.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n9.: Fontaine K.R., Redden D.T., Wang C., Westfall A.O., Allison D.B.: Years of life lost due to obesity . JAMA 2003; 289 (2): pp. 187-193.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n10.: El-Serag H.: Role of obesity in GORD-related disorders . Gut 2008; 57 (3): pp. 281-284.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n11.: Pandolfino J.E., El-Serag H.B., Zhang Q., Shah N., Ghosh S.K., Kahrilas P.J.: Obesity: a challenge to esophagogastric junction integrity . Gastroenterology 2006; 130 (3): pp. 639-649.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n12.: El-Serag H.B., Tran T., Richardson P., Ergun G.: Anthropometric correlates of intragastric pressure . Scand J Gastroenterol 2006; 41 (8): pp. 887-891.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n13.: Wilson L.J., Ma W., Hirschowitz B.I.: Association of obesity with hiatal hernia and esophagitis . Am J Gastroenterol 1999; 94 (10): pp. 2840-2844.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n14.: Che F., Nguyen B., Cohen A., Nguyen N.T.: Prevalence of hiatal hernia in the morbidly obese . Surg Obes Relat Dis 2013; 9 (6): pp. 920-924.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n15.: Corley D.A., Kubo A., Levin T.R., et al.: Abdominal obesity and body mass index as risk factors for Barrett\u2019s esophagus . Gastroenterology 2007 Jul; 133