flux Surgery', 'Obesity and GERD / Physiologic Effects of Obesity on the Antireflux Barrier', 'Obesity and GERD / Management of GERD in Obesity', 'Obesity and GERD / Perioperative Considerations'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '17', '172-179', 2, 44, FALSE, TRUE),
('Cricopharyngeal Dysfunction and Zenker Diverticulum', 'shackelford-9th-ed-18-cricopharyngeal-dysfunction-and-zenker-diverticulum', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Cricopharyngeal Dysfunction and Zenker Diverticulum\n\nMario Costantini; Giovanni Zaninotto\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 18, 181-199\n\nSwallowing (deglutition) is a complex process involving voluntary and involuntary neuromuscular contractions coordinated to permit breathing and swallowing through the same anatomic pathway. Deglutition is commonly divided into the oropharyngeal and esophageal stages. In the oropharyngeal phase, food is chewed and mixed with saliva to form a bolus of appropriate consistency in the mouth. When swallowing begins, the bolus is propelled into the oropharynx by the tongue through the upper esophageal sphincter (UES), mainly but not exclusively constituted by the cricopharyngeal muscle. Other structures simultaneously seal the nasopharynx and larynx to prevent regurgitation or aspiration. Dysfunction in this delicate coordination leads to \u201coropharyngeal dysphagia\u201d (OPD). With this term, we differentiate it from esophageal dysphagia, defined as the difficulty in the progression of the bolus along the esophageal body, propelled by peristalsis through the midthoracic and distal esophagus and into the stomach through the now fully relaxed lower esophageal sphincter (LES).\n\n## Oropharyngeal Dysphagia\n\nThe WHO has recognized dysphagia as a medical disability associated with increased morbidity, mortality, and cost of care. A 2018 study estimated that OPD increases the cost of hospitalization by 40%. The real incidence of such a condition is poorly understood, but it is continuously increasing, probably related to the aging of th general population and, probably, due to a better understanding and assessment of the disease. In the nonhospitalized elderly population, the prevalence of OPD is 11% to 16%, whereas it may rise to 35% to 44% in hospitalized patients, especially in geriatric wards, where it is >50%, the same prevalence as in nursing home residents. Dysphagia is reportedly present in >70% of patients with dementia. Moreover, dysphagia is now recognized as a symptom of concern in conditions, such as acquired brain injury, cervical spine surgery, and head and neck cancer treatment with chemoradiation or surgery. Dysphagia may complicate an inflammatory myopathy in about half the cases and may represent the first symptom in different neuromuscular diseases (e.g., inclusion body myositis). In these patients, OPD increases the risk of pneumonia and mortality by three and four times, respectively, compared with patients without OPD. In 2022 an estimated prevalence of OPD of 35% was reported among hospitalized patients with COVID-19, with a 6.4 times mortality risk compared with nonhospitalized patients. In these patients, intubation, tracheostomy use, and proning were significantly associated with the development of OPD.\n\nThe various causes of OPD are listed in Box 18.1 .\n\nBOX 18.1\n\nCauses and Classification of Oropharyngeal Dysphagia\n\n## Anatomic\n\n  - \u2022\n\tInflammation (abscesses, pharyngitis)\n  - \u2022\n\tNeoplasms\n  - \u2022\n\tWebs (Plummer-Vinson or Patterson-Kelly syndrome)\n  - \u2022\n\tExtrinsic causes (head and neck surgery and radiation, thyroid masses, lymphadenopathy, other)\n\n## Neurological\n\n## Central Nervous System\n\n  - - \u2022\n\t\tStroke (pseudobulbar palsy)\n  - \u2022\n\t\tParkinson disease\n  - \u2022\n\t\tAmyotrophic lateral sclerosis\n  - \u2022\n\t\tMultiple sclerosis\n  - \u2022\n\t\tWilson disease\n  - \u2022\n\t\tNeoplasms\n\n## Peripheral Nervous System\n\n  - - \u2022\n\t\tBulbar poliomyelitis\n  - \u2022\n\t\tViral neuropathies (COVID-19, tetanus, botulism)\n  - \u2022\n\t\tChronic neuropathies (alcoholic, diabetic)\n  - \u2022\n\t\tMedications\n  - \u2022\n\t\tNeoplasms\n\n## Neuromuscular Junction\n\n  - - \u2022\n\t\tMyasthenia gravis\n\n## Muscular\n\n  - - \u2022\n\t\tPolymyositis and dermatomyositis\n  - \u2022\n\t\tOculopharyngeal dystrophy\n  - \u2022\n\t\tMyotonic dystrophy (Steinert syndrome)\n  - \u2022\n\t\tMetabolic myopathies (myxedema, thyrotoxicosis)\n\n**Psychogenic**\n\n### Assessment of Oropharyngeal Dysphagia\n\n#### Clinical Evaluation\n\nThe first step when evaluating a patient with dysphagia is to distinguish between oropharyngeal and esophageal pathologies based on characteristic symptoms. In the case of OPD, the patient clearly describes his/her difficulty transferring food from the mouth to the pharynx and to initiate the involuntary (esophageal) phase of swallowing. The patient is usually very accurate in describing the food accumulating in the mouth, his/her inability to control the bolus in the oral cavity, and the aspiration of food before, during, or after the swallowing act. A few direct and simple questions may help to clarify the diagnosis. The feeling that food is stuck suggests dysphagia of esophageal origin, regardless of the perceived location. Associated symptoms of OPD include nasal regurgitation and cough, related to the inadequacy of protective mechanisms described earlier, and dysarthria or nasal speech related to the weakness of the palate. A gurgling sound may suggest a Zenker diverticulum (ZD; see later). Other symptoms, when present, may be helpful to the final diagnosis, such as a speech disorder or other signs of impairment of the cranial nerves. Often, dysphagia is only part of the symptom complex of the patient, and the diagnosis of a neuromuscular disorder is well evident; however, sometimes it is the first symptom that causes the patient to be seen by a doctor, and only the subsequent physical and neurologic examination may reveal the underlying disease. Finally, weight loss may be the only sign of a swallowing disorder as patients may avoid eating because of the difficulties they experience.\n\n#### Endoscopic Evaluation\n\nSince dysphagia is an ominous sign, endoscopy is mandatory to rule out any anatomic abnormality or organic disease, especially cancer. It must be performed with utmost care, avoiding undue efforts to penetrate the cervical esophagus if resistance or abnormalities are encountered since iatrogenic perforation may occur, especially if a ZD is present. Careful examination of the entire esophageal body and cardia must be obtained to rule out other gastroesophageal diseases, namely reflux, that may affect the swallowing capabilities of the patient or eosinophilic esophagitis. Rarely, rigid endoscopy under general anesthesia may be required.\n\n#### Radiological Studies\n\nThe definitive diagnosis and exact quantification of the swallowing disorder are possible only through a careful radiologic examination. Conventional studies (barium swallow) are usually inadequate because of the rapidity of events during these initial phases of swallowing. They may reveal, however, possible anatomic abnormalities, such as strictures, webs, diverticula, or the so-called cricopharyngeal bar ( Fig. 18.1 ). A dedicated videofluoroscopic swallow study (modified barium swallow) is the most widely used tool and is considered the gold standard in order to evaluate swallowing function. It allows the recording of the rapid movements of the mouth, pharynx, palate, epiglottis, larynx, and cervical esophagus while swallowing, and fluid boluses of different consistencies mixed with radiopaque substance, such as barium. The patient should be studied both in the anteroposterior and lateral positions, and the entire swallowing process is recorded and digitized as video clips and transferred to a computer for further (slow or normal motion) visualization and analysis.\n\nA radiograph shows vertebrae and spinal alignment. Ch18\n\nFig. 18.1\n\nVideofluoroscopy has limitations, such as the need for radiation, the need to move the patient to the radiological suite, and the mainly qualitative rather than quantitative nature of information obtained. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n#### Fiberoptic Endoscopic Evaluation of Swallowing\n\nThe fiberoptic endoscopic evaluation of swallowing (FEES) using a flexible laryngoscope allows evaluating pharyngeal and laryngeal structures before, during, and after deglutition, and is generally well-tolerated, easily repeatable, and can be performed at the bedside of the patient. During the test, the device is introduced transnasally and advanced to enable visualization of the mucosal surface and movement of the tongue base, pharynx, and larynx, as well as the bolus transit and airway protection. The patient is asked to swallow a variety of foods and liquids with a coloring contrast (blue dye). During the normal swallow, however, a blind period of \u223c0.5 second occurs when the epiglottic tilts backward and the pharynx squeezes, preventing the complete visualization of the actual passage of the bolus. The presence of secretion, residual colorized food in the pharynx, or its penetration or aspiration in the airway provides useful qualitative information on the deglutitive capacity of the patient and allows the calculation of a Penetration-Aspiration Scale. The main limitation of FEES is that it does not allow a direct evaluation of the swallow physiology. Still, it only relies on indirect and subjective interpretation of findings, such as residual food and/or penetration.\n\n#### Manometry\n\nSince its introduction in the mid-70s, conventional water-perfused manometry has struggled to evaluate the pharyngoesophageal function because of the axial movements of the region during a swallow, its asymmetry, and the rapidity of the motor events, consistently underestimated with these manometric settings. Be that as it may, some sophisticated combined manometric and radiological studies were basilar for a better understanding of the pathogenesis of OPD (and Zenker diverticula), such as the \u201cintrabolus\u201d pharyngeal pressure, as a counterpart of reduced compliance of the pharyngoesophageal segment and the UES.\n\nThe rapid diffusion of high-resolution manometry (HRM) has greatly enhanced the possibility of investigating the muscular function of the pharynx and UES during swallowing, but further work on its clinical implementation is needed. The possibility of combining this technique with videofluoroscopy has allowed a better understanding of bolus transport because of the pharyngoesophageal motor patterns ( Fig. 18.2 ). Moreover, with the addition of impedance evaluation, an attempt to classify pharyngoesophageal and UES motility disorders was proposed in 2023. This proposal somewhat recalls the dichotomic and descending step approach of the Chicago Classification of esophageal motor disorders, focusing first on the pressurization of the pharyngoesophageal tract with or without UES complete relaxation. The absence of pressurization, even with an incomplete UES relaxation, precludes the diagnosis of a pharyngoesophageal disorder, whereas weak or absent pharyngeal contractility defines a propulsive disorder. The latter and other HRM abnormalities need further studies, but a process to categorize pharyngoesophageal dysmotility was started and hopefully will soon aid the clinical management of these patients. Of note, care with esophageal intubation should be taken when attempting manometry on suspected ZD to avoid perforation.\n\nA photo of two panels shows radiographs and manometry plots of the pharynx while swallowing and captures post-swallow bolus residue and absent pharyngeal contraction. The photos consist of two panels, each with a radiograph on the left and a manometry plot on the right. Panel A shows a radiograph with a box that highlights the pharynx area. A manometry plot shows the position along the catheter centimeters on the vertical axis and time seconds on the horizontal axis, with pressure levels. Labels indicate the velopharynx, oropharynx, and upper esophageal sphincter. Panel B shows a radiograph with a label that points to post swallow bolus residue in piriform sinuses. The manometry plot shows Absent pharyngeal contraction with similar axes.\n\nFig. 18.2\n\n### Treatment\n\nThere is no pharmacologic treatment for OPD, although a 2022 review showed that transient receptor potential channel agonists (capsaicin), nifedipine and metoclopramide, revealed some beneficial effects for patients with neurogenic dysphagia compared with placebo. For patients with OPD and/or cricopharyngeal dysfunction, treatment generally begins with behavioral intervention. A 2022 European survey showed that this is the preferred approach in most interviewed centers, even if only half declared having a specific protocol for treatment. Speech and language therapists, physiotherapists, and dietitians are the professionals most frequently involved, even if the importance of a multidisciplinary team in managing these patients is emphasized. The most important is the modifications in texture, viscosity, consistency, composition, and bolus size of the prescribed food. Also, the posture and position of the body and head are important factors. Therefore, the patient must be cognitively alert, oriented, and responsive before food is given, and this excludes a significant proportion of patients with neurogenic dysphagia. Various maneuvers and techniques are used to ensure feeding safety, including supraglottic swallow, super supraglottic swallow, the Mendelsohn maneuver (to promote pharyngeal and laryngeal elevation), neck flexion, neck extension, head turning, and retraction of the base of the tongue. Behavioral interventions also include exercise programs to improve the range of motion of the structures involved in swallowing, such as the oral tongue, hyoid, and larynx, and strengthening exercises to improve tongue and lip movement. Once therapy is initiated, these compensatory techniques can be varied as progress occurs, but some persons will always require these strategies and risk-reduction diets to ensure that they minimize the risk of aspiration during a meal. Also, acupuncture was used to treat dysphagia caused by pseudobulbar paralysis after stroke, showing some benefits. Its use has been limited to Chinese centers only so far; therefore, it is impossible to evaluate the efficacy of acupuncture in different countries and different ethnic groups.\n\nInterventional procedures can be divided into those adapted to promote alimentation, those designed to protect the airway, and those specifically directed to alleviate swallowing difficulties. Patients at high risk of aspiration and who cannot meet their nutritional needs through oral feedings will need supplementary (or total) alternative nutrition. If these needs are short term, peripheral intravenous alimentation or nasogastric tube feeding may suffice. Because this is rarely the case and considering the shortcomings of nasogastric tubes for chronic feedings (discomfort, risk of aspiration), alternative methods such as a percutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy (PEG) should be considered. This can be performed with the patient under local anesthesia and minimal sedation with little discomfort. If reflux and aspiration are suspected, a slow infusion rate of the formula or the conversion to a feeding jejunostomy is recommended. A gastrostomy may also be safely performed radiologically, avoiding the need for endoscopy.\n\nIn patients unable to adequately clear their secretions from the tracheobronchial tree and aspiration of saliva or gastric refluxed material, a tracheostomy with a cuffed tube is probably one of the most common procedures used in such circumstances. This procedure can be performed with the patient under local anesthesia; it is reversible and allows vocalization to be maintained if the cuff can be deflated at times. Sometimes, however, more radical and irreversible procedures may be used, such as injection of Teflon or other substances to medialize vocal cords, laryngoplasty, subcricoid cricoidectomy, epiglottic sew-down, or the narrow-field laryngectomy.\n\nInterventional procedures specifically aimed at treating dysphagia may be directed at either restoring lost muscle function of the pharyngoesophageal segment or eliminating the obstacle of a dysfunctional UES. Neuromuscular electrical stimulation (NMES) belongs in the first category, which aims to restore and enhance the motor function of weak pharyngeal muscles and enables muscle contraction in order to prevent atrophy. In recent years, numerous studies have investigated NMES as a treatment option for OPD, but study protocols, patient groups, electrode placements, and treatment protocols differ greatly. A couple of recent reviews of studies using NMES to treat patients with dysphagia after stroke, Parkinson disease, or different kinds of brain injuries reported that NMES, coupled with traditional swallowing therapy, could be an optional intervention to improve swallowing function after stroke in rehabilitation department. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> However, only level 2 studies are available to date. The most effective NMES and therapy parameters, the types of patients to be treated, and the outcome of NMES therapy have not been defined yet; thus, it cannot be recommended besides well-designed research settings.\n\nThe current operative management directed toward UES dysfunction is quite variable, and there are little data to support the relative superiority in outcomes of one intervention over another ( Box 18.2 ).\n\nBOX 18.2\n\nPros and Cons of Different Treatment Options for Zenker Diverticula (ZD)\n\n| Treatment | Pros | Cons | Comments |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Open surgical myotomy | - \u2022 \tAllows very good results (>93%) - \u2022 \tLow recurrence rate (1.5%) - \u2022 \tAvailable in any surgical service | - \u2022 \tGeneral anesthesia - \u2022 \tComplications (>10%) - \u2022 \tLonger hospital stay and recovery time - \u2022 \tCosts - \u2022 \tCosmesis (surgical scar) | - \u2022 \tBest suited for young patients |\n| Stapler diverticulostomy | - \u2022 \tAllows good results (>80%) - \u2022 \tLow complication rate (<8%), mostly minor - \u2022 \tShort hospital stay and quick recovery time - \u2022 \tAvailable in most surgical and ENT services | - \u2022 \tGeneral anesthesia - \u2022 \tHigh recurrence rate (15%) - \u2022 \tNeed adequate neck extension and mouth opening - \u2022 \tNot indicated for small ZD | - \u2022 \tBest results in 3\u20135 cm ZD |\n| Rigid CO <sub>2 </sub> diverticulostomy | - \u2022 \tAllows good results (>80%) - \u2022 \tLow complication rate (<8%), mostly minor - \u2022 \tShort hospital stay and quick recovery time | - \u2022 \tGeneral anesthesia - \u2022 \tHigh recurrence rate (15%) - \u2022 \tAvailable in dedicated esophageal centers only | - \u2022 \tAlternative to rigid stapler, possible when stapler introduction not possible |\n| Flexible endoscopic septum division (FESD) | - \u2022 \tAllows good results (>80%) - \u2022 \tLow complication rate (<8%), mostly minor - \u2022 \tOvercomes issues of rigid endoscope introduction - \u2022 \tConscious sedation - \u2022 \tSame-day discharge - \u2022 \tQuick recovery time - \u2022 \tPossible in ZD of any size | - \u2022 \tHigh recurrence rate (15%) - \u2022 \tNeeds endoscopic expertise - \u2022 \tMore than one session usually required - \u2022 \tIncomplete UES myotomy in small diverticula | - \u2022 \tIndicated in high-risk patients and when rigid endoscopy is not feasible |\n| Endoscopic submucosal tunneling techniques (Z-POEM and POES) | - \u2022 \tAllows very good results (>90%) - \u2022 \tLow complication rate (<8%), mostly minor - \u2022 \tOvercomes issues of rigid endoscope introduction - \u2022 \tConscious sedation - \u2022 \tSame-day discharge - \u2022 \tQuick recovery time - \u2022 \tPossible in ZD of any size | - \u2022 \tIntermediate recurrence rate (>10%) - \u2022 \tNeeds high endoscopic expertise - \u2022 \tNot widely available - \u2022 \tOnly initial small series available | - \u2022 \tMost promising option - \u2022 \tNeeds more studies and follow-up results |\n\n### Endoscopic Dilations\n\nDilation of the UES might be most helpful in patients with known fibrosis within the region, which is commonly found after radiation therapy, but would also include patients with traumatic injury, peptic stricture, webs, cricopharyngeal bar, or radiation-induced strictures. This procedure usually often requires repetition. In a study on patients with radiation-induced stricture, the mean number of dilations was 3, although some patients required up to 8 dilations; using this serial dilatation technique, the clinical success rate was 83%. Dilations have the advantages of being simple, relatively safe, and are usually performed under conscious sedation with balloon dilators or with serial tapered bougie dilators. They surely reduce the risk of surgery, especially in a patient after radiation or previous oral or neck surgery. They seem to have a success rate like other invasive procedures, but further treatment with surgical myotomy is eventually indicated in a consistent percentage of patients.\n\n### Injection of Botulinum Toxin\n\nInjection of botulinum toxin (BoT) in the cricopharyngeal muscle (transcutaneously with electromyography guidance or endoscopically) has gained some popularity after its introduction in 1994. BoT inhibits muscle tonic contraction by inhibiting acetylcholine release across the neuromuscular junction; therefore, it will primarily benefit patients with hypertonicity of the UES and a retained ability to complete pharyngeal bolus formation. Further, it has a distinct appeal in patients who are not ideal candidates for surgery. In a review performed in 2013 only two of the analyzed studies, however, reported on more than 20 patients, most articles being either case reports or limited series of fewer than 10 patients. The causes of cricopharyngeal dysfunction in these published series encompassed numerous diagnoses, and the dosages and administration techniques of BoT quite variable. In general, most patients reported improved swallowing function, approximately 75% in the combined analysis. Complications were infrequent and included transient vocal fold paresis, temporary worsening of dysphagia, neck cellulitis, and aspiration pneumonia. There were no reported deaths directly related the procedure. BoT injections may also be used as a test to determine whether myotomy would be effective, even if success with myotomy has also been reported in patients who failed BoT treatment.\n\n### Cricopharyngeal Myotomy\n\nCricopharyngeal myotomy has long been used for treating patients with cricopharyngeal dysfunction of neurologic or myogenic origin, with the aim of removing the obstructive effect of the UES below a pharynx unable to initiate an effective contraction to push the bolus into the cervical esophagus ( Fig. 18.3A\u2013E ). The technique is the same as the cricopharyngeal myotomy performed as part of the open surgical treatment of a ZD. The real challenge in patients with OPD is to identify which patients will benefit from such a surgical treatment. An intact voluntary oral phase of deglutition with good control of the tongue, good control of the laryngeal aditus with normal phonation, and absence of dysarthria are reliable prognostic factors for a successful outcome. The cumulative analysis of published data (most uncontrolled case series) showed an overall favorable response rate of 63%, with an average mortality of 1.8%. Other reviews report a success rate of 78%, with a morbidity of 7%. A 2018 systematic review of 10 studies (only 1 was a pilot RCT) published between 1995 and 2015 revealed insufficient evidence for guiding clinical practice due to small and heterogeneous sample groups, poor standardization of procedures, and the lack of validated rating instruments of evaluation of the results. At present, there are therefore no clear and accepted indications for cricopharyngeal myotomy in OPD of neurologic or myogenic origin, and the final clinical decision needs to be made on a case-by-case basis.\n\nA diagram of five surgical steps for thyroidectomy labeled from A to E. The diagram of the five-panel surgical procedure at the neck, labeled A through E. Panel A shows a side view of the patient with the head and shoulder. A dashed line labeled Line of incision is demonstrated at the neck. The cricoid cartilage is also labeled. Panel B depicts a view of neck muscles, including parathyroid muscles, omohyoid muscles, and sternomastoid muscles. A dashed line with the label Line of incision is shown. Panel C depicts the neck with the thyroid gland and inferior thyroid artery covered by deep cervical fascia, and the middle thyroid vein is labeled. Panel D depicts the use of surgical instruments to separate tissue. The scale is shown as 4 centimeters. Panel E shows a close-up view of muscle separation.\n\nFig. 18.3\n\n## Zenker Diverticulum\n\nPharyngoesophageal diverticula are protrusions of pharyngeal mucosa through a weak zone in the posterior wall of the pharynx that is limited inferiorly by the upper border of the cricopharyngeal muscle and laterally by the oblique fibers of the thyropharyngeal muscle, the so-called Killian triangle. These diverticula are named after the German pathologist Friedrich Albert von Zenker, who published a review of 27 patients with this disease. Though not the first to describe this condition, Zenker is credited for realizing that the pathogenesis of the diverticula lay in an increased intrapharyngeal pressure, thus causing a \u201cpulsion\u201d diverticulum. Anatomically, ZD develops more frequently on the left side, probably related to a significant difference in muscle thickness between the left and right sides of Killian triangle.\n\nInfrequently, a muscular dehiscence is located inferior to the cricopharyngeal muscle and lateral to the longitudinal muscle of the esophagus, where it inserts at the inferior border of the cricoid cartilage. This causes the occurrence of the so-called *Killian-Jamieson diverticula* . First described by Ekberg and Nylander in 1983, this is a rare occurrence (<100 cases were reported in literature with a variable clinical presentation and treatments) and represents <5% of hypopharyngeal diverticula undergoing surgical intervention. This very infrequent pathology will not be discussed further.\n\n### Physiology and Pathophysiology\n\nAfter the recognition of the central role of the UES in causing the diverticulum, different theories have been suggested over the years. An increased resting pressure of the UES, a lack of complete relaxation (achalasia) or premature or discoordinated UES relaxation with the incoming pharyngeal contraction have all been proposed. At the end of the past century, with the manometric techniques in use at that time, the UES in patients with ZD was shown to have a resting pressure similar and even decreased compared with controls, and apparently to relax properly at manometry during deglutition; finally, pharyngosphincteric incoordination was an inconsistent finding. Elegant concurrent manometric and videofluorographic studies demonstrated a significantly reduced radiological sphincter opening despite a manometrically \u201ccomplete\u201d relaxation. Further, in these patients, greater \u201cintrabolus\u201d pressure was found, demonstrating that the pathophysiologic abnormality is indeed a diminished UES opening with increasing intrapharyngeal pressure, which probably accounts for the development of the diverticulum. The authors postulated that degenerative changes cause a lack of elasticity of the sphincter muscle preventing it from relaxing completely and introduced the concept of reduced compliance of the pharyngoesophageal segment.\n\nSeveral histologic and contractility studies on biopsy specimens taken from patients with ZD and controls endorsed this theory, showing a slower and weaker contraction curve, with lower amplitude ( Fig. 18.4 ). Histologic, electron microscopy, and immunohistochemical alterations were also found, with a significantly higher collagen content, higher isodesmosine/desmosine and collagen/elastine ratios in the cricopharyngeal muscle and the cervical esophagus muscularis propria in patients with ZD compared with controls. More recently, with the use of esophageal HRM, a higher residual pressure of the UES at swallowing was found in patients with ZD than in controls, more due to persistent UES pressurization during relaxation than due to high tonic resting pressure. This observation with state-of-art technology confirms the old findings of a reduced compliance of the pharyngoesophageal region obtained with traditional manometry.\n\nA photo represents a radiography view of two participants with a functional lumen probe balloon in the upper esophageal sphincter. The radiography view of two participants with a Functional lumen probe balloon positioned in the upper esophageal sphincter. The right side of the photo shows measurements of upper esophageal sphincter distension at 35 milliliters for both participants in three conditions, at rest, during the dry swallow, and with the head turned to the right. For Participant 1, the measurements are 4 millimeters at rest, 13 point 6 millimeters during dry swallow, and 4 point 2 milliliters with the head turned to the right. For Participant 2, the measurements are 4 point 3 millimeters at rest, 17 point 7 millimeters during the dry swallow, and 6 point 2 millimeters with the head turned to the right.\n\nFig. 18.4\n\n### Symptoms and Diagnosis\n\nThe main symptom in these patients is dysphagia, which is present in nearly all the cases. One can distinguish this intrinsic dysphagia from the extrinsic one, caused by the distension of the pouch by accumulated food that can further compress the esophageal lumen. Regurgitation of indigested food particles (from previous meals), abnormal noise during swallowing, and halitosis are also common. The most frequent symptoms are listed in Table 18.1 . Dysphagia may lead to weight loss, penetration, and inhalation of food particles into the airways, causing cough and recurrent pulmonary infections. Other symptoms related to the upper gastrointestinal tract are often present. In particular, a high presence of reflux symptoms and esophagitis have been reported, with pH-proven GERD in as high as 44% of patients. GERD has long been postulated as a chronic irritative element in causing damage in the cricopharyngeal muscle that predisposes to the development of a ZD. GERD should be properly investigated in these patients given the theoretic but unproven risk that the cricopharyngeal myotomy may favor esophagopharyngeal and laryngeal reflux by eliminating the barrier between the pharynx and the esophagus.\n\nTable 18.1\n\nZenker Diverticulum: Clinical Presentation and Symptoms\n\nModified from Lerut T, Coosemans W, Decaluw\u00e9 H, et al. Pathophysiology and treatment of Zenker diverticulum. In: Yeo CJ, ed. *Shackelford\u2019s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract* . 7th ed. Elsevier Sunders, Philadelphia; 2013.\n\n| **Mean Age** | 68 years (38\u201392) |\n| --- | --- |\n| \\>70 years | 50% |\n| \\>80 years | 20% |\n| **Symptoms** | |\n| Mean duration | 37.4 months |\n| Dysphagia | 80% |\n| Regurgitation | 58% |\n| Choking | 20% |\n| Coughing | 18% |\n| Globus sensation | 21% |\n| Weight loss | 23% |\n| Others | 14% |\n| **Associated Pathology** | |\n| Pulmonary infections | 37% |\n| Upper gastrointestinal tract pathology | 60% |\n| Documented gastroesophageal reflux disease | 44% |\n| Other comorbidity | 52% |\n\nThe diagnosis of a Zenker is radiological in most patients. A barium or Gastrografin swallow will readily show the posteriorly located pouch in the neck. Penetration or aspiration in the airways may also be seen. In the lateral projection, the diverticulum can be adequately measured, especially as far as the distance from the septum and the bottom of the pouch is concerned, since this measure may guide the choice of treatment ( Fig. 18.5 ). Radiological evaluation should precede any endoscopic examination in a patient with dysphagia and suspected ZD, given the risk of iatrogenic perforation during endoscopy. Endoscopy may be useful in evaluating the dimensions of the pouch and its neck further, and in assessing the morphology of the septum between the esophageal lumen and the diverticulum. It may reveal inflammation of the diverticular mucosa due to stasis, and even a possible, albeit anecdotic, neoplastic degeneration.\n\nA radiographic view labeled A and an adjacent diagram labeled B. Part A shows a marked structure with arrows and an asterisk. Part B illustrates the same structure with a label d and dots. The radiographic view is labeled A and an adjacent diagram is labeled B. In A, a radiograph displays a tubular structure with a marked region that contains an asterisk. Two arrows point to the upper part of the structure. The contrast medium outlines the anatomy that displays an area of interest. In B, an adjacent line drawing represents the same structure, which highlights the marked region with a label d and small dots. The diagram simplifies the radiograph for interpretation. Both radiographs and diagrams focus on an anatomical abnormality or medical condition within the tubular structure.\n\nFig. 18.5\n\nIn dedicated centers, HRM combined with fluorography is the most useful tool to investigate the complex pharyngoesophageal swallowing events, but detailed pharyngoesophageal manometric studies, outside a research program, are not necessary for the routine diagnosis of ZD. However, manometry may reveal coexisting esophageal motility abnormalities and, combined with pH-monitoring, detect an underlying GERD.\n\n### Therapy\n\nTreatment is indicated for symptomatic ZD. A conservative treatment with a \u201cwait and see\u201d attitude may be reasonable in asymptomatic patients. Still, possible complications (namely aspiration and \u201cab ingestis\u201d pneumonia) should always be considered, especially in old and frail patients. There is no medical treatment for ZD, and the modification of the diet and rehabilitation play little role. The treatment of symptomatic ZD is invasive and has evolved over the last decades. Currently there are three main treatment options: open surgery, rigid endoscopy, and flexible endoscopy. The key intervention common in all three options is the division of the cricopharyngeal muscle, for which dysfunction is the main cause of the development of the diverticulum and forms the septum between the esophagus and the pouch.\n\nThe traditional standard surgical treatment of ZD consisted the myotomy of the UES, the resection or suspension (pexy) of the pouch, or even myotomy alone for small diverticula. Alternative endoscopic procedures that divided the septum between the diverticula and the esophageal wall using cautery or laser were also described but gained little popularity because of the high risk of severe complications. The situation changed in 1993 when Collard proposed dividing and suturing the diverticular and esophageal wall simultaneously using a laparoscopic stapler introduced through a special endoscope (the Weerda diverticuloscope). This procedure rapidly gained popularity and became the treatment of choice for ZD in many centers. Then in 1995, Ishioka et al. in Brazil and Mulder et al. in the Netherlands reported their first results using a flexible endoscope for cutting the diverticular septum. Finally, in 2016 per-oral endoscopic myotomy (POEM) techniques such as those used at the LES for achalasia were introduced for the treatment of ZD.\n\nA description of therapeutic options for ZD is given later.\n\n#### Cricopharyngeal Myotomy With or Without Diverticulectomy\n\nUnder general anesthesia, the patient is positioned supine on the operating table with a small pillow under the shoulders and with the head hyperextended and slightly turned on the right side. The incision is performed along the anterior border of the left sternocleidomastoid muscle ( Fig. 18.3A ). After dividing the subcutaneous tissue and the platysma, the pharynx and esophagus are exposed by retracting the sternocleidomastoid muscle and vessels (carotid artery and jugular vein) laterally, and the laryngothyroid bloc medially ( Fig. 18.3B ). The region\u2019s exposure is facilitated by dividing the omohyoid muscle and the middle thyroid vein ( Fig. 18.3C ). Dividing the lower thyroid artery helps in further exposing and preventing the risk of damaging the recurrent laryngeal nerve. After exposing the pharyngoesophageal region, the diverticulum is identified and isolated from the surrounding tissues by blunt dissection until its neck is identified on the posterior pharyngeal wall. The transverse fibers of the cricopharyngeal muscle are easy to see below the neck of the diverticulum. The myotomy is performed from this level to the cervical esophagus, over a length of at least 5 cm, using a scalpel and scissors ( Fig. 18.6A ). When the myotomy is complete, the mucosa bulges free through the muscle edges ( Fig. 18.3E ). If the diverticulum is 3 cm or more in size, it is transected with a linear stapler ( Fig. 18.6A ). Diverticula nearing 2 cm in size can be inverted below the pharyngeal muscles and sutured to the muscle layer with two re-absorbable stitches, thus performing a sort of intramural suspension. The suspension of the diverticulum to the prevertebral fascia (diverticulopexy) with four to five suspending stitches is preferred by some surgeons as an alternative to the resection even for diverticula larger than 2 cm. Very small (<1 cm) pouches can be safely left in place as the myotomy alone reduces the pouch and alleviates the symptoms. A drain is left for 24 hours to avoid hematomas in the neck region, and after a hydrosoluble contrast study, the patient is allowed to start a liquid and soft diet. Complications of the procedure may be the development of hematomas of the cervical region, which can jeopardize the airway patency and require immediate surgical revision, and perforations of the esophageal mucosa, that can be repaired during the operation (a pedunculated muscle flap from the sternocleidomastoid muscle may be used to buttress the repairing suture) or conservatively treated (with nil per os \\[NPO; nothing by mouth\\] and parenteral support) if discovered with the contrast control study. These surgical complications are rare; other more severe and potentially lethal complications such as aspiration and pneumonia may occur in patients with neurological or myogenic dysphagia, and are related to the underlying pathology and the severity of the swallowing impairment.\n\nTwo diagrams of a surgical procedure show steps with surgical tools and clamps. The diagrams labeled A and B of a surgical procedure. In A, a surgical tool and a clamp are used to measure and manipulate, with a label that indicates 4 centimeters. Clamps secure the area in B, and the procedure continues with additional tools.\n\nFig. 18.6\n\n#### Endoscopic Stapling Diverticulostomy\n\nUnder general anesthesia with orotracheal intubation, the patient is placed supine on the operating table, with a small pillow under the upper torso and the head hyperextended. The surgeon sits behind the patient\u2019s head. A Weerda diverticuloscope is inserted in the hypopharynx, positioning its anterior blade in the esophageal lumen and the posterior blade in the diverticulum. A 5-mm diameter telescope is passed through the scope. After visualization of the septum between the esophagus and the diverticulum, the diverticuloscope is fixed with the help of a chest support. The length of the diverticulum is accurately measured with a graduated rod. A surgical endostapler is then inserted through the Weerda diverticuloscope to divide the septum between the diverticulum and the esophageal lumen and to perform the diverticuloesophagostomy. The anvil is placed in the lumen of the diverticulum and the cartridge in the esophageal lumen. The endostapler sutures the posterior esophageal wall to the anterior wall of the diverticulum over a length of about 30 mm and transects the tissue between three rows of staples on each side ( Fig. 18.7 ). With this technique, provided the pouch has adequate dimensions, the section of the UES (cricomyotomy) is also performed. A second stapling step is typically required depending on the actual size of the diverticulum. Two traction sutures applied at the apex of the septum with a laparoscopic endostitching device can help to engage the septum between the stapler jaws and allow a more complete septal division ( Fig. 18.7 ). Electrocoagulation with endosurgical scissors may be used to complete the dissection of the septum at the distal end on the stapled line. The suture lines are then checked for hemostasis and the scope is removed. The procedure takes about 20 minutes to complete, with the major complication being the inability to adequately extend the neck and damage to the teeth, tongue, jaw, or pharynx during attempts at insertion of the diverticuloscope. Mucosal damage and perforation of the diverticulum are also possible complications, albeit rarer than with the open access ( Fig. 18.8 ).\n\nA closer view of a mechanical device with sharp and pointed components. #REF!\n\nFig. 18.7\n\nAn endoscopic view of the internal area during surgery, with stitches and some blood. #REF!\n\nFig. 18.8\n\nThe harmonic scalpel (Ultracision, Ethicon) operating through the diverticuloscope has been also used to divide the septum as an alternative to stapling. This device can simultaneously cut and coagulate tissue with minimal thermal spreading and optimal hemostasis, and its small caliber allows easy maneuverability through the scope. The CO <sub>2 </sub> laser, first introduced in 1981 by van Overbeek may represent another alternative to stapling. This is a very precise technique, but widespread adoption has been limited since it is strictly operator dependent and carries an intrinsic risk of perforations and mediastinitis.\n\n#### Fiberoptic Endoscopic Septum Division (FESD)\n\nA flexible endoscope avoids the issues with the inability to place the rigid diverticuloscope, and several endoscopic techniques have been used to divide the septum between the esophageal lumen and the diverticulum. These can be valuable in elderly patients at high risk for general anesthesia or with contraindications for the previously described techniques (e.g., the inability to open their mouth widely, or diverticula <2 cm in size). Usually, the patients are under conscious sedation and the procedure is performed in the endoscopy unit. It is generally possible to obtain a good view of the septum. In addition, a nasogastric tube is useful to optimize the exposure and it helps to protect the anterior esophageal wall. A variety of different endoscopic accessories (caps, hoods, overtubes) can be used to improve the septum exposure and protect the esophagus and the pouch from thermal injury. The new soft diverticuloscope (Zenker overtube, Cook Endoscopy) is a transparent soft-rubber overtube that has two distal flaps that protect the esophagus anteriorly and the diverticulum posteriorly. The overtube is passed over the endoscope and advanced under direct vision to properly display the septum to be cut. The incision is made starting from the rim between the esophageal orifice and the opening of the diverticulum. Different cutting devices can be used (e.g., the needle-knife, the monopolar forceps, the hook-knife, the argon plasma coagulator). A clip-assisted technique has been introduced by some authors to reduce the risk of perforation and mediastinitis. With this technique (clip and cut), prior to dissection, two endoclips are placed on either side of the septum. A metal endoclip may also be placed at the apex of the incision to prevent tearing of the section and microperforation. As with the stapling technique described above, the aim of the procedure is to completely obliterate the septum, thus achieving a wide opening between the diverticulum and the esophagus (diverticulostomy) ( Fig. 18.9 ). Only one session is usually needed for small diverticula (\u22642 cm), whereas repeated sessions become necessary if they are larger. At any session, a 1.5- to 2.0-cm incision is performed, repeated in 1-week time. A nasogastric tube is usually placed for nutritional purposes for 2 days. Complications of this technique are represented by bleeding from the suture line, usually managed endoscopically, and perforations that account for 3% of procedures but very seldom require surgical treatment.\n\nAn endoscopic view inside a body cavity, with debris and tissue. #REF!\n\nFig. 18.9\n\n#### Per-Oral Endoscopic Myotomy of Zenker Diverticulum\n\nIn 2016 Li et al. described a new endoscopic technique for the treatment of ZD, inspired by the POEM procedure developed for achalasia, which they named \u201csubmucosal tunnelling endoscopic septum division.\u201d Subsequently, the term Z-POEM was introduced and was adopted in further studies as the preferred acronym to define the tunneling technique for ZD. The theoretical advantage of this approach is that it can more readily perform a complete transection of the entire muscular septum by operating within a submucosal tunnel, thus maintaining mucosal integrity. This procedure has the potential to reduce the risk of perforation, mediastinitis, and recurrence. As with the FESD technique, the procedure is performed with the patient in the left lateral decubitus position under conscious sedation. No prophylactic antibiotic therapy is required. A submucosal injection and subsequent longitudinal mucosotomy is performed 3 cm proximal to the septum to make the tunnel entry ( Fig. 18.10A ). A submucosal tunnel is then created along both sides of the septum, ending 1 to 2 cm distal to the bottom of the diverticulum, in order to have an adequate endoscopic view of the entire muscular septum ( Fig. 18.10B ). The UES fibers forming the septum are then transected down to the bottom of the diverticulum and further into the normal esophageal muscle. The mucosal incision site is finally sealed with up to three clips. In 2020 Repici et al. conceived an alternative third space approach, called per-oral endoscopic septotomy (POES), to overcome the technical challenges of the Z-POEM technique. In the \u201cstandard\u201d Z-POEM approach, the initial mucosotomy is created approximately 1 to 3 cm proximal to the septum, at the transition between the pharynx and the UES. In this area, muscular contractions and anatomical limitations may reduce the ability to open and close the mucosal incision properly ( Fig. 18.10C ). Thus, in order to gain direct access to the ZD muscular septum without the need for long tunnelling starting at the pharyngeal level, they proposed to perform the mucosal cut alongside the long axis of the septum, and directly on top of it ( Video 18.1 ). Unlike the \u201cclassic\u201d Z-POEM, the procedural time is shorter, and it seems to be comparable with that of standard FESD. The procedure is generally performed in an outpatient setting with discharge the same day or after an overnight admission. The adverse events reported to date are represented, as for the FESD technique, by rare bleeding episodes, mucosal perforations, and gas diffusion among neck and mediastinal tissues: they seem to be, however, less frequent than with FESD.\n\nThree diagrams labeled A, B, and C, show different stages of a medical procedure that involves a tube and a body part. The diagram consists of three panels labeled A, B, and C. Diagram A shows the normal body path. Diagram B shows a tube inserted into a body part. Diagram C shows the tube partially inside the body part with a star that indicates a specific point. The fourth diagram shows the tube fully inserted with two stars indicating particular points. The diagrams illustrate different stages of a medical procedure that involves the insertion of a tube.\n\nFig. 18.10\n\n### Results and Discussion\n\nThe fundamental step in the therapy for ZD lies in dividing the cricopharyngeal muscle fibers (i.e., the UES). The pouch may be excised (as in the open surgical approach) or left in place after a wide communication with the esophagus has been created (as in all transoral procedures). As obvious as it may seem today, this notion is a recent acquisition that is based empirically on the finding of much lower complication (i.e., leakage) and recurrence rates when myotomy is added to the diverticulectomy. The surgical cricopharyngeal myotomy, combined with either diverticulectomy or diverticulum suspension (or diverticulopexy), or even alone in the case of small (<2 cm) diverticula, ensures symptom relief in nearly all treated patients ( Table 18.2 , Fig. 18.11 ) and was the mainstay of ZD treatment during the last century. Common to any neck surgery, the related morbidity is represented by some local hematomas and recurrent nerve palsy, whereas leakages, which occur in about 2% of cases, are directly linked to the procedure. In a 2019 study using the National Surgical Quality Improvement Program (NSQIP) dsatabase of the American College of Surgeons, evaluating 597 patients undergoing open transcervical diverticulectomy for a ZD from 2005 to 2017, 4.2% of patients had surgical and 4.4% medical complications with 6.5% unplanned reoperations and 2.7% readmissions. Moreover, the mortality rate of this procedure was far from negligible, being 0.7% in the said report and directly related to the age and the ASA status of the patients.\n\nTable 18.2\n\nOutcome of Open Surgical Treatment for Zenker diverticulum. Only papers published after 2000 and a sample size >20 patients were considered\n\n| Author, Year | Time Period | Method | *N* | Adverse Events *N* (%) | Mortality *N* (%) | Good Results *N* (%) | Median Follow-Up (months) | Recurrence or Failure *N* (%) |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Leporrier, 2001 | 1988\u201398 | DM, PM | 39 | 6 (15.4) | 0 | 39 (100) | 36 | 0 |\n| Gutschow, 2002 | 1984\u20132000 | M, DM, PM | 67 | 3 (4.5) | 1 (1.5) | 65 (97) | 72 (2\u2013167) | 0 |\n| Jougon, 2003 | 1987\u20132000 | DM | 73 | 3 (4) | 0 | 73 (100) | 72 (3\u2013156) | 0 |\n| Bonavina 2007 | 1976\u20132006 | DM | 116 | 4 (3.5) | 1 (0.9) | 109 (94) | 48 | 2 (1.7) |\n| Lerut, 2013 | 1975\u20132003 | PM, M, DM | 289 | 26 (8.5) | 0 | 283 (98) | n.r. | 6 (2) |\n| Rizzetto, 2008 | 1993\u20132007 | DM, PM | 77 | 10 (13) | 0 | 74 (96) | 41 (18\u201388) | 0 |\n| Henry, 2013 | n.r. | DM | 24 | 4 (16.7) | 0 | 23 (95.8) | 33 | 0 |\n| Leibowitz, 2014 | 1995\u20132011 | DM | 27 | 3 (11.3) | 0 | 26 (96.3) | n.r. | 1 (3.7) |\n| Nitschke, 2020 | 2004\u201316 | DM | 41 | n.r. | n.r. | 27 (66) | 36.5 | 3 (7.3) |\n| Patel, 2020 | 2013\u20138 | DM, PM, M | 90 | 13 (14.4) | 0 | 63 (70) | n.r. | n.r. |\n| W\u0142odarczyk, 2021 | 2000\u201320 | DM | 65 | 12 (16.9) | 0 | 63 (96.9) | n.r. | 2 (3.6) |\n| Total | | | 908 | 94 (10.3) | 2 (0.22) | 845 (93.6) | \u2013 | 14 (1.5) |\n\n*D* , Diverticulectomy; *M* , Myotomy; n.r., not reported; *P* , diverticulopexy.\n\nTwo radiographs labeled A and B show different views. Part A shows the pharynx area while Part B reveals the pharyngeal contraction. The radiographic views are labeled A and B. In A, a radiograph with contrast highlights a tubular structure with a pouch-like formation. The contrast medium outlines the structure that displays an out pouch or dilation in the upper part. The adjacent anatomical features are faintly visible. In B, a different radiographic view shows a narrowed and irregular contrast-filled structure. The contrast medium highlights a constricted region which suggests a structural abnormality. The bony structures of the neck and spine are partially visible in the background. The photos likely represent a medical condition that affects the tubular structure.\n\nFig. 18.11\n\nThe risks of complications and even death cannot be completely overcome with endoscopic techniques, which show a mortality rate of 0.31% (stapler) and 0.23% (FESD), but they are generally lower than with open surgery. The results in Tables 18.3\u201318.5 show that satisfactory results can be achieved in more than 80% of patients with any endoscopic approach ( Fig. 18.11 ). A 2022 meta-analysis on 12 studies using Z-POEM in treating patients with ZD reported a pooled rate of treatment success of 90.6% (87.1%\u201394.1%) with no evidence of heterogeneity ( *I* <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> \\=0%). Moreover, the rates of treatment success observed at 3 months (90.6%) were maintained at 1 year (90%) and 2 years (89.6%), with a very low recurrence rate (2.6%) and with only 7.6% and 3.3% of overall and serious adverse events, respectively. This figure is very attractive, as the procedure demands only about 20 minutes of general anesthesia or, better still, conscious sedation in the endoscopic unit with the flexible endoscope. This is particularly relevant given the intrinsic characteristics of these patients. The endoscopic treatment of ZD, with its \u201cminimally invasive\u201d nature, has spread rapidly among most centers and, at present, it is considered the treatment of choice in this condition.\n\nTable 18.3\n\nOutcome of Transoral Rigid Procedures With Stapler for Zenker Diverticulum. Only papers published after 2000 and a sample size >20 patients were considered\n\n| Author, Year | Time Period | *N* | Adverse Events *N* (%) | Mortality *N* (%) | Good Results *N* (%) | Median Follow-Up (months) | Recurrence or Failure *N* (%) |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Cook, 2000 | 1995\u20139 | 74 | 4 (5.4) | 0 | 70 (95) | n.r. | 6 (8.4 |\n| L\u00fcscher, 2000 | 1997\u20138 | 23 | 1 (4.3) | 0 | 20 (86.9) | 12 | 1 (4.3) |\n| Sood, 2