7) | 27 (100) | 18 | 0 |\n| <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">a </sup> Visser, 2016 | 2004\u201314 | 33 | 4 (12.1) | 0 | 22 (67) | n.r. | 11 (33) |\n| Nitschke, 2020 | 2004\u201311 | 57 | 6 (10.6) | 0 | 46 (80.7) | 36.5 | 11 (19.3) |\n| Total | | 660 | 55 (8.3) | 3 (0.4) | 541/624 (86.7) | \u2013 | 101 (15.3) |\n\n*n.r.,* Not reported.\n\nTable 18.5\n\nOutcome of Transoral Flexible Procedures for Zenker Diverticulum. Only papers published after 2000 and a sample size >20 patients were considered\n\n| Author, Year | Time Period | *N* | Adverse Events *n* (%) | Mortality *n* (%) | Good Results *n* (%) | Median Follow-Up (months) | Recurrence or Failure *n* (%) |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Rabenstein, 2007 | 2002\u20136 | 41 | 8 (19.5) | 0 | 36 (87.8) | 16 (6\u201343) | 5 (12.2) |\n| Vogelsang, 2007 | 2001\u20134 | 31 | 7 (22.6) | 0 | 26 (84) | 26 (14\u201349) | 5 (16) |\n| Christiaens, 2007 | n.r. | 21 | 1 (4.8) | 0 | 19 (90.5) | 22.6 | 2 (9.5) |\n| Case, 2010 | 2006\u201310 | 22 | 8 (36.4) | 0 | 22 (100) | 12.7 \u00b1 9.2 | 7 (31.8) |\n| Repici, 2010 | 2005\u20138 | 32 | 2 (6.2) | 0 | 29 (91.7) | 23.9 (12\u201348) | 3 (8.3) |\n| Huberty, 2013 | 2002\u201311 | 150 | 4 (2.7) | 0 | 119 (79.3) | 43 (13\u2013121) | 31 (20.7) |\n| Laqui\u00e8re, 2015 | 2009\u201313 | 42 | 8 (19) | 0 | 37 (88) | \\>16 | 6 (14.2) |\n| Halland, 2016 | 2006\u201313 | 52 | 11 (21) | 0 | 38 (73.1) | 26 (0.5\u201368) | 14 (26.9) |\n| Pescarus, 2016 | 2008\u201314 | 26 | 2 (7.7) | 0 | 26 (100) | 22 (1\u201368) | 3 (11.5) |\n| Antonello, 2016 | 2010\u20136 | 34 | 3 (8.8) | 0 | 28 (82.3) | 18 (6\u201350) | 5 (14.7) |\n| Costamagna, 2016 | 2007\u201313 | 89 | 3 (3.4) | 0 | 71 (85.5) | 48 | 9 (10.8) |\n| Rouquette, 2017 | 2012\u20136 | 24 | 2 (8.3) | 0 | 21 (87.5) | 19.5 (6\u201353) | 3 (12.5) |\n| Ishaq, 2020 | 2013\u20138 | 36 | 2 (5.5) | 0 | 32 (88.3) | 19 | 2 (5.6) |\n| Calavas, 2021 | 2009\u201317 | 40 | 14 (26.4) | 0 | 34 (91) | 41 \u00b1 27 | 5 (9) |\n| Mittal, 2021 | 2012\u20138 | 137 | 9 (6.6) | 0 | 76/101 (75.2) | 5.7 \u00b1 7.5 | 23 (16.8) |\n| Total | | 777 | 82 (10.5) | 0 | 614/741 (82.9) | \\- | 123 (15.8) |\n\nThus far, there have been no prospective trials comparing the different endoscopic treatments, one with the other or with open surgery. Information comes from retrospective series or prospectively recorded case series, using one or more of these techniques. Moreover, given the rarity of the disease and its prevalence in elderly patients, often with severe comorbidities, it is unlikely that randomized studies can be performed in the near future. A systematic review on available literature (28 comparative studies and 43 cohort studies), analyzing the results of surgical and the various endoscopic techniques (except Z-POEM), reported that the rate of failure was significantly higher with endoscopic techniques than with external surgical approaches (18.4% vs. 4.2%, *P* <.001). A further network meta-analysis on nine cohort studies, consisting of 903 patients treated with transcervical diverticulectomy ( *n* \\= 150), stapler-assisted diverticulostomy ( *n* \\= 470), or laser-assisted diverticulostomy ( *n* \\= 283), was published in 2021 ; this study confirmed that the open approach has a decreased likelihood of persistent or recurrent symptoms following surgery compared with both endoscopic techniques. On the contrary, overall postoperative complications tended to occur more frequently after the transcervical approach (11% vs. 7 %) and presented a different pattern with the various approaches. Mediastinitis (1.2% vs. 0.3%, *P* <.01) and emphysema (3.0% vs. 0.1%, *P* <.01) occurred more often with the endoscopic treatment than fistula (3.7% vs. 1.2%, *P* <.01), recurrent nerve palsy (3.4% vs. 0.3%, *P* <.001), and hematoma (2.2% vs. 0.6%, *P* <.01), which occurred more frequently with the transcervical treatment. Procedure-related deaths were infrequent in both groups (0.9% for the open approach vs. 0.4% for endoscopic techniques). The length of stay was significantly shorter after endoscopic treatment. Finally, the cost-effectiveness of open versus endoscopic repair of ZD was also evaluated in 2022 utilizing the economic decision tree ; the overall cost of open and endoscopic surgery was $48,433 and $34,179, respectively. Particularly with the current focus on rising healthcare costs, these results can serve as an important adjunct to medical decision making for patients undergoing treatment for ZD.\n\nRegarding the comparison between Z-POEM and the other described techniques, a systematic review was published in 2022. Five studies compared Z-POEM with FESD in 225 and 258 patients, respectively; Z-POEM showed a better clinical outcome than FESD (92.9% vs. 84.9% of good results, respectively, *P* \\=.004), whereas all the other considered parameters (technical success rate, adverse event rate, and clinical recurrence) showed no differences between the new and the consolidated technique. These selected studies were all retrospective, with huge differences in follow-up (from 3.4 to 24 months) and some published in abstract form only. Table 18.6 summarizes the studies using this technique published to date. Of course, more comparative studies need to be performed to achieve better evidence on the role of this new treatment. Nevertheless, Z-POEM seems very promising and possibly superior to other endoscopic, consolidated techniques.\n\nTable 18.6\n\nOutcome of \u201cThird Space\u201d Procedures (Z-POEM or POES) for Zenker Diverticulum\n\n| Author, Year | Time Period | *N* | Adverse Events *n* (%) | Mortality *n* (%) | Good Results *n* (%) | Median Follow-Up (months) | Recurrence or Failure (%) |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">a </sup> Mittal, 2021 | 2012\u20138 | 24 | 4 (16.7) | 0 | 20 (91) | n.r. | 2 (8.3) |\n| <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">b </sup> Yang, 2020 | 2014\u20138 | 75 | 5 (6.7) | 0 | 69 (92) | 10 (3.4\u20134.5) | 1 (1.3) |\n| <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">a </sup> Repici, 2020 | 2017\u20139 | 20 | 0 | 0 | 19 (95) | 12 (6\u201320) | 0 |\n| <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">a </sup> Klingler, 2021 | 2015\u201320 | 19 | 2 (10.5) | 0 | 17 (89.5) | 9.6 (4.7\u201315.5) | 2 (10.5) |\n| <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">b </sup> Al Ghamdi, 2022 | 2016\u20139 | 119 | 20 (16.8) | 0 | 110 (92.7) | (9 \u00b1 10) | 17 (14.3) |\n| <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">b </sup> Budnicka, 2021 | 2019\u201320 | 22 | 3 (13.6) | 0 | 20 (90.9) | 8.8 (7\u201310) | 0 |\n| <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">b </sup> Elkholy, 2021 | 2018\u20139 | 24 | 0 | 0 | 23 (95.8) | 10 (6\u201324) | 0 |\n| <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">b </sup> Kahaleh, 2022\u00b0 | 2017\u201320 | 52 | 5 (9.6) | 0 | 48 (92) | 3.4 | 3 (6) |\n| Total | | 355 | 39 (11) | 0 | 326 (91.8) | | 35 (9.8) |\n\n*n.r.,* Not reported.\n\nIt is difficult to draw final conclusions from these studies. Endoscopic treatment is very attractive because it is less invasive and has a lower complication rate although, when compared with surgery, it is sometimes less effective in relieving dysphagia completely. For these reasons, in the last two decades the endoscopic treatment (which any described technique) has become the treatment of choice of ZD. Endoscopic stapling has other drawbacks mainly related to the size of the diverticulum; in the case of a small diverticulum (<2 cm), the stapler anvil is too long to be properly accommodated inside the pouch and the cricopharyngeal fibers cannot be transected completely. The same is true for FESD, which can manage to transect the septum completely but, again, the fibers of the UES cannot be cut entirely in case of small diverticula. This may change with the new Z-POEM (and POES) technique, where the third space access allows the complete division of the muscular fibers of the UES and cervical esophagus.\n\nOn the other hand, very large diverticula (>5 cm) plunging into the mediastinum carry the risk of vascular lesions if they are transected blindly. Moreover, with such a long septotomy, the risk of creating a wide \u201ccloaca\u201d must be considered. The myotomy of the UES is probably more effectively achieved with open surgery, when the muscle fibers are cut under direct vision and the edges of the myotomy are further separated by a blunt dissection, leaving the submucosa widely exposed.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThe paradigm of treating ZD has shifted in the last two decades from the surgical to the endoscopic treatment. The surgical treatment, with its intrinsic better long-term results, can be reserved nowadays only for young patients (<60 years), with a low surgical risk, which represent however the minority of the patients with ZD. All the other patients can be treated with rigid or flexible endoscopic techniques, with their intrinsic advantages and limitations. The choice of the type of treatment must be made therefore on the single patient\u2019s basis and, of not lesser importance, on the expertise locally available, since old and frail patients (as the rule in ZD) cannot travel too far away to get the best possible treatment. New per-oral flexible endoscopic techniques may be indicated in all the patients with any size diverticulum, but more studies with longer follow-up are necessary to support this very attractive technique.\n\n## References\n\n1.: World Health Organization : International Classification of Functioning, Disability and Health (ICF) . 2001 . WHO ,\n\nView In Article\n\n2.: Attrill S., White S., Murray J., Hammond S., Doeltgen S.: Impact of oropharyngeal dysphagia on healthcare cost and length of stay in hospital: a systematic review . BMC Health Serv Res 2018; 18 (1): pp. 594.\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: Rivelsrud M.C., Hartelius L., Bergstr\u00f6m L., L\u00f8vstad M., Speyer R.: Prevalence of oropharyngeal dysphagia in adults in different healthcare settings: a systematic review and meta-analyses . Dysphagia 2023; 38 (1): pp. 76-121.\n\nView In 