4.3%20156%207.1c-.2-.4%200-.7.3-.7h5.8c.4%200%20.6.1.8.5l6.5%2011.3h.1L176%206.9c.2-.4.5-.5.9-.5h5.7c.4%200%20.5.3.3.7l-10%2017.2L183.7%2043c.2.4%200%20.7-.3.7h-5.8zM192.015%2019c-.2%200-.338-.004-.3-.2V8.4h-3.3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n\n\nNeed help? Chat with AI Buddy!\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[17. Obesity and GERD - ClinicalKey|17. Obesity and GERD]]\n**Next:** [[19. Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment - ClinicalKey|19. Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "18. Cricopharyngeal Dysfunction and Zenker Diverticulum - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Cricopharyngeal Dysfunction and Zenker Diverticulum', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Cricopharyngeal Dysfunction and Zenker Diverticulum', 'Oropharyngeal Dysphagia', 'Anatomic', 'Neurological', 'Central Nervous System', 'Peripheral Nervous System', 'Cricopharyngeal Dysfunction and Zenker Diverticulum / Oropharyngeal Dysphagia', 'Cricopharyngeal Dysfunction and Zenker Diverticulum / Anatomic', 'Cricopharyngeal Dysfunction and Zenker Diverticulum / Neurological'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '18', '181-199', 2, 73, FALSE, TRUE),
('Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment', 'shackelford-9th-ed-19-achalasia-diagnosis-and-treatment', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment\n\nMonica Polcz; Paul D. Colavita; Lee L. Swanstr\u00f6m\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 19, 200-210\n\n## Epidemiology of Achalasia\n\nAchalasia is a rare, primary motility disorder of the esophagus, defined by absence of normal peristalsis and failure of swallow-induced relaxation of the lower esophageal sphincter (LES). The first described treatment for \u201ccardiospasm\u201d in the 1600s was self-dilatation with oral passage of a whale rib-bone with an attached sponge. In 1937 Lendrum proposed the pathologic mechanism of failed LES relaxation, leading to the new name of achalasia.\n\nThe annual incidence of achalasia has previously been estimated at approximately 1 in 100,000 with a prevalence of 10 in 100,000 ; however, recent studies suggest these values likely underestimate current metrics. A recent analysis of IBM MarketScan and Medicare databases suggests an annual incidence closer to 10.5 per 100,000 persons <65 years and 26 per 100,000 for ages \u226565, with prevalences of 18 in 100,000 and 162 in 100,000, respectively. Estimated direct medical costs in the United States exceeded $408 million in 2018.\n\nThe pathophysiology of achalasia involves lymphocyte-mediated inflammation and damage to the ganglion cells in Auerbach myenteric plexus, leading to loss of neurotransmitters such as vasoactive intestinal peptide and nitric oxide. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The inhibitory ganglionic neurons, which serve to mediate LES relaxation and the timing of peristalsis, are disproportionately affected. Autoimmune (including antimyenteric neuron antibodies), viral (measles, varicella), and genetic processes have been implicated, and gene expression profiling demonstrates enrichment of signaling pathways related to cytokine response and viral defense in patients with achalasia. As the exact underlying mechanism precipitating the development of achalasia remains unknown and may vary between patients, current treatment options are not considered curative and focus instead on symptom relief through disruption of the LES.\n\n## Diagnosis of Achalasia\n\nAt the time of presentation, dysphagia is the most frequent complaint (94%), followed by regurgitation (75%) and heartburn (52%). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Chest pain, weight loss, odynophagia, cough, and recurrent aspiration pneumonias may also be present. Prior to referral, symptoms may often be mistaken for gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) and often have been present for a number of years. The Eckardt score (ES) is the most commonly utilized grading system for symptom severity in achalasia ( Table 19.1 ) and has been validated for assessment of symptom improvement posttreatment. The ES assigns 0 to 3 points based on the quantity of weight loss and the frequency of the following symptoms: dysphagia, regurgitation, and chest pain, with the ES equaling the sum of these values. A score of \u22643 posttreatment is generally considered treatment success although this is sometimes criticized as it is unweighted and rather general, for example, a patient could have complete relief of their primary symptom (e.g., dysphagia) but still have reflux symptoms giving them an ES >3, etc.).\n\nTable 19.1\n\nEckardt Score\n\n| Score | Weight Loss, kg | Dysphagia | Retrosternal Pain | Regurgitation |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| *0* | None | None | None | None |\n| *1* | <5 | Occasional | Occasional | Occasional |\n| *2* | 5\u201310 | Daily | Daily | Daily |\n| *3* | \\>10 | Each meal | Each meal | Each meal |\n\nAn upper gastrointestinal series, or contrast esophagram, along with upper endoscopy are the usual initial tests to evaluate dysphagia. Definitive diagnosis is made with high-resolution manometry. Endoscopy is important to rule out pseudoachalasia from an obstruction, such as cancer, and endoscopic ultrasound or computed tomography should be considered when suspicion for malignancy causing obstructive symptoms is high.\n\n### Esophagram\n\nA contrast esophagram will often demonstrate a \u201cbird\u2019s beak\u201d tapering of the distal esophagus, with progressive dilation and tortuosity of the esophagus demonstrated in later stages of the disease. Failure or delayed passage of a barium tablet also supports the diagnosis of an esophagogastric junction (EGJ) outlet obstruction such as that seen with achalasia.\n\nA timed barium swallow (TBS) is another measure that provides objective data on esophageal emptying and is commonly used before and as follow-up after treatment for achalasia. TBS involves ingestion of 200 mL of low-density barium sulfate, with radiographs taken at baseline and then 1, 2, and 5 minutes after ingestion. The height and width of the barium column at each time period are recorded to estimate percentage of emptying. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Endoscopy\n\nUpper endoscopy is mandatory to rule out other causes of esophageal obstruction such as malignancy. Upper endoscopy may appear normal in early stages of the disease. Esophagitis from stasis and/or yeast esophagitis may be present. As the disease progresses, dilatation of the esophageal body with tortuosity or sigmoidization may be noted, as well as esophageal narrowing or resistance at the gastroesophageal junction (GEJ).\n\nImpedance planimetry (Endoscopic Functional Lumen Imaging Probe, EndoFLIP, Medtronic, Minneapolis, MN) can also be used during endoscopy to gain detailed geometric data of the esophageal lumen and EGJ, which may help support the diagnosis of achalasia. This involves distention of an endoscopically placed balloon to a fixed volume; measurements of luminal cross-sectional area and pressure in the balloon are used to estimate the distensibility index (DI) of the EGJ. Although suggested cutoff values for EGJ-DI in the diagnosis of achalasia vary in the literature, a meta-analysis of normative values suggests that at a distention volume of 40 mL, 95% of normal subjects will have an EGJ-DI above 2 mm <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> /mmHg, while at 60 mL in a 16-cm balloon, an EGJ-DI below 3 mm <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> /mmHg is considered abnormal. In addition to low EGJ-DI, absent contractility or repetitive retrograde contractions may be seen.\n\n### High-Resolution Manometry\n\nHigh-resolution manometry (HRM) is the gold standard in diagnosis of achalasia.\n\nThe Chicago Classification, first published in 2009 and most recently updated in 2020 with version 4.0, categorizes esophageal motility disorders based on measurements obtained on HRM ( Table 19.2 ).\n\nTable 19.2\n\nClassification and Definition of Manometric Disorders in Chicago Classification Version 4.0 (CCv4.0)\n\n| Classification | Disorder | Definition |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Disorders of EGJ outflow | Type I achalasia Type II achalasia Type III achalasia EGJ outflow obstruction | Abnormal median IRP and 100% failed peristalsis Abnormal median IRP, 100% failed peristalsis, \u226520% swallows with panesophageal pressurization Abnormal median IRP, 100% failed peristalsis, \u226520% swallows with premature/spastic contraction Abnormal median IRP (upright and supine), \u226520% elevated intrabolus pressure (supine), not meeting criteria for achalasia |\n| Disorders of peristalsis | Absent contractility Distal esophageal spasm Hypercontractile esophagus Ineffective esophageal motility | Normal median IRP, 100% failed peristalsis Normal median IRP, \u226520% swallows with premature/spastic contraction Normal median IRP, \u226520% hypercontractile swallows Normal median IRP, >70% ineffective swallows or \u226550% failed peristalsis |\n\n*EGJ,* Esophagogastric junction; *IRP,* integrated relaxation pressure.\n\nPatients should be nil per os for 4 hours prior to the procedure, and the study is performed in both supine and upright positions. The catheter is placed and anatomic landmarks including the upper esophageal sphincter (UES), LES, respiratory inversion point (RIP), and basal EGJ pressure are identified. This is followed in the supine position by ten 5 mL wet swallows of room-temperature water or saline, with 30 second intervals in between. One multiple rapid swallow sequence consisting of five 2 mL wet swallows administered using a 10\u2013mL syringe 2 to 3 seconds apart is performed. The patient is then positioned upright, sitting at 80 degrees or higher, and after reconfirmation of anatomic landmarks and a short adaptation period, five 5 mL wet swallows are performed with 30 second intervals in between. Finally, a rapid drink challenge with 200 mL of water is performed, which is ingested as quickly as possible through a straw. Additional tests to be considered include solid test swallows and a solid test meal.\n\nThe most updated Chicago Classification version 4.0 defines three subtypes of achalasia. Type I (classic) achalasia is defined as an abnormal median integrated relaxation pressure (IRP) with absent contractility (100% failed peristalsis). Threshold IRP is defined as 15 mmHg in supine or 12 mmHg in upright position for Medtronic systems, and 22 mmHg in supine and 15 mmHg in upright positions for Laborie/Diversatek systems. Type II achalasia meets the same IRP criteria but is associated with panesophageal pressurization in at least 20% of swallows. Type III (spastic) achalasia is defined as an abnormal IRP with absent normal swallows and evidence of spasm or premature contraction in at least 20% of swallows ( Fig. 19.1 ). Because opioids may be associated with type III achalasia, patients should be studied off opioid medication if possible. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> A newer addition to the Chicago Classification is the revised definition of esophagogastric junction outflow obstruction (EGJOO), which may be secondary to mechanical obstruction from paraesophageal hernia, benign or malignant tumors, or in some cases may represent a variant of or early achalasia. Clinically relevant EGJOO is defined as an elevated median IRP and at least 20% of swallows with elevated intrabolus pressure in the supine position, with evidence of intact peristalsis, and associated with clinically relevant symptoms and additional imaging supportive of obstruction (TBS, EndoFLIP, etc.). EGJOO is described in the context of the pattern of peristalsis: with spastic features, with hypercontractile features, with ineffective motility, or with no evidence of disordered peristalsis.\n\nA photo depicts three radiography views of the esophagus labeled Type One, two, and Three, paired with respective pressure waveforms below. The photo depicts three esophageal structural classifications paired with their adjacent spectrograms of pressure readouts. The first part on the top row, labeled type one, displays a smooth, narrow esophageal outline. The spectrogram below reflects minimal zones that indicate low-pressure activity. The second part, labeled type two, presents a dilated esophagus with a narrow bottom. The spectrogram below reflects multiple bands that indicate areas of variable pressure. The third part, labeled type three, presents an irregular esophageal outline with distortion. The spectrogram below reflects a wide patch, which indicates intense and irregular pressure activity.\n\nFig. 19.1\n\n## Treatment of Achalasia\n\nA variety of surgical and nonsurgical treatments for achalasia exist with variable efficacy and durability. The foundation of all available treatments is based on decreasing LES tone to improve esophageal emptying. These treatments are not curative as meaningful restoration of esophageal peristalsis is not routinely achieved with any of these modalities.\n\n### Pharmacologic Therapy\n\nPharmacologic therapy is aimed at inducing smooth muscle relaxation at the LES. Drug classes that have been utilized for this purpose include nitrates (sublingual isosorbide dinitrate 5\u201310 mg), calcium channel blockers (sublingual nifedipine 10\u201320 mg), and 5-phosphodiesterase inhibitors (sildenafil 50 mg). Data regarding long-term improvement in dysphagia are lacking, and the side-effect profile of these agents often limits their use. Therefore, these treatments are generally reserved for patients who are poor candidates for surgical or endoscopic therapies or as a temporizing measure before more definitive intervention.\n\n### Endoscopic Therapies\n\n#### Pneumatic Dilation\n\nPneumatic dilation involves disruption of the LES fibers through dilation with a 30-, 35-, or 40-mm balloon (e.g., Rigiflex, Boston Scientific, Marlborough, MA), usually under fluoroscopic guidance. Graded dilations may be needed with successively larger balloons to achieve clinical effect. Review of the current literature suggests clinical success in 83% of patients over a follow-up period between 3 and 6 months, with decrease in average LES pressure from 34.47 mmHg to 20.80 mmHg. Success rates are lower at longer follow-up periods of 2 to 5 years (40%\u201354%). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Recurrence of dysphagia varies between 8.3% and 58.8% with reintervention rates of 16% to 47.1%. Predictors of treatment failure include young age, <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> LES pressure >15 mmHg, cardia width <5 mm, and esophageal barium column height >1 cm 4 to 12 weeks postdilation. Though there is some evidence suggesting improved relative efficacy in type II achalasia, others do not demonstrate achalasia subtypes as predictive of success. Complications of pneumatic dilation include GERD (9%), esophageal perforation (2.8%), and bleeding requiring additional intervention (2%). Considering the risk for esophageal perforation which may require emergent surgical intervention, pneumatic dilation should only be performed at experienced centers with surgical backup. Although pneumatic dilation carries a higher rate of reintervention when compared to Heller myotomy or per-oral endoscopic myotomy (POEM), sequential dilations may be a reasonable alternative to surgery. Pneumatic dilation is also an option after failed Heller myotomy, without increased risk of perforation.\n\n#### Botulinum Toxin\n\nThe use of botulinum toxin in the treatment of achalasia was first described by Pasricha et al. in 1993. Most commonly, a total of 100 IU of toxin divided into four aliquots is injected into four quadrants at the LES, where it functions through blocking acetylcholine release from nerve endings to reduce LES tone. A recent systematic review of clinical outcomes after botulinum toxin injection demonstrates clinical success in 77% over an early follow-up period of 1 to 6 months, with decrease in average LES pressure from 38.23 mmHg to 23.30 mmHg. Chest pain was reported by 11% of patients but no serious adverse events were reported. However, most patients require retreatment within a year. Results are generally temporary as clinical effect typically decreases over time. Therefore, botulinum toxin injection is usually used as a temporizing measure, in poor surgical candidates, or to assess response when the diagnosis of achalasia is inconclusive. Although the risk profile is low, repeated injections may obliterate the submucosal plane making subsequent surgical myotomy more difficult.\n\n#### Esophageal Stenting\n\nThe use of self-expanding covered metal stents for treatment of achalasia is less common but has been described, with variable rates of success and morbidity such as stent migration and chest pain based on duration of stent placement and type of stent used. More data are needed to define the role of esophageal stenting in the management algorithm for achalasia but it may be an appealing option in high-risk patients.\n\n### Surgical Therapy for Achalasia\n\nSurgical myotomy was initially described by Heller in 1913 and was performed via a thoracotomy with two separate 8 cm myotomies 180 degrees apart. The technique has undergone several modifications and now typically involves a single anterior myotomy through abdominal access, with addition of a partial fundoplication to reduce the incidence of iatrogenic reflux. In the early 1990s, laparoscopic and thoracoscopic approaches to the Heller myotomy were described. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> POEM was developed in the first decade of this century, but has roots in the 1980s. Ortega described an endoscopic myotomy in 1980, consisting of division of the mucosa and muscle of the LES with two short full-thickness incisions. Despite satisfactory outcomes, the technique was not adopted due to concern for esophageal perforation. POEM was first proposed by Pasricha in 2007 as a \u201csubmucosal endoscopic esophageal myotomy\u201d in a porcine model. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Inoue presented the first human experience in 2008 with four patients and coined the term \u201cPOEM.\u201d He published a series on 17 patients 2 years later.\n\n#### Laparoscopic Heller Myotomy With Partial Fundoplication\n\nBy the mid to late 1990s, laparoscopic Heller myotomy (LHM) had become the primary treatment for achalasia. The authors\u2019 practice is to keep patients on a clear liquid diet for 24 hours prior to surgery. The procedure requires general anesthesia and is most commonly performed in a split leg position. The procedure is performed with both arms on arm boards. As with all procedures involving the hiatus, steep reverse Trendelenburg positioning is utilized, so patients should be well secured to the operating room table. The authors\u2019 preferred patient positioning involves footboards at the base of the flat padded and abducted leg boards with sequential compression devices for deep venous thrombosis prophylaxis in place. The legs are covered with a warming device and blankets, and the legs are secured to the leg boards with tape above and below the knee. The operating surgeon stands on the patient\u2019s left side, with the assistant standing between the legs.\n\nStandard laparoscopic equipment is required. Atraumatic graspers are necessary for handling the involved tissues, needle drivers for suturing, and a liver retractor to provide adequate visualization of the hiatus. The harmonic scalpel is useful for dissection, but other devices can also be used. The myotomy can be performed with a hook (with or without cautery), laparoscopic scissors (with or without cautery), or the harmonic scalpel. Five laparoscopic ports are necessary, and they can all be 5-mm trocars. Finally, an upper endoscope should be available for intraoperative evaluation of the anatomy before and after myotomy, as well as to perform an endoscopic leak test. A bougie can be used during myotomy to better spread the muscle fibers.\n\n## Technique\n\nThere are four steps to an LHM: port placement and exposure, dissection of the stomach and hiatus, myotomy, and fundoplication.\n\n  - 1.\n\tPort Placement and Exposure. The setup is identical to that of a laparoscopic fundoplication. A Veress needle is used to establish pneumoperitoneum followed by camera port placement at the same site, to the left of midline and roughly between the umbilicus and the xiphoid. Other ports are placed as illustrated ( Fig. 19.2 ).\n\tA diagram depicts a torso with anatomical structures indicated and numbered with five dots. #REF!\n\tFig. 19.2\n  - 2.\n\tDissection of the Stomach and Hiatus. The amount of dissection depends on the planned fundoplication for the procedure. Most commonly, we perform a partial posterior fundoplication, as described by Toupet. Further discussion of fundoplication choice is detailed in subsequent text. To prepare for myotomy and posterior partial fundoplication, the stomach must be mobilized and the hiatus completely dissected. The assistant retracts the gastroesophageal fat pad inferiorly to reduce any hiatal hernia, and the surgeon then divides the gastrohepatic ligament to expose the right crus. The mediastinum is then entered anteriorly, and the esophagus is mobilized circumferentially. The short gastric arteries are divided if a posterior partial fundoplication is planned but may be left intact at the surgeon\u2019s discretion for anterior partial fundoplications/Dor. To expose the esophagus for myotomy, the gastroesophageal fat pad is removed, taking care to protect the left vagus nerve.\n  - 3.\n\tMyotomy. A bougie, or more recently the impedance planimetry balloon, is inserted transorally. The myotomy is initiated with the hook cautery, 2 cm above the GEJ. The myotomy should be performed with a low-power setting to avoid transmission to the esophageal mucosa. The longitudinal and circular fibers are dissected off the mucosa and are divided. A fine grasper, such as the Maryland forceps, can be used to elevate the muscle on either side of the myotomy to allow passage of the hook cautery, laparoscopic scissors, or harmonic scalpel into the submucosal plane ( Fig. 19.3 ). Blunt dissection can be used to separate the muscle from the submucosa, which allows for elevation of the muscle away from the submucosa for continued proximal myotomy. The myotomy should be 4 to 5 cm onto the esophagus; bleeding muscle edges can be controlled with delicate cautery or compression. Extending the myotomy above the diaphragm should be avoided, as this can result in a diverticulum in the future. After completing the esophageal myotomy, the distal gastric myotomy is performed for a length of 2 to 3 cm with the energy device. After completing the myotomy, the muscle edges are mobilized laterally to each side to better expose the submucosa. Any remaining circular muscle fibers are divided. The bougie is removed, and an endoscope can be used to evaluate the myotomy and perform an air leak test.\n\tA photo depicts surgical instruments that hold open a tissue incision. #REF!\n\tFig. 19.3\n  - 4.\n\tFundoplication. To prevent postoperative GERD, a fundoplication should be added. Given the aperistaltic nature of the esophageal body, a partial fundoplication is typically performed. A posterior partial fundoplication involves loose posterior crural closure and fastening the left and right wrap to the corresponding crura. Finally, the right and left sides of the wrap are secured to the esophageal myotomy edges with three interrupted nonabsorbable sutures.\n\nAn anterior partial fundoplication (Dor) is used if there is no hiatal hernia and adequate intraabdominal esophageal length for myotomy. This requires minimal mobilization of the fundus and minimizes mediastinal dissection. The fundus is folded over the myotomy and secured to each arch of the hiatus and to each side of the myotomy with three permanent sutures ( Fig. 19.4 ).\n\nTwo photos of surgical views that present the edge of myotomy and the gastroesophageal junction. The photos present two intraoperative endoscopic views of the esophagus in an esophageal myotomy procedure. The first view presents the distal esophagus and gastroesophageal junction. The second view presents the proximal esophagus after completion of the myotomy, with the mucosa visible at the edge of the myotomy.\n\nFig. 19.4\n\n## Postoperative Care\n\nBefore initiating oral intake, the authors\u2019 standard practice is to obtain a water-soluble contrast esophagram on postoperative day 1 to exclude perforation or obstruction, followed by 14 days of a pureed diet, and then a regular diet. A routine postoperative visit is planned for 3 to 4 weeks postoperatively with endoscopy, TBS, and pH testing planned for 6 months to evaluate for GERD. Although recent guidelines have suggested that routine follow-up endoscopy is not warranted as the risk of reflux or stasis related cancers is fairly low, the authors still recommend it to patients as the chronicity of the disease and relatively high rates of reflux even with a partial fundoplication are fairly high. Long term, patients are evaluated endoscopically every 5 years.\n\n### Complications\n\nThe most common complication of an esophageal myotomy is mucosal perforation. These are infrequent and are usually detected and treated at the time of occurrence. These can be repaired laparoscopically with fine interrupted absorbable sutures and do not seem to increase postoperative complications unless missed. Rates of perforation during primary laparoscopic Heller myotomies range from 1.9% to 6.0% in large series, with increased rates of perforation after prior endoscopic treatments, and can be as high as 31.2% in redo Heller myotomies. Some reports of robotic-assisted laparoscopic myotomy have shown lower incidences of mucosal perforation, though as perforations have little effect on outcomes the value of this is questionable.\n\nThe outcome after repair of intraoperative mucosal injury is similar to patients who undergo uncomplicated laparoscopic Heller myotomies.\n\n### Results\n\nSchlottmann et al. described outcomes after LHM through a large systematic review and meta-analysis of 5834 patients. Improvement in dysphagia was noted in 87.7% of patients at a mean follow-up of 40 months. GERD symptoms were reported in 17.5% of patients, with evidence of GERD by endoscopy in 11.5% of patients and by pH monitoring in 11.1%. In patients who develop recurrent dysphagia, dilation has been demonstrated to provide durable relief in up to 75% of patients.\n\nIn 2022 the Cochrane Library released a systematic review of several randomized controlled trials comparing the addition and type of fundoplication to LHM performed with minimal hiatal dissection, specifically with regard to postoperative reflux and dysphagia. It remains unclear whether LHM + Dor compared to LHM without fundoplication results in differences with regard to pathologic reflux (relative risk \\[RR\\] 0.37, 95% confidence interval \\[CI\\] 0.07\u20131.89, 2 studies, 97 participants) or severe dysphagia (RR 3.00, 95% CI 0.34\u201326.33, 3 studies, 142 participants). When LHM + Dor was compared to LHM + Toupet, no differences were noted in pathological reflux (RR 0.75, 95% CI 0.23\u20132.43, 3 studies, 105 participants) or severe dysphagia (RR 0.78, 95% CI 0.19\u20133.15, 3 studies, 123 participants). When comparing LHM + Dor to LHM + Nissen, no difference in pathological acid reflux was noted (RR 4.72, 95% CI 0.23\u201396.59, 1 study, 138 participants); however, dysphagia rates were significantly less with Dor (RR 0.19, 95% CI 0.04\u20130.83, 1 study, 138 participants).\n\n#### Per-Oral Endoscopic Myotomy\n\nThere are no current absolute contraindications to POEM, other than inability to tolerate general anesthesia. Patients with end-stage \u201csigmoid\u201d achalasia or those with prior interventions are no longer considered to be relative contraindications; patients have successfully undergone POEM after dilatation, botulinum toxin treatment, prior POEM, and even open and laparoscopic myotomy. Hiatal hernias are considered contraindicated for POEM due to a higher risk of GERD postprocedurally. LHM with hernia repair and partial posterior fundoplication is preferred in these patients.\n\nSimilar to Heller myotomy candidates, the authors\u2019 practice is to place patients on a clear liquid diet for 24 hours prior to the procedure. Because of risk of yeast esophagitis, 5 days of preoperative nystatin swish and swallow are given prophylactically, as well as a single dose of first-generation cephalosporin within 30 minutes of mucosotomy. A single dose of dexamethasone (10 mg) is given intravenously in the preoperative holding area to minimize mucosal edema at the site of the mucosotomy and to facilitate closure. The procedure requires endotracheal intubation and general anesthesia and most commonly occurs in the operating room to allow for close monitoring and potential intervention if complications occur.\n\n## Technique\n\nThere are five steps to POEM: endoscopic measurements, saline lift/mucosotomy, submucosal tunneling, circular myotomy, and mucosotomy closure. Reported operative times are 90 to 120 minutes. The learning curve has been estimated to be approximately 20 procedures, with 30 procedures suggested before attempting POEM after failed Heller myotomy. Basic equipment for the procedure is listed in Table 19.3 .\n\n  - 1.\n\tEndoscopic Measurements. A short overtube is placed at the beginning of the case, with the exception of long endoscopic myotomies for spastic disorders or achalasia type III. In addition to reducing the risk of oropharyngeal trauma, the overtube provides added stability to the endoscope and results in less tension at the mucosotomy, yielding less tearing and a smaller mucosotomy to close at the end of the procedure. Anatomic landmarks are measured in reference to the overtube. The optimal length of the myotomy can be determined using intraoperative impedance planimetry using EndoFLIP and in general, the shortest myotomy possible\u2014tailored to the EndoFlip readings seems to decrease postoperative reflux.\n  - For achalasia types I and II, a relatively shorter myotomy is generally performed; the start of the myotomy is planned for 2 to 3 cm proximal to the high-pressure zone. For achalasia type III, a longer myotomy is performed, based on impedance planimetry and preoperative HRM, to include the entire spastic segment in the planned myotomy.\n  - 2.\n\tSaline Lift and Mucosotomy. The site for the mucosal incision should be 3 to 4 cm proximal to the determined start of the myotomy. The authors prefer the anterior lesser curve position (2 o\u2019clock) for the myotomy, although the posterior position (6 o\u2019clock) is possible as well. The saline lift is performed by injecting a dilute methylene blue saline solution, with or without epinephrine (\u201clifting solution\u201d), into the submucosal space through a 23-gauge endoscopic injection needle. A 1.5-cm mucosotomy is then created using a hook or triangle-tip (TT) cautery device with cutting current. A combined injection knife can also be used.\n  - 3.\n\tSubmucosal Tunnel. The endoscope, which is fitted with a vented, taper, or angled dissection cap, is inserted through the mucosotomy and into the submucosal plane. Insertion can be aided with the use of a 15-mm biliary extraction balloon to elevate the edges of the mucosa for challenging cases. Hydrostatic dissection can also be performed through the extraction balloon by instilling lifting solution. After initial hydrostatic dissection, the esophageal mucosa and submucosa are separated from the underlying circular muscle fibers using spray cautery ( Fig. 19.5 ). Hydrostatic dissection is repeated every few centimeters. Large bridging vessels are occasionally encountered and can be controlled with a coagrasper and soft cautery. Difficult bleeding can be controlled with direct pressure by advancing the dissecting cap and holding the endoscope in place. The distal extent of the dissection can be identified by encountering the tattoo placed previously or by visualizing the transition from orderly esophageal vessels to the submucosal palisades characteristic of the gastric plane. Finally, a retroflexed view can confirm mucosal blanching caused by the tunnel extending across the EGJ.\n  - During creation of the submucosal tunnel, care must be taken to avoid mucosal injury from cautery or shear injury from bowing of the endoscope; most inadvertent mucosotomies are small and can be repaired with an endoscopic clip from the lumen of the esophagus at the end of the procedure. Maintaining the same operative position and ensuring the circular fibers are parallel to the end of the cap will prevent spiraling of the tunnel.\n\tAn endoscopic view that presents a close-up of a human organ with a surgical instrument inside. #REF!\n\tFig. 19.5\n  - 4.\n\tCircular Myotomy. The myotomy begins 2 to 3 cm distal to the most distal extent of the mucosotomy and proceeds antegrade to allow the dissecting cap to place tension on the muscle fibers. The myotomy consists of division of the circular muscle fibers using an Endocut current using a TT, hook cautery, or combined injection knife. Once the circular fibers are divided, the longitudinal muscle fibers are easily visible ( Fig. 19.6 ). The longitudinal fibers are very thin and splitting often occurs under the pressure of the dissecting cap, which will reveal mediastinal structures beyond the intact esophageal adventitia. This \u201cmediastinal exposure\u201d is common and does not indicate a full-thickness perforation. The plane between the longitudinal and circular muscle fibers is followed distally with continued myotomy. The myotomy plane often becomes tight at the EGJ due to the thickened musculature, the curve from the esophagus to the stomach, and the impression of the diaphragm. Progressive lifting and dissection will always eventually permit passage of the endoscope into the gastric submucosal plane. Forcing the dissecting cap through this area can cause endoscopic bowing and further mucosotomy tearing. The myotomy should be continued well onto the gastric wall, as confirmed by the previously placed tattoo and/or confirmation by endoscopic retroflexion. We also repeat the impedance planimetry to ensure an increase in the cross-sectional area and, more importantly, an improvement in the distensibility or compliance of the LES ( Fig. 19.7 ).\n\tAn endoscopic view shows the circular fibers close to the outer region and longitudinal fibers in the inner region. #REF!\n\tFig. 19.6\n\tA photo depicts the pressure variations of the catheter balloon in two instances. The photo captures a digital display comparing the pressure variations. The neck formation on the left is more in comparison to the right. The color contour depicts the balloon pressures that are also displayed with numerical values on the left and right of the digital display. The date and time of the diagnosis with the conditions are mentioned for the respective pressure contours.\n\tFig. 19.7\n  - 5.\n\tMucosotomy Closure. Once adequate dissection has occurred, the mucosotomy is then closed using endoscopic clips or endoscopic sutures. Any mucosal burns or perforations should be first clipped, and then the mucosotomy is closed from distal to proximal.\n\nTable 19.3\n\nEquipment List for Peroral Endoscopic Myotomy\n\n<table><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\" colspan=\"2\">Peroral Endoscopic Myotomy Equipment</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align=\"\">Basic Equipment<ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Video tower</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Endoscope</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>CO <sub>2 </sub>regulation unit with low-flow tubing</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Flushing pump</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Large pitcher for lifting solution</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>10-cc controlled syringes for hydrodissection</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Alcohol swabs for lens cleaning</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Toothbrushes for cleaning knives</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Wire bucket for temporary wire storage</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\">Mucosotomy/Tunnel<ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Generator/ground pad (mucosotomy: 60 cut; tunnel: 60 spray tunnel; myotomy: 40 spray)</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Active cord</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Injection needle</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Endoscopic knife</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Sphincterotomy balloon</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Dissecting caps\u2014soft, hard, or angled</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Hemostatic graspers</p></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Measurement<ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Data sheet</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Overtube</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\" rowspan=\"2\">Closure<ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Clip\u2014large and small</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Suture\u2014overstitch\u2014requires dual-channel scope</p></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Lifting Solution<ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>1 mL indigo carmine diluted in 500 mL NS \u00b1 epinephrine 1:1000 1 mg/mL</p></li></ul></td></tr></tbody></table>\n\n*CO* <sub><i>2 </i></sub> *,* Carbon dioxide; *NS,* normal saline; *POEM,* per-oral endoscopic myotomy.\n\n## Other Considerations\n\nExtended proximal myotomy should be considered for noncardiac chest pain and for type III achalasia and can be extended from a few centimeters from the cricopharyngeus to the gastric cardia. POEM has been shown to be both safe and effective for these extended indications. Due to concerns for submucosal fibrosis from dilations or injections, previous treatments were initially felt to be contraindications to POEM. As experience has increased, POEM has been successfully completed in these cases with no increases in procedure length or perioperative complication rates after prior intervention. POEM has also been reported after prior laparoscopic myotomy, and even though it is somewhat more technically difficult, it is both safe and effective with published efficacy of 91.7% to 100%. In the setting of failed Heller myotomy, some recommend creation of the submucosal tunnel in the posterior aspect of the esophagus or lateral wall. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nEnd-stage achalasia or \u201csigmoid\u201d esophagus is perhaps the most difficult technically to treat and has somewhat poorer clinical results. As with dilation or Heller myotomy, many end-stage patients will have continued functional deterioration, and up to 5% will require esophagectomy. End-stage achalasia was felt to be a contraindication for POEM in the past, but successful therapy has been described in small subsets of larger studies <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> as well as one recent study of 32 patients with long-term follow-up and a 96% success rate.\n\n## Postprocedure Care\n\nBefore initiating oral intake, we obtain a water-soluble contrast esophagram on postoperative day 1, followed by 7 days of a pureed diet, and then a regular diet. The pureed diet is required so that the endoscopic clips are not dislodged too early. The hospital length of stay is approximately 1 day, and patients return to regular activity after 4 days. The same schedule for Heller myotomies is followed: office visit is planned for 3 to 4 weeks postoperatively with endoscopy, TBS, and pH testing planned for 6 months to evaluate for GERD.\n\n## Complications\n\nInadvertent mucosal injuries, such as burns and small perforations, occur at an overall rate of approximately 4.8% and can occur in up to 25% of cases during the learning curve. These can almost always be treated with simple endoscopic measures such as clips or sutures, and rarely stents, Endoloops, or fibrin sealant. Full-thickness perforations are very rare (0.2%) but can cause serious harm to patients if not recognized and repaired at the time of the procedure. Mucosotomy dehiscence and postoperative bleeding are also rare and can almost always be controlled endoscopically. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nPneumoperitoneum, pneumomediastinum, and pneumothorax are not felt to be complications, but rather side effects of the procedure. As long as carbon dioxide is used for the procedure, these rarely require intervention due to rapid reabsorption. If necessary, due to symptoms, sterile needle decompression without indwelling drain placement can be performed in the peritoneal cavity or the anterior chest during or after the procedure. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Results\n\nOutcomes after POEM were evaluated in a large meta-analysis by Akintoye et al., which included 2373 patients. Clinical success, defined as an ES of 3 or less, was achieved in 98% of patients. Mean ES prior to treatment was 6.9 \u00b1 0.15, and decreased to 0.77 \u00b1 0.10, 1.0 \u00b1 0.10, and 1.0 \u00b1 0.08 within 1, 6, and 12 months of treatment. Average IRP decreased from 30 \u00b1 1.4 mmHg prior to the procedure to 13 \u00b1 1.6 mmHg within 6 months. Objective improvements were also noted in height of barium column during TBS from 14 \u00b1 2.3 to 4.2 \u00b1 0.77 cm at 1 minute. GERD symptoms are reported in 18.5% of patients, with evidence of GERD on endoscopy in approximately 22.4% of patients and on pH monitoring in 47.5% of patients. Up to 50% of patients with post-POEM reflux can be asymptomatic, and up to 44% of patients with symptoms of reflux have normal acid exposure ; the authors therefore recommend postoperative pH testing in all patients to identify those with increased acid exposure after POEM, and consideration of antacid medication or even selective fundoplication in this subset.\n\nPOEM has successfully been performed after failed POEM, with 85% of patients having improvement in ESs to a threshold below 3, and after failed Heller myotomy, with clinical success achieved in 90%.\n\n#### Per-Oral Endoscopic Myotomy Compared to Heller Myotomy and Pneumatic Dilation\n\nPOEM has compared favorably with LHM with fundoplication. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The cost-effectiveness of the two procedures is also similar. Werner et al. published data from a multicenter controlled trial comparing POEM with LHM + Dor, which evaluated 221 patients randomly assigned to treatment groups with clinical success defined as ES of 3 or less. Statistically similar rates of clinical success were noted at 2-year follow-up (POEM 83%, LHM 82%), as well as serious adverse events (POEM 3%, LHM 7%), and mean length of stay (POEM 2.9 days, LHM 2.3 days). The incidence of reflux esophagitis (all grades) was higher in the POEM group versus the LHM group at 3 months (57% vs. 20%) and at 24 months (44% vs. 29%). Esophageal pH monitoring demonstrated similar proportions of patients with abnormal reflux at 3 months (44% vs. 33%) and 24 months (30% vs. 30%). Proton pump inhibitors were used more frequently at 2 years in the POEM group (52.8%) than in the LHM group (27%). They concluded that POEM was noninferior to LHM in controlling symptoms of achalasia but resulted in more cases of gastroesophageal reflux, the long-term sequelae of which warrant further study. In patients with type III achalasia, data favor POEM over LHM, with clinical response (defined as ES of 1 or less) in 98.0% of POEM patients versus 80.8% of LHM patients, and shorter operative time for POEM despite longer myotomy (16 cm vs. 8 cm). Achalasia-specific expert guidelines also currently support POEM over LHM for type III achalasia. Lastly, a landmark multicenter trial comparing POEM to pneumatic dilation was published in JAMA. One hundred thirty-three patients with newly diagnosed achalasia were randomized. There was a significantly higher success rate in the POEM group compared to the pneumatic dilation group (92% vs. 54%, *P* \u2264.001). Reflux esophagitis was more prevalent in the POEM group than in the pneumatic dilation group (41% vs. 29%, *P* \\=.002). Current consensus guidelines strongly support POEM over pneumatic dilation in most scenarios except when there is concern of continued proton-pump inhibitor use, and support either POEM or Heller myotomy with fundoplication to treat achalasia, again favoring POEM for type III achalasia.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nAchalasia is a devastating disease with no cure. Treatment, laparoscopic or endoscopic, aims at providing palliation by disrupting the esophageal outflow obstruction. POEM is a newer less invasive technique that compares favorably with the standard laparoscopic myotomy with fundoplication. Long-term results and comparative studies are still in progress, but sufficient evidence currently exists to consider both surgical myotomy and POEM as valid treatment alternatives.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Spiess A.E., Kahrilas P.J.: Treating achalasia: from whalebone to laparoscope . JAMA 1998; 280 (7): pp. 638-642.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Lendrum F.C.: Anatomic