7.2L183.7%2043c.2.4%200%20.7-.3.7h-5.8zM192.015%2019c-.2%200-.338-.004-.3-.2V8.4h-3.3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n\n\nNeed help? Chat with AI Buddy!\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[18. Cricopharyngeal Dysfunction and Zenker Diverticulum - ClinicalKey|18. Cricopharyngeal Dysfunction and Zenker Diverticulum]]\n**Next:** [[20. Surgical Management of Mid- and Distal Esophageal Diverticula - ClinicalKey|20. Surgical Management of Mid- and Distal Esophageal Diverticula]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "19. Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment', 'Epidemiology of Achalasia', 'Diagnosis of Achalasia', 'Treatment of Achalasia', 'Technique', 'Postoperative Care', 'Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment / Epidemiology of Achalasia', 'Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment / Diagnosis of Achalasia', 'Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment / Treatment of Achalasia'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '19', '200-210', 2, 49, FALSE, TRUE),
('Esophageal Motility: Techniques Used for the Diagnosis of Esophageal Motility Disorders and for Surgical Decision Making', 'shackelford-9th-ed-2-esophageal-motility-techniques-used-for-the-diagnosis-of-esophageal-motility-di', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "- Skip to search\n  - Skip to navigation\n  - Skip to content\n  - Skip to help and feedback\n\nClinicalKey\n\n\u00a0\n\n-\n-\n-\n-\n-\n-\n-\n-\n-\n-\n-\n-\n-\n-\n\n1.\n2. CME/MOC\n3. Login\n4. Register\n5. - Call Us\n  - Email Us\n  - Help\n6.\n7. Anonymous (Login or Register)\n\t\u00a0\n  - Books\n  - Journals\n  - Clinical Overviews\n  - Drug Monographs\n  - Guidelines\n  - Patient Education\n  - Multimedia\n  - Procedure Videos\n\t\u00a0\n  - Clinical Calculators\n  - CME/MOC\n\t-\n  - Remote Access\n\t### Help & Feedback\n  - Call Us\n  - Email Us\n  - Help\n\tAbout ClinicalKey\n\tLearn more about other offerings and editions\n\n  - Books\n  - Journals\n  - Clinical Overviews\n  - Drug Monographs\n  - Guidelines\n  - Patient Education\n  - Multimedia\n  - Procedure Videos\n\n\u00a0\n\n  - Clinical Calculators\n\nEsophageal Motility: Techniques Used for the Diagnosis of Esophageal Motility Disorders and for Surgical Decision Making\n\n### Share and save tools\n\n-\n-\n-\n  - Download PDFDownload PDF\n\nBook Chapter\n\n# Esophageal Motility: Techniques Used for the Diagnosis of Esophageal Motility Disorders and for Surgical Decision Making\n\nChe Simon; Michael B. Ujiki\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 2, 14-22\n\n## Introduction\n\nDysphagia can be the presenting symptom of either anatomic obstruction, neuromuscular dysfunction, or both. Dysphagia symptoms warrant urgent workup and treatment as they may indicate underlying malignancy. Clinical history alone can often differentiate between oropharyngeal and esophageal dysphagia. Identifying the degree of dysphagia (solids, liquids, or both) as well as associated symptoms, such as gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD), weight loss, anemia, or regurgitation, may give important clues as to the underlying clinical etiology.\n\nThe diagnosis of esophageal dysmotility often begins with a timed barium esophagram (TBE). Retention of liquid barium can indicate underlying esophageal dysmotility or outflow obstruction. TBE is often followed by an upper endoscopy to identify anatomic sources of dysphagia such as stricture, esophageal webs and rings, hiatal hernia, or esophageal cancer. An unrevealing upper endoscopy indicates further testing with high-resolution manometry (HRM).\n\nHRM remains the gold standard for diagnosis of esophageal dysmotility. It provides information on pressure changes within the entire length of esophagus on a continuous time spectrum. This assessment provides information about esophageal peristalsis and the lower esophageal sphincter (LES). The Chicago Classification was designed to classify dysphagia based on manometric findings. The current version 4 (CCv4.0) provides a diagnostic algorithm for classifying esophageal motility diseases based on HRM.\n\nImpedance planimetry, an innovative technique using the functional lumen imaging probe (EndoFLIP; Medtronic Inc., Minneapolis, Minnesota), is gaining popularity. Compared with HRM, the FLIP provides diagnostic information regarding secondary peristalsis and esophageal sphincter distensibility during endoscopy.\n\nAccurate diagnosis of the etiology of the dysphagia is imperative for prescribing proper treatment, whether it be medical or surgical. Both HRM and EndoFLIP have been useful in identifying the proper treatment algorithm, predicting patient outcomes and the development of post-treatment dysphagia or gas bloat.\n\nCurrent society guidelines recommend the use of a TBE and HRM in the routine assessment of esophageal dysmotility. These guidelines also state the FLIP can be complimentary to HRM and may be useful in symptomatic patients with borderline HRM findings. Accurate diagnosis of esophageal motility disorders is dependent on identification of esophageal function and defining esophagogastric junction (EGJ) morphology. We discuss the techniques for diagnosing esophageal motility disorders with each modality.\n\n## Timed Barium Esophagram\n\nA TBE is often the first study in a patient with dysphagia. TBE is widely available, well tolerated, and easy to perform. It provides generalized information on esophageal structure and emptying. It can be immensely valuable as a screening tool to look for esophageal obstruction or major structural problems, especially when access to HRM or endoscopy is delayed. Although TBE alone is rarely sufficient to accurately differentiate esophageal motility disorders, it is helpful to predict the adequacy of therapy and symptom recurrence. TBE can also provide important adjunctive information when HRM is equivocal or not in congruity with patient symptoms.\n\n### TBE Protocol\n\nAn established TBE protocol must be followed to obtain an accurate study. The TBE protocol includes a standardized volume (8 oz or 237 mL) of thin, liquid barium administered orally to an awake patient in the upright position. Left posterior oblique radiographs are obtained at 1, 2, and 5 minutes. At each time point, measurements of barium column height are obtained, conveying quantitative information on esophageal emptying. Complete emptying of the barium column at 1 minute and 5 minutes is expected in normal individuals. Barium column height at 5 minutes correlates with reduced esophageal gastric junction distensibility as seen in achalasia.\n\n### TBE Metrics\n\nRetained barium can differentiate achalasia from non-achalasia dysphagia when barium height is greater than 5 cm at 1 minute (95% sensitivity, 71% specificity) or greater than 2 cm at 5 minutes (sensitivity 85%, specificity 86%). TBE has an 81% sensitivity and 35% specificity for detecting achalasia dysphagia. However, TBE has low accuracy in differentiating non-achalasia causes for dysphagia. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> More recent studies also look at the diameter of the barium column to provide a percentage emptying. Surface area change at 1 minute and 5 minutes is a better correlate for esophageal emptying than the height of barium column alone.\n\nA standard 13-mm barium tablet can also be administered during TBE. Tablet retention can help distinguish achalasia from non-achalasia causes for dysphagia, increasing the diagnostic yield of TBE for achalasia to 100%. However, HRM is still recommended in all cases where TBE is abnormal and is integral in the classification of non-achalasia dysphagia.\n\nThe contour of the barium column can identify structural abnormalities of the esophagus. Many radiologists will administer additional contrast to perform a routine esophagram study after TBE if structural abnormalities such as diverticulum or hiatal hernia are noted. Multiple anatomic and functional findings have characteristic features on contrast esophagram such as the \u201cbird-beak\u201d appearance in achalasia or \u201ccork-screw\u201d sign in distal esophageal spasm (see Chapter 5 for more details). Abnormal findings on esophagram may necessitate subsequent endoscopy, which can be both diagnostic and therapeutic.\n\n### TBE: Surgical Decision Making\n\nBesides screening for esophageal dysmotility, TBE has also been used to assess improvement in esophageal emptying after treatment for achalasia with either myotomy or pneumatic dilation. Compared with pre-treatment TBE, a 50% reduction in the height of the barium column after treatment or a 45% reduction in surface area is considered to be successful. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Improved emptying on post-treatment TBE is associated with improved symptom scores. Studies have also shown that despite symptomatic improvement, poor results on TBE predicted development of recurrent dysphagia. Conversely, improved esophageal emptying on TBE can predict long-term success. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n## High-Resolution Manometry\n\nHRM has remained the gold standard in the assessment of esophageal motility and EGJ morphology since its widespread adoption began in the early 1990s. It provides information on esophageal function by measuring intraluminal pressure during awake swallows. HRM also provides essential information regarding EGJ relaxation and morphology.\n\n### HRM: Technical Aspects\n\nSolid-state HRM has replaced conventional water-perfused line tracing manometry as the best test for diagnosing esophageal motility disorders, improving both data procurement and display. Compared with conventional manometry, HRM has circumferential sensors spaced closer together which significantly amplify the details of data acquisition with fewer unsampled areas along the length of the esophagus. HRM displays its data as a continuous pressure color topography plot allowing for ease of interpretation.\n\nThe HRM catheter ( Fig. 2.1 ) is 4.2 mm in diameter and has 36 circumferential, solid-state pressure sensors placed 1 cm apart. HRM obtains continuous measurement of the entire esophagus and both LES and upper esophageal sphincter (UES). HRM has improved patient tolerance and decreased procedure duration, absolving the need for pull-through techniques to obtain complete measurements. The proximity of the probes also increases accuracy in determining LES pressure and relaxation but has lost some accuracy with which to ascertain sphincter length.\n\nA photo of a manometry catheter with sensors. The manometry catheter has a curved and segmented structure that contains multiple pressure sensitive zones. The text next to the sensors states, \"Each of the 36 sensors has 12 pressure sensitive segments that are averaged to yield the signal at the location\".\n\nFig. 2.1\n\n### Manometry Protocol\n\nTo standardize the manometry test, the CCv4.0 developed a consistent protocol for performing HRM. Following fasting, the HRM catheter is placed transnasally in an awake patient in the supine position. The catheter is advanced so that the last three distal ports lay within the stomach. Deep inspiration can help identify the location of the diaphragmatic crura. After a minimum adaptation period of 60 seconds, baseline measurements are obtained for 30 seconds in a resting esophagus to identify the location and pressure of the high-pressure zones. This is followed by examination of 10 wet swallows of 5 mL with water or saline. Each swallow should have a 30-second break to allow for sufficient esophageal recovery and avoid inadvertent deglutitive inhibition. The study in the supine position is completed with a provocative maneuver, the multiple rapid swallow sequence.\n\nThe patient is then repositioned in an upright, seated position. Again, there is a 60-second adaptation period, documentation of catheter position, and 30-second baseline measure. Next, 5 wet swallows of 5 mL are then completed followed by another provocative maneuver, the rapid drink challenge. Compared with the supine position, swallows in the seated position are aided by gravity and have increased velocity and decreased vigor. Performing HRM in both supine and upright positions can uncover esophageal dysmotility and increases diagnostic certainty when findings are present in both supine and upright positioning.\n\n#### Provocative Maneuvers\n\nOne of the key updates in CCv4.0 is the inclusion of provocative testing during routine HRM. Provocative maneuvers more closely mimic daily, physiologic swallowing conditions compared with a single wet swallow. They demonstrate peristaltic reserve and may uncover abnormal motility not found during the standard HRM protocol. The multiple rapid swallow sequence and rapid drink challenge are most commonly used. Other techniques include using more viscous or solid materials such as a test meal or even pharmacologic challenges. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nThe multiple rapid swallows sequence is a physiologic challenge that can reveal abnormal inhibition of the esophagus seen in hypercontractile esophageal motility disorders. During this maneuver, a patient in the upright position is given five 2-mL boluses in rapid succession. The normal physiologic response of subsequent, rapid swallows is of deglutitive inhibition of all prior triggered peristalsis followed by an augmented contraction to clear the esophagus. Loss of inhibitory response can be seen in spastic, type III achalasia or hypercontractile disorders such as esophageal spasm. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nThe rapid drink challenge changes bolus volume and replicates normal drinking patterns. This test can identify impaired LES relaxation. In the upright position, patients drink 100 to 200 mL of liquid through a straw as quickly as possible. Normally, this leads to inhibition of esophageal peristalsis and complete relaxation of the LES to allow free passage of fluid. This test helps to increase the sensitivity for EGJ outlet obstruction which is characterized by isolated improper relaxation of the LES. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Similar to the multiple rapid swallow maneuver, loss of deglutitive inhibition can indicate a spastic or hypercontractile esophagus.\n\n### Manometric Color Topography\n\nEsophageal pressure topography (EPT), also known as a Clouse plot, is a topographic representation of manometric pressure measurements. Intraluminal pressure is displayed with time on the continuous axis and length along the esophagus as the ordinate axis. Intraluminal pressure is displayed topographically with \u201chot\u201d colors (red, orange) representing high pressures and \u201ccool\u201d colors (green, blue) depicting lower pressures. Baseline recordings can determine resting pressures of the UES and LES. Wet swallows are propagated in a left to right fashion.\n\nFig. 2.2 shows a Clouse plot of a normal swallow. During periods of rest, there is tonic contraction of the UES and LES. On the Clouse plot, this is seen as two areas of high pressure along the proximal and distal esophagus that relax during initiation and completion of a swallow. A normal swallow is initiated by the passage of a food or liquid bolus. The oropharyngeal phase passes the contents across the UES into the esophagus. This then triggers the normal peristaltic reaction. After a period of latency, excitatory cholinergic neurons of the esophageal body cause a propagation of smooth muscle contraction down the esophagus. The contractile segment is bounded by two low-pressure troughs: proximal (P) and distal (D). Sometimes, a third mid-esophageal trough is also present. Along the mid-esophagus, there is a morphologic transition where peristaltic control transitions from the central nervous system to the enteric nervous system. On EPT, this area is the contractile deceleration point (CDP) and found as an inflexion point when tangential lines are drawn along the initial and terminal portions of the swallow at the 30-mmHg isobaric contour. During the normal swallow, inhibitory neurons release nitric oxide, leading to relaxation of LES complex which is seen as a deglutitive window on EPT.\n\nA pressure topography depicts pressure variations along the esophagus during the swallowing process. The pressure topography depicts the pressure contour as food moves in the esophagus. The horizontal axis shows time in seconds, while the vertical axis represents length along the esophagus in centimeters, ranging from 0 to 35 centimeters. The pressure contour varies from blue to green indicating low pressure to yellow and red indicating high pressure. Initially, the upper esophageal sphincters are tightly closed with normal pressure. When swallowing begins, the upper sphincter relaxes to let food pass, then tightens again to prevent backflow. A wave of high pressure moves downward, creating two high pressure zones at proximal and distal troughs. A normal swallowing motion includes a key transition point called the contractile deceleration point obtained by two intersecting dotted lines originating from the proximal and distal troughs. As food reaches the esophagogastric junction, the sphincter relaxes momentarily to allow food to enter the stomach. The esophagogastric junction relaxes after the food passes the distal trough. The span of swallowing till the food passes to the stomach is labeled deglutitive window.\n\nFig. 2.2\n\nCompared with line tracings, EPT provides more information and has led to the identification of diseases of esophageal motility that were not distinguishable by conventional methods. EPT is also easier to interpret. In a study assessing diagnostic accuracy of clinicals reading EPT and conventional line tracing, there was 3.3 times higher odds of an incorrect diagnosis with conventional manometry than with EPT ( Fig. 2.3 ).\n\nA flowchart outlines the diagnostic process for disorders related to esophagogastric junction outflow and peristalsis. The flowchart is divided into two main sections, which include the Disorders of esophagogastric junction outflow on the left and disorders of peristalsis on the right. It uses rectangular boxes for decision points and arrows to guide the reader through the diagnostic criteria. The key terms include abnormal median integrated relaxation pressure, failed swallow tests, and various types of achalasia, with steps that lead to outcomes like no evidence of Esophagogastric junction outflow obstruction.\n\nFig. 2.3\n\n### HRM Metrics\n\nThe CCv4.0 uses manometric data to classify esophageal motility disorders as either a disorder of EGJ outflow (EGJ outflow obstruction \\[EGJOO\\]) or a disorder of peristalsis. LES relaxation is measured as an integrated relaxation pressure (IRP). Esophageal peristalsis is gauged by contraction vigor, reported as a distal contractile integral (DCI) and deglutitive inhibition, reported as a distal contractile latency (DCL). Peristaltic contraction patterns and esophageal pressurization patterns are also described. The normal values of HRM metrics are listed in Table 2.1 .\n\nTable 2.1\n\nEsophageal Pressure Topography Scoring of Individual Swallows\n\nFrom Kahrilas PJ, Bredenoord AJ, Fox M, et al. The Chicago Classification of esophageal motility disorders, v3.0. *Neurogastroenterol Motil* . 2015:27;160\u2013174; Teitelbaum EN, Dunst CM. In: Yeo CJ, ed. *Shackelford\u2019s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 2 Volume Set* . 8th ed. Elsevier; 2019:115\u2013128, Table 8.1 .\n\n<table><tbody><tr><td align=\"\" colspan=\"2\">Contraction Vigor</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Failed</td><td align=\"\">DCI &lt;100 mmHg \u00d7 s \u00d7 cm</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Weak</td><td align=\"\">DCI &gt;100 mmHg \u00d7 s \u00d7 cm, but &lt;450 mmHg \u00d7 s \u00d7 cm</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Ineffective</td><td align=\"\">Failed or weak</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Normal</td><td align=\"\">DCI \u2265450 mmHg \u00d7 s \u00d7 cm, but &lt;8000 mmHg \u00d7 s \u00d7 cm</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Hypercontractile</td><td align=\"\">DCI \u22658000 mmHg \u00d7 s \u00d7 cm</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\" colspan=\"2\">Contraction Pattern</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Premature</td><td align=\"\">DCL &lt;4.5 seconds</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Fragmented</td><td align=\"\">Large break (&gt;5 cm length) in the 20-mmHg isobaric contour with DCI &gt;450 mmHg \u00d7 s \u00d7 cm</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Normal contraction</td><td align=\"\">Not achieving any of the above diagnostic criteria</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\" colspan=\"2\">Intrabolus Pressure Pattern (30-mmHg Isobaric Contour)</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Panesophageal pressurization</td><td align=\"\">Uniform pressurization extending from the UES to the EGJ</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Compartmentalized esophageal pressurization</td><td align=\"\">Pressurization extending from the contractile fron to the EGJ</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">EGJ pressurization</td><td align=\"\">Pressurization restricted to zone between the LES and CD with LES-CD separation (i.e., presence of a hiatal hernia)</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Normal pressurization</td><td align=\"\">No bolus pressurization &gt;30 mmHg</td></tr></tbody></table>\n\n*CD,* Crural diaphragm; *DCI,* distal contractile integral; *DCL,* distal contractile latency; *EGJ,* esophagogastric junction; *LES,* lower esophageal sphincter; *UES,* upper esophageal sphincter.\n\n#### EGJ Morphology and Integrated Relaxation Pressure\n\nWhile the original Chicago Classification focused on dysphagia and abnormal LES relaxation, the CCv4.0 is meant to provide diagnostic certainty when EGJ morphology is normal. The presence of a hiatal hernia can confound findings. Normal EGJ pressure has contribution from both the LES complex and crural diaphragm (CD). Hiatal hernias are diagnosed during the identification of catheter position during inspiration. This leads to separation of the LES and CD. LES\u2013CD separation is the best metric for manometric diagnosis of hiatal hernia. It has a 94% specificity and 92% sensitivity for detecting hiatal hernias >1.2 cm.\n\nFurthermore, decreased LES pressure during inspiration can also indicate hiatal hernia. When anatomy is normal, inspiration leads to augmentation of LES pressure due to crural contraction. When hiatal hernias are present, the negative intrathoracic pressure can decrease the LES pressure. The respiratory inversion point (RIP) identifies where the polarity of the respiratory pressure waves recorded by the catheter change from negative intrathoracic pressure to relative positive intra-abdominal pressure. Also known as the pressure inversion point, RIP is used in differentiating LES from the crural pressures. There is no consensus regarding interpretation of HRM results in the presence of significant EGJ morphologic abnormalities.\n\nNormal LES relaxation is a major branchpoint in CCv4.0. The IRP is the HRM metric used. IRP is defined as the mean lowest 4 seconds of intraluminal pressure across the EGJ obtained within 10 seconds of UES relaxation. Normal median IRP varies depending on the specific software used (<15 or 22 mmHg in the supine position and <12 or 15 mmHg in the upright position). Impaired EGJ relaxation is the hallmark of achalasia and EGJOO. Abnormal IRP has a 98% sensitivity and 96% specificity for the identification of EGJ outflow disorders.\n\n#### Esophageal Body Peristalsis: Contraction Vigor, Distal Contractile Latency, Contraction and Pressurization Patterns\n\n## Contraction Vigor\n\nContraction vigor is the HRM measurement for the strength of peristalsis and reported as a DCI (mmHg \u00d7 s \u00d7 cm). On EPT, DCI is represented by the volume of esophageal peristalsis between the proximal and distal low-pressure troughs. Conceptually, it represents the amplitude, time, and length of each swallow. Normal DCI ranges from 450 to 8000 mmHg \u00d7 s \u00d7 cm. DCI in ineffective swallows is <450 mmHg \u00d7 s \u00d7 cm and DCI in hypercontractile swallows is >8000 mmHg \u00d7 s \u00d7 cm. Ineffective swallows can be weak (DCI 100\u2013450 mmHg \u00d7 s \u00d7 cm), failed (DCI < 100 mmHg \u00d7 s \u00d7 cm), or fragmented (DCI > 450 mmHg \u00d7 s \u00d7 cm, but transition zone defect of greater than 5 cm identified).\n\n## Distal Contractile Latency\n\nDCL is the measure of peristaltic timing to identify normal, premature, or spastic contractions. DCL is defined as the time from swallow initiation (beginning of UES relaxation) to swallow contraction (measured at the CDP). DCL less than 4.5 seconds in the setting of normal DCI is considered abnormal or rapid. DCL is most helpful in describing premature contraction patterns and helps to characterize subtypes of major esophageal motility disorders.\n\n## Contraction and Pressurization Patterns\n\nContraction and pressurization patterns aid in the characterization of esophageal dysmotility subtypes. Broadly, a contraction represents complete closure of the esophageal lumen on the catheter, whereas a pressurization is non-compartmentalized pressure on the catheter. This can result from distal obstruction causing a rise in the luminal pressure exerted on the catheter from the bolus or from severely weak esophageal contractions. Abnormal contraction can be premature, when DCL is less than 4.5 segments, or fragmented, when there is a greater than 5 cm break in the 20-mmHg isobaric contour in the setting of a normal DCI. Premature contraction patters can be seen in type III achalasia or distal esophageal spasm. Panesophageal pressurization (PEP) is characterized by pressurization of the entire length of the esophagus from EUS to EGJ to greater than 30 mmHg. This be seen on EPT as a straight column at the 30-mmHg isobaric contour. PEP is a hallmark of type II achalasia. Pressurization associated with EGJOO more typically follows the path of the contraction front resulting in pressurized segments in the distal esophagus as a result of isolated LES dysfunction.\n\n#### HRM: Surgical Decision Making\n\nHRM provides detailed information regarding the function of the esophagus by detailing the contraction vigor and the status of the EGJ. This information can impact surgical decision making such as defining the length of a myotomy in achalasia subtypes and alerting the surgeon to potential increased risk of postoperative dysphagia following fundoplication. Some studies report improved outcomes with a tailored myotomy based on HRM results. Poor peristaltic reserve has been shown to be predictive for development of dysphagia following fundoplication. HRM can also gauge treatment success. In the setting of achalasia, a normalized IRP is a predictor of good clinical response. See Chapter 14 , Chapter 19 for more details on surgical decision making in these clinical scenarios.\n\n## Functional Lumen Imaging Probe\n\nFLIP is an emerging, balloon catheter-based method for diagnosing esophageal motility disorders. Unlike HRM, which measures pressure, the FLIP catheter measures changes in luminal diameter and pressure in relation to set volumetric distention. FLIP is used to assess secondary peristalsis and EGJ distensibility. Compared with HRM, it is not as widely adopted or as standardized. However, FLIP does pose several advantages. FLIP may be better tolerated by the patient when compared with HRM. It also has the advantage that it can detect non-occlusive contractions not identified on HRM and has identified abnormal panometry results in symptomatic patients with normal HRM. LES distensibility may be a better measurement for diagnosis of achalasia than LES pressure.\n\nFLIP can also be completed and interpreted by the surgeon, providing important real-time information. Its biggest benefit is that it can be used in the operating room and can guide changes in operative technique including tightness of crural closure or fundoplication during surgical management of GERD or identifies the need for additional myotomy during the treatment of achalasia. Currently, it is complimentary to HRM, but additional study and adoption may put FLIP into the forefront.\n\n### FLIP: Technical Aspects\n\nThe FLIP (EndoFLIP; Medtronic Inc.) is a commercially available catheter that consists of a pressure sensor and axially oriented impedance planimetry electrodes centered around an inflatable balloon ( Fig. 2.4 ). There are two FLIP catheters, a 16-cm catheter with 16 electrodes spaced 1 cm apart (EF-322) and an 8 cm catheter with 8 electrodes spaced 0.5 cm apart (EF-325 **)** . The 16-cm catheter is used for assessing esophageal function, and the shorter balloon is best for targeted LES assessments.\n\nTwo photos show a flip catheter inside a tube like balloon with pressure sensors. The top photo shows the deflated balloon, while in the bottom photo, the balloon is inflated with a liquid. #REF!\n\nFig. 2.4\n\nThe FLIP catheter is connected to an infusion pump and the balloon is inflated to a set volume. Balloon pressure and axial diameter at each electrode are measured with electrical impedance. These measurements allow for calculation of a distensibility index (DI, mm <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> /mmHg). Its initial iteration, FLIP 1.0, only allowed for measuring luminal distensibility. The current module, FLIP 2.0, obtains continuous measurements of cross-sectional area across a space\u2013time continuum allowing for assessment of secondary esophageal peristalsis in response to volumetric distention. Similar to EPT, FLIP topography plots are used to visualize esophageal peristalsis. Open-source software (Interactive Flip Analysis; W.K. Analytics and Northwestern Medicine GI lab, Chicago) is used to convert impedance planimetry into a dynamic, topographic plot of diameter across a space\u2013time continuum ( Fig. 2.5 ). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nAn illustration shows the antegrade contractions in a flip catheter guided in the esophagus. The illustration consists of a diagram on the left of a digital display of an impedance planimetry plot. The diagram depicts the movement of the flip catheter 2 point 0 into the esophagus, which monitors the pressure variations on the impedance planimetry plot. High pressures are prominent as the flip catheter is in the esophagus labeled antegrade contractions, while in the esophagogastric junction, the pressure drops to normal pressure. The lowest pressure is visible in the stomach. The plot consists of the balloon illustration with various pressure zones varying from moderate pressure in the upper esophagus to normal pressure in the stomach. A green arrow points to the waist of the balloon illustration in the esophagogastric junction.\n\nFig. 2.5\n\n### FLIP Protocol\n\nImpedance planimetry is completed under sedation. It is usually performed in conjunction with preoperative endoscopy or as an adjunct while undergoing surgical management in the operating room. Halogenated gasses can affect esophageal motility, and their use is avoided during FLIP panometry. After calibration, the balloon catheter is passed through the oropharynx and across the EGJ to measure esophageal peristalsis and EGJ distensibility.\n\nTo assess esophageal body function (panometry), the 16-cm catheter is positioned such that the distal 2\u20133 cm of the catheter is placed within the stomach, and the remainder of the catheter lies within the esophagus. Positioning can be adjusted based on the location of the UES and LES. The balloon is the filled with 50, 60, and 70 mL with a 30- to 60-second observation time at each fill. Balloon distention of the esophagus elicits secondary peristalsis that can be measured in real time. Changes in balloon pressure and diameter along the length of the FLIP catheter are seen with each esophageal contraction. The patterns of secondary peristalsis can then be recorded and classified.\n\nEGJ distensibility can be measured with either the 8-cm or 16-cm catheters. The middle of the catheter is positioned across the EGJ. The balloon is then filled with a series of set volumes, typically 30, 40, and 60 mL. Time is given for the balloon to mold around the esophageal wall. FLIP allows for measurement of a DI, which is a function of balloon pressure and luminal cross-sectional area. It is imperative for balloon pressures to exceed 15 mmHg to ensure reliable data.\n\n### FLIP Metrics\n\nFLIP assesses both EGJ outflow and esophageal body peristalsis. However, unlike HRM, it measures EGJ distensibility or compliance and secondary peristalsis. New algorithms are being developed to classify FLIP panometry.\n\n#### EGJ Compliance: Distensibility Index\n\nFLIP provides information characterizing the EGJ such as length, diameter, and cross-sectional area. DI defines the relationship between cross-sectional area and pressure. DI is the most reliable and studied FLIP metric for EGJ compliance. Using the 16-cm catheter, the normal EGJ-DI is >3.0 mm <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> /mmHg or 2.0\u20133.0 mm <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> /mmHg with a maximum diameter >12 mm. Reduced EGJ opening is seen with DI <2.0 mm <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> /mmHg and maximum diameter <12 mm. EGJ morphology was further classified as borderline normal and borderline reduced EGJ opening. Abnormally low DI values are seen in achalasia or EGJOO, and CCv4.0 includes FLIP in the diagnosis of EGJOO. In a study with 287 symptomatic patients, 86% with reduced EGJ opening as determined by FLIP were found to have an EGJ outflow disorder on CCv4.0. Furthermore, FLIP has also been shown to identify achalasia in a subgroup of patients with normal IRP on HRM.\n\n#### FLIP Panometry\n\nUnlike HRM, which examines peristalsis in an awake patient, FLIP panometry analyzes secondary peristalsis in a sedated patient. Secondary peristalsis occurs in response to distention of the esophagus. Similar to HRM, secondary peristalsis can be categorized to identify underlying esophageal motility disorders. Patterns of contractions are characterized by direction, repetitiveness of contractions, and rate of contractions ( Fig. 2.6 ). Early studies showed a pattern of repetitive antegrade contractions (RACs) in response to esophageal contraction in 77% of patients with normal HRM. Additional studies identified the presence of retrograde contractions and repetitive retrograde contractions in patients with ineffective esophageal motility on HRM, as well as lack the presence of spastic occluding contractions in those with spastic mobility disorders, and absence of secondary contractions in patients with absent contractility on HRM.\n\nA graphical representation of four panels, A, B, C, and D that illustrate variations in diameter measurements across an anatomical region over time. The graphical representations consist of four distinct panels, A, B, C, and D, each with the pressure contour anatomic locations including esophageal body, esophagogastric junction, and stomach. The horizontal axis in panels A and D, covers 50 seconds, while in panels B and C represent 125 seconds. The vertical axis indicates the anatomic lengths of 16 centimeters in all graphs. Panel A shows regular forward pressure variations in the esophageal body and esophagogastric junction. Panel B shows unclear forward pressure variations in the esophagogastric junction and stomach. Panel C shows a flat pressure contour in the esophagogastric junction and stomach for 125 seconds. Panel D shows unclear pressure contours in the esophageal body and esophagogastric junction progressing forward.\n\nFig. 2.6\n\nIn 2021, Carlson et al. performed a prospective study on 539 patients who underwent both HRM and FLIP panometry. A classification system was created for esophageal motility with FLIP panometry based on EGJ morphology and contractile response to balloon distention and is comparable with HRM findings. Normal secondary peristalsis, known as the \u201crule of 6s\u201d was defined as 6 consecutive RACs occurring over 6 cm in length with at least 6 contractions in 1 minute. Additional classification includes borderline contractile response, impaired/disordered contractile response, absent contractile response, and spastic-reactive contractile response.\n\n### FLIP: Surgical Decision Making\n\nFLIP can guide surgical decision making in multiple settings. Preoperatively, it can aid in proper diagnosis as seen in the setting of EGJOO. FLIP can also be predictive of treatment success and development of complications. Perhaps, its greatest benefit comes in its intraoperative use to give objective feedback regarding EGJ distensibility when used to determine the adequateness of myotomy in achalasia and EGJOO. EndoFLIP has been used to assess LES distensibility following laparoscopic Heller myotomy, peroral endoscopic myotomy, and even pneumatic dilation. A persistently low DI has been associated with poor outcomes following treatment. Dysphagia relief is optimized when preoperative DI (typically <2.0 mm <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> /mmHg) improves to 4.5\u20138.5 mm <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> /mmHg following myotomy. EndoFLIP has also been an integral part in determining optimal reduction in EGJ-DI following surgical management of GERD. A low DI after fundoplication may predispose a patient to development of postoperative dysphagia, especially in the setting of ineffective esophageal motility. Conversely, a high DI may result in untreated GERD symptoms.\n\n## Acknowledgments\n\nThe authors thank and acknowledge Ezra N. Teitelbaum, MD, and Christy M. Dunst for their contributions to the prior edition of this chapter.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Gyawali C.P., et al.: ACG clinical guidelines: clinical use of esophageal physiologic testing . Am J Gastroenterol 2020; 115: pp. 1412-1428.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Neyaz Z., Gupta M., Ghoshal U.C.: How to perform and interpret timed barium esophagogram . J Neurogastroenterol Motil 2013; 19: pp. 251-256.\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: Rohof W.O., Hirsch D.P., Kessing B.F., Boeckxstaens G.E.: Efficacy of treatment for patients with achalasia depends on the distensibility of the esophagogastric junction . Gastroenterology 2012; 143: pp. 328-335.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Blonski W., Kumar A., Feldman J., Richter J.E.: Timed barium swallow: diagnostic role and predictive value in untreated achalasia, esophagogastric junction outflow obstruction, and non-achalasia dysphagia . Am J Gastroenterol 2018; 113: pp. 196-203.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: Sanagapalli S., Plumb A., Sweis R.: Timed barium swallow: esophageal stasis varies markedly across subtypes of esophagogastric junction obstruction . Neuro Gastroenterol Motil 2022; 34:\n\nView In Article\n\n6.: Sanagapalli S., Plumb A., Maynard J., Leong R.W., Sweis R.: The timed barium swallow and its relationship to symptoms in achalasia: analysis of surface area and emptying rate . Neuro Gastroenterol Motil 2020; 32:\n\nView In Artic