eal Motility', 'Timed Barium Esophagram', 'High-Resolution Manometry', 'Functional Lumen Imaging Probe', 'Surgical Decision Making', 'Esophageal Motility / Timed Barium Esophagram', 'Esophageal Motility / High-Resolution Manometry', 'Esophageal Motility / Functional Lumen Imaging Probe'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '2', '14-22', 2, 32, FALSE, TRUE),
('Surgical Management of Mid- and Distal Esophageal Diverticula', 'shackelford-9th-ed-20-surgical-management-of-mid-and-distal-esophageal-diverticula', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Surgical Management of Mid- and Distal Esophageal Diverticula\n\nWhitney A. Wright Mattes; Brian E. Louie\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 20, 211-223.e1\n\n## Introduction\n\nDiverticular disease of the esophagus consists of outpouchings of one or more layers of the gut wall that are lined with epithelium. These outpouchings can be found along the entire length of the esophagus and can be numerous. Esophageal diverticula are described by their location along the upper digestive tract: pharyngoesophageal, mid-esophagus, and epiphrenic. Often these diverticula are asymptomatic. When they are symptomatic, they create a significant constellation of symptoms that reduce a patient\u2019s quality of life and may lead to life-threatening complications, such as aspiration pneumonia. Because esophageal diverticula occur often in the elderly or patients with multiple comorbidities, careful pre-surgical evaluation should be completed before treatment is rendered to ensure an optimal outcome. This chapter focuses on the presentation, diagnostics, and management of mid- and distal esophageal diverticula.\n\n## Distal Esophageal (Epiphrenic) Diverticulum\n\nAn epiphrenic diverticulum is an outpouching of mucosa and submucosa through the muscularis propria layer of the distal esophagus that was first described by Mondiere. It is generally accepted that this is a pulsion diverticulum found in the distal 10 cm of the esophagus. These are considered false diverticula because not all layers of the esophagus are involved in the outpouching, though in practical terms, the muscle layer can often be delineated overlying the diverticulum in a very thin layer.\n\nThe incidence of epiphrenic diverticulum is estimated to be 0.02%\u20133% and occurs one-third as frequently as pharyngoesophageal diverticula. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The majority of epiphrenic diverticula are identified in middle-aged or elderly patients, but reported age ranges include patients in the teenage years and mid-20s. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> There is no sex predilection, with most recent series showing that it affects both men and women relatively equally. The majority of patients will present with a single diverticulum. Up to 15% of patients present with two diverticula, and findings of more than two diverticula ( Fig. 20.1 ) occur with a decreasing frequency. The diverticulum arises from the right side of the esophagus in approximately 70% of patients ( Fig. 20.2 ), is usually within 5 cm of the gastroesophageal junction (GEJ), and measures between 4 and 7 cm in maximal dimension ( Fig. 20.3 ). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nA barium swallow radiograph with an esophageal abnormality with contrast. Ch20\n\nFig. 20.1\n\nTwo radiographs depict hip joint abnormalities and spinal conditions where Part A depicts a hip joint with irregularities, and Part B depicts a spinal radiograph with a deformity. The two radiographs depict a barium swallow evaluation. Photo A, an oval window view, displays a contrast-enhanced esophagus with constriction above a stomach bubble-filled contrast. Photo B, a rectangular view, depicts linear esophagus contrast against the background chest anatomy, which ends in a contrast-filled bubble near the stomach. Some areas within the photo indicate areas where the barium contrast is present, which illuminates the structures.\n\nFig. 20.2\n\nA radiograph of the diverticulum with measurement scale alongside. #REF!\n\nFig. 20.3\n\n### Pathophysiology\n\nDespite advances in manometric evaluation, the pathogenesis of an epiphrenic diverticulum has not been fully elucidated. It is generally accepted that this type of diverticulum is almost always secondary to an underlying esophageal motility disorder. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Named motility disorders associated with these diverticula include achalasia, diffuse esophageal spasm, nutcracker esophagus, hypertensive lower esophageal sphincter (LES), and esophagogastric junction outflow obstruction (EGJOO), with the most common being achalasia followed by diffuse esophageal spasm. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> One theory suggests that dysmotility causes an increased intraluminal pressure upstream of high distal outflow pressure or obstruction resulting in subsequent herniation through a weakened area of the esophagus. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Other reported etiologies such as a distal stricture, prior fundoplication, and hiatal hernia all act to create the same outflow pressure dynamics as a motility disorder. Another study identified that esophageal diverticula are associated with areas of low peristaltic pressure amplitude, bizarre peristaltic wave forms, and hypertensive peristaltic pressures.\n\n### Clinical Presentation\n\nPatients with epiphrenic diverticula present with considerable variation from no symptoms to significant complications. Symptomatic patients most commonly present with dysphagia (90%), regurgitation of undigested food (80%), and repetitive episodes of aspiration (30%). Substernal chest pain, pyrosis/heartburn, and weight loss are also commonly reported. However, there is a range of symptomatic patients, some who have minimal or only intermittent symptoms of dysphagia and others who have incapacitating and at times life-threatening symptoms particularly from regurgitation of undigested food that is often precipitated by position and is most often at night. It is often difficult to determine whether the symptoms originate from the diverticulum itself or the underlying motility disorder. In one study, comparing symptoms of different size diverticula in patients with and without a motility disorder, increasing diverticula size, particularly those 5 cm or greater, was more likely to produce symptoms irrespective of the presence of a motility disorder. This suggests that symptoms are more likely derived from the motility disorder early in the disease process. However, with disease progression and increasing anatomic distortion, the diverticulum may contribute more to the severity of symptoms.\n\nRare but reported presentations of esophageal diverticula include food impaction, bleeding, perforation, or malignancy. These complications are described in a small number of case reports. Upper gastrointestinal bleeding has been reported to arise from ulcerations, arteriovenous malformations, or malignancy within a diverticulum. Malignancy, most frequently squamous cell carcinoma, is reported to arise within an epiphrenic diverticulum in a suspected incidence of 0.3%\u20133%. Unfortunately, in most reports, malignancy tends to be detected at a later stage with poor prognosis. Predisposition towards malignant degeneration is thought to arise from chronic inflammation within the diverticulum secondary to underlying dysmotility and associated stasis. Risk factors for malignancy include male sex, longstanding diverticula, older age, and large size of diverticula.\n\n### Diagnosis\n\nAll patients should undergo a thorough history and physical examination to document associated symptoms, comorbidities, and prior foregut surgery or endoscopic interventions. The initial imaging test of choice for evaluating esophageal diverticula is a barium esophagram. It is an essential study for many esophageal diagnoses including hiatal hernias, strictures, and motility disorders. Contrast esophagrams provide information regarding the size (length and volume), orientation (left sided vs. right sided), and location of diverticula in relation to the diaphragm. However, for patients being considered for surgical treatment, the barium esophagram is only the start of a comprehensive evaluation.\n\nEsophagogastroduodenoscopy (EGD) is the second necessary study to define anatomy of the diverticulum including precise location relative to the GEJ ( Fig. 20.4 ). Further assessment for concomitant pathology such as ulceration or malignancy is also elucidated. Additional endoscopic interventions that may be needed include biopsies, treatment of bleeding, placement of a manometry catheter, and feeding tube insertion.\n\nAn endoscopic photo of the diverticulum displays an interior view of an organ of irregular textures. #REF!\n\nFig. 20.4\n\nHigh-resolution manometry (HRM) is the third essential study to define underlying motility disorders and potentially guide location and length of surgical myotomy. Placement of the catheter may be challenging, and a plan should be put in place in advance of the EGD so that it may be placed endoscopically or with fluoroscopy when necessary.\n\nIn addition to the three primary studies mentioned above, there are several additional studies that may provide information preoperatively and during long-term follow-up. First, a timed barium swallow has been used to manage patients treated for achalasia. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Performing this standardized test prior to surgery provides baseline assessment of esophageal emptying and provides a useful objective comparison with post-treatment studies when symptoms may be unreliable. Second, a computed tomography (CT) scan of the chest can be helpful in planning an operative approach. For example, determining the true proximal extent of the diverticulum in reference to surrounding structures, such as the inferior pulmonary veins, may guide a surgeon\u2019s planned approach to diverticular resection. Third, the endoluminal functional lumen imaging probe (EndoFLIP) may be helpful in patients where HRM has not provided a clear motility disorder. For example, in situations where there is normal esophageal motility but evidence of manometric EGJOO, a low distensibility index (<2.0 mm <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> /mmHg) or reduced maximal EGJ opening diameter (<20 mm) could provide support for a potential myotomy. Noh et al. described five patients with and without motility disorders who had decreased esophagogastric junction (EGJ) distensibility index on preoperative EndoFLIP. All patients underwent both cardiomyotomy and diverticular septotomy with normalization of their distensibility index postoperatively and significant improvement in dysphagia scores. Lastly, patients with suspected symptoms of gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) may undergo pH testing for diagnosis and interrogation of symptom correlation.\n\n### Management\n\nThe decision to offer treatment to a patient with an epiphrenic diverticulum is based on the type and severity of a patient\u2019s symptoms. Patients who are asymptomatic or minimally symptomatic may forgo treatment. Subsequent clinical follow-up guidelines in surveillance of diverticula are lacking. Two long-term follow-up studies from the Mayo Clinic provide conflicting data. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Debas et al. in 1980 detailed the outcomes of 37 patients undergoing nonoperative treatment. In this group of patients, seven remained without symptoms and were followed, two underwent surgery elsewhere, and six were treated with esophageal dilation with resolution of symptoms. In the remaining 22, 4 patients experienced an aspiration event with 1 associated death, 2 patients became malnourished, and 1 patient developed an esophageal carcinoma. This suggests that continued follow-up is necessary because of the development of worsening symptoms, complications related to the diverticula, or rarely, malignancy. Comparatively, Benacci et al. in 1993 documented outcomes of 71 patients either presenting with no symptoms or clinically mild symptoms. Of the 47 patients who were asymptomatic, 27 were lost to follow-up. The remaining 20 asymptomatic patients were followed for a median of 4 years (range 1\u201317) and remained asymptomatic. In the group classified as having mild symptoms, 15 were followed a median of 11 years (range 1\u201325 years) with either EGD or barium swallow and remained clinically stable with minimal symptoms. In this study, all patients who were followed remained clinically stable. However, the outcomes of 9/24 were lost in follow-up. Because the symptoms that develop can be progressive, unpredictable, and devastating, it seems reasonable to follow these patients given the rarity of this disease.\n\nSurgery should be considered in those with appropriate physiologic reserve when symptoms significantly affect quality of life and are attributable to the diverticulum or underlying motility disorder. Evaluation is mandatory if a patient develops incapacitating symptoms or respiratory compromise from aspiration of the esophageal contents. Regardless of the surgical approach, there are several surgical principles that have been described for successful treatment of these diverticula. These key steps include:\n\n  - 1.\n\tDelineation of the entire diverticulum at the mucosal level.\n  - 2.\n\tDefinition of the \u201cneck\u201d of the diverticulum.\n  - 3.\n\tResection of the diverticulum.\n  - 4.\n\tClosure of the overlying muscle with or without buttress.\n  - 5.\n\tDistal myotomy with or without partial fundoplication.\n\nAt present, there are a variety of approaches used to surgically treat an epiphrenic diverticulum including transthoracic, video-assisted thoracic surgery (VATS), laparoscopic, and combined VATS\u2013laparoscopic ( Video 20.1 )\n\n### Surgical Approaches\n\n#### Transthoracic Approach\n\nTraditionally, an epiphrenic diverticulum was approached via a seventh or eighth interspace left thoracotomy though both thoracic cavities have been used ( Fig. 20.5 ). Most often the diverticulum resides on the right side of the esophagus; consequently, the entire distal esophagus is mobilized through the left chest including the diaphragmatic hiatus to allow access to the diverticulum. Once the diverticulum is identified, any overlying muscle is split along the length of the diverticulum taking care to avoid the vagus nerve. The mucosa can be grasped carefully, and the muscle dissected away to expose the superior and inferior margins of the diverticulum along with the \u201cneck\u201d or \u201cwaist.\u201d Most surgeons will place either a bougie or an endoscope into the esophagus at this point in preparation for division of the diverticulum with an endoscopic stapler. After division of the diverticulum, the adjacent muscle is approximated with sutures. A buttress of pleura or an intercostal muscle can also be added to cover the suture line.\n\nThree diagrams of surgical procedures in three stages around the heart, diaphragm, and esophagus, focused on the diverticulum. The surgical diagrams are marked A, B, and C. Part A presents a cross-sectional view of the thoracic cavity, which illustrates the heart, diaphragm, esophagus, and aorta, and adjacent anatomical structures with surgical instruments positioned strategically. Part B focuses on the aortic arch and an esophageal surgical technique, detailed on stitch with precise annotations. Part C elaborates on the myotomized esophagus, and represents the surgical incision and manipulation of esophageal tissue.\n\nFig. 20.5\n\nThe esophagogastric myotomy is begun on the contralateral side of the esophagus at the level of the inferior aspect of the diverticulectomy and extended onto the stomach for 2 cm. Some surgeons will also extend the myotomy proximally for 1\u20132 cm, whereas other surgeons will extend the myotomy up to the aortic arch as shown in Fig. 20.5 . However, the value of this proximal extension is unclear as the high-pressure zone is distal to the diverticulum. Many surgeons favor the addition of a partial antireflux repair to provide an element of reflux control, and in this circumstance, most opt to create a Belsey Mark IV fundoplication. A flexible drain such as a Blake or JP is frequently left near the diverticulectomy prior to closure.\n\n#### Video-Assisted Thoracic Approach Then Laparoscopic Myotomy/Fundoplication\n\nAfter placement of a double-lumen endotracheal tube, the patient is placed in the left lateral decubitus position with the bed flexed at the top of the iliac crest. A total of four ports are placed (seventh intercostal space \\[ICS\\] posterior axillary line for surgeon\u2019s left hand/stapler, ninth ICS in the line of the scapular tip for the camera, fourth ICS posterior axillary line for retraction and suctioning, and seventh ICS just inferior and posterior to the scapular tip for the surgeon\u2019s right hand) ( Fig. 20.6 ). Similar to the approach via thoracotomy, the diverticulum is identified, and the muscular layers of the esophageal wall split to identify the mucosa at the inferior and superior aspect of the diverticulum. Once the neck of the diverticulum ( Fig. 20.7A ) is exposed and dissected free, the stapler is then applied over the neck of the diverticulum with either a bougie or upper endoscope *in situ* and resected with an endoscopic stapler ( Fig. 20.7B ). The muscular layers are closed with interrupted sutures and occasionally reinforced with pleura. A 24-French chest tube and/or a 24-French drain is placed adjacent to the esophagus prior to closure.\n\nA photo of the incision sites indicated on a patient''s side torso. The photo presents the lateral aspect of a person''s torso, with skin texture. The marked areas are labeled with text fourth Inter-costal space Assistant port near the upper section, two instances of seventh Inter-costal space in the central region, and ninth Inter-costal space Camera located lower down. Small lines are marked at each incision site.\n\nFig. 20.6\n\nTwo photographs of the diverticulum in the medical procedure. The photos are arranged in two panels, A and B, which display close-up views of human tissue under possible surgical examination. High contrast and saturated red hues dominate the scene. Panel A showcases the tissue in its apparent natural state, without any indication of surgical intervention, while panel B includes parts of surgical instruments amidst the tissue. Panels are sharply divided by a vertical line, with labels A and B situated at the bottom left of each panel in a small font size.\n\nFig. 20.7\n\nThe challenge in using a VATS-first approach is accessing the GEJ to perform a distal esophageal myotomy. As most diverticula are found in the right chest and access to the proximal stomach is limited from this approach, several options have been proposed. First, it has been suggested to perform pneumatic dilation of the LES prior to diverticulectomy in patients with a documented motility disorder. It is likely this will need to be repeated to achieve a similar result to surgical myotomy based on a recent trial. Second, the patient can be repositioned supine or low lithotomy and a laparoscopic myotomy with or without partial fundoplication can be performed. To ensure the proper extent of the myotomy, the distal end of the diverticulum is marked with a clip on the anterior surface of the esophageal wall at the completion of the VATS portion. The clip can then be identified at laparoscopy and the esophagomyotomy performed from the clip on the left side of the esophagus onto the gastric cardia. Lastly, if the diverticulum is left sided, the myotomy can be performed similar to the approach described by Pellegrini et al. though the relief of dysphagia and ability to create a fundoplication favors adding a laparoscopic myotomy.\n\n#### Laparoscopic Approach With or Without Video-Assisted Thoracic Approach Diverticulectomy\n\nA laparoscopic transhiatal approach is becoming increasingly common. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Most surgeons position the patient as they would for a modified Heller\u2013Dor or Nissen fundoplication procedure. We favor the patient in low lithotomy with placement of five laparoscopic ports. The initial exposure is to dissect and mobilize the entire esophageal hiatus for maximal exposure. The vagal nerves are identified as dissection is performed cranially up the esophagus until the distal aspect of the diverticulum is identified. Once identified, the dissection proceeds anterior and posterior along the diverticulum until circumferential dissection is complete. The distally identified vagus nerves are then traced toward the diverticulum; occasionally, it is necessary to separate a nerve from the diverticulum. The neck of the diverticulum is then identified by separating any remaining muscle fibers and then dissecting down to expose the mucosa. Similar to the open and VATS approaches, the neck of the diverticulum is exposed, and an endoscopic stapler is applied over the neck of the diverticulum with either a bougie or upper endoscope *in situ* ( Fig. 20.8 ). The staple line is then imbricated using permanent sutures.\n\nA diagram and a photo, where one is a laparoscopic stapled resection of an epiploic diverticulum and the other is the stapler. The diagram and the photo are featured in two panels. The left panel is an illustration of an anatomic view of a gastric diverticulum, annotated with surgical instruments in place for a laparoscopic approach, with curved lines that indicate tension on the tissue. The right panel is a high-resolution photo taken during surgery, that displays a surgical instrument that grasps tissue surrounded by a background that depicts the internal anatomy with some bleeding. The overall composition highlights the surgical context and techniques used in the procedure.\n\nFig. 20.8\n\nThe esophageal myotomy is performed along the anterior wall of the esophagus just to the left of midline. The myotomy is extended distally from at least the inferior aspect of the diverticulum through the LES and extended 2 cm onto the proximal stomach. The hiatus is then reapproximated posteriorly, taking care not to close too tightly, and either a Toupet fundoplication is created posteriorly, or a Dor fundoplication is created anteriorly ( Fig. 20.9 ).\n\nTwo diagrams of the steps of a procedure related to esophageal wall manipulation and staple attachment. #REF!\n\nFig. 20.9\n\nWhen the diverticulum is unable to be completely delineated or completely stapled, it is left alone and the esophageal myotomy performed with fundoplication. The patient is then reintubated with a double-lumen endotracheal tube and the appropriate chest is entered as described above to perform and complete the diverticulectomy.\n\n### Endoscopic Approach\n\nThird-space endoscopic surgical techniques such as endoscopic tunneling and endoscopic myotomy have become widely used and accepted. Not surprisingly, there are multiple reports of their use in the management of epiphrenic diverticula as an alternative to laparoscopic or open surgery. This option may be best for patients who are poor surgical candidates for various reasons including comorbidities or prior surgical history or those who have not responded to prior therapeutic interventions or are high risk for continued attempts at dilation.\n\nAs endoscopic techniques are still evolving, there is no single approach that is accepted to be the standard. Therefore, nuance as to the extent, location, and length of myotomy as well as treatment of the diverticula exists. The first distinction in endoscopic therapy addresses whether or not the EGJ is treated. In one case series of four patients, the choice to extend the myotomy across the LES was determined by the presence of a motility disorder on preoperative HRM. Newer studies include EndoFLIP measurements as part of an algorithm to determine myotomy extent, particularly whether or not to carry the myotomy through the GEJ onto the cardia. In most reports, a submucosal tunnel was created to facilitate a distal esophageal myotomy of the circular muscle fibers using the same technique as peroral endoscopic myotomy (POEM) for achalasia including 2\u20133 cm onto the gastric cardia. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nThe next distinction is the location of the myotomy. Sato et al. described creating the myotomy on the contralateral wall of the esophagus in relation to the diverticulum following submucosal tunneling. Alternatively, similar to techniques used to treat Zenker\u2019s diverticula by performing an endoscopic septotomy, often referred to as diverticular POEM (D-POEM), are also described. Lastly, the length of the myotomy is also variable. Long myotomies encompassing the mid- and distal esophagus regardless of diverticulum location are described, while other myotomies are tailored to begin at or just above the level of the diverticulum.\n\nEndoscopic management of the diverticulum differs among reports as well. Early reports describe creation of the tunnel with completion of the myotomy and no intervention on the diverticulum particularly if small and minimized after myotomy. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> With the septotomy method akin to flexible endoscopic Zenker\u2019s therapies, the septotomy diminishes the amount of intraluminal redundancy and \u201csink\u201d of the diverticula and no further treatment is performed for the diverticulum itself. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Alternatively, others invert the diverticulum into the lumen and use an endoscopic snare placed around the neck of the diverticulum with eventual mucosal sloughing and healing of the defect over time. A fourth option described is creation of a channel between the diverticulum and the gastric body by means of a transdiverticulum-to-gastric puncture and subsequent dilation of the channel with placement of an endoscopic stent.\n\nA meta-analysis released in 2022 reported a greater than 90% treatment success with use of POEM and D-POEM to treat epiphrenic diverticula, which was maintained at 2 years with a 0% recurrence rate of symptoms. Additionally, the reported serious adverse event rate was 8.4% (0%\u201316.8%). At the present time, endoscopic approaches for creating a distal myotomy seem feasible with a relatively low risk and morbidity profile; however, the number of patients is limited and although short-term outcomes seem reasonable, long-term outcomes remain unknown given the novelty of endoscopic surgical techniques. Additionally, no large population studies exist comparing endoscopic with surgical therapies have been published. Additional experience on how to manage the diverticulum itself is also needed as most techniques should still be classified as experimental given the lack of standardization and supportive data.\n\n### Current Controversies in Surgical Approach\n\nSurgeons caring for patients with an epiphrenic diverticulum who wish to approach these minimally invasively should be sufficiently skilled in both laparoscopy and thoracoscopy. Although the diverticulum is commonly just above the GEJ, it can be located anywhere in the distal esophagus with the cephalad edge located above the inferior pulmonary veins. During laparoscopic hiatal hernia repair, access to the level of the inferior pulmonary veins can consistently be achieved, but rarely above this point. In the patient with a normal hiatus (i.e., without a hiatal hernia) access and visualization into the mediastinum may be limited and the hiatus may need to be enlarged. It is likely that diverticula that are greater than 5 cm from the GEJ will be inadequately addressed with a transhiatal dissection with a higher propensity for incomplete resection or a staple line leak at the superior-most aspect of the diverticulectomy. This is supported by a report by Allaix et al. in which 13 patients with achalasia and epiphrenic diverticulum underwent attempted resection. The diverticulum was excised in six patients but left *in situ* in seven patients. In four of the seven patients, the diverticulum was left in place because it was too far from the GEJ and could not be safely dissected laparoscopically. Postoperatively, patient symptoms were controlled as measured by the Eckardt score, but patients were only followed for 2 years. This contrasts with other reports recommending the addition of a VATS in these high diverticula. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nRegardless of symptoms, it is unclear what the impact is of leaving the diverticulum *in situ* with its long-term potential for bleeding, impaction, and stasis with regurgitation. Until further data are reported, it is advisable to resect the diverticulum except in extenuating circumstances or a small diverticulum that disappears after myotomy. In patients with high diverticula, a combined VATS and laparoscopic approach may be a more suitable and efficacious option. One strategy to assess the location of the diverticulum endoscopically is to measure the location of the upper border of the diverticulum in relation to the GEJ. For diverticula less than 5 cm above the GEJ, a laparoscopic transhiatal approach is likely to be successful, whereas for those greater than 5 cm above the GEJ or above the inferior pulmonary vein, a combined thoracoscopic\u2013laparoscopic minimally invasive approach is likely necessary.\n\nThe addition of an esophagomyotomy is accepted by most esophageal surgeons as a standard component of management as most diverticula are associated with an underlying motility disorder. Theoretically, a distal obstruction or high-pressure zone potentially increases the risk for diverticulectomy staple line dehiscence and subsequent leakage. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> However, a myotomy does not always eliminate the chance for leak. The selective use of a myotomy in patients without a motility disorder has been proposed based on a small series of patients. The rationale for abstaining from a myotomy is that patients with a normal LES will have resolution of their symptoms after diverticulectomy alone and that a myotomy creates the potential for gastroesophageal reflux. There has been no clear resolution about the controversy of a myotomy, but the majority of cases reported in the literature include a myotomy, and it is suggested to include a myotomy as part of treatment until additional data supporting its exclusion is provided.\n\n### Complications\n\nRegardless of the approach (surgical or endoscopic), the operative risks remain significant in a patient population that is often malnourished, elderly, with significant comorbidities, and potentially longstanding pulmonary injury from aspiration. A wide variety of postoperative complications have been reported, but complications specific to this operation include staple line leak, myotomy bleeding, incomplete myotomy, vagal nerve injury (manifested by delayed gastric emptying), and pleural effusion. Broader complications that are more commonly associated with open resection have also been reported and include intraoperative hemorrhage, pulmonary complications (acute respiratory distress syndrome, pneumonia), and cardiac events (atrial fibrillation, infarction). Complications specific to endoscopic management include abscess from full-thickness injury, and GERD. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nThe most significant complication is a staple line leak ( Fig. 20.10 ). These are best avoided by careful and meticulous dissection of the diverticulum to the mucosal origin (neck), reapproximation of the esophageal muscle, and complete myotomy. When a staple line leak occurs, treatment is individualized for the patient and the extent of leak. Patients are made nil per os (NPO, or nothing by mouth), antifungal and antibiotics to cover gram-negative enteric organisms are begun, and alternative forms of nutrition are tailored to the specific patient and situation. Upper endoscopy is crucial in determining early management. Whenever feasible, endoscopic clips, or suturing to control leakage can be attempted as these procedures are far less morbid than traditional open interventions. However, endoscopic stenting or endoluminal wound vac sponge to manage the staple line disruption is far more likely to be successful. However, if less invasive endoscopic measures prove unsuccessful in mitigating leakage, return to the operating room is always available for wide drainage, control of contamination, and diversion (when necessary).\n\nA computed tomography scan of a cross-section of the chest that highlights abscesses in the cavity. #REF!\n\nFig. 20.10\n\n### Outcomes of Diverticulectomy and Myotomy\n\nThe surgical treatment results for epiphrenic diverticula in series reporting at least 10 cases are tabulated in Tables 20.1 and 20.2 . Regardless of the approach, transthoracic or minimally invasive, the reported outcomes show good to excellent relief of symptoms in the majority of patients. The operative mortality rate has decreased with transition to a minimally invasive approach, but the rates of morbidity remain significant, likely reflecting the underlying age and comorbidities that are carried by patients with this disease. Lastly, while the postoperative leak rate remains the Achilles heel of any operation on the esophageal mucosa, long-term outcomes and mortality are not compromised with prompt and successful leak management. The results of endoscopic treatment are tabulated in Table 20.3 promising clinical results in early follow-up albeit with small numbers of patients.\n\nTable 20.1\n\nOutcomes of Transthoracic Epiphrenic Diverticulum Surgery\n\n<table><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Author</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Years</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\"><i>N</i></th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Approach</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Operation</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Mortality (%)</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Morbidity (%)</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Leak</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Outcomes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align=\"\" rowspan=\"2\">Allen and Claggett <button><sup>24</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">1944\u20131953</td><td align=\"\">24</td><td align=\"\">RT</td><td align=\"\">D</td><td align=\"\">4</td><td align=\"\">25</td><td align=\"\"></td><td align=\"\">10/24 persistent symptoms</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">1954\u20131963</td><td align=\"\">17</td><td align=\"\">LT</td><td align=\"\">D/M</td><td align=\"\">6</td><td align=\"\">18</td><td align=\"\"></td><td align=\"\">15/27 good to excellent relief of symptoms</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Streitz et al. <button><sup>46</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">1960\u20131990</td><td align=\"\">18</td><td align=\"\">LT</td><td align=\"\">D (8)<br>D/M (10)</td><td align=\"\">0</td><td align=\"\">33</td><td align=\"\">6</td><td align=\"\">Median follow-up = 7 years<ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>13/18 good to excellent relief of symptoms</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Neurogenic</p></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">F\u00e9k\u00e9te and Vonns <button><sup>53</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">1969\u20131989</td><td align=\"\">27</td><td align=\"\">RT/LT<br>Lap</td><td align=\"\">D (10)<br>D/M/F (10)<br>M/F (4)</td><td align=\"\">11</td><td align=\"\">19</td><td align=\"\">7</td><td align=\"\"></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Altorki et al. <button><sup>54</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">1970\u20131990</td><td align=\"\">17</td><td align=\"\">LT</td><td align=\"\">D/M/F (14)</td><td align=\"\">6</td><td align=\"\"></td><td align=\"\"></td><td align=\"\">Median follow-up = 7 years<ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>13/17 symptom free</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>1/17 poor result</p></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Benacci et al. <button><sup>12</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">1975\u20131991</td><td align=\"\">33</td><td align=\"\">LT</td><td align=\"\">D (7)<br>D/M (22)<br>M (1)<br>Resection (3)</td><td align=\"\">9.1</td><td align=\"\">33</td><td align=\"\">18</td><td align=\"\">Median follow-up = 7 years<ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>67% good to excellent outcomes</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>33% poor to fair outcomes</p></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Castrucci et al. <button><sup>55</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">1983\u20131995</td><td align=\"\">27</td><td align=\"\">LT</td><td align=\"\">D (5)<br>D/M (5)<br>D/M/F (17)</td><td align=\"\">7</td><td align=\"\">11</td><td align=\"\">4</td><td align=\"\">Mean follow-up = 47 months<ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>92% satisfied</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Visick I and II</p></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Nehra et al. <button><sup>14</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">1987\u20131996</td><td align=\"\">21</td><td align=\"\">LT</td><td align=\"\">D/M/F</td><td align=\"\">5</td><td align=\"\"></td><td align=\"\">5</td><td align=\"\">Median follow-up = 24 months<ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>88% good to excellent outcomes</p></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Varghese et al. <button><sup>8</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">1976\u20132005</td><td align=\"\">35</td><td align=\"\">LT</td><td align=\"\">D/M/F (33)</td><td align=\"\">2.8</td><td align=\"\">9</td><td align=\"\">6</td><td align=\"\">Median follow-up = 33 months<ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>76% excellent resolution of symptoms</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>21 mild dysphagia</p></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">D\u2019Journo et al. <button><sup>56</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">1977\u20132008</td><td align=\"\">23</td><td align=\"\">LT</td><td align=\"\">D/M/F</td><td align=\"\">0</td><td align=\"\">9</td><td align=\"\"></td><td align=\"\">Median follow-up = 61 months<ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Significant symptom improvement</p></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Sudarshan et al. <button><sup>48</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">1990\u20132016</td><td align=\"\">94</td><td align=\"\">LT (80)<br>RT (2)<br>C (20)</td><td align=\"\">D (91)<br>M (89)<br>F (55)</td><td align=\"\">3.2</td><td align=\"\">26</td><td align=\"\">7.4</td><td align=\"\">Median follow-up= 7 months</td></tr></tbody></table>\n\n*C,* Combo/conversion; *D,* diverticulectomy; *F,* fundoplication; *Lap,* laparoscopic transhiatal; *LT* , left thoracotomy; *M,* myotomy; *RT* , right thoracotomy.\n\nTable 20.2\n\nOutcomes of Minimally Invasive Epiphrenic Diverticulum Surgery\n\n| Author | Years | *N* | Approach | Operation | Mortality (%) | Morbidity (%) | Leak (%) | Outcomes |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Rosati et al. Fumagalli et al. | 1994\u20132020 | 30 | Lap | D/M/F | 0 | 6 | 3.3 | Median follow-up = 52 months - \u2022 \tExcellent results - \u2022 \t3/19 mild symptoms |\n| Klaus et al. | 1996\u20132000 | 10 | Lap | D/M (6) D (4) | 0 | 20 | 10 | Median follow-up = 26 months - \u2022 \tSymptom score significantly improved |\n| Fernando et al. Macke et al. | 1997\u20132020 | 57 | V (33) Lap (18) Lap/V (6) | D (6) D/M (27) D/M/F (20) D/F (3) | 2 | 30 | 11 | Mean follow-up = 21 months - \u2022 \tDysphagia improved - \u2022 \tGERD-HRQL = 5 |\n| Del Genio et al. | 1994\u20132002 | 13 | Lap | D/M/F | 8 | 30 | 23 | Median follow-up = 58 months - \u2022 \t100% good to excellent outcome |\n| Soares et al. | 1997\u20132008 | 23 | Lap (19) Lap/V (4) | D/M/F (16) | 4.3 | 26 | 0 | Median follow-up = 45 months - \u2022 \t85% good to excellent |\n| Zaninotto et al. | 1993\u20132010 | 24 | Lap (17) Lap/RT (7) | D/M/F (14) D/F (3) | 0 | 35 | 16.6 | Median follow-up = 96 months - \u2022 \t71% successful treatment |\n| Melman et al. | 1999\u20132006 | 13 | Lap | D/M | 0 | 15 | 8 | Median follow-up = 13 months - \u2022 \t15% with persistent dysphagia - \u2022 \t8% with GERD |\n| Palanivelu et al. | 2008 | 20 | Lap (8) V (4) | D (7) D/M (1) D/M/F (2) D/F (2) | 0 | | 8 | Median follow-up = 24 months - \u2022 \tOne patient with GERD |\n| Allaix et al. | 2009\u20132013 | 13 | Lap | M/F (7) D/M/F (6) | 0 | | 17 | Mean follow-up = 21 and 11 months - \u2022 \tEckardt score = 0 |\n| Achim et al. | 2004\u20132015 | 17 | Lap (9) Lap/V (5) V (3) | D/M/F (14) D (3) | 6 | 23.5 | 18 | Median follow-up 10 months - \u2022 \tEckhardt score = 0 - \u2022 \tGERD-HRQL = 1 |\n\n*D* , Diverticulectomy; *F,* fundoplication; *GERD-HRQL,* Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease Health-Related Quality-of-Life score; *Lap,* laparoscopic transhiatal; *M* , myotomy; *RT* , right thoracotomy; *V,* right video-assisted thoracic surgery (VATS).\n\nTable 20.3\n\nOutcomes of Endoscopic Epiphrenic Diverticulum Surgery\n\n| Author | Years | *N* | Approach | Operation | Mortality (%) | Morbidity (%) | Leak (%) | Outcomes |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Yang et al. | 2014\u20132017 | 4 | Endoscopic | D-POEM | 0 | No events reported | 0 | Median follow-up= 145 days - \u2022 \t100% clinical success |\n| Basile et al. | 2017\u20132018 | 7 | Endoscopic | D-POEM | 0 | No events reported | 0 | Median follow-up = 3 months - \u2022 \t85% clinical improvement |\n| Orlandini et al. | 2017\u20132018 | 4 | Endoscopic | POEM | 0 | 1/4 aspiration pneumonia | 0 | Median follow-up = 7 months - \u2022 \t100% clinical improvement |\n| Noh et al. | 2019\u20132021 | 9 | Endoscopic | D-POEM | 0 | 22% | 0 | Median follow-up = 7 months - \u2022 \t8/9 with improved and normalized DI - \u2022 \t100% clinical success - \u2022 \t1/9 mild GERD |\n\n*D-POEM,* Diverticular peroral endoscopic myotomy; *DI,* distensibility index; *GERD,* gastroesophageal reflux disease.\n\nCurrently, epiphrenic diverticula remains a rare disease with most surgeons reporting on 20 to 30 cases over decades of care. Since the early 2000s, there has been a slow but steady transition away from an open transthoracic approach to the use of minimally invasive techniques. The cumulative experience to date suggests that a laparoscopic approach is quickly becoming the approach of choice with the addition of VATS for diverticula placed higher in the mediastinum.\n\n## Mid-Esophageal Diverticulum\n\nMid-esophageal diverticula are true diverticula that involve all layers of the esophagus (mucosa, submucosa, and muscularis) and are found in the middle one-third of the esophagus within 4\u20135 cm of the tracheal carina. They are traditionally thought of as traction diverticula that occur due to mediastinal inflammation pulling on the esophageal wall to create the diverticulum. These adhesions are most often caused by a granulomatous inflammatory reaction in subcarinal lymph nodes or by scar tissue. The granulomatous diseases typically associated with these adhesions include sarcoidosis, histoplasmosis, and tuberculosis ( Fig. 20.11 ). In addition, etiologies include a congenital component related to an incomplete tracheal\u2013esophageal fistula or foregut duplication. In addition to the traction etiology, there is most likely a pulsion component, as motility disorders are present in over 80% of patients who present with this type of diverticulum.\n\nA computed tomography of a chest that represents internal organs and structures of the thoracic cavity. #REF!\n\nFig. 20.11\n\n### Symptoms and Diagnosis\n\nMid-esophageal diverticula are typically asymptomatic due to their typical wide-mouth opening and dependent drainage. They are therefore often diagnosed incidentally on esophageal imaging in the work-up of another condition. When symptomatic, most patients present with intermittent dysphagia and some with occasional retrosternal pain, heartburn, and/or acid reflux. Patients will also present due to complications of the traction diverticula. Ongoing inflammation in the region can lead to the development of a fistula between the diverticulum and the airway and bleeding secondary to erosion into a bronchial artery, small esophageal vessel, or even major vessel. Bleeding is also caused by the friable granulation tissue found at the tip of the diverticulum.\n\nThe diagnostic approach to the mid-esophageal diverticulum involves the same investigations that are used for an epiphrenic diverticulum. However, the initial test that identifies the diverticulum is most often a CT scan of the chest during evaluation for mediastinal adenopathy or for chronic cough due to a small fistula. A contrast radiographic study should be included in the evaluation. In the absence of obvious mediastinal pathology being the causative agent, HRM should be undertaken given that many of these patients will have an underlying disorder that may impact surgical decision-making. During endoscopic evaluation, the option of bronchoscopy should be available, particularly if there is a suspicion for a fistula. This can often be difficult to ascertain, and an injection of dilute methylene blue into the esophagus may be visualized in the proximal airways ( Fig. 20.12 ).\n\nA medical photo of the diverticulum with a blue stain evident on the right. #REF!\n\nFig. 20.12\n\n### Treatment\n\nMost mid-esophageal diverticula are incidentally diagnosed and need no further treatment. The indications for surgery are related to the presence of symptoms from the diverticulum. This is best approached with a right thoracotomy through the fifth ICS given the ease of access to the carina, mediastinal nodes, and esophagus. The surgeon should expect extreme scarring and distorted anatomy due to the ongoing inflammation. The first step will be to separate the esophagus and diverticulum from the adjoining mediastinal nodes. Once this is accomplished, any fistulous tract should be divided and controlled. The diverticulum should be isolated, and the mucosa should be evaluated and repaired or resected depending on the degree of damage. The overlying muscle layers should be reapproximated over top with an interposition graft usually of intercostal muscle placed between the repair and the inflamed tissue to prevent recurrence. If an underlying motility disorder has been identified, a distal myotomy should be considered.\n\nExpected outcomes from surgical management of a mid-esophageal diverticulum should approximate those of a distal diverticulum. Specific series addressing these outcomes are limited only to case reports or to a handful of cases included in a larger series of distal esophageal diverticula.\n\n## Summary\n\nMid- and distal esophageal diverticula are uncommon diseases that often present without symptoms. However, some patients will have incapacitating or life-threatening symptoms from either the diverticulum, the underlying motility disorder, or both. After identification by barium swallow, careful evaluation of the patient followed by upper endoscopy, HRM, and sometimes CT scan of the chest will provide the key information upon which to plan surgical treatment. Like many esophageal procedures, treatment of these diverticula has moved toward minimally invasive surgery to perform the diverticulectomy, distal esophageal myotomy, and in most instances a partial fundoplication. Diverticula near the inferior pulmonary vein may be better addressed with combined VATS and laparoscopy. Endoscopic treatment is emerging and shows promise, but innovation continues to evolve and the optimal endoscopic management of esophageal diverticula has yet to be determined. For most patients, surgical treatment results in relief of the presenting symptoms and a low rate of mortality but not insignificant rate of morbidity. The staple line leak remains the key complication surgeons hope to avoid.\n\n## Acknowledgments\n\nThe authors and editors acknowledge and thank the previous edition authors Shane P. Smith and Oliver C. Bellevue for their contribution to this chapter.\n\n\u2022 Video 20.1 Laparoscopic hiatal dissection and mobilization of epiphrenic diverticulum with diverticulectomy. Intraoperative esophagogastroduodenoscopy clip included for intraluminal definition of diverticulum proximal and distal extent. Heller myotomy performed followed by Dor fundoplication.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Mondiere J.: Notes sur quelques m