6.6h-21.8c-.3%200-.6-.3-.6-.6V7zm28.8%200c0-.4.2-.6.5-.6h5.2c.3%200%20.6.2.6.6v30.5c0%20.3%200%20.4.3.4H151c.3%200%20.5.2.5.5V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.5.6h-20.8c-.3%200-.517-.3-.5-.6V7zm47.7%2036.7c-.4%200-.6-.2-.8-.5l-7.3-12.7-7.4%2012.7c-.2.3-.4.5-.8.5h-5.8c-.3%200-.5-.3-.3-.7L166%2024.3%20156%207.1c-.2-.4%200-.7.3-.7h5.8c.4%200%20.6.1.8.5l6.5%2011.3h.1L176%206.9c.2-.4.5-.5.9-.5h5.7c.4%200%20.5.3.3.7l-10%2017.2L183.7%2043c.2.4%200%20.7-.3.7h-5.8zM192.015%2019c-.2%200-.338-.004-.3-.2V8.4h-3.3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n\n\nNeed help? Chat with AI Buddy!\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[19. Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment - ClinicalKey|19. Achalasia Diagnosis and Treatment]]\n**Next:** [[21. Paraesophageal Hernia:: Etiology, Presentation, and Indications for Repair - ClinicalKey|21. Paraesophageal Hernia:: Etiology, Presentation, and Indications for Repair]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "20. Surgical Management of Mid- and Distal Esophageal Diverticula - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Surgical Management of Mid- and Distal Esophageal Diverticula', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Surgical Management of Mid- and Distal Esophageal Diverticula', 'Distal Esophageal (Epiphrenic) Diverticulum', 'Mid-Esophageal Diverticulum', 'Pathophysiology', 'Clinical Presentation', 'Diagnosis', 'Surgical Management of Mid- and Distal Esophageal Diverticula / Distal Esophageal (Epiphrenic) Diverticulum', 'Surgical Management of Mid- and Distal Esophageal Diverticula / Mid-Esophageal Diverticulum', 'Surgical Management of Mid- and Distal Esophageal Diverticula / Pathophysiology'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '20', '211-223', 2, 45, FALSE, TRUE),
('Paraesophageal Hernia:: Etiology, Presentation, and Indications for Repair', 'shackelford-9th-ed-21-paraesophageal-hernia-etiology-presentation-and-indications-for-repair', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Paraesophageal Hernia: : Etiology, Presentation, and Indications for Repair\n\nRobert Acho; Vic Velanovich; Christopher Ducoin\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 21, 225-232\n\n## Introduction\n\nParaesophageal hernias occur when the contents of the abdomen migrate superiorly through the diaphragmatic hiatus into the posterior mediastinum. The term \u201cparaesophageal\u201d literally means \u201cnext to the esophagus,\u201d because intraabdominal contents herniate through the diaphragmatic hiatus \u201cnext to\u201d or \u201calongside\u201d the esophagus. Paraesophageal hernias are distinct from sliding (type I) hiatal hernias in which the gastroesophageal junction migrates through the diaphragmatic hiatus in the axis of the esophagus; thus, there are no intraabdominal contents alongside the esophagus. The true prevalence of paraesophageal hernias is not known, although they are thought to be less common than type I (sliding) hiatal hernias.\n\nThe importance of paraesophageal hernia is due to the spectrum of symptoms, presentations, and consequences which run the gamut from completely asymptomatic and inconsequential to life-threatening gastric volvulus and necrosis, with perforation of the stomach and subsequent sepsis. Due to these potential complications, it was once thought that all paraesophageal hernias should be repaired upon diagnosis. Recent evidence, however, has demonstrated that observation with an awareness of paraesophageal-related symptoms is a safe option in many cases. Surgical intervention is usually reserved for patients who are exhibiting symptoms secondary to paraesophageal hernias. Given that paraesophageal hernias tend to occur in older individuals who may have significant comorbidities or frailty, decisions on treatment require nuanced calculations. Therefore, knowledge of such symptoms and presentations is essential for patient-specific decision-making.\n\nThe general etiology, presentation, and indications for repair of paraesophageal hernias will be reviewed here; this review will not cover traumatic diaphragmatic hernias or congenital diaphragmatic defects such as posterolateral Bochdalek hernias and retrosternal Morgagni hernias.\n\n## Pathogenesis and Etiology\n\nThe defining salient defect in paraesophageal hernia is the widening of the diaphragmatic hiatus. The reasons for this can be variable and multifactorial.\n\nNormal intraabdominal pressures at rest are between 5 and 14 mmHg, and transiently can become much higher. The normal intrathoracic pressures at rest are between\u20134 and\u201316 mmHg. This results in a normal pressure difference between the two cavities of between 9 and 30 mmHg and can be transiently much higher. In a normal hiatus, the phrenoesophageal ligament obliterates any space between the esophagus and diaphragm which allows maintenance of the relative pressure differential between the negative thoracic environment and the positive abdominal cavities. However, these structures can stretch and loosen with respiration and other stressors over time which creates a space or gap between the esophagus and diaphragmatic hiatus. This gap between the esophagus and hiatus allows for the equilibration of pressure between the abdomen and the chest. The phrenoesophageal ligament also functions to maintain the gastroesophageal junction within the abdomen. The phrenoesophageal ligament is responsible for returning the gastroesophageal junction to its normal position after a swallow. As with the hiatus, over time, the pressure exerted on a phrenoesophageal ligament of susceptible tensile strength will eventually reach its yield point and permanently stretch, increasing mobility at the hiatus. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nThis pressure differential will be transmitted through the gap between the esophagus and the hiatus, resulting in stress at the edge of the hiatus ( Fig. 21.1 ). Depending on the tensile strength of the hiatus and phrenoesophageal ligament to oppose this stress, little strain on these structures may result. However, if the pressures are great enough or the tensile strength weak enough, eventually the yield point of the tissues will be reached so that the hiatal crura are permanently elongated and a hernia sac will form from the phrenoesophageal ligament and peritoneum. This makes the hernia sac of paraesophageal hernias unique among hernias as it is the only hernia sac which contains two layers, the peritoneum and the phrenoesophageal ligament, as opposed to only the one layer of peritoneum in other hernias.\n\nTwo diagrams illustrate esophageal pressure and stress in the diaphragm. The left diagram displays a series of curved lines with arrows that demonstrate airflow and indicate pressure levels between 9 and 20 millimeters of mercury. The right diagram depicts a cross-section of the esophagus and features an oval shape labeled Esophageal Hiatus surrounded by arrows that signify force. An equation labeled Stress equals Force divided by Area is included, with additional labels that identify the esophagus, diaphragm, and the range of pressure 9 to 20 millimeters of mercury applied to the hilal periphery.\n\nFig. 21.1\n\nThere is evidence that the biochemical properties of the hiatal tissue can lower its tensile and yield strengths. Studies into the molecular make-up and microarchitecture of the hiatus have found differences between patients with and without hiatal hernias which may account for lower tensile strength in patients prone to hiatal hernia. Fei et al. found that 94% of patients with a hiatal hernia had one or more of the following microscopic changes in the hiatus: dilation of the intermyofibrillar spaces, swelling of the sarcotubular structures, focal degeneration of the myofibrils, and extended disruption\u2013degeneration of the muscle architecture. In another study, these investigators found 75% of the disruption\u2013degeneration to be severe. Others have found evidence of absent collagen fibers, while others an overall lower total, type I, and type III collagen in the phrenoesophageal ligament of patients with hiatal hernia. Another study found altered collagen metabolism related to COL3A1 expression in patients with hiatal hernia. Although these changes have not be proven to lead to lower tensile and yield strengths, they are certainly suggestive that some biochemical and ultrastructural changes may result in these alterations. Moreover, the left margin of the esophageal hiatus is thinner. So it stands to reason that the amount of force required to produce the same amount of strain would be less, because of smaller surface area exposed to the stress. Thereby, as the surface area decreases, stress will increase for the same amount of force. Supporting the concept of altered pressure\u2013force\u2013surface relationship in hiatal hernia, Lottrup et al. found that the hiatus in patients with hiatal hernia had lower distensibility pressures (i.e., lower yield strength) than patients without hiatal hernia.\n\nMost cases of hiatal hernia are acquired rather than congenital, although familial clusterings have been reported. This suggests that etiologies related to transdiaphragmatic pressures and hiatal/phrenoesophageal ligament tensile strength are temporally continuous phenomena. Risk factors associated with paraesophageal hernia, such as such as age, female sex, obesity, and spinal deformities (e.g., kyphosis, scoliosis, and lordosis), are generally associated with either an increase in transdiaphragmatic pressure or a reduction in tensile strength.\n\n### Classification\n\nType I hiatal hernia is also known as the \u201csliding\u201d hiatal hernia ( Fig. 21.2 ). Types II, III, and IV hiatal hernias are the paraesophageal hernias, where the stomach is juxtaposed to the esophagus. Type II or \u201crolling\u201d hiatal hernias occur when the gastric fundus herniates anterior to the esophagus, with a normally positioned intraabdominal gastroesophageal junction. Type II is also referred to as a \u201ctrue\u201d paraesophageal hernia. Congenital defects in the esophageal hiatus can lead to this type of paraesophageal hernias. Type III hiatal hernias are a combination of types I and II, in which both the gastroesophageal junction and a portion of the stomach\u2014usually the gastric fundus\u2014herniate into the mediastinum. Type IV hiatal hernias contain stomach and other abdominal organs such as small bowel, colon, pancreas, or spleen in the posterior mediastinum. Giant paraesophageal hernia refers to large hiatal hernias where at least 50% of the stomach is located in the mediastinum or the hernia measures at least 6 cm on endoscopy.\n\nFive diagrams of the stomach anatomy of normal and four types of hiatal hernias. The diagrams feature the stomach in five configurations. Diagram A displays normal stomach anatomy in a side view, with a clear outline. Diagrams B to E display variations associated with hiatal hernias. That is, B type 1 depicts a sliding hernia with minimal displacement, C type 2 represents a paraesophageal hernia with significant displacement, D type 3 indicates a combination of sliding and paraesophageal features, and E type 4 presents a large paraesophageal hernia with complex displacement.\n\nFig. 21.2\n\nIn addition, paraesophageal hernias can be classified by the type of gastric rotation which can occur. Organo-axial rotation occurs when the stomach rotates on the long axis of the organ, that is, from the fundus to the antrum. Mesentero-axial rotation occurs when the stomach rotates on the short axis of the organ, that is, from the lesser curvature to the greater curvature. The mesentero-axial rotation is sometimes referred to as the \u201cupside-down stomach.\u201d\n\n### Prevalence\n\nThe majority of patients with paraesophageal hernias are asymptomatic. Because of this, the actual prevalence of paraesophageal hernias is not known. The most common hiatal hernia is type I, accounting for up to 95% of all hiatal hernias, depending on how they are discovered. Paraesophageal hernias may account for up to 14% of all hiatal hernias, and the majority of paraesophageal hernias are classified as type III. The presence of a hiatal hernia has also been identified in nearly 40% of obese patients. As body mass index increases, so does the risk of developing a hiatal hernia.\n\n## Presentation\n\nThe majority of patients with paraesophageal hernias are asymptomatic, but often the symptoms are minor and overlooked ( Table 21.1 ). Of the patients who are symptomatic, the typical symptoms of gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) are the most common, including heartburn, regurgitation, and water brash. Patients may also present with obstructive symptoms such as dysphagia, which may be caused by compression of the herniated viscera leading to external compression on the esophagus. Furthermore, food stasis within the herniated stomach can reportedly lead to dysphagia. Some patients can present with anemia or upper gastric hemorrhage secondary to ulcer formation within the hernia. These ulcers, called Cameron ulcers, are typically associated with chronic iron-deficiency anemia, with overt hemodynamically significant bleeding less common. Other patients may present with respiratory complaints, such as dyspnea, asthma, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, and aspiration pneumonia. Other symptoms associated with paraesophageal hernia include lower chest pain or discomfort, bloating, gassiness, and early satiety. Because many of these symptoms are vague or can be attributed to other causes, their relationship to paraesophageal hernia is commonly missed. Therefore, it is not unusual for patients to be suffering from these symptoms for many years.\n\nTable 21.1\n\nPreoperative Symptoms and Findings of Paraoesophageal Hernias\n\nFrom Pierre AF, Luketich JD, Fernando HC, et al. Results of laparoscopic repair of giant paraesophageal hernias: 200 consecutive patients. *Ann Thorac Surg* . 2002;74:1909\u20131916.\n\n| Typical heartburn | 47% |\n| --- | --- |\n| Dysphagia | 35% |\n| Epigastric pain | 26% |\n| Vomiting | 23% |\n| Anemia | 21% |\n| Barrett epithelium | 13% |\n| Aspiration | 7% |\n\nCaveat: many paraesophageal hernias are asymptomatic.\n\n### Incarceration and Strangulation\n\nOverall, the risk of incarceration and strangulation in patients with paraesophageal hernia is small, although the exact risk is unknown. It is even more rare that this will be the first symptom manifested due to a paraesophageal hernia. Many patients with gastric incarceration secondary to paraesophageal hernias present with epigastric pain and anterior chest pain. Gastric incarceration can lead to obstruction, ischemia and strangulation, anemia, perforation, and even death. A gastric volvulus can occur when the stomach turns on its long axis (organo-axial), when it turns on its short axis (mesentero-axial), or there is a combination of the two. Organo-axial is the most common, seen in 60% of volvulus cases, and is typically associated with a hiatal hernia. Mesentero-axial is about 30%, and the rest is a combination of both which is very rare. Mesentero-axial volvulus can also occur without associated hiatal hernia. The classic symptoms for a gastric volvulus include chest pain, retching with the inability to vomit, and inability to pass a nasogastric tube. These findings make up Borchardt\u2019s triad. These symptoms, however, are not always present. Acute gastric volvulus carries a mortality rate of 30%\u201350% and is a surgical emergency if ischemia or perforation is suspected. The presentation of gastric incarceration or strangulation, however, is often misdiagnosed initially.\n\n### Compression of the Esophagus or Stomach\n\nParaesophageal hernias can cause symptoms as a result of mechanical forces from the displaced stomach. When gastric volvulus occurs, there is compression of the stomach and gastroesophageal junction, leading to symptoms such as chest pain or epigastric pain, and retching without emesis. As the stomach distends, the esophagus can be compressed and this can result in dysphagia or chest pain. Many patients with heartburn report that their acid reflux symptoms stop at the same time they begin to complain of symptoms attributed to mechanical obstruction or compression such as retching or chest pain. Compression and herniation of the stomach can cause compression of the stomach against other organs and structures.\n\n### Anemia\n\nAn important but less obvious symptom of paraesophageal hernia is that of chronic anemia secondary to blood loss. Anemia due to chronic blood loss will present with laboratory results demonstrating iron-deficiency anemia and is seen in about one-third of patients with paraesophageal hernias. Bleeding can be caused by ischemia or by ulcers within the herniated stomach. As mentioned above, Cameron lesions are single or multiple gastric erosions or ulcerations that can be seen at the diaphragmatic hiatus and can be the source of bleeding in patients with hiatal hernias. The most common location of these ulcers are on the lesser curve of the stomach, at the diaphragmatic hiatus. In those patients with hiatal hernias, Cameron lesions are visualized in up to 4.7%. Haurani et al. reported that patients with paraesophageal hernia and anemia were greater than seven times more likely to have evidence of linear ulcerations or erosions in gastric mucosa than patients who had paraesophageal hernias without evidence of bleeding. They also demonstrated that anemia secondary to these lesions resolved in the majority of patients undergoing surgical repair of their paraesophageal hernias.\n\n### Respiratory Symptoms\n\nPatients with paraesophageal hernias can also develop respiratory symptoms, such as dyspnea and cough. These patients report a progression of their symptoms throughout the day. Gastroesophageal reflux is an infrequent complication of type II hiatal hernia and may present in the form of respiratory complaints. Evaluation for paraesophageal hernia should be considered in patients with a history of reflux, who present with unexplained dyspnea or new-onset bronchospasm. GERD secondary to hiatal hernia has been specifically linked to idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis, and GERD in this patient population is an indication for hernia repair. There have been multiple reports that pulmonary symptoms attributed to paraesophageal hernias improve after operative repair. This is evident in the lung transplant patient population where both GERD and hiatal hernia often necessitate repair prior to lung transplant and are viewed as an urgent surgical condition if identified in the post-transplant patient with altered lung function. The size of hiatal hernia, specifically those who have greater than 50% of their stomach herniated, inversely correlates with total lung capacity and vital capacity, and improvements in lung volumes have been reported after surgical repair. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Nearly all patients with large hiatal hernias will have some degree of clinically relevant compression of the inferior vena cava and the left atrium which causes a tamponade effect and cardiogenic dyspnea. This should completely resolve after successful surgical repair.\n\n## Diagnostic Approach\n\nEvaluation for paraesophageal hernias begins with a history and physical examination. Physical exam can appear benign in the majority of cases. Sometimes, however, chest examination can reveal decreased breath sounds on the affected side, or the presence of bowel sounds within the chest. Many patients undergo noncardiac chest pain evaluation that eventually leads to upper gastrointestinal evaluation, and the diagnosis of a paraesophageal hernia. Not uncommonly, radiographic or endoscopic evaluations for other reasons reveal paraesophageal hernias in those patients with minimal or no symptoms at all.\n\n### Radiographic Studies\n\nChest radiographs are obtained many times as part of the workup of cardiac-related chest pain or other noncardiac chest pain symptoms. An upright radiograph of the chest may be diagnostic, revealing a retrocardiac air\u2013fluid level within the paraesophageal hernia. Lateral radiographs usually demonstrate retrocardiac opacities or air\u2013fluid levels ( Fig. 21.3 ). A radiograph demonstrating coiling of a nasogastric tube in the thorax can be used to help demonstrate the presence of an intrathoracic stomach. Computed tomography (CT) scans can demonstrate anatomical details in a patient with a hiatal hernia, such as the presence of a type IV hernia. CT can potentially delineate the level of the gastroesophageal junction. This level of detail could be important in the preoperative setting when considering the possible need for Collis gastroplasty. CT scan is useful for differentiating between other types of hernias of the diaphragm such as Bochdalek, Morgagni, or traumatic hernias.\n\nTwo chest radiographs of frontal and lateral views of the thoracic region. Panel A displays an anteroposterior projection and emphasizes the ribcage, lungs, heart, and upper abdomen. Panel B is a lateral view that depicts lung depth and spine. Both appear with bones as opaque and air more translucent. Panel A is marked Ratio 22.6. Panel B is marked Ratio 22.4 at the upper left corner of each respective panel.\n\nFig. 21.3\n\n### Contrast Esophagography\n\nBarium or water-soluble contrast esophagography can be useful for the diagnosis of paraesophageal hernias and often gives the most accurate information regarding the hernia\u2019s anatomy and location. An esophagogram can help differentiate between type II and type III hiatal hernias ( Fig. 21.4 ). The key characteristic of a paraesophageal hernia on contrast esophagography is that there is fundus residing above the level of the gastroesophageal junction within the mediastinum, often accompanied by at least some tortuosity of the distal esophagus. An esophagram can also help provide functional information regarding the presence of presbyesophagus, diverticulum, esophageal foreshortening, esophageal motility, esophageal spasms and tertiary contractions, and specifics around volume of reflux and anatomical level of reflux, i.e., to mid-chest or to the clavicles. Diagnostic accuracy of hiatal hernias can be improved using the right anterior oblique esophagram technique in patients undergoing bariatric surgery.\n\nTwo radiographs of two different anatomical views of esophageal outgrowths labeled A and B. The radiographs are labeled A and B. Photo A, on the left, captures an anteroposterior view, which displays a barium-filled stomach distended by a large gastric diverticulum. Photo B, on the right, depicts a lateral view of the same barium-enhanced stomach and diverticulum, which offers a profile perspective. Both photos are presented with typical radiographic contrast.\n\nFig. 21.4\n\n### Upper Endoscopy\n\nEsophagogastroduodenoscopy (EGD) allows for evaluation of the gastroesophageal junction location and the size of the hernia. EGD can be used to assess the presence of esophageal or gastric pathology, such as ulceration and mucosal ischemia. Endoscopy can help delineate the size of the hernia defect both in the long axis (i.e., from the gastroesophageal junction to the hiatal impression) and the trans-crural axis ( Fig. 21.5A and B ). This is best accomplished by acquiring a retroflexed view during the EGD which allows for better visualization of the hernia and location of the gastroesophageal junction. For example, noticing a second orifice next to the gastroesophageal junction during retroflexion can help diagnose a type II hiatal hernia. Retroflexion will reveal the gastroesophageal junction and portion of stomach above the diaphragm impression in the setting of a type III hiatal hernia. As with contrast studies, a key feature of diagnosing a paraesophageal hernia is visualizing fundus tissue cephalad to the gastroesophageal junction. The gastroesophageal flap valve within the hernia can be separately assessed according to the Hill grade classification ( Fig. 21.5B ). Upper endoscopy also helps to screen for Barrett esophagus and malignancy, and to diagnose Cameron ulcers, which can alter management for the hiatal hernia.\n\nFour endoscopic photos of Hill classification of the gastroesophageal junction flap-valve grades one to four. The photos are divided into four quadrants, each of which contains a high-resolution endoscopic view of the esophagus. Hill Grade One at the top left depicts a slight abnormality indicated by an arrow, while Hill Grade Two at the top right reveals moderate changes. Hill Grade Three at the bottom left displays more notable irregularity, and Hill Grade Four, at the bottom right, includes extensive mucosal alterations. The photos emphasize differences in tissue texture, and overall morphology, with a consistent endoscope focus and lighting across views.\n\nFig. 21.5\n\n### Esophageal Manometry and pH Monitoring\n\nEsophageal manometry and pH monitoring are not routinely used when evaluating patients with paraesophageal hernias. These tests may be difficult to perform, as intubation of the lower esophageal sphincter may be difficult to achieve due to anatomic distortion. Manometry may be used to plan fundoplication as an adjunct procedure in these patients but may be technically challenging as the anatomy is distorted and peristalsis may not be accurately depicted during the study. Instead, many surgeons rely on the functional information provided by the esophagram. However, in patients with dysphagia for whom a mechanical cause is not present, esophageal manometry is useful for identifying weak esophageal peristalsis, which may alter the choice of fundoplication or use of a magnetic sphincter augmentation device. Also, in our practice, we have noted a handful of patients with both a paraesophageal hernia and achalasia necessitating hiatal hernia repair and a Heller myotomy. Being caught unawares is such a situation that can lead to the unfortunate performance of a fundoplication worsening the dysphagia in these patients. Esophageal manometry would prevent a wrong operation being done. In patients with suspected reflux, pH monitoring may be used prior to surgical intervention if it will alter the surgical plan. pH monitoring is not necessary if Los Angeles (LA) grade B, C, or D esophagitis is reported or Barrett esophagus is found on endoscopy.\n\n## Indications for Repair\n\nThe decision-making in the management of patients with paraesophageal hernias can be challenging, especially as many patients are older and have associated comorbidities. In the past, operative repair was implemented for all paraesophageal hernias once diagnosed. Symptomatic and asymptomatic patients underwent surgical repair due to fear that incarceration and strangulation would lead to life-threatening complications. In the 1960s, Skinner and Belsey followed 21 patients without surgery, and 6 of these patients (29%) died of causes related to the paraesophageal hernia. This led to the preference of elective surgery, with the lower mortality rate of 1% compared with emergency surgery. In the 1970s, Hill reported up to 30% incidence of incarceration in patients with paraesophageal hernia. There are also reports that support paraesophageal hernia repair in good-risk surgical patients. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> There are also reports that laparoscopic repair of large hiatal hernias can be effective and durable.\n\nA detailed assessment of symptoms and a thorough discussion regarding risks versus benefits should drive the decision for operative repair. The probability of developing symptoms requiring emergency surgery has been estimated from analyses of several studies. The pooled annual probability of developing symptoms was estimated to range between 0.69% and 1.93%. The lifetime risk of developing acute symptoms decreases exponentially as the patient\u2019s age increases. An analysis of outcomes in asymptomatic or minimally symptomatic elderly patients with paraesophageal hernias concluded that watchful waiting would be more beneficial than elective paraesophageal hernia repair in over 80% of patients. However, more modern surgical technique may shift this data to favor surgery.\n\nAn analysis of 1005 patients with paraesophageal hernia examined the morbidity and mortality in octogenarians after nonelective repair. A six- to seven-fold increase in mortality was associated with nonelective repair compared with elective repair. This same analysis revealed that nonelective repairs were associated with a 50% longer length of stay versus elective repair and were found to be the predictor of inpatient mortality in patients over the age of 80 years. It is important to distinguish between asymptomatic patients and those patients with symptoms attributed to their paraesophageal hernia. Patients with symptoms of acute incarceration or strangulation should undergo prompt surgical repair. Patients with obstructive symptoms, bleeding, or respiratory symptoms attributed to their paraesophageal hernia should also undergo surgical repair. Surgical management of the elderly patient with a paraesophageal hernia should be individualized. A study of 354 patients who underwent paraesophageal hernia repair revealed that mortality was highest in patients over the age of 75 years. This study also revealed that morbidity was higher in patients with an American Society of Anesthesiologists class 3 or 4, and in patients with a type IV hiatal hernia.\n\nAnother topic of discussion in paraesophageal hernia repair is the need for an antireflux procedure. Most patients develop symptoms of GERD after paraesophageal hernia repair, and unless there is a contraindication, these patients would benefit from a fundoplication procedure in addition to their hiatal hernia repair. Adding a fundoplication to the paraesophageal hernia repair can help prevent GERD symptoms in these patients, which can result from the extensive dissection required during the procedure. In general, a fundoplication should be a routine consideration in paraesophageal hernia repair, whether a complete Nissen or partial Toupet or Dor, unless specific circumstances as judged by the surgeon determine that the additional time and effort to perform such a maneuver places the patient at unacceptable risk.\n\nIn summary, surgical management of paraesophageal hernias should be offered to symptomatic patients, but should be individualized, especially in the elderly patient with high surgical risk.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Watson T.J., Ziegler K.M.: The pathogenesis of hiatal hernia . Foregut 2022; 2 (1): pp. 36-43.\n\nView In Article\n\n2.: Gordon C., Kang J.Y., Neild P.J., Maxwell J.D.: The role of the hiatus hernia in gastro-oesophageal reflux disease . Aliment Pharmacol Ther 2004; 20: pp. 719-732.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: Velanovich V., Saad A.R.: Toward a unified theory of occurrence and recurrence of hiatal hernia . Surgery 2020; 168: pp. 1170-1173.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Menon S., Trudgill N.: Risk factors in the aetiology of hiatus hernia: a meta-analysis . Eur J Gastroenterol Hepatol 2011; 23: pp. 133-138.\n\nView In Article\n\n5.: Fei L., Del Genio G., Rossetti G., et al.: Hiatal hernia recurrence: surgical complication or disease? electron microscope findings of the diaphragmatic pillars . J Gastrointest Surg 2009; 13: pp. 459-464.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n6.: Fei L., Rossetti G., Allaria A., et al.: Laparoscopic hiatal hernia repair. Is the mesh hiatoplasty justified? . Ann Ital Chir 2014; 85: pp. 38-44.\n\nView In Article\n\n7.: Filho J.J.D.O., Filho B.H., Reis F.P., et al.: Contribution towards the anatomy of the esophageal hiatus and its relationship with the presence of bundles of collagen fibers in its margins . Int J Morphol 2012; 30: pp. 858-865.\n\nView In Article\n\n8.: von Diemen V., Trindade E.N., Trindade M.R.M.: Hiatal hernia and gastroesophageal reflux: study of collagen in the phrenoesophageal ligament . Surg Endosc 2016; 30: pp. 5091-5098.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n9.: Asling B., Jirholt J., Hammond P., et al.: Collagen type III alpha I is a gastro-oesophageal reflux disease susceptibility gene and a male risk factor for hiatus hernia . Gut 2009; 58: pp. 1063-1069.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n10.: Kumar D., Zifan A., Ghahremani G., et al.: Morphology of the esophageal hiatus: is it different in 3 types of hiatus hernias? . J Neurogatroenterol Motil 2020; 26: pp. 51-60.\n\nView In Article\n\n11.: Lottrup C., McMahon B.P., Ejstrud P., et al.: Esophagogastric junction distensibility in hiatus hernia . Dis Esophagus 2016; 29: pp. 463-471.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n12.: Velanovich V.: Epidemiology and socioeconomics of gastroesophageal reflux disease and Barrett\u2019s esophagus . In Swantrom L., Dunst C. (eds): Antireflux Surgery . 2015. Springer , New York\n\nView In Article\n\n13.: Kleitsch W.P.: Embryology of congenital diaphragmatic hernia. I. Esophageal hiatus hernia . Arch Surg 1958; 76: pp. 868-873.\n\nView In Article\n\n14.: Stringham J.R., Phillips J.V., McMurry T.L., et al.: Prospective study of giant paraesophageal hernia repair with 1 year follow-up . J Thorac Cardiovasc Surg 2017; 154: pp. 743-751.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n15.: Hyun J.J., Bak Y.T.: Clinical significance of hiatal hernia . Gut Liver 2011; 5: pp. 267-277.\n\nView In Article\n\n16.: Postlethwait R.W., Sealy W.C.: Surgery of the Esophagus . 1979 . Appleton-Century-Crofts , New York\n\nView In Article\n\n17.: Che F., Nguyen B., Cohen A., Nguyen N.T.: Prevalence of hiatal hernia in the morbidly obese . Surg Obes Relat Dis 2013; 9: pp. 920-924.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n18.: Kissane N., Rattner D.: Paraesophageal and other complex diaphragmatic hernias . In Yeo C.J. (eds): Shakelford\u2019s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract ., 7th ed. 2013. Elsevier , Amsterdam\n\nView In Article\n\n19.: Saad A.R., Corey B.L.: Classification and evaluation of diaphragmatic hernias . In Grams J., Perry K.A., Tavakkoli A. (eds): The SAGES Manual of Foregut Surgery . 2019. Springer Nature , Cham, Switzerland\n\nView In Article\n\n20.: Chang C.C., Tseng C.L., Chang Y.C.: A surgical emergency due to an incarcerated paraesophageal hernia . Am J Emerg Med 2009; 27 (1): pp. 134.e1-134.e3.\n\nView In Article\n\n21.: Haurani C., Carlin A.M., Hammoud Z., et al.: Incidence and resolution of anemia with paraesophageal hernia repair . J Gastrointest Surg 2012; 16: pp. 1817-1820.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n22.: Channer L.T., Squires G.T., Price P.D.: Laparoscopic repair of gastric volvulus . J Soc Laparoendosc Surg 2000; 4 (3): pp. 225-230.\n\nView In Article\n\n23.: Ghosh R.K., Fatima K., Ravakhah K., Hassan C.: Gastric volvulus: an easily missed diagnosis of chest pain in the emergency room . BMJ Case Rep 2016; 2016:\n\nView In Article\n\n24.: Louren\u00e7o S., Pereira A.M., Guimar\u00e3es M., Nora M.: Gastric volvulus: a complication of hiatal hernia . Cureus 2020; 12 (10):\n\nView In Article\n\n25.: Gray D.M., Kushnir V., Kalra G., et al.: Cameron lesions in patients with hiatal hernias: prevalence, presentation, and treatment outcome . Dis Esophagus 2015; 28: pp. 448-452.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n26.: Greub G., Liaudet L., Wiesel P., et al.: Respiratory complications of gastroesophageal reflux associated with paraesophageal hiatal hernia . J Clin Gastroenterol 2003; 37: pp. 129-131.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n27.: Myers D., Jacobson X., Dale M., et al.: Impact of paraesophageal hernia repair on respiratory function: a syst