\n\n**Previous:** [[20. Surgical Management of Mid- and Distal Esophageal Diverticula - ClinicalKey|20. Surgical Management of Mid- and Distal Esophageal Diverticula]]\n**Next:** [[22. Laparoscopic Paraesophageal Hernia Repair:: Key Components of Repair - ClinicalKey|22. Laparoscopic Paraesophageal Hernia Repair:: Key Components of Repair]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "21. Paraesophageal Hernia:: Etiology, Presentation, and Indications for Repair - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Paraesophageal Hernia:: Etiology, Presentation, and Indications for Repair', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Paraesophageal Hernia: Etiology, Presentation, and Indications for Repair', 'Pathogenesis and Etiology', 'Diagnostic Approach', 'Classification', 'Prevalence', 'Incarceration and Strangulation', 'Paraesophageal Hernia: Etiology, Presentation, and Indications for Repair / Pathogenesis and Etiology', 'Paraesophageal Hernia: Etiology, Presentation, and Indications for Repair / Diagnostic Approach', 'Paraesophageal Hernia: Etiology, Presentation, and Indications for Repair / Classification'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '21', '225-232', 2, 30, FALSE, TRUE),
('Laparoscopic Paraesophageal Hernia Repair:: Key Components of Repair', 'shackelford-9th-ed-22-laparoscopic-paraesophageal-hernia-repair-key-components-of-repair', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Laparoscopic Paraesophageal Hernia Repair: : Key Components of Repair\n\nOlga Lebedevskiy; Christy M. Dunst\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 22, 233-238\n\n## Introduction\n\nParaesophageal hernia (PEH) represents a primary disease of the diaphragm in which structural defects of the diaphragmatic musculature and altered connective tissue metabolism lead to elongation of the phrenoesophageal ligament (PEL) and enlargement of the esophageal hiatus. This causes progressive anatomic disruption of the crural diaphragm and subsequent migration of abdominal contents into the posterior mediastinal space, most commonly the stomach. This pathophysiology contrasts with the more common and typically smaller axial-type hiatal hernias (HHs), which are often described with gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD). However, evidence demonstrates that PEH often evolves from type I HHs suggesting that the underlying etiologies can coexist in some patients.\n\nHHs are classified based on the relationship between the gastroesophageal junction (GEJ) and the esophageal hiatus and hernia contents (see Chapter 21 , Fig. 21.2 ). One of the defining features of a PEH is the formation of a prominent hernia sac which can be separated from the mediastinal pleura. As the hernia enlarges, it allows for progressive migration of intraabdominal contents, which can eventually lead to full gastric migration and volvulus.\n\nType V PEH has been used to describe the presence of a herniated fundoplication. Type V hernias can be more challenging to repair surgically than the other types due to disruption of the native anatomy and extensive scar tissue and fused hernia sac planes from prior hiatal surgery.\n\nPrinciples of repair include:\n\n  - 1.\n\tComplete reduction and excision of the hernia sac.\n  - 2.\n\tEsophageal mobilization to obtain at least 3 cm of intra-abdominal esophageal length.\n  - 3.\n\tRepair of the diaphragmatic hiatus.\n  - 4.\n\tAntireflux procedure.\n\n## Surgical Anatomy\n\nApertures, or hiatuses, exist in the diaphragm to allow for passage of structures between the thoracic and abdominal cavities such as lymphatics, blood vessels, and the esophagus. The three major hiatuses include the esophageal hiatus, the aortic hiatus, and the caval hiatus. The esophageal hiatus normally accommodates only the esophagus and is anchored by the PEL. During embryonic development, the right and left diaphragmatic crura originate from the central tendon, and as the two legs develop, they fall to either side of the esophagus, tethering the diaphragm to the vertebral column posteriorly while forming the esophageal hiatus. The right and left crura cross posteriorly behind the esophagus and across the aorta. This area is called the crural decussation and contains the median arcuate ligament typically located just cephalad to the celiac artery. Attention to the major vascular structures at the hiatus and within the mediastinum is a key component of a safe repair ( Fig. 22.1 ). In some instances, the decussation may be poorly formed or attenuated from a large PEH resulting in the esophagus residing almost directly adjacent to the aorta at the hiatus.\n\nA photo of heart structures with labeled parts of the pericardium, aorta, and esophagus represents a hernia. The photo presents the esophagus located towards the upper right, the pericardium above the aorta, and the right crus vertically situated beside the liver. The inferior vena cava is labeled on the lower left. The composition centers around the exposed internal cavity with adjacent organic textured tissues.\n\nFig. 22.1\n\nAs the PEL elongates in the development of a PEH, the hiatus often widens asymmetrically with the right crus remaining straight but the left crus stretching with a leftward curve, often forming a \u201cD\u201d-shaped hiatus. The shape of the hiatal defect must be considered during crural reapproximation to ensure symmetric closure and to avoid a persistent defect (\u201cdog ear\u201d) on the left side. The caval hiatus is posterior to the liver to the right side of the central tendon with the inferior vena cava (IVC) posterior to the caudate lobe. In normal anatomy, the distance between the caval hiatus and the esophageal hiatus is several centimeters but with PEH defects, these two hiatuses may be close together with sometimes less than 2 cm between the right crus and the IVC.\n\nWithin the mediastinum, there are multiple tissue planes, including retroperitoneum, mediastinal fascia, and pleura. In a PEH, the peritoneum and retroperitoneum form the anterior and posterior hernia sac ( Fig. 22.2 ). Understanding mediastinal anatomy is critical when performing dissection during PEH repair, as mass effect from herniated contents may alter normal anatomy. Furthermore, patients with severe spinal kyphosis associated with development of PEH may have significant anterior curvature of the mediastinal aorta that can be encountered during esophageal mobilization. When performing extended mediastinal dissection, the azygous vein and thoracic duct may be encountered to the right of the spine. It is therefore prudent to avoid dissection posterior to the level of the aorta. It is also important to note that the right inferior pulmonary vein enters the pericardium posteriorly and can be encountered if esophageal mobilization proceeds too far anteriorly. The vagal trunks run laterally along the thoracic esophagus, but because of the embryologic rotation of the stomach, the left and right trunks transition at the level of the GEJ into their respective anterior and posterior positions, which should be identified early and protected to avoid damage or transection.\n\nA diagram illustrates the anatomy of a paraesophageal hernia sac, as well as the stomach and adjacent ligaments. The diagram features a circular representation of a paraesophageal hernia sac with a central, oval stomach. The adjacent structures are labeled as the anterior sac and the posterior sac that flanks the stomach. The gastrosplenic ligament is represented on the right, while the gastrohepatic omentum is on the left. At the bottom, an illustrative circle represents the aorta.\n\nFig. 22.2\n\n## Surgical Technique\n\n### Preoperative Preparation\n\nPreoperative preparation for elective PEH repair ideally involves optimizing weight as much as possible and reasonable before surgery depending on the severity of disease as patients with normal body mass index have significantly lower long-term hernia recurrence rates. In patients who present with an acute gastric volvulus or incarceration, optimization prior to surgery is key. Intravenous fluid resuscitation should be immediately initiated, followed by nasogastric tube (NGT) decompression. Surgical repair should then be performed within a few days, depending on the clinical situation. Endoscopy should be considered to decompress the stomach if NGT placement is unsuccessful and to evaluate for signs of ischemia, bleeding, or perforation, which would dictate the urgency of operative therapy. If gastric decompression is unsuccessful, then emergent reduction and repair must be performed.\n\n### Positioning and Access\n\nSurgeon preference dictates positioning and trocar placement for laparoscopic and robotic PEH repair ( Fig. 22.3 ). Regardless, the patient positioning needs to ensure safe steep reverse Trendelenburg positioning to optimally visualize the hiatus and facilitate hernia reduction. Generally, footboards are placed to accommodate the positioning. All pressure points are padded to prevent patient injury and pre-draping positioning test will ensure security. The patient is prepped from mid-sternum to pubis, making sure that the xiphoid is draped into the operative field.\n\nA diagram of surgical positions and instrument locations from three angles, such as the surgeon between the legs, the patient''s right, and the left. The diagram depicts a surgeon''s hand position during laparoscopic surgery on a patient. The first panel labeled Surgeon between legs, displays the surgeon''s hands and surgical tools from a view between the patient''s legs. The second panel, labeled Surgeon patient right, provides a view from the patient''s right side. The third panel is labeled Surgeon patient left displays the position from the left side of the patient. The diagrams use colored dots and symbols to indicate the placement of the surgeon''s left and right hands, camera ports, assist ports, and a liver retractor.\n\nFig. 22.3\n\nThe following will describe the author\u2019s preferred techniques with split leg position, arms out, and surgeon on the patient\u2019s left side. Insufflation is achieved with Veress needle technique in the left mid-abdomen along the mid-clavicular line near Palmer\u2019s point, followed by placement of a 10-mm trocar which will become the camera port. A 10-mm 30- to 45-degree laparoscope is then inserted. The remaining ports are placed under laparoscopic visualization. A 10-mm trocar is placed just below the left costal margin laterally for the surgeon\u2019s right hand. Internally, this port enters just superior to the colon. A 5-mm trocar is placed subxiphoid for the surgeon\u2019s left hand, and two additional 5-mm trocars are placed in the right mid-abdomen for the assistant and a reticulating liver retractor. The liver retractor is used to elevate the left lobe of the liver to expose the hiatus. It is secured using a table-mounted retractor holder.\n\nIn robot-assisted approach to repair, arms are tucked to minimize interaction with the robot arms. Following Veress needle insufflation, four 8-mm trocars are placed approximately 15 cm below the xiphoid in an up-facing semilunar shape. A liver retractor may be placed in the subxiphoid position to facilitate exposure, and consideration should be made to secure this to the bed in a position that does not hinder mobility of the robotic arms. A 10-mm or 12-mm assistant port may be used to facilitate passing of sutures or mesh during repair.\n\n### Hernia Sac Reduction\n\nReverse Trendelenburg positioning allows loose, non-incarcerated hernia contents to naturally reduce from the hernia sac ( Fig. 22.4 ). At this point, the hernia sac is pressurized from laparoscopic insufflation, so the first crucial step in the operation is to divide the PEL to allow for equalization of pressure on both sides of the hernia sac which greatly assists hernia reduction ( Fig. 22.5 ). The safest place to achieve this is on the left anterior hiatus anywhere from 12:00\u20133:00 to avoid the potentially herniated left gastric artery. The hernia sac is grasped from within the mediastinum and retracted caudally between two graspers. A small incision is made with ultrasonic dissection shears at the edge of the hernia sac to allow entry into the mediastinum. This creates an avascular incision plane at the hiatal rim and allows positive pressure from laparoscopic insufflation to enter the hernia sac, equalizing pressures between these cavities which will aid in dissection and hernia reduction ( Fig. 22.6 ). If bleeding occurs, it is likely due to disruption of the muscular plane of the crura, and dissection should be redirected away from the hiatal margin. Once the correct plane is identified and the hernia sac has been dissected off the crural margin anteriorly, blunt dissection is used to sweep the mediastinal tissues from the hernia sac. Minimal ultrasonic energy or cautery should be needed to maintain a hemostatic field if the surgeon remains in the correct plane between the peritoneum/retroperitoneum of the hernia sac and the mediastinal fascial planes. Direct traction on the stomach or other herniated viscera should be avoided during repair, as this may result in traumatic injury due to chronic inflammation and relative devascularization resulting in fragile visceral tissue. A \u201cno touch\u201d technique to hernia reduction is recommended, which focuses on reducing the hernia sac to facilitate reduction of the herniated contents ( Video 22.1 ).\n\nA photo indicates a hiatus, hernia sac, diaphragm, and stomach. The photo depicts a hiatal hernia, where the stomach protrudes through the esophageal hiatus in the diaphragm. The photo includes labels that identify the anatomical structures such as the hernia sac, stomach, right crus, diaphragm, and hiatus. It allows the viewer to understand the placement and extent of the hernia.\n\nFig. 22.4\n\nA diagram of the gap between the stomach and the hiatal brim that forms a bulged structure. #REF!\n\nFig. 22.5\n\nA photo of a surgical view of a retracted hernia sac and divided pelvic region in a procedure. The photo shows the surgical site with visible internal organs and tissues. Surgical clamps and a divider tool are prominently featured, one which holds a Retracted Hernia Sac and the other pointed at the divided phrenoesophageal ligament marked with text labels and arrows within the scene, which indicates key surgical actions. Stainless steel surgical instruments provide metallic contrast against the organic tissue.\n\nFig. 22.6\n\nConstant gentle caudal traction reduces the hernia sac and exposes the edge of the PEL. The PEL is often elongated and loose in a PEH, and traction on the hernia sac allows for visualization of the leading edge of the PEL along the left and right crus as a triangular point of tissue extension ( Fig. 22.7 ). We recommend dividing the PEL at least 1 cm off the crural edge to prevent from denuding the crura of its peritoneal fascia.\n\nA photo of the surgical view of the phrenoesophageal ligament edge and surrounded tissue with arrows directed for relevance. The photo depicts the close-up view of the peritoneal edge which is indicated by a labeled box and arrows. This structure is adjacent to the esophagus, which is also partially visible with labeled text. A surgical instrument is seen to the left. The photo displays the anatomy of a surgical procedure.\n\nFig. 22.7\n\nOnce the hernia sac is largely reduced anteriorly, along with associated herniated vascular (left gastric artery) and vagal contents, the pars flaccida can be safely divided to expose the right crus. The PEL is now divided similarly along the right crus down to the decussation with the left crus posteriorly. A retro-esophageal window is created through which an assistant can pass an atraumatic grasper, or Penrose drain if preferred, to facilitate anterior and caudal retraction of the esophagus during mediastinal dissection. The anterior and posterior vagus nerves should be identified early and preserved. With the hernia reduced, an extended mediastinal dissection is performed to fully mobilize the esophagus to obtain at least 3 cm of intraabdominal esophageal length ( Video 22.2 ).\n\n#### Assessment of Esophageal Length\n\nThe main principle of PEH repair is achieving adequate intraabdominal esophageal length as an indication that axial tension has been relieved and therefore the chance of hernia recurrence minimized. See Chapter 24 for a more thorough discussion on tension and esophageal length. For most patients, adequate intraabdominal length can be achieved with type II mediastinal dissection (dissection of at least 5 cm cephalad to the hiatus, generally extending to the inferior pulmonary vein). Continuing the dissection further to the level of the carina will divide the bronchial branches of the vagus nerve, which can allow for extra intraabdominal esophageal length. Division of the main vagal trunks can allow additional length, but this is generally avoided due to potential unwanted side effects. If necessary, one vagus nerve can be taken without significant consequence.\n\nTo measure the intraabdominal esophagus, the GEJ must be clearly identified. The distance between the angle of His and the left crus is the most accurate area to measure the intraabdominal esophagus ( Fig. 22.8 ). Measurements taken under tension or on the right side overestimate the true anatomic length. Consideration of the configuration of the hiatus after closure may eliminate underestimation of intraabdominal esophageal length. Intraoperative endoscopy can be useful in patients with severely distorted anatomy. Removal of the anterior hernia sac will more clearly expose the angle of His and the GEJ. To facilitate exposure of the anterior vagus and avoid injury, the right side of the sac is retracted caudally and toward the right lower quadrant, which helps to visualize the anterior vagus under tension. The left side of the sac is then retracted toward the left lower quadrant ( Fig. 22.9 ). Starting to the left of the anterior vagus nerve, the sac is divided up to the distal esophagus and then dissected off the cardia just past the greater curve and removed. Excessive rotation of the GEJ during sac excision should be avoided, as it can risk injury to the posterior vagus nerve and the left gastric artery, as prolonged herniation can lead to redundancy in these critical structures and distortion of their typical anatomy, particularly with dissection of the posterior sac.\n\nA photo of the surgical view of the Angle of His with a ruler and surgical tool. The photo of a surgical scene focused on the angle of His. The instrument is inserted at the right side, which touches the angle of the His to make the measurement. The angle of His is labeled with an arrow that originates from the bottom left corner. The backdrop features the tissue within the anatomical structures of the gastroesophageal junction.\n\nFig. 22.8\n\nA photo of the surgical view of the stomach and vagus nerve near the esophagus. The photo depicts the dissection of the anterior vagus nerve on the esophagus in the surgery. Surgical instruments are involved in the manipulation of tissues over the stomach. An arrow points to the anterior vagus nerve and a label identifies the stomach within the surgical field.\n\nFig. 22.9\n\n### Crural Closure\n\nPEH is associated with relatively large hiatal defects which makes hiatal closure the critical component in management of this disease. Once the hernia sac has been completely reduced, a posterior cruroplasty is performed using heavy braided, non-absorbable suture. The posterior approach is preferred due to the linear anatomy of the crura which facilitates primary reapproximation but, in some cases, an anterior or lateral approach may be necessary, particularly as a supplement to posterior repair. Various suture techniques have been described with no definitive method proving superior. Although the use of routine permanent mesh is contraindicated at the hiatus, the use of absorbable mesh to reinforce the hiatal closure remains controversial. See Chapter 23 for a full discussion of mesh at the hiatus. Despite these controversies, we have adopted an incorporated absorbable mesh technique with respectable results. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The technique utilizes a pledgeted horizontal mattress technique that can be performed with or without mesh ( Video 22.3 ). The closure is tailored to the size of the tension-free esophagus such that there are no visible gaps between the hiatus and the esophagus but also no compression. A closed grasper should slide into the closed hiatus easily. Most routine PEH hiatuses can be closed with a 5-cm height mesh with three sutures, but additional sutures can be used if necessary. In revision surgery, many closures require fewer than three sutures due to the postsurgical changes to the hiatal anatomy. Attention is paid to make sure the discordance between the length of the left and right crura are considered to avoid a \u201cdog ear\u201d on the left diaphragm. In some cases, anterior or lateral sutures may be required. This technique is successful in the vast majority of repairs, but occasionally the hiatus is too large or stenotic for primary closure without additional interventions. See Chapter 21 for discussion of tension on hiatal closures.\n\n### Fundoplication\n\nRoutine fundoplication is the final step in PEH repair. Proponents report GERD rates of 53% in patients who had a PEH repair without fundoplication compared with 17% in a randomized trial. Alternatives to standard fundoplication have also been reported to address postoperative reflux. As we discussed in the introduction, PEH may or may not be associated with GERD as a separate entity. Therefore, it seems reasonable that a cohort of patients undergoing PEH repair may not benefit from the routine addition of a fundoplication. This approach has been reported with generally less than satisfying results when clinical symptoms are taken into account. Although the concept of selective fundoplication is intriguing, at the time of writing, fundoplication remains a standard part of a routine PEH repair. The choice of fundoplication is beyond the scope of this chapter. Gastropexy of the stomach to the anterior abdominal wall has also been described in patients with or without fundoplication to fixate the stomach intraabdominally in attempts to reduce early recurrence of PEH. This technique was first described by Nissen, and he found that gastropexy alone has a relatively high failure rate. Selectively, placement of a gastrostomy tube or full-thickness gastric fixation may be used, though success rate is limited and overall this should be reserved for frail patients or those with other indications for gastrostomy tube.\n\n### Conclusion of the Operation\n\nAt the conclusion of the operation, we advocate for the routine use for upper endoscopy to evaluate the construction of the fundoplication and ensure that there is no undue constriction at the hiatus causing esophageal outflow obstruction, which would lead to postoperative dysphagia. We routinely place a transhiatal mediastinal drain that is removed prior to discharge unless bilateral pleurectomy was performed, as the fluid that drains into the chest will be easily absorbed by a healthy pleura. NGT decompression is used selectively. Patients are awakened from anesthesia gently to avoid coughing and aggressive Valsalva that can disrupt the fresh repair.\n\n## Postoperative Management\n\nPatients are admitted postoperatively following PEH repair for pain and nausea control. Antiemetic medications must be used liberally to prevent nausea and retching that can lead to early recurrence. If gas bloat is encountered, patients may be given simethicone liberally. Rarely an NGT is needed for gastric decompression, but this condition can have severe consequences if not recognized early. NGTs are typically removed after 1\u20132 days if nausea is well controlled and volumes are low. An upper gastrointestinal contrast study is performed on the first postoperative day to ensure an intact repair without excessive esophageal outflow impairment. Liquid diet is started and continued for 2 weeks followed by 2 weeks of soft diet. The diet is advanced slowly as tolerated to normal textures and volumes. Most patients are discharged within 1\u20132 days. Patients are counselled against heavy lifting (>15 pounds) or activities that significantly increase intraabdominal pressures for 2\u20133 months following surgery to allow the diaphragm to heal.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Abdelmoaty W., Dunst C., Fletcher R., et al.: The development and natural history of hiatal hernias: a study using sequential barium upper gastrointestinal series . Ann Surg 2022; 275 (3): pp. 534-538.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Parker B.C., Fletcher R., Dunst C., et al.: The impact of body mass index on recurrence rates following laparoscopic paraesophageal hernia repair . Foregut 2022; 3 (2):\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: Oelschlager B.K., Yamamoto K., Woltman T., et al.: Vagotomy during hiatal hernia repair: a benign esophageal lengthening procedure . J Gastrointest Surg 2008; 12 (7): pp. 1155-1162.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Diwan T.S., Ujiki M.B., Dunst C.M., Swanstr\u00f6m L.L.: Biomesh placement in laparoscopic repair of paraesophageal hernias . Surg Innov 2008; 15 (3): pp. 184-187.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: Abdelmoaty W.F., Dunst C.M., Filicori F., et al.: Combination of surgical technique and bioresorbable mesh reinforcement of the crural repair leads to low early hernia recurrence rates with laparoscopic paraesophageal hernia repair . J Gastrointest Surg 2020; 24 (7): pp. 1477-1481.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n6.: M\u00fcller-Stich B.P., Achtst\u00e4tter V., Diener M.K., et al.: Repair of paraesophageal hiatal hernias\u2014is a fundoplication needed? A randomized controlled pilot trial . J Am Coll Surg 2015; 221 (2): pp. 602-610.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n7.: Buckley F.P., Bell R.C.W., Freeman K., et al.: Favorable results from a prospective evaluation of 200 patients with large hiatal hernias undergoing LINX magnetic sphincter augmentation . Surg Endosc 2018; 32: pp. 1762-1768.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n8.: Clapp B., Hamdan M., Mandania R., et al.: Is fundoplication necessary after paraesophageal hernia repair? A meta-analysis and systematic review . Surg Endosc 2022; 36 (8): pp. 6300-6311.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\nPrevious ChapterGo to the previous chapter\n\nNext ChapterGo to the next chapter\n\n\n\n## Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract\n\nNinth Edition\n\nCopyright \u00a9 2026 by Elsevier Inc. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies.\n\n## Get rights and content\u00a0\n\n##\n\n281240\n\n  - Google Play - Go to our Google Play page\n  - Apple App Store - Go to our Apple App Store page\n  - Facebook - Go to our Facebook page\n  - LinkedIn - Go to our LinkedIn page\n  - X - Go to our X page\n\nElsevier (opens in a new 