%20.4.3.4H151c.3%200%20.5.2.5.5V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.5.6h-20.8c-.3%200-.517-.3-.5-.6V7zm47.7%2036.7c-.4%200-.6-.2-.8-.5l-7.3-12.7-7.4%2012.7c-.2.3-.4.5-.8.5h-5.8c-.3%200-.5-.3-.3-.7L166%2024.3%20156%207.1c-.2-.4%200-.7.3-.7h5.8c.4%200%20.6.1.8.5l6.5%2011.3h.1L176%206.9c.2-.4.5-.5.9-.5h5.7c.4%200%20.5.3.3.7l-10%2017.2L183.7%2043c.2.4%200%20.7-.3.7h-5.8zM192.015%2019c-.2%200-.338-.004-.3-.2V8.4h-3.3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n\n\nNeed help? Chat with AI Buddy!\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[21. Paraesophageal Hernia:: Etiology, Presentation, and Indications for Repair - ClinicalKey|21. Paraesophageal Hernia:: Etiology, Presentation, and Indications for Repair]]\n**Next:** [[23. Mesh at the Hiatus - ClinicalKey|23. Mesh at the Hiatus]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "22. Laparoscopic Paraesophageal Hernia Repair:: Key Components of Repair - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Laparoscopic Paraesophageal Hernia Repair:: Key Components of Repair', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Laparoscopic Paraesophageal Hernia Repair: Key Components of Repair', 'Surgical Anatomy', 'Surgical Technique', 'Postoperative Management', 'Preoperative Preparation', 'Positioning and Access', 'Laparoscopic Paraesophageal Hernia Repair: Key Components of Repair / Surgical Anatomy', 'Laparoscopic Paraesophageal Hernia Repair: Key Components of Repair / Surgical Technique', 'Laparoscopic Paraesophageal Hernia Repair: Key Components of Repair / Postoperative Management'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '22', '233-238', 2, 21, FALSE, TRUE),
('Mesh at the Hiatus', 'shackelford-9th-ed-23-mesh-at-the-hiatus', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Mesh at the Hiatus\n\nSumeet K. Mittal; Andres R. Latorre-Rodriguez; Ross M. Bremner\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 23, 239-248\n\n## Introduction\n\nHiatal hernia (HH) reduction and adequate crura repair are paramount to achieving satisfactory results after antireflux surgery. During the early laparoscopic era of the 1990s, high recurrence rates of HHs after primary repair were documented. Simultaneously, the routine use of synthetic non-absorbable mesh to repair inguinal and ventral hernias was gaining widespread acceptance among surgeons, given emerging reports of its safety and efficacy. These findings set the stage for some surgeons to advocate for the use of mesh at the hiatus.\n\nThereafter, several case series described the use of various types of synthetic mesh materials and configurations of mesh at the hiatus. These series were strengthened by significantly lower recurrence rates. However, these early reports were followed by isolated case reports describing complications related to mesh use, including catastrophic cases that required esophagogastric resections. These disastrous complications were thought to result from the synthetic and permanent nature of the mesh materials being used, so bioprosthetic materials were suggested as attractive alternatives to synthetic mesh; however, a systematic review including 16 clinical trials demonstrated that both types of mesh were associated with significant mesh-related complications, and the complication rates between synthetic mesh and biological mesh were similar (5.1% and 4.6%, respectively). Furthermore, other authors have reported that reoperation after the use of mesh is significantly more challenging than reoperation in patients without mesh, and those with mesh are at greater risk of needing an esophagogastric resection. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nPerhaps the benchmark for HH repair, with or without mesh, is the open transthoracic series by Maziak et al. They achieved a mean follow-up of 94 months in 90 of 94 patients who underwent surgical repair of a large paraesophageal hernia (PEH). They reported excellent results in 72 of 90 patients (80%), with anatomic recurrence in only 2 patients, both of whom underwent reoperation. Since the publication of these early laparoscopic reports, advancements in minimally invasive surgery (e.g., improved visualization, better instrumentation, and more significant experience) have helped surgeons achieve more extensive mediastinal dissection, better esophageal mobilization, complete excision of the hernia sac, and less crus damage. All of these are associated with improved perioperative outcomes with primary crural repair at the hiatus, even for larger HHs. The goal of this chapter is to briefly review the advantages and disadvantages of using mesh at the hiatus, summarizing the most recent available evidence.\n\n## Primary Crural Closure: Recurrence and Outcomes\n\nIt is important to recognize the differences in the recurrence rates of HHs after primary crural closure between two periods: (1) the early laparoscopic era when the first case series of HH repair were just beginning to be reported, and recurrence was determined by the reappearance of related symptoms as objective follow-up (e.g., barium esophagram or upper gastrointestinal endoscopy) was not a widespread practice; and (2) the modern laparoscopic era where there are more robust surgical technologies and equipment, and patient follow-up routinely involves objective assessment.\n\n### Early Laparoscopic Era\n\nThe laparoscopic approach for HH repair was initially questioned based on the theoretical possibility of higher recurrence rates compared with the classical transthoracic approach. Thus, in 2000, Hashemi et al. reported their experience with 54 patients who underwent surgery for large PEH repair at the University of Southern California. In the subset of patients who underwent laparoscopic repair of a large PEH ( *n* \\= 27), objective follow-up was available for 21 patients (78%). These authors found HH recurrence in 9 of 21 patients (43%), with 8 of 21 patients (38%) reporting recurrent symptoms. This report led to widespread uncertainty about the safety and efficacy of laparoscopy for PEH repair. However, this was an isolated report with an unusually high recurrence rate, especially symptomatic recurrences, as most other series reported not only a lower anatomic recurrence rate but also, more importantly, that the vast majority of these patients were clinically asymptomatic.\n\nLater, two interesting reviews aimed to objectively measure the incidence of HH recurrence. The first, published in August 2004 by Puri et al., synthesized data from 35 studies and reported a global recurrence rate of 11.9% (240/2016) for patients who underwent open PEH repair before 2001 with a follow-up between 12 and 180 months. The overall recurrence rate for patients undergoing laparoscopic PEH repair before 2001 was 8% (49/612), with a follow-up between 1 month and 56 months, whereas for studies published from 2001 to 2003, it was 11% (79/721), with a follow-up from 3 to 58 months. The second review published 4 months later by Targarona et al. described a high recurrence rate in eight HH case series published up to that point. The evaluated studies incorporated systematic radiographic follow-up for laparoscopic PEH repair, and objective follow-up was available for 277 of 460 patients. The mean overall reported recurrence rate was 27% (range, 7%\u201343%).\n\n### Modern Laparoscopic Era\n\nAlthough laparoscopic HH repair is currently the most favored approach, there is no consensus regarding the specific surgical technique. Some studies have revealed unexpectedly high recurrence rates, even over 50%. Andujar et al. reported the systematic radiographic follow-up of 166 patients who underwent laparoscopic repair of a large PEH. At a mean follow-up of 15 months, they found a recurrence rate of 25% (5% PEH and 20% sliding HH). Nine years later, Gibson et al. described the outcomes of their single-center experience of HH repair in 100 consecutive patients. They reported a recurrence in only 9 of 100 patients, 7 of whom had only a small (<2 cm) recurrent HH. The same group later reported medium-term follow-up, describing a total recurrence rate of 24% at a mean follow-up of 24 months (5% PEH and 19% small HH). They also reported excellent continued gastroesophageal reflux disease-related quality-of-life scores.\n\nNason et al. reported their long-term follow-up of 187 patients who underwent laparoscopic repair of a giant PEH from 1997 to 2003. Over a median follow-up of 77 months, they found a radiographic recurrence rate of 15%. Mittal et al. later reported 5-year follow-up findings in 73 patients who underwent surgical intervention for an intrathoracic stomach. They reported objective (radiographic) failure rates of 5%, 11%, and 17% at 1, 3, and 5 years after surgery, respectively. Moreover, the same authors reported follow-up data at 11 years, indicating a long-lasting reduction in clinical foregut symptoms and a high degree of patient satisfaction. Table 23.1 summarizes the findings of studies on open PEH repair with objective follow-up and studies reporting outcomes after laparoscopic PEH repair.\n\nTable 23.1\n\nOpen and Laparoscopic Hiatal Hernia Repair\n\n| Author, Year | Study Design | Surgical Approach | Main Findings |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Maziak et al., 1998 | Prospective cohort including patients with massive incarcerated PEH. | Open ( *n* \\= 94) | Mean follow-up of 94 months; 93% of patients had good or excellent outcomes, and only 2% had a symptomatic recurrence. |\n| Hashemi et al., 2000 | Retrospective cohort. Single-center experience, including patients with large type III HH. | Open ( *n* \\= 27) and laparoscopic ( *n* \\= 27) | Symptomatic outcomes: excellent/good in 76% laparoscopic; 88% in the open group. Recurrence was 42% after laparoscopy and 15% after open surgery. |\n| Mattar et al., 2002 | Retrospective cohort. Consecutive patients who underwent PEH repair. | Laparoscopic ( *n* \\= 136) | Mean follow-up of 40 months. Significant improvement of all symptoms. Three patients had a symptomatic recurrence. |\n| Targarona et al., 2004 | Literature review. The objective follow-up was reported in 9 studies. | Open ( *n* \\= 22) and laparoscopic ( *n* \\= 277) | The mean overall recurrence rate was 27% (range, 7%\u201343%) for the laparoscopic group and 8% for the open surgery group. |\n| Low and Unger, 2005 | Retrospective cohort. Single-surgeon experience, including patients who underwent PEH repair. | Open ( *n* \\= 72) | Mean follow-up of 29.8 months. 18% of patients had a recurrent HH. No patient required revision surgery. 73% of the recurrences were less than 2 cm sliding HH. |\n| Ferri et al., 2005 | Retrospective cohort. Single-center experience, including patients with PEH. | Open ( *n* \\= 25) and laparoscopic ( *n* \\= 35) | Objective follow-up was available for 78% of open and 91% of laparoscopic repairs, and the recurrence rates were 44% and 23%, respectively. |\n| Rathore et al., 2007 | Meta-analysis of 13 retrospective reviews, 965 patients. | Laparoscopic ( *n* \\= 965) | The overall recurrence rate was 99/965 (10.2%), but the objective recurrence rate was 77/301 (25.5%). No associated learning curve. Hiatoplasty and esophageal lengthening had a significant protective influence. |\n| White et al., 2008 | Retrospective cohort. Single-center experience, including patients with PEH. | Laparoscopic ( *n* \\= 52) | Significant improvement in symptoms at 10 years compared with preoperative symptoms. 10 recurrences (2 within the first postoperative year). |\n| Luketich et al., 2010 | Retrospective cohort. Single-center experience, including patients with giant PEH. | Laparoscopic ( *n* \\= 662) | Mesh and Collis gastroplasty use decreased over time with stable morbidity rates. QoL scores were excellent or good at 90%, and radiological recurrence was 16%. Symptomatic recurrence in none. The reoperation rate was 3%. |\n| Le Page et al., 2015 | Retrospective cohort. Single-center experience, including patients with giant HH. | Open ( *n* \\= 33) and laparoscopic ( *n* \\= 432) | Mean follow-up of 42 months. Mesh used in 6%. Overall recurrence: 35.6%; follow-up at over 10 years: 50%. Recurrence in 14.8%; revision surgery in 4.8% of cases. |\n| Mittal et al., 2011 | Retrospective cohort. Single-center experience, including patients with ITS. | Open ( *n* \\= 9) and laparoscopic ( *n* \\= 64) | Mesh used in 14%. Objective failure at 1, 3, and 5 years was 5%, 11%, and 17%, respectively. Long-lasting reduction in symptoms and high patient satisfaction were reported at 11-year follow-up. |\n\n*HH,* Hiatal hernia; *ITS,* intrathoracic stomach; *QoL,* quality of life; *PEH,* paraesophageal hernia.\n\n#### Laparoscopic Versus Robot-Assisted Hiatal Hernia Repair\n\nThe introduction and rapid adoption of robotic surgery platforms have led to an increase in the number of annual cases performed with this approach; the use of robot-assisted HH repair brings with it novel functions that may be beneficial for the surgeon, such as improving rotational motion, three-dimensional visualization, and ergonomics. However, despite its theoretical benefits, this surgical approach is complex, and the added value of this procedure has been questioned. In 2021, Ward et al. published a retrospective national registry analysis based on information obtained from the National Inpatient Sample (NIS) registry, including more than 30,000 surgical records between 2010 and 2015; the authors found that the laparoscopic approach generally had a lower rate of surgical complications (i.e., lower rate of esophageal perforation and respiratory failure) and similar or better outcomes (i.e., shorter length of stay, lower costs) compared with robotic HH repair. Conversely, Soliman et al. performed a retrospective analysis of 293 consecutive cases of HH repair (151 laparoscopic and 142 robotic), revealing that postoperative complication rates and hospital length of stay were lower with the robotic approach than with the laparoscopic approach; however, the results and rates of HH recurrence were comparable. Howell et al. also compared short-term outcomes between robotic and laparoscopic approaches in a cohort of 128 patients, concluding that perioperative complications, conversion rate to open surgery, 30-day readmission, reintervention, and mortality were similar between the two approaches. The vast difference between national databases and individual center reports is likely due to the experience of surgeons at these centers compared with the outcomes in general across differing levels of foregut expertise rather than an inherent advantage of one technique over the other. Regardless, longer follow-up is needed for mid- and long-term outcomes.\n\n## Mesh-Reinforced Crus Closure: Recurrence and Outcomes\n\n### Early Reports\n\nIn 1999, Carlson et al. published the first relevant case series using mesh for HH repair; in this study, 31 patients with hernia defects >8 cm underwent posterior cruroplasty ( *n* \\= 16) or cruroplasty with non-absorbable mesh reinforcement ( *n* \\= 15). Postoperatively, all patients were objectively followed every 6 months using barium esophagram. The authors reported three recurrences (19%) in the cruroplasty-only group and none in the mesh-reinforcement group; the follow-up ranged from 12 to 36 months. Later, an early review of the literature published in 2004 summarized the outcomes of 432 patients in 22 studies who underwent mesh-reinforced HH repair. Recurrence rates ranged from 0% to 24%, but most of the studies in this review reported zero recurrences. Different mesh configurations and materials were used in different series. In 2006, when the use of laparoscopic mesh reinforcement had gained more popularity among surgeons, Oelschlager et al. published the results of the first multicenter randomized clinical trial (RCT), including 108 subjects and comparing postoperative outcomes between patients who underwent cruroplasty alone and those who underwent cruroplasty with mesh reinforcement (Surgisis; Cook Medical, Bloomington, IN); the authors reported a recurrence in 12 of 50 (24%) and 4 of 45 (8.9%) subjects in each group, respectively, at their 6-month follow-up with objective radiological assessment. This study opened an exciting avenue for conducting clinical trials comparing the effectiveness and safety of these two interventions. However, the same group reported long-term follow-up at 5 years with an equal and disappointing recurrence rate of over 50% in both groups.\n\n### New Insights\n\nMultiple groups worldwide have attempted to pinpoint the exact recurrence of HH after primary laparoscopic repair using mesh; however, the available evidence suggests that HH recurrence with mesh is highly variable and uncertain as recurrence is multifactorial, depending on factors such as the surgeon\u2019s experience, the quality of the patient\u2019s connective tissue, the size of the hernia defect, the mesh material, the mechanical properties, and other patient factors. An interesting study performed radiological follow-up 1 year after laparoscopic PEH repair of 70 patients and reported a 27% recurrence rate of HHs larger than 2 cm after biological mesh reinforcement. Lee et al. reported an even higher recurrence rate of 40% at 5-year follow-up with routine use of AlloDerm (LifeCell Corporation, Branchburg, NJ) for all cruroplasty patients (not just PEH). Table 23.2 summarizes recurrence rates and other follow-up data from some studies reporting mesh-reinforced closure. It is striking that many studies and reviews have recently reported that mid- and long-term HH recurrence rates using mesh reinforcement tend to be higher than those using simple suture repair. In 2020, Watson et al. reported the results of imaging performed between 36 and 48 months after surgery for an RCT including 126 patients. The authors documented a recurrent hernia (of any size) in 39.3% after suture repair, 56.7% after absorbable mesh reinforcement, and 42.9% after non-absorbable mesh reinforcement; the findings of this study and other RCTs are discussed later in this chapter.\n\nTable 23.2\n\nMesh-Reinforced Hiatal Hernia Repair\n\n| Author, Year | Study Design | Intervention | Follow-up, Recurrence, and Other Outcomes |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Carlson et al., 1998 | Retrospective cohort. Patients with large PEH and ITS ( *n* \\= 44). | Posterior cruroplasty and onlay prolene mesh. | Mean follow-up of 52 months. No clinical recurrence was reported. 11 postoperative complications were documented. |\n| Lee et al., 2008 | Retrospective cohort. Consecutive patients with large HH ( *n* \\= 52). | Cruroplasty with AlloDerm mesh reinforcement. | Early recurrence was 4%, and a 5-year follow-up was 47%. Postoperative complications were reported in five patients. |\n| Alicuben et al., 2014 | Retrospective cohort. Patients with type I\u2013IV HH ( *n* \\= 114). | Cruroplasty with GOREBIO-A mesh reinforcement. Crural relaxing incision in 4%, and Collis in 39%. | Median objective follow-up of 12 months and objective recurrence in 1/99 (0.9%). No mesh-related complications were reported. |\n| Lidor et al., 2015 | Prospective cohort. Patients with type III HH ( *n* \\= 111). | Cruroplasty with biological mesh (Veritas collagen matrix; Synovis). | Mean follow-up of 43.5 months with clinical recurrence in 27%. Four patients required reoperation (one of whom had symptomatic recurrence). Significant relief of symptoms and improved QoL. |\n| Ward et al., 2015 | Prospective cohort. Patients with type I\u2013IV HH ( *n* \\= 54). | Cruroplasty with Flex HD mesh ( *n* \\= 37) and with AlloDerm ( *n* \\= 17). | Median clinical follow-up of 33 months. Recurrence in 15% (18% with AlloDerm; 14% with Flex HD mesh). Improved QoL in both groups. |\n| Chang and Thackeray, 2016 | Retrospective cohort. Consecutive patients with HH ( *n* \\= 221). | Cruroplasty with biological mesh (Veritas collagen matrix; Synovis). | Mean follow-up of 14.5 months. Recurrence was reported in eight patients, and reoperation was required in one. One perioperative death. Significant decline in QoL. |\n| Priego et al., 2016 | Retrospective cohort. Consecutive patients with large PEH ( *n* \\= 93). | Cruroplasty with Crurasoft mesh reinforcement. | Median objective follow-up of 25.8 months. Recurrence in 8/93 (8.6%). Reintervention rate was 5.4%. Late postoperative complications were 20.4%. |\n| Watkins et al., 2018 | Retrospective cohort. Consecutive patients with type II\u2013IV HH ( *n* \\= 30). | Cruroplasty with AlloDerm mesh reinforcement. | Mean objective radiological follow-up of 8 months. Objective recurrence in 2/11 (18.2%). No instances of postoperative complications or reoperation. |\n| Rosen et al., 2019 | Multicenter prospective trial. Patients with PEH ( *n* \\= 41). | Cruroplasty with Miromesh mesh reinforcement. | Median objective follow-up of 24 months. Objective recurrence in 3/27 (11.1%). QoL significantly improved. Eighteen postoperative adverse events were registered. |\n| Khaled et al., 2019 | Retrospective cohort. Consecutive patients with large PEH ( *n* \\= 27). | Cruroplasty with BioCer TiO\u2082Mesh mesh reinforcement. | Mean objective follow-up of 18 months. Recurrence in 2/27 (7.4%). No mesh-related complications were documented. |\n| Armijo et al., 2021 | Retrospective cohort. Patients with HH ( *n* \\= 292). | Cruroplasty with AlloDerm ( *n* \\= 162), GORE BIO-A ( *n* \\= 83) and Strattice ( *n* \\= 47). | Median objective follow-up of 48 months. Recurrence in 114/272 (41.9%). Six patients needed postoperative balloon dilation for new-onset dysphagia. |\n| Aiolfi et al., 2022 | Retrospective cohort. Patients with PEH ( *n* \\= 68). | Cruroplasty with Phasix-ST mesh reinforcement. | Median objective follow-up of 27 months. Recurrence in 6/68 (8.8%). Two patients needed postoperative balloon dilation for new-onset dysphagia. |\n\n*HH,* Hiatal hernia; *ITS,* intrathoracic stomach; *QoL,* quality of life; *PEH,* paraesophageal hernia.\n\n## Mesh Configurations and Materials\n\nEarly on, synthetic meshes (e.g., polypropylene and polytetrafluoroethylene) were used for hiatus reinforcement as a direct extension of use in ventral and inguinal hernias. There are currently over 70 mesh brands on the market, each with unique properties, absorbability, tensile strength, and pore size; the possible configurations are simply too numerous to list individually. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Table 23.3 summarizes some characteristics of the meshes most frequently used for HH repair. The mesh can be placed either as a bridge to cover a gap in the crural defect (either anterior or posterior) or more commonly as an overlay to cover the primary crural closure. Some surgeons have advocated circumferential placement of the mesh with a keyhole-shaped opening to accommodate the esophagus. Others have advised the creation of relaxing incisions in the diaphragm to allow for primary crural closure and the use of synthetic non-absorbable mesh to bridge the created defect. Fig. 23.1 shows the various mesh placement configurations described above.\n\nTable 23.3\n\nCommonly Used Meshes for Hiatal Hernia Repair\n\nAdapted from Bilsel et al. and Wang et al.\n\n| Reference | Material | Absorption | Other Characteristics |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Surgipro mesh | PP | Non-absorbable | Classical mesh with macroporous, multifilaments, and high tensile strength. |\n| TiMesh | PP/Titanium | Non-absorbable | Lower inflammatory response compared to ePTFE meshes. |\n| Crurasoft mesh | PTFE/ePTFE | Non-absorbable | Lighter-weight mesh, the overlap of ePTFE should reduce adhesions at the edge. |\n| Composix | PP/ePTFE | Non-absorbable | Lightweight mesh with monofilament. Reports minimal adhesion and optimal tissue ingrowth. |\n| VYPRO I | PP/Polyglactin 910 | Partial-absorbable | First lightweight mesh with large pores. |\n| Surgisis mesh | Porcine intestinal submucosa | Absorbable | Good safety profile, but susceptible material to collagenases, requires hydration. |\n| AlloDerm | Human acellular dermis | Absorbable | Good safety profile; it must be refrigerated/rehydrated and placed under tension; stretches out over time due to elastin content. |\n| Gentrix UBM | Porcine-derived extracellular matrix | Absorbable | Novel material with promising remodeling response which may signal strength and durability. Requires long-term follow-up data. |\n| Strattice | Xenogenic acellular dermis (porcine/bovine) | Absorbable | Provides an average tensile strength and is available in large sizes. Limited long-term follow-up. |\n| GORE BIO-A | ePTFE | Absorbable | Adequate safety profile. Widespread used. It is a heavyweight mesh with a discrete minimum tensile strength of 16 N/cm. |\n| Phasix-ST | P4HB | Absorbable | Recent release; has rapid tissue incorporation. Available in large sizes, but there is a lack of information on the long-term follow-up for HH repair. |\n\n*e-PTFE,* Expanded polytetrafluoroethylene; *HH,* hiatal hernia; *PP,* polypropylene; *PTFE,* polytetrafluoroethylene; *P4HB,* poly-4-hydroxybutyrate.\n\nA diagram of four stages of a surgical or medical procedure involved in hernia. The diagram depicts the surgical repair of anal stenosis. The diagram illustrates four stages, which progress from left to right. Each stage represents the anus with skin flaps brought together, secured potentially by sutures or surgical staples, to widen the anal opening. The progression illustrates reduced stenosis toward a more normal state.\n\nFig. 23.1\n\nAlthough each mesh type provides unique benefits and drawbacks, biological mesh has become the preferred material by many for reinforcement due to the safety concerns described earlier. Biological meshes are also reported to cause a lower inflammatory response and less fibrosis. Many types of available biological mesh have been reported and recommended for use, including porcine submucosa (Surgisis; Cook Medical), bovine pericardium (Varitas; Baxter International, Deerfield, IL), human acellular dermis (AlloDerm; LifeCell Corporation), and porcine dermal collagen (Permacol; Medtronic, Dublin, Ireland). Over the last decade, synthetic bioabsorbable mesh has gained acceptance; the most widely used of these is Gore-BioA (Gore Medical, Flagstaff, AZ), which comes as a pre-fashioned rectangular mesh with a U-shaped defect anteriorly to accommodate the esophagus and can be tailored for posterior hiatal reinforcement. Another recent addition to the arsenal of available meshes is Phasix-ST (BD, formerly C.R. Bard, Inc./Davol, Inc., Warwick, RI), which is made with poly-4-hydroxybutyrate. It has been characterized as having a low\u2013moderate inflammatory response profile and resorbs within 12\u201318 months. In the present era, the routine use of non-absorbable mesh has mostly been abandoned, especially in the United States, as has circumferential mesh placement.\n\n## How to Secure the Mesh\n\nMesh can be secured to the hiatus in multiple ways and using different techniques; however, the best practices to prevent recurrences or avoid complications are unknown. The most widely used technique uses non-absorbable sutures and a three- to five-point suture fixation. Each surgeon determines the precise location according to the anatomical configuration and the type of mesh selected. By contrast, despite its ease of application and the reduction in surgical times, the safety of tacks (i.e., titanium or absorbable tacks) has been widely questioned <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> ; some authors and surgical societies warn surgeons on the use of tacks and even recommend avoiding them for mesh fixation in the diaphragm above the costal arch due to several reports documenting severe cardiac injuries and cardiac tamponade.\n\nSince the late 2000s, the use of bioglue has gained popularity as a primary or secondary procedure (i.e., in addition to the use of sutures or tacks) to secure the mesh to the diaphragm. Products based on purified bovine serum albumin and glutaraldehyde, such as BioGlue (CryoLife Inc, Kennesaw, GA,) or fibrin sealants like Tissecol/Tisseel (Baxter, Austria), are currently available on the market. In 2009, Zehetner et al. reported that the recurrence rate of HHs after primary fixation of the mesh using BioGlue in a cohort of 35 patients was 9.5% (2/35) after 1 year of objective follow-up, comparable with other studies where the mesh was secured with sutures or tacks only. Despite these results, long-term outcomes remain unknown, and the complexity of repairing a recurrent HH after BioGlue use is not well documented.\n\nFurthermore, the application of autologous platelet-rich plasma (PRP) as a structural reinforcement strategy in addition to mesh is under investigation. It is thought that the growth factors provided by PRP (i.e., FGF-\u03b2, TGF-\u03b21, PDGF-\u03b2\u03b2, etc.) favor remodeling of the connective tissue and increase the collagen matrix of the crura, making it more resistant to traction. In 2021, Paranyak et al. reported, at 48 months of follow-up, that HHs recurred in 2 of 54 patients (3.7%) with type I or III HH who underwent primary cruroplasty with non-absorbable mesh reinforcement and infiltration of autologous PRP.\n\n## Mesh Reinforcement-Related Complications\n\n### Mesh Erosion\n\nReports of mesh-related complications were initially isolated in the literature, but they raised safety concerns nonetheless. The most dreaded is mesh erosion, which can result in severe morbidity and mortality and frequently requires esophagogastric resection. Parker et al. reported a series of 78 patients from a single institution who required reoperation for antireflux surgery. They compared 10 patients who had prior mesh at the hiatus with 68 patients who did not and concluded that the incidence of HH recurrence did not differ between the groups, which suggested that mesh does not provide complete protection from recurrence. However, they also reported a significantly higher need (30%) for esophagogastric resection in patients with prior mesh at the hiatus. The authors cautioned against the liberal use of mesh, advising surgeons to weigh the higher recurrence rate without mesh against the need for esophagogastric resection associated with mesh in the event that reoperation is needed.\n\nNandipati et al. reported the largest single-center experience with reoperation for patients in whom mesh had previously been used at the hiatus. Their series of 26 patients included 3 patients with mesh erosion, and they found that 70% of patients had a recurrent HH, indicating that mesh does not eliminate the risk of developing a recurrent HH (also noting that the frequency of recurrent HH between patients with prior mesh use and those without prior mesh use was similar). They also reported that 8 of 26 patients (31%) required esophagogastric resection as a corrective procedure with high perioperative morbidity, although no postoperative mortalities were reported. Similarly, Priego et al. described the long-term follow-up of 93 patients who had mesh placed at the hiatus at the time of primary surgery. They reported a 30-day mortality of 4.3%, including 1% related to the use of mesh. Additionally, at a mean follow-up of 76 months, reoperation was required in five patients (5.4%), including three patients (3.2%) who required removal of the mesh, and the overall rate of recurrent HH was 9%.\n\n### Other Complications\n\nMesh reinforcement in HH repair carries the risk of extensive fibrosis of the mesh, potentially resulting in undesirable new-onset dysphagia. Gryska and Vernon reported that 15 of 135 (11.1%) patients who underwent HH repair with non-absorbable mesh presented with dysphagia lasting more than 6 weeks after surgery and required management with balloon dilation. In 2020, Watson et al. reported the presence of any degree of dysphagia in 24.4%, 8.6%, and 15.5% of patients who underwent cruroplasty with suture repair, absorbable mesh, and non-absorbable mesh, respectively, after 5 years of follow-up; in this study, the authors also documented a lower severity of dysphagia among the group with non-absorbable mesh reinforcement.\n\nFinally, mesh-associated local or systemic infections are sporadic, although some cases have been reported. In the event of this postoperative complication, the morbidity can be high as the eradication of infection may require prolonged intravenous antibiotic treatment and surgical reintervention.\n\n## The Big Dilemma: Mesh or No Mesh?\n\n### Comparative Studies\n\nSeveral prospective and retrospective comparative studies have compared primary crus suture closure with mesh reinforcement. Tam et al. summarized 10 of them as part of a systematic review, but the review was hindered by differences in surgical technique, mesh type, duration of follow-up, variation in diagnostic tests, and definition of recurrence. The overall recurrence rate of primary suture closure was 20% (63/312); with mesh reinforcement, that rate was 11% (32/293; 9/10 studies included adequate data). In the same study, the rate of reoperation was 8% (16/200) after primary suture closure and 6.5 % (14/214) after mesh reinforcement (6/10 studies included adequate data). Of all reported complications across the 10 studies, 6 were mesh-related. Two of these patients required esophageal resections. More recent comparative studies have evaluated newly available mesh materials, including bioabsorbable options. For example, in 2019, Wang et al. published a study after a mean objective follow-up of 35 months in a cohort of 65 patients; the authors reported an HH recurrence in 8 of 33 (24.2%) patients who underwent cruroplasty alone, whereas a recurrence was reported in 12 of 32 (37.5%) patients who underwent cruroplasty with absorbable-mesh reinforcement (porcine-derived extracellular matrix). Table 23.4 summarizes the outcomes of some comparative, non-randomized studies.\n\nTable 23.4\n\nMesh Versus No Mesh\n\n<table><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Author, Year</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Study Design</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Interventions</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Findings</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align=\"\" colspan=\"4\">Comparative Studies</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Schmidt et al., <button><sup>59 </sup></button>2014</td><td align=\"\">Retrospective cohort. Patients with 1\u20135 cm HH ( <i>n </i>= 27).</td><td align=\"\">SR ( <i>n </i>= 32) versus Bioabsorable mesh, Allomax ( <i>n </i>= 38).</td><td align=\"\">Median objective follow-up of 12 months. Recurrence for the SR group was 5/32 (15.6%) and 0/38 (0%) for the mesh group. Two patients needed postoperative balloon dilation for new-onset dysphagia in the mesh group.</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Wang et al., <button><sup>60 </sup></button>2016</td><td align=\"\">Retrospective cohort. Patients with &gt;3 cm HH ( <i>n </i>= 101).</td><td align=\"\">SR ( <i>n </i>= 35) versus non-absorbable mesh ( <i>n </i>= 27) versus absorbable mesh ( <i>n </i>= 39).</td><td align=\"\">Median objective follow-up of 32 months. Recurrence in the SR group was 9/29 (31.0%), 6/32 (18.8%) in the absorbable, and 1/22 (4.5%) in the non-absorbable mesh group. Two patients in the Crurasoft mesh group developed new-onset dysphagia.</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Asti et al., <button><sup>61 </sup></button>2016</td><td align=\"\">Retrospective cohort. Patients with type II HH &gt;5 cm ( <i>n </i>= 84).</td><td align=\"\">SR ( <i>n </i>= 43) versus absorbable mesh, GORE BIO-A ( <i>n </i>= 41).</td><td align=\"\">Median objective follow-up of 24 months. Recurrence for the SR group was 8/43 (18.6%) and 4/41 (9.8%) for the mesh group. No reinterventions were reported.</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Wang et al., <button><sup>37 </sup></button>2019</td><td align=\"\">Retrospective cohort. Patients with type II\u2013IV HH ( <i>n </i>= 65).</td><td align=\"\">SR ( <i>n </i>= 33) versus Bioabsorbable mesh, Gentrix UBM ( <i>n </i>= 32).</td><td align=\"\">Median objective follow-up of 235 months. Recurrence was 12/32 (37.5%) for the SR group and 8/33 (24.2%) for the mesh group.</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\" colspan=\"4\">Randomized Clinical Trials</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Frantzides et al., <button><sup>25 </sup></button>2002</td><td align=\"\">RCT. Patients with HH &gt;8 cm ( <i>n </i>= 72).</td><td align=\"\">SR ( <i>n </i>= 36) versus PTFE mesh ( <i>n </i>= 36).</td><td align=\"\">Median clinical follow-up of 30 months. Recurrence was 8/36 (22.2%) for the SR group and 0/36 (0%) for the mesh group.</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Granderath et al., <button><sup>38 </sup></button>2005</td><td align=\"\">RCT. Patients with HH and GERD ( <i>n </i>= 100).</td><td align=\"\">SR ( <i>n </i>= 50) versus prolene mesh ( <i>n </i>= 50).</td><td align=\"\">Clinical follow-up at 3 and 12 months show similar functional outcomes between the groups. Higher postoperative dysphagia in the mesh group. Intrathoracic wrap migration in 26% of SR versus 8% in the mesh group.</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Oelschlager et al., <button><sup>39 </sup></button>2011</td><td align=\"\">RCT. Patients with type II\u2013IV HH &gt;5 cm ( <i>n </i>= 108).</td><td align=\"\">SR ( <i>n </i>= 57) versus PTFE mesh ( <i>n </i>= 51).</td><td align=\"\">Median objective follow-up of 6 months. Recurrence was 12/50 (24.0%) for the SR group and 4/45 (8.9%) for the mesh group. No significant difference in relevant symptoms or QoL. No strictures, erosions, dysphagia, or other complications related to the mesh.</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Ilyashenko et al., <button><sup>40 </sup></button>2018</td><td align=\"\">RCT. Patients with type III HH &gt;10 cm <sup>2 </sup>( <i>n </i>= 98).</td><td align=\"\">SR ( <i>n </i>= 48) versus ProGrip mesh ( <i>n </i>= 50).</td><td align=\"\">Objective follow-up of at 12 months and then annually. Recurrence was 3/48 (6.3%) for the SR group and 4/45, 0/50 (0%) for the mesh group at 12 months and 8/24 (33.3%) and 1/27 (3.7%) at 48 months, respectively. The reoperation rate was 2%.</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Oor et al., <button><sup>41 </sup></button>2018</td><td align=\"\">RCT. Patients with type II\u2013IV HH ( <i>n </i>= 72).</td><td align=\"\">SR ( <i>n </i>= 36) versus TiMesh mesh ( <i>n </i>= 36).</td><td align=\"\">Median objective follow-up of 6 months. Recurrence was 5/35 (14.3%) for the SR group and 5/31 (17.2%) for the mesh group. Bleeding was reported as a complication in 2 (5.6%) cases using non-absorbable mesh.</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Analatos et al., <button><sup>42 </sup></button>2020</td><td align=\"\">RCT. Patients with type I\u2013IV HH ( <i>n </i>= 159).</td><td align=\"\">SR ( <i>n </i>= 77) versus Crurasoft mesh ( <i>n </i>= 82).</td><td align=\"\">Median objective follow-up of 12 months. Recurrence was 2/64 (3.1%) for the SR group and 6/64 (9.4%) for the mesh group. More patients had dysphagia after mesh closure. QoL was comparable between the groups.</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Watson et al., <button><sup>22 </sup></button>2020</td><td align=\"\">RCT. Patients with type I\u2013IV HH ( <i>n </i>= 126).</td><td align=\"\">SR ( <i>n </i>= 43) versus absorbable mesh, Surgisis ( <i>n </i>= 41) versus non-absorbable mesh, TiMesh ( <i>n </i>= 42).</td><td align=\"\">Objective follow-up of 36\u201348 months. Recurrence was 11/28 (39.3%) in the SR group, 17/30 (56.7%) in the absorbable, and 12/28 (42.9%) in the non-absorbable mesh group. At 5 years, chest pain, diarrhea, and gas bloat were more common after repair with absorbable mesh. No advantages were demonstrated for mesh use.</td></tr></tbody></table>\n\n*GERD,* Gastroesophageal reflux disease; *HH,* hiatal hernia; *PTFE,* polytetrafluoroethylene; *QoL,* quality of life. *RCT,* randomized clinical trial; *SR,* suture repair.\n\n### Randomized Clinical Trials\n\nTo date, seven RCTs have compared primary crural closure and mesh-reinforced crural closure. In 2002, Frantzides et al. showed a definitive decline in rates of recurrent HH with the use of fenestrated polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE, DualMesh Gore-Tex; W. L. Gore & Associates, Inc, Phoenix, AZ)\u2014from a recurrence rate of 22% with primary crus closure to 0% with mesh reinforcement with a mean follow-up of 3.3 years after surgery. In 2005, Granderath et al. reported outcomes in a larger RCT of 100 patients in whom Prolene mesh (Ethicon, Somerville, NJ) was used for posterior crus reinforcement. At 12 months follow-up, they found significantly lower rates of intrathoracic wrap migration in patients with mesh than in those with primary crus closure (8% vs. 26%, respectively). In 2011, Oelschlager et al. reported a 5-year follow-up of their multicenter RCT, including patients who received a U-shaped biological prosthesis and those who did not. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> They defined hernia recurrence as a herniation of 2 cm or more on contrast study and found that the rate of recurrence was alarmingly high: 59% in the primary suture repair group and 54% in the prosthesis group. Therefore, they concluded that biological mesh does not protect patients against recurrent HH.\n\nIn 2018, Ilyashenko et al. reported an objective 5-year follow-up of 51 of 98 (52%) patients who underwent laparoscopic HH repair, of whom 1 of 27 (3.7%) presented with HH recurrence after non-absorbable mesh reinforcement and 8 of 24 (33.3%) after suture repair. Conversely, Oor et al. and Analatos et al. found that in a follow-up period of 6 and 12 months, respectively, the groups with non-absorbable mesh reinforcement had a higher objective HH recurrence rate than the control groups: 17.2% versus 14.3% and 9.4% versus 3.1%, respectively. Furthermore, in 2020, Watson et al. reported a 5-year follow-up of a three-armed RCT that evaluated primary crus closure, absorbable mesh reinforcement, and non-absorbable mesh reinforcement. They found no significant differences in the objective recurrence rate between the groups during the first year (primary closure: 26.3%; absorbable mesh: 25%; non-absorbable mesh: 31.7%) or at 5 years (primary closure: 39.3%; absorbable mesh: 56.7%; non-absorbable mesh: 42.9%). Table 23.4 summarizes the outcomes of RCTs.\n\nIn 2022, Petric et al. performed a meta-analysis of the seven aforementioned RCTs. They concluded that mesh-reinforced and simple suture cruroplasty produce comparable results, and routine use of mesh cannot be endorsed. Table 23.5 presents the main meta-analyses and systematic reviews comparing primary suture repair with mesh-reinforced HH repair.\n\nTable 23.5\n\nMeta-Analyses and Systematic Reviews\n\n| Author, Year | Study Design | Summary of Findings |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Antoniou et al., 2015 | SLR with meta-analysis, including 2 RCTs and 3 observational studies ( *n* \\= 295). | HH recurrence risk: lower with mesh. |\n| Huddy et al., 2016 | Expert survey and meta-analysis, including 4 RCTs and 5 observational studies ( *n* \\= 676). | HH recurrence risk: lower with mesh. Reintervention risk: lower with mesh. Postoperative complications risk: similar. |\n| Memon et al., 2016 | Meta-analysis, including 4 RCTs ( *n* \\= 406). | HH recurrence risk: similar. Reintervention risk: lower with mesh. Postoperative complications risk: similar. |\n| Tam et al., 2016 | SLR with meta-analysis, including 3 RCTs and 10 observational studies ( *n* \\= 1194). | HH recurrence risk: lower with mesh. Reintervention risk: similar. |\n| Zhang et al., 2017 | SLR and meta-analysis, including 4 RCTs and 9 observational studies ( *n* \\= 1474). | HH recurrence risk: lower with mesh. Reintervention risk: lower with mesh. Postoperative complications risk: similar. |\n| Sathasivam et al., 2019 | SLR with meta-analysis, including 4 RCTs and 5 observational studies ( *n* \\= 942). | HH recurrence risk: lower with mesh. Reintervention risk: similar. Postoperative complications risk: similar. |\n| Campos et al., 2020 | SLR with meta-analysis, including 6 RCTs and 2 prospective cohorts ( *n* \\= 520). | HH recurrence risk: similar. Reintervention risk: similar. Postoperative complications risk: similar. |\n| Petric et al., 2022 | SLR with meta-analysis, including 7 RCTs ( *n* \\= 735). | HH recurrence risk: similar. Postoperative complications risk: similar. |\n| Angeramo and Schlottmann, 2022 | SLR with meta-analysis, including 7 RCTs ( *n* \\= 735). | HH recurrence risk: similar. Reintervention risk: similar. Postoperative complications risk: lower with SR. |\n\n*HH,* Hiatal hernia; *RCT,* randomized clinical trial; *SLR,* systematic literature review; *SR,* suture repair.\n\n## Novel Alternatives to Mesh Reinforcement\n\nNovel surgical techniques using autologous onlay flaps to replace the use of mesh at the hiatus have been described, specifically for cases of a giant HH. In 2004, Varga et al. published a case series of four patients who underwent cruroplasty with teres ligamentum reinforcement for an HH >6 cm. No perioperative complications or HH recurrence was observed after 3 months. Furthermore, in 2012, Park et al. documented the use of the falciform ligament as a vascularized autologous onlay flap in 15 patients with a PEH in whom adequate hiatal closure by crural approximation was not possible. The authors reported that there were no short-term symptomatic recurrences. Using a similar technique, Asti et al. performed HH repair with rotational falciform ligament flap on 18 patients. The patients presented with a significant improvement in quality-of-life scores and no anatomical recurrences were detected by Gastrografin swallow studies at a median follow-up of 8 months (range, 3\u201315 months). In 2022, Vigneswaran et al. described the use of the posterior rectus sheath as a vascularized onlay flap in two patients during robotic HH repair. Neither patient presented with evidence of HH recurrence after 5 months of follow-up.\n\nUsing autologous flaps may avoid undesirable mesh-related complications; however, the technique requires longer intraoperative times and carries the potential risks of flap ischemia and abdominal wall hernias. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Most case series with autologous onlay flaps have only a few patients, and medium- and long-term outcome data are limited. Therefore, a conclusive argument for their use cannot be made at present.\n\n## Conclusions\n\nMost studies report a higher short-term HH recurrence rate when it has been repaired without mesh. All prospective series, comparative studies, and RCTs report significant improvement in quality-of-life parameters both with and without mesh reinforcement\u2014a finding not necessarily associated with endoscopic or radiographic recurrence. Only a few comparative studies and RCTs reported long-term follow-up (>60 months), and the paucity of long-term data from large centers that experienced initial success with synthetic mesh is troubling. The long-term outcomes regarding recurrence rates and mesh-related complications would greatly help resolve the controversy.\n\nUntil further studies and meta-analyses analyzing the long-term outcomes are available, it can be concluded only that although mesh reinforcement at the hiatus seems to lessen the likelihood of short-term radiographic recurrence, the evidence for long-term recurrence is leaning in the other direction. Additionally, reoperation, after the use of mesh (regardless of mesh composition), is challenging and possibly even hazardous\u2014sometimes requiring esophagogastric resection. Thus, the routine use of mesh cannot be justified at present, and its use should be restricted to individual cases based on the treating surgeons\u2019 discretion based on operative findings.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Carlson M.A., Condon R.E., Ludwig K.A., Schulte W.J.: Management of intrathoracic stomach with polypropylene mesh prosthesis reinforced transabdominal hiatus hernia repair . J Am Coll Surg 1998; 187 (3): pp. 227-230.\n\nView In Article\n\n2.: Castelijns P.S.S., Ponten J.E.H., van de Poll M.C.G., Nienhuijs S.W., Smulders J.F.: A collective review of biological versus synthetic mesh-reinforced cruroplasty during laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication . J Minimal Access Surg 2018; 14 (2): pp. 87-94.\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: Nandipati K., Bye M., Yamamoto S.R., Pallati P., Lee T., Mittal S.K.: Reoperative intervention in patients with mesh at the hiatus is associated with high incidence of esophageal resection\u2014a single-center experience . J Gastrointest Surg 2013; 17 (12): pp. 2039-2044.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Parker M., Bowers S.P., Bray J.M., et al.: Hiatal mesh is associated with major resection at revisional operation . Surg Endosc 2010; 24 (12): pp. 3095-3101.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: Maziak D.E., Todd T.R.J., Pearson F.G.: Massive hiatus hernia: evaluation and surgical management . J Thorac Cardiovasc Surg 1998; 115 (1): pp. 53-62.\n\nView In Article\n\n6.: Hashemi M., Peters J.H., DeMeester T.R., et al.: Laparoscopic repair of large type III hiatal hernia: objective followup reveals high recurrence rate1 . J Am Coll Surg 2000; 190 (5): pp. 553-560.\n\nView In Article\n\n7.: Puri K., Awad F.: Hiatal hernia recurrence: 2004 . Hernia 2004; 8 (4): pp. 311-317.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n8.: Targarona E.M.: Mesh in the hiatus . Arch Surg 2004; 139 (12): pp. 1286.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n9.: Lidor A.O.: Long-term quality of life and risk factors for recurrence after laparoscopic repair of paraesophageal hernia