[24. Reducing Tension:: Diaphragmatic Relaxing Incisions and Esophageal Lengthening During Large Hiatal Hernia Repair - ClinicalKey|24. Reducing Tension:: Diaphragmatic Relaxing Incisions and Esophageal Lengthening During Large Hiatal Hernia Repair]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "23. Mesh at the Hiatus - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Mesh at the Hiatus', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Mesh at the Hiatus', 'Primary Crural Closure: Recurrence and Outcomes', 'Mesh-Reinforced Crus Closure: Recurrence and Outcomes', 'Mesh Configurations and Materials', 'How to Secure the Mesh', 'Mesh Reinforcement-Related Complications', 'Mesh at the Hiatus / Primary Crural Closure: Recurrence and Outcomes', 'Mesh at the Hiatus / Mesh-Reinforced Crus Closure: Recurrence and Outcomes', 'Mesh at the Hiatus / Mesh Configurations and Materials'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '23', '239-248', 2, 48, FALSE, TRUE),
('Reducing Tension:: Diaphragmatic Relaxing Incisions and Esophageal Lengthening During Large Hiatal Hernia Repair', 'shackelford-9th-ed-24-reducing-tension-diaphragmatic-relaxing-incisions-and-esophageal-lengthening-d', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Reducing Tension: : Diaphragmatic Relaxing Incisions and Esophageal Lengthening During Large Hiatal Hernia Repair\n\nMarc Andrew Ward; Stephanie G. Worrell; Joshua A. Boys; Steven Ryan Demeester\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 24, 249-254\n\n## Introduction\n\nThe prevalence of large hiatal hernias, and in particular paraesophageal hernias (PEHs), is increasing. Meanwhile, it is recognized that over 50% of laparoscopic repairs will be associated with radiographic and often clinical evidence of a recurrent hernia within 5 years. The history of abdominal hernia repair in the inguinal and ventral locations has shown that tension on the repair of a hernia is a major risk factor for failure and hernia recurrence. In light of this fact, efforts have been made to find sources of tension during a PEH repair. The two forms of tension at the hiatus are axial tension related to esophageal shortening, and lateral tension related to a very wide hiatus. Axial tension can be addressed with further esophageal mobilization into the mediastinum or a Collis gastroplasty which effectively lengthens the esophagus. Lateral tension can be addressed with a right, left, or bilateral diaphragm relaxing incision. The indications and techniques for these procedures are addressed in this chapter.\n\n## Collis Gastroplasty\n\nOver 50 years after Dr. John Leigh Collis described his procedure for lengthening the esophagus, there is still controversy about the existence and prevalence of a foreshortened esophagus. Furthermore, the laparoscopic management of a short esophagus is challenging, and as a result there is a tendency by many surgeons to ignore esophageal length and proceed with a standard repair. Almost certainly, this contributes to the high documented rate of hernia recurrence after laparoscopic repair of a large sliding or PEH.\n\nNormally, up to several centimeters of the distal esophagus and the gastroesophageal junction (GEJ) lie below the hiatus within the abdomen. When the GEJ, the fundus of the stomach, or both migrate into the chest above the hiatus, a hiatal hernia is present. Intrinsic to the repair of a hiatal hernia is the need to bring the GEJ, stomach, and distal esophagus back into the abdomen. However, since 1950 it has been known that in some patients this can be challenging, particularly those with severe gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) or a large hiatal hernia. In these patients, esophageal shortening can lead to loss of intraabdominal esophageal length and put axial tension on the repair of a hiatal hernia. Dr. Leigh Collis described a technique in 1957 to address acquired esophageal shortening. His technique, now referred to as a Collis gastroplasty, creates an extension to the esophagus from the high lesser curvature of the stomach. His gastroplasty was done as a transthoracic procedure. Subsequently, several techniques have been described to create a similar gastroplasty using a laparoscopic approach.\n\n## Identifying the Short Esophagus\n\nPatients at risk for acquired esophageal shortening include those with advanced GERD with esophagitis, stricture, long-segment Barrett\u2019s esophagus, a history of sarcoidosis, caustic ingestion, or scleroderma and those with a large sliding or PEH. The presence of a foreshortened esophagus in patients with severe GERD is understandable because exposure to refluxed gastric juice causes mucosal injury and can lead to transmural inflammation, fibrosis, and collagen contraction. An esophageal stricture is strongly associated with a shortened esophagus and the need for a gastroplasty. The presence of both a large hiatal hernia (>5 cm) and an esophageal stricture further increases the risk of a shortened esophagus. In addition, a history of a previous failed antireflux procedure with recurrent hiatal hernia should raise suspicion that the length of the esophagus is short. The etiology of esophageal shortening in patients with a PEH is unclear, but may be related to loss of elasticity in the longitudinal esophageal muscle related to chronic loss of intraabdominal fixation of the GEJ. Although any of these histories should increase the suspicion that a patient may have a short esophagus, none are definitive. Objective studies in patients with GERD or PEH are useful to define the size, type, and reducibility of any hiatal hernia, presence of a stricture or erosive esophagitis, esophageal function, and the presence and severity of increased esophageal exposure to refluxed gastric juice. A foreshortened esophagus can effectively be ruled out when a hiatal hernia fully reduces on barium esophagram, but in any nonreducing hiatal hernia a short esophagus may be present. Therefore, although objective studies can rule out a short esophagus, none can accurately identify its presence. Instead, a foreshortened esophagus can be confirmed only by the intraoperative inability to reduce the GEJ below the hiatus by 2\u20133 cm after mediastinal esophageal mobilization and posterior crural closure.\n\n## Management of the Short Esophagus\n\nFailure to obtain an adequate length of intraabdominal esophagus during hiatal hernia repair is likely a leading cause for re-herniation and breakdown of the repair. Mediastinal mobilization and posterior crural closure, particularly in a patient with kyphosis, are routinely used to add esophageal length. To accomplish a fundoplication without tension, there should be 2\u20133 cm of intraabdominal esophagus below the hiatal closure. If standard methods for esophageal mobilization are insufficient to provide 2\u20133 cm of abdominal esophagus, esophageal lengthening is recommended.\n\nThere are several methods to accomplish a Collis gastroplasty during a laparoscopic procedure. The authors\u2019 preferred approach was described by Terry et al. and is the wedge fundectomy Collis gastroplasty (WFCG) technique. Following mobilization, the esophagogastric junction is very mobile, allowing manipulation for stapling. When performing a WFCG, we place a 52-French bougie along the lesser curve of the stomach and use a 45-mm Endo GIA blue load stapler to excise a small piece of fundus. We try to excise as small a wedge of fundus as possible. Given the limitations of articulating Endo GIA staplers, we found that to excise only a small portion of the fundus it was necessary to create a starfish-shaped piece of the proximal fundus by successively cutting through the inferior staple line with each successive staple load until a mark approximately 3 cm below the angle of His was reached ( Fig. 24.1 ). The staple line was not reinforced but was buried by the fundoplication. A partial Toupet or complete Nissen fundoplication was added to the WFCG in all patients. Importantly, the fundoplication was kept as high on the gastroplasty as possible, preferably at the top near the true GEJ. The importance of this is the fact that the gastroplasty is made from stomach, and acid production by the gastroplasty above the fundoplication can lead to erosive esophagitis in some patients, particularly if there are several centimeters of gastroplasty above the fundoplication. It is also important to recognize that the gastroplasty tube is aperistaltic. Therefore, bolus transport through the gastroplasty relies on the motility of the distal esophagus above the gastroplasty. Consequently, we are more liberal with the use of a partial fundoplication in patients who have a WFCG added for a shortened esophagus and keep the Collis segment smaller than the diameter of the native esophagus so that food and liquid are funneled down through the gastroplasty.\n\nFour diagrams show the stages of a gastroplasty procedure with notes on measurements. The diagrams demonstrate a laparoscopic gastric surgery. The first two diagrams focus on the adjustments made to the stomach''s size that indicate a restriction of 2 centimeters. The third and fourth diagrams illustrate further alterations that display a 3 centimeter modification. The diagrams utilize clear anatomical representations to convey the surgical process effectively. Each diagram is labeled with the measurement corresponding to the procedure''s focus.\n\nFig. 24.1\n\n## Outcome With a Collis Gastroplasty\n\nBefore the introduction of laparoscopic surgery, most antireflux procedures were performed in patients with severe GERD, often with impaired esophageal body function. A Collis gastroplasty in these patients frequently led to protracted postoperative dysphagia. The availability of potent acid-suppressing medications has led to a reduction in the acid-related complications of reflux disease including strictures. Furthermore, the number of patients presenting for elective repair of a PEH in the era of laparoscopic surgery is increasing. In these patients, a Collis gastroplasty seems to be better tolerated. A recent evaluation of our laparoscopic Collis gastroplasties showed that dysphagia was a common preoperative symptom; however, it resolved in the majority (71%) postoperatively. Importantly, new-onset dysphagia occurred in only two patients (5.5%) and resolved after one endoscopic dilatation in both patients. Dysphagia that was present preoperatively and persisted was typically mild and did not significantly impact the patient\u2019s diet or lifestyle.\n\nThe prevalence of esophagitis in this series was 11%. This is substantially less than the 36% rate reported by Jobe et al., and may in part be related to our efforts to keep the fundoplication above the Collis whenever possible. It is also possible that the degree of shortening in our patients was less than that in the series by Jobe et al., because in patients with a very short esophagus, the Collis gastroplasty can extend above the hiatus. In that circumstance, it is not possible to position the fundoplication at the top of the gastroplasty. As esophagitis in these patients is often asymptomatic, we recommend that at least one postoperative endoscopy be done after a Collis gastroplasty to evaluate for esophagitis. If esophagitis is found in the setting of an intact fundoplication, treatment with acid suppression medication is recommended to prevent stricture formation or other complications related to ongoing mucosal injury.\n\nThe key issue of course with a Collis gastroplasty is whether it reduces hernia recurrence rates. There are no randomized studies addressing this issue. However, a number of retrospective analyses suggest that a Collis can contribute to a reduced risk of hernia recurrence. Further studies will be useful to understand this complex issue more clearly.\n\n## Diaphragm Relaxing Incisions\n\nTension on the repair of any hernia contributes to an increased risk for recurrence. This was first recognized for inguinal hernias and led to the incorporation of relaxing incisions and tension-free repairs. Subsequently component separation has been adopted to release tension during ventral hernia repair. Logically this concept can be extended to the hiatus for patients with large crural defects where achieving primary approximation of the crural pillars would be difficult or impossible without significant tension. Like the tension-free inguinal hernia repair, bridging the crural defect with mesh has been considered. However, bridging with synthetic mesh has been associated with mesh erosion into the esophagus and is ill-advised ( Fig. 24.2 ). Bridging with a biologic mesh is only a temporary solution as the bridged biologic or absorbable material will go away, setting the stage for hernia recurrence. In our opinion, a better alternative is a relaxing incision in either the right or left diaphragm, and occasionally in both.\n\nAn endoscopy of the esophagus that represents soft tissue and a disrupted object. #REF!\n\nFig. 24.2\n\nThe concept of a relaxing incision is to create a defect adjacent to the area of interest that is less critical (muscle or fascia) to allow the principal tissues to come together. In the case of the hiatus, relaxing incisions are ideal as there is available diaphragm on either side. In addition, there is little (if any) downside to making a relaxing incision in the diaphragm. Because there is a pressure differential between the thorax (negative pressure) and the abdomen (positive pressure), all relaxing incisions must be closed. Even small diaphragmatic defects can lead to herniation of abdominal contents into the chest. We routinely close relaxing incision defects with polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE) mesh, as there is a large experience with this mesh for chest wall and diaphragm reconstruction. Unlike other types of synthetic mesh, the lung does not typically fuse to PTFE mesh, so future thoracic surgical procedures, if needed, will not be made more complex. Although there is concern about the use of PTFE mesh in a clean-contaminated case, six of our patients in our published series had a concomitant WFCG, and no patient developed an infection of the PTFE mesh used in the reconstruction. Unlike ventral hernia repairs with mesh, the use of simple interrupted sutures to sew the PTFE mesh to the edges of the defect with no overlap works well on the diaphragm. This is likely possible because as the mesh contracts, the diaphragm has enough compliance to accommodate without tearing the stitches out. In fact, the large amount of shrinkage that occurs with PTFE mesh may be beneficial in restoring a more natural contour to the diaphragm over time after a relaxing incision. Absorbable or biologic mesh should be avoided, as it will not permanently repair the defect.\n\nBoth right- and left-sided relaxing incisions are relatively straightforward laparoscopic procedures, provided that important landmarks are recognized. In our study, none of our patients suffered complications or paralyzed diaphragms related to the relaxing incisions. Furthermore, it is important to recognize that a wide communication between the abdomen and thorax during a laparoscopic procedure with 15 mmHg carbon dioxide capnoperitoneum is well tolerated. Small pleural holes can lead to a ball-valve effect and tension pneumothorax, but large openings are not associated with such problems. In fact, large openings of the pleura are standard when we repair large hiatal defects, even without a relaxing incision, to neutralize the diaphragm against pneumoperitoneum prior to crural closure. This allows the mediastinal space to drain into the right, left, or both pleural cavities once the hernia has been repaired. Furthermore, putting the diaphragm into a neutral position reduces crural closure tension and can in some cases help avoid the need for a diaphragm relaxing incision.\n\n## Technique for Right-Sided Relaxing Incision\n\nThe right-sided relaxing incision is straightforward and adds only 15\u201330 minutes to the overall procedure. It is the preferred release, but the right crus must be at least 1\u20131.5 cm wide to have enough tissue to reconstruct the hiatus following this maneuver. Rarely, but particularly in reoperations, the right crus may be so thin that there is insufficient room between the edge of the crus and the inferior vena cava to do a right-sided relaxing incision. In these patients, or in the rare patient where a right-sided relaxing incision is insufficient to allow tension-free crural closure, a left-sided relaxing incision is necessary.\n\nA right relaxing incision is performed by opening the right crus parallel to the inferior vena cava, saving a 3-mm cuff of tissue along the cava to allow a patch to be sewn into place. The right-sided relaxing incision entails a full-thickness incision through the right crus into the right pleural space. It is started in the midportion of the right crus and ends below the anterior crural vein ( Fig. 24.3 ). The diaphragm in this area is quite tendinous, so ultrasonic energy or a hook cautery work well to make the incision on the right side. Typically, the incision only needs to go anteriorly to the level of the crural vein, but if that is insufficient, the crural vein can be ligated and the incision carried further anterior and medially to allow additional release. It is surprising how well this release will allow the right crus to move medially and in the process leave a gaping defect in the right diaphragm ( Fig. 24.4 ). The only structure of significance to avoid injuring with the right-sided relaxing incision is the intrathoracic vena cava, but this should be anterior and lateral to the incision. If not used routinely, pledgeted sutures are recommended after a right relaxing incision to minimize the risk that the crural closure sutures pull through the residual right crural pillar. Once the hiatus is reconstructed, the defect created by the relaxing incision is repaired with a permanent mesh. The authors\u2019 preference is 1 mm PTFE sewn in with interrupted 3-0 monofilament sutures ( Fig. 24.5 ). The authors then prefer to reinforce the primary crural closure with absorbable biologic or biosynthetic mesh ( Fig. 24.6 ). The absorbable mesh is secured to the diaphragm using short 5-mm non-spring-loaded tacks.\n\nA photo of the esophagus and hiatus with phrenic vein and other blood vessels. The photo depicts a surgical site with the esophagus, associated tissue, and hiatus visible. Labels point to the Esophagus and Hiatus. Two arrows, with one followed by a dashed line, point to additional key features of the anatomy.\n\nFig. 24.3\n\nA photo of the surgical anatomy of a Nissen fundoplication procedure labeled with hiatus, esophagus, and hiatal closure. The photo captures esophageal hiatus and anatomical structures in surgery and depicts Nissen fundoplication, hiatal closure, and 1 millimeter polytetrafluoroethylene mesh placement, which addresses a right diaphragm and relaxes incision defect. Arrows indicate specific areas of medical context that require caution.\n\nFig. 24.4\n\nA photo of the surgical view inside the body reveals a foreign object surrounded by tissue and blood, indicating a medical procedure. #REF!\n\nFig. 24.5\n\nA photo of the surgical repair of a hiatal hernia with the aid of mesh reinforcement made of polytetrafluoroethylene. The photo focuses on a surgical site in a patient. Text labels with arrows indicate key features of Hiatal repair with bioresorbable mesh reinforcement, the right diaphragm that relaxes the incision closed with polytetrafluoroethylene-mesh and Nissen Fundo. The mesh is a webbed patch on the injured place. The overall view is dominated by blood and exposed tissue.\n\nFig. 24.6\n\n## Technique for Left-Sided Relaxing Incision\n\nThe left-sided relaxing incision is not difficult but requires more time to repair the defect as a larger incision is required. Unlike the radial incision paralleling the crus on the right side, the left-sided incision should be made laterally following the seventh rib. The phrenic nerve is protected on the right side by the vena cava, but a radial incision on the left side puts the phrenic nerve at risk, which could lead to paralysis of the left hemidiaphragm. The only other structure of significance with a left-sided relaxing incision is the heart, which should be anterior and medial to the site of the incision ( Fig. 24.7 ). Prior to starting the left relaxing incision, it is important to create a left capnothorax by opening the left pleura, if not done already. This takes the left diaphragm off tension, making it easier to begin the relaxing incision. As previously discussed, this may obviate the need for a relaxing incision in some cases. Further, this allows the diaphragm to be pulled away from the heart, which minimizes the risk of injury.\n\nA photo of a hiatus and spleen with landmarks for a left diaphragm that relaxes the incision procedure. The photo reveals the intraoperative endoscopic view. The Hiatus is circled at the top above the spleen at the bottom. Dashed and dotted lines demarcate a surgical path. The overall view reflects the internal organs of the patient.\n\nFig. 24.7\n\nThe incision is started lateral to the heart approximately 1\u20132 cm below the seventh rib. The 1\u20132 cm of diaphragm attached to the rib is necessary to allow subsequent closure of the defect. The incision is full thickness, extending into the left pleural space. Typically the incision needs to be carried laterally and posterior to the spleen to allow sufficient release. For this incision, the authors prefer ultrasonic energy to minimize diaphragm twitching and bleeding. Once sufficient release has been achieved to allow tension-free closure of the hiatus, the diaphragmatic defect can be reconstructed. On occasion the left diaphragm slides medially without creating a wide defect, and the medial portion of the relaxing incision can be closed primarily with interrupted figure-of-eight permanent sutures with only a small patch posterior laterally. In some cases, a larger patch is needed when the diaphragm is pulled medially and downward. For the left side mesh, the authors prefer 2 mm PTFE sewn in with interrupted 0-Ethibond or similar suture ( Figs. 24.8 and 24.9 ). The tension-free crural closure can then be reinforced with an absorbable biologic or biosynthetic mesh.\n\nA photo of the surgical view of a 2-millimeter polytetrafluoroethylene patch and primary closure in a medical procedure. The photo depicts the hernia surgery in progress. A small polytetrafluoroethylene patch is visible laterally, secured with sutures. Primary closure is seen medially. A surgical instrument is present in the lower center of the area in the abdomen.\n\nFig. 24.8\n\nA photo of the diaphragm that relaxes the incision procedure with threads and needles attached to the tissue. #REF!\n\nFig. 24.9\n\n## Outcomes With Crural Relaxing Incisions\n\nThe use of crural relaxing incisions, when necessary, has eliminated the need for a bridged crural repair. In our initial series of 15 patients published in 2013, the hiatal reconstruction was completed laparoscopically in all patients with primary crural closure. No drains were left in the pleural space or mediastinum, and no patient developed a pleural effusion prior to discharge. On follow-up chest x-ray, three patients had developed a pleural effusion and two patients required pigtail drainage. An asymptomatic mild elevation of the left hemidiaphragm was seen in one patient. At short-term follow-up, no patient had required reoperation, and no patient developed a diaphragmatic hernia through the repaired relaxing incision or evidence of PTFE mesh infection. Objective follow-up in 11 of the 15 patients showed that the repair was intact in all but one patient who had an asymptomatic, trivial (<2 cm) recurrent hernia at 4.5 months. An updated analysis with more patients and longer follow-up has been recently submitted for publication.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nAxial and lateral tension during the repair of a large hiatal hernia likely leads to an increased risk for hernia recurrence, and efforts to reduce tension are warranted to improve outcomes. WFCG works well in patients with esophageal shortening. In those with a large hiatal defect that makes crural approximation difficult or impossible without substantial tension, a diaphragm release allows successful crural approximation while keeping permanent mesh away from the esophagus. This minimizes the risk of mesh erosion. Continued follow-up after these procedures will allow a better understanding of the role of tension in hiatal hernia recurrence.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Oelschlager B.K., Pellegrini C.A., Hunter J.G., et al.: Biologic prosthesis to prevent recurrence after laparoscopic paraesophageal hernia repair: long-term follow-up from a multicenter, prospective, randomized trial . \\[Erratum appears in *J Am Coll Surg* . 2011 Dec;213(6):815\\] . J Am Coll Surg 2011; 213: pp. 461-468.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Collis J.L.: An operation for haitus hernia with short esophagus . J Thorac Surg 1957; 34: pp. 768-778.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference30296-8)\n\n3.: Terry M.L., Vernon A., Hunter J.G.: Stapled-wedge Collis gastroplasty for the shortened esophagus . Am J Surg 2004; 188: pp. 195-199.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Zehetner J., DeMeester S.R., Ayazi S., et al.: Laparoscopic wedge fundectomy for collis gastroplasty creation in patients with a foreshortened esophagus . Ann Surg 2014; 260: pp. 1030-1033.\n\nView In Article\n\n5.: Jobe B.A., Horvath K.D., Swanstrom L.L.: Postoperative function following laparoscopic collis gastroplasty for shortened esophagus . Arch Surg 1998; 133: pp. 867-874.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n6.: Greene C.L., DeMeester S.R., Zehetner J., et al.: Diaphragmatic relaxing incisions during laparoscopic paraesophageal hernia repair . Surg Endosc 2013; 27: pp. 4532-4538.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n7.: Bradley D.D., Louie B.E., Farivar A.S., et al.: Assessment and reduction of diaphragmatic tension during hiatal hernia repair . Surg Endosc 2015; 29: pp. 796-804.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n8.: Abdelmoaty W., Dunst C.M., Filicori F., et al.: Combination of surgical technique and bioresorbable mesh reinforcement of the crural repair leads to low early hernia recurrence rate with laparoscopic paraesophageal hernia repair . J Gastrointest Surg 2020; 24: pp. 1477-1481.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\nPrevious ChapterGo to the previous chapter\n\nNext ChapterGo to the next chapter\n\n\n\n## Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract\n\nNinth Edition\n\nCopyright \u00a9 2026 by Elsevier Inc. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies.\n\n## Get rights and content\u00a0\n\