('Management of Barrett’s Esophagus', 'shackelford-9th-ed-26-management-of-barretts-esophagus', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Management of Barrett\u2019s Esophagus\n\nSunil Gupta; Michael J. BourkE; Reginald V.N. Lord\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 26, 264-269\n\n## Introduction\n\nThe management of Barrett\u2019s esophagus (BE) has two aspects. The first is managing the symptoms of gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD)\u2014the underlying condition responsible for the development of BE\u2014which is addressed in the following chapter. The second aspect, which is addressed in this chapter, is managing Barrett\u2019s disease, which involves assessing and limiting the risk of disease progression to dysplasia and esophageal adenocarcinoma (EAC) including adenocarcinoma at the gastroesophageal junction (GEJ). Management of BE involves monitoring via endoscopic surveillance and potentially reducing modifiable risk factors, limiting reflux, chemoprevention, and endoscopic intervention.\n\nThe diagnosis of BE has both macroscopic (i.e., visible columnar lined metaplasia on endoscopy) and microscopic criteria, with the latter requiring the histopathological presence of mucus-secreting columnar cells, termed intestinal metaplasia (IM). For patients diagnosed with endoscopic BE but without biopsy-proven IM, reasonable initial management is therefore to perform one repeat endoscopy with biopsies to clarify whether BE is truly present.\n\n## Modifiable Risk Factors\n\nSome major risk factors associated with BE development cannot be modified: age, non-Hispanic White/Caucasian race, male sex, and family history of BE or EAC. Of these factors, male sex, family history, and (in some studies) increasing age are also associated with progression of non-dysplastic BE (NDBE) to cancer. Modifiable factors include tobacco smoking (associated with BE development and with higher risk of EAC ) and obesity, especially central adiposity (associated with BE but not clearly with BE progression).\n\nWeight management may also be beneficial. Specifically, weight loss measured as a BMI decrease of \u22653.5kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> has been shown to be associated with a 40% decrease in GERD symptoms in women. Some suggest a healthy, low-calorie diet high in fruits, vegetables, nonfried fish and low in fat and meat can be beneficial in decreasing risk of the development of cancer. Such a diet will certainly help promote weight loss, but associations with BE are uncertain.\n\n## Limiting Gastroesophageal Reflux\n\n### Acid Suppression Medical Therapy\n\nMost patients with BE have at least moderately severe GERD and are more likely to report severe or very severe GERD symptoms. Observational studies have demonstrated that GERD symptoms are a significant risk factor for EAC, with increased risk associated with longer duration and severity of GERD symptoms. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The mechanism for this is presumably through BE induced by GERD; therefore, limiting gastroesophageal reflux is considered an important part of the management of BE. Proton pump inhibitor (PPI) therapy, the mainstay of medical management, is recommended by all society guidelines. An outline of medical treatment for GERD is provided in Chapter 27 and in the recent American College of Gastroenterology (ACG) summary.\n\nThe primary indication for antireflux therapy, whether medical or surgical, is control of GERD symptoms, but whether limiting GERD has a beneficial effect on the biology of BE is also relevant regardless of symptom profile. For example, some patients with BE deny ever having GERD symptoms, but PPIs would still be indicated if they had a chemoprevention effect. A chemopreventative effect of PPI against BE progression may impact PPI dosage recommendations outside of symptom control. Complete control of acid reflux, without breakthrough episodes, can be difficult to achieve in patients with BE depending on the severity of GERD. High-dose twice-daily PPI therapy has been traditionally prescribed as preferred therapy in patients with BE, even if GERD symptoms are well controlled with a lower dose; however, these recommendations are evolving as more information about the effects of PPI emerge.\n\nTwo meta-analyses have investigated whether PPIs reduce the risk of EAC or high-grade dysplasia (HGD) in patients with BE. Both included only observational studies and are thus liable to the bias and confounding inherent in such studies. In 2014, Singh et al. found that use of a PPI at the time of BE diagnosis is associated with a decreased risk of EAC and/or HGD (unadjusted odds ratio \\[OR\\] 0.26, 95% confidence interval \\[CI\\] 0.10\u20130.71). There was a nonsignificant trend towards a dose\u2013response relationship with PPI use for longer than 2\u20133 years being protective against EAC or HGD (three studies; PPI use >2\u20133 years vs. <2\u20133 years: OR 0.45 \\[95% CI 0.19\u20131.06\\] vs. 1.09 \\[0.47\u20132.56\\]). In 2017, Hu et al. included nine observational studies comprising five cohort and four case-control studies (including a total of 5712 patients with BE). PPIs were found to have no association with the risk of EAC and/or HGD in patients with BE (unadjusted OR 0.43, 95% CI 0.17\u20131.08). Analysis for duration\u2013response relationship revealed no significant trend towards protection against EAC or HGD with PPI use for >2\u20133 years compared with shorter time periods (PPIs use >2\u20133 years vs. <2\u20133 years: OR 0.91 \\[95% CI 0.25\u20133.31\\] vs. 0.91 \\[0.40\u20132.07\\]). There also was considerable heterogeneity between studies. The authors concluded that no HGD or EAC-protective effects of PPI use in patients with BE were identified, with implications for clinicians who discuss the potential chemopreventive effects of PPIs with their patients.\n\nA randomized clinical trial (AspECT, discussed further below) did not find a significant protective effect against EAC or HGD development or a significant dose\u2013response relationship for high-dose PPI versus low-dose PPI for protection against EAC or HGD. Data on the use of histamine-2 receptor antagonists in BE are limited, but no protective association has been found. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Antireflux Surgery\n\nThe role of antireflux surgery for patients with BE is also included in Chapter 27 ; the discussion here is limited to whether antireflux surgery has a preventive effect on the rate of BE progression. Most patients with BE have a hiatal hernia, which is typically larger than that in patients with no BE, as well as a more severely defective lower esophageal sphincter and impaired body motility. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Mechanistic reasoning suggests that antireflux surgery, which repairs the hernia and restores the gastroesophageal antireflux barrier, should have a beneficial effect on the biology of Barrett\u2019s disease, but studies on this topic report highly variable results.\n\nIn a 2007 systematic review Chang et al. included 700 patients who underwent antireflux surgery and 996 medically treated patients, for totals of 2939 and 3711 patient-years, respectively. The probability of regression to any of a lower-grade dysplasia, from dysplasia to NDBE/IM or to no IM was higher in the surgical arms. This difference was significant for all studies ( *P* \\-value =.004). Specifically, the frequency of regression was 6.4% in surgically treated patients versus 0.5% in medically treated patients ( *P* \\=.024) for the RCT/cohort studies. However, there were no significant differences found in the probability of progression to worse dysplasia, and the rate of EAC development was not different in the other controlled studies. In a later meta-analysis in 2016, Maret-Ouda et al. found a pooled incidence risk ratio (IRR) for EAC in patients with BE treated surgically compared with medical treatment of 0.46 (95% CI 0.20\u20131.08). This trend became significant when restricted to publications after the year 2000: IRR 0.26 (95% CI 0.09\u20130.79).\n\nFour RCTs have been performed, but in 2003 Parrilla et al. published the only RCT that specifically examined BE progression after medical treatment compared with surgical therapy. The study included 101 patients with BE with a median follow-up period exceeding 5 years (range 1\u201318 years). Patients underwent annual clinical, endoscopic, and histopathologic assessment, with all endoscopies performed by the same endoscopist taking four quadrant biopsies every 1\u20132 cm. The competence of the fundoplication was assessed by postoperative esophageal pH and manometry studies at 1 year, 5 years, and every 5 years thereafter. There were no significant clinical, demographic, manometric, pH, or bile reflux (Bilitec probe) differences between the cohorts. Approximately 90% of patients had NDBE; three patients (7%) had low-grade dysplasia (LGD) in the medical arm and five patients (9%) had LGD in the surgical arm. There were no significant differences in rates of progression to dysplasia or EAC: new dysplasia developed in 20% of patients treated medically and 6% of patients treated surgically. Two patients in each arm developed endoscopic HGD; all four had EAC on final pathology after esophagectomy. The importance of performing durable effective surgery was suggested in this study by the finding that none of the 49 patients who had successful surgical treatment demonstrated by objective reflux testing developed HGD and only one developed LGD. A Swedish population-based case-control study similarly presented data that indicated the importance of effective versus less effective GERD control by fundoplication.\n\nThe Nordic GERD Study Group RCT <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> primarily investigated GERD and was underpowered for the outcomes BE and EAC, including only 48 patients with BE, of whom 26 were treated by PPI therapy and 22 by antireflux surgery. The LOTUS trial reported that endoscopic suspicion of esophageal metaplasia remained stable at 5 years of follow-up in both medical and surgical arms. An RCT by Spechler et al. also found no advantage for surgical therapy but, similar to the Nordic and LOTUS trials, was primarily designed to investigate GERD, underpowered for the outcomes BE and EAC, and quality of surgery was not assessed.\n\n## Chemoprevention\n\nIn addition to PPIs, as discussed above, additional agents have been studied for their potential role in chemoprevention of EAC. Use of statins (HMG co-A reductase inhibitors which act to lower serum cholesterol) is significantly associated with a lower rate of progression to EAC in observational studies, <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> but statin use has not been recommended as routine chemoprevention in individuals with BE. Following some positive studies for nonsteroidal antiinflammatory drugs including acetylsalicylic acid (aspirin), the randomized, phase 3 AspECT trial by Jankowski et al. in 2018 enrolled 2557 individuals with BE to investigate the chemoprevention role of aspirin and compare high- versus low-dose PPI therapy. The four arms in this study were: high-dose PPI (esomeprazole 40 mg twice daily) alone, high-dose PPI with aspirin (300 mg in UK, 325 mg in Canada), low-dose PPI (esomeprazole 20 mg once daily), and low-dose PPI with aspirin. Median follow-up and treatment were 8.9 years. The study was co-sponsored by Astra Zeneca. Pathologists were blinded, but drug treatment was not. The authors reported a composite event endpoint that included EAC and HGD as well as all-cause mortality. Using this method, a significant benefit was found for high-dose PPI with aspirin versus low-dose PPI alone. No significant protective benefit for EAC or HGD as endpoints without all-cause mortality was demonstrated, 95% CIs tended to be wide, and aspirin chemoprevention for BE has not been incorporated into BE guidelines. Another randomized trial compared the cyclo-oxygenase 2 (COX-2) inhibitor celecoxib (200 mg) with placebo in 100 patients with BE with either HGD or LGD. No benefit was found, but the trial was underpowered at only 100 patients.\n\n## Surveillance\n\nPatients with BE are routinely managed with regular endoscopic surveillance to monitor the BE disease, with the aim of detecting and treating dysplasia and EAC at an early curable stage. However, surveillance has not resulted in a substantial improvement in EAC outcomes over the last 50 years. This is likely due to the fact that most individuals with BE are undiagnosed in the community and thus not enrolled in surveillance. No randomized trials have reported on surveillance but an RCT is underway in the United Kingdom: the Barrett Oesophagus Surveillance versus endoscopy at need Study (BOSS). The one case-control study that has been reported by Corley et al. did not find evidence in support of the effectiveness of surveillance. This study included 8272 patients with BE and used data linkage between a large hospital database and the US Surveillance, Epidemiology, and End Results (SEER) Medicare database. The rates of receipt of surveillance between patients with known BE who died of EAC were compared with a matched sample of patients with BE who did not die of EAC, finding no improvement in EAC-related mortality associated with having undergone endoscopic surveillance within the previous 3 years.\n\nA systematic review and meta-analysis by Codipilly et al. in 2018 found that surveillance was associated with detection of EAC at earlier stages and may provide a small survival benefit. A meta-analysis of four cohort studies found that lower EAC-related and all-cause mortality were associated with regular surveillance (relative risk 0.60; 95% CI 0.50\u20130.71; hazard ratio 0.75; 95% CI 0.59\u20130.94). Meta-analysis of 12 cohort studies showed lower EAC-related and all-cause mortality among patients with surveillance-detected EAC versus symptom-detected EAC (relative risk 0.73; 95% CI 0.57\u20130.94; hazard ratio 0.59; 95% CI 0.45\u20130.76). The authors noted that lead- and length-time bias adjustment substantially attenuated or eliminated the observed benefits.\n\nOne study found that a majority of patients diagnosed with EAC at endoscopy had undergone a prior endoscopy within the previous year. These cancers were probably present at the earlier endoscopy, indicating the importance of a thorough endoscopy whenever BE is found, but also illustrating that EAC can progress very rapidly in some cases. BE endoscopy requires adequate inspection time. A significantly higher yield of endoscopically suspicious lesions when the mean inspection time was more than 1 minute per cm of BE (54.2%) compared with less than 1 minute (13.3%) was found in one study, with a trend towards a higher detection rate of HGD or EAC.\n\nUse of high-definition white light endoscopy (HD-WLE) is recommended, and guidelines also suggest using chromoendoscopy to improve detection rates. Chromoendoscopy is performed either by spraying a dye such as acetic acid, which requires equipment, additional time, and some expertise, or with virtual chromoendoscopy (VC). VC data are mostly for narrow-band imaging (NBI), which is very simple to use in comparison with dye-based chromoendoscopy as NBI is incorporated into most recent model gastroscopes.\n\nThe procedure for Barrett surveillance endoscopy includes defining the macroscopic GEJ, which in patients with BE is often the upper limit of a hiatus hernia. Desufflation may help to clearly define the GEJ at the upper margin of the gastric rugal folds. The extent of the Barrett\u2019s segment is then measured using the Prague classification for circumferential (C) and maximal (M) length. For example, a segment with 3-cm circumferential columnar mucosa and 1-cm Barrett\u2019s tongues is C3M4. Barrett\u2019s islands are often present above the circumferential BE or tongues but are not included in the Prague measurements. The location of lesions such as nodules or ulcers should be noted precisely and biopsied separately. Superficial neoplastic lesions can be described using the Paris classification.\n\nThe Seattle protocol uses four-quadrant biopsies of the BE every 1\u20132 cm and is recommended as it has been shown to detect Barrett neoplasia in more patients than non-systematic biopsies. Alternative biopsy strategies, such as molecular imaging to identify higher-risk areas within the BE segment, are needed to overcome problems with the four-quadrant system including frequent lack of adherence to protocol, cost, and the time required.\n\nMultiple guidelines for BE surveillance for NDBE (IM only), indefinite for dysplasia, and BE with LGD have been published: American Gastroenterology Association (AGA), American College of Gastroenterology (ACG), American Society of Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ASGE), British Society of Gastroenterology (BSG), <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> European Society for Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ESGE), and Australian guidelines. Fortunately, these guidelines or position statements share very similar recommendations. Confirmation of any dysplasia by a second pathologist with gastrointestinal pathology expertise is recommended.\n\n### Nondysplastic BE\n\nEndoscopic surveillance without intervention is the accepted management for NDBE (IM only), with intervals dependent upon the length of the BE segment. The time period over which NDBE has been diagnosed may also be a consideration. For long-segment BE, defined as \\> 3cm, the suggested surveillance interval is 3 years, whereas for short-segment BE (>1 cm, <3 cm), the interval is 5 years.\n\n### Indefinite for Dysplasia\n\nIn some cases, biopsies may be reported as indefinite for dysplasia, a finding that can occur with reflux-related inflammation. These patients should be placed on maximal acid suppression with a PPI and undergo repeat endoscopic evaluation in 6 months. Some data indicate an increased EAC risk for patients diagnosed with indefinite for dysplasia.\n\n### Low-Grade Dysplasia\n\nRepeat endoscopy at 6 months, followed by surveillance endoscopy every 6\u201312 months is recommended. As more accurate data become available regarding the EAC risk for LGD, the recommendation for either surveillance or treatment will become clearer. This risk is currently uncertain, as the reported rates of disease progression for LGD vary very widely as do surveillance intervals in practice.\n\n### High-Grade Dysplasia\n\nIntervention rather than surveillance is recommended after a diagnosis of HGD.\n\n## Newer Endoscopic Surveillance Methods\n\n### Wide-Area Transepithelial Sampling\n\nWide-area transepithelial sampling (WATS-3D) may be used as an adjunctive technique to Seattle protocol biopsies to increase the sensitivity of sampling. This method involves use of an abrasive brush to sample larger surface areas of the esophagus. Analysis of large sheets of cells while maintaining the three-dimensional aspects of the tissue is a reported advantage with this method. Software using convoluted neural networks identifies abnormal cells, which are subsequently confirmed by an expert pathologist using microscopy. A recent systematic review and meta-analysis of seven studies demonstrated an incremental yield for dysplasia detection of 7.2%. As such, the recent ASGE guidelines support the use of WATS-3D in addition to Seattle protocol in select patients (e.g., indeterminate for dysplasia or clinically high-risk NDBE) undergoing surveillance.\n\n### TissueCypher Pathology Assay\n\nTissueCypher is a tissue systems pathology assay that has become commercially available in the United States. It was shown to risk stratify patients with NDBE for progression to HGD/EAC with a 4.7-fold increased risk in patients stratified as high risk compared with those stratified as low risk. The assay is performed on routine biopsies from the Barrett\u2019s segment and quantifies nine protein-based biomarkers (p16, p53, AMACR, HER2, Cytokeratin 20, CD68, COX-2, HIF-1alpha, and CD45Ro), along with nuclear morphology and tissue architecture. To date, there have been five independent studies with a high specificity but low sensitivity for detecting likelihood of progression in patients with NDBE.\n\n### Confocal Laser Microendoscopy\n\nConfocal laser microendoscopy (CLM), also known as confocal laser endomicroscopy (CLE), is a technique that enables real-time microscopic imaging during endoscopy. The process relies on tissue illumination and subsequent detection of reflected fluorescent light passing through a confocal pinhole aperture. Tissue fluorescence is provided by contrast agents, primarily fluorescein injected intravenously. Two CLM endoscopic systems exist, one which is integrated into the distal tip of the endoscope (Optiscan, Optiscan Imaging Ltd., Melbourne) and the other which uses an external flexible probe that is passed through the working channel of the endoscope (Cellvizio, Mauna Kea Technologies, Paris). Both allow for magnification up to 1000\u00d7 greater than normal, with the Optiscan providing a depth of up to 250 microns. This may also enable evaluation for sub-squamous IM and dysplasia. In a recent multicenter trial, patients were randomized to HD-WLE examination with random biopsies every 2 cm or combined CLM and HD-WLE with targeted biopsies. The latter group had a per-patient sensitivity of 95%, specificity of 92%, and negative predictive value of 98%. There was a 2.7-fold increase in the diagnostic yield and a 4.8-fold decrease in the number of biopsies by using CLM and targeted biopsies.\n\n### Optical Coherence Tomography\n\nOptical coherence tomography (OCT) is an ultra-high-resolution device that encompasses a fiber-optic probe that can be inserted into the accessory port of the endoscope. It enables cross-sectional tissue images to be obtained as a result of the backscattering of light. The backscattered tissue light is combined with a reflected mirror source, and measurement of backscattering at different depths is obtained through alteration of mirror position. It is estimated that a scanning depth of 1\u20133mm is achieved. Using OCT to determine HGD and EAC in BE provided a sensitivity and specificity of 83% and 75%, respectively, in one study. A further study reported a sensitivity of 66% and specificity of 57% for the diagnosis of IM at the squamocolumnar junction on the basis of irregular architecture and good image penetration. However, there is a lack of standardized, validated criteria, added time to procedure, expense of the probes, variable endoscopic expertise, and limited speed of image processing.\n\n## Nonendoscopic Surveillance Methods\n\nSurveillance by endoscopy for BE is expensive, causes anxiety, not uncommonly causes minor adverse events, very rarely causes severe complications such as perforation, and is inconvenient for some patients. These factors have stimulated efforts to develop non-endoscopic, low- or non-invasive alternatives to endoscopic surveillance for individuals with known BE. Depending on test accuracy and cost, these may also have a role in population screening for BE\u2014screening those aged over 50 years with a history of GERD symptoms, for example, to detect new cases of BE.\n\nNon-endoscopic tests collect diagnostic samples using circulating blood, exhaled breath, or esophageal epithelium via an ingestible sponge-on-string (e.g., Cytosponge) or balloon-based sampling device. Although many studies have reported on blood biomarkers for either diagnosis or monitoring of EAC, with moderately accurate results for detecting advanced stage EAC in particular, relatively few studies have reported on diagnostic blood tests for BE. In 2018 Shah et al. described early validation phase data for a serum panel of 10 glycoprotein biomarkers for detecting HGD/EAC versus IM/LGD. Breath tests use electronic nose devices to detect volatile organic compounds (VOCs) as biomarkers for BE/EAC. Using a VOC BE prediction model, Peters et al. reported 91% sensitivity and 74% specificity for distinguishing between patients with and without BE in a study of 402 patients.\n\nMany swallowed sponge- or balloon-based device studies report on BE diagnosis, with variable results. Swallowing the device is unpleasant for many patients. Biomarkers investigated included Trefoil factor 3 (TFF3) and panels of abnormal DNA methylation, as well as cytology. In 2017 Ross-Innes et al. reported a multicenter cohort study in which 476 patients with BE underwent a swallowed sponge test (Cytosponge) prior to their surveillance endoscopy. Clinical and demographic data and sponge sample analysis for glandular atypia, three protein biomarkers (P53, c-Myc, Aurora kinase A), two methylation markers ( *MYOD1, RUNX3* ), and TP53 mutation were evaluated. A low-risk group with a 96.0% (99% CI 73.80\u201399.99) probability of having no dysplasia was identified, but a large minority of patients were classified as moderate risk, with either no dysplasia or HGD on histopathology. A recent (preprint, Moinova HR et al., 2023) report of a DNA methylation panel test using a swallowed balloon found an overall sensitivity for detecting all Barrett pathologies of 85% (95% CI 0.76\u20130.91) with specificity of 84% (95% CI 0.77\u20130.89). Sensitivity for short-segment BE was 76%. Severe gagging was the main patient complaint, but the test detected all (18/18, 100%) cancers.\n\n## Endoscopic Eradication Therapy (EET)\n\nEndoscopic eradication therapy (EET) for BE, including tissue resection and ablation, is recommended for dysplastic BE and early cancers. EETs are discussed in Chapter 29 . NDBE (IM without dysplasia) constitutes approximately 90% of the total BE population. Because the risk of progression to EAC in this subset of patients is only 0.12%\u20130.25% per annum, endoscopic therapy is not recommended. Rather, endoscopic surveillance is recommended as discussed above, with intervals dependent upon the length of the BE segment and time period over which the NDBE has been demonstrated.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Abrams J.A., Fields S., Lightdale C.J., Neugut A.I.: Racial and ethnic disparities in the prevalence of Barrett\u2019s esophagus among patients who undergo upper endoscopy . Clin Gastroenterol Hepatol 2008; 6 (1): pp. 30-34.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Eusebi L.H., Cirota G.G., Zagari R.M., Ford A.C.: Global prevalence of Barrett\u2019s oesophagus and oesophageal cancer in individuals with gastro-oesophageal reflux: a systematic review and meta-analysis . Gut 2021; 70 (3): pp. 456-463.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: Balasubramanian G., Gupta N., Giacchino M., et al.: Cigarette smoking is a modifiable risk factor for Barrett\u2019s oesophagus . United European Gastroenterol J 2013; 1 (6): pp. 430-437.\n\nView In Article\n\n4.: Cook M.B., Kamangar F., Whiteman D.C., et al.: Cigarette smoking and adenocarcinomas of the esophagus and esophagogastric junction: a pooled analysis from the international BEACON consortium . J Natl Cancer Inst 2010; 102 (17): pp. 1344-1353.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: Ness-Jensen E., Lindam A., Lagergren J., Hveem K.: Weight loss and reduction in gastroesophageal reflux. A prospective population-based cohort study: the HUNT study . Am J Gastroenterol 2013; 108 (3): pp. 376-382.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n: 5a. Kubo A., Levin TR., Block G., et al.: Dietary patterns and the risk of Barrett\u2019s esophagus . Am J Epidemiol 2008; 167 (7): pp. 839-846.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n6.: Bakr O., Zhao W., Corley D.: Gastroesophageal reflux frequency, severity, age of onset, family history and acid suppressive therapy predict Barrett esophagus in a large population . J Clin Gastroenterol 2018; 52 (10): pp. 873-879.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n7.: Lagergren J., Bergstrom R., Lindgren A., Nyren 