Factors', 'Management of Barrett''s Esophagus / Limiting Gastroesophageal Reflux', 'Management of Barrett''s Esophagus / Chemoprevention'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '26', '264-269', 2, 32, FALSE, TRUE),
('Medical and Surgical Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and Barrett’s Esophagus', 'shackelford-9th-ed-27-medical-and-surgical-therapy-for-gastroesophageal-reflux-disease-and-barretts-', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Medical and Surgical Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and Barrett\u2019s Esophagus\n\nJennifer M. Kolb; Sagar N. Shah; Kenneth J. Chang\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 27, 270-275\n\n## Introduction\n\nBarrett or Barrett\u2019s esophagus (BE) is characterized by the metaplastic transformation of stratified squamous epithelium to intestinal-type columnar epithelium in the distal esophagus as a result of chronic acid exposure. These histologic changes precede the development of esophageal adenocarcinoma (EAC), a cancer with a rising incidence in Western countries. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) occurs due to dysfunction of the antireflux barrier, made up of the lower esophageal sphincter and its sling fibers, the crural diaphragm, and the gastroesophageal flap valve. Disruption of this mechanism leads to reflux of acid as well as non-acid, or bilious gastric contents into the distal esophagus. This is the perfect set-up for the development of BE. Therefore, medical and surgical interventions that prevent esophageal acid exposure are critical aspects in BE prevention and management.\n\nAntiacid medications are first-line therapy for GERD for symptom control and to decrease esophageal acid exposure and prevent complications such as esophagitis, peptic stricture, and BE. Escalation to antireflux surgery (ARS) is suggested for individuals who have medication refractory symptoms, are medication averse, or have a significant anatomic defect causing regurgitation. These same principles apply to the patient with BE, with the added caveat that preventing esophageal acid exposure and enhancing the mechanical properties of the antireflux barrier may also help prevent progression to EAC. There are also several clinical scenarios where management of refractory GERD and BE may pose unique challenges. These include nonhealing erosive esophagitis precluding endoscopic eradication therapy (EET) for BE-related neoplasia and inability to eradicate dysplasia due to ongoing acid exposure. In this chapter, we review key aspects of decision-making along the continuum of medical and surgical management for individuals with GERD and BE ( Fig. 27.1 ).\n\nA flowchart depicts the progression from gastro-esophageal reflux disease to recurrent intestinal metaplasia or dysplasia with relevant conditions, treatment stages, and risk factors. The flowchart outlines the progression of conditions for medication-refractory symptoms. It highlights patient preference and abnormal esophageal acid exposure with optimal proton pump inhibitor therapy. It starts with gastroesophageal reflux disease. It moves through various stages, such as gastroesophageal reflux disease with Barrett esophagus, followed by Barrett esophagus-related neoplasia, endoscopic eradication therapy, complete eradication of intestinal metaplasia, and recurrent intestinal metaplasia or dysplasia. Each stage is linked with specific considerations, such as medication-refractory symptoms, patient preference, and abnormal esophageal acid exposure. Between Barrett esophagus-related neoplasia and endoscopic eradication therapy marks the presence of risk factors for disease refractory to endoscopic eradication. It also mentions hiatal hernia, long-segment Barrett''s, and advanced histology at diagnosis, esophagitis, or ulceration. Between endoscopic eradication therapy and complete eradication of intestinal metaplasia marks intestinal metaplasia or dysplasia refractory to endoscopic eradication therapy. Again, the same risk factors are included between complete eradication of intestinal metaplasia and recurrent intestinal metaplasia as in Barrett esophagus-related neoplasia and endoscopic eradication therapy.\n\nFig. 27.1\n\n## Medical Management of Barrett\u2019s Esophagus: Acid Suppression and Chemoprophylaxis\n\nThe mainstay of medical management for BE is acid suppression, and the main class of drugs used to achieve this are proton pump inhibitors (PPI). PPIs play a central role in acid suppression as well as preventing BE progression to dysplasia and cancer. Other agents have been evaluated for chemoprophylaxis, but there is insufficient data to support their use.\n\n### Acid Exposure and Carcinogenesis\n\nThe observed relationship between GERD and BE implicates acid exposure in the metaplastic transformation of normal epithelium and carcinogenesis. An *in vitro* study demonstrated that cultured Barrett\u2019s epithelial cells exposed to acid produce more reactive oxygen species and experience more double-stranded DNA breaks, accumulation of which promotes carcinogenesis. Additional studies indicate that acid exposure promotes dysregulated cellular proliferation and decreases apoptosis through the expression of cyclooxygenase-2 and activation of the protein kinase-C and mitogen-activated protein kinase pathways. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The pathogenic role of acid exposure therefore suggests that the acid-reducing effects of medications might exert their benefit by attenuating this form of damage. However, there is no direct evidence that acid suppression therapy *prevents* the development of BE.\n\n### Proton Pump Inhibitors to Reduce Progression of Neoplasia\n\nThe goal of acid-suppressing therapies is to raise the pH of gastric contents, thereby mitigating the consequences of reflux episodes. Thus far, PPIs remain the most potent and clinically efficacious agent to reduce esophageal acid exposure and improve heartburn symptoms. Meta-analyses of head-to-head trials of PPIs and H <sub>2 </sub> \\-receptor antagonist (H <sub>2 </sub> RA) therapy consistently show faster rates of healing with PPIs, greater symptom relief, and decreased esophageal acid exposure. If acid-induced epithelial injury leads to BE, it follows that acid suppression with PPIs may prevent such metaplasia. Indeed, a growing body of data provides indirect evidence that PPIs reduce the risk of progression to dysplasia or cancer for patients with BE. Two studies were performed at Veterans Affairs hospitals to evaluate this association between PPI use and BE progression to neoplasia. The first study included a cohort of 236 Veterans with BE (with and without dysplasia) over a 10-year study period, and found that those who took PPI had a 75% reduction in the risk of progression to dysplasia compared with those taking no medication or H <sub>2 </sub> RAs. The second study also evaluated prescription records for 344 veterans with BE and found that an active prescription for PPIs was associated with a reduced risk of developing high-grade dysplasia (HGD) or EAC (HR 0.43, 95% CI: 0.21\u20130.83). The protective effects of PPIs for established BE has also been demonstrated in multicenter, prospective cohort studies. Kastelein et al. evaluated data from 540 patients and found that having a dispensed PPI prescription was associated with a 60% reduced risk of progression to HGD/EAC during 5-year follow-up when adjusted for sex, age at BE diagnosis, and BE length. Finally, a large meta-analysis encompassing 12 studies and >150,000 patients found that PPI use was associated with a 53% reduction in risk of BE progression to HGD/EAC. Accordingly, the American College of Gastroenterology suggests at least once-a-day PPI therapy in patients with BE without contraindication to its use (conditional recommendation, very low-quality evidence).\n\n### Acid-Independent Effects of Proton Pump Inhibitors\n\nThe efficacy of PPIs may also be explained by their acid-independent effects. IL-8 is a cytokine that plays a major role in the inflammatory response and facilitates migration of inflammatory cells into areas of infection. The presence of omeprazole reduced the expression of IL-8 mRNA and activation of the IL-8 promoter when Barrett epithelial cells were exposed to acid. Similarly, PPIs have been shown to increase production of heme-oxygenase 1, an antioxidant, *in vitro* , independent of any effect on H+/K+ ATPase inhibition. Importantly, these effects occur independent of the drug action on gastric parietal cells. Such modulation of the local inflammatory milieu may provide added anti-metaplastic and anti-neoplastic protection.\n\nIt should be mentioned that although some patients may have concern regarding long-term PPI use, observational data supporting associations with adverse events are fraught with confounding. In the available, large-scale, experimental studies, no increased risk for cardiovascular disease, kidney disease, dementia, pneumonia, fracture, and all-cause mortality has been demonstrated.\n\nA proposed explanation for the limited utility of antiacid medications in preventing BE is the role of bile acids (BAs) in the pathogenesis of BE, specifically their connection to the emergence and progression of BE. Although PPIs may reduce the volume of BA reflux into the esophagus, some studies suggest that PPIs could even magnify the pathologic effects of BA reflux. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Although there are no medications to control BA reflux, it is thought that surgical antireflux measures might control them through mechanical barriers the same way they control acid.\n\n### Chemoprophylaxis for Barrett\u2019s Esophagus\n\nAdditional antiinflammatory medications may play a role in chemoprophylaxis for BE. For example, evaluation of esophageal biopsies has demonstrated greater COX-2 protein expression in patients with Barrett metaplasia, dysplasia, and adenocarcinoma than in patients with normal esophageal epithelium, implicating the pathogenic role of prostaglandin-mediated inflammation. Furthermore, *in vitro* data suggests that COX-2-selective inhibitors can reduce the proliferation of Barrett epithelium, an effect reversed by the addition of exogenous prostaglandins. Although the Aspirin and Esomeprazole Chemoprevention in Barrett metaplasia Trial (AspECT) trial demonstrated an additive effect of aspirin in combination with PPI for the reduction of a combined endpoint of all-cause mortality, EAC, and HGD, results from other studies evaluating selective and nonselective NSAIDs have been highly variable. Statins are another class of agents with antiproliferative pro-apoptotic effects in Barrett epithelium. A meta-analysis of 11 observational studies evaluating the effect of statin therapy on EAC incidence among patients with BE demonstrated a meaningful reduction in the odds of BE progression (OR 0.54, 95% CI 0.46\u20130.63) with no heterogeneity in the analysis, though not all studies adjusted for known confounding factors (e.g., obesity, smoking, sex). Despite compelling and provocative data, at the present time there is insufficient evidence to recommend any medication as true chemoprophylaxis for BE. PPIs, however, do continue to play a central role in controlling symptoms, reducing esophageal acid exposure, and theoretically preventing progression to neoplasia, though no randomized controlled studies have demonstrated this.\n\n## Surgical Management of Barrett Esophagus\n\nThe main goal of ARS in patients with BE is the same as that in patients without BE\u2014symptom control and correction of an anatomic defect such as hiatal hernia. Similar to the proposed benefit of PPIs, ARS may prevent progression of BE by controlling acid. In addition, we will discuss two unique clinical scenarios where ARS may serve a distinct role: (1) patients with disease refractory to EET and (2) patients at high-risk of recurrence following successful EET.\n\n### Antireflux Surgery to Prevent Progression of Neoplasia\n\nData pertaining to the utility of ARS to prevent neoplastic progression of BE is heterogenous. There is an abundance of observational studies in the surgical literature that demonstrate varying rates of BE regression and progression after ARS. In a cohort study of 91 patients with symptomatic GERD and BE, 36.4% of patients achieved complete remission of intestinal metaplasia (CR-IM) following ARS, compared with 7.1% of 14 patients receiving medical therapy. In the surgical group, regression was seen in 28 patients (17 low-grade dysplasia \\[LGD\\] \u2192 non-dysplastic BE \\[NDBE\\], 11 NDBE \u2192 normal squamous epithelium) and 8 progressed (5 \u2192 LGD, 3 \u2192 HGD). Zaninotto et al. compared a cohort of 45 patients with NDBE undergoing ARS to 44 patients with NDBE treated with medication alone and demonstrated higher rates of regression for those undergoing surgery (40% vs. 16%; *P* \\=.04). Though the overall CR-IM rates in both of these studies were low, these investigations provided solid preliminary evidence for the utility of ARS for the management of BE. The most recent systematic review and meta-analysis, performed in 2016, identified a total of 10 studies comparing EAC risk between patients undergoing ARS and those receiving medical treatment. The authors found the risk of progression to EAC to be lower in patients receiving ARS than in patients receiving medical management for BE. The meta-analysis did not find a significant difference between progression to EAC when comparing those patients receiving ARS and all patients with GERD (regardless of the presence of BE). Notably, PPI compliance is not consistently documented in these studies\u2014medically managed patients may not have received optimal PPI therapy and surgical patients may have continued acid-suppressing medications. A randomized controlled trial comparing Nissen fundoplication with medical treatment provides compelling evidence to support surgery; however, the trial was not powered to detect a difference in progression rates and results were not significant. In the medical treatment group, *de novo* dysplasia appeared in 8 of the 40 patients (20%), and 2 developed HGD. In the surgery group, *de novo* dysplasia appeared in 3 of the 53 patients (6%), and 2 developed HGD. Given these limitations in the existing literature, combined with both the low risk of progression to EAC and the significance of undergoing a surgical fundoplication, the American College of Gastroenterology guidelines currently recommend against the routine use of ARS before medical optimization to prevent BE progression.\n\nThere are, however, select clinical scenarios in which ARS *should* be strongly considered for the ablation refractory patient who is unable to achieve CR-IM and for patients at high risk of recurrence following successful EET and CR-IM.\n\n### Ongoing Acid Exposure May Prevent Barrett\u2019s Esophagus Eradication\n\nEET revolutionized our approach to the management of dysplasia and early EAC, providing a minimally invasive, organ-sparing, safe, and effective option for management of Barrett neoplasia. EET consists of endoscopic mucosal resection of nodular or visible BE neoplasia followed by ablation of flat dysplasia. The goal of EET is to achieve CR-IM, defined as absence of dysplasia and intestinal metaplasia on two consecutive endoscopies. A second endpoint is complete remission of dysplasia (CR-D). There is ample evidence to support the efficacy of EET. In a systematic review and meta-analysis, Desai et al. found that 95.9% and 90.9% of patients with HGD or superficial EAC achieved CR-IM and CR-D, respectively, following EET.\n\nNevertheless, failure to achieve CR-IM remains an issue in about 10% of patients undergoing EET. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Patients are generally deemed refractory to EET when repeated ablative treatment fails, though the number of treatments required for this designation varies across the literature. Common definitions used in studies evaluating refractory BE include persistent IM after three or four radiofrequency ablation (RFA) sessions or persistence of dysplasia after three RFA sessions. Alternative ablative modalities such as hybrid argon plasma coagulation (H-APC) <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> and cryotherapy <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> can be utilized when conventional RFA fails. A large proportion of patients that experience treatment failure have ongoing acid exposure, which precludes healing between ablative sessions and prevents neo-squamous regeneration. For example, a patient with a large hiatal hernia and severe erosive esophagitis may never achieve CR-IM despite maximal acid suppression. In these scenarios, early escalation to ARS may be necessary.\n\n### Antireflux Surgery for Patients With Barrett\u2019s Esophagus Refractory to Endoscopic Eradication Therapy\n\nKomanduri et al. describe a stepwise approach to address EET refractory patients that presumes the mechanism of failure is insufficient acid control. They implemented a structured antireflux management protocol for individuals with dysplastic BE who failed to achieve CR-IM after three RFA sessions. This included (1) optimization of PPI therapy (timing, dosage); (2) on-treatment reflux testing; and (3) ARS for abnormal reflux testing after PPI optimization. In this prospective cohort study of 48 patients refractory after three RFA sessions, 45 (93.8%) achieved CR-IM with one additional RFA session *after* completion of ARS ( *n* \\= 39) or PPI optimization ( *n* \\= 9). Importantly, 93% of patients who completed pH impedance after failing to achieve CR-IM had abnormal distal esophageal acid exposure or >60 total reflux events. Similar results have been published in the surgical literature. Johnson et al. retrospectively reviewed 49 patients undergoing EET of whom 23 failed to achieve CR-IM. After surgical fundoplication, 10/16 patients who had initially reached CR-D achieved CR-IM and 4/7 with persistent dysplasia achieved CR-IM with an additional mean 2.5 RFA sessions. Notably, the authors do not pre-specify a definition of EET failure and patients were considered refractory based on the treating physician\u2019s discretion. These data implicate ongoing acid exposure as a major contributor for failure to achieve CR-IM and suggest that refractory patients should be medically optimized with antiacid therapy, undergo reflux testing to determine if medications are providing adequate control, and be considered for ARS. There may also be a rationale for up front surgery prior to EET in patients at high risk for treatment failure, such as long-segment BE (>9 cm), advanced baseline histology, thicker/indurated mucosa, and poor squamous epithelialization after RFA, though data to support this are limited.\n\n### Antireflux Surgery to Prevent Recurrence After Successful Endoscopic Eradication Therapy and Complete Remission of Intestinal Metaplasia\n\nDespite the excellent outcomes of EET and high rates of CR-IM, long-term durability remains a limitation and ongoing surveillance is required to detect recurrence. The definition of recurrence varies somewhat in the literature but is generally defined as new IM or dysplasia that occurs after completion of EET (defined as absence of IM and/or dysplasia on one or two consecutive endoscopies). Several large cohort studies report the incidence of recurrent IM at 4.9\u201310.8/100 person-year and recurrent dysplasia 1\u20132.8/100 person-year. Recurrent disease is associated with long-segment BE and higher initial histologic grade. Ongoing acid exposure is an additional suspected driver of recurrence. Komanduri et al. group also reported lower recurrence rates using the previously described antireflux protocol of medication optimization, reflux testing, and ARS (4.8% vs. 10.9% recurrent IM). Additional data supports this idea that the presence and size of a hiatal hernia increases the risk of recurrence following CR-IM. In a cohort of 807 patients achieving CR-IM, the presence of a hiatal hernia and the length of the hiatal hernia were associated with greater odds of recurrence (adjusted OR \\[aOR\\] 13.8, 95% CI: 3.4\u201356.3 and aOR 2.3, 95% CI: 1.3\u20134.2). Fundoplication was not associated with a reduced risk of neoplastic progression; however, the presence of GERD symptoms at the time of EET was associated with greater odds of recurrence (aOR, 12.1, 95% CI: 4.3\u201334.1). The presence of a hiatal hernia raises the likelihood of persistent acid exposure as the integrity of the antireflux barrier has been compromised. As these patients with BE have lower success rates with ablation and greater risk for recurrence post CR-IM, it may be prudent to refer these individuals to surgery as they may benefit from an anatomic intervention.\n\n### Antireflux Surgery for the Prevention of Barrett\u2019s Esophagus\n\nThere is limited evidence to support performing ARS specifically to prevent BE. \u00d6berg et al. found that patients who underwent ARS were 10.3 times less likely to develop IM compared with patients receiving standard medical therapy. Notably, the authors did not describe the types of ARS performed in the surgical cohort, nor did they provide definitions of \u201cstandard medical therapy\u201d and medication adherence. A second study prospectively compared between 83 patients with GERD treated with medical therapy and 42 patients undergoing ARS after failure or discontinuation of medical therapy. After 2years of follow-up, 14.5% of patients on medical therapy developed BE compared with no patients who had ARS (Nissen or posterior fundoplication). Interpretation of these results is limited by the fact that patients in the medical treatment group did not receive up-titration of PPIs to maximal dosing by today\u2019s standard. Even though these studies suggest a possible benefit from ARS that cannot be achieved with medications, there is no role for performing an invasive surgical intervention as prophylaxis against BE.\n\n### Unique Considerations for Endoscopic or Surgical Antireflux Therapies in the Patient with Barrett\u2019s Esophagus\n\nThere is a growing armamentarium of endoscopic and surgical antireflux interventions, though there are no comparative trials examining outcomes specifically in BE cohorts. Decision-making regarding the optimal therapy should be patient centered (in line with patient preferences), symptom driven, and based on clinical and anatomic features. A few key points should be considered in the patient with GERD/BE undergoing EET and ARS. In the last 70 years, many variations and modifications of the original surgical fundoplication described by Nissen have also been developed. While no one surgical approach is considered \u201cbest\u201d for the management of GERD and concomitant BE, it is thought that this cohort of patients have the phenotype of a severely incompetent antireflux barrier and therefore might benefit from a more aggressive surgical intervention such as a Nissen fundoplication. On the contrary, there has been some concern that a full wrap may bury or obscure part of the BE segment and impact future surveillance efforts, though this has largely been rebuked. Transoral incisionless fundoplication (TIF) with or without concomitant laparoscopic hiatal hernia repair (cTIF) is an endoscopic technique intended to recreate the gastroesophageal flap valve using full-thickness plications. Polypropylene T-fasteners are used to secure the wrap in place and may be susceptible to damage from heat. Therefore, we would avoid TIF/cTIF in a patient with BE who has an anticipated need for ablation. Roux-en-Y gastric bypass as a treatment for GERD and BE has been also shown to provide excellent regression of BE.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe management of BE has evolved dramatically with the refinement of many impactful medical, endoscopic, and surgical options to interrupt this premalignant cascade. The goal in BE treatment is to prevent progression to neoplasia and EAC. A key pillar in this effort is control of distal esophageal acid exposure through medications and ARS, as appropriate. Recognition of key points along the GERD and BE treatment continuum for step-up to more aggressive approaches is emphasized. Collaborative efforts between gastroenterologists and foregut surgeons are critical to determine the indications and timing for medical and surgical interventions in BE at all points in their care.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Kolb J.M., Fox C., Friedman C., et al.: Prognostic impact of the presence of Barrett\u2019s esophagus and intestinal metaplasia on esophageal adenocarcinoma survival . Foregut 2021; 263451612110332 .\n\nView In Article\n\n2.: Kolb J.M., Han S., Scott F.I., et al.: Early-onset esophageal adenocarcinoma presents with advanced-stage disease but has improved survival compared with older individuals . Gastroenterology 2020; 159 (6): pp. 2238-2240.e4.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: Nguyen N.T., Thosani N.C., Canto M.I., et al.: The American Foregut Society white paper on the endoscopic classification of esophagogastric junction integrity . Foregut: The Journal of the American Foregut Society 2022; 263451612211269 .\n\nView In Article\n\n4.: Zhang H.Y., Hormi-Carver K., Zhang X., Spechler S.J., Souza R.F.: In benign Barrett\u2019s epithelial cells, acid exposure generates reactive oxygen species that cause DNA double-strand breaks . Cancer Res 2009; 69 (23): pp. 9083-9089.\n\nView In Article\n\n5.: Fitzgerald R.C., Omary M.B., Triadafilopoulos G.: Dynamic effects of acid on Barrett\u2019s esophagus. An ex vivo proliferation and differentiation model . J Clin Invest 1996; 98 (9): pp. 2120-2128.\n\nView In Article\n\n6.: Souza R.F., Shewmake K., Terada L.S., Spechler S.J.: Acid exposure activates the mitogen-activated protein kinase pathways in Barrett\u2019s esophagus . Gastroenterology 2002; 122 (2): pp. 299-307.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n7.: Tofil N.M., Benner K.W., Fuller M.P., Winkler M.K.: Histamine 2 receptor antagonists vs intravenous proton pump in