urg 2011; 142 (5): pp. 1152-1160.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n31.: Thomas T., Loke Y., Beales I.L.P.: Systematic review and meta-analysis: use of statins is associated with a reduced incidence of oesophageal adenocarcinoma . J Gastrointest Canc 2018; 49 (4): pp. 442-454.\n\nView In Article\n\n32.: Gurski R.R., Peters J.H., Hagen J.A., et al.: Barrett\u2019s esophagus can and does regress after antireflux surgery: a study of prevalence and predictive features . J Am Coll Surg 2003; 196 (5): pp. 706-712.\n\nView In Article\n\n33.: Zaninotto G., Parente P., Salvador R., et al.: Long-term follow-up of Barrett\u2019s epithelium: medical versus antireflux surgical therapy . J Gastrointest Surg 2012; 16 (1): pp. 7-15.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n34.: Maret-Ouda J., Konings P., Lagergren J., Brusselaers N.: Antireflux surgery and risk of esophageal adenocarcinoma: a systematic review and meta-analysis . Ann Surg 2016; 263 (2): pp. 251-257.\n\nView In Article\n\n35.: Parrilla P., Mart\u00ednez de Haro L.F., Ortiz A., et al.: Long-term results of a randomized prospective study comparing medical and surgical treatment of Barrett\u2019s esophagus . Ann Surg 2003; 237 (3): pp. 291-298.\n\nView In Article\n\n36.: Shah S.N., Kolb J.M.: Today\u2019s toolbox for Barrett\u2019s endotherapy . Techniques and Innovations in Gastrointestinal Endoscopy 2023; 25 (2): pp. 167-176.\n\nView In Article\n\n37.: Desai M., R\u00f6sch T., Sundaram S., et al.: Systematic review with meta\u2010analysis: the long\u2010term efficacy of Barrett\u2019s endoscopic therapy\u2014stringent selection criteria and a proposal for definitions . Aliment Pharmacol Ther 2021; 54 (3): pp. 222-233.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n38.: Phoa K.N., Pouw R.E., Bisschops R., et al.: Multimodality endoscopic eradication for neoplastic Barrett oesophagus: results of an European multicentre study (EURO-II) . Gut 2016; 65 (4): pp. 555-562.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n39.: Sengupta N., Ketwaroo G.A., Bak D.M., et al.: Salvage cryotherapy after failed radiofrequency ablation for Barrett\u2019s esophagus\u2013related dysplasia is safe and effective . Gastrointest Endosc 2015; 82 (3): pp. 443-448.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n40.: Komanduri S., Kahrilas P.J., Krishnan K., et al.: Recurrence of Barrett\u2019s esophagus is rare following endoscopic eradication therapy coupled with effective reflux control . Am J Gastroenterol 2017; 112 (4): pp. 556-566.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n41.: Trindade A.J., Inamdar S., Kothari S., Berkowitz J., McKinley M., Kaul V.: Feasibility of liquid nitrogen cryotherapy after failed radiofrequency ablation for Barrett\u2019s esophagus . Dig Endosc 2017; 29 (6): pp. 680-685.\n\nView In Article\n\n42.: Akiyama J., Marcus S.N., Triadafilopoulos G.: Effective intra-esophageal acid control is associated with improved radiofrequency ablation outcomes in Barrett\u2019s esophagus . Dig Dis Sci 2012; 57 (10): pp. 2625-2632.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n43.: Johnson C.S., Louie B.E., Wille A., et al.: The durability of endoscopic therapy for treatment of Barrett\u2019s metaplasia, dysplasia, and mucosal cancer after Nissen fundoplication . J Gastrointest Surg 2015; 19 (5): pp. 799-805.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n44.: Van Munster S.N., Nieuwenhuis E., Bisschops R., et al.: Development and external validation of a model to predict complex treatment after radiofrequency ablation for Barrett\u2019s esophagus with early neoplasia . Clin Gastroenterol Hepatol 2022; 20 (11): pp. 2495-2504.e5.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n45.: van Munster S., Nieuwenhuis E., Weusten B.L.A.M., et al.: Long-term outcomes after endoscopic treatment for Barrett\u2019s neoplasia with radiofrequency ablation \u00b1 endoscopic resection: results from the national Dutch database in a 10-year period . Gut 2022; 71 (2): pp. 265-276.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n46.: Tan M.C., Kanthasamy K.A., Yeh A.G., et al.: Factors associated with recurrence of Barrett\u2019s esophagus after radiofrequency ablation . Clin Gastroenterol Hepatol 2019; 17 (1): pp. 65-72.e5.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n47.: Krishnamoorthi R., Singh S., Ragunathan K., et al.: Factors associated with progression of Barrett\u2019s esophagus: a systematic review and meta-analysis . Clin Gastroenterol Hepatol 2018; 16 (7): pp. 1046-1055.e8.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n48.: Fujii-Lau L., Cinnor B., Shaheen N., et al.: Recurrence of intestinal metaplasia and early neoplasia after endoscopic eradication therapy for Barrett\u2019s esophagus: a systematic review and meta-analysis . Endosc Int Open 2017; 05 (06): pp. E430-E449.\n\nView In Article\n\n49.: Sami S.S., Ravindran A., Kahn A., et al.: Timeline and location of recurrence following successful ablation in Barrett\u2019s oesophagus: an international multicentre study . Gut 2019; 68 (8): pp. 1379-1385.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n50.: Guthikonda A., Cotton C.C., Madanick R.D., et al.: Clinical outcomes following recurrence of intestinal metaplasia after successful treatment of Barrett\u2019s esophagus with radiofrequency ablation . Am J Gastroenterol 2017; 112 (1): pp. 87-94.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n51.: Wani S., Han S., Kushnir V., et al.: Recurrence is rare following complete eradication of intestinal metaplasia in patients with Barrett\u2019s esophagus and peaks at 18 months . Clin Gastroenterol Hepatol 2020; 18 (11): pp. 2609-2617.e2.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n52.: \u00d6berg S., Johansson J., Wenner J., et al.: Endoscopic surveillance of columnar-lined esophagus: frequency of intestinal metaplasia detection and impact of antireflux surgery . Ann Surg 2001; 234 (5): pp. 619-626.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n53.: Wetscher G.J., Gadenstaetter M., Klingler P.J., et al.: Efficacy of medical therapy and antireflux surgery to prevent Barrett\u2019s metaplasia in patients with gastroesophageal reflux disease . Ann Surg 2001; 234 (5): pp. 627-632.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\nPrevious ChapterGo to the previous chapter\n\nNext ChapterGo to the next chapter\n\n\n\n## Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract\n\nNinth Edition\n\nCopyright \u00a9 2026 by Elsevier Inc. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies.\n\n## Get rights and content\u00a0\n\n##\n\n281240\n\n  - Google Play - Go to our Google Play page\n  - Apple App Store - Go to our Apple App Store page\n  - Facebook - Go to our Facebook page\n  - LinkedIn - Go to our LinkedIn page\n  - X - Go to our X page\n\nElsevier (opens in a new window)\n\n  - Contact Us (opens in a new window)\n  - Resource Center (opens in a new window)\n  - Registered User Agreement (opens in a new window)\n  - Help (opens in a new window)\n  - Terms & Conditions (opens in a new window)\n  - Privacy Policy (opens in a new window)\n  - Accessibility (opens in a new window)\n\nWe use cookies to help provide and enhance our service and tailor content. By continuing you agree to the .\n\nAll content on this site: Copyright \u00a9 2025 Elsevier Inc. or its licensors and contributors. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies. For all open access content, the relevant licensing terms apply.\n\n RELX''%20d=''M20.7%2023.4c11%200%2024.2-2.6%2024.2-13.1C44.9%202.8%2037.2%200%2030.3%200%2019.6%200%200%206%200%2027c0%2010.5%208%2016.6%2020.8%2016.6%2013.5%200%2023.2-8.8%2026.2-20.5C39.1%2036.7%2029%2041%2021%2041%2010.7%2041%206.8%2033.4%206.8%2027%205.869%2013.417%2016.685%201.91%2030.3%202c6.1%200%209.7%204%209.7%208.3%200%2011.9-17.2%2011.5-25%2011.5h-3.8l-1.6%201.8c3.6.5%208.5%201.5%2014%204.2%2011.1%205.6%2021.7%2020.6%2035.6%2020.6%205%200%206.4-1.6%207.4-3-6.9%204.4-18.3-3.1-24.5-9-5-4.8-9.6-10.2-21.4-13.1''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23e9711c''/%3e%3cpath%20clip-path=''url(%23b)''%20d=''M89.3%2043.6c-.5%200-.7-.2-.8-.6l-7-14.5h-6.1c-.2%200-.3.1-.3.3V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.6.6h-5.1c-.4%200-.6-.3-.6-.6V7c0-.4.2-.6.6-.6h13.9c6.6%200%2011.5%204.6%2011.5%2011.1%200%205-2.7%208.7-6.9%2010.3L95.5%2043c.2.3%200%20.7-.4.7h-5.8zm-.7-26.2c0-3.2-2.2-5.3-5.5-5.3h-7.7c-.2%200-.3.1-.3.4v9.9c0%20.2%200%20.3.3.3H83c3.3%200%205.5-2%205.5-5.3M101%206.9c0-.4.3-.6.6-.6h21.8c.4%200%20.6.2.6.6v4.7c0%20.3-.2.5-.6.5h-15.8c-.2%200-.3.1-.3.4v9c0%20.3.1.4.3.4h12.7c.4%200%20.6.2.6.5v4.7c0%20.4-.2.6-.6.6h-12.7c-.2%200-.3%200-.3.3v9.4c0%20.3.1.4.3.4h15.8c.4%200%20.6.2.6.5V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.6.6h-21.8c-.3%200-.6-.3-.6-.6V7zm28.8%200c0-.4.2-.6.5-.6h5.2c.3%200%20.6.2.6.6v30.5c0%20.3%200%20.4.3.4H151c.3%200%20.5.2.5.5V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.5.6h-20.8c-.3%200-.517-.3-.5-.6V7zm47.7%2036.7c-.4%200-.6-.2-.8-.5l-7.3-12.7-7.4%2012.7c-.2.3-.4.5-.8.5h-5.8c-.3%200-.5-.3-.3-.7L166%2024.3%20156%207.1c-.2-.4%200-.7.3-.7h5.8c.4%200%20.6.1.8.5l6.5%2011.3h.1L176%206.9c.2-.4.5-.5.9-.5h5.7c.4%200%20.5.3.3.7l-10%2017.2L183.7%2043c.2.4%200%20.7-.3.7h-5.8zM192.015%2019c-.2%200-.338-.004-.3-.2V8.4h-3.3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[26. Management of Barrett\u2019s Esophagus - ClinicalKey|26. Management of Barrett\u2019s Esophagus]]\n**Next:** [[28. Epidemiology, Risk Factors, and Clinical Manifestations of Esophageal Cancer - ClinicalKey|28. Epidemiology, Risk Factors, and Clinical Manifestations of Esophageal Cancer]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "27. Medical and Surgical Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and Barrett\u2019s Esophagus - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Medical and Surgical Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and Barrett’s Esophagus', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Medical and Surgical Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and Barrett''s Esophagus', 'Medical Management of Barrett''s Esophagus: Acid Suppression and Chemoprophylaxis', 'Surgical Management of Barrett Esophagus', 'Acid Exposure and Carcinogenesis', 'Proton Pump Inhibitors to Reduce Progression of Neoplasia', 'Acid-Independent Effects of Proton Pump Inhibitors', 'Medical and Surgical Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and Barrett''s Esophagus / Medical Management of Barrett''s Esophagus: Acid Suppression and Chemoprophylaxis', 'Medical and Surgical Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and Barrett''s Esophagus / Surgical Management of Barrett Esophagus', 'Medical and Surgical Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and Barrett''s Esophagus / Acid Exposure and Carcinogenesis'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '27', '270-275', 2, 28, FALSE, TRUE),
('Epidemiology, Risk Factors, and Clinical Manifestations of Esophageal Cancer', 'shackelford-9th-ed-28-epidemiology-risk-factors-and-clinical-manifestations-of-esophageal-cancer', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Epidemiology, Risk Factors, and Clinical Manifestations of Esophageal Cancer\n\nLuke Meredith; Francesco Palazzo; Talar Tatarian\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 28, 277-283\n\nEsophageal cancer accounts for 1.1% of new cancer diagnoses in the United States annually and 2.7% of cancer-related deaths. An estimated 0.5% of men and women will be diagnosed with esophageal cancer during their lifetime. The two most common subtypes of primary esophageal cancer include esophageal adenocarcinoma (EAC) and esophageal squamous cell carcinoma (ESCC). These differ tremendously in their natural history, epidemiologic pattern, and risk factors. ESCC arises from the native squamous epithelium of the esophagus. Chronic inflammation due to environmental exposures causes progression to dysplasia and eventually malignant change. EAC typically arises in areas of the esophagus where the squamous epithelium is replaced by columnar-lined metaplastic epithelium (Barrett\u2019s esophagus), usually due to the presence of gastroesophageal reflux.\n\nThis chapter reviews the epidemiologic pattern, risk factors, and clinical manifestations of esophageal cancer and its histologic subtypes.\n\n## Epidemiology\n\n### Incidence\n\nIn 2023, an estimated 21,560 people were diagnosed with esophageal cancer in the United States alone. Worldwide, over 600,000 people are diagnosed annually. Beginning in the late 20th century, there has been a major shift in the incidence of esophageal cancer worldwide and in the United States with trends differing by histologic subtype. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nIn the United States, the overall incidence of esophageal cancer has decreased to an average of 1.1% per year from 2010 to 2019 ( Fig. 28.1 ). The most recent Surveillance Epidemiology, and End Results (SEER) data estimate 4.2 new cases annually per 100,000 men and women. Across all races, EAC is the most common histologic subtype in the United States and Europe.\n\nA line graph that plots the comparison of incidence and mortality rates over time. The line graph displays the incidence and mortality rates per 100,000 people from 1975 to 2020. Diamonds represent the incidence rate, and triangles show the mortality rate. Both rates started at a similar level in 1975, with the incidence rate steadily in the increment phase. Mortality initially rose but then decreased slightly after 2005. The data reveals that the incidence rate has been consistently higher than the mortality rate throughout the period and gradually declined by 2020.\n\nFig. 28.1\n\nFrom 1992 to 2019, SEER data shows that EAC incidence increased 5.17% from 1992 to 2000 followed by a plateau in incidence from 2000 to 2019 with an annual percent change (APC) of 0.22%. ESCC has shown a linear decline since 1992 with an average annual percent change (AAPC) of\u20132.85%. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nWorldwide, the incidence of esophageal cancer varies significantly by region and histologic subtype, with ESCC accounting for 85% of cases overall. However, in North America, Australia, and Europe, EAC is the predominant subtype, accounting for 70% of cases. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The highest-risk region, referred to unofficially as the *esophageal cancer belt* , extends from the Middle East to Northeast China. On a global scale, Eastern Asia carries the greatest burden of esophageal cancer, with 53.7% of cases worldwide occurring in China alone. The highest age-adjusted rates of esophageal cancer occur in Malawi, Mongolia, Bangladesh, China, and Kenya (17.5, 17.1, 14.8, 13.8, and 12.7 per 100,000 people, respectively). The lowest rates are seen in Western and Central Africa and Central America. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nA recent review of esophageal cancer epidemiology presented projections of esophageal cancer prevalence in 2030 and 2040. The projections were calculated based on recent rates of esophageal cancer multiplied by the projected population growth. Based on these calculations, 739,666 new cases in 2030 and 987,723 new cases in 2040 are projected. Along with the new cases, 723,446 deaths in 2030 and 914,304 deaths in 2040 are anticipated. The review suggests that due to the aging population of the world along with the prevalence of known risk factors, these projections are very likely to be reached. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Mortality and Prognosis of Patients with Esophageal Cancer\n\nEsophageal cancer is the 6th leading cause of cancer-related death in the world and the 11th leading cause in the United States. It accounted for an estimated 16,410 deaths in the United States in 2022. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nThe death rate has declined in recent decades, with a death rate of 4.4 per 100,000 person-years in 2000 which decreased to 3.7 in 2020. Across all races, the death rate is approximately five times higher in men than in women. The overall 5-year survival rate has increased from 4% in the 1970s to 20.6% in 2020. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Improved prognosis is seen in patients with localized disease. However, only 18% of patients are found to have localized disease at diagnosis, while 33% have spread to regional lymph nodes, and 39% have metastatic cancer. The 5-year survival rate in the United States for localized, regional, and metastatic disease at diagnosis are 47%, 26%, and 5%, respectively ( Table 28.1 ).\n\nTable 28.1\n\nStage Distribution at Diagnosis and Respective 5-Year Relative Survival\n\n| Stage at Diagnosis | Stage Distribution (%) | 5-year Relative Survival (%) |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Localized (confined to primary site) | 18 | 47.3 |\n| Regional (spread to regional lymph nodes) | 33 | 26.3 |\n| Distant (cancer has metastasized) | 39 | 5.7 |\n| Unknown (unstaged) | 10 | 13.4 |\n\n### Age, Sex, and Race Distribution\n\nEsophageal cancer is more common with increased age. In the United States, about 90% of cases occur in persons over the age of 55. One-third of people diagnosed are between the ages of 65 and 74, with a median age at diagnosis of 68. Globally, it has a male preponderance, with males being affected about twice as often as females. Across races, substantial differences are seen in the incidence of esophageal cancer and the distribution of the histologic subtypes. In the United States, the age-adjusted incidence rate of esophageal cancer is highest in White and Black males (8.4 and 5.7 per 100,000 people, respectively) and lowest in females of Asian/Pacific Islander and Hispanic descent (1.0 and 1.1 per 100,000 people, respectively). In the early 2000s, American Black males experienced the greatest decrease worldwide in the rate of ESCC, although the rate for this subtype of esophageal cancer remains higher than in White males ( Fig. 28.2 ).\n\nA line graph plots the incidence of a specific condition per 100,000 people by gender and race from 1975 to 2015. The line graph compares the incidence rate per 100,000 people over time from 1975 to 2015. The y-axis represents the incidence per 100,000 people, and the x-axis represents the years. The graph shows a significant decline in incidence for both male and female groups in one population, with males having a higher incidence than females at the initial point, then followed by a similar decreasing trend. This decline mainly occurs from 1980 to 1985. The rates for another population group remain relatively low and stable throughout the period. Females in this group consistently have lower levels compared to males, who have a higher incidence.\n\nFig. 28.2\n\n### Anatomic Distribution of Esophageal Cancer\n\nSquamous cell carcinoma of the cervical esophagus is rare, accounting for only 10% of cases, with 58% occurring in the mid-esophagus and 32% occurring in the lower thoracic esophagus. Adenocarcinoma occurs almost exclusively in the lower thoracic esophagus (96% of cases). Tumors of the esophagogastric junction (EGJ) represent an entity that has historically been difficult to classify. EGJ tumors are defined as those located between the distal 5 cm of the esophagus and the proximal 5 cm of the gastric cardia. Siewert and Stein subclassified these tumors into three types based on their location with relation to the Z line: type I (esophageal), type II (cardiac), and type III (subcardiac). The eighth edition of the American Joint Commission on Cancer (AJCC) Cancer Staging Manual grouped EGJ tumors with esophageal cancer for staging and treatment.\n\n### Effect of the COVID-19 Pandemic on Esophageal Cancer\n\nThe COVID-19 pandemic decreased the screening rate for some cancers by as much as 85%. During the pandemic, there was a 40% decrease in the number of patients with esophageal cancer. In one center, the most significant delay was from the onset of symptoms to the endoscopic diagnosis (70 days in the pre-COVID era vs. 123 days during the pandemic). After the endoscopic diagnosis was obtained, the delay in care was only 2 days on average. There were no findings to suggest worse postoperative or 1-year outcomes for these patients.\n\n## Risk Factors for Esophageal Cancer\n\nThere are several risk factors that are associated with the development of EAC and ESCC. The risk factors and their effects are summarized in Table 28.2 .\n\nTable 28.2\n\nRisk Factors for the Development of Esophageal Adenocarcinoma and Squamous Cell Carcinoma (Presented in Alphabetical Order)\n\n| | Esophageal Adenocarcinoma | Esophageal Squamous Cell Carcinoma |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Achalasia | \u2191\ufe0e | \u2191\ufe0e |\n| Age | \u2191\ufe0e | \u2191\ufe0e |\n| Alcohol | 0 | \u2191\ufe0e |\n| Fruit and vegetable intake | \u2193\ufe0e | \u2193\ufe0e |\n| GERD/Barrett\u2019s esophagus | \u2191\ufe0e | 0 |\n| *Helicobacter pylori* infection | \u2193\ufe0e | ? |\n| Low socioeconomic status | \u2193\ufe0e | \u2191\ufe0e |\n| Lower esophageal sphincter-relaxing medication | \u2191\ufe0e | 0 |\n| Male sex | \u2191\ufe0e | \u2191\ufe0e |\n| NSAIDs | \u2193\ufe0e | \u2193\ufe0e |\n| Obesity | \u2191\ufe0e | \u2193\ufe0e |\n| Poor oral health and hygiene | \u2191\ufe0e | \u2191\ufe0e |\n| Proton pump inhibitors | 0 | 0 |\n| Tobacco | \u2191\ufe0e | \u2191\ufe0e |\n| White race | \u2191\ufe0e | \u2193\ufe0e |\n\n*GERD,* Gastroesophageal reflux disease; *NSAIDs,* nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs; *\u2193\ufe0e,* negative association; *\u2191\ufe0e,* positive association; *0,* no association; *?,* unknown association.\n\n### Tobacco/Alcohol\n\nTobacco use and alcohol consumption have been identified as strong independent risk factors that also act synergistically in the development of esophageal cancer, particularly ESCC. In the United States, tobacco and alcohol use account for 90% of ESCC cases. The risk of esophageal cancer is dependent on the duration of tobacco use, with current smokers having a three- to seven-fold increase in the risk of ESCC and a two-fold increase in the risk of EAC. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Studies have shown that consuming more than three alcoholic beverages per day increases the risk of ESCC. An association has not been shown with alcohol use and EAC.\n\n### Poor Oral Hygiene and Microbiome\n\nPoor oral health, oral hygiene, and tooth loss are associated with increased EAC and ESCC risk. A prospective cohort study in Sweden including over 5 million people found an increased esophageal cancer risk for both histologic subtypes. Further studies are needed to understand the mechanism by which poor oral hygiene and tooth loss can increase esophageal cancer risk. It may be related to changes in the microbiome of the oral cavity and esophagus and resultant carcinogenic immune responses. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Achalasia\n\nAchalasia has been associated with an increased risk of ESCC, presumably due to chronic mucosal irritation caused by nitrosamines released from bacteria in stagnant food debris. The incidence rate of malignancy in these patients varies significantly throughout the literature, with a 10- to 50-fold increase in relative risk (RR) compared with the general population. Leeuwenburgh et al. found an incidence of 0.34% per year of follow-up with malignancy developing an average of 24 years after the onset of achalasia symptoms. An association with EAC has also been reported but is less well established. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Diet and Nutrition\n\nHigh intake of fruits and vegetables has been shown to be protective against esophageal cancer. The majority of data is from case-control or cohort studies evaluating the risk of ESCC in high-risk populations. In high-risk areas, such as countries within the esophageal cancer belt, poor nutritional status, low intake of fruits and vegetables, and drinking hot beverages are suggested to be partially responsible.\n\nDeficiencies in vitamin A, vitamin E, selenium, and zinc are also believed to contribute to the development of ESCC. In a recently published umbrella review of meta-analyses and systematic reviews, 32 dietary factors and their association to esophageal cancer were studied. It was concluded that habitual consumption of calcium, whole grains, fruits, green leafy vegetables, green tea, and zinc was preventive, whereas alcohol, red meat, and processed meat were associated with an increased risk. Importantly, the increased risk associated with alcohol intake was supported by highly suggestive evidence.\n\n## Risk Factors Specific to Esophageal Adenocarcinoma\n\n### Obesity\n\nThe rising incidence of EAC has coincided with the obesity epidemic in the United States. As such, several studies have identified a correlation between obesity and the risk of esophageal cancer. A recent meta-analysis by Turati et al. demonstrated that both men and women with a body mass index (BMI) greater than 30 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> have a three-fold increase in risk (RR = 2.73), and an RR of 1.11 for every 5 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> increase in BMI. Corley et al. found abdominal diameter specifically to correlate with an increased risk of EAC (BMI-adjusted OR, 4.78; 95% CI, 1.14\u201320.11) but not ESCC (OR, 0.78; 95% CI, 0.32\u20131.92). Similarly, a study by Steffen et al. concluded that abdominal obesity (measured by waist circumference) as opposed to general obesity (reflected by BMI) contributed to a considerable risk for EAC.\n\nThe mechanism through which obesity contributes to esophageal cancer risk is not fully understood. It has been suggested that the increased incidence of gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) and low-grade systemic inflammation associated with adipose tissue all contribute to progression along the inflammation\u2013metaplasia\u2013cancer sequence.\n\nBariatric surgery alters the anatomy of the foregut and can make the treatment of esophageal and gastric cancers more complex. Therefore, it is important to study the effect of bariatric surgery on esophageal cancer risk, and the results so far are inconclusive. On the one hand, it has been estimated that approximately 25%\u201340% of patients who undergo sleeve gastrectomy develop GERD with an associated increase in the rate of Barrett\u2019s esophagus. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> On the other hand, it is not clear whether/how Barrett\u2019s esophagus progression to dysplasia/cancer is affected. In a nationwide cohort study in France, 300,000 patients who underwent bariatric surgery were compared with over 600,000 patients with severe obesity who did not undergo weight loss surgery. The results showed a significant reduction in esophageal and gastric cancer risk in the bariatric surgery group.\n\n### Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease\n\nGERD is a highly prevalent disorder worldwide, with prevalence estimates considerably higher in Western populations (18%\u201328%) than in East Asian populations (2%\u20138%). Several studies have investigated the role of GERD in the development of EAC. Lagergren et al. were among the first to evaluate this association in a case-control study comparing 189 patients with EAC and 820 control subjects. They demonstrated an exposure-dependent increase in risk. Compared with asymptomatic patients, those with recurrent symptoms of reflux had an OR of 7.7 (95% CI, 4.3\u201311.5) of developing EAC, whereas those with long-lasting and severe symptoms had an OR of 43.5 (95% CI, 11.3\u2013103.5). It has been reported that up to two-thirds of patients undergoing esophagectomy for EAC have preoperative GERD symptoms. Even still, despite the high prevalence of GERD, the absolute risk of esophageal cancer in a given patient with reflux is low. Therefore, the American Gastroenterological Association does not recommend routine endoscopic surveillance in the setting of chronic GERD without troublesome symptoms such as dysphagia.\n\n### Barrett\u2019s Esophagus\n\nMore so than GERD, Barrett\u2019s esophagus is the most important risk factor in the development of EAC. In patients without dysplasia, the annual risk of esophageal cancer is 0.25% compared with 6% for those with high-grade dysplasia. Risk factors for progression to cancer include chronic GERD, presence of hiatal hernia, advanced age, male sex, White race, tobacco use, and obesity. The risk of cancer also increases as the segment length of Barrett\u2019s increases, with long-segment Barrett\u2019s (\u22653 cm) having a transition rate of 0.22% per year compared with 0.01% in ultra-short-segment Barrett\u2019s (<1 cm).\n\n### Proton Pump Inhibitors\n\nThe increased incidence of EAC has correlated with the increased use of proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) since their discovery in the 1980s, leading to studies investigating any causal relationship between PPIs and EAC. Although PPIs decrease the acidity of the refluxate into the esophagus, they do not eliminate reflux. In fact, studies have shown that reflux of bile salts also contributes to the development of Barrett\u2019s esophagus. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The relationship between gastric acid suppression and the development of EAC was studied in a recently published systematic review and meta-analysis by Kasiri et al. In the analysis there were 20 studies involving 1,115,699 patients. The results determined no statistically significant relationship between PPI use and the development of EAC.\n\n### Lower Esophageal Sphincter-Relaxing Medications\n\nMedications that lower the resting pressure of the lower esophageal sphincter (LES) are thought to increase the risk of esophageal cancer by promoting increased gastroesophageal reflux. A case-control study by Lagergren et al. found a positive association between past use of sphincter-relaxing medications (nitroglycerin, anticholinergics, \u03b2-adrenergic agonists, aminophyllines, and benzodiazepines) and the risk of EAC. They also demonstrated a higher prevalence of reflux symptoms among users of LES-relaxing agents. After adjusting for reflux symptoms, the positive association almost disappeared suggesting that promotion of reflux is the link between the use of sphincter-relaxing drugs and EAC. Ranka et al. demonstrated a similar positive association with cancer risk and the use of bronchodilators, theophylline, and calcium channel blockers.\n\n#### Helicobacter pylori\n\n*Helicobacter pylori* infection is linked to several gastrointestinal malignancies including gastric cancer. Conversely, studies have shown that colonization of the stomach with *H. pylori* , particularly cytotoxin-associated gene A (CagA)-positive strains, may protect against the development of EAC. A recent meta-analysis also demonstrated a negative association with ESCC in East Asian populations but no effect in Western populations. It is hypothesized that *H. pylori* induces gastric atrophy and decreased acid production, hence decreasing acid reflux into the distal esophagus. Another suggested mechanism is through decreased gastric secretion of the hormone ghrelin, which subsequently decreases appetite, leading to lower rates of obesity, a known risk factor for EAC.\n\n## Chemoprevention of Esophageal Cancer\n\nSeveral drugs have been studied in preventing the progression of Barrett\u2019s esophagus to EAC. Based on observational studies, there are several proposed agents that may have a chemopreventive effect, including PPIs, metformin, hormone replacement therapy, aspirin, and statins. The most promising results are seen in combination therapy with PPIs and aspirin, with an associated all-cause mortality reduction of 33%. However, the benefits of aspirin and non-aspirin NSAID use in the reduction of neoplastic progression must be weighed against the potential risks such as gastrointestinal bleeding and peptic ulcer disease.\n\n## Why Is the Epidemiology Changing?\n\nSeveral theories have been proposed to explain the changing epidemiology of esophageal cancer worldwide. The rise in EAC has been the most dramatic change. Some have raised the question of whether the rise in the incidence of EAC is actually a result of reclassification of related cancers or improved diagnosis due to better-quality endoscopy. Pohl and Welch used the SEER database to assess these hypotheses. They noted a shift in the anatomic distribution of esophageal cancer with an increased incidence only in the distal third of the esophagus where EAC is usually found. This would argue that reclassification of ESCC does not account for the increased incidence of EAC. Similarly, it cannot be explained by reclassification of tumors of the gastric cardia because the incidence of tumors below the gastroesophageal junction has also increased over the past three decades. Finally, they noted that since the 1990s the mortality from EAC has increased over seven-fold with only a minor change in the proportion of patients diagnosed with localized disease, excluding improved diagnosis as a cause for the rise in incidence. Because of these data, they concluded that the increased incidence of EAC represented a true increase in disease burden.\n\nThe increase in esophageal cancer may be explained by changes in the prevalence of its known risk factors. The most notable change has been in the increased prevalence of obesity, especially in the United States. As reviewed earlier in this chapter, several studies have identified obesity and central adiposity as risk factors for EAC, possibly due to hormonal effects or due to the increased prevalence of GERD among obese individuals. Since the 1990s the increased incidence of EAC has been greatest in the Netherlands, United States, and Spain, in decreasing order. However, Kroep et al. identified that the prevalence of obesity has not followed the same trend, signifying that there must be other key drivers in the rise of EAC incidence. Parallels have also been noted with the rising prevalence of GERD, PPI use, and *H. pylori* eradication, particularly in the Western world.\n\n## Clinical Manifestations\n\nThe symptoms of esophageal cancer vary by stage. Early-stage tumors are typically asymptomatic, which is why over 50% of patients present with regionally advanced or metastatic disease. The most common presenting symptoms include dysphagia (74%), weight loss (57%), and odynophagia (17%). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Other symptoms such as cough, dyspnea, hoarseness, and pain (abdominal, back, retrosternal) may indicate more extensive disease. In patients with EAC, up to two-thirds of patients have a history of reflux symptoms.\n\nFor early-stage disease, the physical examination is usually unremarkable. Patients with metastatic disease may have hepatomegaly, pleural effusion, or lymphadenopathy, particularly in the left supraclavicular fossa (Virchow node). The most common sites of metastasis are the lymph nodes, lungs, liver, bones, adrenal glands, and brain. Esophageal cancer is also known to metastasize to unusual locations, including the head and neck, abdomen and pelvis, thorax, extremities, skin, and muscle.\n\nRoutine endoscopic screening of the general population is generally not recommended, as the incidence of esophageal cancer is low. The American College of Gastroenterology 2016 guidelines recommend endoscopic screening for Barrett\u2019s esophagus in men with chronic or frequent symptomatic GERD with two or more risk factors for EAC (i.e., age >50, Caucasian race, central obesity, current or past tobacco use, family history of Barrett\u2019s esophagus or esophageal cancer in a first-degree relative). In women, they recommend considering screening on a case-by-case basis as determined by the presence of multiple risk factors listed above. In patients with Barrett\u2019s esophagus, surveillance is recommended every 3 to 5 years in the absence of dysplasia, with more frequent intervals and/or therapy in the setting of dysplasia. Given the preliminary evidence suggesting an increased risk of *de novo* Barrett\u2019s esophagus after sleeve gastrectomy, the American Society for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery (ASMBS) issued a position statement conditionally recommending screening endoscopy for all patients with gastrointestinal symptoms \u22653 years after sleeve gastrectomy, and every 5 years afterward, if initial screening is normal. These are conditional recommendations until the availability of better designed studies can confirm or refute an association.\n\n## Future Direction for Early Detection of Esophageal Cancer\n\nUnderstandably, there is a need to detect esophageal cancer as early as possible to improve outcomes. New techniques for early detection have been created, including the Cytosponge. This detection method involves swallowing a capsule connected to a string. The capsule dissolves, releasing a sponge that collects cells from the inner lining of the esophagus for cytological examination. A randomized controlled trial (BEST3 Trial) compared the Cytosponge-TEF3 test with usual care. The study revealed a 10-fold increase in the detection of Barrett\u2019s esophagus compared with the standard care.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Siegel R.L., Miller K.D., Wagle N.S., Jemal A.: Cancer statistics, 2023 . CA Cancer J Clin 2023; 73 (1): pp. 17-48.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Reichenbach Z.W., Murray M.G., Saxena R., et al.: Clinical and translational advances in esophageal squamous cell carcinoma . Adv Cancer Res 2019; 144: pp. 95-135.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: Fabian T., Leung A.: Epidemiology of Barrett\u2019s esophagus and esophageal carcinoma . Surg Clin North Am 2021; 101 (3): pp. 381-389.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Sung H., Ferlay J., Siegel R.L., et al.: Global cancer statistics 2020: GLOBOCAN estimates of incidence and mortality worldwide for 36 cancers in 185 countries . CA Cancer J Clin 2021; 71 (3): pp. 209-249.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: Uhlenhopp D.J., Then E.O., Sunkara T., Gaduputi V.: Epidemiology of esophageal cancer: update in global trends, etiology and risk factors . Clin J Gastroenterol 2020; 13 (6): pp. 1010-1021.\n\nView In Article\n\n6.: He H., Chen N., Hou Y., et al.: Trends in the incidence and survival of patients with esophageal cancer: a SEER database analysis . Thorac Cancer 2020; 11 (5): pp. 1121-1128.\n\nView In Article\n\n7.: In Howlader N., Noone A.M., Krapcho M., et al. (eds): SEER Cancer Statistics Review, 1975-2018 . 2021. National Cancer Institute , Bethesda, MD based on November 2020 SEER data submission, posted to the SEER web site .\n\nView In Article\n\n8.: Liu K.S., Raza S.A., El-Serag H.B., Thrift A.P.: Trends in esophageal adenocarcinoma and eso