H151c.3%200%20.5.2.5.5V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.5.6h-20.8c-.3%200-.517-.3-.5-.6V7zm47.7%2036.7c-.4%200-.6-.2-.8-.5l-7.3-12.7-7.4%2012.7c-.2.3-.4.5-.8.5h-5.8c-.3%200-.5-.3-.3-.7L166%2024.3%20156%207.1c-.2-.4%200-.7.3-.7h5.8c.4%200%20.6.1.8.5l6.5%2011.3h.1L176%206.9c.2-.4.5-.5.9-.5h5.7c.4%200%20.5.3.3.7l-10%2017.2L183.7%2043c.2.4%200%20.7-.3.7h-5.8zM192.015%2019c-.2%200-.338-.004-.3-.2V8.4h-3.3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[27. Medical and Surgical Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and Barrett\u2019s Esophagus - ClinicalKey|27. Medical and Surgical Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and Barrett\u2019s Esophagus]]\n**Next:** [[29. Endoscopic Management of High-Grade Dysplasia and Superficial Esophageal Carcinoma - ClinicalKey|29. Endoscopic Management of High-Grade Dysplasia and Superficial Esophageal Carcinoma]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "28. Epidemiology, Risk Factors, and Clinical Manifestations of Esophageal Cancer - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Epidemiology, Risk Factors, and Clinical Manifestations of Esophageal Cancer', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Epidemiology, Risk Factors, and Clinical Manifestations of Esophageal Cancer', 'Risk Factors for Esophageal Cancer', 'Risk Factors Specific to Esophageal Adenocarcinoma', 'Chemoprevention of Esophageal Cancer', 'Why Is the Epidemiology Changing?', 'Future Direction for Early Detection of Esophageal Cancer', 'Epidemiology, Risk Factors, and Clinical Manifestations of Esophageal Cancer / Risk Factors for Esophageal Cancer', 'Epidemiology, Risk Factors, and Clinical Manifestations of Esophageal Cancer / Risk Factors Specific to Esophageal Adenocarcinoma', 'Epidemiology, Risk Factors, and Clinical Manifestations of Esophageal Cancer / Chemoprevention of Esophageal Cancer'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '28', '277-283', 2, 34, FALSE, TRUE),
('Endoscopic Management of High-Grade Dysplasia and Superficial Esophageal Carcinoma', 'shackelford-9th-ed-29-endoscopic-management-of-high-grade-dysplasia-and-superficial-esophageal-carci', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Endoscopic Management of High-Grade Dysplasia and Superficial Esophageal Carcinoma\n\nCynthia Kassab; Marta L. Davila; Wayne L. Hofstetter\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 29, 284-294\n\n## Introduction\n\nEndoscopic eradication therapy (EET) has largely replaced esophagectomy for the treatment of high-grade dysplasia (HGD) and superficial esophageal cancer. The detection and treatment of HGD and early esophageal cancer overlap to the point that they are a continuum. In some situations, they can be difficult to separate and exist simultaneously. Because existing studies often combine the descriptions of the two, for the purposes of this chapter we will consider both as superficial neoplasia.\n\nThe biology of superficial neoplasia is distinct from disease that penetrates deeper into the wall of the esophagus as its prognosis is typically excellent and treatment most often curative. Along with advances in endoscopic therapy, the evolution away from surgery is both disruptive to previous therapies and represents a clear advance in medicine. Organ-sparing procedures including endoscopic resection (ER) in combination with various forms of ablation are the preferable option for the treatment of early esophageal neoplasia in the vast majority of cases.\n\nIn the United States the incidence of esophageal adenocarcinoma (EAC) has been increasing, whereas that of squamous cell cancers of the esophagus is decreasing. In fact, the rise in incidence of EAC is inconsistent with most other cancers, which are either stable or declining. The reasons for this are not completely clear, but what is known is that this is an insidious disease. Symptoms occur late in the disease process, leaving most cases of EAC diagnosed at an advanced stage, a point where the disease is lethal in most patients. Therefore, an early diagnosis constitutes our best hope of impacting survival. Emphasis on public awareness regarding the risk factors for EAC has perhaps stimulated a trend toward esophageal surveillance, despite a lack of clarity within the gastroenterology society guidelines. People with longstanding reflux who are not realizing benefits from medical therapy or those who are simply undergoing routine colon screening and describe a long history of reflux to their gastroenterologists are often screened with upper endoscopy. Between formal and informal screening methods, these have been the only methods for us to screen for or serendipitously discover early-stage esophageal disease.\n\n### Screening and Surveillance\n\nBarrett\u2019s esophagus (BE) is the only know histological precursor of EAC. Through a series of genetic alterations, BE appears to progress in a stepwise manner from non-dysplastic BE, to low-grade dysplasia (LGD), to HGD, and to EAC. However, an orderly progression through the metaplasia\u2013dysplasia\u2013cancer sequence may not be recognized or even present in every patient with Barrett\u2019s-associated neoplasia. It is possible that episodic observation of the esophagus misses those events in real time if they have occurred. Another explanation may be that the disease can skip intermediate stages of progression once a critical genetic mutation or mutational load is reached.\n\nScreening programs to detect BE, followed by surveillance of BE to detect and treat dysplasia and/or early EAC, can lead to a decreased incidence of EAC. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Unfortunately, there are no randomized trials that demonstrate screening or surveillance of BE reduces mortality from EAC. It appears, however, that adherence to a screening and surveillance program can lead to the detection of EAC at an earlier stage.\n\nSeveral risk factors have been identified in the development of BE including chronic gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) symptoms (>5 years), age >50 years, male sex, White race, central obesity, presence of a hiatal hernia, smoking, and a family history of BE or EAC.\n\nA systematic review and meta-analysis assessed the prevalence of BE in individuals with and without some of these risk factors. The pooled rate of BE in those with no identifiable risk factors was 0.8%. The prevalence of BE was 2.3% among patients with GERD and 1.9% among those with obesity. A higher prevalence was reported in those with the following risk factors: age >50 years (6.1%), male sex (6.8%), and family history of BE or EAC (23%). Furthermore, the rate of BE increased by 12.2% in those with GERD and one additional risk factor. The same study also revealed a linear relationship between the number of risks factors for BE and prevalence of BE, with the rate of BE increasing by 1.2% for each additional risk factor studied.\n\nRace seems to have an effect on incidence of BE, where White people are at higher risk of BE than Black and Hispanic populations. In a single-center retrospective study from the United States, White people had a significantly higher prevalence of BE than Hispanic people (6.1% vs. 1.7%) and Black people (6.1% vs. 1.6%). Smoking can double the risk of BE and EAC for both men and women with the risk increasing with increasing total pack-years. Alternatively, a risk reduction can be seen after smoking cessation when compared with current smokers. Hiatal hernias are also considered a risk factor in the development of BE. In a single-center prospective study involving 270 patients, patients with BE had hiatal hernias that were significantly longer and hiatal openings that were significantly wider when compared with controls with or without esophagitis.\n\nThese data support the premise of screening for BE in those with multiple risk factors and this is what most gastroenterological societies have endorsed. On the contrary, many patients presenting with a new diagnosis of EAC do not have BE and have never had symptoms of reflux. Perhaps that is because \u201csilent\u201d reflux is present in this subgroup of patients or there are other variables driving the progression to neoplasia that are not fully understood. The American College of Gastroenterology (ACG) recommends screening patients with chronic GERD (>5 years) and with three or more additional risk factors. Similarly, the American Gastroenterological Association (AGA) does not consider chronic GERD alone as a prerequisite for screening and recommends screening in patients with at least three risk factors including male sex, non-Hispanic White, age >50 years, history of smoking, chronic GERD, obesity, and a family history of BE or EAC.\n\nAfter BE has been discovered, endoscopic efforts convert from screening to surveillance, the purpose of which is to detect the presence of esophageal lesions that are at high risk of progressing to EAC. Although the benefit of surveillance has not been conclusively proved, several studies have shown that patients who developed EAC while under surveillance presented at a lower stage of disease and had improved survival when compared with those not undergoing surveillance. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In fact, surveillance guidelines have been developed under the assumption that the practice will reduce deaths.\n\nSurveillance guidelines vary according to the length of the Barrett\u2019s segment and the degree of dysplasia detected in the esophageal biopsies ( Box 29.1 ). The ACG recommends that patients with non-dysplastic BE <3 cm in length be surveyed every 5 years, whereas those with segments \u22653 cm be surveyed every 3 years. Any degree of dysplasia should be confirmed by an expert pathologist. Patients with confirmed BE with LGD are advised to undergo EET. However, endoscopic surveillance remains an alternative. If a surveillance approach is chosen, patients with BE and LGD should undergo EGD with biopsies every 6 months for 1 year, followed by annual endoscopies thereafter. Conversely, patients with BE and HGD should be offered EET as the best management option.\n\nBOX 29.1\n\nRecommended Surveillance Intervals and Management in Patients with Barrett Esophagus\n\nAdapted from Shaheen NJ, Falk GW, et al. Diagnosis and management of Barrett\u2019s esophagus: an updated ACG guideline. *Am J Gastroenterol.* 2022;117:559\u2013587.\n\n*BE,* Barrett\u2019s esophagus; *EGD,* esophagogastroduodenoscopy; *PPI,* proton pump inhibitor.\n\n## Findings Surveillance/Management\n\n  - Non-dysplastic BE <3 cm in length: Repeat EGD in 5 years.\n  - Non-dysplastic BE \u22653 cm in length: Repeat EGD in 3 years.\n  - BE indefinite for dysplasia:\n\tRepeat EGD within 6 months after increasing PPI dose to twice a day.\n  - If repeat EGD shows non-dysplastic BE or low-grade dysplasia, follow appropriate guidelines.\n  - If repeat EGD shows BE indefinite for dysplasia, EGD annually\n  - BE with low-grade dysplasia: Endoscopic eradication therapy\n  - If not, surveillance is an acceptable alternative:\n  - EGD at 6 months from diagnosis\n  - EGD at 12 months from diagnosis\n  - EGD annually thereafter\n  - BE with high-grade dysplasia: Endoscopic eradication therapy\n\nThe rationale behind surveillance and treatment recommendations are based on risks of progression from BE to EAC. A meta-analysis of 4097 patients with BE without dysplasia reported annual rates of progression to EAC of 0.06% for those with short segment (<3 cm) versus 0.31% for those with long segment BE (\u22653 cm). In contrast, the rate of progression to HGD and/or EAC is considerably higher for patients with LGD with estimates ranging from 1.7% to 13% per year. The variability in the reported rates of progression among patients with BE with LGD is likely due to lack of interobserver agreement among pathologists. In a study of 51 international pathologists who reviewed 55 digitalized biopsies, there was excellent agreement in the diagnosis of non-dysplastic BE (79%), or BE with HGD (71%). However, agreement for the diagnosis of BE with LGD was much less at 42%. Five years of professional experience appeared to be protective against major diagnostic errors. In a Dutch retrospective study involving three expert pathologists who reviewed community cases of BE with LGD, the annual rate of progression to HGD/EAC was 2.4% when a single pathologist confirmed LGD, 6.3% when two pathologists confirmed LGD, and 20% when all three pathologists confirmed LGD. Without intervention, the progression risk from flat HGD to EAC is high, ranging from 5% to 19% per year. Furthermore, patients with HGD-associated visible lesions have a much higher risk of progression.\n\n### Endoscopic Evaluation and Staging\n\nScreening and surveillance examinations should be performed with high-definition white light endoscopy (WLE) and chromoendoscopy, allowing for adequate time to evaluate the Barrett\u2019s segment. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The longer the time spent inspecting the Barrett\u2019s segment, the higher the likelihood of detecting suspicious lesions. In a study of 112 patients undergoing surveillance, the authors reported that endoscopists who averaged greater than 1 minute of inspection time per centimeter of Barrett\u2019s detected more suspicious lesions than those who spent less time. Routine use of chromoendoscopy results in higher rates of detection of HGD and EAC. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Chromoendoscopy can be accomplished with the use of vital dyes such as acetic acid or by using virtual or electronic chromoendoscopy systems that have been incorporated in endoscopic platforms. Virtual or electronic chromoendoscopy uses light filters and a variety of post-processing techniques to enhance the imaging of mucosal and vascular patterns. Although the majority of the studies in virtual chromoendoscopy have been with Narrow Band Imaging (NBI; Olympus, Center Valley, PA), all the major endoscopic manufacturers have a version of electronic chromoendoscopy (Fujinon Intelligent Color Enhancement \\[Fujinon, Wayne, NJ\\] and I-scan \\[Pentax Medical, Montvale, NJ\\]). Given the time-consuming nature and cost of dye-based chromoendoscopy, virtual chromoendoscopy has emerged as the preferred advanced imaging technique in the evaluation of patients with BE. Other imaging techniques such as confocal laser endomicroscopy and volumetric laser endomicroscopy (not currently commercially available) have been developed in an effort to enhance the detection of dysplasia and Barrett\u2019s-related neoplasia. However, it is not clear if these techniques add significant value above the level of detection seen with detailed WLE and chromoendoscopy, especially in high-volume centers.\n\nAt least eight biopsies should be obtained in screening examinations when there is suspicion of BE. For surveillance exams, the Seattle protocol for acquisition of biopsy samples has been endorsed by multiple gastroenterological societies. The protocol consists of four-quadrant biopsies performed at 2 cm intervals throughout the entire Barrett\u2019s segment, or every 1 cm in patients with known or suspected dysplasia. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Any visible lesions should be biopsied, and the tissue placed in a separate container. Alternatively, endoscopists may prefer not to sample a suspicious lesion and refer the patient for ER. Studies suggest that the use of a standard biopsy protocol is associated with a higher rate of detection of dysplasia and EAC.\n\nThe American Society for Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ASGE) recommends the use of wide area transepithelial sampling (WATS <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">3D </sup> ; CDx Diagnostics, Suffern, NY) in patients with known or suspected BE, in addition to Seattle protocol biopsy sampling. This technology uses a stiff brush that is advanced through the biopsy channel of the endoscope to sample large areas of the esophagus. The sample is placed on a slide, and a computer reconstructs a 3D image of the sampled Barrett\u2019s glands. Computer software identifies areas of concern that are later reviewed by an expert pathologist. A systematic review of WATS <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">3D </sup> completed as part of the ASGE guidelines published in 2019 included six studies and 6271 patients. WLE with random biopsies detected 125 cases of dysplasia. WATS <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">3D </sup> resulted in the identification of 137 additional cases which were missed by WLE and biopsies. The relative increase in dysplasia detection by WATS <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">3D </sup> was 48% (95% CI 34%\u201360%). For patients with history of dysplasia, the absolute increase in dysplasia detection using WATS <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">3D </sup> was 10.6% (95% CI 1.5%\u201319.8%). In a meta-analysis of 20,392 endoscopies performed in patients with BE, the addition of WATS <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">3D </sup> technology to standard biopsies led to an absolute increase in the detection of dysplasia of 2%. There have been limitations noted in these studies, including the lack of uniformity in the definition of dysplasia, the fact that the studies have assessed WATS <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">3D </sup> as an adjunct to biopsy protocols, and the lack of subsequent biopsy confirmation after a diagnosis of dysplasia was made. Further studies are needed to ascertain the role of this technology in the evaluation of patients with BE.\n\nIn the last decade, a tissue system pathology assay (TissueCypher; Castle Biosciences, Pittsburg, PA, USA) has been developed to risk stratify patients with BE. The assay is performed on biopsies taken from a Barrett\u2019s segment and quantifies nine protein-based biomarkers (p16, p53, AMACR, HER2, Cytokeratin 20, CD68, COX-2, HIF-1alpha, and CD45Ro) along with nuclear morphology and tissue architecture. The system analyses 15 predefined quantitative measures of biomarkers and morphologic features that are integrated to produce a risk score from 0 to 10, which classifies patients as low, intermediate, or high risk for progression to HGD/EAC. Case-control studies have shown consistent and significant associations between a TissueCypher high-risk score and progression to HGD/EAC. The opposite is true, with low-risk scores being associated with lack of progression. In addition, patients with non-dysplastic BE with a high-risk score by TissueCypher progress at a higher rate than patients with expert pathologist\u2013confirmed LGD. Given these results, the AGA has recommended the use of this technology in the risk stratification of patients with non-dysplastic BE.\n\n#### Endoscopic Ultrasound Staging\n\nEndoscopic ultrasound (EUS) plays an important role in the diagnosis and staging of esophageal cancer. In cases of intermediate to locally advanced EAC, EUS is the principal method used to estimate the depth and regional nodal status of the disease. In contrast, EUS has a very limited role in the evaluation of patients with HGD and early EAC. The accuracy of EUS staging in these disease categories is modest at best. In a study of 335 patients, the authors analyzed the test performance of EUS for selecting patients correctly for either endoscopic therapy (T1aN0 or less) or surgery (\u2265T1b or N1). Histology was used as the criterion standard for comparing EUS findings. The sensitivity of EUS for an accurate prediction was poor at 50%. In addition, patients with nodular BE were 65% less likely to be correctly staged by EUS when compared with non-nodular BE. A systematic review of 12 studies compared EUS with endoscopic mucosal resection (EMR) or surgical pathology for early (T1-T2) tumors. In that study, EUS predicted the depth of the target lesion with 67% accuracy. Because some patients had multiple lesions, analysis on an individual patient basis reduced the accuracy to only 56%. In a meta-analysis involving 11 studies and 895 patients with BE and suspected dysplasia, EUS over-staged 9% of cases (staging T1b or worse) when they had disease limited to the mucosa (T1a or less). There are several factors that may contribute to the suboptimal accuracy of EUS in early EAC, including wall thickening due to chronic inflammation, presence of a duplicated muscularis mucosa, anatomic changes at the level of the gastroesophageal junction (GEJ)/cardia, and endoscopist\u2019s experience. Despite these drawbacks, there may be a role for EUS in select cases in which there is a high level of suspicion for deeper invasion or metastatic lymphadenopathy. In a study of patients with BE/HGD (12 patients) and intramucosal adenocarcinoma (13 patients) undergoing EUS evaluation, 7 patients were found to have suspicious lymphadenopathy. Fine-needle aspiration confirmed malignancy in five of these seven patients. EUS identified five patients (20%) who were unsuitable candidates for endoscopic therapy. Such studies highlight the importance of a careful, individual approach to patients with early esophageal cancer.\n\n#### Endoscopic Resection for Staging\n\nThe preferred diagnostic and therapeutic tool for patients with nodular BE and early EAC is ER. A staging EMR or endoscopic submucosal dissection (ESD) provides crucial information regarding depth of tumor invasion as well as important histologic features such as grade of differentiation, lymphovascular or perineural invasion, and tumor length. ER is superior to EUS for the assessment of depth of invasion by the simple fact that depth is determined by histologic examination under the microscope. This is important given the low prevalence of metastatic lymphadenopathy in T1a disease compared with T1b disease involving the mid and deep submucosa (20%\u201330%). In a multicenter study of 138 patients with dysplastic BE and early EAC, 83% had visible lesions that were resected endoscopically. ER led to a change in histologic diagnosis in 31% of patients, with an upgrade in diagnosis in 10% and a downgrade in diagnosis in 21%. In a retrospective study of 150 ERs performed for focal lesions, ER led to a change in diagnosis in 49% and a change in treatment strategy in 30% of patients. These are very significant findings; imagine redirecting the recommended therapy of an individual patient from combined multimodality therapy consisting of chemoradiation followed by esophagectomy to an organ-sparing, curative ER.\n\nIn summary, optimal evaluation is fundamental to the management of dysplastic and early-stage mucosal and selected submucosal lesions. ER is an important diagnostic and potentially therapeutic tool for patients with early neoplastic disease.\n\n## Endoscopic Eradication Therapy\n\nThe EET consists of methods that resect tissue (EMR or ESD) or ablate tissue. The current paradigm of endoscopic treatment is to resect any visible lesions and ablate any residual BE to reduce the risk or recurrent or metachronous dysplasia/EAC.\n\nAblative therapies are recommended to patients with flat BE with LGD and/or HGD. Ablation of non-dysplastic BE is not recommended due to the low risk of progression to EAC ( Table 29.1 ). The goal of ablative therapies is the complete eradication of intestinal metaplasia (CE-IM), which is defined as the absence of any visible BE with biopsies negative for intestinal metaplasia in both the tubular esophagus and the cardia.\n\nTable 29.1\n\nRecommended Surveillance Intervals and Management in Patients With Barrett\u2019s Esophagus\n\nAdapted from Shaheen NJ, Falk GW, et al. Diagnosis and management of Barrett\u2019s esophagus: an updated ACG guideline. *Am J Gastroenterol.* 2022;117:559\u2013587.\n\n| Findings | Surveillance/ Management |\n| --- | --- |\n| Nondysplastic BE <3 cm in length | Repeat EGD in 5 years |\n| Nondysplastic BE \u22653 cm in length | Repeat EGD in 3 years |\n| BE indefinite for dysplasia \u2217 | Repeat EGD within 6 months after increasing PPI dose to twice a day If repeat EGD shows NDBE or LGD, follow appropriate guidelines If repeat EGD shows BE indefinite for for dysplasia, EGD annually |\n| BE with low-grade dysplasia \u2217 | Endoscopic eradication therapy If not, surveillance is an acceptable alternative: - EGD at 6 months from diagnosis - EGD at 12 months from diagnosis - EGD annually thereafter |\n| BE with high-grade dysplasia \u2217 | Endoscopic eradication therapy |\n\n*BE,* Barrett\u2019s esophagus; *EGD,* esophagogastroduodenoscopy; *LGD,* low grade dysplasia; *NDBE,* nondysplastic Barrett\u2019s esophagus; *PPI,* proton pump inhibitor.\n\nAblation therapies use energy (hot or cold) to eradicate flat intestinal metaplasia and dysplasia. The advantage of ablative therapies is that large surface areas can be treated with mild side effects. Repeat applications are possible and typically required (every 2\u20133 months) to achieve CE-IM and complete eradication of all dysplasia (CE-D). Ablative therapies do not provide a pathologic specimen for evaluation and are not as effective in treating raised or ulcerated lesions. Radiofrequency ablation (RFA) and cryoablation are the most studied ablative modalities in the treatment of dysplastic BE and they will be discussed in further detail ( Fig. 29.1 ).\n\nA group of six photos depicts endoscopic views of various procedures and discoveries in the gastrointestinal tract. The photos feature six endoscopic views of the gastrointestinal tract, each labeled with parts A to F. It displays different stages of a medical procedure. A medical device, possibly a stent or balloon, is inserted into the tract in part A. Part B depicts a clear view inside the endoscope with a medical instrument in place. Part C presents a section of the gastrointestinal lineage with visible irregularities or lesions. In part D, contrast material is used to highlight a specific area of the tract. Part E displays the insertion of a catheter or another instrument, likely for a treatment or biopsy. Finally, part F captures an abnormal section of the tract with noticeable changes which suggests a potential pathology or infection.\n\nFig. 29.1\n\n### Radiofrequency Ablation\n\nRFA applies energy via electrodes in contact with the tissue to achieve mucosal ablation. The depth of ablation is typically between 500 and 1000 \u03bcm, depending on the intrinsic properties of the esophagus and the energy setting used for the RFA. This will typically ablate through the epithelium and into the lamina propria layer of the esophageal mucosa.\n\nSeveral catheters of different sizes and shapes are available to tailor therapy. Treatment of a long, circumferential Barrett\u2019s segment can be accomplished with the help of catheter-based electrodes on an inflatable balloon (Barrx 360 Express balloon catheter; Medtronics, Minneapolis, MN). The balloon is advanced over a guidewire under endoscopic visualization and energy is applied at 10 J/cm <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> in sequential 4-cm segments, starting at the proximal end of the segment. The resulting coagulum is then scraped with the help of a cap attached at the tip of the endoscope. A second ablation treatment is subsequently performed in the same manner as the initial treatment. Short-segment Barrett\u2019s can be treated with a focal device that is mounted at the tip of the endoscope or advanced through the biopsy channel of the endoscope (Barrx RFA focal catheters, Barrx Channel RFA endoscopic catheter). Focal ablation is performed with two applications of energy at 12 J/cm <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> . The coagulum is scraped with a cap or with the distal end of the focal ablation device. This is followed by a second round of ablations performed in a similar fashion. Treatments are usually performed every 2\u20133 months until therapeutic goals are met.\n\nSeveral studies have demonstrated the efficacy, safety, and durability of RFA to treat dysplastic Barrett\u2019s. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In the AIM-Dysplasia trial, a randomized multicenter study, 127 patients with dysplastic BE were assigned to receive either RFA or sham procedure. Eighty-four patients were randomized to the RFA treatment group (42 patients with HGD and 42 with LGD). After an average of 3.5 treatments per patient, CE-D occurred in 81% of patients with HGD assigned to the ablation group compared with 19% of those assigned to the control group ( *P* <.001). Overall, 77% of patients in the RFA group had CE-IM compared with 2% of those in the control group ( *P* <.001). Progression from HGD to cancer occurred in 19% of patients in the control group and in 2% of patients in the RFA-treated group ( *P* \\=.045). The study was a crossover design, and at 3-year follow up, CE-D was reported in 98% of patients and CE-IM in 91%. The annual rate of progression to EAC among those treated with RFA was 0.55%.\n\nThe Surveillance versus Radiofrequency ablation (SURF) European multicenter study randomized 136 patients with confirmed LGD to either RFA or surveillance. The primary outcome was neoplastic progression to HGD or EAC. RFA reduced the risk of progression to a combined endpoint of HGD/EAC to 1.5% ( *n* \\= 1) in the RFA group versus 26.5% ( *n* \\= 18) in the control group ( *P* <.001). Ablation also reduced the risk of progression to adenocarcinoma from 8.8% to 1.5%. The long-term results of the SURF study have been published comprising a 6-year follow-up data. The effects of ablation were sustained with an absolute risk reduction in progression to HGD/EAC of 32.4% (95% CI 22.4%-44.2%).\n\nThe safety profile of RFA has also been described. The most common complications reported include chest pain lasting less than 1 week, strictures requiring dilation (6%\u20138%), and gastrointestinal hemorrhage (1%). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Although operator experience has been shown to impact the success of RFA and the number of sessions needed to achieve CE-IM, it does not appear to impact the risk of complications including stricture formation, gastrointestinal hemorrhage, perforation, or hospitalization.\n\nSeveral factors have been identified as predictors of a poor response to RFA, such as uncontrolled GERD, presence of a hiatal hernia, and BE segment >5 cm. Additional non-validated predictors reported include non-Caucasian race, increasing body mass index, and current or prior smoking history. However, these may not be the only factors that lead to a poor response. In a large, multicenter study of 278 patients, poor initial response was defined as less than 50% regression of the BE surface area 3 months after circumferential balloon-based RFA. Thirty-six patients (13%) were deemed to have a poor initial response. Independent predictors of poor response on multivariate analysis included the presence of active reflux esophagitis, regeneration of Barrett\u2019s at the ER scar, relative esophageal narrowing prior to RFA, and number of years with dysplastic changes before RFA. Salvage endoscopic therapies after RFA failure include cryotherapy and ER.\n\n### Cryotherapy\n\nThere are two systems currently available: a spray cryotherapy platform that uses liquid nitrogen (TruFreeze; Steris, Mentor, OH), and a balloon-based nitrous oxide cryotherapy device (C2 Cryoballoon; Pentax Medical, Montvale, NJ). Cryotherapy produces mucosal injury through multiple different mechanisms including apoptosis and tissue ischemia.\n\nThere are no randomized controlled studies assessing the efficacy of cryotherapy in the treatment of dysplastic BE. For liquid nitrogen spray cryotherapy, a spray catheter is advanced through the working channel of an endoscope. The spray catheter will deliver liquid nitrogen at a low temperature to freeze the tissue. A decompression tube is placed alongside the endoscope to suction the expanding nitrogen gas produced during treatment. Prospective and retrospective studies have reported rates of complete eradication of HGD (CE-HGD) in 81%\u201387% and CE-IM in 57%\u201361%. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> A meta-analysis of 14 studies of liquid nitrogen spray cryotherapy in both ablation-na\u00efve and-experienced patients ( *n* \\= 707) demonstrated overall pooled rates of CE-D, CE-HGD, and CE-IM of 81%, 90%, and 56%, respectively. The most common adverse events reported with liquid nitrogen spray cryotherapy are strictures in 3%\u20134% of patients, chest pain in 2%\u201310%, and perforation in 0.8%. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nThe cryoballoon ablation (CBA) device freezes the tissue by surface contact with a balloon infused with nitrous oxide. The system consists of a hand-held controller that houses a capsule containing liquid nitrous oxide. The controller is attached to a low-pressure balloon catheter which can be advanced through the biopsy channel of a therapeutic upper endoscope. Nitrous oxide released from the capsule travels through the balloon catheter shaft and through a small opening in the diffuser at the center of the balloon, resulting in balloon inflation and a freeze. In a prospective multicenter study of CBA in patients ( *n* \\= 120) with dysplastic BE (20% with history of intramucosal adenocarcinoma), the CE-D and CE-IM rates were 76% and 72%, respectively, in the intention-to-treat analysis. In the per-protocol analysis, the CE-D and CE-IM rates were 97% and 92%, respectively. The incidence of serious events was 1%, including one perforation, one upper gastrointestinal hemorrhage, and one laceration.\n\nThere have been no head-to-head trials comparing RFA with cryotherapy; however, it appears that the rates of CE-D and CE-IM seen with RFA may be comparable with those reported with cryotherapy. A recent nonrandomized study comparing two cohorts of patients, one treated with RFA and the other one with CBA, revealed that the chance of reaching CE-IM was not influenced by the ablation modality. Propensity score-matched analysis revealed a comparable chance of achieving CE-IM and CE-D when using either RFA or CBA. The only difference noted was a higher stricture rate among those treated with CBA (10.4%) compared with the RFA group (4.4%).\n\nCryotherapy has been used as second-line therapy after RFA. In a meta-analysis of 148 patients who underwent cryotherapy with a variety of cryogens (liquid nitrogen, nitrous oxide, and carbon dioxide) for persistent dysplasia or intestinal metaplasia after RFA treatment, the pooled proportion of CE-D and CE-IM were 76% and 46%, respectively, with adverse effects reported in 6.7% of patients.\n\n#### Surveillance Postablation Therapy\n\nAll patients with Barrett\u2019s-related dysplasia or neoplasia who have undergone successful EET should enter a surveillance program, given the risk of recurrence. All patients should receive maximal reflux control for best outcomes, typical with high-dose proton pump inhibitor (PPI) therapy. In a systematic review and meta-analysis that included 21 RFA studies, the annual incidence of recurrence of IM was 9.5%, whereas the incidence of recurrence of dysplastic BE and HGD/EAC was 2% and 1.2%, respectively. Predictors of recurrence include worse pretreatment histologic grade (HGD/EAC), long-segment BE, and older age. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nBased on modeling analysis from data reported in the US RFA Registry and the UK National Halo Registry, proposed surveillance intervals were developed for patients with BE LGD, and BE HGD/intramucosal adenocarcinoma. These surveillance intervals have been adopted by gastroenterological societies. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> For patients with BE LGD pre-ablation, surveillance is recommended at 1 year following CE-IM and every 2 years thereafter. For patients with HGD and/or intramucosal adenocarcinoma, the recommended surveillance interval after achieving CE-IM is 3 months, 6 months, 12 months, and annually thereafter. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Endoscopic Resection\n\nCurrently, ER is the leading therapy for nodular BE and suspected early esophageal tumors. This procedure originally gained acceptance as a treatment for polyps and early-staged cancers within the colon. It later translated into treatment for esophageal squamous cell carcinoma within Asian medical centers. Now it is used throughout the world after groups in Germany, the Netherlands, and North America have shown that this modality is a preferable treatment option over surgery for HGD and early EAC. In patients diagnosed with HGD, the main goal of ER is to resect visible lesions within the esophagus. Solitary nodules, areas of nodularity, and superficial ulcers are all high-risk areas for concurrent, unrecognized carcinoma or progression to invasive disease. Areas of flat HGD are often adequately managed by endoscopic ablation therapies alone, but there are times when a strategy of resection may be more definitive, cheaper, and effective. Short segments of flat HGD are amenable to complete ER with a low risk of complication. This is especially true when the diseased area is not circumferential. In cases of circumferential ER, the risk of postprocedural symptomatic stricture increases significantly. Patients with the lowest risk for regional or systemic disease will usually have lesions that are less than 2 cm in maximal dimension. Well-differentiated mucosal adenocarcinomas are associated with very low rates of lymph node metastases (<3%) and can be managed with endoscopic therapies, whereas tumors invading the submucosa may have a substantial risk of lymph node metastases (>20%) and are usually referred for esophagectomy.\n\nHowever, with careful diagnostic evaluations, the risk of a major potentially life-threatening surgery can be mitigated if ER is feasible. A study by Nelson et al. has shown that clinically staged cT2N0 disease by EUS can be safely resected with ER, 57% had total disease clearance, and the rest required further management. Out of those who had R0 resection, 30% were pT1a, 17% pT1b, and the rest were either Tis or T0 disease. Thus, selected lesions that are cT2N0 merit an attempt at ER for diagnostic and/or therapeutic purposes.\n\n#### Endoscopic Mucosal Resection or Endoscopic Submucosal Dissection?\n\nER can be either EMR or ESD. The EMR procedure uses a cap and snare technique, to retrieve mucosal tissue removed in \u223c1- to 2-cm pieces. Larger areas can be removed with multiple applications of the EMR technique resulting in a piecemeal specimen. Alternatively, ESD is a submucosal space dissection which removes larger lesions *en bloc* . ESD is typically used in cases where invasion of submucosa is evident or highly suspicious. Choosing between EMR and ESD depends on the tumor characteristics, invasion depth, and comfort of the operator/physician. Ideally, invasive lesions amenable to EMR must be superficial (T1) and small enough to be completely resected endoscopically. More specifically, EMR is used for lesions that are easily visualized, such as nodular, raised, ulcerated, and have other high-grade features for invasive cancer; it does overcome the limit of depth treatment that is not appropriately managed by ablation without destroying the tissue histology. It has a high percentage of eradication in low-grade well-differentiated tumors that do not have submucosal invasion or lymphovascular invasion (LVI). The eradication rate also remains relatively high for lesions with high-grade features and may reach up to 80% average with T1a lesions eradication rate observed to be up to 98% in some studies. ESD may have a role in deeper lesions when need for complete ER outweighs the benefits of esophagectomy. ESD has been adopted worldwide in centers of excellence, but it is technically challenging and requires about 80 cases to achieve competence level and about 120 cases benchmark for proficiency level. Complications specific to the EMR procedure include bleeding and perforation, an event that is seen in less than 0.1% of cases using most cap techniques. Bleeding risk is \u223c2% for EMR. This is in contrast to reports of perforation upward of 40% for aggressive ESD procedures. Combining mucosal resection with ablation has shown to decrease these risks significantly. Fortunately, with or without ablation, most complications associated with ER can be managed nonoperatively. In the long term, stricture may occur, and this depends on previous pathology in the individual patient and the extent of circumferential resection. Removing more than 50% circumference significantly increases the risk of stricture. Complete circumferential resections can be performed, but the authors typically like to stage procedures that will require circumferential resections into several episodes. Single-session circumferential resection is associated with healing to high-grade stenosis; therefore, stenting at the time of resection should be considered. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n#### Step-by-Step Endoscopic Resection ( Fig. 29.2 )\n\n  - 1.\n\t*Procedure setup and setting.* Patients are advised to remain nothing by mouth (NPO) overnight and preferably stay on a liquid diet the evening before. Performing this procedure with food in the stomach is inconvenient and perhaps incurs a bit more risk. The appropriate setting is in a monitored suite with full anesthesia capability. Avoiding cough, hiccoughs, and excess patient movement at the most critical point of the case when the tissue is acquired into a cap or band is beneficial. Therefore, the authors prefer to perform the procedure with monitored sedation in most cases, but it is not absolutely imperative that the patient is under a general anesthetic.\n  - 2.\n\t*Identification of the lesion.* The endoscopy equipment is critical to the outcome of therapy and high-definition equipment is mandatory. Techniques that improve topographic visualization are encouraged because early lesions around the GEJ/cardia can be easily overlooked. Endoscopists must be experienced at detecting early esophageal/gastroesophageal pathology.\n  - 3.\n\t*Outline the area of resection.* It is frequently surprising how an obvious lesion becomes difficult to see once a scope with a cap partially obstructs the view in the esophagus. Pre-marking the area to be removed prior to introducing a cap for therapy can be very helpful. Chromoendoscopy of some sort can facilitate marking the lesion with adequate margins. The endoscopist may also choose to place marks (cautery, ink, or clips) on the tissue to be resected that will orient the tissue margins for the clinician and pathologist. This is probably only relevant in situations in which there is a single resection because piecemeal resections render peripheral margins interpretable in most situations.\n  - 4.\n\t*Choose a method of resection.* Multiple methods of EMR or ESD are currently used. EMR with a cap and snare technique or mucosal banding followed by a cauterized snare will resect into the submucosal layer of the esophagus, and the procedure is facile after a relatively short learning curve. The cap and band technique is the most commonly performed technique as the ER cap and snare alone has been associated with a higher cost and risk of perforation. Smaller lesions and selected lesions that are up to 2 cm can be removed entirely *en bloc* with suction cap techniques. Larger lesions resected with an EMR cap typically require a \u201cpiecemeal\u201d approach in which the lesion is removed by multiple applications of the cap and snare to include overlapping areas to avoid unresected mucosal bridges, ultimately resulting in a complete resection. In cases where a lesion is tough to lift or is a little larger, the authors will often use a larger oblique cap as these are capable of handling larger tissue areas. Another alternative is ESD ( Fig. 29.3 ). This more aggressive approach has the potential to achieve an *en bloc* resection for larger or deeper lesions; however, ESD skills are more difficult to master and there are more frequent reports of complications, such as perforation or bleeding. For this reason, it is performed only in selected centers where specialized training has been performed and there is adequate system support to increase the acuity of care.\n  - Retrieve the tissue samples and grossly examine the specimen to confirm complete capture and adequate margins. Take more tissue around the margins with additional ER if necessary to achieve a complete resection. Pinning the tissue to cork will help the pathologist to orient the deepest margin; omitting this step allows the tissue to invert its shape into a little mushroom button that may lead to misinterpretation of the deep margin.\n\tA set of six endoscopic photos depicts various discoveries and procedures in the gastrointestinal tract. The endoscopic views of the gastrointestinal tract, capture various discoveries and procedures labeled parts A to F. In part A, a close-up view depicts an aperture in the gastrointestinal lineage, possibly a lesion or ulcer. Part B displays a more significant section with visible abnormal tissue or lesions. Part C presents a different part of the tract, with potential changes in the lineage, with an instrument inserted. In part D, a close-up view depicts the application of a medical instrument, possibly for biopsy or treatment of the abnormal tissue. Part E displays a section of the gastrointestinal tract with visible changes in the tissue. Part F depicts a similar view that follows an intervention or treatment, with a close-up focus on the area of interest.\n\tFig. 29.2\n\tThree photos of endoscopy depict various stages of ulcerative lesions in the digestive tract. The photos present endoscopic views of the digestive tract. Part A depicts an early-stage ulcerative lesion with minimal damage to the mucosal lineage. Part B displays a more advanced ulcerative lesion with distinct irregularities on the surface. Part C represents a significantly damaged area with visible inflammation and possible necrosis in the lines, which indicates a severe condition.\n\tFig. 29.3\n  - 5.\n\t*Postresection management.* Patients are discharged home on the same day unless there are comorbidities or complications that direct otherwise. The authors typically allow full liquid diet on the first day, then liberalize the diet when symptoms allow, starting on a soft diet for the first few days after the procedure. Patients and caregivers need to be educated on expected outcomes and potential signs of complications. Expected short-term outcomes will include mild to moderate chest discomfort and odynophagia for a few days after resection, so a prescription compound may be provided that includes an ionic binder to help heal the iatrogenic ulcer and a local anesthetic to alleviate symptoms. Narcotics are not usually required; in our experience, GEJ ER is more easily tolerated than a high to mid-esophageal lesion. Mild to moderate dysphagia can be a frequent complaint associated with healing but most often subsides after 6 to 8 weeks. Most patients are already on an acid reduction medication. The authors recommend continuing with a high-dose PPI for at least 2 weeks after the ER, then resuming the previous dose that the patient was taking. If not on a PPI previously, a patient will typically be kept on them at least until the next endoscopic evaluation. Aggressive reflux control is imperative to successful EET. Patients with lower EAC with or without BE are typically maintained on PPIs indefinitely.\n\n#### Individualizing Therapy Based on Interpretation of Pathology\n\nConfirming the diagnosis by expert gastrointestinal pathologist and sometimes two is crucial in selection of treatment modality. Lesions that are limited to the mucosa are most often definitively treated with EMR. Submucosal invasion automatically upgrades the lesion and increases the risk of lymph node invasion and/or cancer-related events of recurrence or death significantly. LVI is the most important prognostic determinant of outcome for resected early-stage cancer. In current surgical literature, the risk of nodal involvement has been estimated to increase from 2% to 3% for a T1a lesion without LVI but up to 60%+ for T1b lesions with LVI. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Size of tumor and differentiation are other factors that have been shown to be independent prognostic variables in some studies, indicating that lesions less than 2 cm and well to moderately differentiated are less likely to harbor concurrent adenopathy. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nAccording to some reports it is possible to identify patients with early submucosal disease at low risk for nodal disease that may be adequately treated by ER alone. Given that there is still some question about interobserver variability regarding submucosal invasion and the presence of LVI even among expert pathologists, selecting appropriate patients who can avoid resection should be done only at centers of excellence and in the presence of a multidisciplinary group.\n\n#### Post-Endoscopic Resection Surveillance\n\nIt has been our practice to perform endoscopy every 2 to 3 months while in the process of ablating residual metaplasia/dysplasia, followed by increasing intervals between procedures depending on individual findings. The need for cross-sectional imaging is debated in small T1a lesions given the low risk of regional or distant metastasis, and it is not at all indicated for patients with dysplasia only. Patients at higher risk for regional and distant disease such as those with deeper or larger lesions, or those patients with LVI who have opted for endoscopic treatment alone based on risk for esophageal resection should undergo imaging every 4 to 6 months and consider EUS to screen for regional disease.\n\n## Endoscopic Resection, Mucosal Ablation, or Both?\n\nAfter initial endoscopic therapy directed at nodular areas, any remaining areas of metaplasia/dysplasia should undergo ablation with the goal of total eradication. Past reports indicated that untreated segments increased the risk of metachronous lesions to as high as 30%. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Combining ER with ablation to eradicate residual intestinal metaplasia is both safe and efficacious. Pouw et al. reported their experience with 23 patients who underwent EMR for visible lesions; 16 patients had early cancer and 7 patients had BE-HGD. In this study, RFA was performed at least 6 weeks after the EMR. CE-neoplasia was achieved in 100% of patients (median follow-up 22 months) and CE-IM in 88% of patients.\n\nAnother retrospective study reported on the treatment of 65 patients with EMR and RFA for nodular disease and an additional 104 patients treated with RFA alone for flat segments of Barrett\u2019s disease. There were no significant differences in eradication of dysplasia and intramucosal carcinoma between the two groups. The complication rates were also similar, including strictures that occurred in 4.6% of the EMR-before-RFA patient group and in 7.7% of patients in the RFA only group. This study suggests that similar results may be achieved when ER is reserved for dysplasia-associated lesions that are visible, while RFA alone may suffice for flat pathology.\n\nCertainly, there is the possibility that one could resect the entire area of pathology in the esophagus using ER techniques. This may be favorable in situations in which there is limited, noncircumferential disease. However, it is unadvisable to use ER in circumferential lesions as the severe stricture rate can reach 50%. In contrast, combined EMR with ablation may be the preferred approach over stepwise radical ER (SRER) for the treatment of Barrett\u2019s associated with early cancer. In a Dutch multicenter study, patients with a BE segment \u22645 cm containing HGD/early cancer were randomized to SRER or ER followed by RFA. Although both groups achieved excellent (>90%) and comparable rates of CE-neoplasia and CE-IM, those in the SRER group developed a significantly higher number of strictures requiring endoscopic dilation (88% in the SRER group vs. 14% in the EMR-RFA group; *P* <.001).\n\nEndoscopic treatment compares favorably with esophagectomy as well. A retrospective comparison of endoscopic therapy performed in 40 patients (22 with HGD and 18 with intramucosal cancer \\[IMC\\]) with esophagectomy in 61 patients (13 with HGD and 48 with IMC) reported that there was no difference in survival between the two groups (94% at 3 years). However, compared with esophagectomy, endoscopic therapy was associated with significantly lower morbidity (39% vs. 0%; *P* <.0001). One should note that endoscopic therapy was not finite in this study, consisting of 102 ERs and 79 ablations in 40 patients. Nonetheless, cost comparisons still seem to favor endoscopic treatment over esophageal resection in most situations.\n\nIn summary, ER followed by ablation is an effective treatment modality for early cancer arising in the setting of BE. However, these techniques are best performed at high-volume referral centers by experienced endoscopists. The outcomes may not apply to general practices.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nEndoscopic eradication therapies have been shown to be effective and safe in the treatment of patients with BE-HGD and early esophageal cancer while preserving the esophagus. ER is currently the cornerstone modality. Ablation alone can be done, but it serves its best role as adjunct when performed with resection or in purely flat mucosa devoid of visible lesions. It can still be performed after ER; however, done *a priori* renders ER challenging. Attempts at total eradication of all dysplasia/metaplasia followed by close surveillance is recommended after endoscopic therapy because of the risk of recurrence. Given the complexities in the evaluation and management of these patients, they are best managed by a multidisciplinary team in a tertiary referral center with expertise in esophageal diseases.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Spechler S.J., Sharma P., Souza R.F., et al.: American Gastroenterological Association medical position statement on the management of Barrett\u2019s esophagus . Gastroenterology 2011; 140: pp. 1084-1091.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Sampliner R.E.: Practice guidelines on the diagnosis, surveillance and therapy of Barrett\u2019s esophagus . Am J Gastroenterol 1998; 93: pp. 1028-1031.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: Jung K.W., Talley N.J., Romero Y., et al.: Epidemiology and natural history of intestinal metaplasia of the gastroesophageal junction and Barrett\u2019s esophagus: a population-based study . Am J Gastroenterol 2011; 106: pp. 1447-1455.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Hvid-Jensen F., Pedersen L., Drewes A.M., S\u00f8rensen H.T., Funch-Jensen P.: Incidence of adenocarcinoma among patients with Barrett\u2019s esophagus . N Engl J Med 2011; 365: pp. 1375-1383.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: Hur C., Miller M., Kong C.Y., et al.: Trends in esophageal adenocarcinoma incidence and mortality . Cancer 2013; 119 (6): pp. 1149-1158.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n6.: Goldblum J.R.: Barrett\u2019s esophagus and Barrett\u2019s-related dysplasia . Mod Pathol 2003; 16: pp. 316-324.\n\nView In Article\n\n7.: Shaheen N.J., Sharma P., Overholt B.F., et al.: Radiofrequency ablation in Barrett\u2019s esophagus with dysplasia . N Engl J Med 2009; 360: pp. 2277-2288.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n8.: Phoa K.N., van Vilsteren F.G., Weusten B.L., et al.: Radiofrequency ablation vs endoscopic surveillance for patients with Barrett\u2019s esophagus and low grade dysplasia: a randomized cli