xt and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies. For all open access content, the relevant licensing terms apply.\n\n RELX''%20d=''M20.7%2023.4c11%200%2024.2-2.6%2024.2-13.1C44.9%202.8%2037.2%200%2030.3%200%2019.6%200%200%206%200%2027c0%2010.5%208%2016.6%2020.8%2016.6%2013.5%200%2023.2-8.8%2026.2-20.5C39.1%2036.7%2029%2041%2021%2041%2010.7%2041%206.8%2033.4%206.8%2027%205.869%2013.417%2016.685%201.91%2030.3%202c6.1%200%209.7%204%209.7%208.3%200%2011.9-17.2%2011.5-25%2011.5h-3.8l-1.6%201.8c3.6.5%208.5%201.5%2014%204.2%2011.1%205.6%2021.7%2020.6%2035.6%2020.6%205%200%206.4-1.6%207.4-3-6.9%204.4-18.3-3.1-24.5-9-5-4.8-9.6-10.2-21.4-13.1''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23e9711c''/%3e%3cpath%20clip-path=''url(%23b)''%20d=''M89.3%2043.6c-.5%200-.7-.2-.8-.6l-7-14.5h-6.1c-.2%200-.3.1-.3.3V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.6.6h-5.1c-.4%200-.6-.3-.6-.6V7c0-.4.2-.6.6-.6h13.9c6.6%200%2011.5%204.6%2011.5%2011.1%200%205-2.7%208.7-6.9%2010.3L95.5%2043c.2.3%200%20.7-.4.7h-5.8zm-.7-26.2c0-3.2-2.2-5.3-5.5-5.3h-7.7c-.2%200-.3.1-.3.4v9.9c0%20.2%200%20.3.3.3H83c3.3%200%205.5-2%205.5-5.3M101%206.9c0-.4.3-.6.6-.6h21.8c.4%200%20.6.2.6.6v4.7c0%20.3-.2.5-.6.5h-15.8c-.2%200-.3.1-.3.4v9c0%20.3.1.4.3.4h12.7c.4%200%20.6.2.6.5v4.7c0%20.4-.2.6-.6.6h-12.7c-.2%200-.3%200-.3.3v9.4c0%20.3.1.4.3.4h15.8c.4%200%20.6.2.6.5V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.6.6h-21.8c-.3%200-.6-.3-.6-.6V7zm28.8%200c0-.4.2-.6.5-.6h5.2c.3%200%20.6.2.6.6v30.5c0%20.3%200%20.4.3.4H151c.3%200%20.5.2.5.5V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.5.6h-20.8c-.3%200-.517-.3-.5-.6V7zm47.7%2036.7c-.4%200-.6-.2-.8-.5l-7.3-12.7-7.4%2012.7c-.2.3-.4.5-.8.5h-5.8c-.3%200-.5-.3-.3-.7L166%2024.3%20156%207.1c-.2-.4%200-.7.3-.7h5.8c.4%200%20.6.1.8.5l6.5%2011.3h.1L176%206.9c.2-.4.5-.5.9-.5h5.7c.4%200%20.5.3.3.7l-10%2017.2L183.7%2043c.2.4%200%20.7-.3.7h-5.8zM192.015%2019c-.2%200-.338-.004-.3-.2V8.4h-3.3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[28. Epidemiology, Risk Factors, and Clinical Manifestations of Esophageal Cancer - ClinicalKey|28. Epidemiology, Risk Factors, and Clinical Manifestations of Esophageal Cancer]]\n**Next:** [[30. Endoscopic Ultrasound of the Esophagus - ClinicalKey|30. Endoscopic Ultrasound of the Esophagus]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "29. Endoscopic Management of High-Grade Dysplasia and Superficial Esophageal Carcinoma - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Endoscopic Management of High-Grade Dysplasia and Superficial Esophageal Carcinoma', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Endoscopic Management of High-Grade Dysplasia and Superficial Esophageal Carcinoma', 'Findings Surveillance/Management', 'Endoscopic Eradication Therapy', 'Endoscopic Resection, Mucosal Ablation, or Both?', 'Screening and Surveillance', 'Endoscopic Evaluation and Staging', 'Endoscopic Management of High-Grade Dysplasia and Superficial Esophageal Carcinoma / Findings Surveillance/Management', 'Endoscopic Management of High-Grade Dysplasia and Superficial Esophageal Carcinoma / Endoscopic Eradication Therapy', 'Endoscopic Management of High-Grade Dysplasia and Superficial Esophageal Carcinoma / Endoscopic Resection, Mucosal Ablation, or Both?'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '29', '284-294', 2, 53, FALSE, TRUE),
('Endoscopic Evaluation of the Esophagus: Key Components for Surgeons', 'shackelford-9th-ed-3-endoscopic-evaluation-of-the-esophagus-key-components-for-surgeons', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Endoscopic Evaluation of the Esophagus: Key Components for Surgeons\n\nCorbin Cleary; Clayton Rooks; Jacob R. Moremen\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 3, 23-32\n\nAny surgeon performing foregut operations should be a competent endoscopist to optimally understand the full spectrum and impact of the disease states in question. By its nature, a surgical view of endoscopy will be one that focuses principally on treatable disorders and less on esoterica. However, surgeons need to know a broad spectrum of findings to better distinguish those requiring intervention from those best left alone.\n\nEndoscopically the esophagus is a slightly irregular muscular tube whose primary function is to convey swallowed material from the mouth to the stomach. It is demarcated by high-pressure sphincters at each end\u2014the upper esophageal sphincter (UES) proximally and the lower esophageal sphincter (LES) distally\u2014the latter of which is discussed in detail later. The whole of the esophagus is approximately 25 cm in length measured from its origin in the neck (UES) just below the cricoid cartilage (approximately 15 cm from the incisors endoscopically) to its termination in the abdomen at the esophagogastric junction (EGJ) (approximately 40 cm from the incisors). Proximally, the UES separates the pharynx from the esophagus. The UES extends approximately 3 cm in length and comprises three skeletal muscle groups: the distal portion of the inferior pharyngeal constrictor, the cricopharyngeus, and the circular muscle of the proximal esophagus. Introduction of the endoscope into the UES often causes gagging, and the muscles relax only briefly during a swallow. Consequently, the endoscope typically is passed quickly through the UES, and endoscopic visualization of its mucosal lining often is limited (Zenker\u2019s diverticula can be overlooked as a result) ( Fig. 3.1 ).\n\nA photo shows a pouch formation in the upper esophagus covered with a smooth and moist esophageal lining. An arrow points at the pouch formation. Ch03\n\nFig. 3.1\n\nThe esophagus passes from the chest into the abdomen through the diaphragmatic hiatus. Approximately 2 cm of the distal esophagus normally lie within the abdomen ( Fig. 3.2 ). The LES comprises both the skeletal muscle of the crural diaphragm (external LES muscle) and the circular smooth muscle of the distal esophagus itself (internal LES muscle); however, endoscopists often refer to only the latter when describing the LES. Unlike the UES, endoscopic examination of the LES region generally is not limited either by sustained sphincter muscle contraction or by patient discomfort. Careful attention to unusual resistance at the LES can help identify achalasia or nonmucosal malignancies.\n\nAn anatomical diagram of the human esophagus at various points along the esophagus, with annotations for the esophagogastric junction. The anatomical diagram illustrates the human esophagus. Measurement markers indicate the distances in centimeters from the incisors, where 15 centimeters at the cervical esophagus, 20 centimeters at the upper thoracic region, 25 centimeters at the middle thoracic region, 30 centimeters at the lower thoracic region, and 40 centimeters at the esophagogastric junction. The sternal notch, azygos, and inferior pulmonary veins are key structures.\n\nFig. 3.2\n\nLandmark orientation may change with patient position among other variables. Here we describe a supine patient with the scope oriented 12 o\u2019clock ventrally. Within the chest at approximately 23 cm from the incisor teeth, the esophagus is indented on its left side by the aortic arch ( Fig. 3.3 ). Just below the arch at approximately 25 cm, the left main bronchus causes a subtle indentation on the left anterior aspect of the esophagus (see Fig. 3.3 ). Below the bronchus, the esophagus abuts the left atrium. In the typical esophagus, the heart causes no prominent indentation of the lumen, but atrial pulsations often can be visualized at a level approximately 30 cm from the incisors, particularly in the dilated esophagus.\n\nAn endoscopic photo shows the anatomical impression inside the proximal esophagus due to the aortic arch, left main bronchus, and vertebral column prominent along the esophageal wall. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.3\n\n## Mucosal Exam and Disorders\n\nA thorough investigation of the esophagus necessarily starts with an evaluation of the mucosa. The esophageal lumen is collapsed at rest and must be distended with air (room air or CO <sub>2 </sub> ) during endoscopy so that the stratified squamous epithelial lining can be visualized well. When so distended, the squamous epithelium appears pale, glossy, and relatively featureless. A detailed evaluation of the mucosa can provide the surgeon with a key understanding of the underlying pathology and provides hints as to associated issues awaiting discovery. This pale, smooth tissue continues caudally until the surgeon reaches the squamocolumnar junction (SCJ) where changes in color and texture indicate the presence of gastric tissue.\n\n### Reflux Esophagitis\n\nDamage to the esophagus, whether due to reflux, chemical irritation, or immunological causes, can be described as esophagitis. There is a wide spectrum of presentations of esophagitis, and the Los Angeles Classification was developed to create a common vocabulary ( Table. 3.1 ). Based on the number of lesions, their size, and their circumference, the Los Angeles Classification grades esophagitis from A to D. Grade A esophagitis, for example, is confined to folds with one or more mucosal breaks less than 5 mm in length. Grade D esophagitis, on the other hand, demonstrates a more severe disease; mucosal breaks are present between folds and over 75% of the luminal circumference is affected ( Figs. 3.4 and 3.5 ).\n\nTable 3.1\n\nLos Angeles Classification for Reflux Esophagitis\n\n<table><tbody><tr><td align=\"\" colspan=\"2\">The Los Angeles Classification</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Grade A</td><td align=\"\">\u22651 mucosal break &lt;5 mm long that does not extend between the tops of 2 mucosal folds</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Grade B</td><td align=\"\">\u22651 mucosal break &gt;5 mm long that does not extend between the tops of 2 mucosal folds</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Grade C</td><td align=\"\">\u22651 mucosal break that extends between the tops of \u22652 mucosal folds involving &lt;75% of the esophageal circumference</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Grade D</td><td align=\"\">\u22651 mucosal break that involves \u226575% of the esophageal circumference</td></tr></tbody></table>\n\nAn endoscopic photo shows evident mucosal damage in the esophagus near the folds. The damaged regions appear red and irritated. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.4\n\nTwo endoscopic photos show the severe form of esophageal inflammation. Large mucosal damage appears across the esophageal wall more prominent and swollen in the right photo. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.5\n\n### Nonreflux Esophagitis\n\nWhile reflux plays a significant role in esophagitis, there are a number of other potential causes of which the endoscopist should be aware. Like most mucosal surfaces, the esophagus can be susceptible to infection, and a variety of organisms can cause esophagitis. Most commonly, infectious esophagitis is caused by *Candida* . Typically, candidal esophagitis is found in patients who are immunocompromised, either through underlying immunological disorders or other conditions, including medical suppression, diabetes mellitus, pregnancy, steroid or antibiotic therapy, or poor clearance from esophageal dysmotility.\n\nCandidal esophagitis ( Fig. 3.6 ) often presents with pain and difficulty swallowing. Oral thrush may be seen at the same time. Endoscopically, it often appears with white or yellow adherent plaques on the esophageal mucosa, unable to be washed off with simple irrigation. When suspected, brushings and biopsies should be taken. Treatment consists of systemic antifungal therapy.\n\nAn endoscopic photo shows the fungal infection of the esophagus with white lesions on the esophageal lining. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.6\n\nEsophagitis can also occur due to viral infection. Again, immunocompromised patients are the primary victims. Both herpes simplex virus (HSV) and cytomegalovirus (CMV) can cause esophagitis. As with most causes of esophagitis, dysphagia and odynophagia are the most common presentations. Endoscopically, HSV will typically present in the distal esophagus with vesicles or \u201cpunched out ulcers\u201d; CMV presents as few or solitary ulcers that are typically large, some up to 1 cm.\n\nEsophagitis can also be caused by synthetic materials. Corrosive esophagitis and drug-induced esophagitis both represent the esophagus responding to damaging foreign stimuli. Corrosive esophagitis is caused by ingestion of either acidic or alkaline substances. Perforation, strictures, and motility disorders are all possible outcomes. Pill esophagitis is one form of drug-induced esophagitis. In this subset of esophageal inflammation, the mucosa of the esophagus is exposed to an ingested drug, causing injury. This typically occurs at the narrowing points of the esophagus, namely at the arch of the aorta as it crosses the esophagus. Localized ulceration is the rule, but occasionally significant hemorrhage can develop.\n\nAdditional potential causes of nonreflux esophagitis are many, including Crohn\u2019s disease (which is typically found in the distal esophagus and seen rarely in isolation), lymphocytic esophagitis, sloughing esophagitis, and radiation-induced esophagitis. Radiation-induced esophagitis is seen in patients receiving therapy for head/neck or thoracic lesions; it can present in both the acute and chronic phases.\n\n### Eosinophilic Esophagitis\n\nEosinophilic esophagitis (EoE) is a unique, immunological form of nonreflux esophagitis. Histologically, EoE is identified by the presence of eosinophilic invasion into the mucosal layer of the esophagus. EoE is an allergic disorder caused by food or environmental factors, leading to mucosal damage. These allergens lead to increased eosinophilic recruitment and subsequent mucosal invasion. Typically, it presents as dysphagia, although reflux, retrosternal pain, and dyspepsia can also be present. Long-term effects include stricture development and decreased esophageal laxity ( Fig. 3.7 ).\n\nAn endoscopic view shows a series of concentric rings indentation along the esophageal lining similar to the trachea. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.7\n\nEndoscopic evaluation of EoE demonstrates a broad spectrum of disease. Normal mucosa may be noted, but classically, \u201ctrachealization of the esophagus\u201d with demonstration of circular rings, white exudates and nodules, and linear furrows can be appreciated ( Fig. 3.8 ). Diagnosis is based on symptoms, exclusion of other causes of esophagitis, and mucosal biopsies demonstrating more than 15 eosinophils per high-powered field. Biopsies should be performed throughout the esophagus, with at least five specimens taken due to uneven distribution of eosinophils in the mucosa.\n\nA photo of the inner esophagus shows long and narrow grooves forming a rough esophageal lining. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.8\n\n### Barrett\u2019s Esophagus\n\nBarrett\u2019s esophagus is the condition in which metaplastic columnar epithelium that predisposes to cancer development replaces the stratified squamous epithelium normally lining the distal esophagus. Although there are emerging nonendoscopic screening tools available, endoscopic examination and biopsy are still required to establish a diagnosis of Barrett\u2019s esophagus. Specifically, the endoscopist must ensure that the following two criteria are fulfilled : (1) columnar epithelium lines the distal esophagus and (2) biopsy specimens of the columnar-lined esophagus show specialized intestinal metaplasia with goblet cells. To document that columnar epithelium lines the esophagus, the endoscopist must identify both the SCJ and gastroesophageal junction (GEJ) ( Fig. 3.9 ). Few studies have addressed specifically the problem of endoscopic localization of the GEJ, and even in those that have done so, the accuracy of the criteria used cannot be assessed meaningfully in the absence of a gold standard. This unresolved problem continues to confound clinicians and investigators who deal with Barrett\u2019s esophagus.\n\nA diagram depicts the esophageal lining in the esophagogastric junction. The squamocolumnar junction appears at the distal esophagus followed by the columnar lined esophagus at the gastric inlet. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.9\n\nColumnar epithelium has a reddish color and coarse texture on endoscopic examination, whereas squamous epithelium has a pale, glossy appearance. Narrow band imaging (NBI) is invaluable for assessing this ( Fig. 3.10 ). The juxtaposition of these epithelia at the SCJ forms a visible line commonly called the Z-line. When the SCJ and GEJ coincide ( Fig. 3.11 ), the entire esophagus is lined by squamous epithelium. When the SCJ is located proximal to the GEJ (see Fig. 3.9 ), there is a columnar-lined segment of esophagus, which may be circumferential or noncircumferential to varying lengths. If the endoscopist takes biopsy specimens from that columnar-lined segment and histologic evaluation shows specialized intestinal metaplasia, then the patient has Barrett\u2019s esophagus (by the US definition of Barrett\u2019s esophagus). Though guidelines vary and will be discussed in detail elsewhere, four-quadrant random biopsies every 1 to 2 cm of salmon-colored mucosa should be taken in addition to targeting any irregular or nodular areas.\n\nTwo endoscopic photos show changes in the esophagus lining. The left photo shows salmon mucosa lining under white light prevailing deeper in the esophagus. The right photo depicts the affected esophageal lining in dark patches extending deeper into the esophagus.\n\nFig. 3.10\n\nA diagram of a human stomach with its curved shape and folded internal textures. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.11\n\nSeveral classification systems for Barrett\u2019s esophagus have been proposed based on the extent of columnar-lined esophagus and on the appearance of the Z-line. Perhaps, the most widely used system classifies patients as having either \u201clong-segment\u201d or \u201cshort-segment\u201d Barrett\u2019s esophagus. Patients have long-segment Barrett\u2019s esophagus when the distance between the GEJ and the most proximal extent of the Z-line is 3 cm or more, and they have short-segment Barrett\u2019s esophagus when that distance is less than 3 cm. Though the 3-cm length distinction is somewhat arbitrary, the length of the Barrett\u2019s esophagus segment has direct bearing on the risk of malignancy.\n\nThe Prague classification describes both the extent of circumferential metaplasia (C, measured from the GEJ to the most proximal extent of circumferential esophageal metaplasia) and of the longest tongue of esophageal metaplasia (M, measured from the GEJ to the most proximal extent of esophageal metaplasia). For example, a patient classified as C2M5 has columnar metaplasia involving the distal 2 cm of the esophagus in a circumferential fashion with a tongue of metaplasia that extends 5 cm above the GEJ ( Fig. 3.12 ).\n\nA magnified endoscopic view of Barrett''s esophagus shows a distinct pit pattern in the columnar epithelium. An arrow marks the circumferential extent of Barrett''s segment denoted by C 2, while another arrow points to the maximal extent denoted by M 5, indicating the infected area of columnar lined mucosa.\n\nFig. 3.12\n\nA variety of specialized endoscopic techniques are available for the evaluation of Barrett\u2019s esophagus. These techniques have been used to enhance the identification of both intestinal metaplasia in the esophagus and neoplasia in Barrett\u2019s esophagus. Only chromoendoscopy, either via dyes or virtual chromoendoscopy, is recommended by the most recent American College of Gastroenterology (ACG) and American Society for Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ASGE) guidelines.\n\nIn dye-based chromoendoscopy, the esophageal mucosa is painted with dyes that either stain the cells that absorb them or that accumulate in mucosal crevices to enhance the architectural features of the epithelium. However, in clinical practice dye-based techniques have problems that limit their usefulness, including the need for spray catheters, difficulty in uniform coating, and their time-consuming nature. Only acetic acid, which enhances mucosal surface patterns by contrast staining ( Fig. 3.13 ), met the ASGE PIVI (Preservation and Incorporation of Valuable Endoscopic Innovations) thresholds.\n\nAn endoscopic view shows the pit pattern of columnar epithelium at the squamocolumnar junction. The textured columnar epithelium is prominent with red outlines. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.13\n\nElectronic or virtual chromoendoscopy systems are now a part of all endoscope platforms: NBI (Olympus, Center Valley, PA, USA), Fujinon intelligent color enhancement (Fujinon, Wayne, NJ, USA), and i-Scan (Pentax Medical, Montvale, NJ, USA); these systems allow for a better view of the mucosal surface and vascular patterns. NBI is the most widely available VC and uses blue light with narrow-band filters to produce a high-resolution image of mucosal patters without the need for dyes. Both ACG and ASGE give a strong recommendation to use of chromoendoscopy along with white-light endoscopy in Barrett\u2019s esophagus surveillance.\n\n### Esophageal Cancer\n\nAs a result of the improved diagnosis, treatment, and surveillance of Barrett\u2019s esophagus, esophageal adenocarcinoma is being diagnosed in asymptomatic patients more than ever before ( Fig. 3.14 ). While surveillance endoscopies have certainly led to earlier diagnoses in some patients, the majority of esophageal cancers are still found in symptomatic patients. Symptoms prompting further investigation can include dysphagia, weight loss, and bleeding resulting in iron deficiency anemia. Symptomatic esophageal cancers tend to be more advanced at the time of diagnosis and appear as masses protruding into the esophageal lumen on conventional endoscopy. The lesions are often nodular, irregular, ulcerated, and may have a different color and texture than the surrounding normal mucosa ( Fig. 3.15 ). Esophageal cancers can also appear as strictures endoscopically. Squamous cell and adenocarcinomas of the esophagus cannot be differentiated by endoscopic appearance, but tumor location can be an important clue regarding the histology. Tumors that involve the proximal and mid-esophagus are more likely to be squamous cell carcinomas. Distal esophageal tumors can be either squamous cell carcinomas or adenocarcinomas, though the vast majority are adenocarcinomas. It can be especially difficult to determine the origin of an adenocarcinoma that straddles the GEJ ( Fig. 3.16 ). Such tumors can arise either from Barrett\u2019s esophagus or the proximal stomach, and symptomatic esophageal adenocarcinomas can be so large that underlying Barrett\u2019s esophagus is difficult to visualize. If no Barrett\u2019s esophagus is apparent, investigators have relied on the location of the tumor epicenter to classify the tumor as esophageal or \u201ccardiac\u201d to guide treatment decisions.\n\nAn endoscopic photo of the esophagus that represents areas of inflammation and ulceration. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.14\n\nA closer view of a section of anatomical tissue characterized by areas with signs of swollen structures. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.15\n\nTwo photos show adenocarcinoma at the gastroesophageal junction. Photo A captures the abnormal growth from the esophageal side, while photo B shows it from the gastric side. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.16\n\n## Structural Exam and Disorders\n\n### Endoscopic Evaluation of the Esophagogastric Junction\n\nThe EGJ is the level at which the esophagus ends and the stomach begins. Unfortunately, there are no universally accepted landmarks that clearly delimit the distal esophagus and the proximal stomach, and the EGJ has been defined differently by anatomists, radiologists, surgeons, and endoscopists. Landmarks suggested by anatomists, such as the peritoneal reflection or the character of the muscle bundles in the esophageal wall, are not useful for endoscopists. Radiographically, considering a target as broad as the binary choice of hiatal hernia or not\u2014let alone precise EGJ location\u2014in a high-risk group (prebariatric surgery), the sensitivity and specificity for the preoperative barium swallow were only 30% and 94%, respectively. Manometrically the distal border of the LES can define the GEJ precisely, but it is not straightforward to correlate this endoscopically. This ambiguity has implications for evaluating the need for and subsequent quality of fundoplication and cruroplasty.\n\nWhen defining GEJ, without a clear-cut \u201cgold standard\u201d any proposed landmarks can be considered arbitrary. For this reason, the surgeon might better consider the implications of the EGJ as an antireflux barrier (ARB) and be familiar with the anatomic components contextually. The ARB is an amalgamation of anatomic and physiologic structures whose degradation toward hiatus hernia (discussed elsewhere) ( Fig. 3.17 ) correlates with worsening gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) and its consequences, namely Barrett\u2019s esophagus. The components of the ARB include the LES and its sling fibers, the crural diaphragm, and the gastroesophageal flap valve. Historically, these have been best described using the Hill classification. Described classically in 1996, the Hill classification grades the endoscopic view of the EGJ in retroflex, specifically noting the integrity of the flap valve. Endoscopic evaluation of the gastroesophageal valve was further described by Jobe et al. ( Fig. 3.18 ) who suggested 10 criteria to be evaluated and commented on during endoscopy: lip thickness, body length, anterior groove, posterior groove, lesser curvature width, adherence to endoscope, respiration, type, intraabdominal location, proper repair position, and unique characteristics. A thorough understanding of these parameters is essential to diagnosing, monitoring, and intervening at the hiatus on behalf of the GERD patient.\n\nA closer view of the gastroesophageal junction shows folds in the lining. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.17\n\nA diagram shows the gastroesophageal valve positioned within the esophagus. The diagram depicts the anterior positioned to the right and the posterior to the left in anatomical terms. The valve body beneath the lining forms a curved surface and a lip at the beginning of the curved surface.\n\nFig. 3.18\n\nIn 2022 the American Foregut Society (AFS) convened a working group to propose a more nuanced update to the Hill classification that takes all the ARB components into consideration and may prove more practically useful for the surgeon endoscopist than the Hill grade alone. Prior to the retroflex exam, one first needs observe the EGJ antegrade before breaching with the scope or significantly insufflating the stomach. Mucosal exam is discussed earlier. Here we consider useful landmarks. Suggested endoscopic criteria for locating the EGJ include (1) the level at which the tubular esophagus flares to become the sack-like stomach, (2) the proximal margin of the gastric rugal folds when the esophagus and stomach are partially distended, and (3) the Z-line or SCJ. There are many reasons why none of these three criteria alone will precisely locate every EGJ, but searching routinely for congruence in 2 or 3 of them will typically yield reliable results. The SCJ should be distal to the high-pressure zone (HPZ) or EGJ. The EGJ should open slightly with respiration, but patient observation may also reveal a sliding hiatal hernia. This is also an ideal moment to observe a subtle stricture or Schatzki ring ( Fig. 3.19 ).\n\nThe closer view of the thin and circular band of tissue in the lower esophagus. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.19\n\nNow passing into the stomach, we again consider the AFS approach to the valve assessment. Germane to our topic is the need for 30 to 45 seconds of insufflation of the stomach or sufficient time to flatten most of the rugal folds, followed by retroflexed provocative maneuver. Rotating the retroflexed scope onto the lesser curve and drawing back in toward the hiatus will open the reluctant hiatus providing the most accurate assessment of the lateral separation of the crural pillars ( Fig. 3.20 ).\n\nAn inner view of the esophagogastric junction shows bulges and mucosal folds as the endoscope inspects the stomach portion. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.20\n\n### Endoscopic Evaluation of Patients Who Have Had Antireflux Surgery\n\nA critical skill for the surgeon endoscopist is to identify postsurgical anatomy accurately at the hiatus. Routine examination of the EGJ in retroflex within a sufficiently distended stomach will help familiarize one with the distinct differences of postsurgical anatomy. Endoscopy is being performed either to evaluate a wrap immediately postoperative or some amount of time later, likely due to recurrent symptoms of reflux or dysphagia. Here we discuss what the surgeon should expect to see in the newly constructed fundoplication and various malformations that might be seen in the symptomatic patient some amount of time after surgery. Magnetic sphincter augmentation, Collis gastroplasty, and transoral incisionless fundoplication are discussed in detail elsewhere and will not be covered here.\n\nThe two most commonly used fundoplication procedures in the United States (Nissen and Toupet) create characteristic folds in the proximal stomach that are best appreciated with the endoscope in the retroflexed position. As before, however, take time to examine the EGJ antegrade. The SCJ or the top of the rugal folds should now be below the HPZ created primarily by the crural pillars; however, the distinction between the fundoplication and cruroplasty contribution may not be evident. Particularly, in cases of Barrett\u2019s esophagus or dilated distal esophagus where the SCJ is incongruous with the EGJ, preoperative endoscopy is imperative to optimally understand the postoperative appearance and not wrongly assume a shortened esophagus is present.\n\nNow considering the symptomatic patient whether days or years postoperatively, the most common cause of return of GERD symptoms or new dysphagia will be hiatal hernia. The most common causes to look for are failure of cruroplasty, inadequate mediastinal dissection, or misplaced fundoplication. Be mindful of the previously mentioned unreliable SCJ and carefully evaluate both antegrade and retroflexed views of the EGJ.\n\nThe folds of the fundoplication should be located just below the diaphragm ( Fig. 3.21 ). If the folds are seen above the diaphragm, it is an indication that the fundoplication has herniated into the chest. Often a fundoplication will flatten out or seem to be not present in the setting of mediastinal herniation ( Fig. 3.22 ). Careful retroflexed examination will almost always demonstrate a widened hiatus with stomach above the diaphragm ( Fig. 3.23 ). A pouch of stomach proximal to the folds of the fundoplication when no hiatal hernia is present is rare and likely represents a poorly constructed fundoplication that incorporated the top of the stomach rather than the distal esophagus. The notion of a truly \u201cslipped\u201d fundoplication (e.g., a \u201cslipped Nissen\u201d) only occurs in the setting of mediastinal herniation. Gastric rugal folds above the pinch of the fundoplication might indicate that a Collis gastroplasty was performed as an esophageal extension of stomach is created, so the specifics of the prior surgical procedure are important to know, if possible, when evaluating the postsurgical patient.\n\nA photo captures an endoscope inside the esophagogastric junction. Stacked coils of the linings form circular folds around the endoscope. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.21\n\nA photo of an endoscope inside the esophagogastric junction with folded layers on the lining surrounding the scope. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.22\n\nAn examination of the inner lining of the esophagus with evident folds wrapping the endoscope. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.23\n\nTo consider the specific identification and evaluation of unknown hiatal operations, we return to the work of Jobe et al. who describe the Nissen fundoplication as \u201cstacked coils\u201d and Toupet as \u201comega\u201d shaped ( Figs. 3.21 and 3.24 ). The folds of a properly constructed fundoplication should be oriented parallel to the diaphragm. An oblique orientation of the folds suggests twisting of the fundoplication or improper construction of the wrap using the body rather than the fundus of the stomach ( Fig. 3.25 ). Either of these conditions can cause postoperative gastroesophageal reflux, dysphagia, or both. The folds should measure approximately 1 to 2 cm in span. A wider span indicates a too-generous fundoplication that can cause dysphagia.\n\nAn endoscope inspects the wrap caused by the folded lining in the stomach. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.24\n\nA closer view of the endoscope examines the esophagus and reveals the folds in the esophagus''s inner walls with the presence of a pouch. #REF!\n\nFig. 3.25\n\n## References\n\n1.: Netter F.H.: Anatomy of the esophagus . In Oppenheimer E. (eds): The CIBA Collection of Medical Illustrations. Vol. 3. Digestive System. Part I. Upper Digestive Tract . 1959. CIBA Pharmaceutical Company , New York pp. 34.\n\nView In Article\n\n2.: Goyal R.K., Martin S.B., Shapiro J., Spechler S.J.: The role of cricopharyngeal muscle in pharyngoesophageal disorders . Dysphagia 1993; 8: pp. 252.\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: Johnson L.F., Moses F.M.: Endoscopic evaluation of esophageal disease . In Castell D.O., Johnson L.F. (eds): Esophageal Function in Health and Disease . 1983. Elsevier Science Publishing Co., Inc. , New York pp. 237.\n\nView In Article\n\n4.: Cotton P.B., Williams C.B., Haycock A.: Upper endoscopy: diagnostic techniques . Cotton and Williams\u2019 Practical Gastrointestinal Endoscopy the Fundamentals . 2014. Wiley-Blackwell , Essay pp. 33-53.\n\nView In Article\n\n5.: Leiman D.A., Metz D.C.: Gastroesophageal reflux disease . Clinical Gastrointestinal Endoscopy . 2019. Elsevier , Essay pp. 268-278.\n\nView In Article\n\n6.: Almashat S.J., Duan L., Goldsmith J.D.: Non-reflux esophagitis: a review of inflammatory diseases of the esophagus exclusive of reflux esophagitis . Semin Diagn Pathol 2014; 31 (2): pp. 89-99.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n7.: Mohamed A.A., Lu X., liang , Mounmin F.A.: Diagnosis and treatment of esophageal candidiasis: current updates . Can J Gastroenterol Hepatol 2019; 2019: pp. 1-6.\n\nView In Article\n\n8.: Gonsalves N.P., Aceves S.S.: Diagnosis and treatment of eosinophilic esophagitis . J Allergy Clin Immunol 2020; 145 (1): pp. 1-7.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n9.: Lo W, Hamilton MJ. Eosinophilic esophagitis. Friedman S, & Blumberg RS, & Saltzman JR, eds. In: *Greenberger\u2019s CURRENT Diagnosis & Treatment Gastroenterology, Hepatology, & Endoscopy* . 4th ed. McGraw Hill.\n\nView In Article\n\n10.: Spechler S.J., Fitzgerald R.C., Prasad G.A., Wang K.K.: History, molecular mechanisms, and endoscopic treatment of Barrett\u2019s esophagus . Gastroenterology 2010; 138: pp. 854.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n11.: Spechler S.J.: The role of gastric carditis in metaplasia and neoplasia at the gastroesophageal junction . Gastroenterology 1999; 117: pp. 218.\n\nView In Article\n\n12.: Shaheen N.J., Falk G.W., Iyer P.G., et al.: Diagnosis and management of Barrett\u2019s esophagus: an updated ACG guideline . Am J Gastroenterol 2022; 117 (4): pp