R.K., Bauer J., Spiro H.M.: The nature and location of the lower esophageal ring . N Engl J Med 1971; 284: pp. 1175.\n\nView In Article\n\n22.: Goitein D., Sakran N., Rayman S., Szold A., Goitein O., Raziel A.: Barium swallow for hiatal hernia detection is unnecessary prior to primary sleeve gastrectomy . Surg Obes Relat Dis 2017; 13 (Issue 2): pp. 138-142.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n23.: Paull A., Trier J.S., Dalton M.D., Camp R.C., Loeb P., Goyal R.K.: The histologic spectrum of Barrett\u2019s esophagus . N Engl J Med 1976; 295: pp. 476.\n\nView In Article\n\n24.: Patti M.G., Goldberg H.I., Arcerito M., Bortolasi L., Tong J., Way L.W.: Hiatal hernia size affects lower esophageal sphincter function, esophageal acid exposure, and the degree of mucosal injury . Am J Surg 1996; 171 (1): pp. 182-186.\n\nView In Article\n\n25.: Nguyen N.T., Thosani N.C., Canto M.I., et al.: The American Foregut Society white paper on the endoscopic classification of esophagogastric junction integrity . Foregut 2022; 2 (4): pp. 339-348.\n\nView In Article\n\n26.: Hill L.D., Kozarek R.A., Kraemer S.J., et al.: The gastroesophageal flap valve: in vitro and in vivo observations . Gastrointest Endosc 1996; 44: pp. 541-547.\n\nView In Article\n\n27.: Jobe B.A., Kahrilas P.J., Vernon A.H., et al.: Endoscopic appraisal of the gastroesophageal valve after antireflux surgery . Am J Gastroenterol 2004; 99 (2): pp. 233-243.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n28.: Bozymski E.M.: Barrett\u2019s esophagus: endoscopic characteristics . In Spechler S.J., Goyal R.K. (eds): Barrett\u2019s Esophagus: Pathophysiology, Diagnosis, and Management . 1985. Elsevier Science Publishing Co., Inc. , New York pp. 113.\n\nView In Article\n\n29.: McClave S.A., Boyce H.W., Gottfried M.R.: Early diagnosis of columnar-lined esophagus: a new endoscopic criterion . Gastrointest Endosc 1987; 33: pp. 413.\n\nView In Article\n\n30.: Spechler S.J.: The management of patients who have \u201cfailed\u201d antireflux surgery . Am J Gastroenterol 2004; 99: pp. 552.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\nPrevious ChapterGo to the previous chapter\n\nNext ChapterGo to the next chapter\n\n281240\n\n  - Google Play - Go to our Google Play page\n  - Apple App Store - Go to our Apple App Store page\n  - Facebook - Go to our Facebook page\n  - LinkedIn - Go to our LinkedIn page\n  - X - Go to our X page\n\nElsevier (opens in a new window)\n\n  - Contact Us (opens in a new window)\n  - Resource Center (opens in a new window)\n  - Registered User Agreement (opens in a new window)\n  - Help (opens in a new window)\n  - Terms & Conditions (opens in a new window)\n  - Privacy Policy (opens in a new window)\n  - Accessibility (opens in a new window)\n\nWe use cookies to help provide and enhance our service and tailor content. By continuing you agree to the .\n\nAll content on this site: Copyright \u00a9 2025 Elsevier Inc. or its licensors and contributors. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies. For all open access content, the relevant licensing terms apply.\n\n RELX''%20d=''M20.7%2023.4c11%200%2024.2-2.6%2024.2-13.1C44.9%202.8%2037.2%200%2030.3%200%2019.6%200%200%206%200%2027c0%2010.5%208%2016.6%2020.8%2016.6%2013.5%200%2023.2-8.8%2026.2-20.5C39.1%2036.7%2029%2041%2021%2041%2010.7%2041%206.8%2033.4%206.8%2027%205.869%2013.417%2016.685%201.91%2030.3%202c6.1%200%209.7%204%209.7%208.3%200%2011.9-17.2%2011.5-25%2011.5h-3.8l-1.6%201.8c3.6.5%208.5%201.5%2014%204.2%2011.1%205.6%2021.7%2020.6%2035.6%2020.6%205%200%206.4-1.6%207.4-3-6.9%204.4-18.3-3.1-24.5-9-5-4.8-9.6-10.2-21.4-13.1''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23e9711c''/%3e%3cpath%20clip-path=''url(%23b)''%20d=''M89.3%2043.6c-.5%200-.7-.2-.8-.6l-7-14.5h-6.1c-.2%200-.3.1-.3.3V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.6.6h-5.1c-.4%200-.6-.3-.6-.6V7c0-.4.2-.6.6-.6h13.9c6.6%200%2011.5%204.6%2011.5%2011.1%200%205-2.7%208.7-6.9%2010.3L95.5%2043c.2.3%200%20.7-.4.7h-5.8zm-.7-26.2c0-3.2-2.2-5.3-5.5-5.3h-7.7c-.2%200-.3.1-.3.4v9.9c0%20.2%200%20.3.3.3H83c3.3%200%205.5-2%205.5-5.3M101%206.9c0-.4.3-.6.6-.6h21.8c.4%200%20.6.2.6.6v4.7c0%20.3-.2.5-.6.5h-15.8c-.2%200-.3.1-.3.4v9c0%20.3.1.4.3.4h12.7c.4%200%20.6.2.6.5v4.7c0%20.4-.2.6-.6.6h-12.7c-.2%200-.3%200-.3.3v9.4c0%20.3.1.4.3.4h15.8c.4%200%20.6.2.6.5V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.6.6h-21.8c-.3%200-.6-.3-.6-.6V7zm28.8%200c0-.4.2-.6.5-.6h5.2c.3%200%20.6.2.6.6v30.5c0%20.3%200%20.4.3.4H151c.3%200%20.5.2.5.5V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.5.6h-20.8c-.3%200-.517-.3-.5-.6V7zm47.7%2036.7c-.4%200-.6-.2-.8-.5l-7.3-12.7-7.4%2012.7c-.2.3-.4.5-.8.5h-5.8c-.3%200-.5-.3-.3-.7L166%2024.3%20156%207.1c-.2-.4%200-.7.3-.7h5.8c.4%200%20.6.1.8.5l6.5%2011.3h.1L176%206.9c.2-.4.5-.5.9-.5h5.7c.4%200%20.5.3.3.7l-10%2017.2L183.7%2043c.2.4%200%20.7-.3.7h-5.8zM192.015%2019c-.2%200-.338-.004-.3-.2V8.4h-3.3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n\n\nNeed help? Chat with AI Buddy!\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[2. Esophageal Motility: Techniques Used for the Diagnosis of Esophageal Motility Disorders and for Surgical Decision Making - ClinicalKey|2. Esophageal Motility: Techniques Used for the Diagnosis of Esophageal Motility Disorders and for Surgical Decision Making]]\n**Next:** [[4. pH and Impedance Evaluation of the Esophagus - ClinicalKey|4. pH and Impedance Evaluation of the Esophagus]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "3. Endoscopic Evaluation of the Esophagus: Key Components for Surgeons - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Endoscopic Evaluation of the Esophagus: Key Components for Surgeons', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Esophageal Endoscopy', 'Mucosal Disorders', 'Barrett''s Esophagus', 'Esophageal Cancer', 'Antireflux Surgery', 'Esophageal Endoscopy / Mucosal Disorders', 'Esophageal Endoscopy / Barrett''s Esophagus', 'Esophageal Endoscopy / Esophageal Cancer', 'Esophageal Endoscopy / Antireflux Surgery'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '3', '23-32', 2, 28, FALSE, TRUE),
('Endoscopic Ultrasound of the Esophagus', 'shackelford-9th-ed-30-endoscopic-ultrasound-of-the-esophagus', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Endoscopic Ultrasound of the Esophagus\n\nTahir Shaikh; Thomas Tielleman; Hendrikus Vanderveldt; Anna Tavakkoli\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 30, 295-301\n\nEndoscopic ultrasound (EUS) is an endoscopic procedure that combines the use of an endoscope (a flexible tube with a light and camera) and ultrasound technology to visualize and examine the internal organs and tissues in the upper and lower gastrointestinal (GI) tract. EUS is commonly used to evaluate the digestive system, including the esophagus, stomach, small intestine, colon, and rectum, as well as surrounding organs such as the pancreas, liver, and lymph nodes. The benefit of EUS, over other imaging modalities such as CT or MRI, is the potential to obtain tissue samples for histopathology and molecular testing. For this chapter\u2019s purposes, we will describe basic principles of endosonography and then focus on EUS in the esophagus as it pertains to esophageal cancer.\n\n## Principles of Endosonography\n\nThe fundamental principles of ultrasonography are based on high-frequency sound waves produced by applying voltage to a transducer (piezoelectric crystal) to produce images of the inside of the body. These sound waves are transmitted through the lumen of the GI tract and into the body. When the sound waves encounter a boundary between different types of tissue (such as between solid organs and fluid-filled areas), they are reflected back to the ultrasound probe (transducer). The time it takes for the sound waves to travel from the probe to the tissue and back again, as well as the strength of the reflected sound waves, is used to create an image of the inside of the body. Ultrasonography also allows for Doppler evaluation to measure blood flow in the body through a change in frequency of the sound wave.\n\nThe ability of a tissue to reflect or transmit ultrasound waves in the context of surrounding tissues is referred to as echogenicity. A visible difference in contrast will be visible on the screen whenever there is an interface of structures with different echogenicity. A structure can be classified as hyperechoic (white on the screen), hypoechoic (gray on the screen), isoechoic (same echogenicity as the surrounding tissue), or anechoic (black on the screen) based on its echogenicity. Tissues with high echogenicity, such as fat and air, reflect a greater amount of ultrasound waves and appear hyperechoic. Hypoechoic structures, such as lymph nodes and tumors, are darker than surrounding structures. Fluid-filled structures, such as cysts, arteries, and veins, tend to conduct sound waves producing anechoic images since they reflect fewer ultrasound waves. Isoechoic lesions can be difficult to distinguish from surrounding tissues on an ultrasound image, as they do not stand out due to their similar echogenicity. However, to the trained endosonographer, these tissues can be identified using subtleties in tissue interface and by their shape, size, and location within the body.\n\nThere are two main types of echoendoscopes: radial and linear. The radial EUS endoscope has a 270- to 360-degree ultrasonic probe at the tip used to examine organs and lesions on the wall close to the GI tract. The images on the monitor are perpendicular to the endoscope tip\u2019s axis in a cross-sectional orientation, like an axial CT scan image. The linear echoendoscope has a 100- to 180-degree ultrasonic probe along one side of the endoscope tip. This generates a view parallel to the echoendoscope\u2019s shaft. The optical viewing field is oblique to the axis of the endoscope, providing a 45- to 60-degree viewing angle. The greatest advantage of linear endoscopes is the ability to perform fine-needle aspiration or biopsy (FNA/FNB). The needle exits the endoscope obliquely along the side of the ultrasound probe, permitting the location and depth of the needle to be monitored under ultrasound guidance. The ability to advance a needle into the periluminal space allows not only for sampling of tissue but also for a myriad of therapeutic interventions within the esophagus.\n\nEndosonography of the esophagus is often more difficult since it is prone to tangential imaging as the ultrasound probe can lead to wall compression. Tangential imaging is when the transducer is at an angle other than 90 degrees to the structure. This is important because tangential imaging will lead to overestimating the thickness of the object being interrogated. Other imaging artifacts also exist within endosonography, including reverberation, mirror image, and attenuation artifact. There are several ways to reduce artifact imaging during endosonography of the esophagus. First, the use of a thin balloon over the ultrasound probe that fills with water can help to reduce attenuation artifacts that occur when there is insufficient contact between the ultrasound probe and the wall of the GI tract. A balloon is most often used during radial examinations of the esophagus; however, it is often unnecessary for linear examinations of the esophagus as excellent images can be obtained without them. Second, water can be placed into the esophageal lumen either through the biopsy channel or by pressing the air/water button. However, there is a risk of aspiration with high volumes of water in the esophagus, so water should be used cautiously.\n\n## Normal Anatomy of the Esophagus: Layers of the Esophagus\n\nKnowing the layers of the esophageal wall is vital to many aspects of esophageal endosonography, including staging of esophageal cancers and the evaluation of subepithelial lesions. There are five concentric layers of hyperechoic and hypoechoic tissue that can be visualized using EUS ( Fig. 30.1 ). Starting with layers closest to the tip of the scope, the first layer is hyperechoic and represents the interface between the superficial mucosa and water. The second layer is hypoechoic and is the deep mucosa. The third layer is hyperechoic and is the submucosa and the acoustic interface between the submucosa and muscularis propria. The fourth layer is hypoechoic and corresponds to the muscularis propria. Finally, the fifth hyperechoic layer corresponds to the outer adventitia at the level of the esophagus. The layers of the esophageal wall are best examined using a radial echoendoscope.\n\nAn ultrasound scan depicts a circular hollow structure with labeled regions identified as serosa, muscularis propria, submucosa, muscularis mucosa, and Mucosa. Ch30\n\nFig. 30.1\n\n## Normal Esophageal Anatomy: Radial Endosonography\n\nTo begin the EUS exam in the esophagus/mediastinum, place the radial echoendoscope at the gastroesophageal junction (GEJ). At the GEJ, inflate the balloon on the radial echoendoscope. At this location, the first structure seen is usually the aorta, a round, anechoic structure confirmed by using the Doppler flow. To present the radial echoendoscope image similar to a CT scan slice, use the electronic rotation function on the instrument panel to rotate the aorta to the 5 o\u2019clock position ( Fig. 30.2 ). Once the aorta is at the 5 o\u2019clock position, make sure the transducer is in the center of the balloon and start to slowly withdraw the scope.\n\nAn ultrasound scan depicts the liver, inferior vena cava, and aorta, labels mentioned in the scan, and 000 distal is mentioned at the top right corner. #REF!\n\nFig. 30.2\n\nAs the scope is withdrawn from the GEJ, the first anatomical landmark is the left atrium, which is usually seen between 33 and 35 cm from the incisors at the 10-12 o\u2019clock position ( Fig. 30.3 ). As the echoendoscope is withdrawn further, and the left atrium disappears, the endosonographer will note the subcarinal space at the 12 o\u2019clock position. The subcarinal space is 3 to 4 cm in length and should be examined for lymph nodes ( Fig. 30.4 ). Further withdrawal of the echoendoscope to about 27 to 29 cm from the incisors brings the endosonographer to the left and right mainstem bronchi at the 2 and 10 o\u2019clock position. The bronchi appear as bright strands on the monitor due to the air-filled bronchi. With further withdrawal, three anatomic findings can be noted over the span of next 2 to 3 cm: (1) the left and right main stem bronchi come together to form the trachea at the 12 o\u2019clock position; (2) the azygous vein joins the superior vena cava; and (3) elongation of the aorta to represent the aortic arch ( Fig. 30.5 ). Once the aortic arch is identified, advance the scope 2 to 3 cm to identify the aorta pulmonary window at the 3 o\u2019clock position. This window is an important window to identify pathological lymph nodes ( Fig. 30.6 ).\n\nAn ultrasound scan depicts the left atrium, spine, aorta, and subcarinal lymph node, with respective labels. #REF!\n\nFig. 30.3\n\nAn ultrasound scan depicts the aorta-pulmonary window, the aortic arch, and the carina, with respective labels. #REF!\n\nFig. 30.4\n\nAn ultrasound scan depicts the tracheal bifurcation, azygos arch, aortic arch, thoracic duct, and a labeled structure marked as X. #REF!\n\nFig. 30.5\n\nAn ultrasound scan depicts the aortic arch and aorta-pulmonary window, with an arrow that points to an abnormal or focused structure. #REF!\n\nFig. 30.6\n\n## Normal Esophageal/Mediastinal Anatomy: Linear Endosonography\n\nLinear ultrasound of the esophagus is more challenging because the plane of view is parallel to the axis of the endoscope and therefore less intuitive than radial EUS. Achieving an optimal window requires an in-depth knowledge of anatomy and optimal rotation of the echoendoscope. The linear EUS examination of the esophagus can be divided into the distal, mid, and proximal esophagus. After intubation of esophagus, the linear EUS scope is advanced to the GEJ before being withdrawn. The first structure to be identified is the descending thoracic aorta. Once the descending aorta is located, the scope can be rotated clockwise to identify the left atrium, which will appear as a contracting chamber with the mitral valve opening into the left ventricle. With continued withdrawal, the ascending aorta and pulmonary artery will come into view. This view is important for identifying subcarinal lymph nodes (thoracic node station 7, Fig. 30.7 ). Continued clockwise rotation at this level will bring the superior vena cava into view. As the scope continues to be withdrawn proximally, a blind spot will appear as the scope is pulled over the air-filled left mainstem bronchus. At this level, some rotation will show the arch of the aorta and just distal to the arch will be the cross-sectional view of the right pulmonary artery. This area is important because between the arch and the right pulmonary artery is the aortopulmonary window (thoracic nodal station 5, Fig. 30.8 ), where malignant mediastinal lymph nodes can often be identified. Further proximal withdrawal of the echoendoscope into the neck will identify the trachea anteriorly and the spine posteriorly. In addition, the left common carotid, right common carotid, and deep internal jugular veins may be identified in the very proximal esophagus.\n\nA diagram and an ultrasound scan depict the left atrium, left ventricle, pulmonary artery, and aortic outflow. The top portion is a labeled diagram with the left atrium, left ventricle, pulmonary artery, and aortic outflow. The diagram features these structures depicted with various shapes and colors. The bottom portion is an ultrasound scan of the same anatomical structures. It also labels the areas of the left atrium, left ventricle, and pulmonary artery, with the aortic outflow.\n\nFig. 30.7\n\nAn ultrasound scan depicts the pulmonary artery, the aortic arch, and the aorta-pulmonary window, with respective labels. #REF!\n\nFig. 30.8\n\nUpon returning the linear echoendoscope to the distal esophagus, the endosonographer can also identify the azygous vein. Rotation counterclockwise from the descending aorta will bring the azygous vein into view. Withdrawal of the EUS scope while tracking the azygous vein will then reveal the superior vena cava.\n\n## Indications for EUS of the Esophagus: Esophageal Cancer\n\nEUS is both a diagnostic and therapeutic tool with a wide variety of indications. In terms of the esophagus, the primary role for EUS includes local staging of esophageal cancer, evaluation, and sampling of subepithelial lesions, posterior mediastinal lesions, and paraoesophageal/posterior mediastinal adenopathy. For this chapter\u2019s purposes, we will focus on the role of EUS in esophageal cancer. When compared to CT scan, EUS is more accurate in T-staging of esophageal cancer. One systematic review found that the accuracy of T-staging by CT was 45% and EUS accuracy was 85%. Furthermore, EUS can allow for tissue acquisition (FNA) of nodal structures in and around the esophagus. Accurate evaluation of esophageal cancer using EUS requires an excellent understanding of esophageal and periesophageal anatomy, staging classifications and basic understanding of EUS techniques, and imaging interpretation. In this section, we will review the staging of esophageal cancer and the use of EUS for accurate T- and N-staging.\n\n### Esophageal Cancer Staging: AJCC Staging System\n\nEsophageal cancer staging is defined by the American Joint Committee on Cancer (AJCC) staging system that uses the tumor-node-metastasis (TNM) subclassifications. The TNM subclassifications are based on the depth of invasion of the primary tumor (T), lymph node involvement (N), and extent of metastatic disease (M). The TNM components for staging esophageal adenocarcinoma and squamous cell carcinoma are the same.\n\n### Esophageal Cancer Staging: Tumor Staging\n\nT1 disease includes cancerous involvement limited to the mucosa and/or the submucosa. T1 disease is further divided into T1a (disease confined to the mucosa) ( Fig. 30.9 ) when the mass invades into the lamina propria or the muscularis mucosae or T1b disease when invasion extends into the submucosa. T2 tumors invade the muscularis propria, which is the fourth hypoechoic layer seen on EUS ( Fig. 30.10 ). T3 tumors invade through the muscularis propria to involve the adventitia ( Fig. 30.11 ) and T4 disease is characterized by the tumor invading through the adventitia to involve adjacent structures ( Fig. 30.12 ).\n\nAn ultrasound scan depicts the vessel wall layers labeled muscularis mucosa, submucosa, tumor, and Adventitia. #REF!\n\nFig. 30.9\n\nAn ultrasound scan depicts a structure with a labeled area marked as Muscular Propria. #REF!\n\nFig. 30.10\n\nAn ultrasound scan depicts a lymph node, aorta, tunica, and other labeled structures. #REF!\n\nFig. 30.11\n\nAn ultrasound scan depicts a structure with an arrow that points to a labeled area. #REF!\n\nFig. 30.12\n\nThe role of EUS in superficial esophageal cancers is often debated. While some prior studies have suggested that EUS is not as accurate for T-staging in patients with early disease, since distinguishing between T1a, T1b, and T2 tumors can be difficult and may lead to overstaging, a meta-analysis found a sensitivity of 85% for distinguishing between T1a and T1b tumors in the esophagus with EUS. Distinguishing between T1a and T1b tumors is an important distinction because T1b tumors are associated with a 15% to 30% rate of lymph node metastasis and are treated with surgical resection, whereas T1a tumors have a <5% risk of nodal metastasis and can be treated with endoscopic resection. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Esophageal Cancer Staging: Nodal Staging\n\nThe nodal stage (N) of esophageal cancer is determined by the number of lymph nodes involved. Prior studies have found that the number of positive lymph nodes directly correlated with decreased survival with a 66-month median survival if zero malignant lymph nodes and a 6.5-month median survival if more than two malignant appearing lymph nodes. Furthermore, the detection of suspicious appearing lymph nodes has the potential to change treatment course for patients, especially if they have T2 disease.\n\nFeatures of malignant appearing lymph nodes on EUS include (1) size greater than 1 cm, (2) round shape, (3) clearly demarcated borders, and (4) hypoechogenic. When all four characteristics are present in a lymph node, the probability of metastatic involvement increases from 80% to 100%.\n\nThe accuracy of EUS for N-staging is superior to CT scan and improves with the addition of FNA of suspicious lymph nodes. In one prospective study, the accuracy of EUS FNA for lymph node staging was 87%, EUS alone was 74%, and helical CT was 51%. However, EUS FNA is often limited by potential seeding risk, added time, cost, and inability to sample nodes through tumor. For this reason, it is not part of our practice to perform FNA of suspicious appearing lymph nodes.\n\n### Esophageal Cancer Staging: Distant Metastasis Staging\n\nDistant metastasis (DM) is defined as the spread of tumor outside of regional lymph nodes, and the role of EUS in the setting of detecting metastatic disease is limited. In a large population-based study, the liver was the most common site of DM (33.4%), followed by distant (nonregional) lymph nodes (26.6%), lung (20.5%), bone (15.7%), and brain (3.8%). For the detection of distant metastases, positron emission tomography (PET) is more accurate than the combined use of CT and EUS (86% vs. 62%). The National Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) recommends a CT of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis at the time of cancer diagnosis. If no overt distant metastatic disease is seen on CT, both EUS and PET are recommended for additional examination.\n\n### Role of EUS in Obstructing Tumors\n\nObstructive esophageal tumors pose a challenge when using EUS for locoregional staging. The passage of the echoendoscope is prevented by 20% to 36% esophageal cancers due to the presence of high-grade malignant strictures. The inability to pass the EUS endoscope through the obstructing lesion may limit accurate assessment of the T and N stage. Accuracy of staging has shown to be much higher in traversable than in nontraversable esophageal cancers. However, there are a few methods that can be used to overcome the limitations of EUS in this setting:\n\n  - 1.\n\tPerforming a limited EUS staging examination proximal to the stricture. This approach may be a safe alternative to esophageal dilation. However, limited EUS staging has been found to have an accuracy of 28%. Lymph node assessment distal to the lesion is also limited due to the inability to visualize the celiac axis.\n  - 2.\n\tDilation of the stricture to allow for the passage of the 12- to 13-mm diameter echo endoscope. The success rate of passing the EUS scope was low (33%) and the risk of esophageal perforation has been shown to be as high as 24%. Furthermore, only 33% of patients had an accurate preoperative assessment of tumor depth after dilatation. A study conducted in 2000 demonstrated a higher success rate of passing the EUS endoscope (87%) when dilated to 14 to 16 mm.\n  - 3.\n\tUse of high-frequency catheter ultrasonic probes (HFCP) or mini probes. These probes are not routinely used in clinical practice. That said, their small diameter (3 mm) may permit passage of the probe beyond the stenotic lumen. A detailed examination of the esophageal wall may be obtained. However, the higher frequency (20 MHz) may limit the depth of the penetration of the ultrasound. As a result, the linear mini probe has been shown to have poor accuracy of N-staging and unable to discriminate between T3 and T4 tumors.\n\nIn our own practice, dilation of obstructing tumors is not regularly performed given the risk of perforation and the detailed information that could be obtained from CT and PET scans. Furthermore, obstructing tumors are usually at least T3 stage and require neoadjuvant chemotherapy for treatment.\n\n### Role of EUS After Neoadjuvant Chemotherapy\n\nThe role of EUS after neoadjuvant chemoradiation (CRT) in esophageal cancer is controversial because treatment can cause inflammation, fibrosis, and necrosis, leading to a hypoechoic appearance of the esophageal wall. These changes can limit the ability of EUS to accurately differentiate wall layers. One study found that EUS correctly identified a complete response to CRT in surgical specimens of esophageal cancer in 27% of cases. Another study found that the ability for EUS to downstage disease after chemotherapy was marginal, with tumor and nodal staging accuracy after chemotherapy of 60%. Because of the limited sensitivity, it is not common practice at our center to perform EUS after neoadjuvant chemotherapy.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nEUS is a powerful tool in the diagnosis and staging of esophageal cancer. Linear endoscopes have expanded the role of EUS to allow for accurate visualization and tissue acquisition (FNA/FNB), enabling accurate diagnosis and locoregional staging. The clinical data obtained by EUS has a meaningful and significant impact on the medical and surgical management of this condition. Although this chapter was limited to esophageal cancer, EUS also plays a significant role in the evaluation of esophageal subepithelial lesions, mediastinal masses and lymphadenopathy, and lung cancer. Since the introduction of EUS, advances in technology and techniques have dramatically expanded its applications from diagnostic to interventional EUS. In the coming years, EUS is expected to continue to evolve and emerge as an invaluable tool in the management of esophageal diseases.\n\n## References\n\n1.: ASGE Technology Committee , Murad F.M., Komanduri S., Abu Dayyeh B.K., et al.: Echoendoscopes . Gastrointest Endosc 2015; 82 (2): pp. 189-202.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Kimmey M.B., Martin R.W., Haggitt R.C., Wang K.Y., Franklin D.W., Silverstein F.E.: Hist