20.3-.2.6-.6.6h-21.8c-.3%200-.6-.3-.6-.6V7zm28.8%200c0-.4.2-.6.5-.6h5.2c.3%200%20.6.2.6.6v30.5c0%20.3%200%20.4.3.4H151c.3%200%20.5.2.5.5V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.5.6h-20.8c-.3%200-.517-.3-.5-.6V7zm47.7%2036.7c-.4%200-.6-.2-.8-.5l-7.3-12.7-7.4%2012.7c-.2.3-.4.5-.8.5h-5.8c-.3%200-.5-.3-.3-.7L166%2024.3%20156%207.1c-.2-.4%200-.7.3-.7h5.8c.4%200%20.6.1.8.5l6.5%2011.3h.1L176%206.9c.2-.4.5-.5.9-.5h5.7c.4%200%20.5.3.3.7l-10%2017.2L183.7%2043c.2.4%200%20.7-.3.7h-5.8zM192.015%2019c-.2%200-.338-.004-.3-.2V8.4h-3.3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[29. Endoscopic Management of High-Grade Dysplasia and Superficial Esophageal Carcinoma - ClinicalKey|29. Endoscopic Management of High-Grade Dysplasia and Superficial Esophageal Carcinoma]]\n**Next:** [[31. Esophageal Cancer Diagnosis and Staging - ClinicalKey|31. Esophageal Cancer Diagnosis and Staging]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "30. Endoscopic Ultrasound of the Esophagus - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Endoscopic Ultrasound of the Esophagus', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Endoscopic Ultrasound of the Esophagus', 'Principles of Endosonography', 'Normal Anatomy of the Esophagus: Layers of the Esophagus', 'Normal Esophageal Anatomy: Radial Endosonography', 'Normal Esophageal/Mediastinal Anatomy: Linear Endosonography', 'Indications for EUS of the Esophagus: Esophageal Cancer', 'Endoscopic Ultrasound of the Esophagus / Principles of Endosonography', 'Endoscopic Ultrasound of the Esophagus / Normal Anatomy of the Esophagus: Layers of the Esophagus', 'Endoscopic Ultrasound of the Esophagus / Normal Esophageal Anatomy: Radial Endosonography'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '30', '295-301', 2, 23, FALSE, TRUE),
('Esophageal Cancer Diagnosis and Staging', 'shackelford-9th-ed-31-esophageal-cancer-diagnosis-and-staging', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Esophageal Cancer Diagnosis and Staging\n\nTaha Qaraqe; Donald E. Low; Michal Hubka\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 31, 302-317\n\n## Epidemiology\n\nAn estimated 20,640 cases of esophageal cancer are diagnosed each year, and 16,410 deaths are expected from the disease in the United States according to the American Cancer Society. In 2020 there were 604,000 new cases and 544,000 related deaths, making it the seventh most common cancer and sixth most common cause of cancer-related death globally. Histologically, approximately 90% of esophageal cancers worldwide are squamous cell carcinoma (SCC). There is a marked variation in histologic incidence of esophageal cancer with respect to geographic region, patient intrinsic factors, and environmental exposures. In the United States, esophageal adenocarcinoma (AC) is the fastest growing subtype surpassing the incidence of esophageal SCC, in contrast to worldwide incidence where SCC still predominates. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> SCC is three times more frequent in Blacks compared with Caucasians. In the United States, the age-adjusted incidence among Whites is up to 5 per 100,000 versus 12.5 per 100,000 in France versus >100 per 100,000 in some parts of China. Esophageal cancer is usually three to four times more common in males than in females. Genetic predisposition has also been clearly established; however, other risk factors such as smoking and alcohol have been strongly associated with SCC, gastroesophageal reflux disease, Barrett\u2019s esophagus, and AC. In a 2021 prospective study using UK Biobank cohort of around 500,000 patients, participants with bronchiectasis, diabetes, Parkinson\u2019s disease, and eczema demonstrated a greater risk of esophageal cancer. Esophageal SCC usually arises in the upper and mid-esophagus, whereas esophageal AC develops in the distal esophagus and gastroesophageal junction (GEJ).\n\nEsophageal cancer remains one of the deadliest cancers with an overall 5-year survival rate estimated to be around 20%. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nEsophagectomy has historically been the mainstay treatment for regional invasive cancers; however, less invasive therapy such as endoscopic mucosal resection (EMR) has become an accepted alternative treatment for intramucosal (T1a) carcinoma. Multimodality therapy (neoadjuvant chemotherapy, or chemoradiotherapy followed by esophagectomy) has shown increased survival benefits when compared with surgery alone in locally advanced cases. Therefore, accurate staging is essential for a stage-directed treatment approach, for prognostication, for quality control in clinical trials, and for proper communication among healthcare workers as well as patients.\n\nBoth invasive and noninvasive staging techniques are employed. Although new technologies have upgraded staging accuracy, the best overall approach remains controversial. This chapter describes the current staging classifications and methods for esophageal cancer and highlights some of the difficulties and controversies.\n\n## Anatomy\n\nThe esophagus is approximately 20\u201330 cm in length and is located in the posterior mediastinum. It extends from the hypopharynx, posterior to the trachea and the heart, to the stomach passing through the esophageal hiatus. Through its descent, three critical anatomic points of narrowing are identified: the cricopharyngeus muscle, the broncho-aortic constriction, and the GEJ, which are also the most common sites of iatrogenic and mechanical perforation. The esophagus, a muscular tube, is composed of three general layers: mucosa (stratified squamous epithelium), submucosa, and muscularis propria. The tissue immediately attached to the esophagus is called the adventitia.\n\nThe esophagus is divided into three anatomic areas including cervical, thoracic, lower thoracic/esophagogastric junction ( Fig. 31.1 ). The esophagus can also be divided into thirds with 50% of AC occurring in the lower third. Cancer location in the esophagus does not play a role in AC staging, but it is necessary to subgroup pT3N0M0 SCC according to Eighth Edition of TNM. The primary site of tumors in the esophagus can be defined according to the typical endoscopic measurements from the incisors as the following:\n\n  - 1.\n\tThe cervical esophagus extends from the esophageal orifice (lower border of the cricoid cartilage) to the sternal notch (or thoracic inlet). Typical endoscopic measurements for the cervical esophagus from the incisors are from 15 to <20 cm.\n  - 2.\n\tThe upper thoracic esophagus extends from the sternal notch to the azygos vein arch. Typically, this is located from 20 to <25 cm from the incisors. The middle thoracic esophagus is bordered superiorly by the lower border of the azygos vein and inferiorly by the inferior pulmonary vein. Typical endoscopic measurements from the incisors are from 25 to <30 cm.\n  - 3.\n\tThe lower thoracic esophagus extends from below the inferior pulmonary vein to the GEJ. Typical measurements from the incisors are from 30 to 40 cm.\n\nA sagittal diagram of the esophagus shows anatomic landmarks and corresponding distances divided into cervical, thoracic, and abdominal regions. The labeled sagittal anatomical diagram of the human upper body with a focus on the esophagus highlights key landmarks along its course. The esophagus is illustrated begins at the pharynx, passing behind the trachea and heart, and terminating at the stomach. Distances from the incisors are indicated with dashed lines at intervals of 15, 20, 25, 30, and 40 centimeters. These distances correspond to labeled landmarks, including the upper esophageal sphincter at 15 centimeters, the sternal notch at 20 centimeters, the azygos vein at 25 centimeters, the inferior pulmonary vein at 30 centimeters, and the esophagogastric junction at 40 centimeters. These points demarcate the cervical esophagus, upper thoracic esophagus, middle thoracic esophagus, and lower thoracic esophagus. The surrounding anatomy, including the trachea, lungs, and major blood vessels.\n\nFig. 31.1\n\nAccording to the Eighth Edition of TNM, cancers involving the GEJ with an epicenter located within the proximal 2 cm of the cardia (dotted yellow line in Fig. 1 ) are staged as esophageal cancers, whereas tumors with an epicenter distally are staged as gastric cancers.\n\nLymph node involvement and number of lymph node metastases are important prognostic factors. The esophagus has a complex pattern of a dense and rich interconnected network of lymphatic vessels deep within submucosa that communicate freely longitudinally and transversally with the lymphatics of the muscular layers; thus, the pattern of lymph node metastases is very complex. Lymphatic channels in the submucosa facilitate the longitudinal spread of neoplastic cells along the esophageal wall. They can drain to cervical, tracheobronchial, mediastinal nodes, gastric, and celiac nodes.\n\nMany patients will present late in the disease process with unresectable tumors or distant metastasis. The most common distant metastatic sites are retroperitoneal or celiac lymph nodes, liver, lungs, and adrenal glands. Metastatic disease can also manifest as malignant pleural effusion, ascites, and bone pain of the affected site in bone metastasis or as hypercalcemia secondary to paraneoplastic syndrome. ACs most frequently metastasize to intraabdominal sites, whereas metastases from SCCs more commonly spread to intrathoracic or cervical locations.\n\n## Nomenclature\n\nDifferent stage nomenclatures are used to define the state of the disease at specific phases in the care of the cancer patients. These include the pretreatment stage or \u201cclinical stage,\u201d and postsurgical or \u201cpathologic stage.\u201d In addition, stage is further classified according to neoadjuvant therapy or at the time of recurrence.\n\nClinical stage or pretreatment stage is the extent of disease defined by diagnostic studies such as physical examination, imaging tests, endoscopic examination, biopsies of the primary tumor, and surgical exploration without resection of the affected areas. The nomenclature for clinical staging is cT, cN, and cM.\n\nPathologic stage is defined by the same diagnostic studies used for clinical staging supplemented by findings from surgical resection and histologic examination of the surgically removed tissues. This pathologic extent of disease is expressed as pT, pN, and pM.\n\nPost-therapy stage documents the extent of the disease after neoadjuvant therapy or when systemic therapy or radiation is the only treatment. Post-therapy stage may be recorded as clinical or pathologic depending on the source of post-treatment information. The nomenclature is recorded by adding the prefix \u201cyc\u201d or \u201cyp\u201d such as: ycT, ycN, ycM following neoadjuvant therapy; and ypT, ypN, ypM following surgical resection.\n\nRestaging is used to determine the extent of the disease following completion of neoadjuvant therapy and if a cancer recurs after treatment. This is done to determine if additional treatment is warranted or appropriate.\n\nIn addition to the TNM components, residual tumor and surgical margins are two important elements that may have a prognostic implication on the cancer patients after surgery. Residual tumor is denoted by the symbol \u201cR\u201d; it reflects the effect of therapy and the completeness of surgical resection and is a strong predictor of prognosis. Although not formally integrated into TNM staging, \u201cR\u201d status is an important component of the pathological record within the cancer registry.\n\nThe \u201cR\u201d categories for the primary tumor site are as follows:\n\n  - \u2022\n\tR0: no residual tumor\n  - \u2022\n\tR1: microscopic residual tumor\n  - \u2022\n\tR2: macroscopic residual tumor\n  - \u2022\n\tRX: presence of residual tumor cannot be assessed\n\nIt should be noted that \u201cR1\u201d designation varies among countries. In the United States, which uses the College of American Pathologists designation of R1 is \u201ctumors at the surgical margin,\u201d whereas the United Kingdom uses the definition from the Royal College of Pathologists, which designates R1 as \u201ctumor within 1 mm of the surgical margin.\u201d In practice, the pathologist should state the definition used.\n\n## Histologic Type\n\nEsophageal cancers are histologically classified as SCC or AC. AC is a malignant epithelial tumor with glandular differentiation arising predominantly from Barrett\u2019s esophagus mucosa in the lower third of the esophagus. Infrequently, they originate from heterotopic gastric mucosa in the upper esophagus, or from mucosal and submucosal glands. SCC is a malignant epithelial tumor with squamous cell differentiation, microscopically characterized by keratinocyte-like cells with intercellular bridges and/or keratinization. They are assumed to have different biological behaviors which might influence treatment choices. SCC seems to be more sensitive to chemotherapy, chemoradiation, and radiotherapy than AC, but the long-term outcome of therapy appears to be similar. AC may be associated with a better long-term prognosis after resection than SCC. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Another histologic subtype that has been reported is the \u201cprimary mixed adeno-squamous carcinoma\u201d (ASC). It is a rare kind of malignancy characterized by mixed glandular and squamous differentiation as well as a propensity for aggressive clinical behavior.\n\n## Histologic Grade\n\nTumor grade reflects the histologic aggressiveness of the cancer. It can be an indicator of how quickly a tumor is likely to grow and spread. Cancers which are \u201cwell-differentiated\u201d tend to grow and spread at a slower rate than tumors that are \u201cundifferentiated\u201d or \u201cpoorly differentiated.\u201d Tumor grade is defined by numbers: \u201c1, 2, 3, or 4\u201d depending on the amount of abnormality as following :\n\n  - \u2022\n\tGX: grade cannot be assessed (undetermined grade)\n  - \u2022\n\tG1: well-differentiated (low grade)\n  - \u2022\n\tG2: moderately differentiated (intermediate grade)\n  - \u2022\n\tG3: poorly differentiated (high grade)\n  - \u2022\n\tG4: undifferentiated (high grade)\n\n## TNM Classification\n\nThe TNM staging system for all solid tumors was devised by Pierre Denoix between 1943 and 1952. Currently, it is maintained and developed by the American Joint Committee on Cancer (AJCC) and the International Union for Cancer Control (UICC). The TNM staging system is updated every 6\u20138 years to include advances in our understanding of cancer prognostication. The TNM system classifies and groups cancers primarily by the extent of local tumor invasion into the esophageal wall and advanced invasion into adjacent structures (T), the status of regional draining lymph nodes (N), and the presence or absence of distant metastases (M). In the Eighth Edition of the AJCC Cancer Staging Manual, the characteristics of all cancers are named \u201ccategories,\u201d and this include anatomic and nonanatomic cancer categories. Anatomic categories include TNM, whereas nonanatomic categories include histopathologic cell type (AC vs. SCC), histology grade (G), and location (L).\n\nThe T stage is assessed by evaluation of the depth of invasion into the four distinct layers involving the esophageal wall and adventitia according to the following nomenclature:\n\n  - \u2022\n\tTX: primary tumor cannot be assessed\n  - \u2022\n\tT0: no evidence of primary tumor\n  - \u2022\n\tTis: high-grade dysplasia\n  - \u2022\n\tT1: tumor invading mucosal lamina propria, muscularis mucosae, or submucosa\n  - \u2022\n\t\tT1a: tumor invading into the lamina propria or muscularis mucosa\n  - \u2022\n\t\tT1b: tumor invading submucosa\n  - \u2022\n\tT2: tumor invading muscularis propria\n  - \u2022\n\tT3: tumor invading adventitia\n  - \u2022\n\tT4: tumor invading adjacent structures\n  - \u2022\n\t\tT4a: resectable tumor invading pleura, pericardium, diaphragm or as per the Eighth Edition; peritoneum\n  - \u2022\n\t\tT4b: unresectable tumor invading other adjacent structures such as aorta, vertebral body, or trachea\n\nT stage is important in the prognostication and is crucial to determining suitability for surgical resection and establishing a treatment plan.\n\nThe nodal classification (N) is one of the most controversial aspects in TNM staging. Different N stages are defined as:\n\n  - \u2022\n\tN0 (no positive node)\n  - \u2022\n\tN1 (one to two nodes)\n  - \u2022\n\tN2 (three to six nodes)\n  - \u2022\n\tN3 (seven or more nodes)\n\nThere is no consensus on the ideal number of nodes that must be resected for optimal staging. Data suggests that the number of lymph nodes recovered rather than their location is an independent predictor of survival after esophagectomy. In the SEER database, when 12 lymph nodes were examined, significant reduction in mortality has been noted compared with no lymph node evaluation. Moreover, patients who had 30 or more lymph nodes examined had significantly lower mortality than any other groups. This may be secondary to enhanced N staging or to a therapeutic effect of lymphadenectomy. In addition, the number of involved lymph nodes can be used to predict the likelihood of systemic disease. There is a general agreement that a two-field lymph node dissection should be done in an invasive cancer. To avoid false-positive radial margins, lymph node retrieval should be performed after complete resection of the tumor and obtaining the deepest extent of invasion into the adventitia. For lymph nodes mapping, a lymph nodes map that extends the nomenclature and numbering system used for the staging of non\u2013small cell lung cancer can be used ( Fig. 31.2 ).\n\nA human thoracic and abdominal regions diagram depicts lymph nodes and organs. The two diagrams of the human thoracic and abdominal regions with numbered labels that indicate specific anatomical structures. In the anterior view left side, it shows cervical lymph nodes 1, left jugular trunk 2, right jugular trunk 2 R, left subclavian trunk 3, right subclavian trunk 3 P, left Broncho mediastinal trunk 4, right Broncho mediastinal trunk 4 R, thoracic duct 5, left bronchopulmonary lymph nodes 6, right bronchopulmonary lymph nodes 7, middle mediastinal lymph nodes 8 M, left mediastinal lymph nodes 8 L, right mediastinal lymph nodes 8 R, right hilar lymph nodes 9, left hilar lymph nodes 10, diaphragmatic lymph nodes 15, left gastric lymph nodes 16, right gastric lymph nodes 17, celiac lymph nodes 18, superior mesenteric lymph nodes 19, and inferior mesenteric lymph nodes 20. The lateral view on the right side represents cervical lymph nodes 1, left jugular trunk 2, right jugular trunk 2 L, left subclavian trunk 3, right subclavian trunk 3 P, left Broncho mediastinal trunk 4, thoracic duct 5, left bronchopulmonary lymph nodes 6, middle mediastinal lymph nodes 8 M, left mediastinal lymph nodes 8 L, right hilar lymph nodes 9, diaphragmatic lymph nodes 15, left gastric lymph nodes 16, right gastric lymph nodes 17, celiac lymph nodes 18, superior mesenteric lymph nodes 19, and inferior mesenteric lymph nodes 20.\n\nFig. 31.2\n\nDistant metastasis is simply designated as:\n\n  - \u2022\n\tM0 (no distant metastases)\n  - \u2022\n\tM1 (distant metastases)\n\nAll esophageal tumors arising in the cervical, thoracic, or abdominal esophagus and those involving the GEJ that have an epicenter within 2 cm of the GEJ share the same criteria for T, N, and M stage designation regardless of histology.\n\n## Updates in the Eighth Edition\n\nThe Eighth Edition of TNM staging is the most updated version published in 2017. This update involved the analysis of data collected from 33 institutions worldwide on 22,654 patients treated for esophageal and GEJ cancer. The clinical and pathological staging criteria were established based on clinical data derived from the World Esophageal Cancer Collaboration (WECC). The Eighth Edition includes clinical (cTNM), pathological (pTNM), and post-neoadjuvant therapy (ypTNM) stage groupings.\n\n### Changes Compared With the AJCC Seventh Edition ( Table 31.1 )\n\nTable 31.1\n\nTNM Classification Changes\n\nData from Amin MB, Edge SB, Greene FL, et al. AJCC Cancer Staging Manual. 8th ed. Springer Cham, 2017.\n\n| AJCC Seventh Edition | AJCC Eighth Edition |\n| --- | --- |\n| **T Classification** | **T Classification** |\n| - Tx: primary tumor cannot be assessed - Tis: high-grade dysplasia - T1: tumor invades lamina propria or submucosa \t- T1a: tumor invades lamina propria or muscularis mucosae \t- T1b: Tumor invades submucosa - T2: tumor invades muscularis propria - T3: tumor invades adventitia - T4: tumor invades adjacent structures <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">b</sup> \t- T4a: resectable tumor invades pleura, pericardium, or diaphragm \t- T4b: unresectable tumor invading other adjacent structures such as aorta, vertebral body, trachea | - Tx: primary tumor cannot be assessed - Tis: high-grade dysplasia - T1: tumor invades lamina propria or submucosa \t- T1a: tumor invades lamina propria or muscularis mucosae \t- T1b: tumor invades submucosa - T2: tumor invades muscularis propria - T3: tumor invades adventitia - T4: tumor invades adjacent structures <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">b</sup> \t- T4a: resectable tumor invades pleura, pericardium, azygos vein, diaphragm, or peritoneum <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">a</sup> \t- T4b: unresectable tumor invading other adjacent structures such as aorta, vertebral body, trachea |\n| **N Classification** Any periesophageal lymph node from cervical nodes to celiac nodes - Nx: regional lymph nodes cannot be assessed - N0: no regional lymph node metastases - N1: one to two involved nodes - N2: three to six nodes - N3: seven or more nodes | **N Classification** Any periesophageal lymph node from cervical nodes to celiac nodes - Nx: regional lymph nodes cannot be assessed - N0: no regional lymph node metastases - N1: one to two involved nodes - N2: three to six nodes - N3: seven or more nodes |\n| **M Classification** - Mx: distant metastases cannot be assessed - M0: no distant metastases - M1: distant metastases | **M Classification** - Mx: distant metastases cannot be assessed - M0: no distant metastases - M1: distant metastases |\n| | **Adenocarcinoma and Squamous Cell Carcinoma G Category** **<sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">a </sup>** <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\"><b>, </b></sup> **<sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">b</sup>** - Gx: differentiation cannot be assessed - G1: well differentiated - G2: moderately differentiated - G3: poorly differentiated (undifferentiated) <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">a</sup> **Squamous Cell Carcinoma L Category** **<sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">a </sup>** <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\"><b>, </b></sup> **<sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">b </sup>** <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\"><b>, </b></sup> **<sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">c</sup>** - Lx: location unknown - Upper: cervical esophagus to lower border of the azygos vein - Middle: lower border of the azygos vein to the lower border of the inferior pulmonary vein - Lower: lower border of the inferior pulmonary vein to the stomach including the gastroesophageal junction |\n\nFor the T category, T4a resectable cancers have been expanded to include lesions infiltrating the peritoneum and azygos vein in addition to pleura, pericardium, or diaphragm. T1 lesions have also been subdivided into T1a (invading into the lamina propria or muscularis mucosa) and T1b (invading submucosa) but only used for the staging of pathologic and post-neoadjuvant pathologic prognostic staging. This has produced two and three pathologic subgroups of stage I (IA, IB, IC) in SCC and AC histologic groups, respectively.\n\nDifferent from the seventh edition, the eighth edition has staged N3 as stage IVA for any T. On another note, the eighth edition has still accounted for the nodal burden by classifying the number of involved lymph nodes into categories: N1, 1\u20132; N2, 3\u20136; N3, \u22657. Lymphadenectomy has not affected survival in patients who underwent neoadjuvant therapy before resection; therefore, preoperative therapy should not affect the extent of lymphadenectomy.\n\nAlthough the eighth edition still has different staging system for AC and SCC with no change in M category staging, in the grade-differentiation (G) subgrouping, G4 was eliminated from the eighth edition and undifferentiated histopathological types were categorized as G3.\n\nTumor location (L) has also been introduced to subcategorize this staging, with a new definition for GEJ cancers in the eighth edition of TNM staging. As mentioned earlier, tumors of GEJ that have an epicenter within 2 cm of the GEJ share the same criteria for T, N, and M stage designation regardless of histology, whereas tumors with epicenter distal to that are staged as gastric cancers. In addition, tumor location is used in the eighth edition to subcategorize T3 SCC tumors and excluded T2 from this stratification that was used in the seventh edition.\n\n### Stage Groupings\n\nStage groups are arrangements of cancer TNM categories that are monotonically decreasing in survival with increasing stage. Although they have distinctive survival between groups, they have homogenous survival within each stage group. Accordingly, separate stage groups were identified for each classification including pathologic, clinical, and post-neoadjuvant pathologic stage groups.\n\nSCCs and ACs are grouped differently ( Table 31.2 ). Patients with early and intermediate stage SCC had worse survival than patients with similarly staged AC. It is worth mentioning that histopathological tumor type significantly affected the survival of clinically and pathologically staged patients, but less so in post-neoadjuvant pathologically staged patients. The addition of grade differentiation (G1\u2013G3) by histopathological review and subcategorizing pT1 led to the subgrouping of stage I to stages IA and IB in SCC, while adding location of SCC tumors was important for subgrouping pathologic stage II. In AC tumors, subcategorization of T1 combined with grade differentiation produced three pathologic subgroups for stage I: IA, IB, and IC. On the contrary, post-neoadjuvant pathologic groupings were similar for both SCC and AC. Categories are uniquely combined such as ypT0-T2 cancers are always grouped together and staging them depends on ypN category.\n\nTable 31.2\n\nAJCC Eighth Edition Pathologic Stage Groupings\n\nData from Amin MB, Edge SB, Greene FL, et al. AJCC Cancer Staging Manual. 8th ed. Springer Cham, 2017.\n\n<table><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\" rowspan=\"2\">Stage</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\" colspan=\"4\">Adenocarcinoma</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\" colspan=\"5\">Squamous cell carcinoma</th></tr><tr><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">T</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">N</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">M</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Grade</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">T</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">N</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">M</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Grade</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Location <a href=\"><sup>a</sup></a></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align=\"\">0</td><td align=\"\">is</td><td align=\"\">0</td><td align=\"\">0</td><td align=\"\">NA</td><td align=\"\">is</td><td align=\"\">0</td><td align=\"\">0</td><td align=\"\">Any</td><td align=\"\">Any</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">IA</td><td align=\"\">1a</td><td align=\"\">0</td><td align=\"\">0</td><td align=\"\">X,1</td><td align=\"\">1a</td><td align=\"\">0</td><td align=\"\">0</td><td align=\"\">X,1</td><td align=\"\">Any</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">IB</td><td align=\"\">1a<br>1b</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">2<br>X,1-2</td><td align=\"\">1a<br>1b<br>2</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">2-3<br>X,1-3<br>1</td><td align=\"\">Any<br>Any<br>Any</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">IC</td><td align=\"\">1<br>2</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">3<br>1-2</td><td align=\"\"></td><td align=\"\"></td><td align=\"\"></td><td align=\"\"></td><td align=\"\"></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">IIA</td><td align=\"\">2</td><td align=\"\">0</td><td align=\"\">0</td><td align=\"\">X,3</td><td align=\"\">2<br>3<br>3</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">X,2-3<br>Any<br>1</td><td align=\"\">Any<br>Lower<br>Upper, middle</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">IIB</td><td align=\"\">3<br>1</td><td align=\"\">0<br>1</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">Any<br>Any</td><td align=\"\">3<br>3<br>3<br>1</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0<br>0<br>1</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0<br>0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">2-3<br>X<br>Any<br>Any</td><td align=\"\">Upper, middle<br>Any<br>X<br>Any</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">IIIA</td><td align=\"\">1<br>2</td><td align=\"\">2<br>1</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">Any<br>Any</td><td align=\"\">1<br>2</td><td align=\"\">2<br>1</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">Any<br>Any</td><td align=\"\">Any<br>Any</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">IIIB</td><td align=\"\">2<br>3<br>4a</td><td align=\"\">2<br>1-2<br>0-1</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">Any<br>Any<br>Any</td><td align=\"\">2<br>3<br>4a</td><td align=\"\">2<br>1-2<br>0-1</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">Any<br>Any<br>Any</td><td align=\"\">Any<br>Any<br>Any</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">IVA</td><td align=\"\">4a<br>4b<br>Any</td><td align=\"\">2<br>0-2<br>3</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">Any<br>Any<br>Any</td><td align=\"\">4a<br>4b<br>Any</td><td align=\"\">2<br>0-2<br>3</td><td align=\"\">0<br>0<br>0</td><td align=\"\">Any<br>Any<br>Any</td><td align=\"\">Any<br>Any<br>Any</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">IVB</td><td align=\"\">Any</td><td align=\"\">Any</td><td align=\"\">1</td><td align=\"\">Any</td><td align=\"\">Any</td><td align=\"\">Any</td><td align=\"\">1</td><td align=\"\">Any</td><td align=\"\">Any</td></tr></tbody></table>\n\n## Anatomic Location and Gastroesophageal Junction Tumors\n\nThe classification of AC of the GEJ was originally described by Siewert et al. He divided it into three types according to the anatomic location of the epicenter or the location of the tumor mass. When the epicenter or more than two-thirds of the mass is located >1 cm above the anatomic GEJ, the tumor is considered in the distal esophagus as type I. When the epicenter or tumor is located within 1 cm proximal and 2 cm distal to the anatomic GEJ, it is classified as type II. When the epicenter or more than two-thirds of the mass is located >2 cm below the anatomic GEJ, the tumor is classified as type III. In 2000, the classification was modified: Siewert type I or AC of the distal esophagus, the epicenter of the tumor is identified within 1 to 5 cm above the anatomic GEJ; Siewert type II or true carcinoma of the cardia, the epicenter is identified within 1 cm above and 2 cm below the GEJ; and Siewert type III or cardia carcinoma, the epicenter is identified between 2 to 5 cm below the GEJ, infiltrating the GEJ and the distal esophagus from below.\n\nThe AJCC eighth edition simplified the definition of GEJ tumors and considered cancers with epicenters no more than 2 cm in the gastric cardia to be staged as AC of the esophagus, whereas those with >2 cm involvement of the gastric cardia to be staged as gastric cancers ( Fig. 31.3 ). The epicenter of the tumor is determined from the upper and lower borders of the tumor length. Also, it is always essential for the surgical resection to know the upper border for the cervical and upper thoracic tumors and the lower border for cancers of the lower esophagus and GEJ.\n\nA diagram of the esophagus which depicts different sections and distances from the incisors. The diagram of the esophagus highlights various sections and their distances from the incisors. The esophagus is divided into the Cervical Esophagus, Upper Thoracic, Middle Thoracic, and Lower Thoracic sections. The diagram reads labels for the Upper Esophageal Sphincter, Sternal notch, Azygos vein, Inferior pulmonary vein, Lower Esophageal Sphincter, and Esophagogastric Junction. The distances from the incisors are marked at 15 centimeters, 20 centimeters, 25 centimeters, 30 centimeters, 40 centimeters, and 42 centimeters, respectively.\n\nFig. 31.3\n\n## Diagnostic Tools\n\n### Tumor Detection\n\nEsophageal cancers are usually discovered upon investigation of upper GI symptoms such as dysphagia and weight loss or on follow-up for Barrett\u2019s esophagus via surveillance upper flexible endoscopy and biopsy.\n\n### Upper GI Contrast Studies\n\nTraditionally, before endoscopy and as a \u201croad map,\u201d barium swallow was performed when patients presented with dysphagia. Barium swallow can clearly identify a polypoid tumor, strictures with mucosal irregularity, and \u201capple core\u201d constrictions ( Fig. 31.4 ). Additional diagnostic information such as location of the tumor, the axis of the esophagus at the level of the tumor, and the presence of other pathology (such as a hiatal hernia or diverticulum) are also provided by barium swallow. Double contrast barium studies have been found to be a useful technique in the absence or delayed availability of endoscopy, although the positive predictive value (PPV) is 42%. With the routine availability of endoscopy, upper GI barium studies are not a routine component of initial assessment due to decreased accuracy and inability to biopsy suspicious lesions. Upper GI studies should be considered when patients present with dysphagia and weight loss and endoscopy is not readily available. In situations where strictures preclude a complete endoscopic evaluation, barium studies may help to demarcate distal extent of the tumor.\n\nA radiographic scan depicts the internal structure of a human chest, with various shades that indicate different tissue densities with prominent dark areas in the center. #REF!\n\nFig. 31.4\n\n### Upper Endoscopy and Biopsy\n\nFlexible upper endoscopy has become the standard initial diagnostic modality for evaluating the esophagus in patients with dysphagia and weight loss when cancer is part of the differential diagnosis. Endoscopy provides valuable and necessary details of the esophageal lumen morphology and can identify other abnormal lesions. Endoscopic reports should include visual description of any gross lesion characteristics such as tumor morphology, distance measured from the incisors, length of the lesion, percent of circumferential involvement, and position in relation to the GEJ (length of extension into cardia if present), in addition to a description of any skip lesions. Presence, location, and length of Barrett\u2019s esophagus should also be noted.\n\nLesions seen endoscopically within the columnar-lined portion of the esophagus are at high risk to be cancerous. Therefore, in addition to visual details, tissues for histological evaluation are obtained. Several biopsies should be performed which will increase the diagnostic accuracy of the study. The diagnostic yield approaches 100% when six or more samples are obtained using a standard endoscopic biopsy protocol. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Biopsy of necrotic or fibrotic areas will decrease diagnostic accuracy. Brush cytology can also be utilized in cases of tight malignant strictures where conventional biopsies may be difficult to obtain. In these cases, to maximize the yield, brushings should be obtained before biopsy. In situations where standard biopsy or brushings do not yield a diagnosis in cases with high suspicion, endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) should be considered. Suspicious lesions other than the index lesions should also be biopsied as submucosal spread or skip lesions within the esophagus are not uncommon.\n\nOnce the histologic diagnosis of cancer has been established, subsequent studies are warranted in patients who might be considered surgical candidates for an accurate staging which will guide the treatment plan. Transmural tumors have a higher possibility of lymph node or systemic involvement, hence will relatively benefit from multimodality therapy compared with very early lesions that may be amenable to surgery alone or curative endoscopic therapy.\n\nStaging usually begins with a computed tomography (CT) scan or positron emission tomography (PET) scan to evaluate the presence of metastatic disease (see below). If distant metastases are excluded, a more detailed evaluation of locoregional disease extent (T and N stage) should be obtained.\n\n## Initial Staging\n\n### FDG-PET/CT scans\n\nFDG-PET/CT or 2-\\[ <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">18 </sup> F\\]-fluoro-2-deoxyglucose\u2013PET/CT is now routinely used in the staging of esophageal cancer. By highlighting the metabolically active tissue via the use of a glucose analog (\\[ <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">18 </sup> F\\]-fluoro-2-deoxyglucose) which remains trapped in cancer cells during metabolism, PET scans can detect primary tumors as well as provide a functional assessment of metabolically active lymph nodes or metastatic sites ( Fig. 31.5 ). By determining the degree of metabolic activity via standardized uptake value, PET may also be able to distinguish between inflammatory and malignant lymph node involvement. PET scanners have been integrated with CT scanners which enable direct comparison of metabolic information with anatomical location. Combined PET/CT has many advantages over PET scan alone and it significantly improves the diagnostic accuracy.\n\nA Positron Emission Tomography scan includes coronal and sagittal views of the abdomen on top and the axial slice below, which depicts some abnormal activity. #REF!\n\nFig. 31.5\n\nHistologically, SCCs were found to highly accumulate FDG at the primary tumor site in contrast to ACs which demonstrate more limited FDG accumulation. FDG avidity in AC was found to be related to tumor growth type, differentiation degree, and mucus content. Non-avid tumors were often poorly differentiated, showing a diffuse, non-intestinal growth type and mucus-containing tumor type.\n\nSensitivity and specificity of the study in the assessment of the TNM stage might be affected by different factors. In the detection of a primary tumor, the sensitivity ranges between 78% and 95%, with most false-negative tests occurring in patients with small tumors (T1 and T2). PET does not provide enough definition of the esophageal wall and thus has no value in T staging. In addition, PET has a poor spatial resolution which renders it insufficient to separate the primary tumor from juxta-tumoral lymph nodes secondary to the interference from the primary tumor. The sensitivity of PET is poor in the identification of lymph node involvement ranging from 38% to 82%. This is especially true for nodes in the middle and lower mediastinum, where most primary tumors are found. In one study, the sensitivity of PET for detecting cervical, upper thoracic, and abdominal nodes was 78%, 82%, and 60%, respectively, but it was only 38% and 0%, respectively, for the mid- and lower mediastinum. The specificity of PET scan is much better than its sensitivity for the N staging with a high pooled specificity ranging from 76% to 95% compared with 77% to 89% in CT scans. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nThe main utility of PET scanning is in its ability to identify the presence of distant metastasis as compared with contrast CT alone. A study recently demonstrated a change in the plan of management from curative into palliative in 47% of cases seen to be negative on CT but were positive for distant metastasis on PET. In addition, Luketich et al. reported 69% sensitivity, 93.4% specificity, and 84% accuracy in detecting metastases with PET compared with 46.1% sensitivity, 73.8% specificity, and 63% accuracy with CT. A meta-analysis of 12 publications on the use of PET in esophageal cancer showed that the pooled sensitivity and specificity for the detection of locoregional metastases were 0.51 and 0.84, respectively. The PPV and negative predictive value (NPV) were 0.60 and 0.46, respectively. For distant metastases, the pooled sensitivity and specificity were 0.67 and 0.97, respectively. The corresponding PPV and NPV were 0.92 and 0.83. When two studies that had particularly low sensitivities for the detection of distant metastases were excluded (probably because they included more early tumors), the pooled sensitivity improved to 0.72 and the specificity to 0.95. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> This study highlights that the accuracy of PET in detecting locoregional nodes is only moderate. Endoscopic ultrasound-guided fine-needle aspiration (EUS-FNA) is more accurate in this regard. However, PET is clearly more accurate for identifying distant nodal and visceral metastases.\n\nThe diagnostic utility of PET in early-stage disease (Tis, T1) may be low because the incidence of lymph node metastases increases with increasing T stage. Cost studies suggest that using PET in early-stage disease is unlikely to be supported. PET should routinely be performed in patients in whom standard staging methods (CT and EUS) demonstrate regional invasive cancer with no distant metastatic disease as it has been shown to be an independent predictor of overall survival in patients with non-metastatic esophageal cancer. PET/CT improves the detection of metastatic disease and thus can often result in a change in the management strategy. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Overall management strategies were reported to be changed because of PET findings in 3%\u201320% of patients in a recent meta-analysis.\n\n### CT Scan and MRI\n\nCT is typically performed as the first radiologic test in the staging evaluation of an endoscopically diagnosed esophageal cancer. An esophageal wall thickness of greater than 5 mm on a CT scan is generally regarded as abnormal and warrants further investigation. CT scan can display the lesion and surrounding structures, regional organ invasion, and lymph node metastasis ( Fig. 31.6 ). Its role is particularly important to exclude T4 disease with a sensitivity and specificity of 25% and 94%, respectively. A CT performed with intravenous and oral contrast provides anatomic details that are critical before considering surgical treatment. Obliteration of the fat plane between the esophagus and the aorta, trachea and bronchi, and the pericardium is suggestive of invasion, but the paucity of fat often makes this assessment unreliable. Thickening or indentation of the normally flat membranous trachea and left main bronchus also is suggestive of invasion, but it should always be confirmed by bronchoscopic examination. When the area of contact between the esophagus and the aorta extends beyond 90 degrees of the circumference, an 80% accuracy of infiltration is reported. However, CT scan cannot reliably distinguish the various T stages; T1 and T2 lesions generally show an esophageal wall thickness between 5 and 15 mm, and T3 lesions have a thickness greater than 15 mm, but this is far from accurate.\n\nA computed tomography scan of the abdomen highlights the porta hepatis lymph node. #REF!\n\nFig. 31.6\n\nThe sensitivity of detecting mediastinal and abdominal nodal involvement is suboptimal with CT because size alone is used as a diagnostic criterion. Intrathoracic and abdominal nodes greater than 1 cm are considered enlarged, and supraclavicular nodes with a short axis greater than 0.5 cm and retro-crural nodes greater than 0.6 cm are pathologic. However, normal-sized lymph nodes may contain metastatic deposits, and enlargement of lymph nodes may be due to reactive and inflammatory processes. The sensitivity and specificity of detecting lymph node involvement is 50% and 83% respectively.\n\nThe main value of CT lies in its ability to detect distant systemic disease, such as hepatic, adrenal, and lung metastases; however, it has been reported to be only 37%\u201366% sensitive. With AC of the GEJ and gastric cardia, peritoneal metastases are more likely than with SCC of the tubular esophagus. CT scanning is inferior to laparoscopy in detecting peritoneal metastases. Solitary lung metastases are rare in patients with esophageal carcinoma and, thus, when seen on CT, are more likely to be primary lung cancer or benign nodules and additional assessment including PET are required.\n\nMagnetic resonance imaging (MRI) presents the advantage of direct multiplanar imaging capabilities, which may be of particular use in assessing tracheobronchial, aortic, and pericardial invasion. Conventional MRI correctly assessed the T-stage in 60% of patients versus 81% when using high-resolution T2-weighted MRI. A study performed using high-resolution T2-weighted MRI with faster sequences and cardiorespiratory motion gating in combination with diffusion-weighted imaging demonstrated detection rates of 33% for T1, 58% for T2, 96% for T3, and 100% for T4 carcinomas. Experience with MRI has shown limitations similar to those of CT, especially with respect to the low detection rate of mediastinal lymph nodes.\n\n### Endoscopic Ultrasound and EUS-FNA\n\nSeveral modalities have been used to assess the depth of invasion of cancer into the tubular esophagus. Dedicated EUS operating at frequencies of 7.5 and 12 MHz are able to identify the wall as a five-layered structure ( Fig. 31.7 ) with relatively accurate sensitivities ranging from 81% to 92% and also provide information on the presence of abnormal or enlarged lymph nodes. However, low-frequency endoscopes cannot visualize the muscularis mucosa. Therefore, authorities consider the deeper the tumor, the higher the sensitivity of EUS. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> There is conflicting data on the ability to accurately discriminate invasion of the mucosa and submucosa (i.e., T1a vs. T1b stages). A comparative prospective blinded trial concluded that neither standard probes nor newer high-resolution 20-MHz probes are able to accurately distinguish intramucosal from submucosal tumor invasion. In contrast, Thosani et al. demonstrated a sensitivity and specificity for T1a tumors of 85% and 87%, respectively, and 86% for both sensitivity and specificity for T1b tumors. The accuracy of EUS in determining T4 stage was found to be 86%.\n\nAn ultrasound scan depicts a circular structure with labels and measurements mentioned on the right. The ultrasound scan displays a circular structure with concentric rings. The technical labels on the diagram provide details about the settings and measurements used during the scan. The frequency is set to C 20, with a range of 4 centimeters and a gain of 16 slash 19. The image count is 15 slash 8, and the distance measured in the image is 4.0 millimeters. The scale bar at the bottom-left corner indicates 5 millimeters, with the current frame being frame 1 out of 92. The direction of the scan is labeled as NORMAL, and the spatial-temporal contrast is set to 65.\n\nFig. 31.7\n\nOver-staging may occur as peritumoral edematous changes may be mistaken for tumor, whereas under-staging can result when tumor penetration is below the resolution of sonography. Other technical obstacles might preclude complete EUS examination such as stenotic esophageal tumors. To negotiate the stenotic esophagus, maneuvers such as dilatation of the lumen can be selectively considered or different instruments such as small-caliber ultrasound catheter or a wire-guided echoendoscope without fiberoptics might be used. However, there are currently no comparative studies to determine their accuracy. In view of these conflicting results, currently the only method capable to accurately determine the depth of invasion of a small visible lesion is EMR (see below).\n\nEUS improves the accuracy of N staging by identifying suspicious nodal characteristics and by providing cytological confirmation of nodal metastatic disease aspirated by FNA biopsy. Optimal criteria for identifying malignant lymph nodes based upon EUS criteria and for helping to select patients for whom EUS-FNA is required continue to evolve. The modified EUS criteria (four standard criteria plus EUS-identified celiac lymph nodes, more than 5 lymph nodes, or EUS T3/4 tumor) were more accurate than standard criteria (hypoechoic, smooth border, round, or width >5\u201310 mm) at identifying malignant lymph nodes. Compared with the gold standard final pathologic evaluation of esophageal resected specimen along with dissected lymph nodes, sensitivity, specificity, and accuracy of EUS-FNA for locoregional lymph nodes are all >85%, <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> in particular, sensitivity is highest for cervical and upper thoracic paraesophageal, infracarinal, left paratracheal, and recurrent laryngeal nodes. A prospective study comparing the performance characteristics of CT, EUS, and EUS-FNA for preoperative lymph node staging of esophageal carcinoma in 125 patients demonstrated that EUS-FNA was more sensitive than CT (83% vs. 29%) and more accurate than CT (87% vs. 51%) or EUS (87% vs. 74%) for nodal staging.\n\nEUS accuracy is operator-dependent, and interobserver reliability was found to be influenced by experience and tumor stage. Agreement among experienced endosonographers for both T and N stage was good, except for T2 tumors in which agreement was poor. There is a tendency to overstage T2 cancers by expert endosonographers in 8% to 14% of cases due to peritumoral inflammation.\n\nHowever, FNA nodal aspiration should be considered in all cases of celiac, porta hepatis, cervical, and upper thoracic adenopathy. It should only be performed when nodes are accessible and when the primary tumor is not in the pathway of the aspiration needle.\n\n### Endoscopic Mucosal Resection\n\nAny malignant, visible lesion cannot be assumed to be limited to the mucosa, in fact, even very small cancers may penetrate into the submucosa. EMR is a technique by which the mucosa and in most patients part or all the submucosa are resected down to the muscularis propria for definitive histologic diagnosis. It was described first in 1992 by Dr. Inoue from Japan. Different techniques have been described, but the more popular method involves the use of a cap that fits over the end of a standard endoscope. The aim is to excise the specimen in one piece; however, piecemeal excision remains acceptable but raises the potential for incomplete resection and makes pathologic evaluation of the resection margins more complex. This technique has evolved and revolutionized the staging and treatment of superficial esophageal AC, particularly the 20% of all esophageal AC in the United States presenting at early stage (T1) with disease confined to mucosa (T1a) or submucosa (T1b). It permits accurate assessment of depth of infiltration, presence of lymphovascular invasion, and degree of differentiation, thus providing a relevant estimation of the risk for local lymph node metastasis. However, histopathologic interpretation of endoscopic resection specimens may not be straightforward. There is a high rate of discordance (up to 48%) between pathologists\u2019 assessment for the depth of tumor invasion in EMR specimens, particularly for lesions called T1b. However, recent studies have shown that EMR and submucosal dissection are highly effective in confirming EUS cT1N0M0 and differentiating cT1a from cT1b. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nThe appropriate treatment modality is best selected in a multidisciplinary fashion with EMR providing the most accurate staging. Several studies have demonstrated that EMR is safe and effective for complete resection with excellent comparable long-term disease control, lower rate of complications but higher rate of recurrence when compared with surgery for high-grade dysplasia and intramucosal AC (T1aN0). In these lesions, the risk of lymph node involvement or hematogenous dissemination is estimated to be less than 2%, justifying a nonsurgical approach. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> For lesions penetrating into the submucosa, more definitive treatment such as esophagectomy with lymphadenectomy continues to be indicated.\n\n### Bronchoscopy and Endobronchial Ultrasound\n\nFlexible bronchoscopy is performed to assess mid- and high esophageal tumor invasion into the tracheobronchial tree and to evaluate mediastinal lymph nodes, especially in situations where the presence of an obstructing esophageal tumor prevents the progression of an echoendoscope to perform EUS or when the tumor is located in the mid- and upper portions of the esophagus.\n\nSigns of involvement include a widened carina, external compression, tumor infiltration, and fistulization. The last two signs contraindicate resection. The gross macroscopic bronchoscopic appearance may not be accurate; in fact, a bulge of the posterior tracheobronchial wall or minimal mucosal changes (erythema, edema) do not confirm neoplastic invasion of the wall and biopsy plus brush cytology is recommended. In one study involving patients with supracarinal cancer, endoluminal tumor mass, protrusion of the posterior tracheal wall, and signs of mucosal invasion were visible in 5.9%, 28.6%, and 4.1% of bronchoscopic examinations, respectively. However, in only 8.6% of 220 bronchoscopic examinations cancer invasion was proved by biopsy or cytology. Bronchoscopy excluded 18.1% of otherwise potentially operable patients from surgery because of airway invasion, with an overall accuracy of 93.3%.\n\nEndobronchial ultrasound (EBUS) has been investigated as a staging tool. The diagnosis of tracheobronchial invasion was based on an interruption in the most external hyperechoic layer of the tracheobronchus (corresponding to its adventitia). In one study of 26 patients determined to be invasion-free by bronchoscopic ultrasound, only 2 had invasion. This compares to 7 of 22 patients who were found to have invasion not suggested by CT alone.\n\nIn another study evaluating patients with esophageal or thyroid cancer with suspicion of tracheobronchial invasion, the sensitivity and specificity of tracheal involvement were 92% and 83%, respectively, compared with 59% and 56%, and 75% and 73% in CT and MRI, respectively. In addition, other recent studies have demonstrated that EBUS has a greater accuracy than conventional bronchoscopy, CT, and EUS in evaluating tracheobronchial invasion by esophageal neoplasia.\n\nA study by Liberman et al. highlighted the utility of EBUS combined with EUS in sampling peritumoral esophageal lymph nodes as EUS plus FNA run a high risk of false-positive cytopathology secondary to contamination of the sample by piercing the primary tumor. Adding EBUS to EUS for staging esophageal cancer in this study added valuable information for patients with upper and mid-esophageal tumors owing to the inability to assess local lymph node invasion in the peri-tracheal area and subcarinal region. In this study, 12% of patients were upstaged with the addition of EBUS to EUS, and that has an important impact on patient prognostication and treatment planning. However, this technique has not yet seen wide application.\n\n### Laparoscopy and Thoracoscopy\n\nIn order to improve preoperative staging, diagnostic laparoscopy or thoracoscopy is selectively performed. Confirmation of cM1 histopathologically or cytologically is recommended by the AJCC. This pathological confirmation is categorized as pM1, not cM1. Small volume intraperitoneal metastases can be difficult to diagnose noninvasively by either CT or PET scans. Laparoscopic or thoracoscopic assessment can help in identifying occult intraperitoneal or intrathoracic distant metastases as well as in sampling regional lymph nodes in some situations such as in cancers at the GEJ or in the distal esophagus. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> This approach might limit aggressive treatment to patients with locally advanced or metastatic disease.\n\nLaparoscopic staging includes visual inspection of the peritoneal cavity and surface of the liver, as well as the potential for laparoscopic ultrasound examination of the liver, collection of peritoneal fluid for cytologic examination, and biopsy of suspicious lesions.\n\nIn a study of 53 patients who underwent preoperative evaluation including minimally invasive staging, a change in the stage originally assigned by CT scan and EUS occurred in 32.1% of patients with AC of the esophagus. The multi-institutional study from the Cancer and Leukemia Group B (CALGB 9380) reported on combined thoracoscopic and laparoscopic staging in 113 patients; the strategy was feasible in 73% of patients. Thoracoscopy and laparoscopy identified nodes or metastatic disease missed by CT in 50% of patients, by MRI in 40%, and by EUS in 30%. Although no deaths or major complications occurred, it did involve general anesthesia, one-lung anesthesia, a median operating time of 210 minutes, and a hospital stay of 3 days.\n\nCurrently diagnostic thoracoscopic assessment is not utilized except in highly selective cases where other staging studies suggest metastatic disease. Many consider diagnostic laparoscopy in patients with AC with extensive gastric involvement or in patients with suspicious CT and PET findings.\n\nEUS-FNA is an effective approach for sampling mediastinal nodes. Laparoscopy, however, has its role especially for AC of the lower esophagus or GEJ tumors as the chance of metastases in the abdomen is considerably greater compared with SCC of the esophagus. Laparoscopy can be of use in diagnosing abdominal metastases such as peritoneal secondaries or identifying unsuspected cirrhosis, which is a relative contraindication to surgical resection. Its value is minimal for more proximally located tumors. Following CT and EUS, laparoscopy may upstage nodal status in 0% to 21% of patients and downstage in 4% to 19%. Together with other findings, change in management can occur in up to 20% of patients. Although thoracoscopy and laparoscopy can identify some additional patients with advanced disease, the application of these approaches should involve our highly selected patients.\n\nThe increased accuracy of PET/CT may decrease the application of other invasive staging methods, especially with regard to distant disease. It does seem that with better PET, CT, and EUS, staging laparoscopy is less indicated. Laparoscopic assessment is indicated in cases where liver metastases or peritoneal metastases are suspected, and confirmation is required.\n\nProper staging of esophageal cancer patients is critical in view of the wide available variation in treatment approaches. Fig. 31.8 highlights all steps for the workup of patients with esophageal cancer. After completion of staging and physiologic assessment, patients should be considered for presentation at multidisciplinary tumor board whenever it is feasible.\n\nA flowchart outlines the stages and investigation algorithm for patients with dysphagia or weight loss. The flowchart outlines detailed staging and investigation algorithms for patients with dysphagia or weight loss. The process begins with an upper endoscopy biopsy or a barium swallow if the upper endoscopy is unavailable. If no cancer is detected, appropriate treatment is provided with follow-up. If cancer is diagnosed, further steps include obtaining a second pathological opinion on equivocal biopsies, followed by a referral for oncologic and physiologic assessment. This may consist of a contrast computed tomography scan, a fluorodeoxyglucose-positron emission tomography scan, and a repeat endo-bronchial ultrasound with biopsy or Endoscopic Mucosal Resection. For patients with invasive cancer greater than or equal to T 1 b, a computed tomography scan with contrast is used to assess for lymphadenopathy. Barrett esophagus and High-grade dysplasia and potential superficial cancer follow Endoscopic mucosal resection or Esophagogastroduodenoscopy with Endoscopic Ultrasound may be performed for a more detailed evaluation. If metastatic disease is suspected, histologic confirmation is considered, and a regionally invasive disease may require additional evaluation with bronchoscopy slash Endo-bronchial ultrasound to rule out airway invasion. Laparoscopy may be considered if regional disease or extensive gastric involvement with peritoneal disease is suspected. Multidisciplinary tumor board discussions and further physiologic assessments play a role in determining treatment decisions.\n\nFig. 31.8\n\n## Therapy Monitoring\n\n### Clinical Restaging Following Neoadjuvant Chemoradiotherapy\n\nNeoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy followed by surgery has demonstrated favorable long-term outcome compared with surgery alone. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> This approach is currently recommended by National Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) guidelines. In addition, treatment response assessment is recommended using FDG-PET/CT, contrast CT scan, and endoscopy with biopsy if surgery is planned.\n\nConventional imaging techniques for monitoring nonsurgical therapy, such as CT and EUS, are based on morphologic imaging. General restrictions of these methods include difficulty in distinguishing viable tumor from necrotic or fibrotic tissue and delay between cell kill and tumor shrinkage. CT scan has been used to assess tumor wall thickness, volumetric measures of the tumor, or CT perfusion blood flow values after neoadjuvant therapy. A recent meta-analysis found that CT had a sensitivity of 35% and a specificity of 83% in evaluating the pathologic tumor response. The available data do not support using CT scan alone as part of the surveillance protocol.\n\nEUS is typically not recommended for response assessment because of its limited accuracy and poor reproducibility. Moreover, EUS is invasive and not always feasible, especially in case of postradiation esophagitis or severe structuring. A study assessing the prognostic value of endoscopic biopsy and EUS demonstrated an accuracy of approximately 50% when correlated with percentage of residual viable cells in the surgical specimen and survival. Two more recent meta-analyses concluded that endoscopy with biopsy and EUS with or without FNA were not reliable tools to evaluate pathological response. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In light of these results, preSANO trial published results of bite-on-bite biopsies where a second, deep biopsy was taken at the same location as first bite to increase the chance of detecting residual submucosal disease, and FNA of abnormal lymph nodes. It was found that for endoscopy with regular biopsies and FNA, there was a 31% false-negative rate and sensitivity and specificity of 54% and 69% for residual tumor detection, whereas bite-on-bite biopsies had an 11% false-negative rate and 74% and 77% for sensitivity and specificity, respectively.\n\nAlthough the results of bite-on-bite biopsies were better than conventional methods, SANO trial will attempt to test the applicability of this method in active surveillance after neoadjuvant therapy. On another note, safety of this method warrants additional study.\n\nA potentially more accurate diagnostic modality that has the potential to predict response early in the course of neoadjuvant treatment is FDG-PET scanning which has been shown to be moderately sensitive in esophageal cancer. The evaluation of FDG-PET for early monitoring of nonsurgical therapy response is described in several small studies and in one large phase II trial, with promising results. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> A recent meta-analysis investigated the correlation between PET results and tumor response after neoadjuvant therapy and found moderately successful results with pooled sensitivities and specificities in 62% and 73%, respectively. The SANO trial group published results of evaluating FDG-PET/CT in treatment response assessment where sensitivity, specificity, and NPV were 80%, 37%, and 42%, respectively. New interval metastases were detected on FDG-PET/CT in 10% patients. Although, the trial group concluded that this modality did not detect residual disease or discriminate substantial residual disease from inflammation, they thought that it was useful for detection of interval metastasis and hence for active surveillance after therapy.\n\n### Surveillance Strategy Following Definitive Therapy\n\nSurveillance, following either surgical or medical management of esophageal cancer, is typically done in order to implement salvage therapy in cases of locoregional failure. However, the number of salvageable cases after recurrences is small. Sudo et al. demonstrated in a study that only 2% of 518 patients with esophageal AC who underwent a trimodality therapy were salvageable when they recurred at a median of 29.3 months of follow-up, which raised the question of the benefit of the surveillance/salvage strategies.\n\nFollowing nonsurgical management, it is difficult to evaluate the lesion as distinguishing between fibrosis, inflammation, and true histologic response is not easy. Conversely, there is a group of patients who can have both complete clinical and pathological response after induction therapy, who can be actively surveilled especially patients who do not wish or are suitable for surgical resection. However, there is still very limited data on the ability to detect true pathological complete treatment response and to predict outcomes after surgery or surveillance. While we are looking forward to the results of the ongoing prospective trials and maturation of molecular tools including liquid biopsy that can detect preclinical recurrences in other malignancies, the post-treatment surveillance strategy suggested by the consensus-based guidelines from the NCCN include the following steps:\n\n  - 1.\n\tHistory and physical examination every 3\u20136 months for 1\u20133 years, then every 6 months for years 4 and 5, then annually\n  - 2.\n\tComplete blood count and chemistry profile, as clinically indicated\n  - 3.\n\tRadiologic imaging and upper GI endoscopy, as clinically indicated\n  - 4.\n\tDilation for anastomotic stenosis\n  - 5.\n\tNutritional counseling\n\n### Additional Considerations for Upcoming Editions\n\nCurrent UICC/AJCC includes three stagings: clinical, pathological, and pathological prognostic according to the different two histopathological types of AC and SCC. Continuous updating and adjustment of TNM classification is essential and aims at improving the survival of patients with esophageal and GEJ cancer. As the current guidelines support the standard treatment with neoadjuvant therapy, post-neoadjuvant therapy staging may be suggested to predict survival after esophagectomy in WECC in the future. However, its role in treatment decision-making in currently limited. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> As the ninth edition AJCC TNM classification is expected to be published in 2024, we hope it will provide individualized precision surgical treatment.\n\nStandardization of key elements in the process of TNM staging should be considered for future editions. As response to neoadjuvant therapy should be reported, modified Ryan tumor regression grading (TRG) system is currently suggested which reportedly provides good interobserver reproducibility and prognostic significance in rectal cancer. Although adopting this system should not preclude from using other advocated systems, a standard TRG system is promising. The international TRG assessment system should be a mandatory variable in national registers of esophageal cancer and in the Esophagectomy Complication Consensus Group ESODATA study to create widely adopted standards and to improve the quality of future research and, ultimately, survival of esophageal and GEJ cancer.\n\nAnother area for standardization is the circumferential resection margin. The majority of current evidence is favoring adoption of the College of American Pathologists\u2019 measure of actual margin involvement rather than the Royal College of Pathologists\u2019 criteria. In order to enable more research, it is also proposed to include the distance from the margin (in mm).\n\nLymph node status evaluation is considered to be the most important prognostic element in esophageal and GEJ cancer. Hence the authors propose, based on the available evidence, a simpler and more practical method to record only the number of involved and total nodes, and for these to be submitted separately as abdominal, lower mediastinal, upper mediastinal, and cervical. The authors suggest this would spare the pathologists much extra work and avoid any unnecessary increased lymph node yield.\n\nFinally, future use of advanced investigational methods such as ctDNA and imaging would be helpful to realize precision esophageal cancer care and could be of value in patients who have residual disease. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n## Acknowledgments\n\nWe would like to acknowledge Dr. Law for using parts of his chapter published in the seventh edition.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Siegel R.L., Miller K.D., Fuchs H.E., Jemal A.: Cancer statistics, 2022 . CA Cancer J Clin 2022; 72 (1): pp. 7-33.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Sung H., Ferlay J., Siegel R.L., et al.: Global cancer statistics 2020: GLOBOCAN estimates of incidence and mortality worldwide for 36 cancers in 185 countries . CA Cancer J Clin 2021; 71 (3): pp. 209-249.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: Baquet C.R., Commiskey P., Mack K., et al.: Esophageal canc