3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[30. Endoscopic Ultrasound of the Esophagus - ClinicalKey|30. Endoscopic Ultrasound of the Esophagus]]\n**Next:** [[32. Neoadjuvant Treatments in Locally Advanced Esophageal Cancer - ClinicalKey|32. Neoadjuvant Treatments in Locally Advanced Esophageal Cancer]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "31. Esophageal Cancer Diagnosis and Staging - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Esophageal Cancer Diagnosis and Staging', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Esophageal Cancer Diagnosis and Staging', 'Epidemiology', 'Anatomy', 'Nomenclature', 'Histologic Type', 'Histologic Grade', 'Esophageal Cancer Diagnosis and Staging / Epidemiology', 'Esophageal Cancer Diagnosis and Staging / Anatomy', 'Esophageal Cancer Diagnosis and Staging / Nomenclature'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '31', '302-317', 2, 69, FALSE, TRUE),
('Neoadjuvant Treatments in Locally Advanced Esophageal Cancer', 'shackelford-9th-ed-32-neoadjuvant-treatments-in-locally-advanced-esophageal-cancer', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Neoadjuvant Treatments in Locally Advanced Esophageal Cancer\n\nJames Tankel; Jonathan Cools-Lartigue; Lorenzo Ferri\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 32, 318-329\n\n## Introduction\n\nIn patients with locally advanced esophageal cancer, the appreciation that multimodal therapy affords better survival has been central to the evolution of neoadjuvant treatment regimens. However, initial experiences with these regimens were marred by high levels of toxicity, treatment-related mortality and marginal survival benefits. Nevertheless, over the past 40 years, neoadjuvant chemotherapy (nCT) and chemoradiotherapy (nCRT) regimens have evolved immensely with treatment decisions being now driven by a better understanding of tumor histology and biology.\n\nMultiple randomized studies have shown that nCT or nCRT confers better survival outcomes when compared with surgery alone. This is achieved by controlling local as well as micrometastatic disease and is particularly important as a majority of patients will ultimately die of recurrence. While this highlights the necessity of neoadjuvant therapy, the ideal regimen has yet to be elucidated. Confusing matters further is the advent of immunotherapy, the role of which has yet to be clearly defined in esophageal cancer.\n\nFor the majority of patients, effective surgical resection is also required. The transthoracic en bloc esophagogastrectomy with extended lymphadenectomy remains the standard bearer for surgical resection with a high rate of complete resection and low incidence of locoregional recurrence compared with standard non\u2013en bloc or transhiatal esophagectomy. The nature of surgical intervention is beyond the scope of this chapter. Rather we will focus on the evolution of neoadjuvant treatments and present the evidence base on which treatment decisions should be made recognizing that the type of surgery may impact selection of type of treatment or the need to include an additional form of local therapy. We will also highlight trends in the literature that may alter the way locally advanced esophageal cancer is managed in the future.\n\n### Neoadjuvant Radiotherapy Versus Surgery Alone\n\nThe first studies exploring the use of neoadjuvant radiotherapy (nRT) for locally advanced esophageal squamous cell carcinoma (ESCC) were published in the 1950s and born from an attempt to achieve local disease response and R0 resection rates. However, these studies found that the addition of preoperative radiotherapy was associated with a 5-year overall survival of just 6% to 10% and did not afford much benefit over surgery alone. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The cumulative results of these studies were summarized in a Cochrane review, which included 1147 patients from five of these trials. Despite a majority of those included having ESCC, an absolute survival benefit of only 4% at 5 years could be detected in comparison with surgery alone. While this failed to reach a level of statistical significance, the dose of nRT given was considerably lower than that given in modern regimens and failed to combine nRT with concurrent systemic chemotherapy. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> However, evidence suggests that when used alone, even higher doses of nRT fail to achieve meaningful improvements in survival. For example, in a multiarm Chinese study that, in part, compared 40 Gy of nRT versus surgery alone, although an improved 3-year overall survival among those receiving nRT was noted, this was not sustained at 5 years. Therefore, nRT alone is not an accepted standard of care for locally advanced esophageal cancer and its use as a solitary treatment strategy should remain in the palliative realm.\n\n### Neoadjuvant Chemoradiotherapy Versus Surgery Alone\n\nBuilding on the experience of nRT, attention focused on adding concurrent chemotherapy to radiotherapy before surgery. This approach was based on principle that by combining neoadjuvant systemic treatment with radiation affords efficacy for treating micrometastatic disease that lies beyond the radiation field. In addition, several chemotherapy agents, such as 5FU, cisplatin, and paclitaxel, act as radiosensitizers resulting in greater sensitivity of target tissue to ionizing radiation. Finally, ESCC seems to be particularly sensitive to the effects of radiotherapy making this an attractive treatment option.\n\nBuilding on these principles, the outcomes of nCRT have been extensively described in the academic literature and a summary of the recent randomized trials on this topic are presented in Table 32.1 . A meta-analysis summarized 26 earlier studies and found that among the 1335 patients included, pathological complete response occurred in 24% of patients. A dose-related response was also found and the role of combined systemic treatment formalized. However, balancing the toxicity of trimodal therapy with improved survival outcomes was historically challenging. In one study exploring the benefits of high-dose nCRT (64.8 Gy), 9% of patients died due to treatment-related complications. Similarly, in a single-arm study utilizing cisplatin, vinblastine, and 5FU by Forastiere et al. in 1990, grade III\u2013IV myelosuppression occurred in 93% of patients. A study by Bosset et al. found neoadjuvant treatment\u2013related deaths to be significantly higher than those after surgery.\n\nTable 32.1\n\nRandomized Studies Comparing Neoadjuvant Chemoradiotherapy With Upfront Surgery\n\n| Trial | Year | *N* | Histology | Neoadjuvant Regimen | %pCR | Survival Outcomes |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Nygaard | 1992 | Sx 46 nCRT 41 | ESCC | Cisplatin, bleomycin, 35 Gy | \u201324 | 3-yr overall survival 9% 13% |\n| Le Prise | 1994 | Sx 45 nCRT 41 | ESCC | Cisplatin, 5FU, 20 Gy | \u201310 | 3-yr overall survival 14% 19% |\n| Apinop | 1994 | Sx 34 nCRT 35 | ESCC | Cisplatin, 5FU, 40Gy | \u201320 | 3-yr overall survival 20% 26% |\n| Walsh | 1996 | Sx 55 nCRT 58 | EAC | Cisplatin, 5FU, 40 Gy | \u201322 | 3-yr overall survival 6% 32% \u2217 |\n| Bosset | 1997 | Sx 139 nCRT 143 | ESCC | Cisplatin, 37 Gy | \u201320 | 3-yr overall survival 34% 36% |\n| Urba | 2001 | Sx 50 nCRT 50 | EAC/ESCC | Cisplatin, vinblastine, 5FU, 45 Gy | \u201328 | 3-yr overall survival 15% 32% \u2217 |\n| Lee | 2004 | Sx 50 nCRT 51 | ESCC | Cisplatin, 5FU, 45.6 Gy | \u201343 | Median survival (mo) 27.3 28.2 |\n| Burmeiste | 2005 | Sx 128 nCRT 128 | EAC/ESCC | Cisplatin, 5FU, 35 Gy | \u201312.5 | Median survival (mo) 19.3 22.2 |\n| Natsugo | 2006 | Sx 23 nCRT 22 | ESCC | Cisplatin, 5FU, 40 Gy | \u201313.6 | 5-yr overall survival 41% 57% |\n| Tepper | 2008 | Sc 30 nCRT 26 | EAC/ ESCC | Cisplatin, 5FU, 50.4 Gy | \u201333.3 | 5-yr overall survival 16% 39% \u2217 |\n| Cao | 2009 | Sx 118 nCRT 118 | ESCC | Cisplatin, mitomycin, 5FU, 40 Gy | \u201322.3 | 3-yr overall survival 53.4% 73.3% \u2217 |\n| Lv. | 2010 | Sx 80 nCRT 78 | ESCC | Paclitaxel, cisplatin, 40 Gy | \u2013NR | 5-yr overall survival 33.8% 87.5% \u2217 |\n| CROSS | 2012 | Sx 188 nCRT 178 | EAC/ESCC | Carboplatin, paclitaxel, 41.4 Gy | \u201329 | Median survival (mo) 24.0 49.4 \u2217 |\n| Mariette | 2014 | Sx 97 nCRT 98 | ESCC | Cisplatin, 5FU, 45 Gy | \u201333.3 | Median survival (mo) 31.8 41.2 |\n| Bass | 2014 | Sx 107 nCRT 104 | EAC/ESCC | Cisplatin, 5FU, 40 Gy | 25/ 31 | Mean overall survival (mo) 23.5 63.8 \u2217 |\n| Yang | 2018 | Sx 227 nCRT 224 | ESCC | Vinorelbine, cisplatin, 40 Gy | \u201343.2 | Median survival (mo) 66.1 100.1 \u2217 |\n\n*EAC,* Esophageal adenocarcinoma; *ESCC,* esophageal squamous cell carcinoma; *nCRT,* neoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy; *pCR,* pathological complete response; *Sx,* Surgery.\n\nWhile it became clear that myelosuppression and other drug-related toxicities rose with the number of drugs used and dose of radiotherapy delivered, historic planning and treatment techniques do not compare with modern technologies. This may explain why subsequent randomized studies, such as those by Le Prise et al., Apinop et al., and Nygaard et al., not only confirmed the safety of nCRT but also showed that it does not increase the risk of perioperative morbidity or mortality.\n\nIn the study by Le Prise et al. specifically, the radiation dose\u2013related response was again highlighted. Using only 20 Gy of external beam radiotherapy, a significant downstaging effect of the primary tumor was seen. However, this did not result in an improvement in the rate of R0 resections, and a very low incidence of pathological complete response was seen in the trimodality group. Furthermore, the low dose of radiotherapy used in this study may have contributed to nCRT not having improved overall survival when compared with the upfront surgery group. Similarly, in the study by Bosset et al., patients were randomized to receive either nCRT or upfront surgery. Despite using only 18.5 Gy of radiotherapy, 26% of these patients had a pathological complete response and significantly fewer lymph node metastases at the time of surgery (25% vs. 57%). The authors also demonstrated a significant increase in R0 resection rate following nCRT (81% vs. 69%). While disease-free survival and incidence of cancer-related deaths were lower in the trimodality group, overall survival did not significantly differ. Finally, in a similar study by Burmeister et al., a dose of only 35 Gy was used, and although a similar picture of improved resectability and lymph node downstaging among trimodality patients was seen, this was not associated with an improvement in overall survival.\n\nIt is important to note that these studies included, either solely or predominantly, patients with ESCC. Furthermore, the surgical technique rarely included an en bloc intrathoracic dissection or formal D2 celiac lymph node dissection, both shown to reduce locoregional recurrences. The omission of these technical details during esophagectomy may require an additional form of local therapy to improve locoregional control. The study by Walsh et al. included 113 randomized patients with locally advanced esophageal adenocarcinoma (EAC) to be treated either with neoadjuvant 5FU, cisplatin, and 40 Gy of radiation or surgery alone. A pathological complete response rate of 25% and a significant downstaging effect was seen, with 42% of patients treated with nCRT found to harbor positive lymph nodes at the time of surgery compared with 82% of patients in the surgery alone arm ( *P* <.001). The median survival of the trimodality group was 16 months versus 11 months for those receiving surgery alone with a 3-year overall survival of 32% versus 6%, respectively. Although this trial provided a foundation for treating EAC with nCRT, the survival among patients treated with surgery alone was far lower than that in contemporary unimodality surgical cohorts. As such, the results of this study may not have been driven by the benefit derived from nCRT rather by substandard surgical resection. Comparatively, in a study by Tepper et al. in which 77% of patients had EAC, those treated with trimodality therapy had a 5-year overall survival of 39%, whereas for those who received surgery alone it was 16%.\n\nWhile these studies may suggest that both EAC and ESCC benefit from being treated with nCRT, these two histological subtypes have a differing sensitivity to ionizing radiation. This difference was powerfully highlighted in the study by Urba et al. in which 100 patients were randomized to receive cisplatin, 5FU, and 45 Gy of radiotherapy or surgery alone. Pathological complete response rates differed between EAC and ESCC patients (25% vs. 38%, respectively). The rate of R0 resections was also improved in the nCRT group (96% vs. 90%). Although no overall survival benefit was seen with nCRT, in patients who exhibited a pathological complete response, a survival benefit could be appreciated (median survival of 49.7 vs. 12 months, *P* \\=.01). This benefit appeared to be driven by improved local control with no difference in systemic recurrence rates between the two groups.\n\nIn the presence of a growing, contrasting, and heterogenous evidence base regarding the value of nCRT in treating esophageal cancer, the CROSS study firmly established the benefit of trimodality therapy. This trial is the largest study to date to show a survival benefit of nCRT compared with surgery alone. Consequently, nCRT became an established standard of care for both ESCC and EAC in the West. A slightly different chemotherapeutic regimen was employed comprising paclitaxel and carboplatin in conjunction with concurrent radiation at a dose of 41.4 Gy. With respect to local control, pathological complete response was found in 25% of patients with EAC compared with 49% in patients with ESCC. In keeping with previous studies, R0 resection was achieved in a greater proportion of patients receiving nCRT compared with surgery alone (92% vs. 69%). In addition, significantly more patients who underwent surgery alone were found to harbor metastatic lymph nodes compared with patients receiving nCRT (75% vs. 31%) despite comparable preoperative clinical staging. Finally, a significant reduction in locoregional recurrence was noted in patients with both EAC and ESCC following nCRT compared with surgery alone (22% vs. 38%, hazard ratio \\[HR\\] 0.45, 95% CI 0.3\u20130.66, *P* \\= <.001), thus supporting the locoregional benefit of nCRT.\n\nThe durability of this response was described in 2015 when long-term data was published on the same cohort. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> With a median follow-up of 45 months, 366 patients were analyzed. The median survival of the trimodality group was 48.6 months compared with the 24.0 months of the surgery alone group ( *P* \\=.003). Importantly, among ESCC patients the median overall survival was 81.6 months compared with just 43.2 months in EAC patients.\n\nSubsequent studies based on similar neoadjuvant protocols confirmed these findings. For example, Bass et al. demonstrated among 211 ESCC and EAC patients improved locoregional control and rates of pathological complete response following nCRT. In this study, this consisted of cisplatin and 5FU plus 40 Gy of radiotherapy. For patients with EAC, pathological complete response was found in 25% versus 31% for patients with ESCC. Downstaging of mediastinal disease following nCRT was inferred based on a 64% rate of nodal positivity in patients treated with surgery alone versus 29% in patients undergoing nCRT. This effect was more pronounced among ESCC patients in whom 85% were node negative following trimodal therapy versus 58% in EAC patients. One caveat with the CROSS trial that should be considered is the influence of surgical approach on outcomes after chemoradiation. Long-term outcomes comparing surgical approach from the Dutch centers involved in the CROSS trial demonstrated persistent benefit of chemoradiation for patient with a transhiatal resection but limited benefit for this neoadjuvant regimen in patient who underwent transthoracic esophagectomy. These results call in question, albeit still controversially, the need for an additional form of local therapy if the surgical approach includes en bloc esophagectomy.\n\nThe French FFCD9901 trial, which included 195 patients, of whom 70% had ESCC, also randomized patients to nCRT versus upfront surgery. The trial failed to show a significant difference in R0 resections and 3-year overall survival was also similar between the arms. There was a sixfold increase in postoperative mortality in the radiated arm, suggesting that any possible oncological benefit was overshadowed by the influence of the neoadjuvant regimen on postoperative morbidity. However, this trial included only stage I and II disease and hence the results may be interpreted as showing the unsuitability for trimodal therapy in early ESCC rather than for locally advanced disease.\n\nThe NEOCRTEC5010 study randomized 451 patients with potentially resectable ESCC to receive vinorelbine and cisplatin with 40 Gy of concurrent radiotherapy followed by surgery or surgery alone. nCRT was associated with pathological complete response in 43.2%, a higher R0 resection rate (98.4% vs. 91.2%, *P* \\=.002), and a better median overall survival (100.1 months vs. 66.5 months, *P* \\=.002). Of note, the 5-year overall survival of the trimodality and surgery only group was higher than that reported among CROSS patients (59.1% vs. 49.1% compared with 47% vs. 33%, respectively). Postoperative complications were similar between the groups although the incidence of arrythmias was higher in the trimodality group.\n\nTaken together, the bulk of evidence to date demonstrates improved local control following nCRT compared with surgery alone as evidenced by a significantly higher pathological complete response rate, reduction in lymph node disease burden within the mediastinum, and consequently, an improved R0 resection rate. These pathological outcomes have become increasingly recognized as factors that strongly correlate with improved survival. Therefore, considering that nCRT has a less impressive impact on EAC in terms of these metrics, an alternative treatment modality for this histological subtype may be more appropriate.\n\n### The Role of Chemoradiotherapy in Providing Improved Systemic Control\n\nAny treatment paradigm given with curative intent should ideally be given with the goal of minimizing the incidence of systemic recurrence. While it has been shown consistently that nCRT provides more effective locoregional control than surgery alone, this may not be true across all histological subtypes.\n\nData concerning recurrence among patients with mixed histological subtypes following nCRT have been well described. In a retrospective study of 204 patients, locoregional recurrence was lower following nCRT compared with upfront surgery (12% vs. 28%, *P* \\= 0.001), whereas distal recurrence was similar (25% vs. 35%, *P* \\=.210). However, it seems that the risk of recurrence is related to the relative sensitivity of ESCC tumor to nCRT. This was demonstrated in the study by Burmeister et al., in which 5-year progression-free survival rates were significantly improved following nCRT compared with surgery alone in patients with squamous histology but not in patients with adenocarcinoma. Similarly, in a study on patients with ESCC by Lv et al., significantly more patients receiving surgery alone died as a result of systemic recurrence in comparison with patients receiving nCRT (38.8% vs. 25.0%, *P* \\=.011).\n\nRecurrence data from the CROSS study further demonstrates this point. Among patients originally treated in the trial, nCRT had a clear effect on reducing locoregional recurrence but not distant disease relapse. However, a subset analysis of patients with ESCC suggested that some systemic benefit may be derived from nCRT at 5 years (HR for death of 0.75, 95% CI 0.56\u20131.01). Data exploring the recurrence among patients with ESCC recruited to the NEOCRTEC5010 study also found significantly better locoregional failure-free survival in patients who received multimodal treatment than those treated with surgery alone.\n\nThe initial degree of response of the primary tumor to nCRT also plays an important role in the risk of developing disease recurrence. In a retrospective, multicenter study with a median follow-up of 52.9 months, of the 895 patients studied 34.3% of patients with EAC and 43.2% of patients with ESCC suffered from recurrence of disease ( *P* \\=.023). Among patients with pathological complete response, recurrence occurred in 21% of patients with ESCC and 24% of patients with EAC, with locoregional and distal recurrence in 4.3% and 1.7%, and 14.0% and 17.4%, respectively. If pathological complete response was not achieved, recurrence was much higher in both ESCC and EAC (56% and 50%). ESCC was equally likely to recur locoregionally and distally (16.7% and 17.5%), whereas EAC was more likely to recur distally (32.5% vs. 6.3%). Specifically, for those with ESCC, recurrence was more common in supraclavicular lymph nodes, whereas in EAC, metastases occurred via hematogenous spread to the liver and retroperitoneum. In another large retrospective study, for patients in whom pathological complete response was achieved, locoregional recurrence occurred in 6%, whereas distant metastases were found in 26%.\n\nCollectively, this data suggests that nCRT provides excellent local control, particularly when there is pathological complete response. However, when this is not the case, both local and distal disease control is suboptimal. Therefore, although this effect may be observed in some patients with EAC, it is with an attenuated response.\n\n### The Role of Neoadjuvant Chemoradiotherapy in Early Esophageal Cancer\n\nThe benefit of CRT in patients with earlier stage (I, II) disease is less clear, and data seem conflicting. The randomized controlled study by Mariette et al. compared nCRT in patients with stage I and II esophageal cancer followed by surgery against surgery alone. A total of 195 patients with both ESCC and EAC were randomly assigned to nCRT with 5FU and cisplatin alongside 45 Gy of concurrent radiation or upfront surgery. All patients who underwent surgery were subject to a transthoracic approach with two-field lymphadenectomy. The R0 resection rate was comparable between the two groups (92.9% and 92.1%, respectively). Pathological complete response rate was 33% in the nCRT group and significant downstaging of the primary tumor and associated lymph node positivity was noted. This was associated with improved locoregional control with nCRT patients demonstrating a local failure rate of 28.6% compared with 44.3% in patients treated with surgery monotherapy ( *P* \\=.02). However, no difference was observed with respect to distant recurrence (22.5% vs. 28.9%, *P* \\=.31) or overall survival (median \\[range\\] 31.8 months \\[25.2\u201367.8\\] vs. 41.1 months \\[29\u201353.9\\]). In hospital, mortality was significantly higher in patients randomized to the nCRT arm (11.1% vs. 3.4%, *P* \\=.049). This demonstrates that the oncologic benefit of nCRT in patients with locally advanced esophageal cancer is not maintained in patients with earlier stage disease.\n\nHowever, a retrospective study including data from over 30 European centers including 382 patients with both ESCC and EAC who had cT3N0 lesions found that the addition neoadjuvant treatment led to more R0 resections, fewer pathologically positive lymph nodes, more tumor downstaging, and longer median overall survival (38.4 vs. 29.9 months, *P* \\=.007). Importantly, these outcomes did not change whether nCRT or nCT was used.\n\nSquamous cell carcinoma is so sensitive to radiotherapy that some authors have questioned whether surgery adds a survival benefit in the setting of early ESCC. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Although in 2017 a registry-based study of 3123 patients with stage I\u2013III squamous cell carcinoma found that the addition of surgery to nCRT was indeed associated with a survival benefit, patients with non-nodal disease were underrepresented. Furthermore, the survival benefit found in this study only became significant with stage IIA and above. In the JCOG0502 trial, an attempt was made to randomize patients with cT1bN0 ESCC to either definitive chemoradiotherapy or upfront surgery. Although recruitment was limited, 5-year overall survival was similar in the surgery and nonsurgery groups (86.5% and 85.5%, respectively). The question of requiring surgery after chemoradiation for locally advanced disease in both adenocarcinoma and squamous cell carcinoma is currently the topic of several trials for which results are anticipated in the mid-2020s. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Balancing the Toxicity and Benefit of Neoadjuvant Chemoradiation\n\nThe morbidity and mortality associated with nCRT can be divided into preoperative and postoperative periods. With regards to the former, bone marrow suppression, nutritional depletion, renal damage, and liver damage were the most commonly reported systemic side effects. Historic data originating from early experiences with nRT also raised concerns of the treatment-related morbidity and mortality associated with nCRT. Bosset et al. concluded that the mortality due to nCRT negated the potential survival benefit associated with trimodality therapy. However, treatment-related mortality in this study was higher than expected (12% vs. 5% in the surgery only arm) and the nRT was given as split dose, which is now known to be deleterious. The authors attributed this, in part, to the high dose of radiation administered per fraction indicating the toxicity of their regimen. Data from other randomized studies has shown similar, albeit less marked, peritreatment-associated mortality during nCRT.\n\nLooking toward data from more recent studies, nCRT seems to be better tolerated with an incidence of treatment-related deaths of less than 2%. In the CROSS study, the most common side effects were leukopenia, neutropenia, anorexia, and fatigue affecting 2% to 6% of participants with only 1/176 in the trimodality arm dying whilst awaiting surgery. Similarly, in the NEOCRETC5010 study, treatment-associated mortality occurred in just 1.3%.\n\nThere is a large body of data exploring the effect of nCRT on the postoperative period. Evidence varies as to whether nCRT increases the risk of perioperative complications. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In a multi-institutional study of 2944 patients, nCRT was not associated with an increased risk of anastomotic leak, pneumonia, or the overall incidence of morbidity or mortality. However, nCRT was associated with an increased risk of chylothorax (2.5% vs. 0.2%, *P* \\=.020), cardiovascular complications (8.6% vs. 0.1%, *P* \\=.037), and thromboembolic events (8.6% vs. 6.0%, *P* \\=.037). A Chinese study suggested that mortality is higher among patients treated with nCRT who subsequently underwent minimally invasive esophagogastrectomy. Among patients who died within 1 year of treatment randomization, 45.8% in the nCRT group versus 15% in the nCT group were associated with treatment-related causes of death.\n\nA meta-analysis of 12 randomized controlled studies including 1529 patients concluded that nCRT did not increase the risk of postoperative morbidity (risk ratio 0.97, 95% CI 0.86\u20131.09, *P* \\=.056) nor mortality (risk ratio 0.56, 95% CI 0.97\u20132.50, *P* \\=.070). However, a great degree of heterogenicity was found between the included studies.\n\nTherefore, although the data is varied, the safety of nCRT has improved significantly in recent decades. Nevertheless, preoperative morbidity and mortality are still a feature of this treatment option and some patients may also experience increased postoperative morbidity relative to upfront surgery. Considering the survival benefit for patients with locally advanced disease discussed earlier, we suggest that nCRT be reserved for these specific patients as the role of trimodality therapy in early disease is less clear.\n\n### The Case for Neoadjuvant Chemotherapy\n\nEffective systemic therapy with chemotherapy to control occult distant disease is a cornerstone of treatment for locally advanced esophageal cancer. Systemic therapy treats micrometastatic disease and improves survivability while improved dysphagia affords patients a better nutritional intake before surgery. Furthermore, nonresectable lesions may be downstaged such that they may be rendered resectable and an R0 margin achieved. In the preoperative setting, optimal drug delivery also occurs via an intact blood supply. Finally, the administration of nCT provides a unique opportunity to observe the clinical efficacy of the drug regimen in question. Assessment of tumor response has important prognostic significance and alternate treatment strategies can be selected for patients who do not respond and, rarely, futile surgery avoided in the presence of progression of disease during neoadjuvant therapy. As is shown in Table 32.2 , in which a summary of randomized trials comparing nCT versus upfront surgery is presented, a majority of the data support preoperative treatment.\n\nTable 32.2\n\nRandomized Trials Comparing Neoadjuvant Chemotherapy With Upfront Surgery\n\n| Trial | Year | *N* | Histology | Neoadjuvant Chemotherapy Regimen | %R0 | Survival Outcomes |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Schlag | 1992 | Sx 24 nCT 22 | ESCC | Cisplatin, 5FU | NR | Median survival (mo) 5 7.5 |\n| Kelsen | 1998 | Sx 213 nCT 227 | EAC, ESCC | Cisplatin, 5FU | 135 133 | Median survival (mo) 16.1 14.9 |\n| Ancona | 2001 | Sx 47 nCT 47 | ESCC | Cisplatin, 5FU | 24 25 | Median survival (mo) |\n| MRC OEO2 | 2002 | Sx 402 nCT 400 | EAC, ESCC | Cisplatin, 5FU | 233 215 | Median survival (mo) 13.3 16.8 |\n| MAGIC | 2006 | Sx 253 nCT 250 | EAC | Epirubicin, Cisplatin, 5FU | NR | 5-year overall survival 23% 36% \u2217 |\n| Schuhmacher | 2010 | Sx 72 nCT 72 | EAC | Cisplatin, 5FU | 49 59 | Median survival (mo) 52.3 64.6 |\n| Boonstra | 2011 | Sx 84 nCT 85 | ESCC | Cisplatin, etoposide | 40 49 | Median survival (mo) 12.0 16.0 \u2217 |\n| FNLCC/FFCD | 2011 | Sx 111 nCT 113 | EAC | Cisplatin, 5FU | 81 95 | 5-year overall survival 24% 38% \u2217 |\n\n*EAC,* esophageal adenocarcinoma; *ESCC,* esophageal squamous cell carcinoma; *nCT,* neoadjuvant chemotherapy plus surgery; *Sx,* upfront surgery only.\n\nDespite these potential benefits, a number of early studies failed to clearly demonstrate a survival benefit to nCT. In the American Intergroup 0113 study by Kelsen et al., neoadjuvant cisplatin and 5FU failed to improve overall survival when compared with upfront surgery. It is important to note, however, that subset analysis showed significantly better survival in patients who responded to chemotherapy than in those who did not (response vs. no response, HR 2.83, 95% CI 1.84\u20134.35, *P* <.001). This concept of improved survival specifically among patients with disease who respond to nCT is supported by the finding of improved survival of patients with ESCC who demonstrated a major pathological response to vinblastine, cisplatin, and bleomycin-based chemotherapy (median survival 20 months vs. 6 months, *P* \\=.008). Schlag similarly demonstrated significant increases in survival for patients with ESCC who demonstrated a response to neoadjuvant cisplatin and 5FU. For the cohort as a whole, overall survival did not improve when comparing between upfront surgery and nCT. Median survival in the nCT arm versus upfront surgery arm was 16.8 months versus 13 months. However, in patients who demonstrated a response to nCT, median survival significantly improved from 13.8 months to 42.2 months.\n\nFurthermore, Ancona et al. similarly randomized patients with ESCC to two cycles of preoperative cisplatin and 5FU or upfront surgery. The rate of major pathological response of resected tumors in the nCT arm was 40% with a complete response found in 12.8%. No difference in median survival was noted on an intention-to-treat basis (24 and 25 months for surgery alone vs. nCT, respectively). However, in the 40% of patients who demonstrated a major response to nCT, a significant improvement with respect to median (53 months) and both 3- and 5-year overall survival was found (74% and 60%, respectively). Conversely, for the upfront surgery arm and nonresponders to nCT, this was 28 months, 46%, and 26% and 19 months, 38%, and 19%, respectively.\n\nSimilar evidence exists regarding patients treated for EAC. Based on an outdated triplet therapy regimen (cisplatin, 5FU, and leucovorin), the European EORTC 40954 study failed to show survival benefit in the neoadjuvant arm. Although the study was stopped early due to poor accrual, recipients of nCT nevertheless had a lower incidence of lymph node metastases (61.4% vs. 76.5%, *P* \\=.018) and a higher rate of R0 resection (81.9% vs. 66.7%, *P* \\=.036).\n\nAlthough survival data relating to these specific patients was not made available, these data suggest that an effective nCT regimen could confer a survival advantage by improving R0 resection rates and thus contribute to improved survival through improved locoregional control.\n\nIn order to assess whether nCT indeed confers a survival advantage beyond those who had a major pathological response, one must look toward several randomized trials that clearly demonstrated this positive impact. However, in many of these studies, histologies were commonly mixed and disease above and below the diaphragm combined. Therapeutic agents are also varied including cisplatin and 5FU\u2013based doublet regimen, triplet regimens based on anthracyclines such as epirubicin, and more recently docetaxel-based triplet and quadruplet regimens.\n\nThe Medicine Research Council OEO2 study was one of the first trials to explore the use of nCT versus surgery alone in locally advanced EAC and ESCC. Contrary to the intergroup 0113 study, preoperative cisplatin and 5FU was associated with a significant downstaging of the tumor and lymph node disease. The 2- and 5-year survival increased significantly from 34% to 43% and from 17% to 23%, respectively (HR 0.79, 95% CI 0.67\u20130.93, *P* \\=.004). This study was responsible for firmly establishing the role of nCT for locally advanced EAC. Interestingly, no difference was noted in the response to nCT when comparing between the histological subtypes. There was, however, a perioperative mortality rate of 10% in both arms of the trial. Long-term follow-up from the OEO2 study revealed a tendency towards EAC having a slightly greater survival benefit with nCT compared with ESCC.\n\nThe value of perioperative chemotherapy was not properly assessed until the British MAGIC and French FNLCC/FFCD trials were performed. In the British MAGIC trial, perioperative therapy with epirubicin, cisplatin, and 5FU (ECF) was found to be particularly effective in patients with EAC. However, these patients only represented 25% of the total cohort. In comparison with those treated with upfront surgery, perioperative chemotherapy was associated with an improvement in the rate of R0 resections (79.3% vs. 70.3%, *P* \\=.03), a tendency for smaller tumors, and less advanced nodal disease. In keeping with these findings, improved overall survival was noted in those receiving systemic treatment with a 5-year survival of 36.3% versus 23% (HR 0.75, 95% CI 0.6\u20130.93, *P* \\=.009). However, it is important to note that only 55% were able to receive the postoperative systemic therapy. In the French FNLCC/FFCD study based on cisplatin and 5FU, comparable survival outcomes were found and a similar number received the adjuvant chemotherapy. Unlike the MAGIC study, however, 75% harbored lower esophageal or junction tumors.\n\nWith regards to ESCC, Boonstra et al. conducted a clinical trial comparing perioperative chemotherapy using a regimen of cisplatin and etoposide. In keeping with other studies of EAC, a partial response rate of 40% and complete response rate of 7% were observed. However, despite these promising pathological results, no difference in the rate of R0 resections (71% vs. 57%) or lymph node positivity between the two treatment arms was noted. However, significantly more patients in the surgery alone arm demonstrated unresectable tumors or underwent an R2 resection. Accordingly, a significant survival advantage in patients receiving perioperative chemotherapy was noted (median, 2-, and 5-year survival of perioperative chemotherapy vs. surgery alone was 16 months vs. 12 months, 42% vs. 30%, and 26% vs. 17%, respectively).\n\nCollectively, the data demonstrate that when given in the perioperative setting, chemotherapy can effectively reduce tumor burden, facilitate curative resection, and confer a significant survival benefit in patients with locally advanced ESCC and EAC. Therefore, despite some data that failed to find a survival advantage with systemic treatment, a bulk of the evidence supports nCT as a standard of care regardless of histology.\n\n### The Dawn of the Docetaxel Era\n\nThe studies mentioned thus far have predominantly employed doublet chemotherapy regimens, typically comprising a platinum agent and 5FU. The rationale for this regimen stems from the observation of significant pathological and clinical response to these agents in conjunction with a good toxicity profile. The MAGIC trial built on this principle and tested the theory that by adding an anthracycline to create a triplet regimen, survival may be further improved.\n\nBased on the observation that metastatic gastric cancer could be effectively treated with a docetaxel-based triplet therapy, an investigator-initiated phase II single-arm trial was undertaken in our department for patients with EAC. Utilizing perioperative docetaxel, cisplatin, and 5FU (DCF), an exceptional 5-year survival of over 50% despite a heavy tumor burden was found. A subsequent landmark study by Al-Batran et al. formalized the use of 5FU, leucovorin, oxaliplatin, and docetaxel (FLOT) and as a perioperative regimen for the treatment of gastroesophageal adenocarcinoma. In this study, 716 patients were randomized to receive either FLOT or the ECF regimen popularized by the MAGIC study. The median overall survival of patients significantly improved from 35 to 50 months with an equivalent toxicity profile and incidence of postoperative complications. Beyond the trial setting, data from 206 patients recruited to the RealFLOT study confirmed the trial results in a real-world cohort of patients. It is important to note that while the FLOT trial included type II esophagogastric junction cancers, type I and true EACs were excluded. However, recent genomic analysis of proximal gastric and EAC suggest that these two tumor types are almost identical and should be considered a single disease (gastroesophageal adenocarcinoma) and thus treated similarly. Supporting this claim, we recently published a multicenter observational cohort study from three high-volume centers that demonstrated the excellent results from the FLOT4 trial can be extrapolated to patients with EAC patients. Furthermore, when neoadjuvant FLOT is combined with an en bloc transthoracic surgery, a 5-year overall survival of 60% despite disease burden can be achieved. These data have led to docetaxel-based nCT becoming the standard of care for resectable locally advanced EAC.\n\nWith respect to stage II/III ESCC, based on the phase III Japanese JCOG 9204 study by Ando et al., cisplatin and 5FU clearly demonstrated a survival benefit when used in the adjuvant setting. The role of neoadjuvant, rather than adjuvant, cisplatin, and 5FU was subsequently explored in the JCOG9907 trial, in which better survival outcomes were associated with preoperative treatment. In this study, preoperative rather than postoperative chemotherapy was associated with an increase in 5-year overall survival by 12% to 55%. However, concerns about undertreatment and relatively high numbers of early postoperative recurrence have led to other treatment avenues being explored.\n\nThe addition of docetaxel is the most promising of these avenues. The addition of this agent has been shown to be safe in both the neoadjuvant and palliative setting. While the formal results of the NExT trial are awaited, preliminary results suggest that DCF significantly improves survival over CF alone in patients with ESCC (3-year overall survival 62.6% vs. 72.1%). These findings are supported by retrospective data that found that DCF was associated with a significantly higher 3-year overall survival compared with CF (79% vs. 65%, respectively). Similarly, real-world data from 2148 patients with ESCC treated with either DCF or CF found that overall survival was significantly longer with DCF (HR 0.868, 95% CI 0.770\u20130.978, *P* \\=.002) without an increase in treatment or postoperative morbidity or mortality. Further data from a randomized multicentric study found that when adding Adriamycin to cisplatin and 5FU, overall survival was still inferior to docetaxel-based triplet therapy.\n\nTaken together, the safety of nCT is clearly demonstrated as is the survival advantage conferred in comparison with surgery alone. Older regimens have made way for newer, docetaxel-based treatments in patients with EAC. For patients with ESCC, nCT seems to provide an effective and alternative treatment option to nCRT.\n\n#### Neoadjuvant Chemotherapy or Chemoradiotherapy\n\nA summary of relevant trials comparing nCT versus nCRT is presented in Table 32.3 . Proponents of nCRT cite higher rates of R0 resections and incidence of pathological complete response. Opponents claim that the interaction between these outcomes and improvements in overall survival is not clear. Moreover, it may be that the chemotherapy delivered as part of the nCRT regimen provides sufficient control of disease beyond the irradiated field. However, data comparing nCRT with nCT in the setting of ESCC are conflicting. A randomized controlled trial published in 2021 showed fewer cancer-related deaths among patients with ESCC treated with nCRT (40 Gy, paclitaxel, cisplatin) as opposed to nCT (paclitaxel and cisplatin). However, this did not translate into improved overall survival with 3-year overall survival among recipients of nCRT compared with nCT (64% vs. 55%, 95% CI 47\u201364%). Although progression-free and recurrence-free survival were also similar despite pathological complete response being higher among recipients of nCRT, there was a trend toward a lower risk of recurrence among irradiated patients (38% vs. 49%, *P* \\=.062). Randomized data from a large four-arm (nCT, nCRT, surgery, and nRT) Chinese study found that while all neoadjuvant therapies improved 3-year overall survival, all regimens had similar outcomes at 5 years including nCT and nCRT.\n\nTable 32.3\n\nComparison of Neoadjuvant Chemotherapy With Neoadjuvant Chemoradiotherapy\n\n| Name | Year | Histology | *N* | Neoadjuvant Regimen | Survival Outcomes |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Nygaard | 1992 | ESCC | | nCT: cisplatin, bleomycin nCRT: cisplatin, bleomycin, 35 Gy | 3-year overall survival 17% 3%\u2217 |\n| Cao | 2009 | ESCC | 237 | nCT: cisplatin, mitomycin, 5FU nCRT: cisplatin, mitomycin, 5FU, 40 Gy | 3-year overall survival 57.1% 73.3%\u2217 |\n| Burmeister | 2011 | EAC | 75 | nCT: cisplatin, 5FU nCRT: cisplatin, 5FU, 35 Gy | 5-year overall survival 36% 45% |\n| Klevebro | 2016 | EAC/ESCC | 181 | nCT: cisplatin, 5FU nCRT: cisplatin, 5FU, 40 Gy | 3-year overall survival 49% 47% |\n| Stahl | 2017 | EAC | 119 | nCT: cisplatin, leucovorin, 5FU nCRT: cisplatin, leucovorin, 5FU, etoposide, 50 Gy | 3-year overall survival 27.7% 47.4%\u2217 |\n| Reynolds | 2021 | EAC | 377 | nCT: epirubicin, cisplatin/oxaliplatin, 5FU/capecitabine or 5FU, leucovorin, oxaliplatin, docetaxel nCRT: carboplatin, paclitaxel, 41.4 Gy | 3-year estimated survival 57% 56% |\n| Wang | 2021 | ESCC | 264 | nCT: cisplatin, paclitaxel nCRT: cisplatin, paclitaxel, 40 Gy | 1-year overall survival 82.6% 87.1% |\n\nThe NExT trial by Kato et al. adds important data to this debate. Of the 601 patients included in the study, 200 were enrolled onto the nCRT arm (cisplatin and 5FU alongside 41.4 Gy of radiation). Although impressive, the overall survival of these patients of 6.0 years did not differ from the nCT arms. This was despite progression-free survival being considerably longer among recipients of nCRT (2.7 years vs. 5.3 years). Importantly, treatment-related deaths were similar between the arms (1.0%\u20132.0%). While retrospective data also supports the finding of noninferiority of nCRT over nCT, <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> it does not seem that differing iterations of the systemic aspect of the treatment affects survival outcomes in patients with ESCC. Further randomized data comparing the outcomes in patients with ESCC will be helpful in continuing to delineate this place of nCRT and nCT in the treatment of ESCC.\n\nFor cohorts of patients with EAC, data from several randomized controlled trials have explored whether adding radiotherapy confers additional survival benefit. The Pre-operative therapy in Esophagogastric adenocarcinoma Trial (POET) randomized 119 patients with Siewert I\u2013III adenocarcinoma. Survival in the nCRT arm seemed to be higher than that in the nCT arm (3- and 5-year overall survival was 46.7% and 39.5% vs. 26.1% and 24.4%, respectively). Although this study suggests that nCT outperforms nCRT in terms of survival, the survival in the nCT arm was less than would be expected with modern neoadjuvant regimens. This may be explained, in part, by only 47% of those treated with nCT undergoing transthoracic esophagectomy. Conversely, the NeoRes study randomized 181 patients with EAC and ESCC. Although this study showed a higher rate of pathological complete response and R0 resection across both histologies in those treated with radiation, this did not translate into a superiority in terms of survival when comparing nCRT (CF with 40 Gy of radiotherapy) with nCT (CF). There was however a trend towards improved survival among patients with EAC who were treated with nCT, whereas patients with ESCC did slightly better with nCRT. The long-term results of this trial have also been published in 2019, which confirmed no survival difference between the treatment arms (42.2% vs. 39.6%, *P* \\= 0.60). The ability to generalize the results of this study is limited as it was underpowered to perform a subset analysis, used a dose of radiotherapy below that is commonly used, and also used a chemotherapy regimen that is not currently a standard of care.\n\nThese limitations have been addressed by the NeoAEGIS study, the results of which have also just become available. Randomizing 362 patients with adenocarcinoma of the esophagus and esophagogastric junction, patients received either the CROSS or MAGIC (ECF) regimens. This study also failed to show inferiority of either regimen with a 3-year overall survival of 57% versus 55%, respectively (HR 1.03, 95% CI 0.77\u20131.38). While FLOT was included in the latter phase of the study, these patients only represented 15% of the nCT cohort. Given the vast superiority of FLOT over ECF demonstrated in the FLOT4 trial, it is possible that the outcomes of the chemotherapy arm could have been superior.\n\nThe ESOPEC trial hopes to answer this exact question by comparing the efficacy of FLOT versus CROSS regimens in the treatment of EAC. Survival data from the TOPGEAR and RACE studies, which also compare ECF with CROSS in the treatment of esophagogastric adenocarcinoma, are also eagerly awaited. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nIn lieu of prospective randomized data, some retrospective data compares survival outcomes of modern nCT regimens with nCRT. In a study comparing the CROSS regimen with a historical cohort of patients treated with epirubicin, oxaliplatin, and capecitabine, 5-year overall survival was 17% and 51%, respectively. However, the survival outcomes from the CROSS arm are considerably below those reported in the original study. In comparison, a population-based study of 11,167 patients with EAC and 2367 with ESCC found that compared with nCT, nCRT was associated with a higher chance of pathological complete response and R0 resections but for the cohort as a whole, a similar 5-year overall survival was described (37% vs. 36%, *P* \\=.123). Only when stratified by histological subtype did it become apparent that patients with ESCC fared significantly better in terms of survival after being treated with nCRT (5-year overall survival 45% vs. 38%, *P* \\=.026).\n\nIn summary, nCRT appears to achieve improved local disease control, particularly in the setting of ESCC. However, even when pathological complete response is achieved following nCRT, survival outcomes appear to be inferior as to when this is achieved after nCT (odds ratio 2.50, 95% CI 1.25\u20134.99). This implies that systemic disease control is more important for survival than the local control afforded by radiotherapy. Therefore, for EAC the current data support an approach of nCT being at least noninferior to nCRT although the results of several ongoing trials may tip this needle in favor of docetaxel-based regimens. For ESCC, while the improved local control of nCRT is certainly attractive, this approach is similarly associated with equivalent survival outcomes as nCT. As such, both modalities are accepted standards of care.\n\n#### Safety of Neoadjuvant Chemotherapy Versus Chemoradiotherapy\n\nAssuming the noninferiority of nCT when compared with nCRT, the relative safety of adding radiotherapy before surgery should be considered. With regard to postoperative deaths, early studies by Stahl et al. and Bedenne et al. describe a perioperative mortality of 9% to 12% in patients treated with nCRT followed by surgery. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In the study by Stahl et al., while this was considerably higher than the 3.8% inpatient mortality of the nCT arm, it failed to reach a level of statistical significance.\n\nWith improvements in surgical techniques, perioperative mortality has generally decreased. For example, in data from a 2021 prospective multicenter randomized trial of minimally invasive esophagectomy, postoperative morbidity and mortality were similar irrespective of whether or not irradiation was used (47.4% vs. 42.6% and 3.5% vs. 2.8%, respectively). Conversely, while safety data from the NeoAEGIS trial was similar, significantly more patients treated with nCRT had Clavien-Dindo grade III complications and above (30% vs. 17%, *P* \\=.05) as well as a higher mean comprehensive complication index.\n\nThese results are supported by a 2022 meta-analysis that synthesized randomized and retrospective data of patients with ESCC treated with either nCRT or nCT. In this study of 3137 patients across 18 studies, there was no difference in the incidence of postoperative complications irrespective of the neoadjuvant treatment modality used.\n\n#### Immunotherapy and Biological Agents\n\nSeveral studies have demonstrated efficacy of either immunotherapy or biological agents for patients with advanced or metastatic esophageal cancer. In the ToGA study, the addition of trastuzumab to palliative CF in patients found to be HER2 positive led to a small but significant improvement in median overall survival in patients with advanced gastric adenocarcinoma from 11.1 to 13.5 months. However, adding trastuzumab preoperatively to the treatment of EAC has not translated into a survival benefit as demonstrated by the NRG Oncology/RTOG 1010 phase III multicenter trial. In this study, patients with resectable EAC were treated with cisplatin, paclitaxel, and 50.5 Gy of radiation followed by surgery. Those found to be HER2 positive were randomized to receive neoadjuvant trastuzumab. However, trastuzumab did not affect survival, and the incidence of treatment-related deaths in this arm was twice as high as that in patients who did not receive this treatment (6% vs. 3%). The KEYNOTE 590 study, which randomized the addition of pembrolizumab to cisplatin and 5FU to patients with advanced or metastatic esophageal cancer, also showed an increase in overall survival with an equivalent safety profile.\n\nHowever, the exact role of novel agents in the setting of esophagogastric cancer has yet to be realized. Multiple trials exploring the role of novel agents, including neoadjuvant pembrolizumab and avelumab, are ongoing. While preliminary data suggest that preoperative pembrolizumab and nivolumab independently increase the rate of tumoral response to neoadjuvant therapy, the impact this may have on survival has not yet been described. Similarly, in the single-armed ESONICT-2 trial, which has explored the role of adding neoadjuvant toripalimab to docetaxel and cisplatin for ESCC, found major pathological response of 41.7% with survival data yet to be presented. In lieu of this survival data, several authors have shown that immunotherapy is safe when given concurrently with nCT by not increasing postoperative morbidity or mortality.\n\nThere is a clear paucity of data regarding survival outcomes in patients treated with neoadjuvant immunotherapy. While retrospective data is starting to emerge, it is the results of the prospective trials that will shape treatment outcomes going forward. Nevertheless, in light of the lack of data at present, recommendations with regard to treatment decisions cannot be made.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe differences in EAC and ESCC as disease processes have been highlighted by the advancements in neoadjuvant treatment regimens. In our opinion, these two disease entities should be treated differently. It is clear that chemotherapy or chemoradiotherapy should be given before surgery; however, perioperative systemic regimens have taken over the landscape for patients with EAC in many centers around the world. Although significant regional differences exist, the data suggest that for EAC docetaxel-based therapy given in a perioperative fashion followed by en bloc surgical should be considered the standard of care for this histological subtype. Successful identification of the agent, and patients, who will benefit from immunotherapy or biological agents to the neoadjuvant setting will likely influence future recommendations.\n\nFor patients with locally advanced ESCC, despite the limitations noted earlier, nCRT followed by surgery seems to be the best treatment option available. The addition of adjuvant checkpoint inhibition in the presence of residual disease seems to be the best augment to this approach. However, significant regional differences exist in this setting as well, with docetaxel-based therapy emerging as a viable alternative based on the trial results described earlier. Finally, selective surgery after induction chemoradiation is also on the horizon for both ESCC and EAC, and future studies may provide a foundation for treating certain patients definitively.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Pasquali S., Yim G., Vohra R.S., et al.: Survival after neoadjuvant and adjuvant treatments compared to surgery alone for resectable esophageal carcinoma: a network meta-analysis . Ann Surg 2017; 265 (3): pp. 481-491.\n\nView In Article\n\n2.: Launois B., Delarue D., Campion J.P., Kerbaol M.: Preoperative radiotherapy for carcinoma of the esophagus . Surg Gynecol Obstet 1981; 153 (5): pp. 690-692.\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: Goodner J.T.: Surgical and radiation treatment of cancer of the thoracic esophagus . Am J Roentgenol Radium Ther Nucl Med 1969; 105 (3): pp. 523-528.\n\nView In Article\n\n4.: Arnott S.J., Duncan W., Gignoux M., et al.: Oeosphageal cancer collaborative group. Preoperative radiotherapy for esophageal carcinoma . Cochrane Database Syst Rev 2005; 2005 (4):\n\nView In Article\n\n5.: Gignoux M., Roussel A., Paillot B., et al.: The value of preoperative radiotherapy in esophageal cancer: results of a study of the E.O.R.T.C . World J Surg 1987; 11 (4): pp. 426-432.\n\nView In Article\n\n6.: Arnott S.J., Duncan W., Kerr G.R., et al.: Low dose preoperative radiotherapy for carcinoma of the oesophagus: results of a randomized clinical trial . Radiother Oncol 1992; 24 (2): pp. 108-113.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference90287-5)\n\n7.: Cao X.F., He X.T., Ji L., Xiao J., Lv J.: Effects of neoadjuvant radiochemotherapy on pathological staging and prognosis for locally advanced esophageal squamous cell carcinoma . Dis Esophagus 2009; 22 (6): pp. 477-481.\n\nView In