('Anastomotic Complications After Esophagectomy', 'shackelford-9th-ed-36-anastomotic-complications-after-esophagectomy', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Anastomotic Complications After Esophagectomy\n\nTamar Bella Nobel; Daniela Molena\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 36, 384-391\n\n## Introduction\n\nAnastomotic complications remain the Achilles heel of every surgeon who performs esophagectomy. Management of leak poses a significant technical challenge. Despite improvements in surgical technique, recent data from the Esophageal Complications Consensus Group (ECCG) has demonstrated a leak rate of 11.4%. Leak is associated with a three-fold increased risk of postoperative death and up to 60% mortality. Other sequelae of leak include increased length of hospital stay, delayed initiation of oral feeding, and increased risk of reoperation. Anastomotic leak may also influence oncologic outcome; in a multicenter study of 2994 postoperative patients with esophageal cancer, Markar et al. demonstrated a significant reduction in both overall and disease-free survival in patients with severe anastomotic leak (35.8 vs. 54.8 months, and 34 vs. 47.9 months, respectively) and 35% increased risk of recurrence. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> These grave consequences make prevention, when possible, and early identification of leaks of utmost importance to minimize the impact of such events. In this chapter, we discuss the etiology, diagnosis, and treatment of anastomotic complications after esophagectomy, including leak as well as stricture and conduit-airway fistula.\n\n### Incidence and Classification of Anastomotic Leak\n\nThe incidence of anastomotic leak after esophagectomy ranges from 0% to 35%. Analyses of Society of Thoracic Surgeons (STS) database results reported a 12% incidence of leaks requiring medical or surgical intervention. Variability in the definition of anastomotic leak has led to wide discrepancies in reported rates. Bruce et al. determined that fewer than 40% of articles pertaining to anastomotic leak after esophagectomy included the criteria used to establish the diagnosis, and another systematic review noted definitions included in only 28.3% of studies with 22 different descriptions used. Possible explanations for differences in reported outcomes in the literature include variable diagnostic tools used to identify a leak, time frame used for evaluation (e.g., 30 vs. 90 days), and anastomotic location.\n\nThere have been multiple groups that have sought to reach a consensus on a definition for anastomotic leak. The International Multispecialty Anastomotic Leak Global Improvement Exchange group (IMAGINE) defined gastrointestinal postoperative anastomotic leak as \u201ca defect of the integrity in a surgical join between two hollow viscera with communication between the intraluminal and extraluminal compartments.\u201d In 2015 the Esophagectomy Complications Consensus Group (ECCG), a group of 21 high-volume esophageal surgeons from 14 countries met to create a standardized system for defining and recording complications after esophagectomy ( Table 36.1 ). Another commonly referenced classification system was proposed by Lerut et al. ( Table 36.2 ). In this definition, clinically occult leaks diagnosed on routine postoperative imaging comprise the most minor end of the spectrum, while conduit necrosis is the most severe presentation. The type of leak has significant clinical implications, with grade I/II being relatively low risk and grades III and IV having mortality rates near 60% and 90%, respectively.\n\nTable 36.1\n\nDefinitions\n\nReprinted with permission from Lerut T, Coosemans W, Decker G, et al. Anastomotic complications after esophagectomy. *Dig Surg* . \u00a9 2002 S. Karger AG, Basel19:92\u201398.21.\n\n| Anastomotic Leak |\n| --- |\n| *Defined as* : Full-thickness GI defect involving esophagus, anastomosis, staple line, or conduit irrespective of presentation or method of identification |\n| - Type I: Local defect requiring no change in therapy or treated medically or with dietary modification - Type II: Localized defect requiring interventional but not surgical therapy, for example, interventional radiology drain, stent or bedside opening, and packing of incision - Type III: Localized defect requiring surgical therapy |\n| Conduit Necrosis |\n| - Type I: Conduit necrosis focal \t- \u2022 \t\tIdentified endoscopically \t- \u2022 \t\tTreatment\u2014additional monitoring or nonsurgical therapy - Type II: Conduit necrosis focal \t- \u2022 \t\tIdentified endoscopically and not associated with free anastomotic or conduit leak \t- \u2022 \t\tTreatment\u2014surgical therapy not involving esophageal diversion - Type III: Conduit necrosis extensive \t- \u2022 \t\tTreatment\u2014treated with conduit resection with diversion |\n| Chyle Leak |\n| - Type I: Treatment\u2014enteric dietary modifications - Type II: Treatment\u2014total parenteral nutrition - Type III: Treatment\u2014interventional or surgical therapy <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">a</sup> \t- Severity Level \t\t- < 1 L output/day \t\t- \\> 1 L output/day |\n| For example, a chyle leak initially producing 1200 mL/day and successfully treated by stopping enteric feeds and initiating TPN, Final Type IIB |\n| Vocal Cord Injury/Palsy |\n| *Defined as* : Vocal cord dysfunction post-resection. Confirmation and assessment should be by direct examination. |\n| - Type I: Transient injury requiring no therapy \t- Dietary modification allowed - Type II: Injury requiring elective surgical procedure, for example, thyroplasty or medialization procedure - Type III: Injury requiring acute surgical intervention (due to aspiration or respiratory issues), for example, thyroplasty or medialization procedure \t- Severity Level \t\t- Unilateral \t\t- Bilateral |\n| For example, a unilateral vocal cord injury requiring elective medialization procedure. Final Type IIA |\n\n*GI,* Gastrointestinal; TPN, total parenteral nutrition.\n\nTable 36.2\n\nLerut Classification of Anastomotic Leak\n\nFrom Lerut T, Coosemans W, Decker G, et al. Anastomotic complications after esophagectomy. *Dig Surg* . 2002;19:92\u201398.\n\n<table><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Leak (Grade)</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Definitions</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Treatment</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align=\"\">Radiologic (I)</td><td align=\"\">No clinical signs</td><td align=\"\">No change in management</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\" rowspan=\"3\">Clinical Minor (II)</td><td align=\"\">Local inflammation (cervical wound)</td><td align=\"\">Drain wound</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">X-ray contained leak (thoracic anastomosis)</td><td align=\"\">Delay oral intake</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Fever, leukocytosis</td><td align=\"\">Antibiotics</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\" rowspan=\"2\">Clinical Major (III)</td><td align=\"\">Severe disruption on endoscopy</td><td align=\"\">Change management: CT-guided drainage (reintervention)</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Sepsis</td><td align=\"\"></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Conduit Necrosis (IV)</td><td align=\"\">Endoscopic confirmation</td><td align=\"\">Reintervention</td></tr></tbody></table>\n\n#### Risk Factors for Anastomotic Leak\n\nFailed anastomotic healing is affected by multiple interrelated factors. Understanding these predictive variables is important in the preoperative setting because modifiable factors may be better optimized, and fixed characteristics may be used for risk stratification and patient selection in attempts to minimize poor outcomes. Patient and technical factors associated with leak are discussed below.\n\n## Patient Factors\n\n## Nutrition\n\nEsophagectomy is most often used to treat esophageal cancer and also has a role in the management of motility disorders; therefore, it is not surprising that patients undergoing esophagectomy often present with malnutrition due to impaired alimentation. Poor nutritional status, commonly defined as hypoalbuminemia or weight loss, has previously been demonstrated to be associated with increased risk of anastomotic leak.\n\n## Medical Comorbidities\n\nAnalysis of the STS database found that heart failure, hypertension, renal insufficiency, and procedure type were predictive of anastomotic leak.\n\n## Neoadjuvant Therapy\n\nUse of neoadjuvant therapy has been associated with increased risk of leak in some series, although this appears to be dependent on radiation dose given. A review of 1939 patients demonstrated no increase in complications in patients who underwent preoperative neoadjuvant therapy. Additionally, the presence of diabetes mellitus or advanced patient age surprisingly does not seem to affect leak rates.\n\n## Technical Factors\n\n## Anatomic Considerations\n\nThe esophagus has several unique characteristics that make anastomosis after esophageal resection more technically challenging. Unlike the other organs of the gastrointestinal system, the esophagus does not have a serosal layer. This, in combination with the longitudinal orientation of the muscle fibers of the esophagus, contributes to increased fragility and decreased suture strength. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Attempts to create additional protection using a free peritoneal patch did not demonstrate an impact on the rate of leak but did increase the rate of stricture.\n\nFurthermore, the esophagus is primarily located within the thorax, which may create a unique challenge for esophageal anastomoses when compared with other types of gastrointestinal leaks. The negative intrathoracic pressure may draw gastric fluid across anastomotic lines and result in leakage. Such leaks into the pleural space may affect the dynamics of intrathoracic pressure and result in respiratory and hemodynamic instability.\n\nThe ability of an anastomosis to heal successfully is directly associated with maintenance of adequate tissue perfusion to the conduit. During gastric mobilization and resection of the lesser curvature, the major vessels are ligated leaving approximately 60% of the gastric tube to be supplied by the right gastroepiploic vessels and the remaining proximal portion is supplied by small collateral vessels. As such, the anastomosis, which is usually made at the fundus, is within the most ischemic part. Caution must be exercised to minimize trauma to the collateral vessels during dissection. Tension on the anastomosis can lead to impaired blood supply and result in ischemia. Incidence of gastric conduit ischemia ranges from 0.5% to 10.4%, which includes cases ranging from self-resolving, subclinical ischemia to frank necrosis. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n## Tension and Conduit Type\n\nSome authors have suggested that the utilization of the whole stomach as opposed to a gastric tube may better preserve blood supply by not disturbing collateral circulation. Arguments against use of the whole stomach claim that use of a gastric tube yields less gastric distention and decreased surface area for acid secretion, both of which can be detrimental to the anastomosis and lead to poor quality of life. A narrow gastric conduit with longer length can better reach the cervical anastomosis site without tension but must be balanced against excessive narrowing leading to impaired blood supply. Controversy remains as to whether other types of conduits, most commonly colonic, have a similar incidence of leak; however, colonic interposition does require three anastomoses as opposed to one when using a gastric conduit.\n\n## Anastomosis Site\n\nCervical anastomosis has been associated with a higher incidence of leakage than thoracic, with rates ranging from 2% to 26%. This may be partially explained by the longer distance required for blood supply to travel to the anastomosis site in the neck. In comparison, thoracic anastomoses are associated with leak rates of 0% to 9.3%. There was previously a suggestion in the literature that thoracic leaks are associated with higher postoperative mortality, but more recent data do not support this finding when considering early (30-day) outcomes. The higher leak rate associated with cervical anastomosis is more accepted because it is generally contained and thus associated with lower risk. Thoracic anastomotic breakdown is often associated with mediastinal soilage and may have a more severe clinical course. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n## Anastomotic Technique\n\nThe type of anastomotic technique selected most often depends upon the surgeon\u2019s preference. Stapled anastomotic technique has been used for approximately 25 years and gained increasing popularity due to easier reconstruction, especially in areas where exposure and access are limited. Heitmiller et al. described a 0.8% leak rate after two-layer handsewn anastomosis. Blackmon et al. published a propensity-matched analysis comparing outcomes between side-to-side stapled anastomosis, end-to-end circular stapled anastomosis, and handsewn anastomosis, with no significant difference in leak rate noted. Multiple randomized controlled trials have compared various techniques in an attempt to identify the safest approach but have failed to identify a significant difference in leak rate. Reconstruction can be performed either via an anterior retrosternal route or a posterior mediastinal route when performing a cervical anastomosis. Urschel et al. performed a meta-analysis that failed to demonstrate a significant difference in leak rate; however, the posterior route is alleged to have the advantages of shorter distance to the anastomosis, resulting in decreased tension, avoidance of foregut angulation, less cardiopulmonary morbidity, soft tissue coverage of potentially devascularized airways, and preservation of the skeletal structures of the thoracic inlet. Anterior reconstruction is primarily justified due to the minimization of tumor recurrence by avoiding the posterior tumor bed.\n\n## Operative Approach\n\nLaparoscopic surgery has become the standard approach to many gastrointestinal operations because it has been demonstrated to be safe with better postoperative results. Similarly, there has been increased utilization of minimally invasive approaches to esophagectomy. A 2016 Cochrane Review evaluating open versus laparoscopic transhiatal esophagectomy (THE) observed fewer overall complications and decreased length of stay. Biere et al. performed a randomized control trial comparing open versus minimally invasive transthoracic esophagectomy and demonstrated significant postoperative benefits, including decreased incidence of pulmonary infections, decreased length of stay, decreased operative blood loss, and improved quality of life at 6 weeks postoperatively and postoperative pain scores. In addition, no differences were demonstrated in the number of lymph nodes harvested and rate of R0 resection.\n\n## Leak Diagnosis\n\nDiagnosis of anastomotic leaks is dependent upon the size and location of the leak. In cases of conduit necrosis, patients often present within 48\u201372 hours with catastrophic sepsis. Clinical suspicion is necessary to correctly diagnose more subtle leaks. Cervical leaks usually present within 5\u201310 days with associated fever, drainage, and wound erythema. Intrathoracic leaks may be less apparent. The most obvious sign is bilious output in surgical drains. Unexplained low-grade fever, tachycardia, or leukocytosis should prompt suspicion.\n\nA proposed risk assessment score found that C-reactive protein, white blood cell count, and albumin levels could be used to predict major complications with a sensitivity of 89% and specificity of 63%. Many practices perform routine contrast esophagram studies postoperatively. Usually, water-soluble contrast is used initially followed by barium. Grade I leaks are usually clinically silent and detected on such routine imaging. Computed tomography (CT) scan with oral contrast is more sensitive than contrast swallow study, and it is our preferred approach when suspicious for leak. Endoscopy is a useful adjunctive tool to confirm leak and guide potential intervention. Despite concern regarding an invasive procedure in the setting of a fresh anastomosis, systematic endoscopy following esophagectomy has been demonstrated to be safe ( Table 36.3 ). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nTable 36.3\n\nEndoscopic Grading of Anastomotic Ischemia\n\nFrom Oezcelik A, Banki F, Ayazi S, et al. Detection of gastric conduit ischemia or anastomotic breakdown after cervical esophagogastrostomy: the use of computed tomography scan versus early endoscopy. *Surg Endosc* . 2010;24:1948\u20131951.\n\n| Grade | Findings |\n| --- | --- |\n| 1 | Dusky bluish-colored mucosa near anastomosis covered with metallic appearing mucus |\n| 2 | Partial anastomotic disruption with equivocal viability or normal pink mucosa margins |\n| 3 | Complete circumferential anastomotic breakdown with normal pink mucosa margins |\n| 4 | Completely necrotic black mucosa throughout the conduit with intact anastomosis |\n\n## Management of Esophageal Leak\n\n### General Principles\n\nGeneral principles for management of anastomotic leak include intensive care treatment, maintenance of perfusion to the conduit through minimization of hypotension, optimization of respiratory function, broad-spectrum antibiotics, and nutrition, preferably enteral downstream from the site of leakage. Furthermore, collections near the site of the anastomosis should be drained. In the absence of diffuse conduit necrosis, further treatment is dependent upon the location of leak, timing, and severity of clinical presentation. Although the conventionally accepted approach used to be conduit excision with diversion and delayed reconstruction, conduit salvage is preferred whenever feasible. Comparison between non-operative and operative management has demonstrated no difference in time to leak closure, but patient selection plays an important role in the selection of approach. Important factors to assess when determining the approach to management include the overall clinical status of the patient, leak severity, viability of the conduit, size and circumference of the defect, and extent of contamination. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Nonoperative Management\n\nIn patients who are not septic and have a well-contained leak, a non-operative approach can be considered. The patient should be initially managed with intravenous antibiotics, conduit decompression with nasogastric tube, and nothing per os (NPO) diet. Drainage of the neck or chest should be considered. Patients with contained intrathoracic collections may be treated with image-guided drainage performed by interventional radiology. Data suggest that drain placement alone may be more likely to be successful in stable patients with isolated cervical leak (100%, *n* \\= 23) than in patients with thoracic anastomotic leak (41%, *n* \\= 15). Repeat contrast study or endoscopy may be performed to document healing. Median time to closure is approximately 2 to 3 weeks. If patients fail to respond promptly to management with the above approaches, inadequate drainage or conduit necrosis should be considered and further investigation should be undertaken. There is a high risk of stricture formation following cervical anastomotic leaks. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n#### Endoscopic Adjuncts\n\n## Endoscopic Stenting\n\nStenting has become widely used in the management of esophageal perforation and anastomotic leak with good outcomes. Comparison of 2543 patients treated for esophageal perforation (1314 repair vs. 1229 stenting) demonstrated similar mortality between patients with surgical repair and those with stent. Stents may allow for patients not only to heal their defect but in some cases, patients may also be able to tolerate enteral nutrition. In cases in which less than 30% of circumference of the anastomosis has broken down, stent placement may be appropriate. The stent is left in place for up to 4 weeks prior to removal and assessment of healing. Freeman et al. reported outcomes of 17 patients treated with stents after intrathoracic anastomotic leak and demonstrated 94% success in healing with 18% stent migration. The majority (82%) of patients were able to resume a diet 72 hours after stenting, and stents were removed at a mean of 17 days. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nCovered metal stents are our preferred approach to facilitate ease of removal. Two meta-analyses of 267 and 340 patients demonstrated a similar rate of clinical success between metal and plastic stents (81% and 85%), and plastic stents demonstrated a higher rate of migration (18% and 27%). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nStent migration is a common problem, which may be minimized with the use of longer stents or with adjuncts, including clipping or suturing. Other risks include inadequate coverage resulting in persistent leak, plugging, and erosion into surrounding structures.\n\nAlthough good outcomes have been demonstrated with stenting, patient selection is key. The optimal patient is not septic and has a defect that is amenable to control with stent placement. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n## Endoluminal Vacuum Therapy\n\nThe benefits of negative pressure wound therapy are well described in the surgical literature in the use of external wounds. Endoluminal vacuum therapy (EndoVac) has emerged as an alternative approach to anastomotic leak after esophagectomy which enables both source control and encourages healing via debridement of the involved tissue and encouragement of cavity contraction and healing. In our practice, we prefer to use EndoVac in clinically stabilized patients who have larger size leaks, such as in the case of a patient with some degree of gastric tip necrosis with dehiscence. If the leak is technical, such as a staple line defect, a stent is typically adequate.\n\nThe patient is brought to the operating room and endoscopy is performed under general anesthesia for airway protection. A diagnostic endoscopy is performed to assess whether the leak is amenable to EndoVac placement. The defect location and size are noted. Our preference is to place the sponge across the esophageal defect within the lumen of the esophagus/conduit rather than within the cavity to better assist in healing. The endosponge is created by the surgeon as there are no commercially available endosponges in the United States. Our preferred approach is to use the black GranuFoam by KCI as it compresses more than the WhiteFoam. The foam is tailored with a scissor to the size of the anastomotic defect in a diamond shape. A clamp is used to make a hole though the long axis of the diamond. The nasogastric tube is inserted into the nose of the patient then pulled out through the mouth, and then passed through the hole. The sponge is secured to the nasogastric tube using a nylon suture on Keith needle by passing it through the sponge and nasogastric tube. Three to four stitches are needed as it is important to have a strong connection so that the sponge does not detach upon its withdrawal. A final stitch is placed at the tip of the nasogastric tube to be grabbed with a biopsy forceps to help drag the sponge into the esophagus ( Fig. 36.1 ).\n\nA medical professional with gloves on the hand holds a foam device with four arrows that point to specific parts of it. Ch36\n\nFig. 36.1\n\nThe air-sump port of the nasogastric tube should be taped or occluded to allow for a complete seal. A biopsy forceps is used to advance the sponge to the desired location under direct endoscopic visualization. Negative pressure is then applied using the KCI wound VAC system at a continuous pressure of\u2013125 mmHg. We then perform serial EndoVac changes every 3\u20137 days depending on healing progress and patient clinical status.\n\nData have suggested excellent results. A single institutional study of 77 patients demonstrated a healing rate of 78% ( *n* \\= 60). However, this study also included spontaneous esophageal perforation in addition to postoperative leak. A review of 29 studies with 209 patients with anastomotic leak after resection of esophageal or gastric cancer demonstrated healing rates of 67% to 100% and the most common complication being anastomotic stricture (9%).\n\n## Other Endoscopic Techniques\n\nApplicability of endoscopic closure techniques is limited by the tissue quality and ability to reapproximate dehisced tissue. Amenable defects are not typical with esophagectomy leaks. Therefore, there are limited data on the use of endoscopic procedures such as endoscopic suturing and clips following esophagectomy. As such, it is not our practice to perform these procedures. There has been description of use of these approaches as an adjunct to stent placement.\n\n### Operative Treatment\n\nReoperation after anastomotic leak can be very technically challenging and as such, it is preferrable to avoid this by using endoscopic interventions and other conservative methods. However, there are certain situations in which operative management is inevitable.\n\nIn the case of cervical anastomoses, the initial management may consist of local wound care with opening of the wound at bedside. Larger, contained cervical leaks with associated wound erythema or fluctuance require debridement and drainage. In the case that the anastomotic site is not identified, drainage may be used to temporize the area until the site of leak heals. The management of intrathoracic leaks depends upon the degree of sepsis. Patients with hemodynamic instability in the setting of sepsis should be taken to the operating room for washout, drainage, and esophagostomy. Conservative operative treatment, with debridement and refashioning of the anastomosis, has been described with 25% risk of recurrent leak. The preferred approach is to proceed with conduit excision and cervical esophagostomy if there is insufficient length to recreate the anastomosis. Reconstruction may be performed at a later time using the colon, jejunum, or myocutaneous flap for restoration of continuity of the gastrointestinal tract.\n\n## Prevention of Leak\n\nPreoperative patient optimization with correction of malnutrition, optimization of medical conditions, and decreasing steroid use have been demonstrated to help decrease the risk of leak. Procedures performed at low-volume centers have been associated with increased risk of postoperative and long-term mortality, as well as increased risk of any (and severe) leaks, which highlights the importance of careful surgical technique in minimizing the incidence of leak. Intraoperatively, there have been attempts to better characterize perfusion to the anastomosis because there is no standardized therapy. Multiple approaches exist, including assessment of graft color, temperature, and checking Doppler signals. Doppler is limited to assessment of macrocirculation. Fluorescence imaging is a promising approach to assessment of the microcirculation and macrocirculation of the gastric conduit. Weaker perfusion, as assessed by intraoperative laser-assisted fluorescent dye angiography, has been demonstrated to be correlated to leak and may be a promising approach.\n\nFollowing stomach mobilization, a 50% drop in gastric fundus oxygen tension has been measured, and further study has described a direct correlation between intraoperative gastric fundus oximetry and resultant anastomotic success. Ischemic preconditioning has been described as an attempt to preoperatively redistribute gastric blood supply. Embolization of the left and right gastric and splenic arteries was performed 2\u20133 weeks before esophagectomy, thus leaving the stomach dependent on the right gastroepiploic artery. Results in animal models have demonstrated decreased anastomotic leak using these techniques, but similar results have not been demonstrated in humans. An additional technical consideration includes division of the interclavicular ligament to alleviate conduit venous obstruction. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nPostoperatively, gastric distention may contribute to anastomotic tension and inhibit venous drainage. Minimization of distention with the use of nasogastric tube and promotility agents may help to alleviate this. Although some perform pyloromyotomy or pyloroplasty at the time of original procedure which may reduce incidence of this complication, our current practice is not to perform a gastric emptying procedure. A review of our own institutional data demonstrated that pyloric drainage was not significantly associated with lower postoperative complications, pneumonia, or anastomotic leak nor with improvement in long-term symptoms.\n\nIn addition, use of pharmacologic agents has been previously studied. Administration of prostaglandin E1 within an hour of gastric tube creation has been shown to increase the blood supply to the fundus, which is the part of the conduit that is most at risk for ischemia.\n\n## Conduit Necrosis\n\nConduit necrosis is the most severe grade of anastomotic leak, as described previously. Mortality after conduit necrosis may exceed 90%, highlighting the importance of rapid identification and treatment of this problem, and when possible, prevention. Multiple risk factors for conduit necrosis have been identified, including improper technique in the creation or manipulation of the gastric tube, radiation, low perioperative cardiac output, postoperative hypotension, previous upper abdominal surgery, malnutrition, peptic ulcer disease, twisting of the stomach conduit as it passes into the mediastinum, and a tight hiatal opening. Radiation creates a fibrotic reaction that decreases the microvascular blood supply of the conduit. By using caution while mobilizing the conduit and taking caution in maintaining adequate patient perfusion in the perioperative period, these factors may be minimized. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nPatients with conduit necrosis most commonly present with severe sepsis within the first week postoperatively. They may initially have an unexplained tachycardia or leukocytosis with rapid clinical decompensation. The most important principle for management of such patients is to have a high clinical suspicion. In patients with a questionable diagnosis, there are multiple diagnostic options available. Traditionally, an upper gastrointestinal contrast study may be used to identify the presence of an anastomotic leak and may possibly demonstrate cobblestoning of the mucosa. CT with oral contrast may yield additional information regarding associated effusions, although a normal exam does not exclude the possibility of ischemia, and fluid and air within the mediastinum may be normal in the postoperative state. Endoscopy should be the next diagnostic modality used. Although there was historical concern regarding anastomotic disruption with this study, Page et al. demonstrated that endoscopy within 1 week of operation was safe and effective in detecting anastomotic leakage.\n\nIn the setting of a small leak, non-operative management with possible stenting will allow the patient to recover. Patients with a completely necrotic conduit are most often septic and brought to the operating room for emergent exploration. A video-assisted thoracoscopic investigation or thoracotomy in the case of an intrathoracic anastomosis or reopening of the neck incision must be performed to visualize the conduit. If this confirms necrosis, then the conduit must be resected and the patient should be diverted with an end esophagostomy, venting gastrostomy, and feeding jejunostomy. Care should be taken to maintain the longest possible length of remaining esophagus to facilitate future reconstruction; however, patients should be resuscitated and sepsis should resolve prior to any such attempts. Options for reconstruction include colonic interposition or jejunal transfer.\n\n## Anastomotic Strictures\n\nReported incidence of stricture after esophagectomy is 10% to 40%; however, as strictures are often diagnosed in the setting of patient-reported dysphagia, it is possible that the true incidence is much higher. Strictures that present early postoperatively are most often benign. Later presentation should raise suspicion for tumor recurrence. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nAnastomotic technique defines the resultant size of the esophagogastric connection which is associated with the resultant size of the anastomosis and wound retraction. Two-layer handsewn anastomoses have demonstrated higher rates of stricture than one layer. When comparing stapled versus handsewn anastomoses, circular end-to-end stapled anastomoses demonstrate higher rate of associated stricture in some series; however, the semi-mechanical end-to-side anastomosis as described by Orringer creates a larger cross-sectional area and appears to have a lower stricture rate (48% of handsewn vs. 35% semi-mechanical). Circular staplers provide a fixed internal diameter but contracture does occur. The incidence of stricture has been demonstrated to be inversely proportional to the diameter of the stapler (52.5% with 21 mm stapler, 16.7% with 25 mm and 5.1% with 28 mm). A side-to-side linear stapled approach is also commonly used and theoretically may alleviate some of the risks of the circular approach. In a series comparing stricture rates among all three approaches, the rate of strictures requiring esophageal dilation was highest with the handsewn technique (34.8%; vs. 8.7% side-to-side stapler and 8.7% circular stapler).\n\nEarly postoperative endoscopy has a high predictive value for subsequent stricture development. Anastomotic leak, more than one endoscopically visible stitch, and mucosal ulceration involving more than 50% of the anastomosis have been identified as factors correlated with stricture development. Benign strictures can be well managed using Savary or pneumatic endoscopic dilation, with 93% of patients experiencing initial relief of dysphagia symptoms. Strictures that arise in the setting of severe anastomotic failure, secondary to ischemia, are more likely to be resistant to serial dilation. In addition to endoscopic dilation, it is important to administer proton pump inhibitor treatment to prevent recurrence.\n\n## Conduit-Airway Fistula\n\nThe esophagogastric anastomosis lies close to the lung parenchyma and membranous airway, which increases the risk of fistulization between the airway and the conduit. Such events, although rare with reported incidence of 0.04% to 0.3%, may present a significant challenge to manage.\n\nMost often, fistulas occur in the setting of anastomotic leak secondary to leakage of enteric contents resulting in tissue necrosis and erosion. Intraoperative tracheobronchial injury, with reported incidence of 1.8% during THE and 0.8% during transthoracic esophagectomy, may serve as another potential source of airway conduit fistulization postoperatively due to the opening in the airway. Additional etiologies may include ischemia and tissue injury due to neoadjuvant radiation, extensive dissection around the trachea, stent erosion after management of leak, following endoscopic dilation of anastomotic stricture, or cuff-induced tracheal necrosis in the setting of prolonged endotracheal intubation. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nPatients may have an initially mild presentation, such as cough with oral intake, or more serious symptoms, including recurrent pneumonia or even mediastinitis. A high index of suspicion should be maintained to enable prompt identification and reduce the risk of aspiration of gastric secretions into the lungs. Oral contrast radiologic studies are usually the first diagnostic tool employed but may fail to visualize very small fistulas. Similarly, mucosal folding within the conduit may obscure small openings on endoscopy. Bronchoscopic evaluation should be pursued at the same time as endoscopic assessment; however, bronchoscopy may fail to demonstrate conduit-lung parenchymal fistulas.\n\nThe management of fistulas should be based upon the size and site of the fistula in addition to the severity of the symptoms. In patients with a benign clinical presentation, attempts at conservative treatment (nothing by mouth, antibiotics, jejunal feeding) may be considered; however, failure to heal within 4 to 6 weeks should prompt further intervention. Endoscopic approaches have been described including attempts at closure using fibrin glue, hemostatic clips, and mesh plugs. Stent placement may be considered as a temporizing measure in severe cases to control contamination. Ultimately, a surgical repair may be required. The preferred approach is to repair the anastomosis and close the airway defect with interposition of vascularized soft tissue between the suture lines to prevent recurrent fistulization. Repair may involve resection of the involved component of the conduit with re-anastomosis or in more severe cases, resection of the intrathoracic conduit with esophagostomy diversion and delayed reconstruction after the patient is clinically stabilized from sepsis. Our preferred approach to reconstruction is with colonic interposition in the substernal space to avoid reoperation in the area of inflammation. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n## Summary\n\nAnastomotic complications after esophagectomy can be rapidly life-threatening or have a chronic protracted course causing significant morbidity. Awareness of the type of complications that can occur and the associated clinical presentations is critical for early recognition and management ( Fig. 36.2 ).\n\nA flowchart outlines the management of anastomotic leaks, divided by cervical and intrathoracic locations. The flowchart presents the management of an anastomotic leak. It is categorized into two main areas cervical and intrathoracic. The cervical category is divided into two subgroups labeled occult and clinical symptoms. For occult leaks, the recommended management includes antibiotics and oral hygiene, with a follow-up contrast esophagram after 7 days. Treatment involves antibiotics, open cervical wounds, drain placement, nasogastric tube decompression, and nutritional support for clinical symptoms. The intrathoracic category branches into three distinct groups. They are stapled line defects, which contain dehiscence with gastric tip necrosis, which is stable, and sepsis, which is stable. The approach includes antibiotics, a stent, and optional chest tube drainage for staple line defects. The treatment for dehiscence and gastric tip necrosis in a stable patient involves antibiotics, a stent, EndoVac, and chest tube drainage. In cases of sepsis and instability, the management is antibiotics and possible surgery for washout and diversion with esophagostomy.\n\nFig. 36.2\n\n## References\n\n1.: Low D.E., et al.: Benchmarking complications associated with esophagectomy . Ann Surg 2019; 269 (2): pp. 291-298.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Messager M., et al.: Recent improvements in the management of esophageal anastomotic leak after surgery for cancer . Eur J Surg Oncol 2017; 43: pp. 258-269.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: Markar S., et al.: The impact of severe anastomotic leak on long-term survival and cancer recurrence after surgical resection for esophageal malignancy . Ann Surg 2015; 262 (6): pp. 972-980.\n\nView In Article\n\n4.: Cassivi S.D.: Leaks, strictures, and necrosis: a review of anastomotic complications fo