habilitation, Enhanced Recovery, and Rehabilitation]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "36. Anastomotic Complications After Esophagectomy - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Anastomotic Complications After Esophagectomy', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Anastomotic Complications After Esophagectomy', 'Patient Factors', 'Nutrition', 'Medical Comorbidities', 'Neoadjuvant Therapy', 'Technical Factors', 'Anastomotic Complications After Esophagectomy / Patient Factors', 'Anastomotic Complications After Esophagectomy / Nutrition', 'Anastomotic Complications After Esophagectomy / Medical Comorbidities'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '36', '384-391', 2, 38, FALSE, TRUE),
('Survivorship Pathways in Esophagectomy:: Prehabilitation, Enhanced Recovery, and Rehabilitation', 'shackelford-9th-ed-37-survivorship-pathways-in-esophagectomy-prehabilitation-enhanced-recovery-and-r', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Survivorship Pathways in Esophagectomy: : Prehabilitation, Enhanced Recovery, and Rehabilitation\n\nJakub Chmelo; Pooja Prasad; Alexander W. Phillips\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 37, 392-404\n\nThe majority of patients diagnosed with potentially curable esophageal cancer will present with locally advanced disease. As such, the optimum treatment is likely to involve neoadjuvant modalities (either chemotherapy or chemoradiotherapy) followed by surgery. These patients may present in a deconditioned state, with cachexia secondary to dysphagic symptoms or due to underlying comorbidities. Neoadjuvant treatment has the potential to further decondition these patients and increase the risks of an already highly morbid procedure.\n\nHowever, morbidity and mortality associated with surgery has fallen dramatically since the 1990s, and current multimodal regimes are leading to ever-improving 5-year survival rates. This has led to an increased focus on interventions that can improve outcomes as well as lead to better long-term quality of life.\n\nEnhanced recovery programs (ERPs), often referred to as enhanced recovery after surgery (ERAS) but really encompassing perioperative care, involve a package of care instilled into the routine care pathways of patients undergoing esophagectomy. These programs have demonstrated to dramatically improve outcomes, and a natural evolution has led to increased interest in prehabilitation and more recently rehabilitation. Patients undergoing esophagectomy are an ideal group for prehabilitation, which seeks to assuage the deleterious impact of neoadjuvant treatment and even improve fitness. Equally, rehabilitation programs are a natural extension of ERPs and should help patients pass through their recovery phase as quickly as possible with quality of life as the focus as part of a survivorship pathway ( Fig. 37.1 ).\n\nA flowchart details a comprehensive approach to prehabilitation, treatment, and survivorship for patients, with some focus on fitness, nutrition, and psychological support. The flowchart illustrates a structured pathway for patient care and divides the process into four key stages. Diagnosis, Prehabilitation, Enhanced Recovery After Surgery, Rehabilitation, and Survivorship are the stages. The diagnosis involves fitness assessment through tests like cardiopulmonary exercise testing, 6-6-minute walk test 6-minute walk test, hand-grip strength, early nutritional assessments, and psychological evaluations for cognitive support. Prehabilitation emphasizes fitness with aerobic exercises, strength evaluation, and dietary plans, which may include feeding adjuncts and supplements. Psychological support is also provided through preoperative information and engagement with support networks. Treatment Enhanced Recovery After Surgery focuses on early mobilization with daily targets and regular physiotherapy input, progressive oral intake, tube feeding if needed, and nutritional supplementation. Psychological input and multidisciplinary support are also essential during this phase. Rehabilitation includes walking, medium-high intensity exercises, and resistance training, with feeding adjuncts and weight management. Psychological support continues with engagement in support networks.\n\nFig. 37.1\n\n## Prehabilitation\n\nSurgical prehabilitation involves a group of interventions with an aim of improving the patient\u2019s readiness and functional capacity prior to a surgical stressor\u2014esophagectomy. There has been increasing interest in this relatively new concept due to promising benefits for patients and consequential economic advantages. Studies demonstrating a relationship between preoperative cardiorespiratory fitness and postoperative outcomes including length of stay, morbidity, and mortality have led to postulation that improvement of the former might lead to improvement in the latter. Prehabilitation has been initially viewed as a unimodal entity focusing on the preoperative training of patients to improve their cardiorespiratory fitness similar to training of professional athletes prior to competitions. However, it has been recognized that there are multiple additional modifiable preoperative risk factors. Presently, prehabilitation tends to use a multimodal approach to address the various needs of surgical patients. These modalities usually involve physical training (aerobic and strengthening exercises), nutritional support, psychological interventions, and optimization of medical comorbidities.\n\n### Evidence for Prehabilitation\n\nThere is solid evidence to suggest that prehabilitation leads to improvement of cardiorespiratory fitness. Systematic reviews are limited in their usefulness due to significant heterogeneity between prehabilitation programs. These programs differ in their length of intervention, type of interventions, intensity, and level of supervision. Minnella et al. performed a randomized controlled trial (RCT) analyzing 51 patients undergoing esophagogastric surgery and demonstrated that patients who received a home-based prehabilitation intervention improved their functional capacity compared with patients without this intervention. The majority of patients underwent neoadjuvant therapy and there were 39 patients who underwent esophagectomy. Similar results were showed by Xu et al. in an RCT of 59 patients who received neoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy for predominantly esophageal squamous cell cancer. Barberan-Garcia et al. conducted a multimodal prehabilitation RCT on high-risk patients undergoing abdominal surgery. This study indicated that their mostly home-based program led to a reduction of postoperative complications by 51% in comparison with the control group. However, only 13 patients included underwent esophagectomy. The evidence for prehabilitation is still in its infancy particularly in the field of esophageal surgery. Prehabilitation for those undergoing abdominal surgery is encouraging; however, there is a need for more robust trials to demonstrate the effect of prehabilitation prior to esophagectomy on postoperative outcomes. These should help inform which are the important components of a prehabilitation program and how these should be delivered.\n\n### Prehabilitation for Esophagectomy\n\nMorbidity of esophagectomy remains high despite the advances that have been made since the 1990s. The operation brings significant physiological stress to the patient; however, these patients are commonly deconditioned when they are diagnosed with their disease. This can be a consequence of risk factors associated with cancer such as obesity or smoking. Weight loss is a common presenting symptom whether this is related to cancer itself or associated dysphagia. Loss of muscle mass and function, defined as sarcopenia or sarcopenic obesity, when associated with high body mass index, is frequent among patients with esophageal cancer. Furthermore, patients with locally advanced disease benefit from multimodal treatment consisting of neoadjuvant regimens, and although these extend survival in general, they tend to lead to deconditioning prior to surgery. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Fitness does not normally return to pre-chemotherapy levels even if there is time left to recover in the window between finishing neoadjuvant treatment and surgery. All these factors make the patient undergoing esophagectomy high risk and challenging to manage. The aim of prehabilitation is to reduce this risk.\n\nIt is recognized that a new diagnosis of cancer represents an important teachable moment when adverse lifestyle habits can be changed successfully. Motivation of patients to play an active role in this change is usually high during this time period. Prehabilitation should be started as soon as possible when the diagnosis of cancer is made and should continue until surgery. Neoadjuvant therapies also act as a natural window where the aim is to negate the deleterious effect of treatment on fitness but also to reinforce new habits. It has been proven that a positive effect of training can be seen within 3 weeks of its commencement.\n\n### Physical Training\n\nPhysical training remains the cornerstone of prehabilitation. This usually involves aerobic exercise complemented with strengthening exercises. Aerobic or endurance training improves cardiorespiratory reserve through multiple physiological adaptations. Training should be individualized, and intensity, frequency, length, type, volume, and progression of exercise have to be considered. It is also important to include the patient\u2019s own wishes when discussing prehabilitation with them. The impact of exercise is known to be \u201cdose related,\u201d indicating that the more patients do, the higher the fitness level that can be achieved. Additionally, there is clear evidence that some exercise is better than no exercise. Intensity of the exercise remains an area of great interest. Intensity can be monitored subjectively using the Borg scale of perceived exertion or objectively as a percentage of maximal aerobic capacity or maximal heart rate. Moreover, it has been shown that high-intensity interval training leads to the greatest adaptations. However, intensities above 91% of maximal aerobic capacity or above 96% of maximal heart rate are very demanding and are tolerated by few patients. Progression of a training prescription is important to reach desirable improvements of fitness as adaptations to the prescribed volume of exercise occur continuously. Frequently used aerobic exercises include walking, running, cycling, or swimming; however, only very fit patients will be able to run. Walking is an easily included task that introduces at least a moderate intensity of exercise. Strengthening exercises are another element which aim to improve muscle mass and function of the majority muscle groups within the body and therefore aim to negate sarcopenia. Weightlifting, exercise with one\u2019s own body weight, or with elastic bands and ropes can also be used. Progress and changes in physical fitness can be monitored using cardiopulmonary exercise testing (CPET) or specialized tests such as the 6-minute walk test. CPET has the advantage of being used for risk stratification, identification of unknown comorbidities, and decision making in a multidisciplinary manner. Muscle mass and muscle function changes can be tracked using anthropometric data, dynamic tests like handgrip strength test, or by radiological imaging.\n\nCurrently it remains unclear which components of a prehabilitation program are the most important and what the ideal program should look like. However, it is likely that regular exercise should form the basis of any program. It should be acknowledged that chemotherapy and/or radiotherapy are demanding treatments which are not always well tolerated. During these periods, compliance of patients with exercise may reduce and it is important to support and positively motivate patients.\n\nPhysical training can be conducted in hospital, at home with remote supervision, or in combination. In-hospital training can utilize treadmills, stationary bikes, and other equipment. This training has the advantage of direct supervision. Equally, it can be more costly than a home-based exercise program. The easy availability of wearable devices permits remote monitoring. These devices can measure daily step counts, heart rate, as well as the period and intensity of exercise. Additionally, mobile or internet-based applications have been developed which aid with monitoring, advice, and prescription of exercise.\n\n### Nutritional Optimization\n\nPatients undergoing esophagectomy may be malnourished or are at risk of malnutrition as a result of the malignancy, an associated systemic inflammatory response, and symptoms like dysphagia. The prevalence of sarcopenia is high among this group of patients. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> This is a result of catabolism due to their cancer and chemotherapy treatment. Both malnutrition and sarcopenia lead to the loss of physical functioning and are associated with adverse outcomes after esophagectomy. Nutritional screening and nutritional assessment should therefore be part of routine care for patients undergoing esophagectomy. Several tools to screen for malnutrition exist, such as the Subjective Global Assessment, Nutrition Risk Score, and Malnutrition Screening Tool. Nutritional prehabilitation should include every patient, not only those who are diagnosed with malnutrition, as there is a need to meet the increased nutritional demand of surgery. Dietetic advice consists of advice about food, protein, and energy intake and supplementation. Patients with esophageal cancer will have higher energy demands due to the catabolic state caused by the cancer. However, it is important to consider that prehabilitation, which includes increased levels of exercise, may increase these demands. Establishing if any barriers to nutritional intake exist is important. Food logbooks can be a useful tool for both patients and dietitians to monitor the impact of any intervention. Some patients may need enteral or parenteral feeding adjuncts established, and this should be individualized. Enteral feeding is always preferable to a parenteral option. Consideration for the potential to develop adverse reactions such as nausea, vomiting, anorexia, bloating, constipation, diarrhea, and pain with neoadjuvant treatment should be made as they can have a detrimental impact on the nutritional status of the patient.\n\n### Other Prehabilitation Components\n\nPrior to esophagectomy, patients may experience low mood and emotional distress which negatively impacts on their quality of life, general ability to function, and outcomes after surgery. It is recognized that psychological interventions should be part of a prehabilitation program as psychological wellbeing of patients is closely related to their motivation during treatment and also closely interconnected with physical functioning. Interventions usually involve meetings with a psychologist and support throughout the program.\n\nIn a wider context, correction of medical comorbidities should also be included amongst prehabilitation interventions. This can include optimization of anemia which is common in malignancy and optimization of diabetes. Smoking cessation and support for those with high alcohol intakes are imperative during the preoperative period.\n\n## Enhanced Recovery\n\nThe idea of an ERP was first described by Kehlet in 1995 for patients who underwent colonic surgery. Since then, the components that are included within an ERP have gradually evolved and have been adopted by a wide variety of different surgical specialties for a wide array of procedures. The term ERAS is frequently employed and can be taken to include not just patient management in the postoperative period but also standardization of care preoperatively and intraoperatively.\n\nThe usage within esophageal surgery has become widespread and is now generally recognized as making up the standard of care for patients undergoing esophagectomy for cancer ( Table 37.1 ). This is a group of patients that undergo high-risk complex surgery and an ERP has strong evidence behind it for improving patient outcomes and significantly reducing the length of hospital stay for patients.\n\nTable 37.1\n\nExample of Enhanced Recovery After Surgery for Esophagectomy Program\n\nReproduced with permission of the Northern Oesophagogastric Unit, UK.\n\n<table><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\"></th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\" colspan=\"6\">Post-Operative Day (POD)</th></tr><tr><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\"></th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">POD 0Date:__________</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">POD 1Date: __________</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">POD 2Date:__________</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">POD 3Date: __________</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">POD 4Date: __________</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">POD 5\u2014DischargeDate: __________</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align=\"\"><b>Medications</b></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>IV omeprazole at 20:00</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Tinzaparin as per VTE prophylaxis</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Compression stockings</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>IV omeprazole at 06:00</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Identify and give essential medication via jejunostomy tube (continue to suspend</p><p>__________ACE inhibitors)</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Tinzaparin at 18:00</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Compression stockings</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>IV omeprazole at 06:00</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Give essential medication via jejunostomy tube <i>(be cautious with ACE inhibitors)</i></p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Tinzaparin at 18:00</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Compression stockings</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>15 mg senna via jejunostomy tube at 22:00</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>IV omeprazole at 06:00</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Give essential medication via jejunostomy tube</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Tinzaparin at 18:00</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Compression stockings</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>15mg senna via jejunostomy tube at 22:00</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Sodium docusate 200 mg BD via jejunostomy tube</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Orodispersible lansoprazole 30 mg OD</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Give essential medication via jejunostomy tube</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Tinzaparin at 18:00</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Compression stockings</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>15 mg senna via jejunostomy tube</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Sodium docusate 200 mg BD via jejunostomy tube</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>x1 sachet of movicol TDS via jejunostomy tube</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Glycerine suppository</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Orodispersible lansoprazole 30 mg OD</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Give essential medication via jejunostomy tube</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Tinzaparin at 18:00</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Compression stockings</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Laxatives via jejunostomy tube as POD 4 and continue as required</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Enema if bowels still not opened POD 5</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Review medication that remains suspended on e-record</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\"><b>Pain Control</b></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Regular IV paracetamol</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Multi-modal/PCA observations as per trust policy</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Pain controlled to enable deep breathing and coughing</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Regular IV paracetamol</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Multi-modal/PCA observations as per trust policy</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Pain controlled to enable deep breathing, coughing, and mobilizing</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Regular IV paracetamol</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Multi-modal/PCA observations as per trust policy</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Pain controlled to enable deep breathing, coughing, and mobilizing</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Regular IV paracetamol</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Remove rectus sheath catheter</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>PR diclofenac 50 mg TDS (check renal function and history)</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Pain controlled to enable deep breathing, coughing, and mobilizing</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Regular paracetamol via jejunostomy tube</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Paravertebral block/PCA to be removed</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>PR diclofenac 50 mg TDS (check renal function)</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Oramorph PRN via jejunostomy tube</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Regular paracetamol via jejunostomy tube</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>PR diclofenac 50 mg TDS (check renal function)</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Oramorph PRN via jejunostomy tube</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\"><b>Fluid Management</b></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Intravenous therapy: 1 mL/kg/hr (max 80 mL/hr)</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Fluid balance completed hourly</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Oral fluids: 25 mL/hr of water</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Intravenous therapy: 1 mL/kg/hr (max 80 mL/hr)</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Fluid balance completed hourly</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Oral fluids: 25 mL/hr of water</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Intravenous therapy: + jej feed + oral intake = patients weight (max 80 mL/hr)</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Fluid balance completed 2 hourly</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Oral fluids: 25 mL/hr of water</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Remove central line if not needed</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Intravenous therapy + jej feed + oral intake = patients weight</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Fluid balance completed 2 hourly</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Oral fluids: 50 mL/hr of water</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Remove urinary catheter</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Stop intravenous therapy if consultant agrees</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>50 mL/hr and up to 3 half-cup servings</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Free fluids (FF) POD 5</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\"><b>Physiotherapy</b></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Head of bed &gt;45 degrees at all times</p><p>_________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Encourage active cycle of breathing with support cough</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Encourage circulatory exercises</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Head of bed &gt;45 degrees at all times</p><p>_________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Sit out in chair</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Walk 50\u2013100 ft on ITU/HDU</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Safe transfer to ITU/HDU</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Ambulate 2 times</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Breathing and circulatory exercised as POD 0</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Head of bed &gt;45 degrees at all times</p><p>_________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Ambulate 3 times, mobilize for functional tasks</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Breathing and circulatory exercised as POD 0</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Head of bed &gt;45 degrees</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Up in chair 80% of the day</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Ambulate 4 times, mobilize for functional tasks and encourage to mobilize independently</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Breathing exercises</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Head of bed &gt;45 degrees</p><p>_________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Up in chair 80% of the day</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Ambulate 4 times, mobilize for functional tasks and encourage to mobilize independently</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Breathing exercises</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>As POD 4</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Physio to assess shoulder range of movement</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\"><b>Nutrition</b></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Start 25 mL/hr of water via jejunostomy tube from 22:00</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Please see jejunostomy feeding per local protocol on document viewing under dietetic entry</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Please see jejunostomy feeding per local protocol on document viewing under dietetic entry</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Please see jejunostomy feeding per local protocol on document viewing under dietetic entry</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Please see jejunostomy feeding per local protocol on document viewing under dietetic entry</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Commence jejunostomy education and give information leaflets</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Please see jejunostomy feeding per local protocol on document viewing under dietetic entry</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Liquid diet POD 6 if surgeons agree (will continue liquid diet on discharge)</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td align=\"\"><b>Drains and Tubes</b></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Aspirate nasogastric tube (NG) every 2 hours and leave on free drainage (FD)</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Record chest drain output at midnight and change all bottles</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Aspirate NG every 2 hours and remain on FD</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Record chest drain output at midnight and change all bottles</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Aspirate NG every 4 hours and remain on FD</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Record chest drain output at midnight</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Aspirate NG every 4 hours and remain on FD</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Remove basal chest drain if output &lt;250 mL/24 hr</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Record chest drain output at midnight</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Remove NG if aspirates &lt;200 mL/24 hr</p><p>__________</p></li><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Record chest drain output at midnight</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td><td align=\"\"><ul><li><span>\u2022</span><p>Remove apical chest drain once oral free fluids established</p><p>__________</p></li></ul></td></tr></tbody></table>\n\n*ACE,* Angiotensin-converting-enzyme; *ITU/HDU,* intensive therapy unit/high dependency unit; *PCA,* patient-controlled analgesia; *VTE,* venous thromboembolism.\n\nMany of the enhanced recovery protocols that are currently used are based upon evidence in the medical literature; however, it has frequently been impossible to define any individual factor that significantly leads to an improvement in outcomes. It is likely, that like prehabilitation, a multidisciplinary team approach with standardized care and targets for patients contributes towards the huge impact that enhanced recovery protocols have.\n\nThe enhanced recovery team usually comprises the surgeon, specialist nurses, physiotherapists, and dietitians, and members of the anesthetic team working together to provide achievable and practical targets. It is also important that they continue to evaluate the program employed to ensure compliance and understand why deviations from the pathway occur.\n\n### Preoperative Management\n\nThere is undoubtedly some overlap with prehabilitation and ERAS, with the latter being a natural progression for patients that hopefully have already engaged in their treatment and are keen to help optimize their own outcome.\n\nThe use of multidisciplinary/tumor board meetings is now universal and contributes toward patient staging and identification of treatment options. These boards should also take into account the holistic needs of the patient and evaluate areas where care can be optimized.\n\nPreoperatively, enhanced recovery pathways should look at addressing modifiable factors. These include smoking and alcohol intake, but also address anemia, nutritional status if not already done as part of prehabilitation, and serve to provide important patient education regarding what to expect after surgery.\n\n#### Preoperative Fasting and CHO/Nutrition\n\nMalnutrition is a common feature among patients diagnosed with esophageal cancer, and it is important to be mindful that even patients who are clinically obese may also by malnourished. Dysphagia is a common presenting symptom and may lead to patients not being able to obtain sufficient calories due to local tumor affects causing obstruction as anorexia and cancer cachexia. It may also occur in patients who receive neoadjuvant radiotherapy which can cause localized inflammation and worsen symptoms. Malnutrition is known to have a negative impact on outcome and can lead to increased morbidity and impact on quality of life. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nPatients should therefore have their nutritional status assessed at the time of diagnosis, and clinicians should be mindful that this may also change during the course of neoadjuvant treatment, which is frequently employed for those presenting with locally advanced disease. Ideally assessment should include anthropometric measurements, as well as a history of current nutritional intake and any history of weight loss. The European Society for Clinical Nutrition and Metabolism (ESPEN) have produced guidelines to aid identification of patients who are at high risk for morbidity due to malnutrition. Additionally, their recommendation is for enteral nutrition rather than parenteral nutrition.\n\nFor those patients who are identified as malnourished, or at risk of malnutrition, with weight loss of >10%, severe dysphagia, or a BMI <19 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> , consideration should be made to use a feeding adjunct such as a feeding jejunostomy or nasoenteric feeding tube. This will ensure sufficient nutritional support prior to surgery, often through the period of neoadjuvant treatment. For patients who are identified as being in a lower-risk group (<10% weight loss), it may be possible to address any nutritional concerns with simple dietary advice and oral supplementation with protein and energy drinks.\n\nEsophageal stents have been used by some to improve oral nutrition prior to surgery. While there is a paucity of data, a review by Huddy et al. demonstrated mixed results with regard to weight change and nearly a third of patients experiencing stent migration. Additionally, significant complications such as fistula formation to the airway, stent erosion, esophageal perforation, and stent failure were seen in up to 5% of patients. However, there is little reported on whether stents impact on the subsequent surgery.\n\n#### Preoperative Considerations\n\nThe use of antithrombotic prophylaxis usually in the form of low-molecular-weight heparin is recommended preoperatively; however, it should not be administered less than 12 hours before the start of surgery where central axial neuroblockade (spinal or epidural) are planned as part of the anesthetic.\n\nAntibiotic prophylaxis is used routinely at induction and is shown to reduce the rate of surgical site infection. For prolonged surgery, a further intraoperative dose may be required but there is no evidence for continuing antibiotics postoperatively as a prophylactic measure.\n\n### Intraoperative Management\n\n#### Surgical Considerations\n\nHistorically esophagectomy has been carried out using open surgery with its associated morbidity. The Ivor Lewis esophagectomy involves a laparotomy and thoracotomy; additionally some surgeons prefer a neck anastomosis as part of a three-stage operation, as routine practice or tailored to the tumor location. However, there is increasing use of minimally invasive approaches, either in combination, with part of the operation being done open (hybrid) or alternatively wholly minimally invasive. Minimally invasive approaches are increasingly aided by robotic technology.\n\nThere have been several meta-analyses evaluating the benefit of these less invasive approaches on patient outcome. These have suggested that while a minimally invasive approach is likely to be associated with a longer operative time, there is likely to be oncological parity when judged by lymph node yield. However, importantly these studies suggest there may be lower intraoperative blood loss, reduced overall morbidity, fewer pulmonary complications, and shorter hospital stay. The TIME study sought to compare minimally invasive approaches with a traditional open operation. While it showed comparable oncological outcomes, it sought to also evaluate the impact on pulmonary complications. Minimally invasive surgery was associated with significantly fewer pulmonary complications, but it is worth noting that this study demonstrated nearly double the anastomotic leak rate in the minimally invasive group although the study was not powered to demonstrate significant difference in this area. The MIRO RCT compared hybrid esophagectomy with open surgery. This study showed no difference in median length of stay and no difference in major complications (Clavien\u2013Dindo III+). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nThus, although it would be logical to assume that a minimally invasive approach would reduce the overall surgical stress response, the absolute benefit of these approaches remains unclear and it is likely that much of the other components of ERAS programs lead to the significant benefit with regard to shortened length of stay and fewer complications.\n\n#### Anesthetic Approach\n\nAlthough the anesthetic agent used has not been shown to influence outcomes in patients undergoing esophagectomy, the use of short- or intermediate-acting neuromuscular blockers may aid postoperative extubation, with the vast majority of patients being planned for extubation immediately after surgery. There is some evidence that volatile anesthetics may reduce ischemia-reperfusion injury.\n\nDuring two-lung ventilation, there is evidence for employing lung-protective principles using more physiological tidal volumes (7 mL/kg) and trying to avoid high inspiratory plateau pressures with little need for positive end-expiratory pressure (PEEP) or lung recruitment. However, one-lung ventilation may be challenging. Both shunting of blood and hypoxic vasoconstriction can lead to ischemia and subsequent reperfusion injury. This may be aided by using tidal volumes of 5 mL/kg and 5 cmH <sub>2 </sub> O of PEEP when compared with a non-protective strategy with higher than normal (e.g., 9 mL/kg) tidal volumes.\n\nAdditionally, during one-lung ventilation, oxygen saturations of >92% should be sought reducing the inspired oxygen concentration (FIO <sub>2 </sub> ) as low as possible to still permit this. Ideally one-lung ventilation should be kept as short as possible.\n\nGoal-directed fluid therapy has also been recognized as an important component for patients undergoing esophagectomy. This involves administering fluid to optimize cardiac output and has been reported to enhance gastrointestinal function and mobilization and may lead to fewer complications and shorter hospital stay.\n\n### Postoperative Management\n\n#### Nutrition\n\nWhile it is important to ensure that nutritional status is assessed early in the patient pathway of treatment as patients with esophageal cancer can frequently have nutritional deficiency, it is equally important that consideration is given to nutritional support after surgery.\n\nIt is well established that after esophagectomy, patients experience changes in their nutritional status signified by a reduction in postoperative weight over time. This tends to continue for up to 6 months following surgery and generally plateaus between 6 and 12 months following surgery. The majority of patients will have lost >10% of their body weight at this point and most patients do not return to their premorbid weight.\n\nThere is a large global variation on postoperative nutrition practice with regard to both the route of administering nutrition and the use of any supplements. Administration may vary from early oral intake, the using of feeding adjuncts such as a feeding jejunostomy or nasojejunal tube, to the routine use of total parental nutrition (TPN) after surgery.\n\nGiven the high incidence of malnutrition at 1 year post surgery, it might be supposed that routine use of an adjunct in the postoperative period, and even continued after discharge for a period of time, might mitigate against this weight loss, and consequently improve patient\u2019s quality of life.\n\n#### Jejunostomy\n\nFeeding jejunostomy is the most common adjunct used to provide postoperative nutrition. It has the advantage of ensuring patients can receive nutrition soon after surgery, with the benefit of supplying this enterally compared with TPN. Enteral nutrition has been shown to reduce infection complications, and is associated with a shorter hospital stay than TPN. Additionally, it is less costly, may improve tissue healing, and improve gut motility, reducing prolong ileus.\n\nFurther, it can be used for a prolonged period of feeding including after discharge from hospital and through any adjuvant treatment that might be administered. It also allows patients who suffer an anastomotic leak the opportunity to receive enteral feeding without prolonged placement of a nasojejunal tube.\n\nAlthough a small number of patients may have a jejunostomy placed prior to starting neoadjuvant treatment if they are struggling to obtain sufficient nutrition orally, the majority are placed at the time of esophagectomy. A nationwide study in The Netherlands indicated that >80% of patients had a jejunostomy placed at the time of surgery and this was associated with a shorter length of hospital stay, with a US study indicating that only 45% of patients had a jejunostomy placed again showing a significantly shorter length of stay and reduced mortality in this group.\n\nFeeding jejunostomy has been shown to reduce the incidence of sarcopenia which occurs after esophagectomy. However, a US study suggested that the routine use of feeding jejunostomy is not required after surgery in cohorts with low anastomotic leak rates. In this study, where the leak rates were reported at <5%, BMI reduction was comparable at 2 weeks and 3\u20136 months between patients who had a jejunostomy placed and those who did not. However, while patients with a jejunostomy used them to supplement intake after discharge, they did not explicitly have a standardized regimen.\n\nNotably, placement of jejunostomy is not without risk, including superficial skin infection, tube blockage, small bowel obstruction, and small bowel ischemia and necrosis. Weijs et al. reviewed the use of jejunostomy across studies including over 3000 patients. The associated complications were documented at 13%\u201338%. However, relaparotomy was required for <3% of patients.\n\nA further systematic review and meta-analysis evaluating the routine use of jejunostomy and including 12 studies found that feeding jejunostomy may lead to reduced 30-day mortality but had no impact on overall complications and that jejunostomy should be considered in patients undergoing esophagectomy.\n\nJejunostomy appears to confer some benefits but with potential risk, and several of these studies conclude that judicious use is merited although it can be difficult to predict which patients will suffer complications that would benefit from having the potential for jejunal feeding.\n\n#### Nasojejunal Tubes\n\nNasojejunal tubes confer some of the same advantages that feeding jejunostomies do. They permit enteral feeding soon after surgery and can be used for a prolonged period in the case of anastomotic leak. They also have fewer complications than a surgical jejunostomy tube. However, their main disadvantage relates to patient comfort. For those patients who have a complication that requires prolonged non-oral feeding, there is both the physical and psychological impact of a having a long-term tube supplying nutrition naso-enterically.\n\nAdditionally, nasojejunal tubes may be accidentally displaced and can obstruct. Replacement of these tubes or exchange may lead to surgical morbidity, and in these instances some surgeons would prefer to implement TPN feeding if required.\n\nWang et al. carried out a meta-analysis of the use of feeding jejunostomy versus nasojejunal tubes across major upper gastrointestinal surgery and found that length of hospital stay and duration of nutritional support was lower in the patients with nasojejunal tubes compared with jejunostomy with the advantage that no patient required reoperation in the nasojejunal group. However, this is confounded by the heterogeneity of patients included and procedures performed and takes no account of patient discomfort in the nasopharynx and oropharynx as well as any psychological component that patients may experience.\n\n#### Early Oral Nutrition\n\nThe concerns regarding early oral intake after esophagectomy relate to the high anastomosis and high complication rate associated with this procedure. Historically, these patients are slowly progressed with regard to oral intake in the postoperative phase because of concerns regarding exacerbation or causation of complications. These include the risk of anastomotic leak and subsequent mediastinal sepsis, prolonged ileus, and delayed gastric emptying, which may lead to aspiration.\n\nA systematic review by Mei et al. in 2022 sought to determine whether early oral intake was feasible. This study demonstrated that there was no difference in anastomotic leak rates between those who received early oral intake and those who received \u201ctraditional\u201d oral intake. It also demonstrated significantly fewer pulmonary complications in the early oral intake group. However, there was no difference between groups in overall frequency of complications, although there was a shorter length of stay as well as shorter times to passing flatus and first defecation after surgery in the early oral intake group. The authors defined oral intake as within 5 days of surgery but did not clearly state what constituted \u201coral intake.\u201d\n\nThe NUTRIENT II trial compared early oral intake with traditional oral intake in a cohort of patients undergoing minimally invasive esophagectomy. This included 132 patients randomized between groups and showed that there was no significant difference in anastomotic leak rates and pneumonia. In this study, patients had a stepwise increase in volume of oral intake from 250 mL on day 0 to 1500 mL on day 5 which included soup, water, nutritional drinks, and pureed food. The control arm received early nutrition via a feeding jejunostomy.\n\nThus, the evidence for early oral intake remains equivocal, but enteral nutrition is an important component of ERP.\n\n#### Total Parenteral Nutrition\n\nCurrent evidence suggests that enteral feeding is preferable for patients after esophagectomy and is advocated as such in the Guidelines for Perioperative Care in Esophagectomy. Enteral nutrition is generally regarded as less expensive, associated with fewer complications, and helps maintain the immunological and barrier function of the intestines.\n\nHowever, TPN can be a valuable tool in those patients in whom enteral feeding has failed (loss of access accompanied by anastomotic leak) and in the treatment of persistent chyle leak.\n\n#### Pharmaconutrition and Supplements\n\nA wide variety of supplements have been trialed to determine whether they can improve patient outcomes. However, much of the evidence in this area is limited and the Guidelines for Perioperative Care in Esophagectomy does not support routine use. Provision of nutrients such as arginine, omega-3 unsaturated fatty acids, and nucleotides have all been given with the aim of increasing the immune response and dampening the inflammatory response. The aim is to ameliorate the oxidative stress response after surgery which can lead to organ damage.\n\nTwo systematic reviews have sought to establish the impact of immunonutrition on outcomes. Zhang et al. concluded that immunonutrition is safe and leads to a decrease in both infection- and non-infection-related complications. This study included 19 RCTs and 2331 patients. Mabvuure et al. evaluated enteral immunonutrition versus standard immunonutrition including six studies with a total of 528 patients. However, the limited number of studies included, the heterogeneity of operations performed, and interventions used made it difficult to establish if there was any benefit. Thus, further work is warranted in this area to establish which, if any, supplements are beneficial and the optimal timing of administration.\n\n#### Analgesia\n\nAdequate analgesia is an essential component for patients and a core feature for ERP protocols. Ensuring that a patient is comfortable ensures reduced postoperative morbidity. Patients are better able to mobilize, breathe, cough, and clear secretions, reducing pulmonary complications which are associated with restricted thoracic wall movement and the risk of thromboembolic events in less mobile patients. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Additionally, early postoperative pain due to thoracotomy is associated with an increased incidence of long-term pain.\n\nHistorically, patients have received thoracic epidural as the mainstay for providing analgesia. This is a reliable tool which allows patient mobilization after surgery. However, thoracic epidural may lead to postural hypotension due to thoracolumbar sympathetic nerve disruption of motor blockade of the legs. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Although epidural is regarded as a safe technique, there are rare incidences of long-term neurological complications due to vertebral canal hematoma or abscesses. Some series have also reported a failure rate of approximately 20% which may be due to technical problems in placing the epidural or misplacement of the catheter.\n\nMore recently, multimodal analgesia has been used which comprises intrathecal opioids at induction, local anesthetic infusion to the wounds, and patient-controlled analgesia. These have the ability, in combination, to provide adequate pain control with a reduced risk of hypotensive episodes, thereby lowering the need for pressor support post surgery and permitting mobilization after surgery. This technique can be employed in patients having open thoracic and abdominal phases, as well as those procedures performed using minimally invasive techniques.\n\nThis multimodal analgesia should be accompanied by regular administration of acetaminophen and the use of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs in those patients without renal failure and has been shown to provide comparable postoperative analgesia with thoracic epidural, lowering the need for pressor use and frequency of hypotensive episodes.\n\n#### Mobilization\n\nEarly mobilization forms a key component of enhanced recovery pathways with patients ideally mobilized on the day of surgery. There should be progressive incremental targets which are supervised by physiotherapists and other allied healthcare professionals. While a prolonged intubation post-surgery, as well as hypotension and complications such as delirium may preclude mobilization, patients should be encouraged to take ownership of their own rehabilitation and a structured pathway with daily targets explained.\n\nSchuring et al. evaluated the mobilization practices after esophagectomy within a tertiary center in The Netherlands. An initial postoperative day 1 target of 100 m was set with a final target of 100 m unaided. The median time to reaching this target was day 2 with 45% of patients managing 100 m on day 1. Hemodynamic instability, nausea, pain, and dizziness were among the reasons for the delay in achieving these targets.\n\nThere are few data on the targets that should be set postoperatively, but walking progressive distances with teaching of breathing techniques and chest physiotherapy are all likely to contribute towards improved patient outcomes.\n\n#### Other Postoperative Considerations\n\nLow-molecular-weight heparin should be routinely used to reduce thromboembolic events. An initial dose is usually given the evening before surgery and not usually within 12 hours of spinal administration. A prophylactic dose is then continued in the postoperative period and consideration should be given for continuing this for 28 days after surgery.\n\nMost patients undergoing esophagectomy will have placement of urinary catheters, nasogastric drainage tubes, and chest drains. Routine placement of abdominal drains is rarely used. There should be an agreed protocol for removal of these tubes with some surgeons advocating swift removal of nasogastric tubes, or not placing them at all.\n\nNasogastric tubes are routinely placed to allow gastric conduit decompression reducing the chance of early post-surgery aspiration and irritation of the anastomosis and risk of leak, as well as potentially reducing nausea and vomiting. Two RCTs comparing the placement of nasogastric tubes for decompression with early removal (before day 2) or no tube placement have demonstrated reduced pulmonary complications in the group with standard nasogastric tube use. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nChest drains assist with lung re-expansion and can also be used to monitor chyle leaks and anastomotic leaks. However, chest drains are associated with increased pain and can make mobilization challenging. There is a wide variation in practice that guides drain removal, but early rationalization of drains, if more than one is placed, is recommended and most centers will remove the final chest drain when volume outputs have reduced below 200 mL/day.\n\nUrinary catheters are routinely placed at the time of surgery and aid with the monitoring of fluid balance as well as preventing postoperative urinary retention. The majority of patients still receive epidurals as part of their postoperative pain management and thus urinary catheters are usually left *in situ* until the epidural is stopped with up to 25% of patients requiring re-catheterization if the urinary catheter is removed earlier.\n\n## Rehabilitation\n\nEnhanced recovery pathways provide a structured template for delivering multidisciplinary care in the immediate postoperative setting. This has had concomitant improvements in short- and medium-term outcomes. The physiological impact of a procedure as extensive as an esophagectomy has long-term ramifications upon patient\u2019s health-related quality of life (HR-QOL), oral intake, and psychosocial functioning. With incremental prognostic gains with receipt of multimodal treatment and ERP pathways, there is an increased focus on improving overall survivorship in this patient population.\n\nAkin to prehabilitation, there is a need to implement strategies in the postoperative phase to restore, maintain, and improve patient\u2019s overall HR-QOL and physical functioning. The requirement is justified by consideration of key issues around the receipt of perioperative treatment. Prehabilitation interventions serve to mitigate this reduction and restore fitness in preparation for an esophagectomy. However, the extent of the surgical resection and the potential development of postoperative complications such as anastomotic leaks and pulmonary complications can impact upon recovery, and it is not unreasonable to consider that this will, in turn, lead to a deterioration in HR-QOL. Further, the physiological stress of surgery combined with the development of any complication can adversely impact cardiopulmonary reserve and physical functioning with an associated deleterious impact on mental wellbeing.\n\n### Treatment Implications on Quality of Life\n\nThere is a clear need for the implementation of strategies to address the long-term sequalae of an esophagectomy beyond the remit of enhanced recovery pathways. Patients receive little to no support to improve and restore overall HR-QOL following discharge from hospital, with post-esophagectomy symptoms persisting for prolonged periods of time. Several studies have demonstrated the lasting adverse impact of an esophagectomy on HR-QOL. Lagergren et al. assessed 47 patients from a single UK institution, analyzing HR-QOL scores at regular intervals over 3 years following surgery. They concluded that patients continued to experience poor physical function, dyspnea, diarrhea, and reflux at 3 years post-esophagectomy with symptom burden persistently worse than baseline. Similarly, Derogar and Lagergren assessed HR-QOL among patients identified from the Swedish cancer register who were 5 years on from an esophagectomy. Their study identified patients who reported persistent dyspnea, fatigue, and eating restrictions throughout their follow-up with sleep and reflux progressively worsening during this time period. Patient and disease characteristics are thought to play a role in predicting postoperative HR-QOL. Dj\u00e4rv et al. further investigated this in a nationwide study based in Sweden, analyzing HR-QOL among patients who were 6 months on following an esophagectomy. Their assessment of 355 patients over 4 years identified that patients with comorbidities, tumor location, and more advanced tumor stage were prone to poorer quality of life scores at 6 months. In 2022, a cross-sectional study conducted by Markar et al. comprising 20 European centers and 876 patients demonstrated persistent symptoms at least 1 year on following an esophagectomy. Symptoms patients noted most frequently were pain, low mood, and reduced energy levels and activity tolerance. The same study also noted that only 13.8% of patients returned to work with the same activities, and it is not unreasonable to consider that the physiological impact of these symptoms adversely affects patients\u2019 psychosocial wellbeing.\n\nGiven the morbidity associated with an esophagectomy, it is reasonable to consider that the development of complications can only further compound the deleterious impact on HR-QOL. However, the evidence for this is conflicting. Kauppila et al. report impaired HR-QOL in domains such as physical function, fatigue, pain, sleep, and eating difficulties among a Swedish nationwide prospective cohort study of 92 patients some 10 years on following an esophagectomy, who had developed postoperative complications. In contrast, Jezerskyte et al. report comparable HR-QOL across all domains over a 1-year follow-up of 486 patients undergoing an esophagectomy, comparing HR-QOL among patients who did ( *n* \\= 270) and did not ( *n* \\= 216) develop postoperative complications. This prospective comparative cohort study, based in The Netherlands, reported patients\u2019 HR-QOL returning to baseline at 12 months post-surgery. This study demonstrated that patients who developed anastomotic leaks, requiring endoscopic, radiological, or surgical intervention following an esophagectomy, reported persistent choking symptoms compared with those who did not have an anastomotic leak or indeed, among those patients who had an anastomotic leak amenable to medical management only. It must be noted that these studies vary in terms of setting, cohort sizes, follow-up duration, and modality of surgery necessitating a degree of caution when interpreting findings. Nonetheless, despite the heterogenous nature of studies reporting on patients\u2019 quality of life following an esophagectomy, the presence of symptoms lasting beyond the immediate postoperative period highlight the need for rehabilitative strategies to mitigate and restore HR-QOL into survivorship.\n\n### The Multidisciplinary Role of Rehabilitation\n\nThe United Kingdom National Health Service commissioning guidelines define rehabilitation as \u201ca collaborative process that enables an individual to maximize their potential to live a full and active life within their family, social networks, education/training and the workplace where appropriate.\u201d The need for rehabilitative interventions to address multifaceted needs such as restoration of physical fitness and improving mental wellbeing has been addressed as a key priority among cancer survivors and healthcare professionals who may be responsible for delivering such interventions.\n\nIt is imperative that rehabilitative strategies designed to improve and restore physical function and quality of life include the multidisciplinary team. Deficits in physical function and nutrition are as common as post-esophagectomy symptoms in survivorship, and these need to be adequately addressed as part of post-esophagectomy rehabilitation interventions. With regard to nutrition, initiation of adequate enteral nutrition into survivorship, long-term nutritional status, and maintenance of weight are key considerations. Additionally, malabsorption syndromes such as pancreatic exocrine insufficiency and small intestinal bacterial overgrowth are noted among patients well into survivorship. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Furthermore, post-esophagectomy dysphagia has been noted in the longer term with associated detrimental impact on HR-QOL. Yuen et al. demonstrated mild\u2013moderate pharyngeal dysphagia among a cohort of 29 patients who were over 3 years following an esophagectomy. Similar findings have been reported at 5 and 10 years following an esophagectomy. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Deficits in physical functioning are common in the long term. Exercise capacity and ability to partake in moderate physical activity can remain impaired for at least 6 months following an esophagectomy, although it can be postulated that impairments in other HR-QOL domains such as nutrition or psychosocial wellbeing can further compound this. Further deconditioning as a result of sarcopenia and fatigue are other physical deficits which may be amenable to exercise training.\n\nThus, the need for multidisciplinary input to be embedded into the development and delivery of post-esophagectomy rehabilitation is justified by the wide variety of symptoms patients experience into survivorship ( Fig. 37.2 ). However, there is paucity of sufficient evidence for the successful delivery and assessment of the impact of multidisciplinary rehabilitation. One reason for this may be that the prognostic benefits of multimodal treatment have only been observed more recently, which may have resulted in any rehabilitative strategy development continuing to remain in its nascent stages.\n\nA diagram with associated categories outlines the effects and concerns related to diet, psychosocial aspects, procedure-specific issues, and other health factors. The diagram highlights various concerns and effects in a patient''s recovery process. They are categorized into four sections. At the top are Psychosocial issues such as anxiety, depression, and concerns about the ability to return to work. The Diet and Nutrition section addresses challenges like weight loss, lack of appetite, loss of taste, and difficulties with portion sizes. The Musculoskeletal and Others section notes fatigue, reduced physical strength, and shortness of breath. Procedure-specific concerns include symptoms like early satiety, bloating, cough, regurgitation, dysphagia, and choking episodes. Additionally, the Gastrointestinal section covers abdominal pain, dumping syndrome, and diarrhea and depicts a comprehensive view of the challenges a patient may face that follows treatment.\n\nFig. 37.2\n\n### Evidence for Rehabilitation\n\nCaution must be exercised in interpreting the findings of published data in this field owing to the cohort sizes, study setting, and heterogenous study designs. Additionally, interventions included and the method of delivery are variable, resulting in some difficulties in implementing such programs into clinical practice.\n\nLococo et al. investigated the impact of an intensive multidisciplinary rehabilitation program versus standard pulmonary rehabilitation alone among 58 patients undergoing an esophagectomy in a single Italian center over 5 years. Multidisciplinary intervention included physiotherapists for supervised physical, abdominal muscle, and breathing exercises, dietitians, psychologists, and nursing support and was piloted among eight patients over 6 months. Improvements in physical functioning, exercise intensity levels, and recovery of pulmonary function were noted among those receiving intensive multidisciplinary rehabilitation compared with those receiving standard rehabilitation alone. As one of the first studies conducted in the field of post-esophagectomy rehabilitation, this study provides some of the earliest evidence of the favorable impact of multidisciplinary rehabilitation. However, the findings from this study need to be interpreted with extreme caution not just for the aforementioned reasons but additionally given the wide variation in sample sizes between the two groups.\n\nO\u2019Neill et al. piloted a 12-week multidisciplinary rehabilitation program for patients who were over 6 months following curative treatment for esophageal cancer which included esophagectomy alongside either neoadjuvant and/or adjuvant treatment. This single-center feasibility study included 12 patients with the rehabilitation intervention comprising supervised and home-based exercises, 1:1 dietary counselling, and educational sessions with a variety of multidisciplinary team members such as psychologists and surgical team members. Improvements in global HR-QOL scores and components of pulmonary function were noted, although no significant changes were observed in body composition and activity levels. The same group further investigated the impact of this intervention in an RCT setting, comparing the same 12-week intervention with standard care. Patients completing the multidisciplinary intervention had improved cardiopulmonary fitness, but no changes in body composition or HR-QOL were observed between the two groups.\n\nIn 2021 van Vulpen et al. conducted a multicenter RCT investigating the impact of a 12-week supervised exercise program on HR-QOL, fatigue, and cardiorespiratory fitness. Patients in this nationwide Dutch study were randomized to either usual care or to participate in the rehabilitation program with outcome assessment at 12 and 24 weeks after the intervention. Exercise rehabilitation included twice-weekly hour-long supervised aerobic exercises and daily physical activity for at least 30 minutes. Their findings concluded that exercise rehabilitation improved cardiopulmonary fitness and some aspects of quality of life. Interestingly, effects of exercise on general fatigue and HR-QOL summary scores on patients completing the rehabilitation intervention were attenuated at 24 weeks. The only exception to this was among patients undergoing an open esophagectomy where global HR-QOL favored the exercise group even at 24 weeks post-intervention. It can be postulated that the benefits of exercise on key HR-QOL domains including fatigue are observed only in the short-term owing to a less multidisciplinary approach to rehabilitation.\n\nInterventions need not be restricted to patients who have undergone curative surgical treatment alone.\n\n## Summary\n\nPrehabilitation is being increasingly incorporated alongside enhanced recovery pathways as routine clinical practice in the perioperative optimization of patients with esophagogastric cancer. Given the clinically relevant and significant deterioration in physical function and quality of life among this patient population in the longer term, there is a need to develop post-treatment rehabilitation interventions that can be embedded as part of perioperative patient optimization and recovery. Future studies, ideally in the randomized setting, will need to investigate the impact of delivering a variety of pragmatic multidisciplinary interventions on long-term quality of life and survivorship.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Phillips A.W., Griffin S.M.: Three decades of oesophagogastric cancer care: now a curable disease . Br J Surg 2021; 108: pp. 595-597.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Navidi M., Phillips A.W., Griffin S.M., et al. Cardiopulmonary fitness before and after neoadjuvant chemotherapy in patients with oesophagogastric cancer. 105:900\u2013906\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: Al-Batran S.-E., Homann N., Pauligk C., et al. Perioperative chemotherapy with fluorouracil plus leucovorin, oxaliplatin, and docetaxel versus fluorouracil or capecitabine plus cisplatin and epirubicin for locally advanced, resectable gastric or gastro-oesophageal junction adenocarcinoma (FLOT4): a randomised, phase 2/3 trial. 393:1948\u20131957\n\nView In Article\n\n4.: Dunne D.F.J., Jack S., Jones R.P., et al.: Randomized clinical trial of prehabilitation before planned liver resection . Br J Surg 2016; 103: pp. 504-512.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: Barakat H.M., Shahin Y., Khan J.A., Mccollum P.T., Chetter I.C.: Preoperative supervised exercise improves outcomes after elective abdominal aortic aneurysm repair: a randomized controlled trial . Ann Surg 2016; 264: pp. 47-53.\n\nView In Article\n\n6.: Minnella E.M., Awasthi R., Loiselle S.E., Agnihotram R.V., Ferri L.E., Carli F.: Effect of exercise and nutrition prehabilitation on functional capacity in esophagogastric cancer surgery: a randomized clinical trial . JAMA Surg 2018; 153: pp. 1081-1089.\n\nView In Article\n\n7.: Barberan-Garcia A., Ubr\u00e9 M., Roca J., et al.: Personalised prehabilitation in high-risk patients undergoing elective major abdominal surgery: a randomized blinded controlled trial . Ann Surg 2018; 267: pp. 50-56.\n\nView In Article\n\n8.: Xu Y.-J., Cheng J.C.-H., Lee J.-M., Huang P.-M., Huang G.-H., Chen C.C.-H.: A walk-and-eat intervention improves outcomes for patients with esophageal cancer undergoing neoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy . Oncol 2015; 20: pp. 