.4%200%20.5.3.3.7l-10%2017.2L183.7%2043c.2.4%200%20.7-.3.7h-5.8zM192.015%2019c-.2%200-.338-.004-.3-.2V8.4h-3.3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n\n\nNeed help? Chat with AI Buddy!\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[36. Anastomotic Complications After Esophagectomy - ClinicalKey|36. Anastomotic Complications After Esophagectomy]]\n**Next:** [[38. Palliative Therapy for Esophageal Cancer - ClinicalKey|38. Palliative Therapy for Esophageal Cancer]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "37. Survivorship Pathways in Esophagectomy:: Prehabilitation, Enhanced Recovery, and Rehabilitation - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Survivorship Pathways in Esophagectomy:: Prehabilitation, Enhanced Recovery, and Rehabilitation', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Survivorship Pathways in Esophagectomy: Prehabilitation, Enhanced Recovery, and Rehabilitation', 'Evidence for Prehabilitation', 'Prehabilitation for Esophagectomy', 'Physical Training', 'Nutritional Optimization', 'Other Prehabilitation Components', 'Survivorship Pathways in Esophagectomy: Prehabilitation, Enhanced Recovery, and Rehabilitation / Evidence for Prehabilitation', 'Survivorship Pathways in Esophagectomy: Prehabilitation, Enhanced Recovery, and Rehabilitation / Prehabilitation for Esophagectomy', 'Survivorship Pathways in Esophagectomy: Prehabilitation, Enhanced Recovery, and Rehabilitation / Physical Training'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '37', '392-404', 2, 56, FALSE, TRUE),
('Palliative Therapy for Esophageal Cancer', 'shackelford-9th-ed-38-palliative-therapy-for-esophageal-cancer', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Palliative Therapy for Esophageal Cancer\n\nStephanie G. Worrell; Hope Conrad\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 38, 405-411\n\n## The Palliative Therapy of Esophageal Cancer\n\nThe American Cancer Society estimates that there will be 21,560 esophageal cancer diagnoses and 16,120 esophageal cancer-related deaths in 2023 alone. Over the last 50 years, there has been a modest improvement in disease survival with 5-year survival rates increasing from 5% to 20%. Unfortunately, most patients still present with advanced disease at time of diagnosis.\n\nPalliative therapy aims to improve overall patient quality of life and is best understood when considered in two tiers. The first tier of therapy is available to all patients diagnosed with esophageal cancer and is typically provided by the primary oncology team. This tier includes treatment such as symptom management and can be provided in tandem with definitive treatment. The secondary tier of palliative therapy is tailored to patients with terminal disease and offers a variety of treatments to prolong or improve quality of life. A specialized palliative medicine team is typically involved in the secondary tier of therapy as it involves more complex management.\n\nIt is important to note the difference between palliative therapy, hospice, and comfort care. Although all aim to improve patient quality of life, hospice and comfort care do so specifically in the case of end-of-life management. Palliative care services should be offered to all patients diagnosed with esophageal cancer and have been demonstrated to improve patient quality of life and overall survival.\n\nPalliative therapy treatment is determined on a patient-by-patient basis and varies based on factors like disease extent, comorbidities, and patient preference. Endoscopic interventions such as dilation or stenting can be used to temporarily relieve obstruction and allow patients to maintain oral intake while they receive therapy that offers longer-lasting relief. Ablative procedures utilizing lasers and cryotherapy can help relieve obstructive symptoms. Noninvasive options are also available, including chemotherapy, radiation, and immunotherapy. Immunotherapy is a promising new addition to the armamentarium of palliative therapy interventions. Surgical interventions to improve symptoms and provide nutritional access are also available. It is not uncommon for multiple palliation modalities to be combined to best achieve treatment goals. In this chapter, we will discuss the palliative evaluation of the esophageal cancer patient as well as the treatment options available to this patient population.\n\n## Evaluation of the Palliative Esophageal Cancer Patient\n\n### Goals of Care\n\nAfter a patient has completed oncologic evaluation and has chosen to pursue palliative therapy, it is important to establish individualized goals of care. A shared decision-making approach allows for patients to express their priorities and goals regarding their quality of life, which may also help guide treatment. At this stage, the significance of establishing advanced directives, healthcare power of attorney, and financial power of attorney can be discussed with the patient. Physician orders for life-sustaining treatment (POLST) and medical orders for life-sustaining treatment (MOLST) are documents available in most states that allow for establishing end-of-life treatment wishes outside of the hospital. Multiple resources have been created to help facilitate difficult conversations and decisions, such as the Best Case/Worse Case framework. Unfortunately, some patients who present for palliative evaluation may be too ill to fully participate in their care. In this case, their medical power of attorney should be contacted to assist with decisions.\n\n### Oral Intake and Nutritional Status\n\nThe most common symptom reported by esophageal cancer patients is dysphagia. This is most often due to mass effect of the tumor but can also be caused by motility dysfunction. This symptom, in addition to nausea and tumor metabolism, often leads to malnutrition. Because all patients with esophageal cancer will face some degree of dysphagia in their cancer course, a large portion of palliative therapy is targeted toward relieving obstruction. It is important to understand the extent of dysphagia early in the evaluation. Prolonging the ability to continue oral intake for as long as possible optimizes patient nutrition as well as quality of life.\n\nBy the time a patient has elected to pursue palliative therapy, they have likely undergone multiple imaging and endoscopic evaluations. Additional tests, such as swallow studies, may be helpful in determining the underlying degree of obstruction and cause of dysphagia. Multiple nutritional assessments have been developed to help determine the need for supplementation. Endoscopic interventions such as dilation or stenting can provide immediate relief of dysphagia and may be used as temporizing measures while the patient begins other types of palliative therapy. However, in cases of severe dysphagia or malnutrition, obtaining enteral access by placement of a gastrostomy or jejunostomy tube may be necessary. In some patients with complete obstruction, parenteral nutrition may be appropriate. Ongoing nutritional assessment and reevaluation throughout treatment is warranted.\n\n### Health Maintenance\n\nAn updated medical history and examination is imperative prior to deciding on a course of therapy. Many patients have preexisting medical conditions at the time of their cancer diagnosis. Being aware of these comorbidities and ensuring that they are appropriately managed will reduce the overall risk of complications during treatment. In addition to chronic medical problems, esophageal cancer patients may experience a sudden decline in their baseline health. Evaluations like the Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group (ECOG) performance status score and the Karnofsky Performance Scale are frequently used to assess patient functional status ( Tables 38.1 and 38.2 ). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> As with all patients, appropriate clearance measures should be taken prior to any intervention while keeping in consideration that the patient\u2019s health status can quickly change. A multidisciplinary team, which may consist of nutritionists, dietitians, occupational therapists, gastroenterologists, surgeons, and primary care providers, is often helpful in the management of complex patients.\n\nTable 38.1\n\nKarnofsky Performance Scale\n\nFrom Oken M, Creech R, Tormey D, et al. Toxicity and response criteria of the Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group. *Am J Clin Oncol* . 1982;5:649-655.\n\n| Grade | Status |\n| --- | --- |\n| **100** | Normal, no complaints |\n| **90** | Able to carry on normal activities Minor signs of symptoms or disease |\n| **80** | Normal activity with effort |\n| **70** | Care for self Unable to carry on normal work or do active work. |\n| **60** | Requires occasional assistance, but able to care for most of their needs |\n| **50** | Requires considerable assistance and frequent medical care |\n| **40** | Disabled Requires special care and assistance |\n| **30** | Severely disabled Hospitalization indicated though death nonimminent |\n| **20** | Very sick Hospitalization necessary Active supportive treatment necessar |\n| **10** | Moribund |\n\nTable 38.2\n\nEastern Cooperative Oncology Group (ECOG) Performance Status Score\n\nFrom Oken MM, Creech RH, Tormey DC, et al. Toxicity and response criteria of the Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group. *Am J Clin Oncol.* 1982;5(6):649\u2013656.\n\n| Grade | Status |\n| --- | --- |\n| **0** | Fully active, able to carry on all pre-disease performance without restriction. |\n| **1** | Restricted in physically strenuous activity but ambulatory and able to carry out work of a light or sedentary nature, e.g., light house work, office work. |\n| **2** | Ambulatory and capable of all self-care but unable to carry out any work activities. Up and about more than 50% of waking hours. |\n| **3** | Capable of only limited self-care, confined to bed or chair more than 50% of waking hours. |\n| **4** | Completely disabled. Cannot carry on any self-care. Totally confined to bed or chair. |\n\n## Palliative Interventions\n\n### Esophageal Dilation\n\nEndoscopic esophageal dilation is frequently utilized in the treatment of malignant obstruction. Dilation is performed by passing either a bougie or balloon dilator through the area of stricture ( Figs. 38.1 and 38.2 ). While a bougie dilator utilizes both radial and longitudinal force to open the esophageal lumen, a balloon dilator uses only radial force. Because of these mechanics, bougie dilation is more effective when used for focal strictures while balloon dilation is more effective for longer strictures. Bougie dilation is performed fluoroscopically while balloon dilation can be performed under direct visualization or fluoroscopically.\n\nA photo of the medical equipment labeled part A for a set of balloon catheters and part B represents a photo of an inflation device with a syringe-like structure with a pressure gauge. Ch38\n\nFig. 38.1\n\nA photo depicts medical equipment of a set of curved rods organized in a tool case, each labeled with different sizes that vary in length and thickness. #REF!\n\nFig. 38.2\n\nWhen treating dysphagia, a lumen of 11 to 12 mm is required for the intake of liquids and 14 to 15 mm is needed for soft solids. Dilation can provide prompt relief of dysphagia; however, symptoms typically recur in 1 to 2 weeks if performed alone. Therefore, dilation is often used as a temporizing measure to allow for intake while more durable interventions are initiated. In the setting of severe obstruction, dilation may be required to facilitate other interventions. For example, a balloon dilator can help allow for passage of a self-expanding metal stent (SEMS). Dilation can also establish the necessary luminal diameter for procedures requiring endoscopy past the level of obstruction.\n\nComplications of endoscopic esophageal dilation are infrequent but still occur, including perforation. The risk of esophageal perforation doubles when performed in the setting of malignancy, as high as 14% when performed after chemotherapy, radiation, or laser therapy, and a perforation in the face of cancer can be devastating. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Therefore, dilation alone should be undertaken with caution. There should be a low threshold for further imaging, such as esophagram, to evaluate for the presence of a leak should clinical suspicion arise. Small leaks with sufficient drainage may be treated with nil per os and antibiotics while larger leaks may require more aggressive intervention, such as stent placement or surgery.\n\n### Esophageal Stenting\n\nEndoscopic stents have been utilized for esophageal strictures since 1885 and can provide expeditious relief of malignant dysphagia symptoms. Rigid plastic tubes were initially used in the treatment of malignant obstruction but have since fallen out of favor due to studies demonstrating their inferior safety and efficacy profile when compared to SEMSs. SEMSs are now the most utilized stents in the palliation of esophageal cancer. SEMS placement can be performed under sedation, which is attractive to patients who may be too ill to undergo general anesthesia. Some surgeons and endoscopists prefer to use general anesthesia due to the risk of aspiration during the procedure. While self-expanding plastic stents (SEPSs) exist, they are less frequently used in this patient population as they have been shown to have higher rates of migration and inferior performance when compared to SEMSs. Thus this discussion will be primarily focused on SEMSs.\n\nSEMSs vary based on length, diameter, covering, and placement technique. Understanding the nuances of each stent is necessary to choose the most appropriate stent for your patient. Table 38.3 shows the stents most utilized for malignant obstruction. Most stents are fully or partially covered, which prevents ingrowth of tumor except at the ends, which are left uncovered to lower risk of migration. If tumor ingrowth occurs, interventions such as further stenting, neodymium-yttrium-aluminum-garnet (Nd:YAG) laser, or photodynamic therapy (PDT) can be utilized to ablate the tumor. It is important to note that thermal lasers should be used cautiously as some stents can be damaged in the process. In addition to relieving obstruction, stents can be used to treat esophageal perforation or bronchoenteric fistulas, which can result from tumor erosion.\n\nTable 38.3\n\nStent Options for Palliation of Malignant Dysphagia\n\n| Stent Type | Manufacturer | Covered | Stent Material | Release | Foreshortening |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Ultraflex | Boston Scientific | Partially Fully | Nitinol | Proximal and distal | 35% |\n| WallFlex | Boston Scientific | Partially Fully | Cobalt based | Distal | 35% |\n| Evolution | Cook Medical | Partially Fully | Stainless steel | Distal | None |\n| Alimaxx-ES | Merit Medical | Fully | Nitinol | Distal | None |\n\nStent placement is not without risk, with one study showing up to 20% of patients experiencing severe adverse events. Complications from stent placement can present in an early or delayed fashion and vary based on location of the stent. Chest pain can occur and, although it is typically transient, sometimes necessitates stent removal. Up to a third of patients also experience recurrent dysphagia following stent placement. Other complications include stent fistula formation and pain from radial force and bleeding. Stents that are placed proximally have the risk of airway compromise while stents in the distal esophagus may disrupt sphincter function, leading to reflux and increased risk of migration. Because of its risks, SEMS placement performed alone as treatment for dysphagia is best suited for patients with a short life expectancy who are unable to tolerate more durable treatment options.\n\nAdvancements in stent technology have been developed and have great potential in the palliative treatment of esophageal cancer. However, research regarding these stents is limited with extremely varying results. Radioactive stents impregnated with I-125 beads have been developed to provide the benefits of both stenting and brachytherapy. While this method has been shown to provide longer-lasting dysphagia relief and even increased survival, one study found a significantly increased risk of bleeding with some hemorrhages leading to death. Another new stent is the valved antireflux stent. This stent was developed to treat distal tumors that require stent placement across the gastroesophageal (GE) junction, which can disrupt sphincter function and cause reflux. However, studies have demonstrated varying degrees of efficacy. A recent meta-analysis showed no difference in reflux rates when compared to nonvalved stents. However, this study did not include the randomized controlled trial (RCT) by Coron et al. that found valved stents to be superior in preventing reflux. Biodegradable stents, drug-eluting stents, and three-dimensional (3D) printed stents are further examples of stents that may prove beneficial in the future. While these technologies have demonstrated promise, further research is needed to better understand the role of these innovative stents in the palliation of esophageal cancer.\n\n### Laser Ablation\n\nThermal laser therapy, including argon beam and Nd:YAG, has been utilized in the management of esophageal cancer since the 1980s. While they deliver durable relief of obstructive symptoms, these methods of intervention are associated with a high risk of perforation. PDT is a nonthermal laser ablation technique with a much lower rate of perforation as well as longer symptomatic relief. However, an understanding of the risks and benefits of all laser options is important when considering palliation of esophageal cancer. Laser therapy can prove beneficial in the treatment of tumors in the proximal esophagus, as stenting carries risk of tracheal compression and airway compromise. Distal tumors can also benefit as stents that cross the GE junction can result in reflux. Because laser therapy is limited to the endoluminal surface, it may not relieve obstruction caused by bulky tumors or external compression. It is important to note that laser therapy typically requires multiple sessions to provide symptom relief, limiting its use in patients with short life expectancies.\n\n#### Thermal Laser Ablation\n\nNd:YAG and argon are thermal laser ablation techniques used to treat advanced esophageal cancer. Nd:YAG is performed by using a wavelength of 1064 nm set to 50 to 90 W with a pulse duration of 0.3 to 1.0 seconds to debride tissue. In argon plasma coagulation, argon gas plasma is used to debride tissue. Both techniques can be used to treat dysphagia and even bleeding. While these lasers can also be used to treat stent overgrowth, caution must be taken as some stents can be damaged in the thermal process. Nd:YAG has been shown to have a higher risk of perforation, but both methods carry risk of perforation, fistula, and stricture.\n\n#### Nonthermal Laser Ablation\n\nThe more widely used laser treatment for esophageal cancer is PDT. PDT is a nonthermal laser technique that was approved by the FDA in 1996 for use in malignant dysphagia. In this procedure, the patient is first parenterally injected with a photosensitizing agent, which accumulates in higher amounts in cancerous cells. After 48 to 72 hours, an endoscopy is performed to introduce a nonthermal light with a wavelength of 400 to 600 mW/cm at the site of the tumor for 8 to 10 minutes, causing a local photooxidative reaction. This reaction causes apoptosis of tumor cells through the release of molecular oxygen. Because this reaction is triggered by light, it is imperative that the patient avoids sunlight for 4 weeks after receiving the photosensitizing agent. PDT can also be used to treat tumor in- or overgrowth on stents. While PDT has been demonstrated to provide durable relief with a lower rate of perforations than other forms of laser therapy, it does come with a risk of stenosis, fistula, and photosensitivity reactions. These side effects, along with the inconvenience of avoiding sunlight during treatment in patients with short life expectancy, high cost, and limited availability, limit its usage. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Cryotherapy\n\nThe current data on cryotherapy usage in advanced esophageal cancer demonstrate that it is well-tolerated and safe. This endoscopic intervention directly introduces a cryogen to tumor tissue, inducing freeze and thaw cycles that result in ice crystal formation and fusion. This, along with osmotic changes and cytokine release, causes disruption of cellular membranes and ultimately leads to immediate and delayed cell death. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Because the underlying tissue is not disrupted and the cryoresistant nature of collagen and elastin, there is low risk of scarring and perforation. There are two cryogen options available for endoscopic use: liquid nitrogen and carbon dioxide ( Fig. 38.3 ).\n\nTwo photos show the endoscopic view of a smooth, slightly textured surface on the left and an irregular, rough surface with some abnormality on the right. #REF!\n\nFig. 38.3\n\n#### Liquid Nitrogen\n\nIn the liquid nitrogen technique, a spray of liquid nitrogen is introduced to the affected area using a 7F catheter within the endoscope. Nitrogen gas expansion causes rapid cooling to a temperature of \u2212196\u00b0C, inducing the freeze cycle. Throughout the procedure, gas venting and circuit heating are used to facilitate the thaw cycle and prevent freezing of equipment, allowing the endoscope and catheter to remain functional at such low temperatures. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In order to prevent gastric overdistension and perforation secondary to rapid gas expansion, gastric decompression with orogastric tube and frequent abdominal examinations are required throughout the procedure. Inability to pass an orogastric tube is a contraindication to this procedure.\n\n#### Carbon Dioxide\n\nCarbon dioxide can be used as a cryogen as well, with CO <sub>2 </sub> introduced using a 0.005-inch diameter catheter tip through the endoscope. The freeze cycle is induced at a temperature of \u221278\u00b0C. The number and duration of cycles varies in practice due to limited data. Throughout the procedure, gas is vented using a suction cap on the endoscope. Because equipment will not freeze at this temperature, further measures to warm equipment are not needed. This technique is more cost effective as it does not require specialized cooling during storage. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nCryotherapy can provide significant improvement of dysphagia alone or in combination with other treatments. While it is relatively safe, with low risk of pain or perforation, it is important to note that cryotherapy carries a risk of intraprocedural cardiac arrhythmia due to temperature changes near the heart. Preprocedural cardiac workup is recommended.\n\n### Radiation Therapy\n\n#### Brachytherapy\n\nBrachytherapy, or endoluminal radiation, is an endoscopic procedure that ablates tumor by introducing radiation directly to the tumor. Because it is local, lower doses of radiation are required to achieve symptomatic relief, resulting in less radiation to surrounding tissues than traditional radiation therapy. This procedure is typically repeated on a weekly basis for 3 to 8 weeks and has up to an 87% resolution rate of dysphagia symptoms after 1 month of therapy. Because it takes weeks to see results, this therapy should be reserved for patients with longer life expectancy. Studies have shown that brachytherapy comes with a benefit of increased survival and quality of life when compared to SEMSs alone. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> However, this procedure is not without risk. Brachytherapy has up to a 22.6% risk of adverse events, including stenosis, fistula formation, and perforation.\n\n#### External Beam Radiation Therapy\n\nWhen utilized as a palliative intervention, external beam radiation therapy (EBRT) can effectively provide dysphagia relief and is noninvasive and widely available. While there are mixed results comparing EBRT to brachytherapy, the POLDER study found that a shortened course of EBRT, four gray over five sessions, provided superior dysphagia relief that was more durable than brachytherapy. The combination of brachytherapy and EBRT is controversial, as studies have shown that it is associated with a higher complication rate. In addition to dysphagia treatment, EBRT can provide effective pain relief. Hypofractionated radiation therapy has been proven to help with pain caused by tumor burden at primary and metastatic sites, including bone pain. Because the best results typically occur weeks after radiation treatment, radiation-based interventions should be reserved for patients with longer life expectancies. Adverse effects are dose dependent, including initial worsening of dysphagia, nausea/vomiting, bleeding, cytopenia, and stricture.\n\n### Systemic Chemotherapy and Chemoradiation Therapy\n\nThe addition of chemotherapy in the palliative treatment of esophageal cancer is recommended for patients with good performance status, as it improves overall survival and possibly better quality of life. Systemic chemotherapy can provide dysphagia relief within weeks and remain symptom free for weeks to months. Palliative chemotherapy agents typically include 5-flurorouracil and cisplatin, but regimens vary greatly. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Chemotherapy combined with radiation, or chemoradiation therapy (CRT), is standard of care for locally advanced disease as patients may have a complete pathologic response. However, while CRT has been shown to lengthen survival compared to RT alone in advanced cancer patients, the combination of chemotherapy and radiation therapy is associated with much higher rate of adverse effects with only modest symptom relief. Individual patient tolerance of chemotherapy and radiation, considered within the context of their goals of care, should play a major role in deciding treatment course as the goal of palliative intervention is improved quality of life.\n\nRegional delivery of chemotherapeutic agents limits drug exposure to a more specific region than systemic chemotherapy, allowing for good tumor response with highly concentrated agents while maintaining low toxicity profile. Regional chemotherapy introduces chemotherapeutic agents into specific vasculature through image-guided catheter placement, limiting the drug to the vasculature that feeds the tumor bed. Regional chemotherapy has shown improved survival in patients with progression of disease after primary therapy when compared to other traditional second-line agents.\n\n### Immunotherapy\n\nThe use of immunotherapy in the palliation of esophageal cancer is a relatively new practice and its role is still being determined. Immunotherapy has proven to be well-tolerated and effective in certain patient populations. The immunologic agents most studied in the treatment of esophageal cancer are those targeting human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2), programmed death receptor 1 (PD-1)/programmed death ligand 1 (PD-L1), and cytotoxic T-lymphocyte\u2013associated antigen 4 (CTLA-4) receptors.\n\n#### Anti-HER2 Agents\n\nHER2 receptors, which drive tumor amplification, are overexpressed in approximately 2% to 45% of esophageal and GE junction cancers with esophageal adenocarcinoma having higher rates of overexpression than squamous cell carcinoma (SCC). Trastuzumab, a monoclonal antibody targeting HER2 receptors, has been shown to improve survival in esophageal cancer patients with advanced HER2-positive disease. Trastuzumab is already recommended in standard first-line palliative treatment regimens for HER2-positive tumors. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> While the idea of dual anti-HER2 immunologic therapy is promising, studies involving the addition of pertuzumab and lapatinib have not yet demonstrated efficacy in the palliation of esophageal cancer. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n#### Anti-PD1/PD-L1 and Anti-CTLA-4 Agents\n\nAgents targeting the PD-1 and PD-L1 have been developed to inhibit immune checkpoint pathway of tumor cells while CTLA-4 is a receptor on T cells that downregulates T-cell activation. Nivolumab and pembrolizumab are monoclonal antibodies used in esophageal cancer treatment that target the PD-1/PD-L1 checkpoint and ipilimumab inhibits CTLA-4. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Several clinical trials have demonstrated that these agents can be effective against esophageal cancer in multiple patient populations. A meta-analysis by Chen et al. found anti-PD-1/PD-L1 treatment of advanced GE cancers superior to chemotherapy or palliative care treatments with more tolerable side effects. Current approved uses of nivolumab in the palliative setting include nivolumab + chemotherapy for HER2-positive adenocarcinoma with combined positive score (CPS) \u22655 and SCC with \u22651% PD-L1 expression. Pembrolizumab + chemotherapy has been approved for first-line treatment of metastatic esophageal cancer with CPS \u226510. Nivolumab + ipilimumab is approved for SCC with \u2265% PD-L1 expression and nivolumab monotherapy is approved for second-line treatment of esophageal SCC and GE junction tumors. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Surgical Interventions\n\nMany patients pursuing palliative therapy for advanced esophageal cancer are ineligible for or have failed surgical resection. While surgical procedures in the setting of advanced esophageal cancer are limited and associated with poor survival, they may benefit a small subgroup of patients by providing obstructive relief. Surgery, if it is in line with a patient\u2019s goals of care, may also be necessary in the setting of esophageal perforation, fistula, or bleeding not amenable to more conservative measures.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThere is no gold standard for the palliative treatment of esophageal cancer, and therapy must be chosen based on shared decision making and consideration of individual patient-disease characteristics. Several options are available to enhance patient quality of life and increase the amount of time they are able to spend at home rather than in the hospital. Therapy options for the patient with advanced esophageal cancer are constantly increasing, as noted with the recent addition of immunotherapy in the armamentarium of palliative therapy options. Continued research on immunologic agents is promising, as well as further investigation on optimal combinations of multiple forms of therapy.\n\n## Acknowledgments\n\nThe authors and editors acknowledge and thank the previous edition authors(s), Dennis Wells and Virginia R. Litle, for their contribution to this chapter.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Siegel R.L., Miller K.D., Wagle N.S., Jemal A.: Cancer statistics, 2023 . CA Cancer J Clin 2023; 73 (1): pp. 17-48.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Guyer D.L., Almhanna K., McKee K.Y.: Palliative care for patients with esophageal cancer: a narrative review . Ann Transl Med 2020; 8 (17): 1103-1103 .\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: Ferrell B.R., Temel J.S., Temin S., et al.: Integration of palliative care into standard oncology care: American Society of Clini