uation of the Palliative Esophageal Cancer Patient', 'Palliative Interventions', 'Goals of Care', 'Oral Intake and Nutritional Status', 'Palliative Therapy for Esophageal Cancer / The Palliative Therapy of Esophageal Cancer', 'Palliative Therapy for Esophageal Cancer / Evaluation of the Palliative Esophageal Cancer Patient', 'Palliative Therapy for Esophageal Cancer / Palliative Interventions'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '38', '405-411', 2, 31, FALSE, TRUE),
('Management of Esophageal Perforation', 'shackelford-9th-ed-39-management-of-esophageal-perforation', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Management of Esophageal Perforation\n\nCourtney Cartier; Daniel Davila-Bradley\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 39, 413-421\n\n## Introduction\n\nEsophageal perforations are typically associated with poor outcomes unless treated in a judicious and deliberate manner. There is a broad range of etiologies and presentations of esophageal perforations, with the first description from Herman Boerhaave in the 1720s. The first successful surgical repair was then performed by Norman Barrett in 1947 and since then the management options have evolved substantially due to the development of numerous endoscopic, percutaneous, and operative techniques. With all these options, physicians treating esophageal perforations must have an understanding of the anatomy and pathophysiology in order to perform the appropriate life-saving treatments. The aim of this chapter is to provide a framework of guiding principles in the management of esophageal perforations that can be applied to any scenario.\n\n## Etiology\n\nThe leading cause of esophageal perforation is iatrogenic, with up to 60% of cases associated with endoscopy. Diagnostic flexible upper endoscopy has a very low perforation rate of <0.1%, but therapeutic endoscopy is increasingly being performed and can have much higher perforation rates depending on the specific technique performed. Other causes of esophageal perforation include malignant perforation, trauma, caustic ingestion, and foreign body ingestion.\n\nAnother pathophysiologic entity that deserves commentary is Boerhaave syndrome. Boerhaave syndrome refers to a rupture of the distal esophagus at the gastroesophageal junction in the setting of rapid elevation in intra-abdominal pressure such as in retching or other causes of vigorous Valsalva. Boerhaave syndrome has been associated with the presence of hiatal hernias, based on the theory that a rapid increase in intraabdominal pressure is transmitted to the hernia which is then exposed to negative intrathoracic pressure. This forceful transmission across a pressure gradient can lead to perforations, usually near the gastroesophageal junction on the left side of the distal thoracic esophagus.\n\n## Presentation\n\nDue to an increasing percentage of esophageal perforations from endoscopy, one may expect that these injuries present early. However, up to half of all cases present more than 24 hours after symptom onset, with 25% of cases presenting with sepsis at that time. The presentation of esophageal perforations depends not only on the location of the perforation but also on the extent of contamination. In individuals with a recent history of forceful emesis, exposure to ingested foreign body, endoscopy, or other esophageal intervention, providers must have a high level of suspicion for esophageal perforation to accurately diagnose. Systemic signs of sepsis include fever, tachycardia, tachypnea, leukocytosis, and varying levels of circulatory shock, and may be present with perforation at any level of the esophagus. Cervical perforations may present with difficulty swallowing (dysphagia or odynophagia), neck pain, dysphonia, or hematemesis. On physical exam, crepitus due to subcutaneous emphysema may also be appreciated. Thoracic perforations more commonly present with chest or back pain, dyspnea, emesis, and hematemesis. Arrhythmias may also be present as mediastinitis and can cause the sensation of heart palpitations. Abdominal esophageal perforations have presenting signs similar to other hollow viscous perforations of the abdominal cavity including nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and peritonitis. Esophageal perforations can be missed if suspicion for esophageal perforation is not high enough to prompt deliberate hiatal examination during exploratory surgery.\n\n## Diagnosis\n\nWhen an esophageal perforation is suspected, the goal of the workup is to document the presence, location, extent of the defect in the esophageal wall, and to evaluate the degree of surrounding contamination. In most cases, numerous tests will be required to obtain a complete understanding of the injury, as no single test has been proven to sufficiently achieve these goals. Although plain film radiography is rapid and inexpensive, it is typically only able to demonstrate large volumes of air or fluid that have distributed into adjacent tissues, often missing more subtle injuries. In cervical perforations, this may manifest as air tracking in the soft tissues of the neck. In thoracic perforations, typically pleural effusions or hydropneumothorax may be seen. Abdominal perforations may present with intraperitoneal free air on an upright chest X-ray or on lateral decubitus films. Most importantly, what appears to be extraluminal air around the esophagus on plain film is insufficient alone to confirm the diagnosis of an esophageal perforation.\n\nThe gold standard modality to diagnose esophageal perforation is oral contrast esophogram either by computed tomography (CT) scan (CT esophogram) or by fluoroscopy (UGI). These modalities can confirm a full-thickness injury and help identify the location of the perforation. In stable patients with early presentations, our preference is soluble contrast UGI to evaluate the extent of the defect. UGIs provide a dynamic image of the esophagus, which is useful for further planning of potential surgical or endoscopic approaches. When a perforation is confirmed, the contrast extravasation can be followed to see if it flows freely into adjacent cavities or if remains contained in an adjacent space ( Fig. 39.1 ). In addition, fluoroscopy also has a lower radiation dose, so it can be used for repeat evaluations to determine the efficacy of interventions and to evaluate for healing. If the water-soluble contrast imaging is not clear, thin barium contrast can be used to increase the sensitivity.\n\nA radiographic scan depicts the view of the spine with a marked area with an arrow to indicate an abnormality in the examination process. Ch39\n\nFig. 39.1\n\nA pitfall of UGIs is that they are dependent on the operator, and small extravasations can be missed if complete images are not obtained. CT scans provide a more consistent 360-degree image and are now widely available ( Fig. 39.2 ). Recent studies have shown that the initial imaging modality of CT with oral contrast has higher sensitivity, specificity, and negative predictive value than fluoroscopy. Therefore, CT is typically the preferred imaging modality due to availability, quickness, and the ability to evaluate surrounding contamination. It is not uncommon to find that a screening non-contrast CT scan was performed upon presentation, and if a perforation is suspected, then contrast imaging is required to confirm the diagnosis and quantitate the injury.\n\nA computed tomography scan of the chest area with marked details for examination. The computed tomography scan of the chest, with specific details, reveals a cross-sectional view of the chest cavity, which presents various structures such as the lungs, heart, and spine. The scan was taken with contrast material 100 milliliters S O V U E 300 to provide better clarity. The parameters listed include an exposure of 700, a gap of 5 point 00 millimeters, a thickness of 5 point 00 millimeters, and a localization at 154 point 50 millimeters. The scan also features a zoom position at 1 point 00 times and window level adjustments at W L 350 divided by 40.\n\nFig. 39.2\n\nWhen contrast is contraindicated, although contrast can be administered via a nasogastric tube in the incapacitated patient, direct endoscopy can be used. In experienced hands, endoscopy provides direct visualization to localize and determine the extent of an injury, as well as visualization of the surrounding tissues. It can also assess underlying pathology (such as a tumor or stricture) that may dictate what intervention is performed, and in many cases the definitive intervention is performed at the time of endoscopy. Endoscopic evaluation should be performed with caution though, as insufflation can cause unnecessary dissection of extraesophageal tissue planes, and in the setting of communication with the pleural space (and no prior chest drainage) the development of tension physiology can occur. Therefore, insufflation should be minimally used when esophageal perforation is suspected, and carbon dioxide should be used whenever possible.\n\n## Guiding Principles for Management\n\nFor decades, early and aggressive surgery was the cornerstone of therapy for esophageal perforations due to the associated high mortality rate. In 1979, John Cameron published criteria for non-operative management of esophageal perforations: (1) the esophageal disruption should be well contained within the mediastinum or between the mediastinum and visceral lung pleura; (2) the cavity should be well drained back into the esophagus; (3) minimal symptoms should be present; and (4) there should be minimal evidence of clinical sepsis. Since then, medical technology has substantially developed, therefore expanding the criteria for \u201cnon-operative\u201d management of esophageal perforations. Regardless of injury severity or available resources, successful management of esophageal perforations includes addressing these three guiding principles:\n\n  - 1.\n\tResuscitation and control of sepsis.\n  - 2.\n\tDiversion of the salivary stream.\n  - 3.\n\tNutritional support.\n\n### Resuscitation and Control of Sepsis\n\nThe degree of sepsis upon presentation is the most important factor in predicting outcomes and appropriate interventions. The general principles of resuscitation and supportive critical care, in accordance with the surviving sepsis campaign, should be used upon initial assessment. While the patient is being stabilized, simultaneous plans to achieve source control are essential. Primary source control refers to addressing the injury and the contamination in surrounding tissues. All patients with suspected esophageal perforation should receive prompt initiation of broad-spectrum antibiotic therapy with the addition of an antifungal agent. These broad-spectrum antibiotics should remain onboard until they can be adjusted based on culture data or until the patient improves. In addition to the perforation itself, the primary drivers of persistent sepsis are undrained fluid collections and necrotic tissue. Serial CT scans are frequently required to diagnose, quantify, and monitor these secondary infections. Patients who have fluid collections and minimal clinical sepsis will typically respond well to less invasive approach such as percutaneous drainage and antibiotics. Patients showing clinical decline or more severe sepsis will likely need a more aggressive approach. This may mean additional drain placement; however, if a patient develops worsening sepsis, then alteration to a definitive surgical approach should be considered. Overall, the tenants of controlling sepsis from an esophageal perforation are: (1) identifying and treating sources of infection early; (2) frequent clinical and radiographic surveillance; and (3) escalating care promptly when necessary.\n\n### Diversion of the Salivary Stream\n\nThe goal is to prevent saliva and other esophageal contents from exiting through the injury, thus preventing ongoing contamination and allowing for the perforation to heal. Very small esophageal defects with contained leaks may not require diversion as limiting oral intake is sufficient itself. Some providers may choose to add oral antimicrobial agents. In patients with very large injuries presenting with severe sepsis, salivary diversion with a cervical esophagostomy (spit fistula) may be required. The remainder of perforations exist between these extremes and require a patient-specific approach such as repair, stenting, or resection which will be discussed later in the chapter.\n\n### Nutritional Support\n\nThe third principle in management of patients with esophageal perforations is adequate nutritional support. The goal should be early enteral nutrition, and the benefits of enteral nutrition in septic patients to maximize healing are well documented. Feeding access should be thought of early on, as immediate interventions may make it difficult to perform additional procedures. Patients with small defects that are either observed or repaired primarily may be able to avoid feeding tube placement and resume oral intake within a few days. Temporary feeding access such as nasoduodenal tubes may be adequate to administer tube feeds in patients not predicted to require prolonged time without oral intake. However, these tubes are uncomfortable and prone to dislodgement, so if the patient is predicted to require feeding access for more than 1\u20132 weeks, percutaneous access is preferred. For patients treated with covered stents, radiographic documentation confirming that the stent is well placed and providing adequate salivary diversion are required prior to resumption of oral diet. Occasionally, total parenteral nutrition (TPN) can be used to avoid prolonged nutritional depletion in patients expected to heal within 1\u20132 weeks or in patients malnourished at the time of perforation. In patients expected to need prolonged nutritional support, a surgically placed feeding jejunostomy is preferred. With consideration, gastrostomy feeding can be used in some cases, but there needs to be a confidence that the stomach will not be needed for further reconstruction (i.e., after an esophagectomy) and that gastric feeds will not reflux through the injury in the presence of a defective reflux barrier. A defective reflux barrier may occur from chronic gastroesophageal reflux disease and associated hiatal hernia or may be induced such as from placement of a covered stent across the gastroesophageal junction. In these situations, a post-pyloric jejunal extension tube can be placed if a percutaneous gastrostomy is preferred (gastrojejunostomy tube) over a direct jejunostomy tube. Finally, an oral diet can be initiated after there is radiographic and clinical evidence that the perforation has healed and nutritional support weaned.\n\n## Management of Esophageal Perforations\n\nWith advanced technology, many patients are successfully managed without the morbidity associated with traditional open surgery, but there is not a simple one-size-fits-all management strategy for patients with esophageal perforations. A stable patient may benefit from less invasive interventions, while a patient in extremis needs immediate care. The approach to the three guiding principles depends on the skills and resources available at the facility, as well as the patient\u2019s clinical status, and as such it is perfectly reasonable to utilize a more aggressive approach if the clinical situation demands ( Fig. 39.3 ). The overall goal in treatment should be to perform the most effective treatments in the least invasive way and to decrease morbidity. Physicians must create a treatment strategy best suited to each unique patient and closely monitor the patient\u2019s clinical status to escalate care if needed. Escalation of care may include transfer of patients to experienced tertiary centers, after initial stabilization, as source control is critical.\n\nA flowchart illustrates the management options for esophageal perforation, which includes non-operative, endoscopic, and surgical approaches. The flowchart outlines the management of esophageal perforation, categorized into non-operative, endoscopic, and surgical approaches. Non-operative management is considered for small, contained leaks in stable patients, involving N P O, antibiotics, nutrition support, and minimally invasive interventions. Endoscopic management includes closure clips, suturing, drainage stents, and endoluminal vacuum therapy. Surgical management involves resection with or without immediate reconstruction, suture repair with or without flap and immediate reconstruction, or exclusion or diversion with various techniques. The choice of approach depends on leak size, location, cause, patient condition, and available resources.\n\nFig. 39.3\n\n### Conservative Management\n\nAs many patients who present with perforations will require some type of procedure, true \u201cnon-operative\u201d management is uncommon, and the term \u201cconservative management\u201d is better suited for this cohort. Typically, these patients present early and have small injuries. If stable, with minimal symptoms and the contrast study shows a contained contrast extravasation, they can be observed without formal salivary diversion. Treatment should include hospital admission, nothing by mouth (NPO), broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotics, serial blood work, and a follow-up contrast (or endoscopic) examination to confirm healing. Once healing is confirmed, clear liquids by mouth can be started and advanced to a full liquid or soft diet for 2\u20133 weeks. If the patient has not resumed oral intake by approximately 1 week, but is still responding well to conservative management, an alternative feeding tube or TPN should be considered. Any worsening of symptoms should prompt additional work up and escalation to an interventional approach.\n\n### Interventional Radiology Management\n\nInterventional radiology (IR) often plays a key role in the care of patients with esophageal perforations. IR techniques are used to control surrounding infections by draining retained collections. Although these interventions commonly supplement other procedures, there are times when these are the only treatments needed, such as a percutaneous drain placed as close to, but typically not into, the injury. Although a more definitive esophageal salivary diversion is more efficient, in a clinically stable patient a well-placed IR drain can be enough to control sepsis and divert the salivary stream. As long as the patient is kept NPO, the esophageal mucosa will typically heal quickly in these situations. In some cases, the mucosa heals around the drain creating a tract and eventual spit fistula. These fistula tracts will typically heal if the surrounding contamination is well drained and the volume going through it is low. Finally, in some institutions, IR can place percutaneous feeding tubes if necessary.\n\n### Flexible Endoscopic Management\n\nThe management of esophageal perforations with endoscopy has grown exponentially in the past years. These endoscopic techniques can be grouped into three major categories: stenting, drainage, and defect closure. The most used and well-studied endoscopic intervention for esophageal perforation is stenting. In the 1990s self-expanding metal stents were first introduced for the treatment of malignant strictures. Since then, fully covered stents became available, and are increasingly used for perforations as they can reliably divert saliva away from esophageal defects. Along with adequate external drainage, this can allow for healing of the defect. The keys to stent placement and avoiding migration are selecting the appropriate size such that it abuts the circumferential lumen of the esophagus and covers the entirety of the defect, and ensuring adequate seal on the proximal and distal landing zones. To ensure this, the stent should be at least 5 cm proximal to the defect ( Fig. 39.4 ). Additionally, as prior studies have shown, stent failure was much more likely in the proximal cervical esophagus and the gastroesophageal junction, or if the defect was >6 cm. Thus, we encourage careful clinical evaluation for successful stent placement. Once confirmed in place and ongoing leakage ruled out on contrast study, a diet can be initiated. Stents are typically left in place for 3\u20136 weeks prior to removal ( Fig. 39.5 ). Stent complications are typically minor and the most common is stent migration. However, serious complications such as erosion, development of tracheoesophageal fistula, and bleeding have been documented.\n\nA radiographic scan depicts esophageal perforation labeled A and the placement of an endoscopic stent labeled B. #REF!\n\nFig. 39.4\n\nAn endoscopic view depicts various stages of esophageal perforation and stent placement. Part A depicts extensive tissue damage within the esophagus that indicates severe perforation. Part B displays a hole in the esophageal wall, which validates the presence of the perforation. Part C depicts the placement of a stent inside the esophagus, which supports the damaged tissue and promotes rehabilitation. Part D illustrates the rehabilitation process with the esophagus, which depicts signs of improvement after intervention.\n\nFig. 39.5\n\nEndoscopic drainage procedures can allow for perforations to heal without the need for external drainage. In the setting of a very small perforation with an associated extramural fluid collection, a double pigtail drain (biliary stent) can be placed to allow the adjacent cavity to drain internally and collapse on itself ( Fig. 39.6 ). Another option for endoscopic treatments is primary closure of esophageal perforations, which are best performed on small or linear tears found early before swelling and fibrosis have developed. As such, these techniques are best employed acutely, as closure techniques become more difficult with friable, difficult tissue. Devices available for primary endoscopic closure include over-the-scope clips ( Fig. 39.7 ), through-the-scope clips, endoscopic purse-string devices, and endoscopic suturing devices.\n\nAn endoscopic view depicts esophageal issues and treatment like lesions, stent placement, tissue damage, dilation, and therapeutic intervention. Part A depicts abnormal growths or lesions in the esophagus, with marked regions that mark areas of concern. Part B reveals a stent inside the esophagus to assist recovery. Part C highlights tissue damage or ulceration in the esophageal wall. Part D features a balloon dilation device to expand a narrowed section of the esophagus. Part E illustrates an esophageal configuration, possibly used for diagnostic or treatment plans. Part F depicts a therapeutic intervention, potentially for maintenance and ways to cure the esophageal function.\n\nFig. 39.6\n\nTwo photos show endoscopic views of esophageal perforation and defects. The photos are labeled A and B for the procedures of esophageal perforation and damages. Part A consists of the endoscopic view of esophageal lesions. Some tissue damage and ulceration are in Part B. A pair of photos of computed tomography and fluoroscopic scans of esophageal perforation and defects. Part C depicts a computed tomography scan with damages and air blocks formed in the scanned part. A fluoroscopic view of esophageal perforation and contrast leakage is described in Part D.\n\nFig. 39.7\n\nLastly, for larger defects endoluminal vacuum therapy has been described. A vacuum sponge on the end of a flexible nasogastric tube is advanced through the luminal defect and into the adjacent wound cavity, with continuous negative pressure applied to the nasogastric tube. This simultaneously drains the cavity while also allowing it to collapse and stimulates the production of granulation tissue and neovascularization. This is described in Chapter 36 .\n\n### Surgical Management of Esophageal Perforations\n\nThere are three options for surgical management: repair, resection, and diversion. Primary repair is the gold standard, especially in patients who present within 24 hours. Depending on the location of the injury, laparoscopic or thoracoscopic surgery can be used to primarily close a defect with a flap ( Fig. 39.8 ) or primary suturing ( Fig. 39.9 ). Cervical perforations are approached via an incision along the left sternocleidomastoid, the proximal/mid-thoracic esophagus through the right chest, and the distal thoracic esophagus through the left chest or transabdominally. The key steps to a successful repair are debridement of non-viable tissue, extending the esophageal myotomy to expose the extent of the mucosal injury, a multilayered repair, and wide drainage. In stable patients, repairs can be buttressed by a flap of healthy tissue (intercostal muscle, pleura, or strap muscle) if necessary. In delayed presentations, another option is repair over a T tube to create a controlled esophago-cutaneous fistula, which diverts the flow and helps control sepsis. In extensive injuries not amenable to repair or with known underlying pathology which would require resection, primary esophagectomy should be considered ( Fig. 39.10 ). In these cases, reconstruction should be deferred, and a cervical esophagostomy created at the time of resection due to the risk of reconstruction in a contaminated field. Another option in these patients is esophageal exclusion and diversion. This is done by creating a cervical esophagostomy and stapled division of the esophagus distal to the injury. An open approach is required if the characteristics of the injury and surrounding contamination exceed the technical skill or hospital resources for a less invasive approach. If patient transfer to a higher-level facility is not possible, an open approach to stabilize the patient and control contamination may be necessary and life-saving. Lastly, Boerhaave syndrome represents a unique scenario. These perforations are generally approached transabdominally with reduction of the hernia to expose the full extent of the injury. In a stable patient with minimal contamination endoscopic repair can be considered, although there may be difficulty closing the defect inside of a hernia and with positioning a stent across the gastroesophageal junction. Often a more invasive laparoscopic, or sometimes open approach, is the more efficient and effective treatment.\n\nA photo depicts the steps of the pleural flap procedure for esophageal repair. The photo depicts the surgical steps to raise and use a pleural flap for esophageal repair. In part A, the pleural flap is raised as part of the preparatory procedure, with the pleura lifted and ready to be repositioned. Part B depicts the pleural flap in place, positioned to cover the damaged area of the esophagus. In part C, the flap is sutured securely to ensure proper rehabilitation and closure of the esophageal defect, which completes the surgical intervention.\n\nFig. 39.8\n\nA diagram depicts the extent of the mucosal tear and the appearance of normal submucosa for the esophageal injury. The diagram depicts the identification and assessment of an esophageal mucosal tear. In part A, the diagram depicts the extent of the mucosal tear with pouting mucosa, where the mucosal layer is bulged outward. This damage is identified with curved surgical instruments. In part B, the appearance of the normal submucosa is highlighted, which presents the healthy tissue layers beneath the mucosa, with a distinction from the torn mucosal area. The lower inset further zooms in to reveal the pouting mucosa, which provides a closer view of the damage for examination.\n\nFig. 39.9\n\nA photo depicts a medical scan that depicts computed tomography scans and endoscopic views of a tumor removal procedure. The photo depicts a series of medical scans with a computed tomography scan on the top left that presents a growth near the chest area. It is followed by endoscopic views on the top right, bottom left, and bottom right that depict a surgical procedure for tumor removal. The scans depict different tumor angles. A closure view of the area to be operated on and the tools used to extract the growth are also present in the views.\n\nFig. 39.10\n\n## Conclusion\n\nEsophageal perforations continue to be a challenging disease to treat. Thankfully, a broad and growing spectrum of treatment options exist and can be applied to the key tenets of management. After stabilization, the three principles of controlling sepsis, diversion of the salivary stream, and addressing nutrition provide an overall framework to guide management. With frequent clinical assessments and a willingness to escalate care when indicated, historically devastating outcomes can be avoided.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Barrett N.R.: Report of a case of spontaneous perforation of the oesophagus successfully treated by operation . Br J Surg 1947; 35: pp. 218.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Kuwano H., Yokobori T., Kumakura Y., et al.: Pathophysiology of vomiting and esophageal perforation in Boerhaave\u2019s syndrome . Dig Dis Sci 2020; 65 (11): pp. 3253-3259.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: Sdralis E.I.K., Petousis S., Rashid F., Lorenzi B., Charalabopoulos A.: Epidemiology, diagnosis, and management of esophageal perforations: systematic review . Dis Esophagus 2017; 30 (8): pp. 1-6.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Wei C.J., Levenson R.B., Lee K.S.: Diagnostic utility of CT and fluoroscopic esophagography for suspected esophageal perforation in the Emergency Department . AJR Am J Roentgenol 2020; 215 (3): pp. 631-638.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: Dellinger R.P., Levy M.M., Carlet J.M., et al.: Surviving Sepsis Campaign: International guidelines for management of severe sepsis and septic shock: 2008 . Intensive Care Med 2008; 34: pp. 17-60.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n6.: Cameron J.L., Kieffer R.F., Hendrix T.R., Mehigan D.G., Baker R.R.: Selective nonoperative management of contained intrathoracic esophageal disruptions . Ann Thorac Surg 1979; 27 (5): pp. 404-408.\n\nView In Article\n\n7.: Reintam B.A., Starkopf J., Alhazzani W., et al.: Early enteral nutrition in critically ill patients: ESICM clinical practice guidelines . Intensive Care Med 2017; 43: pp. 380-398.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n8.: Abbas G., Schuchert M.J., Pettiford B.L., et al.: Contemporaneous management of esophageal perforation . Surgery 2009; 146 (4): pp. 749-755. discussion 755-756 .\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n9.: Freeman R.K., Ascioti A.J., Giannini T., Mahidhara R.J.: Analysis of unsuccessful esophageal stent placements for esophageal perforation, fistula, or anastomotic leak . Ann Thorac Surg 2012; 94 (3): pp. 959-964. discussion 964-965 .\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n10.: Ong G.K.B., Freeman R.K., Ascioti A.J., et al.: Patient outcomes after stent failure for the treatment of acute esophageal perforation . Ann Thorac Surg 2018; 106 (3): pp. 830-835.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n11.: Watkins J.R., Farivar A.S.: Endoluminal therapies for esophageal perforations and leaks . Thorac Surg Clin 2018; 28 (4): pp. 541-554.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n12.: Kaman L., Iqbal J., Kundil B., Kochhar R.: Management of esophageal perforation in adults . Gastroenterology Res 2010; 3 (6): pp. 235-244.\n\nView In Article\n\n13.: Grillo H.C., Wilkins F.W.: Esophageal repair following late diagnosis of intrathoracic perforation . Ann Thorac Cardiovasc Surg 1975; 20: pp. 337. by permission of the Society of Thoracic Surgeons .\n\nView In Article\n\n14.: Whyte R.I., Iannettoni M.D., Orringer M.B.: Intrathoracic esophageal perforation: the merit of primary repair . J Thorac Cardiovasc Surg 1995; 109: pp. 140.\n\nView In Article\n\nPrevious ChapterGo to the previous chapter\n\nNext ChapterGo to the next chapter\n\n\n\n## Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract\n\nNinth Edition\n\nCopyright \u00a9 2026 by Elsevier Inc. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies.\n\n## Get rights and content\u00a0\n\n##\n\n281240\n\n  - Google Play - Go to our Google Play page\n  - Apple App Store - Go to our Apple App Store page\n  - Facebook - Go to our Facebook page\n  - LinkedIn - Go to our LinkedIn page\n  - X - Go to our X page\n\nElsevier (opens in a new window)\n\n  - Contact Us (opens in a new window)\n  - Res