-.3%200-.517-.3-.5-.6V7zm47.7%2036.7c-.4%200-.6-.2-.8-.5l-7.3-12.7-7.4%2012.7c-.2.3-.4.5-.8.5h-5.8c-.3%200-.5-.3-.3-.7L166%2024.3%20156%207.1c-.2-.4%200-.7.3-.7h5.8c.4%200%20.6.1.8.5l6.5%2011.3h.1L176%206.9c.2-.4.5-.5.9-.5h5.7c.4%200%20.5.3.3.7l-10%2017.2L183.7%2043c.2.4%200%20.7-.3.7h-5.8zM192.015%2019c-.2%200-.338-.004-.3-.2V8.4h-3.3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[38. Palliative Therapy for Esophageal Cancer - ClinicalKey|38. Palliative Therapy for Esophageal Cancer]]\n**Next:** [[40. Submucosal Tumors in the Esophagus and Gastroesophageal Junction - ClinicalKey|40. Submucosal Tumors in the Esophagus and Gastroesophageal Junction]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "39. Management of Esophageal Perforation - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Management of Esophageal Perforation', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Management of Esophageal Perforation', 'Etiology', 'Presentation', 'Diagnosis', 'Guiding Principles for Management', 'Management of Esophageal Perforations', 'Management of Esophageal Perforation / Etiology', 'Management of Esophageal Perforation / Presentation', 'Management of Esophageal Perforation / Diagnosis'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '39', '413-421', 2, 24, FALSE, TRUE),
('pH and Impedance Evaluation of the Esophagus', 'shackelford-9th-ed-4-ph-and-impedance-evaluation-of-the-esophagus', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# pH and Impedance Evaluation of the Esophagus\n\nGeoffrey P. Kohn\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 4, 33-43\n\nGastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) is a very common global disorder that poses a significant public health burden. GERD affects approximately 20% of the population of the Western world, all age groups and both females and males, with similar prevalence rates reported across many countries. GERD has been ranked as the fourth most prevalent gastrointestinal disease and the most expensive disease of the alimentary tract, with expenditure estimated at >US$10 billion/year in the United States alone.\n\nThere can be no standard diagnostic criteria for the definition of GERD because the threshold distinction between physiologic reflux and reflux disease is arbitrary. The Montreal Consensus panel of experts in this field has defined GERD as \u201ca condition which develops when the reflux of stomach contents causes troublesome symptoms and/or complications.\u201d\n\nPatients with GERD may report \u201ctypical\u201d symptoms of heartburn and regurgitation. The regurgitation is often acidic in nature leading to the sour taste of water brash. \u201cAtypical\u201d symptoms may also be reported and include chest pain and respiratory symptoms of cough and wheeze and dysphonia. Extraesophageal manifestation of reflux disease may result from direct action of the primary refluxate or may be due to complications of GERD and include dysphagia, pneumonia, and sinusitis.\n\nIt is problematic to define a disease based on symptoms that are not specific to the disease, and other conditions may manifest similar symptoms to GERD. In such conditions, antireflux therapy may be unhelpful. Therefore, objective assessment of GERD is often required, with ambulatory pH evaluation being the most widely used technique. However this, and other, reflux monitoring demonstrates the consequence of GERD pathophysiology, evident as either excessive esophageal acid exposure time (AET) or reflux episodes, rather than the mechanism by which that occurs. Perhaps one of the most important roles of pH testing is in the diagnosis of a patient considering antireflux surgery. Particularly with typical heartburn and regurgitation symptoms of reflux, a good patient outcome from antireflux surgery can be predicted by an abnormal preoperative pH study, and unsatisfactory outcomes are much more likely if surgery is performed after a normal pH study. This is due to the reasonably high specificity of typical symptoms for GERD and the excellent reflux control of antireflux procedures.\n\n## Indications for pH Testing\n\nFor patients with the typical symptoms of reflux, symptom relief may be obtained with lifestyle changes of weight loss, avoidance of refluxogenic foods, and avoidance of the full recumbent position, particularly in the postprandial period. For others, a therapeutic trial of acid-suppressive medications such as proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) may suffice, after excluding alternative pathologies. Some clinical practice guidelines recommend empirical trials of PPIs instead of pH testing. The favorable side-effect profile of PPIs has encouraged this initial step although the sensitivity and specificity of this approach as a diagnostic test for GERD are quite low at 71% and 44%, respectively, when compared with endoscopy or pH studies. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Indeed, on average, 69% of patients with esophagitis, 49% of patients with nonerosive reflux disease (NERD), and 35% of patients with normal endoscopy and pH-metry gain symptom relief from a PPI trial. Moreover, a clinical history of typical symptoms, even if obtained by an expert gastroenterologist, reaches at most about 70% sensitivity and specificity compared with pH testing or endoscopy. Therefore, it is prudent to objectively document gastroesophageal reflux before considering invasive procedures such as antireflux surgery. Conclusive endoscopic evidence includes esophagitis with \u201cmucosal breaks\u201d seen at esophagoscopy and graded by the Los Angeles classification as grades C or D; that is, at a minimum, an erosion or erosions extending over mucosal folds, but over less than three-quarters of the circumference; or Barrett\u2019s metaplasia > 1 cm; or the reflux-related complication of peptic esophageal stricture. Lesser degrees of endoscopically visible esophagitis, Los Angeles grades A and B, may be considered to be \u201cborderline\u201d or \u201cinconclusive\u201d evidence of GERD, with the diagnosis being supported by other adjunctive findings. In the absence of endoscopic evidence of reflux, objective evidence can be obtained by 24-hour ambulatory pH measurement of the esophagus. The presence of an abnormal 24-hour pH test has been shown to be the strongest predictor of a good outcome after antireflux surgery. Additionally, pH monitoring is useful in the evaluation of patients with persisting reflux symptoms despite medical or surgical therapy.\n\n## Catheter-Based pH Monitoring\n\nThe conventional catheter-based pH monitoring system principally consists of a flexible catheter with one or more pH sensors and a data recorder. The catheter is passed through the nose, along the posterior wall of the pharynx, and is placed with the pH sensor in the distal esophagus. It is connected to a data recorder, which is carried by the patient during the study. Ambulatory catheter-based pH monitoring is generally performed over a 24-hour period, as a complete circadian cycle allows for determining the effect of physical activity and body positions on esophageal acid exposure, as well as allowing for an increased detection of symptoms for the calculation of symptom associations.\n\nIn general, esophageal pH monitoring is carried out while the patient is off acid-suppressive medication. Patients are normally instructed to discontinue the use of PPIs at least 7 days prior, histamine H <sub>2 </sub> \\-antagonists 5 days prior, and simple antacids 24 hours prior to the investigation. Only when the aim of the study is to measure the esophageal acid exposure that persists during treatment should acid suppressants be continued.\n\nDuring the study, patients are instructed to keep a diary and to record symptoms, mealtimes, and times of supine and upright postures. Meal periods can be excluded from the analysis to avoid potential artifacts produced by acidic meal ingestion and this may improve the clinical reliability of the test. The activity and the diet of the patient during the study should ideally be identical to that of the control population from which the normative values of esophageal acid exposure were developed. Some centers encourage the patient to eat those food products known by the patient to be likely to precipitate their symptoms, so-called \u201cchallenge meals.\u201d\n\nThe catheter-based technique for esophageal pH monitoring has the disadvantage of causing social embarrassment and discomfort in the nose and throat. Consequently, the test is not tolerated by all patients. These adverse symptoms may lead to interference with daily activities and eating and interruption of normal sleep, possibly leading to underestimation of reflux related to physical activity and meals and hampering the evaluation of nocturnal reflux. The placement of the catheter itself across the lower esophageal sphincter (LES) does not induce reflux.\n\n## Wireless pH Monitoring\n\nSome of the limitations of the catheter-based technique have been avoided with the introduction of the catheter-free, wireless pH system (Bravo; Medtronic). In addition to improved patient comfort and less effect on reflux-provoking activities, the capsule-based pH system has the advantages of fixed placement of the pH electrode, minimizing the risk of slipping into the stomach, and allowing for prolonged recordings. The longer duration of pH monitoring has been suggested to increase the sensitivity of reflux monitoring in identifying patients with gastroesophageal reflux. Contraindications for the use of the Bravo capsule are hemorrhagic diathesis, esophageal varices, severe esophagitis, pregnancy, and patients with a pacemaker or a defibrillator. The delivery system for the pH capsule is most commonly passed transorally after completion of an upper endoscopy. Placement of the capsule is based on the endoscopic location of the gastroesophageal junction. Some centers recommend that application should be performed under direct endoscopic vision and not blindly after the endoscopy. The pH capsule can also be placed transnasally without prior endoscopy by using manometric localization of the LES. The capsule should be positioned 6 cm above the gastroesophageal junction identified endoscopically if placed transorally or 5 cm above the upper border of the manometrically determined LES if placed transnasally.\n\nThe pH system consists of a capsule attached to the end of a catheter delivery system and a telemetry receiver ( Fig. 4.1 ). The capsule has a pH electrode and a reference electrode located on the distal tip and contains an internal battery and a transmitter ( Fig. 4.2 ). The capsule has a well that is connected to a vacuum unit, which is activated when suction is applied via the delivery system. The capsule is attached at the desired position in the esophagus by suctioning the mucosa into the well of the capsule and securing by a locking pin. After positioning, the capsule is released from the delivery system. The capsule simultaneously measures and transmits pH data using radiotelemetry to the portable receiver. The patient is instructed to remain within 6 ft (2 m) of the recorder during the study period to ensure effective telemetry signal strength. The capsule is designed to detach in 3 to 7 days and then pass through the gastrointestinal tract. There are reports of the probe remaining attached for longer periods usually without consequence but sometimes requiring endoscopic removal.\n\nA photo of a medical device with a flexible catheter regulated by a vacuum connection and an activation button in a capsule at its distal end. The proximal end consists of sensors. A data recording device collects the data from the catheter.\n\nFig. 4.1\n\nThe Bravo capsule is a small, cylindrical medical device and measures around 3 centimeters. The bravo capsule consists of a tiny sensor labeled pH electrode at the distal end. A transmitter is integrated within the capsule, followed by a battery installed to power the device. The proximal end of the capsule contains a small compartment labeled well.\n\nFig. 4.2\n\nWireless esophageal pH monitoring is associated with fewer adverse symptoms and less interference with normal daily activities and is preferred by patients, though there are limitations associated with the wireless technique. The wireless pH capsule is associated with thoracic discomfort in 10% to 65% of the patients. The severity of chest symptoms ranges from a mild foreign-body sensation to severe chest pain, although the latter is uncommon. In rare cases, the pain is so severe that endoscopic removal of the capsule is necessary.\n\n## Duration of pH Monitoring\n\nThe standard duration of recording is 24 hours for catheter-based esophageal pH testing and 48 hours for the wireless pH system, though approximately 10% of wireless probes detach prior to the completion of this period. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The reported proportion of successful wireless pH recordings of at least 36 hours range from 89% to 96%. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nRecording of pH data from the wireless capsule is commonly carried out over a period of 48 hours but may be extended to even longer periods of time. The extended recording capabilities of the wireless pH system compared with the conventional catheter-based technique appear to increase the sensitivity of the test. Studies have demonstrated that by increasing the pH recording time from 24 to 48 hours, the yield of the procedure increases in capturing more abnormal pH tests or symptom-associated reflux events.\n\nThe 48-hour data can be interpreted using an average of the 2 days, or alternatively using only the 24-hour period with the greatest acid exposure, termed \u201cworst day analysis.\u201d A significant increase in the sensitivity of the pH testing is seen, together with a small decrease in specificity, when using the worst day data compared with either 24-hour data or averaged 48-hour data.\n\n## pH Electrode Placement\n\nConsistent positioning of the pH electrode is vital for obtaining reliable esophageal pH data and for comparison with normal values. By convention, the catheter-based pH electrode is placed 5 cm above the manometrically defined upper border of the LES. This position should avoid inadvertent dislocation of the electrode into the stomach during breathing, movements induced by changes in body position, or swallow-induced esophageal shortening. Thus, to determine this location, esophageal manometry must be performed prior to the pH study. Placement based on the pH profile recorded on withdrawal of the electrode from the stomach has been found to be inferior to placement based on manometric LES localization.\n\nIn wireless esophageal pH monitoring, the pH sensor is most commonly placed according to endoscopic landmarks. By convention, the electrode is placed 6 cm above gastroesophageal junction. For patients without columnar metaplasia, this can reliably be identified by the squamocolumnar junction (SCJ). This position has been derived from the findings of concurrent manometry and fluoroscopy studies, suggesting that the upper border of the LES high-pressure zone typically extends 1 to 1.5 cm above the SCJ. Positioning the pH electrode 6 cm above the SCJ therefore approximates the standard 5 cm above the upper border of the manometrically defined LES electrode position of the catheter-based technique. Transnasal placement of the pH capsule normally requires prior manometry, as the electrode is positioned 5 cm above the upper border of the LES. Although controversial, a conversion factor of 4 cm can be applied to approximate the extra distance between the nares and the oropharynx.\n\n## Interpretation of Esophageal pH Studies\n\nDue to swallowed saliva and esophageal bicarbonate secretion, esophageal pH is normally maintained between pH 5 and pH 7. Gastric acid secretion generates a highly acidic environment within the stomach, with a pH of 1 to 2, and rarely more than 3. During esophageal pH monitoring ( Fig. 4.3 ), gastroesophageal reflux events are detected as abrupt declines in intraesophageal pH. Generally, episodes where pH falls below 4 are taken as evidence of reflux events. The choice of the cutoff of pH 4 is supported by the observation that patients with symptomatic reflux usually report heartburn at an intraesophageal pH below this threshold. When the pH recording is complete, the software generates a report that includes a graphical pH tracing, reflux parameters, and symptom-reflux correlations ( Fig. 4.4 ). In the analysis of esophageal pH tracings, the pattern of acid reflux provides important information. Physiologic acid reflux seen in healthy subjects is characterized by rapidly cleared reflux episodes that occur in the upright position most commonly after a meal, and acid reflux rarely occurs while supine. In patients with mild reflux disease, more reflux episodes occur. The pattern of early reflux is typically increased reflux events in the upright and postprandial time period. With increasing severity of GERD, acid reflux increases first in the upright position, and thereafter typically becomes bi-positional, with acid reflux in both the upright and supine postures. Both the duration and number of acid reflux episodes are known to increase, resulting in prolonged esophageal AETs as GERD progresses. As such, supine reflux is associated with more severe disease.\n\nA line graph of data over time, with the horizontal axis labeled with time intervals, represents overall fluctuations with a significant sharp drop. The line graph depicts the distal esophagus''s potential for hydrogen levels over time. The horizontal axis denotes the time in hours. The vertical axis denotes the pH levels that range from 0 to 1 point 6. The line graph shows the fluctuation in potential of hydrogen levels over time, with sudden plunge between ten twenty four A M and ten twenty six A M.\n\nFig. 4.3\n\nA graph with potential hydrogen fluctuations over time and various statistical tables on acid reflux analysis that include total duration, symptom analysis, and DeMeester score components. The graph displays the potential of hydrogen levels from 0 to 8 over 24 hours with acid reflux episodes shown as spikes below the potential of hydrogen 4. Annotations highlight upright, supine, and total time with a potential of hydrogen less than 4. A table below the graph includes four columns, parameter, result, normal value, and interpretation. It lists total time with the potential of hydrogen less than 4, standing and supine time with the potential of hydrogen less than 4, number of reflux episodes, episodes greater than five minutes, longest episode, and the DeMeester score. This analysis helps assess acid reflux severity and its correlation with body position over time.\n\nFig. 4.4\n\nThe total percentage of time the pH is less than 4, the acid exposure time (AET), is the most useful single discriminator between physiologic and pathologic reflux. The AET is reproducible and predictive of response to both medical and surgical therapy. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> An abnormal test is defined by a value greater than an established threshold, which is typically the 95th percentile of normal controls. The normal values for ambulatory pH monitoring in adults reported in the literature vary widely because of differences in the selection and the age and sex distribution of the control population. Table 4.1 shows reports on normal data for catheter-based and capsule-based pH monitoring. Irrespective of the values selected, the significance of an abnormal AET is proportionate to the degree of abnormality. The recent Lyon international consensus document proposes that AET <4% be considered physiological and AET between 4% and 6% being inconclusive. The Lyon and other consensus statements consider an AET >6% as being definitive evidence of GERD, though a lower AET might be considered pathological in certain, particularly Asian, populations.\n\nTable 4.1\n\nReports on Normal Values for 24-Hour Catheter-Based and 48-Hour Wireless pH Monitoring\n\n<table><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\"></th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Author</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Number of Subjects</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Male/Female</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Median Age (Range)</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Upper Limit of Normal (%)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align=\"\" rowspan=\"4\"><b>Catheter-based</b></td><td align=\"\">Richter et al. <button><sup>85</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">110</td><td align=\"\">47/63</td><td align=\"\">30 (20\u201384)</td><td align=\"\">5.8</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Jamieson et al. <button><sup>86</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">50</td><td align=\"\">20/30</td><td align=\"\">\u2013</td><td align=\"\">4.5</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Johnsson et al. <button><sup>87</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">50</td><td align=\"\">18/32</td><td align=\"\">38 (30\u201377)</td><td align=\"\">3.4</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Johnson &amp; DeMeester <button><sup>47</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">15</td><td align=\"\">\u2013</td><td align=\"\">\u2013</td><td align=\"\">4.2</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\" rowspan=\"3\"><b>Capsule-based</b></td><td align=\"\">Wenner et al. <button><sup>25</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">50</td><td align=\"\">25/25</td><td align=\"\">42 (22\u201365)</td><td align=\"\">4.34</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Ayazi et al. <button><sup>26</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">48</td><td align=\"\">\u2013</td><td align=\"\">\u2013</td><td align=\"\">4.8</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Pandolfino et al. <button><sup>24</sup></button></td><td align=\"\">36</td><td align=\"\">\u2013</td><td align=\"\">\u2013</td><td align=\"\">5.4</td></tr></tbody></table>\n\nAnother method of presenting esophageal acid exposure data is calculation of a composite score, originally proposed by Johnson and DeMeester. The composite score is commonly referred to as the DeMeester Score (DMS) and accounts for six different parameters: (1) total percent time pH less than 4.0; (2) percent time pH less than 4.0 in the upright period; (3) percent time pH less than 4.0 in the recumbent period; (4) the total number of reflux episodes; (5) the total number of reflux episodes longer than 5 minutes; and (6) the duration of the longest reflux episode. The score is automatically calculated and reported in most commercially available pH software. The most referenced value for an abnormal DMS is a value larger than 14.7. Regardless of whether the composite score or individual AET is used, a detailed evaluation of the pH tracing is of fundamental importance to recognize and exclude artifacts, including stasis, and to assess symptom association.\n\n## Symptom Association\n\nReflux symptoms such as heartburn and regurgitation are very common; however, as these symptoms are not very specific for GERD, it is important to be able to determine if there is a temporal relationship between symptoms and reflux events.\n\nThe relationship between symptoms and reflux episodes can be expressed numerically using symptom association analysis. The most frequently used indices are the symptom index (SI), the symptom sensitivity index (SSI), and the symptom association probability (SAP).\n\nThe SI is the percentage of symptoms preceded by a drop in esophageal pH below 4 within a 5-minute time window divided by the total number of symptoms. The SI can be calculated for each symptom attributable to reflux, including heartburn, regurgitation, or an atypical symptom, such as chest pain or respiratory symptoms. A positive symptom association is declared if the SI is greater than or equal to 50% (i.e., at least half of the reported symptoms are preceded within the time window by an intraesophageal pH below 4). Over the years, the definition and use of the SI have been challenged. Based on a sensitivity analysis in patients with chest pain, it has been proposed to use a shorter, 2-minute time window after the onset of a reflux episode in which a symptom has to occur in order for it to be considered associated with reflux.\n\nThe SSI is defined as the percentage of symptoms associated with reflux events. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The SI does not consider the total number of reflux episodes, and the SSI does not include the total number of symptom events. As a consequence, the probability that the SI becomes positive increases with an increasingly high number of reflux episodes and SSI is more likely to be positive when the number of symptom episodes is high. An SSI greater than 10% is usually considered positive and suggests an association between symptom and reflux.\n\nThe SAP is a statistical method to determine the relationship between symptoms and reflux episodes. The SAP is calculated by dividing the entire study\u2019s pH data into consecutive 2-minute segments. For each of these segments, it is determined whether reflux occurred in the segment, allowing for calculation of the total number of 2-minute segments with and without reflux. Subsequently, it is determined whether or not a reflux episode occurred in the 2-minute period before each symptom. A 2\u00d72 contingency table is constructed in which the number of 2-minute segments with and without symptoms and with and without reflux are tabulated. Using the Fisher exact test, a *P* value is calculated and the SAP index is calculated as (1 \u2212 *P* ) \u00d7 100%. The cutoff value for a positive test is often defined as SAP \u226595%. However, even a statistically significant relationship between reflux events and symptoms does not necessarily imply causality. The yield of the SI and SAP is greater when performed off- rather than on-acid-suppressive therapy.\n\nBoth the SI and SAP are predictive, though far from perfectly, of the effect of GERD therapy, independent of AET. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> However, symptom scores alone are not specific enough to justify an operation.\n\n## pH Testing On- Versus Off-Acid-Suppressive Medication\n\nEsophageal pH testing provides objective evidence of abnormal acid exposure in the distal esophagus. Testing can be done with or without acid suppression medication. Testing off-therapy is recommended for patients in whom there is a low index of clinical suspicion for GERD in order to \u201crule out\u201d reflux as a cause of the symptoms. In this indication, esophageal pH testing without medication is more accurate, and a negative result (i.e., normal distal esophageal pH with negative symptom association) is very helpful in suggesting that the symptoms are not caused by acid reflux. The Lyon Consensus proposes that testing always be performed off-therapy to demonstrate distal esophageal AET in \u201cunproven GERD,\u201d that is in patients with no (or low-grade) esophagitis at endoscopy and with no prior abnormal pH testing. This recommendation is widely supported by other international societies. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nHowever, objective esophageal acid exposure while on acid suppression is useful for patients with persistent symptoms despite medication. Therefore, on-therapy testing is commonly used to evaluate patients with refractory reflux symptoms despite medical therapy, or to exclude inadequate acid suppression or poor compliance as the mechanism of persisting symptoms, An abnormal esophageal pH test (i.e., increased amount of distal esophageal acid exposure with therapy and a positive symptom association for acid reflux) performed during therapy is helpful because it suggests that the acid suppression may be insufficient. In these situations, the use of dual pH electrodes to monitor both distal esophageal and gastric pH is sometimes recommended, especially for patients unresponsive to antireflux therapy ( Fig. 4.5 ). Although intragastric pH measurement can help determine the efficacy of acid-suppressive medications or suggest poor patient compliance, its clinical relevance is unclear because there is a paucity of data showing a correlation between intragastric pH and gastroesophageal reflux. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> A negative esophageal pH test while receiving therapy cannot exclude nonacidic or weakly acidic reflux being associated with the residual symptoms. This assessment therefore requires combining intraluminal impedance studies (see below) with pH testing to address this issue.\n\nA waveform graph represents the intensity levels and fluctuations in a process over a specific period. The waveform graph shows the potential of hydrogen levels from 0 to 14 over 3 hour intervals. It records the supine and symptoms below the horizontal axis. The lower channel trend labeled pH 2 consists of more fluctuations in comparison to the upper channel of pH 1.\n\nFig. 4.5\n\n## Proximal Esophageal pH Assessment\n\nProximal pH testing is more commonly indicated as an adjunct to distal esophageal pH testing when a patient has atypical symptoms. Atypical esophageal symptoms, such as cough, globus sensation, dysphonia, throat pain, and respiratory symptoms are less specific for GERD, but if due to GERD may arise from proximal extension of the refluxate. Distal esophageal pH monitoring will be less helpful in these circumstances, and some newer technologies of proximal esophageal pH assessment and multichannel intraluminal impedance (MII) studies may be of use, Most probes for the measurement of pH require liquid to be presented to the sensor for accurate measurement. Drying of the pH sensor, for example, when the pH sensor is placed in the hypopharynx or proximal esophagus, can cause artifacts in the pH recording. Certain sensors such as the Dx-pH probe (Restech) allow for measurement of aerosolized pH, allowing placement of the probe in the oropharynx to diagnose reflux as the cause of respiratory and laryngeal symptoms. However, there are concerns about the accuracy of this probe since detection of pharyngeal pH drops in the absence of accompanying esophageal pH-impedance events has been reported, even in patients with previous total gastrectomy, <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Overall, proximal pH testing may provide some information regarding the likelihood that GERD is associated with atypical symptoms but cannot provide a definitive indication for therapy.\n\n## Multichannel Intraluminal Impedance\n\nFirst described in 1991, MII is a technique for evaluating esophageal bolus transit during swallowing and for monitoring gastroesophageal reflux independent of its pH. The presence and movement of an intraesophageal bolus is detected by MII based on measuring differences in electrical conductivity affected by the presence of various materials within the esophagus. An MII catheter requires an alternating current source connected to a series of metal rings located along the segments of the esophageal lumen. An isolator separates the rings so that the electrical circuit is closed by the electrical charges surrounding the catheter. The impedance within a given segment is then determined by measuring the electrical resistance as a substance passes through the current established by the rings.\n\nLiquid boluses conduct better than the empty esophagus, leading to a rapid decline in intraluminal impedance when the bolus enters the impedance measuring segment. Impedance returns to baseline once the bolus has exited the segment. Multiple impedance measuring segments mounted on the same catheter allow determination of the direction of bolus movement based on the timing of changes in impedance at individual levels. Proximal to distal (antegrade) progression of impedance changes is indicative of swallowing ( Fig. 4.6 ), whereas a distal to proximal (retrograde) progression indicates reflux episodes ( Fig. 4.7 ).\n\nAn impedance waveform shows the downward antegrade of various intensities over time along with minor fluctuations in the potential of Hydrogen levels around five point two. #REF!\n\nFig. 4.6\n\nAn impedance trace shows smooth retrograde consistent with the smooth red waveform and uneven retrograde with a sudden plunge in the red waveform. #REF!\n\nFig. 4.7\n\nImpedance sensors can be mounted on a regular pH catheter; such combined MII-pH measurement has several advantages in monitoring gastroesophageal reflux and is the most sensitive test to detect reflux of all types, whether acid or nonacid. Gastroesophageal reflux episodes are detected by retrograde declines in intraluminal impedance produced by increased conductivity of the liquid reflux, whereas data from the esophageal pH sensor are simply used to categorize the reflux into acid or nonacid. The refluxate can further be differentiated by MII/pH into acidic if the pH drops from above to below 4, weakly acidic if the pH is between 4 and 7, and nonacidic if the intraesophageal pH during an MII-detected reflux episode remains above 7.\n\nIn addition to the chemical properties of the gastroesophageal refluxate, MII has the ability to determine its physical state; MII can differentiate between liquid only, gas only, and mixed gas-liquid reflux episodes based on changes in intraluminal impedance. Gas or air has very poor electrical conductivity and, when present between impedance-measuring rings, will produce a rise in impedance; in contrast, liquid, which has better electrical conductivity, will produce a decline in impedance.\n\nNonacid reflux (i.e., an impedance-detected reflux episode with a pH above 4) is relatively infrequent in subjects not taking acid-suppressive therapy; it occurs primarily in the postprandial periods and rarely at night. However, in subjects taking acid-suppressive therapy, the medications may change the composition of the gastroesophageal refluxate without affecting the total number of gastroesophageal reflux episodes. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Normal values for acid and nonacid reflux in healthy volunteers from multiple centers not receiving acid-suppressive therapy have been published ( Table 4.2 ), as have various population-specific norms. Consensus threshold criteria have also been published, proposing >80 reflux events/24 hours as definitely abnormal and <40 reflux events/24 hours as being physiological. A daily number of events between 40 and 80 is inconclusive.\n\nTable 4.2\n\nThe 24-hour pH/Impedance Normal Values\n\n<table><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\"></th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\" colspan=\"5\">IMPEDANCE PARAMETERS</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\"></th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\" colspan=\"2\">pH PARAMETERS</th></tr><tr><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\"></th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\" colspan=\"2\">All Reflux Episodes</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\" colspan=\"4\">Frequency of Reflux Types</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\"></th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\"></th></tr><tr><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\"></th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Total</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Duration (sec)</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Acid (pH &lt;4)</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Weakly acidic (4\u2264 pH \u22647)</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Nonacid pH &gt;7</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">% Time Bolus Exposure (by Impedance)</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">pH-Only Reflux Events <a href=\">\u2217</a></th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">% Time Acid Exposure</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align=\"\">Total (95th percentile)</td><td align=\"\">73</td><td align=\"\">44</td><td align=\"\">55</td><td align=\"\">26</td><td align=\"\">1</td><td align=\"\">1.4</td><td align=\"\">3</td><td align=\"\">6.3</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Upright (95th percentile)</td><td align=\"\">67</td><td align=\"\">43</td><td align=\"\">52</td><td align=\"\">24</td><td align=\"\">1</td><td align=\"\">2.1</td><td align=\"\">3</td><td align=\"\">9.7</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Supine (95th percentile)</td><td align=\"\">7</td><td align=\"\">51</td><td align=\"\">5</td><td align=\"\">4</td><td align=\"\">0</td><td align=\"\">0.7</td><td align=\"\">1</td><td align=\"\">2.1</td></tr></tbody></table>\n\nNonacid reflux appears to have a role in causing persistent symptoms in patients taking acid-suppressive therapy. There is both direct evidence of postprandial symptoms being associated with nonacid reflux and indirect data from a large PPI trial indicating that 35% to 40% of patients receiving acid-suppressive therapy continue to have symptoms.\n\nCombined MII-pH monitoring of patients with refractory symptoms has been shown to be able to clarify the symptom association with reflux events and has revealed that about 50% of patients with persistent symptoms on such therapy do not have a temporal correlation between their symptoms and any type of reflux, whereas 40% have temporal association between their symptoms and nonacid reflux. A poor symptom correlation provides evidence against reflux as the cause for a patient\u2019s symptoms.\n\nIt is now appreciated that there exists a rare subset of people with normal pH studies but abnormal MII tests that will have good short-term outcomes after fundoplication. The addition of MII testing to standard pH testing may be considered an adjunctive measure to be used when AET is inconclusive (i.e., between 4% and 6%).\n\nFor the aforementioned reasons, MII-pH is being increasingly employed in the assessment of patients with atypical symptoms of GERD. However, the utility of this approach in patients being considered for antireflux surgery remains uncertain, with little evidence demonstrating a prognostic effect on postsurgical outcomes. With studies showing a postfundoplication improvement in extraesophageal symptoms after diagnosis based on pH-only criteria of 15% to 95%, comparison with outcomes of reflux diagnosed by impedance or pH-impedance will be challenging due to the wide range of the results, and these studies are currently lacking.\n\n## Novel Metrics\n\nTwo novel impedance-detected parameters, the postreflux swallow-induced peristaltic wave (PSPW) index and baseline impedance, have been investigated and may augment the diagnostic value of impedance-pH testing, especially in discriminating patients with GERD from those with functional heartburn. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nPSPW is defined as an antegrade 50% drop in impedance occurring within 30 seconds after a reflux event, originating in the most proximal impedance channel, reaching the most distal impedance channel, and followed by at least 50% return to the baseline. Dividing the number of PSPWs by the number of reflux events, the PSPW Index is obtained. The PSPW Index reflects the integrity of primary peristalsis stimulated by reflux episodes and can differentiate erosive esophagitis and pathological acid exposure from functional heartburn and controls (sensitivity 99%\u2013100%, specificity 92%). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nBaseline mucosal impedance reflects the permeability of the esophageal mucosa, with lower values found in erosive and nonerosive GERD. Since frequent swallows impact measurement, assessment is made during sleep as mean nocturnal baseline impedance (MNBI), from the most distal impedance channel during the nighttime recumbent period. Three 10-minute time periods each an hour apart are selected and the mean calculated to obtain the MNBI; time periods including swallows, refluxes, and pH drops are avoided.\n\nThere is some evidence that PSPW index and MNBI can link PPI-responsive heartburn to reflux better than AET and therefore these novel metrics may be considered adjunctive metrics for the diagnosis of GERD.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nObjective confirmation of abnormal reflux is imperative to treating patients with GERD. Ambulatory pH testing remains the gold standard. However, nonacid reflux testing with impedance also has a role particularly in patients with acid suppressive medications. Newer modalities may become more useful in the future.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Fedorak R.N., Veldhuyzen van Zanten S., Bridges R.: Canadian Digestive Health Foundation Public Impact Series: gastroesophageal reflux disease in Canada: incidence, prevalence, and direct and indirect economic impact . Can J Gastroenterol 2010; 24 (7): pp. 431-434.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Locke G.R., Talley N.J., Fett S.L., Zinsmeister A.R., Melton L.J.: Prevalence and clinical spectrum of gastroesophageal reflux: a population-based study in Olmsted County, Minnesota . Gastroenterology 1997; 112 (5): pp. 1448-1456.\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: Mohammed I., Cherkas L.F., Riley S.A., Spector T.D., Trudgill N.J.: Genetic influences in gastro-oesophageal reflux disease: a twin study . Gut 2003; 52 (8): pp. 1085-1089.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Isolauri J., Laippala P.: Prevalence of symptoms suggestive of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease in an adult population . Ann Med 1995; 27 (1): pp. 67-70.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: Knox S.A., Harrison C.M., Britt H.C., Henderson J.V.: Estimating prevalence of common chronic morbidities in Australia . Med J Aust