phageal pH Monitoring', 'Impedance Testing', 'GERD Diagnostics', 'Symptom Association', 'Acid Suppression', 'Esophageal pH Monitoring / Impedance Testing', 'Esophageal pH Monitoring / GERD Diagnostics', 'Esophageal pH Monitoring / Symptom Association', 'Esophageal pH Monitoring / Acid Suppression'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '4', '33-43', 2, 44, FALSE, TRUE),
('Submucosal Tumors in the Esophagus and Gastroesophageal Junction', 'shackelford-9th-ed-40-submucosal-tumors-in-the-esophagus-and-gastroesophageal-junction', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Submucosal Tumors in the Esophagus and Gastroesophageal Junction\n\nMimi Tan; Kevin M. Reavis\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 40, 422-432\n\n## Introduction\n\nSubmucosal tumors (SMTs) of the esophagus and gastroesophageal junction (GEJ) are a group of rare neoplasms. This chapter will review the various types of SMTs arising from the esophagus and GEJ, covering their presentation, diagnosis, and management, as well as evolving surgical and endoscopic techniques in managing SMT.\n\nMost SMTs are benign tumors. It is estimated that only 18% of esophageal tumors are benign and overall prevalence of benign esophageal tumors is 0.5%. Tumors of mesenchymal origin represent the most common SMTs of the esophagus and GEJ. Esophageal mesenchymal tumors (EMTs) include gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST), schwannoma, and leiomyoma, which is the most common.\n\nEsophageal SMTs are often found incidentally, and development of symptoms is largely correlated with tumor size. When diagnosed, endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) is particularly helpful in delineating location, size, and layer of origin of SMTs, which are all key features in planning for resection strategy. While most esophageal SMTs are benign, determination of malignant potential is the next key step in workup for determining appropriate management. Unfortunately, there is no single diagnostic test for making this determination and often requires multiple diagnostic modalities, which we will review further in this chapter. Efforts should be made to differentiate GIST from other common esophageal SMTs, as they are associated with higher malignant potential and can be more challenging to resect.\n\nDue to the rare incidence of SMT, evidence-based management recommendations are largely limited to small case series and case reports. Small, benign lesions can be reasonably surveilled. Effective neoadjuvant and adjuvant therapies are available for GIST and are promising in the setting of esophageal origin GIST. Resection, however, is the mainstay of treatment for SMT. Options for resection are limited to enucleation or esophagectomy. Increasingly minimally invasive techniques are utilized for resection, which has demonstrated improved outcomes with respect to postoperative pain, pulmonary complications, and length of hospital stay. In the last 10 years, endoscopic techniques for resection have advanced significantly and can also be safely utilized for resection of select esophageal SMTs.\n\n## Submucosal Tumors by Type\n\n### Leiomyoma\n\nLeiomyoma is the most common SMT of the esophagus or GEJ comprising 60% to 70% of benign esophageal tumors. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Of all gastrointestinal leiomyomas, 12% originate in the esophagus. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Overall, however, leiomyomas are rare, representing only 0.4% to 1% of all esophageal tumors. Esophageal cancer, by comparison, is 50-fold more common. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Leiomyomas have been reported in all age groups although most commonly found in the third and fifth decade of life. They tend to occur more frequently in males.\n\nThe most common location for leiomyoma is the distal two-thirds of the esophagus. This is consistent with the increased distribution of cells of Cajal in the distal esophagus from which leiomyomas develop. A large study reported leiomyoma esophageal location in the upper third of the esophagus in 8.5% of patients, middle third in 38.2%, lower third in 46.5%, and GEJ in 6.8%. Leiomyomas may originate from the muscularis mucosa, muscularis propria, or submucosa of the esophagus. Half of leiomyomas are less than 5 cm in diameter. Ninety-seven percent of esophageal leiomyomas are solitary. In about 2% of cases, leiomyomatosis can involve the entire esophagus necessitating esophagectomy. Although rare in children less than 12 years of age, 90% of such cases are notable for diffuse leiomyomatosis of the esophagus and may be related to other syndromes. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nLeiomyoma has low malignant potential with a 0.2% reported rate of malignant transformation to leiomyosarcoma. Tumors greater than 4 cm in diameter or rapid growth are the highest risk for malignant transformation. Prognosis for leiomyosarcoma is better than other esophageal malignancies due to overall slow growth and progression to metastatic disease. Survival in one study is reported to be 60.2%, 42.8%, and 32.1% at 1, 3, and 5 years after resection. While not typically radiosensitive, radiotherapy may be attempted in cases of unresectable disease.\n\nAbout 50% of leiomyomas are asymptomatic at time of diagnosis and found incidentally. Symptoms are usually chronic and progressive in nature with development dependent on lesion size. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Symptoms may include dysphagia, substernal pressure or pain, heartburn, and weight loss. Large lesions may present with dyspnea or other respiratory symptoms due to airway compression. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Bleeding is a rare presenting symptom.\n\nDiagnosis and localization of esophageal leiomyoma can be confirmed by endoscopic and radiographic modalities. Contrast esophagram will often show a smooth lesion with crisp margins that bulge into the lumen and impinge upon the column of esophageal contrast ( Fig. 40.1 ). Computed tomography (CT) is useful to evaluate the local involvement in larger tumors and usually depicts an eccentric area of esophageal wall thickening. Positron emission tomography (PET) scans for leiomyoma may demonstrate abnormal 18-fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) uptake ( Fig. 40.2 ) with standardized uptake value (SUV) max ranging from 1.4 to 13.4. Avidity of leiomyoma on FDG-PET scan, however, does not necessarily indicate malignancy. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In fact, only about 8% of FDG avid esophageal lesions are malignant.\n\nA radiographic scan of a tubular structure with an elongated and narrow shape with the presence of a small circular void on its wall. Ch40\n\nFig. 40.1\n\nA computed tomography scan depicts the internal organs in the abdomen region, with a highlighted area indicated by an arrow in the region in the esophagus. #REF!\n\nFig. 40.2\n\nEndoscopically, leiomyoma usually appears as a mobile bulge with intact overlying mucosa ( Fig. 40.3 ). EUS is helpful in identifying the layer involved, extent of lesion, margins, and size. Leiomyoma on EUS usually appears well demarcated, homogenous, and hypoechoic without regional lymphadenopathy. Irregular and heterogeneous lesions or locoregional lymphadenopathy should raise suspicion for malignancy. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> EUS alone, without biopsy, has 80% occurrence of predicting histological diagnosis and 74% accuracy in predicting layer of origin.\n\nAn endoscopic view depicts an abnormal growth that results in a bulged formation on the esophagus wall with a blue appearance beneath the growth. #REF!\n\nFig. 40.3\n\nBiopsy of leiomyoma either via endoscopic forceps biopsy or EUS-guided fine-needle aspiration (FNA) biopsy is controversial. Biopsy has been discouraged with the thought that it contributes to adhesions to the mucosa making subsequent resection more difficult. However, leiomyoma can be difficult to differentiate from other SMT, in particular GIST, and biopsy should be considered when there is diagnostic uncertainty that may impact management. Biopsy should also be strongly considered in lesions that are larger in size (>2 cm in size), grow during observation, or are PET avid. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> EUS-guided FNA is reported to be highly sensitive and specific but obtaining adequate tissue can be difficult. This can be improved by increasing needle passes to improve diagnostic yield.\n\nHistopathology shows fascicles or whorls, low to moderate cellularity, eosinophilic cytoplasm with fibrillary or clumped appearance. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Immunohistochemical staining can be diagnostic for leiomyoma and is key for differentiating from GIST. Leiomyoma is usually positive for smooth muscle actin (SMA), desmin, and estrogen receptors. Leiomyoma is usually negative for CD117 (KIT) and CD34, which are usually positive in GIST. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nIn cases of lesions with clinical and imaging characteristics consistent with a small, benign leiomyoma, observation can be considered. There is no definitive consensus regarding criteria for observation and subsequent surveillance modality and frequency. Size, location, and imaging and histologic features of the tumor should be carefully considered with proceeding with observation to determine frequency of repeat surveillance imaging. Some protocols suggest clinical monitoring along with endoscopy with EUS or CT every 6 months to 2 years.\n\n### Gastrointestinal Stromal Tumor\n\nGIST is the most common mesenchymal tumor of the gastrointestinal tract. The incidence of GIST is estimated to be about 10 cases per million with the most common location in the stomach. GIST with esophageal origin is rare and consists of only 1% of GISTs. Of the mesenchymal SMTs of the esophagus, GISTs account for 25% of these tumors and are less common than leiomyoma but more common than schwannoma.\n\nGISTs, like leiomyoma, develop from the interstitial cells of Cajal, and are most commonly found in the lower third of the esophagus. GISTs are found most frequently in the muscularis propria layer and rarely develop from the muscularis mucosa layer. Esophageal GIST occurs more frequently in males. Median age at presentation is in the sixth decade of life and rarely occurs in patients under the age of 30.\n\nSymptoms of esophageal GIST are similar to leiomyoma and tend to develop with tumor growth. The most common symptom is dysphagia (38%\u201353%). Less common presenting symptoms include weight loss (20%), chest pain (14%), and bleeding (8%\u201312%). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Incidental diagnosis of asymptomatic esophageal GIST is also quite common.\n\nDefinitive diagnosis of esophageal GIST prior to resection can be challenging as it can be difficult to distinguish from other SMTs. Like for leiomyoma, EUS is useful in defining the shape and size of the tumor. GISTs tend to exhibit more echogenicity on EUS but it is often difficult to differentiate from leiomyoma with EUS alone. EUS-guided FNA biopsy or core biopsy is controversial due to concerns over scarring, resulting in higher risk for complication after resection and concerns over tumor rupture and tumor dissemination. Therefore, in cases of small readily resectable suspected GIST, some recommend proceeding with resection without biopsy. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> That said, EUS-guided FNA is generally included in the diagnostic algorithm for suspected GIST. EUS-guided FNA is highly sensitive and specific when sufficient tissue is obtained with reported sensitivity as high as 95% and specificity 100%. FDG-PET can be useful in some cases of esophageal GIST. GISTs are generally highly FDG avid but this cannot reliably diagnose GIST as leiomyomas have also been known to be FDG avid as well. However, FDG-PET remains useful for evaluating postoperative recurrence, response to chemotherapy, and evaluation for metastatic disease. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nHistologically, GIST can be categorized into spindle cell, epithelioid cell, and mixed cell types. The majority of tumors are spindle cell type. Frozen section has been shown to be unreliable to differentiate GIST from leiomyoma so should not be used during resection. Immunohistochemistry is required to confirm diagnosis. Multiple molecular markers are used to differentiate GIST from other mesenchymal tumors including CD117 (KIT), CD34, and DOG1. Few GIST tumors are CD117/KIT negative (about 5%), in which cases DOG1, a calcium-dependent chloride channel protein, should be tested and seems to be consistently expressed in GIST regardless of mutation type.\n\nGISTs are typically classified with sarcomas. While GISTs are often indolent, slow growing tumors, they have greater malignant potential than either leiomyoma or schwannoma. There are several risk stratification systems for GIST to help predict malignant potential that usually involve tumor size, mitotic activity, and tumor location. Generally, tumors larger than 5 cm and mitotic rate >5 per 50 HPFs are associated with higher risk for recurrence. Nongastric origin tumors are also associated with higher risk of recurrence, especially when paired with mitotic rate >5 per 50 HPFs. Unfortunately, very few GISTs of esophageal origin were included when developing these systems, so their utility in predicting malignant potential in esophageal GIST is unclear. One case series has demonstrated that tumor size is correlated with prognosis in esophageal GIST.\n\nOverall, esophageal GIST does seem to have a worse prognosis than GIST occurring in other areas of the GI tract. Theoretically, this may be due to the lack of serosalization of the esophagus or due to the complexity of resection compared to intraabdominal organs. Reported overall 5-year disease free survival is 57% to 65%. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Metastatic recurrence is more common than local recurrence with the most common sites of metastasis being liver and lung. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Average recurrence is at 40 months after resection. Thus long-term surveillance and follow-up are key.\n\nDue to the rarity of esophageal GIST, there are no clear recommendations for optimal management. For localized esophageal GIST, resection is generally recommended. In the esophagus, options for resection are limited to enucleation or esophagectomy. Enucleation is favored when possible due to decreased postoperative morbidity and mortality, with esophagectomy reserved for very large GIST. Principles of GIST resection include obtaining grossly negative margins and avoiding violating the tumor pseudocapsule, which can lead to bleeding, tumor rupture, and potential dissemination. GISTs tend to be soft and friable and should be handled carefully. When resection is performed in a minimally invasive fashion, the specimen should be extracted in a bag to avoid seeding peritoneum or port sites. While metastasis to lymph nodes has been reported, this is rare, and routine lymphadenectomy is not recommended. Endoscopic resection of small GIST has been described. This can be technically challenging, however, due to the relative friability of GIST and concern for perforation or need for piecemeal resection.\n\nThough resection remains the primary treatment for nonmetastatic GIST, complete resection alone may not be curative if the tumor has high-risk features. Current standard of care of GIST includes targeted drug therapies based on risk of recurrence. Imatinib is a tyrosine kinase inhibitor that has been shown to be highly effective in the treatment of GIST. Adjuvant imatinib has been shown to increase recurrence free survival for localized GIST after complete resection. Imatinib is also indicated for unresectable or metastatic GIST with good overall response rate and progression-free survival. Studies regarding use of imatinib therapy have not included esophageal GIST so its efficacy in esophageal lesions is unknown. Case reports have demonstrated efficacy of neoadjuvant imatinib in improving resectability of esophageal GIST. Neoadjuvant therapy may be particularly important to consider in esophageal GIST due to the anatomic limitations related to esophageal resections. When considering management strategy, testing for KIT and PDGFR is strongly recommended. If these mutations are missing, then further staining and mutation analysis should be obtained. Tumor types such as BRAF and SDH are less likely to respond to imatinib. For GIST that does not respond or becomes resistant to imatinib, alternative therapies should be considered such as sunitinib or regorafenib.\n\n### Schwannoma\n\nSchwannoma is the least common esophageal mesenchymal SMT. The majority of these tumors present between the fourth and sixth decade of life and are more common in females. Schwannomas originate from Schwann cells and can present anywhere in the gastrointestinal tract. Overall, gastrointestinal schwannoma is rare with the most common location being the stomach (about 60%). Only about 5% of schwannomas originate in the esophagus.\n\nPresentation and workup of schwannoma are similar to those of leiomyoma and GIST. Most tumors are asymptomatic at diagnosis and found incidentally. Dysphagia is the most common presenting symptom. Schwannoma tends to develop more proximally in the esophagus than leiomyoma or GIST, so larger tumors may present with tracheal compression in addition to symptoms associated with esophageal obstruction.\n\nCT often shows a homogeneous density. Endoscopy will show a submucosal protrusion with intact mucosa. EUS will show a hypoechoic tumor in the submucosa or muscularis propria. Schwannomas may be FDG avid on FDG-PET and so may also be difficult to differentiate from leiomyomas and GIST. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Though typically benign, malignant potential does increase with tumor size. Metastasis to lymph nodes has been reported in a few case reports.\n\nHistologically, schwannoma is moderately cellular with spindle cells, a rim of lymphoid cells, and in some cases melanin pigmentation. Immunohistochemistry should be used to differentiate from GIST, which carries a higher malignant risk. Schwannomas stain positive for S-100 and glial fibrillary acidic protein (GFAP) proteins on immunohistochemical staining and stain negative for CD117, CD34, and SMA.\n\nThe mainstay of treatment is resection. Options include enucleation and esophagectomy. Enucleation is generally preferred when possible. Postoperative outcomes are favorable after resection. Only one case of recurrence has been reported after resection.\n\n### Granular Cell Tumor\n\nGranular cell tumor (GCT) is an SMT that can be found in any organ. It is most frequently found in the tongue (40%), skin (30%), and breast (15%). GCT of the gastrointestinal tract is relatively uncommon (5%). Esophageal GCTs are rare and account for 1% of GCTs. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Only 2% to 3% of GCT are malignant. A gender preponderance has not been identified and the average age of presentation is in the fourth decade. Most esophageal GCTs are found in the distal third of the esophagus. Fifty percent of GCTs are asymptomatic at diagnosis. Symptoms, like other SMTs, correlate with tumor size. One case series of esophageal GCT reported a higher incidence of gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD)-like symptoms and higher incidence of esophagitis documented on endoscopy in their study group, hypothesizing that chronic inflammation may play a role in development of esophageal GCT.\n\nEUS is often helpful in identifying layer of origin and typically shows a hyperechoic solid mass surrounded by hyperechoic submucosa. Grossly, GCT appears as a submucosal bulge in the esophageal lumen and classically has a pale-yellow coloration with a polypoid \u201cmolar-shape\u201d ( Fig. 40.4 ). Microscopically, GCT cells have small nuclei with abundant granular cytoplasm and overlying mucosa with pseudoepitheliomatous hyperplasia. GCT considered to be malignant may demonstrate aggressive histologic findings such as increased cellularity and atypia or aggressive clinical findings such as large size (>4 cm), rapid growth, or recurrence. Both local invasion and metastasis have been reported for malignant GCT.\n\nA photo of a person captures a closure view of an unusual tubular growth from the mouth with the tongue fully extended. #REF!\n\nFig. 40.4\n\nTreatment of GCT is somewhat controversial. Some authors advocate for resection of all tumors due to unknown malignant potential. Others suggest that surveillance for small, asymptomatic lesions is acceptable. Apart from resection, ablative therapies such as yttrium aluminum garnet (YAG) laser or alcohol injections have been performed to avoid surgical resection. The disadvantage of ablation is lack of histologic diagnosis and analysis.\n\n### Hemangioma\n\nHemangioma is a benign vascular tumor that can originate from the esophageal submucosa. Hemangiomas are rare and represent approximately 3% of benign esophageal tumors. There is a slight male preponderance with a broad range of age of diagnosis. Multiple hemangiomatosis has been reported in association with Rendu-Osler Weber syndrome. Esophageal hemangiomas are most commonly found in the middle and distal thirds of the esophagus. Presentation of hemangioma is similar to those of other SMTs. Notably, however, there can be rare massive hemorrhage from these vascular tumors.\n\nHemangioma can occur as small single lesions or large and multinodular. Endoscopically, hemangioma appears as a bluish polypoid lesion that is soft and compressive ( Fig. 40.5 ). Due to their vascular nature, suspected hemangioma should not be biopsied due to risk for hemorrhage. EUS with color Doppler can be helpful in identifying a vascular lesion, but absence of flow does not rule out hemangioma. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nA photo presents the endoscopic view of the esophagus passage, with an abnormal growth area marked by an asterisk. #REF!\n\nFig. 40.5\n\nIncidentally identified, asymptomatic hemangioma may be observed clinically without intervention. Resection, like other SMTs, consists of enucleation and esophagectomy. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Careful dissection and hemostasis are critical during resection to avoid significant bleeding. Endoscopic resection of hemangioma has been reported and successful. Treatment with ablative therapies including YAG laser fulguration, injection sclerotherapy, and radiation therapy has also been reported for definitive treatment for small lesions and for management of symptoms for larger lesions.\n\n### Fibrovascular Polyps\n\nFibrovascular polyps are rare tumors. There is a slight male preponderance and peak prevalence is in the fifth through seventh decades. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Fibrovascular polyps are usually solitary but may be multiple. It is hypothesized that fibrovascular polyps originate as a submucosal thickening in the proximal esophagus near the cricopharyngeus muscle that then elongates into a polypoid shape due to esophageal peristalsis and lumenal compression. Fibrovascular polyps can reach impressive proportions and may grow large enough to dilate the esophageal lumen and long enough to reach the stomach before producing symptoms. Presenting symptoms may include dysphagia and respiratory symptoms. Bleeding can occur if the polyp is long enough to be exposed to gastric acid. Most dramatically the polyp can be regurgitated into the oropharynx ( Fig. 40.6 ). When the polyp is regurgitated, it may be swallowed, captured or severed by the teeth, or aspirated. Several cases of resultant asphyxiation have been reported.\n\nA computed tomography scan of a sagittal view of the neck and chest, with several areas of interest near the thoracic spines indicated by three arrows. #REF!\n\nFig. 40.6\n\nEsophagram and endoscopy are the primary diagnostic modalities for fibrovascular polyp. When seen on esophagram, the study will show a filling defect that moves within the esophageal lumen. However, fibrovascular polyp is often missed on these studies (22% in esophagram and 33% on esophagogastroduodenoscopy \\[EGD\\]). Polyps often develop near the upper esophageal sphincter in the posterior wall. These lesions also often contain redundant mucosa and have similar appearance to surrounding tissue of the esophagus, making identification difficult on diagnostic studies ( Fig. 40.7 ). Alternative imaging approaches should be utilized in cases of diagnostic uncertainty. CT will show a heterogenous mass, which can be confused with food or foreign material ( Fig. 40.8 ). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> MRI may show a hyperintense mass on T1-weighted imaging with decreased signal intensity on T2-weighted imaging.\n\nA photo of a tubular surgical specimen with a bulged end opposite a narrow end is placed next to a measurement scale for size reference. #REF!\n\nFig. 40.7\n\nA diagram of a leiomyoma removal from the esophagus and sutures used to close the incision. The diagram consists of two parts of the surgical procedure labeled A and B. Part A depicts surgical instruments used to pull out the leiomyoma from the incision on the posterior wall and bluntly dissect it. Part B illustrates the sutures of the incision after the leiomyoma''s removal.\n\nFig. 40.8\n\nGrossly, fibrovascular polyp is a cylindrical mass covered in intact mucosa and attached by a stalk to the proximal esophageal wall ( Fig. 40.9 ). Histologically, fibrovascular polyps demonstrate mature fibrous tissue with varying amounts of vascularity and adipose tissue. The varying prominence of dominant tissue type denotes the name of the polyp, which includes fibroma, fibrolipoma, myoma, myxofibroma, and fibroepithelial types. One case of fibrovascular polyp harboring a well-differentiated liposarcoma has been reported.\n\nTwo diagrams of an intragastric lesion resection that uses the surgical instrument and endoscope. The left diagram depicts the endoscope inside the esophageal passage that reaches the stomach orifice blocked with the intragastric lesion. The endoloop around the lesion is monitored by another endoscope that enters the stomach through intragastric ports. In the second diagram, the endoloop tightens with the lesion resection made by the linear stapler.\n\nFig. 40.9\n\nResection is recommended for all fibrovascular polyps due to potential for airway compromise. Resection principles include complete removal of the base of the polyp to avoid local recurrence. This has traditionally been performed via transcervical approach in which the esophagus is opened opposite the origin of the polyp, the polyp and stalk are excised, and the mucosal defect and esophagotomy are closed. Esophagectomy has been required in a handful of cases. In other cases, endoscopic removal has been successful, though some authors raise concerns for potential hemorrhage from the vascular stalk and for incomplete resection.\n\n## Surgical Resection\n\nThe mainstay of treatment for esophageal SMT is resection via enucleation or esophagectomy. Small, asymptomatic, benign esophageal SMTs can reasonably be observed with appropriate surveillance. However, resection is indicated in symptomatic lesions, inability to rule out malignancy, atypical imaging findings, overlying mucosal erosion, dysplastic changes, regional lymphadenopathy, large tumors, and tumor growth during surveillance. While enucleation is generally preferred due to lower associated morbidity and mortality, esophagectomy is indicated in large tumors or diffuse disease and when malignancy is highly suspected or confirmed.\n\nSMTs can be resected by open approach via right or left thoracotomy or laparotomy depending on tumor location. With open access to the esophagus or GEJ, the surgeon can visualize and palpate the tumor to precisely localize it. For enucleation, the overlying pleura is incised and the longitudinal and circular muscles split. The tumor is dissected from the surrounding muscle and submucosa and enucleated from the underlying mucosa. Any mucosal injury can be closed primarily and the overlying muscle layers and pleura are closed. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The safety and efficacy of the open approach have been well documented. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Esophagectomy may be indicated for large tumors or diffuse disease.\n\nMinimally invasive approaches are increasingly utilized in resection of esophageal SMT. Resections are performed via right or left thoracoscopic approaches or laparoscopically depending on the tumor. Robotic-assisted resections have also been described for SMT with success. Length of stay for minimally invasive enucleation is about half that expected for open surgery and is associated with decreased pulmonary complications, postoperative pain, and hospital length of stay. Intraoperative endoscopy can be utilized for identification of the lesion and for testing mucosal integrity after resection. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nLaparoscopic transgastric or intragastric surgery has also been reported for difficult to reach lesions at the GEJ. With this technique, trocars are placed through the abdominal wall and then directly into the lumen of the stomach. Capnogastrum is achieved. This approach may help to avoid excess resection and minimize disruption of the angle of His at the GEJ and has been successful for tumors as large as 7 cm. The specimen can then be removed via a specimen bag through the trocar site or transorally with the endoscope via a grasper or snare if size permits. The gastrostomy is closed primarily with suture or staples. Development of new or worsening GERD after resection of GEJ lesions has been reported. Thus if resection of a significant portion of cardia is required, fundoplication should be considered to prevent postoperative reflux. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n## Endoscopic Resection\n\nEndoscopic resection has grown in popularity due to its minimally invasive nature, and indications have expanded as more surgeons and gastroenterologists gain experience with various resection techniques. Advantages of endoscopic resection techniques include less postprocedural pain and decreased length of stay compared to surgical techniques. While reported rates of recurrence in the literature after endoscopic resection are low, careful preprocedure selection is important due to risk of incomplete or piecemeal resection.\n\n### Endoscopic Mucosal Resection\n\nEndoscopic mucosal resection (EMR) may be used for small tumors that are relatively superficial. EMR separates the full thickness of mucosa from the underlying muscular layers. With this technique, lifting solution is injected in the submucosal layer beneath the tumor to create a pseudopolyp, which can then be banded or snared to complete the resection ( Fig. 40.10 ). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nA series of six photos of an endoscopic procedure includes an initial view of an abnormal growth in the digestive tract, an ultrasound, and stages of the resection process. The photos document a surgery inside the digestive tract labeled A to F. Part A depicts the endoscopic view of the abnormal growth in the digestive tract. Part B features an ultrasound view of the abnormal growth. Part C presents the identification of the abnormal growth from the surrounding layers. Part D depicts the abnormal growth resection with the endoloop. Part E depicts the abnormal growth removed from the surgical site. Part F shows the abnormal growth size lifted with forceps after removal.\n\nFig. 40.10\n\nEndoscopy is performed with a high-definition single- or double-channel endoscope. A 23- or 25-gauge endoscopic needle is then used to infiltrate the submucosa deep to the lesion with dilute indigo carmine or methylene blue solution with or without epinephrine to lift the lesion. Due to the limited working space of the esophagus, the injection is begun distal to the lesion and then sequentially performed proximally. Failure to lift the lesion indicates a misplaced needle tip, usually too deep in the muscular layers, which can be adjusted by slowly withdrawing the tip while gently injecting. If this fails to procedure adequate lift, this may suggest infiltration of scarring of the tumor or origin in deeper muscle layers.\n\nComplete resection is difficult to obtain when inadequate lift is encountered and can be associated with crush injury at the margins of the resected specimen. Cap-assisted EMR can be used with a single-channel endoscope. The targeted lesion can then be suctioned into the cap prior to snaring it. A variceal band can also be applied to position the lesion, which is then snared beneath the band under direct vision. With this technique, a deeper dissection margin can be achieved than with traditional EMR. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nEMR is limited by risk of tumor perforation from attempts at lifting in the submucosal plane and depending on size of tumor may require piecemeal resection. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Endoscopic Submucosal Dissection and Submucosal Tunneling\n\nEndoscopic submucosal dissection (ESD) is indicated for larger tumors that cannot be captured en bloc by EMR. ESD involves incision through normal mucosa overlying the lesion and dissection around the lesion, which is often performed with a variety of endoscopic electrosurgical knives.\n\nFor ESD, the line of planned incision is first demarcated with cautery. This margin is made a few millimeters away from the lesion to allow for shrinkage of the tissue while preserving the pathological margin. A dissection cap is utilized to aid in retraction and visualization. Lifting solution is then injected into the submucosal layer at the marked margin of resection, moving from distal to proximal direction, similar to the technique used for EMR. A small mucosal incision is created distally with electrosurgical knife into the submucosal layer and continued circumferentially. The submucosal tissue is dissected directly, separating the lesion off the muscular layers beneath. Judicious use of cautery is used to achieve hemostasis during this process to full thickness injury. Once resected, the resection bed is inspected for bleeding or full thickness violation of the muscular layers. The specimen can then be collected with a snare, grasping forceps, or retrieval nets.\n\nESD alone is limited to resection of tumors in the muscularis mucosa. Deeper tumors cannot be traditionally approached with ESD due to risk for perforation. Addition of submucosal tunneling, which was initially described for per-oral endoscopic myotomy (POEM), has facilitated resection of deeper tumors while preserving integrity of overlying mucosa. Various terms have been used to describe this technique including \u201csubmucosal endoscopic tumor resection\u201d (SET), \u201csubmucosal tunneling and endoscopic resection\u201d (STER), and \u201cper-oral endoscopic tumor resection\u201d (POET). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> \u201cEndoscopic submucosal excavation\u201d has also been described, which involves reapproximation of mucosal edges after ESD. This has been demonstrated to be safe for resection of tumors arising in the muscularis propria ( Fig. 40.11 ).\n\nA series of nine endoscopic photos of surgery for tumor resection in the esophagus. Part A shows the tumor position with a star mark. Part B represents the tumor accessed with an instrument that marks the mucosal layer. Part C provides a closer view of the mucosal layer above and the muscle layers below. Part D presents a view of the mucosa with the tumor still in place and continuous examination. In Part E, the tumor is to be manipulated and focuses on the muscle layer beneath. Part F depicts the tumor, marked by a star, likely in preparation for removal. Part G illustrates the mucosal layer to be separated, which reveals a defect in the muscle layer, indicated by an arrow. Part H displays the clips used to close the incision. Finally, Part I shows the resected tumor placed on a surgical drape.\n\nFig. 40.11\n\nFor submucosal tunneling, a lift is established 5 cm proximal to the proximal edge of the lesion. A 1- to 2-cm mucosotomy is made, and a submucosal tunnel is created to approach the lesion. The tunnel is continued in this plane, lifting the mucosa off the lesion. The lesion is then dissected off the muscularis. This may require full thickness muscle incision but risk of leak is minimized by careful preservation of the mucosa during dissection. The lesion is extracted once freed with forceps or snare and the mucosa closed with clips. The tunneling technique is recommended when feasible with potential benefit of faster healing time over standard ESD technique.\n\nCapnothorax, capnomediastinum, and capnoperitoneum are managed conservatively as CO <sub>2 </sub> is quickly absorbed. Veress needle decompression can be utilized to minimize postprocedure discomfort.\n\nDelayed leak or fistulas are the most dreaded postoperative concerns. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> A postprocedure swallow study can rule out leak before diet is initiated. Bleeding or persistent painful ulcers can occur and proton pump inhibitors (PPIs) or mucosal protective agents can be used to help with ulcer healing and follow-up endoscopy can be performed to ensure healing. Stricture formation can occur and risk increases with larger lesions.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nSMTs of the esophagus and GEJ are rare but represent a heterogeneous group of neoplasms. Most tumors are benign, and smaller lesions can often be observed. However, some tumors do have malignant potential, so identification of these high-risk lesions is key. This can be challenging and often requires multiple imaging and endoscopic techniques. Resection is largely limited to enucleation and esophagectomy. Minimally invasive and endoscopic techniques are promising and safe in managing these tumors although careful patient selection is required.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Plachta A.: Benign tumors of the esophagus. Review of literature and report of 99 cases . Am J Gastroenterol 1962; 38: pp. 639-652.\n\nView In Article\n\n2.: Choong C.K., Meyers B.F.: Benign esophageal tumors: introduction, incidence, classification, and clinical features . Semin Thorac Cardiovasc Surg 2003; 15 (1): pp. 3-8.\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: He G., Wang J., Chen B., et al.: Feasibility of endoscopic submucosal dissection for upper gastrointestinal submucosal tumors treatment and value of endoscopic ultrasonography in pre-operation assess and post-operation follow-up: a prospective study of 224 cases in a single medical center . Surg Endosc 2016; 30 (10): pp. 4206-4213.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Totten R., Stout A., Humphreys G., et al.: Benign tumors and cysts of the esophagus . J Thor Surg 1953; 25 (6): pp. 606-622.\n\nView In Article\n\n5.: Asteriou C., Konstantinou D., Lalountas M., et al.: Nine years experience in surgical approach of leiomyomatosis of esophagus . World J Surg Oncol 2009; 7: pp. 102.\n\nView In Article\n\n6.: Haddad J., Bouazza F., Barake H., Liberale G., Flamen P., Nakadi I.E.: Surgical strategy in abnormally increased fluorine-18 fluorodeoxyglucose uptake in an asymptomatic lower esophageal submucosal tumor- report of a case . Int J Surg Case Rep 2014; 5 (9): pp. 589-593.\n\nView In Article\n\n7.: Dendy M., Johnson K., Boffa D.J.: Spectrum of FDG uptake in large (>10 cm) esophageal leiomyomas . J Thorac Dis 2015; 7 (12): pp. E648-E651.\n\nView In Article\n\n8.: Beji H., Bouassida M., Kallel Y., et al.: Leiomyoma of the esophagus: a case report and review of the literature . Int J Surg Case Rep 2022; 94:\n\nView In Article\n\n9.: Seremetis M.G., Lyons W.S., deGuzman V.C., Peabody J.W.: Leiomyomata of the esopha