s/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[39. Management of Esophageal Perforation - ClinicalKey|39. Management of Esophageal Perforation]]\n**Next:** [[41. Esophageal Duplication Cyst - ClinicalKey|41. Esophageal Duplication Cyst]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "40. Submucosal Tumors in the Esophagus and Gastroesophageal Junction - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Submucosal Tumors in the Esophagus and Gastroesophageal Junction', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Submucosal Tumors in the Esophagus and Gastroesophageal Junction', 'Submucosal Tumors by Type', 'Surgical Resection', 'Endoscopic Resection', 'Leiomyoma', 'Gastrointestinal Stromal Tumor', 'Submucosal Tumors in the Esophagus and Gastroesophageal Junction / Submucosal Tumors by Type', 'Submucosal Tumors in the Esophagus and Gastroesophageal Junction / Surgical Resection', 'Submucosal Tumors in the Esophagus and Gastroesophageal Junction / Endoscopic Resection'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '40', '422-432', 2, 44, FALSE, TRUE),
('Esophageal Duplication Cyst', 'shackelford-9th-ed-41-esophageal-duplication-cyst', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Esophageal Duplication Cyst\n\nErin Handspiker; Jennifer Hwang; Meredith Anne Harrison\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 41, 433-436\n\n## Pathophysiology\n\nIn normal esophageal embryologic development, the esophagus is recanalized around the eighth week of gestation. Esophageal duplication cysts are hypothesized to develop around weeks 5\u20138 due to error in recanalization. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Recanalization of the esophagus occurs through formation and coalescence of large vacuoles, and the persistence of a vacuole is thought to form the esophageal duplication cyst.\n\nThe location of esophageal duplication cysts varies with about 60% located in the lower third of the esophagus, 23% in the upper third, and the remaining 17% in the middle third. Esophageal duplication cysts must meet histological criteria for classification: location within or attached to the esophageal wall, squamous epithelium or other embryonic esophageal lining, and coverage of the cyst by two muscle layers.\n\nAbout 30% of posterior mediastinal masses in children are esophageal duplication cysts, making them the second most common benign pediatric posterior mediastinal mass after bronchogenic cysts. Although difficult to differentiate clinically, histologically, bronchogenic cysts fail to meet the criteria because they are not covered by two muscle layers and are instead composed of cartilage and/or bronchogenic glands ( Table 41.1 ).\n\nTable 41.1\n\nCharacteristics of Esophageal Duplication Cysts and Bronchogenic Cysts <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n| | Esophageal Duplication Cyst | Bronchogenic Cyst |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| **Embryologic origin** | Foregut | Foregut |\n| **Symptoms** | Dysphagia, pain, chronic cough, wheezing, asymptomatic | Dysphagia, pain, chronic cough, wheezing, asymptomatic |\n| **Histology** | Cyst is covered by two muscle layers | Composed of cartilage, bronchogenic glands |\n| **Specific findings** | Peristalsis caused by the smooth muscle layers on endoscopic ultrasound | Presence of cartilage on histology |\n\n## Clinical Presentation\n\nEsophageal duplication cysts have varying clinical presentations, differing depending on age, size, location, and extrinsic compression. Both respiratory and gastrointestinal symptoms are seen. Some cysts, especially those smaller in size, do not cause symptoms. Of those that become symptomatic, 70%\u201395% present before 2 years of age. Adult cysts are symptomatic in less than 7% of cases and are instead often found incidentally on chest imaging.\n\nEsophageal duplication cysts are most commonly identified in the distal third of the esophagus. Symptoms include dysphagia (70%), epigastric discomfort (20%), and retrosternal pain (10%). Chronic cough and recurrent respiratory infections can be seen with duplication cysts located in the upper esophagus as a result of tracheal compression. Cysts located here are more likely to be diagnosed in infancy because of the resultant respiratory symptoms. Involvement of the mainstem bronchus can require resection during the neonatal period because of ipsilateral lung hyperinflation.\n\nGastric mucosa is prevalent in up to one-third of esophageal duplication cysts, and ulcer formation can occur because of acid formation. An acute onset of symptoms in patients with a known esophageal duplication cyst is concerning for hemorrhage, perforation, or infection. Although rare, malignant transformations have been reported. Both adenocarcinoma and squamous cell carcinoma are documented, the former having higher prevalence. Although malignant transformation has been documented, the exact rate is uncertain due to its rarity. Presentation includes dysphagia and fever; however, some malignant transformations have been discovered incidentally. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Imaging Studies\n\nThe main imaging modalities used to evaluate esophageal duplication cysts are computed tomography (CT), magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), and endoscopic ultrasound (EUS). They are sometimes found incidentally on radiographs and barium swallow studies with nonspecific findings such as a mediastinal mass, esophageal compression, and tracheal displacement or narrowing.\n\nA CT scan with contrast can provide information that is useful for surgical planning, including anatomical landmarks, size of the cyst, and location. An esophageal duplication cyst on CT can appear as a non-enhancing fluid-filled cystic structure with a smooth, well-defined enhancing rim in the esophagus ( Fig. 41.1 ). CT scans provide the added benefit of ruling out other pulmonary and vertebral pathology.\n\nTwo computed tomography scans of the chest labeled parts A and B reveal the internal organs in the coronal and axial views with marks of uneven mass in some areas. Ch41\n\nFig. 41.1\n\nMRI offers similar information to the CT scan but with improved cross-sectional anatomic detail. Esophageal duplication cysts are hypointense on T1-weighted images and hyperintense on T2 ( Fig. 41.2 ). There are some reports of antenatal diagnosis of esophageal duplication cysts using MRI. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nTwo magnetic resonance images of the upper torso, with the sagittal view marked A and the axial view marked B, exhibit a prominent fluid filled region adjacent to the spinal cord. #REF!\n\nFig. 41.2\n\n### Endoscopy\n\nEUS has become the preferred method for imaging and diagnosis of esophageal duplication cysts. The intra- and extra-mural relationship with the gastrointestinal tract is well-defined on EUS. On EUS, these cysts appear homogenous, have three to five layers of cyst walls, and echogenicity of the contents range from anechoic to hypoechoic based on cyst contents ( Fig. 41.3 ). One feature specific for esophageal duplication cysts is peristalsis. The cystic wall muscles can exhibit concentric ring contractions and when taken into consideration with the location of the cyst, can be diagnostic for an esophageal duplication cyst.\n\nA photo of an ultrasound scan depicts a cyst with concentric rings denoted by a plus symbol at the center surrounded by regular margins denoted by a cross symbol. #REF!\n\nFig. 41.3\n\nEUS also offers the option for fine-needle aspiration (FNA) when the echogenicity of the cyst contents raises diagnostic uncertainty. The aspirated contents of the cyst vary and correlate with the echogenicity seen on EUS. In their study investigating FNA for esophageal duplication cysts, Eloubeidi et al. encountered two main types of cysts on EUS\u2014anechoic simple cysts and anechoic cysts with dense, hyperechoic debris. Aspirate from the anechoic simple cysts was clear liquid and CT images were consistent with cystic lesions. The anechoic cysts with hyperechoic debris yielded aspirate ranging from thick debris to thick frothy brown fluid and these were less concordant with CT findings, often misinterpreted as solid masses. Increased risk of infection and sepsis have been reported with the use of FNA, but when used with a combination of a smaller gauge needle and premedication with antibiotics, FNA has been shown to be a well-tolerated diagnostic tool. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n## Treatment\n\nSurgical excision of esophageal duplication cysts provides a definitive treatment and diagnosis. While excision is the treatment of choice in symptomatic patients, the role of surgery is without clear guidelines in asymptomatic patients. Surgical removal of cysts in asymptomatic patients has been advocated due to potential of ulcer formation, bleeding, perforation, and malignant transformation. Asymptomatic patients who opt out of surgical intervention should be closely monitored for symptoms or increasing size of the cyst. A recommended time between follow-up is not well studied. The authors of this chapter recommend annual surveillance.\n\n### Operative\n\nSurgical resection of esophageal duplication cysts has several advantages, including definitive treatment and prevention of serious complications. Open surgical resection using a posterolateral thoracotomy was previously considered the treatment of choice, being replaced in recent years with more minimally invasive techniques such as video-assisted thoracoscopic surgery (VATS) and robotic-assisted thoracoscopic surgery (RATS). The operative approach used is dependent on the cyst location, size, and surgeon preference. An open approach via posterolateral thoracotomy should be considered in cases such as compressive cysts causing mediastinal shift, infected cysts, or hemorrhage.\n\nCurrently, VATS is the surgical approach of choice as it offers reduction in postoperative pain, earlier recovery, shorter hospital stays, and improved cosmetic outcome. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> A major advantage of VATS is better access to lesions irrespective of location, where an open thoracotomy has limited views. RATS is also becoming increasingly used and accepted. In using RATS, surgeons are advantaged with superior visualization of the surgical field ( Fig. 41.4 ) and improved range of motion with more precise movements. Obasi et al. detailed use of a robotic approach for esophageal duplication cyst excision. Successful surgical resection was performed on two pediatric patients using the da Vinci surgical system. Notable postoperative outcomes included decreased pain and early discharge with no complications. The authors of this chapter have successfully completed multiple robotic esophageal duplication cyst resections without complication.\n\nA photo captures an endoscopic view of the inner esophagus with a circular mass and blood vessels in the esophageal lining. #REF!\n\nFig. 41.4\n\nComplete excision of an esophageal duplication cyst requires the cyst to be completely separated from both mediastinal structures and from the esophageal wall with preservation of the cyst wall. Three critical steps are imperative during the procedure: the esophageal mucosa should be approximated, the vagus nerve should be identified and preserved, and the esophagus inspected for a leak. After complete excision of the cyst, intraoperative endoscopy with insufflation is commonly used to assess for esophageal injury. Repair using absorbable suture should be performed if muscular or mucosal injuries are seen. During closure, approximation of transected muscle fibers, muscularis propria, and pleura should be managed similarly to injuries using 3-0 absorbable suture. Suture repair is crucial in prevention of pseudodiverticulum formation. Approximation of the muscularis propria is important to reinforce the defect, minimizing this complication. Incomplete resection of cysts can lead to recurrence. If not able to be removed in its entirety, complete excision of cyst mucosa will decrease the possibility of cavity recurrence.\n\nComplications are rare following surgical excision. Those reported include pneumonia, air leak, pneumothorax, esophageal injury or leak, nerve injuries, pseudodiverticulum formation, bleeding, and infections. Cysts removed near the gastroesophageal junction may result in incompetence of the lower esophageal sphincter, leading to development or exacerbation of reflux symptoms. Patients should be informed of these potential complications during consent. Previous reports of esophageal injury were managed with immediate primary repair. A buttress using intercostal muscle, Brewer\u2019s patch, or omentum can been used.\n\n### Endoscopic\n\nEndoscopic intervention is a consideration in a subset of patients, including those who are at high risk for surgery or those with existing medical conditions that may be exacerbated by surgical complications like acid reflux and esophagitis. Esophageal duplication cysts that are small and pedunculated can be resected with a polypectomy snare. Large duplication cysts that are deep within the esophageal wall can be managed with endoscopic fenestration. Further studies are required to determine long-term efficacy.\n\n## Summary\n\nEsophageal duplication cysts are rare congenital abnormalities with varying presentations, including both respiratory and gastrointestinal symptoms. The most common presenting symptoms are dysphagia, epigastric discomfort, and retrosternal pain. EUS has become the preferred imaging modality for detection, and diagnosis is made based on a combination of imaging and histologic characteristics. Surgical removal is the treatment of choice for symptomatic patients. Open surgical resection by way of posterolateral thoracotomy has been the standard surgical approach for esophageal duplication cysts. However, in recent years, more minimally invasive approaches such as VATS and RATS have become a preferred method due to their numerous advantages, including reduction in postoperative pain, earlier recovery, shorter hospital stays, and favorable cosmesis. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> RATS offers significant advantages for surgeons including improved visualization and dexterity; however, few cases of its use are reported in current literature. While asymptomatic patients can be opted for surveillance and follow-up, surgical removal is recommended due to the potential risks of complications including mucosal ulceration, bleeding, perforation, and rarely the malignant transformation.\n\nBecause of their rarity, scientific evidence to support one surgical approach over another remains limited and further studies are necessary to support the use of robotic surgery in esophageal duplication cysts. With this said, approaches in management and treatment of esophageal duplication cysts should be tailored to each patient based on presenting symptoms, imaging findings, and skill set of the surgeon.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Liu R., Adler D.G.: Duplication cysts: diagnosis, management, and the role of endoscopic ultrasound . Endosc Ultrasound 2014; 3 (3): pp. 152-160.\n\nView In Article\n\n2.: Faigel D.O., Burke A., Ginsberg G.G., Stotland B.R., Kadish S.L., Kochman M.L.: The role of endoscopic ultrasound in the evaluation and management of foregut duplications . Gastrointest Endosc 1997; 45 (1): pp. 99-103.\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: Arbona J.L., Fazzi J.G., Mayoral J.: Congenital esophageal cysts: case report and review of literature . Am J Gastroenterol 1984; 79 (3): pp. 177-182.\n\nView In Article\n\n4.: Kolomainen D., Hurley P.R., Ebbs S.R.: Esophageal duplication cyst: case report and review of the literature . Dis Esophagus 1998; 11 (1): pp. 62-65.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: Watanobe I., Ito Y., Akimoto E., et al.: Laparoscopic resection of an intra-abdominal esophageal duplication cyst: a case report and literature review . Case Rep Surg 2015; 2015:\n\nView In Article\n\n6.: McAdams H.P., Kirejczyk W.M., Rosado-de-Christenson M.L., Matsumoto S.: Bronchogenic cyst: imaging features with clinical and histopathologic correlation . Radiology 2000; 217 (2): pp. 441-446.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n7.: Chan M., Zavala S.R.: Esophageal cyst . StatPearls . 2022. StatPearls Publishing ,\n\nView In Article\n\n8.: Obasi P.C., Hebra A., Varela J.C.: Excision of esophageal duplication cysts with robotic-assisted thoracoscopic surgery . JSLS 2011; 15 (2): pp. 244-247.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n9.: Singh R., Singh A., Mishra A., Agarwal P.N.: Oesophageal duplication\u2013 an uncommon cause of dysphagia in an adult . CMRP 2022; 12 (2): pp. 78.\n\nView In Article\n\n10.: Nayan S., Nguyen L.H., Nguyen V.H., Daniel S.J., Emil S.: Cervical esophageal duplication cyst: case report and review of the literature . J Pediatr Surg 2010; 45 (9): pp. e1-e5.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n11.: Duan X., Cui Y., He Y., Xu S.: Acute attack of recurrent esophageal duplication cyst in an adult: case report and literature review . J Thorac Dis 2018; 10 (5): pp. E335-E339.\n\nView In Article\n\n12.: Joyce A.M., Zhang P.J., Kochman M.L.: Complete endoscopic resection of an esophageal duplication cyst (with video) . Gastrointest Endosc 2006; 64 (2): pp. 288-289.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n13.: Chaudhry I.U.H., A Alsuhaimi M., M Al Ghamdi A., et al.: A sudden hemorrhage in the esophageal duplication cyst: a rare cause of acute dysphagia in an adult . Ann Med Surg 2022; 80 (2012):\n\nView In Article\n\n14.: Stringel G., Mercer S., Briggs V.: Esophageal duplication cyst containing a foreign body . Can Med Assoc J 1985; 132 (5): pp. 529-531.\n\nView In Article\n\n15.: Cioffi U., Bonavina L., De Simone M., et al.: Presentation and surgical management of bronchogenic and esophageal duplication cysts in adults . Chest 1998; 113 (6): pp. 1492-1496.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n16.: Reference deleted in revisions\n\n17.: Rangasami R., Chandrasekharan A., Archana L., Santhosh J.: Case report: antenatal MRI diagnosis of esophageal duplication cyst . Indian J Radiol Imaging 2009; 19 (1): pp. 75-77.\n\nView In Article\n\n18.: Reference deleted in revisions.\n\n19.: Eloubeidi M.A., Cohn M., Cerfolio R.J., et al.: Endoscopic ultrasound-guided fine-needle aspiration in the diagnosis of foregut duplication cysts: the value of demonstrating detached ciliary tufts in cyst fluid . Cancer 2004; 102 (4): pp. 253-258.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n20.: Garofalo S., Schleef J., Guan\u00e0 R., et al.: Esophageal duplication cyst in newborn . Pediatr Neonatol 2020; 61 (1): pp. 121-122.\n\nView In Article\n\n21.: Kumar D., Gupta G., Jhamb U.: Esophageal duplication cyst: two cases presenting as recurrent chest infection and Stridor . J Pediatr Surg Case Rep 2017; 18: pp. 10-12.\n\nView In Article\n\n22.: Salo J.A., Ala-Kulju K.V.: Congenital esophageal cysts in adults . Ann Thorac Surg 1987; 44 (2): pp. 135-138.\n\nView In Article\n\n23.: Bodner J.C., Zitt M., Ott H., et al.: Robotic-ass