-.2%200-.3.1-.3.3V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.6.6h-5.1c-.4%200-.6-.3-.6-.6V7c0-.4.2-.6.6-.6h13.9c6.6%200%2011.5%204.6%2011.5%2011.1%200%205-2.7%208.7-6.9%2010.3L95.5%2043c.2.3%200%20.7-.4.7h-5.8zm-.7-26.2c0-3.2-2.2-5.3-5.5-5.3h-7.7c-.2%200-.3.1-.3.4v9.9c0%20.2%200%20.3.3.3H83c3.3%200%205.5-2%205.5-5.3M101%206.9c0-.4.3-.6.6-.6h21.8c.4%200%20.6.2.6.6v4.7c0%20.3-.2.5-.6.5h-15.8c-.2%200-.3.1-.3.4v9c0%20.3.1.4.3.4h12.7c.4%200%20.6.2.6.5v4.7c0%20.4-.2.6-.6.6h-12.7c-.2%200-.3%200-.3.3v9.4c0%20.3.1.4.3.4h15.8c.4%200%20.6.2.6.5V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.6.6h-21.8c-.3%200-.6-.3-.6-.6V7zm28.8%200c0-.4.2-.6.5-.6h5.2c.3%200%20.6.2.6.6v30.5c0%20.3%200%20.4.3.4H151c.3%200%20.5.2.5.5V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.5.6h-20.8c-.3%200-.517-.3-.5-.6V7zm47.7%2036.7c-.4%200-.6-.2-.8-.5l-7.3-12.7-7.4%2012.7c-.2.3-.4.5-.8.5h-5.8c-.3%200-.5-.3-.3-.7L166%2024.3%20156%207.1c-.2-.4%200-.7.3-.7h5.8c.4%200%20.6.1.8.5l6.5%2011.3h.1L176%206.9c.2-.4.5-.5.9-.5h5.7c.4%200%20.5.3.3.7l-10%2017.2L183.7%2043c.2.4%200%20.7-.3.7h-5.8zM192.015%2019c-.2%200-.338-.004-.3-.2V8.4h-3.3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[40. Submucosal Tumors in the Esophagus and Gastroesophageal Junction - ClinicalKey|40. Submucosal Tumors in the Esophagus and Gastroesophageal Junction]]\n**Next:** [[42. Caustic Esophageal Injury - ClinicalKey|42. Caustic Esophageal Injury]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "41. Esophageal Duplication Cyst - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Esophageal Duplication Cyst', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Esophageal Duplication Cyst', 'Pathophysiology', 'Clinical Presentation', 'Treatment', 'Imaging Studies', 'Endoscopy', 'Esophageal Duplication Cyst / Pathophysiology', 'Esophageal Duplication Cyst / Clinical Presentation', 'Esophageal Duplication Cyst / Treatment'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '41', '433-436', 2, 16, FALSE, TRUE),
('Caustic Esophageal Injury', 'shackelford-9th-ed-42-caustic-esophageal-injury', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Caustic Esophageal Injury\n\nChelsea Megan Loria; Jordan A. Wilkerson; DuyKhanh Pham Ceppa\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 42, 437-444\n\n## Epidemiology\n\nIn the United States, 5000 to 15,000 caustic esophageal injuries are reported annually. It is most commonly encountered within the pediatric population as a result of accidental ingestion. Incidence peaks at 2 years of age, with 80% of all cases occurring in patients aged <5 years. Caustic ingestion within the adult population is most common between ages 18 and 35 years and is typically the result of suicide attempt, or less often, acute intoxication. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Across all ages, male sex is associated with significantly higher risk for caustic ingestion at a 2:1 to 3:1 ratio compared with women. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Other significant risk factors for caustic ingestion include low level of education, low socioeconomic status, and living within a developing country. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Caustic ingestions that occur within developed countries are more likely to occur in the urban setting where children ingest unlabeled household cleaners in the home. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n## Pathophysiology\n\nIn the United States, most caustic esophageal injuries are the result of ingestion of alkaline solutions such as sodium hydroxide and potassium hydroxide with pH >12. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> These solutions are present in drain cleaners, hair relaxers, and dishwashing detergents. The extent of injury from alkaline substance ingestion is determined by the pH, concentration, and time of exposure which is dependent on volume consumed and solution viscosity. Injury occurs almost immediately. Ingestion of 30% solution of sodium hydroxide produces full-thickness injury within 1 second ( Fig. 42.1 ). The mechanism of alkaline injury is liquefactive necrosis, denaturation of proteins, saponification of fats, and thrombosis of blood vessels, which can result in transmural injury with extension into adjacent periesophageal structures. Ingestion of acidic substances is more common in developing countries where access to hydrochloric acid and sulfuric acid is more widely available in the form of toilet bowl and swimming pool cleaners. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Acidic substances with pH <2 result in coagulation necrosis. The eschar formation associated with acidic solutions is thought to limit the depth of contact and therefore result in less severe injury to the esophagus. Examination of esophageal tissue initially after caustic ingestion is notable for necrosis with edema, hemorrhage, and eosinophilic infiltration. Injury is further worsened by blood vessel thrombosis, which results in ischemic injury and venous congestion. Fibroblasts are abundant 4 to 7 days after injury resulting in deposition of fibrin and formation of granulation tissue. The esophagus remains fragile and prone to perforation until 14 days postinjury when there is collagen deposition. Scar formation and strictures may be present as soon as 3 weeks after ingestion. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nA photo of three endoscopic views depicts irregular tissue, an intervention, and a raised lesion with marks of some medical condition. The photos consist of three endoscopic views labeled A, B, and C. Part A displays a tissue section with a rough, irregular surface and presents a medical issue or irritation. In part B, a medical intervention will be performed, with a tool engaged with the tissue, possibly for treatment or examination. Part C depicts a focused view of a central raised lesion surrounded by affected tissue, which indicates a potential concern that may require further medical evaluation.\n\nFig. 42.1\n\n## Initial Presentation and Evaluation\n\nInitial evaluation of patients with known or suspected caustic ingestion includes a complete history and physical exam. Thorough evaluation is critical in guiding initial treatment, diagnostic selection, and disposition of the patient.\n\n### History\n\nInformation should be collected regarding the ingested substance and circumstances of its consumption. Helpful information about the substance includes identity, pH, concentration, and physical form (liquid vs. gel). Although it is often difficult for patients to estimate, knowing the approximate volume ingested and duration of exposure can help predict injury severity. History of depression and suicidal ideation associated with intentional ingestion are predictive of more severe injury which is generally attributed to a larger volume consumed.\n\nThe most common presenting complaints of caustic esophageal injury are nausea and emesis. If emesis occurs shortly after ingestion, the patient is at risk for a more severe injury due to double contact exposure. Other gastrointestinal symptoms include hematemesis, dysphagia, refusal to drink, abdominal pain, drooling, and oropharyngeal burns. Patients can also have symptoms related to respiratory involvement including stridor, hoarseness, and dyspnea. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Physical Exam\n\nThe physical exam should begin with evaluation of the patient\u2019s vital signs to assess for hemodynamic stability. Fever, tachycardia, hypotension, tachypnea, and hypoxia at presentation are all predictive of poor patient outcome. Prompt evaluation of the airway and oropharynx is critical as caustic ingestion can result in tracheal aspiration and laryngopharyngeal edema. The examiner should make note of mucosal burns of the oropharynx, hoarseness, and stridor, which can suggest respiratory involvement and impending airway compromise. The abdomen should be evaluated for signs of peritonitis and the chest wall for subcutaneous emphysema, which would be indicative of gastric and esophageal perforation, respectively.\n\n## Diagnostic Studies\n\nInitial diagnostic studies obtained in the setting of caustic esophageal injury help delineate injury severity, injury related complications, and guide initial management and disposition of the patient.\n\n### Laboratory Studies\n\nBasic laboratory studies should be obtained on all patients including but not limited to complete blood count, basic metabolic panel, liver function tests, coagulation panel, type and screen, and arterial blood gas. Parameters such as pH less than 7.22 and base excess less than\u201312 on arterial blood gas, white blood cell count greater than 20,000, and elevated C-reactive protein have been associated with increased injury severity. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In general, laboratory studies have been shown to be more helpful in monitoring and managing patients than in predicting their outcome.\n\n### Imaging\n\nPlain chest radiograph is used as a first-line study as it is a simple, quick, and inexpensive study to assess for esophageal or gastric perforation. Concerning findings include pneumomediastinum, pleural effusion, and pneumoperitoneum ( Fig. 42.2 ). The use of esophogram as an initial assessment tool has widely been replaced with increased computed tomography (CT) and increased availability of esophagogastroduodenoscopy (EGD). While there is ongoing debate, classically, the use of water-soluble contrast, such as gastrografin, is recommended in this setting as it is proposed to result in less irritation of the mediastinal, pleural, and peritoneal cavities if perforation is present. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Obtaining a CT of the neck, chest, and abdomen to further evaluate patients with known or suspected perforation is widely accepted as it is noninvasive and available 24 hours a day at most centers. CT also allows for better assessment of transmural esophageal involvement as opposed to EGD alone which may be limited to superficial evaluation. Ryu et al. created a CT grading system for caustic esophageal injury as seen in Table 42.1 . This grading system was based on a retrospective review of patients in which CT imaging was performed within 72 hours of caustic ingestion as a means to help predict future complications. It has since been utilized in other studies to evaluate the use of CT in the diagnosis and management of caustic esophageal injury. In a prospective cross-sectional study, 234 adults underwent both CT and EGD within 24 hours after caustic ingestion. CT imaging and EGD severity grades were compared. CT was found to be sensitive, but not specific for esophageal injury from which the authors concluded that CT could be used as a tool to rule out significant esophageal injury, but not to eliminate the need for endoscopy. Similar conclusions were found in a retrospective analysis in which 23 adults underwent both CT and EGD within 48 hours of admission for caustic ingestion. Although these authors found CT to be specific, it was noted to underestimate the severity of injury. Based on these results, the authors concluded that management decisions, including need for surgery, should not be based on CT findings alone. Given the lack of clear guidelines for timing of CT and EGD in evaluation of caustic esophageal injuries, a diagnostic and treatment algorithm was proposed by Chen et al. In their model, CT was performed as a first-line study on all patients with suspected perforation. Patients with evidence of perforation on CT were taken for emergent surgical intervention. Those without radiographic findings of perforation were referred for EGD. CT was only recommended after EGD on patients who had signs of clinical deterioration. Based on current evidence, CT imaging should be used as an adjunct, but not a replacement for EGD in evaluating patients with caustic ingestion.\n\nA composite of four computed tomography scans different views of the chest and abdomen, with various signs of abnormalities. The computed tomography scans are labeled A, B, C, and D. Part A shows a cross-sectional view of the chest and discloses air-filled spaces and bone structure. Part B displays a different angle of the chest, with visible blood vessels and potential abnormalities. Part C depicts an abdominal cross-section with prominent organs, which presents areas of concern, such as lesions and fluids. Finally, part D presents a further abdominal view and highlights possible abnormalities and changes in organ structure like cysts or masses, that require further examination.\n\nFig. 42.2\n\nTable 42.1\n\nComputed Tomography Grading System for Caustic Esophageal Injury\n\nFrom Ryu HH, Jeung KW, Lee BK, et al. Caustic injury: can CT grading system enable prediction of esophageal stricture?. *Clin Toxicol (Phila)* . 2010;48:137\u2013142.\n\n| Injury Grade | Computed Tomography Findings |\n| --- | --- |\n| I | No definite swelling the of esophagus wall (<3 mm, within normal limit) |\n| II | Edematous wall thickening (>3 mm) without periesophageal soft tissue infiltration |\n| III | Edematous wall thickening with periesophageal soft tissue infiltration plus well-demarcated tissue interface |\n| IV | Edematous wall thickening with periesophageal soft tissue infiltration plus blurring of the tissue interface or localized fluid collection around the esophagus or the descending aorta |\n\n### Endoscopy\n\nIn the absence of perforation, upper endoscopy is the gold standard for the diagnosis of caustic esophageal injury. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Endoscopic evaluation should be performed as soon as possible, ideally within 12\u201348 hours after ingestion ( Fig. 42.3 ). Endoscopy should not be performed after 96 hours as there is higher risk for perforation due to the weakness of the esophageal wall during this phase of healing. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Other contraindications for endoscopy include third-degree burns or necrosis of the oral cavity or hypopharynx and edema or erythema of the upper airway indicating airway compromise. In the absence of airway injury or respiratory distress, intubation is not routinely required for upper endoscopy. When endoscopy is performed, one should evaluate if injury is present, and if so, the location and extent of injury. Zargar\u2019s grading system ( Table 42.2 ) is the most widely accepted method for classifying caustic injury by endoscopy. Thorough evaluation includes inspection of the supraglottic and epiglottic regions, esophagus, stomach, and first portion of the duodenum. As the esophageal tissue is fragile and at higher risk for perforation, endoscopy should be performed gently with minimal insufflation. However, it is no longer considered mandatory to abort endoscopy if a circumferential second- or third-degree burn is encountered. While the utility of endoscopy is well established, there is ongoing debate about the need to perform endoscopy in all patients after caustic ingestion. In the adult population, caustic ingestion is typically the result of suicide attempt\u2014with large quantities consumed\u2014which has been associated with severe injury. Therefore, routine use of endoscopy in the adult population is generally accepted. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Several studies have investigated the utility of endoscopy in the pediatric population as these ingestions are typically accidental and in smaller quantities. Multiple retrospective studies have shown that symptoms at presentation are a poor predictor of esophageal injury severity and therefore endoscopy should be performed routinely. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Given the current evidence, the general consensus is to perform endoscopy in all patients with suspected caustic ingestion. Another area of ongoing investigation is the use of endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) as an adjunct to EGD in caustic esophageal injury. The utility of EUS was evaluated by studying 16 patients with both EGD and EUS within 24 hours following caustic ingestion. The authors found that although EUS was a safe adjunct to EGD, it did not help predict early or late complications suggesting that standard endoscopy alone is sufficient. While EUS may not be helpful in predicting short-term complications, EUS evidence of muscular layer involvement has been shown to be helpful in predicting stricture formation. Given this limited information, EUS appears to be safe but its role in management of caustic injuries remains unclear.\n\nA photo of three endoscopic views of various stages of internal tissue, with signs of irritation and possible abnormality. The photos depict three endoscopic views labeled A, B, and C. In part A, the view reveals a section of the internal tissue with creases and folds, which discloses irritation or inflammation. Part B depicts an area with some irregularities on the tissue surface, which includes possible bumps and fluid buildup. In part C, the tissue appears more severely affected, with discolored areas and irregular structures that indicate significant damage and a medical condition that requires further examination.\n\nFig. 42.3\n\nTable 42.2\n\nEndoscopic Grading System for Caustic Esophageal Injury\n\nSource: Zargar SA, Kochhar R, Mehta S, Mehta SK. The role of fiberoptic endoscopy in the management of corrosive ingestion and modified endoscopic classification of burns. *Gastrointest Endosc* . 1991;37:165\u2013169.\n\n| Injury Grade | Endoscopic Findings |\n| --- | --- |\n| 0 | Normal mucosa |\n| I | Superficial mucosal edema and erythema |\n| IIA | Superficial ulcerations, erosions, exudates |\n| IIB | Deep discrete or circumferential ulcerations |\n| IIIA | Focal necrosis |\n| IIIB | Extensive necrosis |\n| IV | Perforation |\n\n## Acute Management\n\n### Prehospital Treatment\n\nThe extent of esophageal injury following caustic ingestion is usually determined within minutes and therefore there is little role for immediate treatments. Induction of emesis, administration of ipecac, and gastric lavage are all contraindicated as they re-expose the tissue to the caustic substance. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Attempting neutralization with ingestion of a weak acid or base can result in an exothermic reaction and is therefore not recommended. Patients should not be given milk or charcoal as they may obscure subsequent endoscopy findings.\n\n### Medical Management\n\nGuidelines for initial management are largely guided by endoscopic findings based on Zargar\u2019s grading system. Patients with grade 0, I, and IIa findings on endoscopy are generally observed with gradual diet progression for 24\u201348 hours prior to being discharged home. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Patients with grade IIb and IIIa injury should be admitted to the intensive care unit for approximately 1 week. Total parenteral nutrition is initiated. A *nil per os* (NPO) status should be observed for 2\u20133 days and diet can slowly be progressed once patients are able to swallow saliva. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Patients with grade IIIb injury should be further evaluated with CT to assess for transmural necrosis or perforation. If absent, these patients may be managed conservatively, but remain at high risk for perforation and hemorrhage 1\u20132 weeks after ingestion. Patients with grade IIIb injury with transmural necrosis or grade IV injury should be taken for emergent surgical intervention. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Once initial disposition and management have been determined, the use of other therapies including nasogastric tube (NGT) placement, steroids, and antacids have been proposed with the goal of preventing stricture formation. Endoscopic placement of an NGT has been proposed as a strategy to keep the esophageal lumen patent to facilitate future dilation procedures and also as a means of enteral access. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Enteral feedings through an NGT have been shown to maintain equal nutrition and have similar stricture rates as feeding jejunostomy tubes. Some caution against their use arguing that the presence of a foreign body may promote stricture formation. NGTs have also been associated with increased gastroesophageal reflux which may result in more severe injury. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In summary, there is no evidence to support routine use of NGTs in caustic injuries. Investigations into the use of systemic steroids for stricture prevention have been primarily studied in children with mixed results. In a randomized control study of 83 children with grade IIb caustic esophageal injury, the treatment arm received 1 g/1.73 m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> of methylprednisolone per day for 3 days. Compared with the control group, these children had significantly less strictures (10.8 % vs. 30%, *P* \\=.038). However, in another randomized control study of 60 children following caustic ingestion, children who received 2 mg/kg/day of intravenous prednisolone which was transitioned to oral prednisone for a 3-week course had no significant difference in stricture formation compared with the control group. Given the lack of current evidence, the use of systemic steroids is generally reserved for patients with airway involvement and should not be routinely used for stricture prevention. In patients who are treated with systemic steroids, the administration of prophylactic antibiotics is recommended to decrease infection risk. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The use of antacids including histamine H <sub>2 </sub> receptor agonists and proton pump inhibitors has been proposed to speed mucosal injury. In a small study of 13 patients, the administration of intravenous omeprazole (80 mg bolus followed by 8 mg/hour infusion for 72 hours) was associated with a significant improvement at 72 hours compared with endoscopy obtained upon admission. The use of sucralfate has also been suggested to decrease the rate of stricture formation by creating a barrier between the caustic substance and the mucosa, preventing further injury. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Overall, there is a lack of evidence to support the routine use of antacids after caustic ingestion. As noted previously, most caustic ingestions in adults are the result of suicide attempt. In these patients, psychiatric consultation should be obtained prior to hospital discharge.\n\n### Emergent Surgical Intervention\n\nPatients with evidence of grade IV injury require immediate surgical intervention. Some surgeons advocate for surgical exploration of patients with grade IIIb injuries; however, others favor conservative therapy unless there is evidence of transmural necrosis with perforation on CT imaging. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The goal of surgery is to excise all necrotic tissue and establish wide drainage. In the setting of caustic ingestion, there is no role for primary repair of the perforation site. Patients with acute perforation secondary to caustic injury require exploratory laparotomy (with possible thoracotomy) with esophagectomy, possible gastrectomy, cervical esophagostomy, and placement of feeding jejunostomy tube. Neighboring organs including the duodenum, pancreas, colon, and small bowel should be examined carefully. All injured organs should be resected at the index operation and \u201csecond-look\u201d procedures are not recommended.\n\n## Subacute Management\n\nFollowing caustic ingestion, patients with at least grade II injury who did not undergo emergent surgical invention require close follow-up for management of esophageal strictures. Patients with grade IIb and III injury have a 71% and >90% stricture rate, respectively. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Strictures can present as early as 3 weeks after injury and therefore routine barium swallow at 3 weeks may be considered for patients with at least grade IIb injury. It is more common for strictures to present at approximately 8 weeks. Standard management of caustic stricture is esophageal dilation. Endoscopic dilation should not be performed within the first 2 weeks following injury due to the high risk of perforation. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Dilation is usually recommended 4\u20136 weeks following injury and is performed at an interval of every 3\u20134 weeks. Waiting beyond this time usually results in extensive esophageal fibrosis which can make successful dilation more challenging. Dilation may be performed with balloon or bougie (Savary) dilators. Savary dilators offer the advantage of tactile feedback which have been proposed to reduce the rate of esophageal perforation. For many patients, three to four dilation sessions can provide long-term esophageal patency. In those who have refractory strictures, the use of intralesional steroids, topical mitomycin C, and esophageal stenting have been proposed as an adjunct to dilation. The use of intralesional steroids has been shown to limit collagen synthesis and scar tissue formation following dilation. While methods vary, treatment typically involves four quadrant injection of triamcinolone acetonide into the affected area. In a study of 11 patients with refractory caustic esophageal stricture, the regimen of weekly intralesional steroid in conjunction with bougie dilation for five sessions was shown to significantly reduce the frequency of patient dilations and improved dysphagia symptoms at 1 year. Similarly, in a study of 17 patients, the use of intralesional triamcinolone acetonide used in combination with esophageal dilation was associated with significant increase in the post-dilation esophageal diameter and decreased frequency of dilations in patients with caustic esophageal strictures. Mitomycin C is an antibiotic with antiproliferative properties preventing collagen synthesis and deposition which has also been used in conjunction with esophageal dilation. Several studies have investigated its efficacy in children with mixed results. A prospective study of four children demonstrated that after one to two applications of mitomycin C, all children had complete response with no dilations, no dysphagia, and no adverse reactions at a mean follow-up of 2 years. In another study of 21 children with long-segment caustic esophageal strictures, there was an 85.7% cure rate after two to six applications. In a third study, 16 children received topical mitomycin C treatment with 62.5% of the patients having complete resolution/cure, 18.7% with a decrease in frequency of esophageal dilations, and 18.7% with no response to therapy. Although not demonstrated in these studies, the use of mitomycin carries a theoretical risk of secondary malignancy and therefore these patients need close long-term surveillance. Esophageal stents have been proposed as another means to avoid serial dilations with reasonable success. In a review of 10 patients aged 1\u201323 years old, patients who had benign esophageal strictures (nine from history of caustic ingestion) were treated with placement of silicone stent. Five patients had cure after stent placement. Similar results were found in a retrospective review of 11 patients undergoing polytetrafluoroethylene esophageal stenting following caustic ingestion. Eight patients were able to resume a normal diet after 9\u201314 months, whereas the remaining patients required ongoing therapy.\n\n## Chronic Management\n\n### Resection or Bypass of Strictures\n\nWhether the esophagus should be resected or left *in situ* during esophageal reconstruction remains a controversial issue. Patients with a history of caustic ingestion have been shown to have an increased lifelong risk of esophageal cancer. Given this elevated risk and lack of endoscopic means for surveillance, resection is typically recommended in children and young adults. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Retained esophagus has also been reported to have a 50% rate of mucocele development at 5 years which can result in abscess formation and compression of surrounding structures. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> However, performing esophagectomy at the time of reconstruction is associated with a nearly double mortality rate (11.0% vs. 5.9%). Dense adhesions are likely to be present and dissection can result in inadvertent injury to the trachea, laryngeal nerve, as well as increased operative time and bleeding. As both resection and retained esophagus are associated with risks, the decision to perform esophagectomy should be made on a case-by-case basis.\n\n### Delayed Surgical Reconstruction\n\nFollowing emergent esophagectomy, reconstruction is generally performed 6\u201312 months after injury. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Patients with esophageal strictures who have failed esophageal dilation may also undergo late reconstruction years after caustic ingestion. Conduit options for reconstruction include the stomach, colon, and jejunum. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> While the stomach is used most often in the setting of malignancy, its use is less common following caustic ingestion due to its involvement in the injury pattern. If the stomach is spared, it is generally the preferred conduit as it has an adequate, consistent blood supply, requires a single anastomosis, and requires shorter operative times. There are data to suggest that gastric conduits also have less incidence of conduit necrosis and in-hospital mortality compared with colon interpositions. If a gastric conduit is not technically feasible, the colon is the next preferred conduit. Advantages of the colon include its long length and acid resistance which helps prevent development of Barrett\u2019s metaplasia of the cervical esophagus. Drawbacks of colon interposition include preoperative bowel preparation, less predictable arterial anatomy, propensity for venous congestion, increased operative time for colon mobilization, two additional anastomoses compared with a gastric conduit, and poor motility. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> When neither the stomach or colon are appropriate for conduit, the jejunum can be used for reconstruction. The jejunum has the benefit of close size match to the esophagus and excellent peristalsis. Its length is limited by the course of the mesenteric vascular arcades which makes replacement of the entire esophagus only possible in 30%\u201340% of patients. If esophageal resection is performed at the time of reconstruction, it can be performed via the transthoracic or transhiatal approach. Passage of conduits through the posterior mediastinum can be difficult due to obliteration from adjacent injury and dense adhesions and therefore many surgeons elect to reconstruct substernally. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Long-Term Considerations\n\nLong-term complications of caustic ingestion include esophageal strictures and dysmotility, dysphagia, gastric outlet obstruction, and aspiration. Although less common, these patients are also at an increased risk for the development of esophageal cancer. Compared with the general population, patients with history of caustic ingestion are 1000\u20133000 times more likely to develop esophageal cancer (either adenocarcinoma or squamous cell carcinoma) with an overall incidence of 2%\u201330%. When esophageal cancer develops as a complication of caustic ingestion, it most commonly occurs at the tracheal bifurcation which is a site of anatomic narrowing. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Cases are reported at 10\u201330 years after caustic ingestion. Endoscopic screening for esophageal cancer is recommended in these patients if technically feasible based on their anatomy.\n\n## Summary\n\nIn summary, caustic esophageal injuries are typically the result of accidental ingestion in children and suicidal attempt in adults. Severity of injury is best evaluated by endoscopy which guides initial disposition and management. CT imaging is a useful adjunct. Grade 0, I, and IIa injuries can undergo oral intake challenge prior to discharge. Grade IIb and IIIa should be admitted for close monitoring and nutritional support. Grade IIIb injuries with transmural involvement and grade IV injuries require emergent surgical intervention. Patients with at least grade IIb injury should be closely followed for development of esophageal stricture which may be managed with esophageal dilation with or without intralesional steroids and stenting. The role of systemic steroids, antacids, and NGT placement to prevent stricture formation remains controversial due to lack of strong, supporting evidence. Patients are at risk for lifelong sequelae including stricture, dysmotility, and malignancy which may require future surgical resection or bypass procedures.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Mowry J.B., Spyker D.A., Brooks D.E., Zimmerman A., Schauben J.L.: 2015 Annual Report of the American Association of Poison Control Centers\u2019 National Poison Data System (NPDS): 33rd Annual Report . Clin Toxicol (Phila) 2016; 54 (10): pp. 924-1109.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Riffat F., Cheng A.: Pediatric caustic ingestion: 50 consecutive cases and a review of the literature . Dis Esophaugs 2009; 22 (1): pp. 89-94.\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: Contini S., Swarray-Deen A., Scarpignato C.: Oesophageal corrosive injuries in children: a forgotten social and health challenge in developing countries . Bull World Health Organ 2009; 87 (12): pp. 950-954.\n\nView In Article\n\n4.: Bautista Casa