7.7%2036.7c-.4%200-.6-.2-.8-.5l-7.3-12.7-7.4%2012.7c-.2.3-.4.5-.8.5h-5.8c-.3%200-.5-.3-.3-.7L166%2024.3%20156%207.1c-.2-.4%200-.7.3-.7h5.8c.4%200%20.6.1.8.5l6.5%2011.3h.1L176%206.9c.2-.4.5-.5.9-.5h5.7c.4%200%20.5.3.3.7l-10%2017.2L183.7%2043c.2.4%200%20.7-.3.7h-5.8zM192.015%2019c-.2%200-.338-.004-.3-.2V8.4h-3.3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[41. Esophageal Duplication Cyst - ClinicalKey|41. Esophageal Duplication Cyst]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "42. Caustic Esophageal Injury - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Caustic Esophageal Injury', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Caustic Esophageal Injury', 'Epidemiology', 'Pathophysiology', 'Initial Presentation and Evaluation', 'Diagnostic Studies', 'Acute Management', 'Caustic Esophageal Injury / Epidemiology', 'Caustic Esophageal Injury / Pathophysiology', 'Caustic Esophageal Injury / Initial Presentation and Evaluation'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '42', '437-444', 2, 31, FALSE, TRUE),
('Radiology of the Esophagus: Barium, Computed Tomography Scan, Positron Emission Tomography Scan, Magnetic Resonance Imaging', 'shackelford-9th-ed-5-radiology-of-the-esophagus-barium-computed-tomography-scan-positron-emission-to', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Radiology of the Esophagus: Barium, Computed Tomography Scan, Positron Emission Tomography Scan, Magnetic Resonance Imaging\n\nEva Mendes Serrao; Stephanie Bee Ming Tan; Soo Yee Naidoo; Vanessa Murad; Rajesh Bhayana; Nasir Jaffer; Myles Margolis; Patrick Veit-Haibach; Eran Shlomovitz; Satheesh Krishna\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 5, 44-75\n\n## Normal Anatomy and Imaging\n\n### Anatomy and Landmarks\n\nThe esophagus is a muscular tube that connects the pharynx to the stomach, measuring 18 to 26 cm. Its superior margin is at the lower border of the cricoid cartilage (C5/C6) and the inferior margin is at the cardia of the stomach. Thus, the esophagus has the unique distinction of crossing three different anatomic divisions (neck, thorax, and abdomen), which is associated with imaging challenges. The relevant anatomy is discussed under each imaging modality.\n\n### Imaging Modalities of the Esophagus\n\nImaging of the esophagus is challenging as it involves identification of static abnormalities in the structure of the esophagus and dynamic abnormalities in the motility of esophagus. This necessitates different imaging techniques, each with its own unique strengths and limitations. Knowledge of when to request each imaging modality or technique is crucial to achieve the correct diagnosis ( Table 5.1 ).\n\nTable 5.1\n\nIndications, Pros, and Cons of Each Imaging Modality in the Evaluation of the Esophagus\n\n| Modality | Indications | Pros | Cons |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Esophagram | Motility Reflux Stricture Postoperative leak | Can assess esophageal function Low radiation | Needs radiologist or advanced practice provider supervision Operator dependent Extraesophageal abnormalities cannot be assessed Dependent on patient mobility |\n| Timed barium esophagram | Objective method to assess esophageal emptying Used in patients with suspected achalasia or to assess postoperative response | Simple Low cost Can be used as a surrogate for manometry if patients are unable to tolerate manometry | |\n| CT | Staging of malignancy Assess postoperative leak Exclude esophageal injury | Quick Available at all times More sensitive for leaks than esophagram Can assess extraesophageal structures | Unable to assess motility Poor spatial resolution of the esophagus Higher dose than esophagram |\n| PET/CT | Staging of malignancy | More sensitive for metastases than CT alone | Unable to assess T stage due to poor resolution Poor assessment of locoregional nodes False positive from esophagitis |\n| MRI | Motility Staging of malignancy Postoperative complications | Promising technique for T staging No radiation | Not enough studies for widespread use Needs trained radiologist Time consuming |\n| Endoscopy/EUS | Local staging Histologic confirmation | Superior for T staging Superior for assessing nodal disease | Limited by esophageal strictures Can cause perforation |\n\n### Esophagram\n\nEsophagogram involves visualization of the esophagus using fluoroscopy after distension with a radiopaque contrast agent. Despite a reduction in utilization over time, the esophagram remains a useful adjunct in the evaluation of swallowing function, esophageal motility, reflux, and hiatal hernias. A routine esophagogram usually includes single-contrast (oral contrast only) and double-contrast (oral contrast with gaseous distension of the esophagus) techniques. Single-contrast technique is superior in evaluation of esophageal strictures and narrowing, and double-contrast technique provides superior mucosal detail for and enables identification of esophagitis or ulcers ( Fig. 5.1 ).\n\nTwo radiographic photos of the esophagus. Ch05\n\nFig. 5.1\n\nThe contrast agent of choice is barium sulfate suspension in various concentrations depending on the indication. Water-soluble iodinated contrast is used in specific indications, such as when an intraperitoneal leak is suspected, but for most indications, barium is superior due to better contrast and more effective coating of the esophageal lining.\n\nEsophagogram involves evaluating different portions of esophagus in different views and often involves multiple swallows. A template for standard esophagogram has been provided below, where each sequence in a standard esophagram serves a purpose. The role and expected findings in each sequence will be discussed. Often, radiologists tailor the study to the specific clinical indication or question.\n\nObtaining a brief clinical history from the patient prior to the procedure complements the clinician-provided history and helps provide an overview of the procedure. If there is a history of prior surgery, scout images (before administration of contrast) can be obtained. A balance between optimum imaging quality and radiation dose serves as the guiding principle in a successful examination.\n\nSequences that delineate structural pathology are obtained first while the patient is standing:\n\n  - 1.\n\tLateral cervical esophagus:\n  - a.\n\t\tTechnique: Single-contrast swallow of thick barium is performed first to ensure there is no aspiration as it is tolerated by the bronchi. Identification of large aspiration during initial swallows may preclude further assessment and result in early termination of the examination.\n  - b.\n\t\tPurpose: To exclude laryngeal penetration (contrast entering larynx but remaining above vocal folds) or aspiration (contrast passing below vocal folds) and to assess the phases of swallowing.\n  - c.\n\t\tAppearance: Smooth outline of the oropharynx and hypopharynx with a closed epiglottis ( Fig. 5.2 ).\n\t\tA set of two lateral computed tomography of the throat and neck with labeled anatomical structures. The left part displays a Computed tomographic scan, and the right side displays a Magnetic Resonance Imaging. Labels point to various structures in the throat. From top to bottom, the labels are oropharynx, epiglottis and valleculae, hyoid, thyroid cartilage, cervical esophagus, and trachea. The structures are marked with arrows that indicate their positions within the throat anatomy.\n\t\tFig. 5.2\n  - d.\n\t\tCommon abnormalities seen: Aspiration, Zenker diverticulum, cricopharyngeal bar or web.\n  - 2.\n\tAnteroposterior (AP) cervical esophagus:\n  - a.\n\t\tTechnique: Single-contrast swallows of barium are followed from cervical esophagus down to the gastroesophageal junction.\n  - b.\n\t\tPurpose: To outline any stricture or subtle esophageal narrowing.\n  - c.\n\t\tAppearance: The esophagus shows satisfactory distension throughout its length and has smooth margins. There are four sites of normal anatomic narrowing at the cricoid cartilage (C5/C6), aortic arch (T3/T4), left main bronchus (T5/T6), and at the esophageal hiatus (T10). These smooth indentations should be at recognized anatomic landmarks and not mistaken for an abnormality ( Figs. 5.3 and 5.4 ).\n\t\tTwo medical scans, where one is the computed tomography of the throat with labeled structures, and the right one presents a radiographic view, labeled with the median epiglottic fold. The medical scan consists of two vertically arranged panels. The left panel features a coronal computed tomographic scan that shows various blood vessels and surrounding tissues with a high contrast display. Key anatomical regions are identified with arrows pointed to the labels Vascular System and Knee Joint respectively. The right panel presents a radiograph of the epiglottis that emphasizes the structure. The composition utilizes clear labels and contrasts the elements to enhance understanding of the anatomical details.\n\t\tFig. 5.3\n\t\tThree photos where one is computed tomography of the thoracic esophagus, a radiograph focused on the gastroesophageal junction, and a view of the thoracic esophagus. The left photo displays the computed tomographic scan while the middle and right photos depict radiography. Labels point to structures in the thoracic esophagus and surrounding areas. From top to bottom, the labels are the thoracic esophagus, the impression at the level of the aortic arch, the impression at the left main bronchus, gastroesophageal junction, and stomach levels. The structures are marked with arrows indicating their positions within the anatomy.\n\t\tFig. 5.4\n  - d.\n\t\tCommon abnormalities seen: Killian-Jamieson diverticulum, branchial cleft cyst type 4 in the cervical esophagus; strictures, vascular rings, tumors in the thoracic esophagus; achalasia, pseudoachalasia, hiatal hernia, malignancy in the lower or abdominal esophagus.\n  - e.\n\t\tPitfall: If the patient is unable to take large enough swallows to adequately distend the esophagus, subtle regions of narrowing may not be detected ( Fig. 5.5 ).\n\t\tA set of two radiographs labeled A and B with arrows that indicate areas of potential narrowing and a closer view of the gastrointestinal walls. #REF!\n\t\tFig. 5.5\n  - 3.\n\tLeft posterior oblique (LPO) thoracic esophagus:\n  - a.\n\t\tTechnique: Double-contrast technique. Patient is instructed to swallow effervescent granules with a sip of water. The patient is then instructed to take multiple consecutive gulps of barium. The effervescent granules release carbon dioxide when mixed with water, which distends the esophagus lined by barium. This is performed in LPO to minimize overlap with the spine. Images of the distended esophagus and the subsequently collapsed esophagus (mucosal relief views) can be obtained.\n  - b.\n\t\tPurpose: Assessment of the mucosa. Mucosal detail is best assessed when the esophagus is distended. Mucosal relief views demonstrate thickened or irregular folds if there is reflux esophagitis.\n  - c.\n\t\tNormal appearance: The esophagus appears featureless when fully distended, and as the gas dissipates, rivulets of barium are trapped between the longitudinal folds of the esophagus causing smooth linear lines of barium ( Fig. 5.6 ). At the lower esophageal sphincter (LES), the vestibule or ampulla normally appears as a slightly dilated segment of esophagus between the \u201cA\u201d ring composed of smooth muscle superiorly and the \u201cB\u201d ring at the gastroesophageal junction inferiorly ( Fig. 5.7 ). The vestibule can be differentiated from a hiatial hernia as it does not contain gastric folds and demonstrates esophageal peristalsis. The Z line, which is infrequently seen, has been described as a zig-zag thin radiolucent stripe, which similar to endoscopy, demarcates the transition from squamous to columnar cells. Esophageal rings may be seen in both upright and prone imaging. If a suspected esophageal ring is not seen on upright imaging, prone drinking imaging often identifies the rings.\n\t\tTwo photos of radiographs labeled A and B depict esophagram impression results. #REF!\n\t\tFig. 5.6\n\t\tTwo radiographs of the anatomical structures in the throat and esophagus with labeled markers. #REF!\n\t\tFig. 5.7\n  - d.\n\t\tCommon abnormalities seen: Esophagitis, ulcers, reflux.\n  - e.\n\t\tPitfall: Precipitated barium can mimic ulceration. Imaging in profile helps differentiate them, because precipitated barium will be limited to the lumen, whereas ulcers project outside the lumen. Undissolved effervescent granules can mimic esophagitis but this is transient, as it dissolves and disappears as patient ingests more barium, whereas esophagitis will be persistently seen.\n  - 4.\n\tAP thoracic esophagus/gastroesophageal junction ( Fig. 5.8 ) with marshmallow:\n  - a.\n\t\tTechnique: A 1-cm marshmallow is swallowed with a small quantity of barium ( Fig. 5.9 ). This can also be done with a barium tablet.\n\t\tA radiograph of an anatomical structure with an arrow directed to a specific area. #REF!\n\t\tFig. 5.9\n  - b.\n\t\tPurpose: This helps to assess both structural and motility issues, such as dysphagia to solids, strictures, Schatzki ring, achalasia type 3.\n  - c.\n\t\tNormal appearance: The marshmallow or tablet should pass through the esophagus without holdup.\n\tTwo radiographs of a contrast filled esophagus, with a notable change marked in the second photograph. #REF!\n\tFig. 5.8\n\nSequences that delineate motility disorders (MDs) are usually obtained in the semi-prone position:\n\n  - 1.\n\tThoracic esophagus in semi-prone position:\n  - a.\n\t\tTechnique: Single-contrast study with swallowing of thin barium with visualization of the entire esophagus. Semi-prone position eliminates the effect of gravity on peristalsis. Patients are instructed to take a single sip of barium so that primary peristalsis can be observed through the esophagus.\n  - b.\n\t\tPurpose: To assess esophageal motility, achalasia, Schatzki\u2019s ring, or dysphagia.\n  - c.\n\t\tNormal appearance: A single bolus of contrast is seen propagating through the esophagus into the stomach. The tail of the bolus in the lower esophagus resembles an inverted V.\n  - d.\n\t\tCommon abnormalities seen: Disorders of peristalsis, namely absent contractility, diffuse esophageal spasm, hypercontractile esophagus (HE), or ineffective esophageal motility. Disorders of esophagogastric junction, such as achalasia or outflow obstruction.\n  - e.\n\t\tPitfall: Swallows between boluses disrupt primary peristalsis; therefore, it is important to instruct patients to take single swallows only. This is to be contrasted with the double-contrast sequence where patients are instructed to take continuous swallows to disrupt normal peristalsis so that the esophagus is adequately distended. With increasing age, abnormalities in peristalsis become more common and therefore require interpretation with caution.\n\nProvocation maneuvers can be performed for various indications, most commonly to assess gastroesophageal reflux. The value of nonphysiological provocation tests in identification of reflux is not well established, and exclusion of the complications of reflux, such as esophagitis, ulcers, strictures, or Barrett\u2019s esophagus, may be more useful.\n\n  - 1.\n\tReflux can be elicited in several ways at the end of the exam when there is already barium in the stomach. Patients are first positioned supine to ensure adequate volume of barium in the stomach. Evaluation for reflux into the esophagus is performed by subsequently turning the patient into a right posterior oblique (RPO) position, as this challenges the gastroesophageal junction. Simple provocative maneuvers include asking the patient to cough or perform the Valsalva maneuver in RPO position. More complex methods include the water siphon test where the patient is positioned supine and instructed to drink water while rolling toward the RPO position.\n  - 2.\n\tHiatal hernia can be provoked by asking the patient to bear down or cough.\n\nVideofluoroscopic swallow study (VFSS), also known as the modified barium swallow, is a study performed by a speech pathologist aimed to evaluate the oral cavity, pharynx, and cervical esophagus for oropharyngeal dysphagia or potential aspiration. It can be done in conjunction with the radiologist, who can perform a concurrent esophagram.\n\n### Timed Barium Esophagram\n\nTimed barium esophagram (TBE) is a form of imaging that allows easy and accurate quantification of esophageal emptying. It is performed in patients with achalasia, or following treatment of achalasia with pneumatic dilation.\n\nPatients are asked to drink a specific volume of barium (100\u2013250 mL depending on the institution) in 15 to 20 seconds. LPO films are taken at 1, 2, and 5 minutes after barium ingestion, and the height of the column of remaining barium is measured ( Fig. 5.10 ). The diameter of the esophagus can also be measured at the widest part of the barium column.\n\nFour radiographs represent changes over time in a specific area at 1 minute, 5 minutes, and 6 minutes. Four radiographs are arranged in two rows. The top row contains two scans labeled A and B, which depict a specific anatomical area 1 minute and 5 minutes after a procedure, with evident changes in contrast and shape. The bottom row consists of two additional scans, labeled C and D, that depict the same area at 1 minute and 6 minutes, respectively. The D scan features arrows that highlight a specific distance measurement, which indicates a measure of change. The radiographs utilize various shades to emphasize structural differences.\n\nFig. 5.10\n\nNormally, barium completely empties from the esophagus in 1 minute in most, and within 5 minutes in all individuals. In patients with untreated achalasia, the esophagus does not empty within 5 minutes. Following treatment for achalasia, there is ideally a 50% or more reduction in height in the barium column compared with pretreatment height at 5 minutes.\n\nImprovement in symptoms and esophageal emptying by TBE is predictive of long-term symptomatic remission following treatment for achalasia. Comparatively, improvement in symptoms only without improvement in esophageal emptying was predictive of recurrence during extended follow-up.\n\n### Computed Tomography\n\nComputed tomography (CT) evaluation of the esophagus is challenging as the esophagus is normally collapsed. This poses challenges in evaluation of both the lumen and the wall of the esophagus. Single-wall thickness is variable, depending on location, degree of distension, and sex, with a range of 2 to 6 mm, the thickest in the abdominal esophagus. Intravenous contrast is usually required for wall evaluation and extraluminal mediastinal abnormalities, such as abscess or trauma.\n\nIf esophageal abnormality is suspected, water-soluble oral contrast can be administered to distend the esophagus, which improves detection and characterization.\n\nIndications for oral contrast use include concerns for esophageal perforation or postoperative leak. Patients are given oral contrast while on the CT table to ensure there is still a small amount of contrast in the esophagus at the time of the scan, compared with the normal protocol where patients drink oral contrast 30 to 60 minutes prior to the CT where the contrast is expected to be within the small bowel or colon. If the patient is unable to tolerate oral intake, a nasogastric tube can be placed at the level of the cricopharyngeal sphincter if the area of leak is unknown, or proximal to the suspected leak if the area is known for delivery of oral contrast. Alternative contrast agents, including barium paste, neutral oral contrast (e.g., water), or effervescent granules, have all been attempted, with limited success in specific indications.\n\n### Fluorodeoxyglucose\u2013Positron Emission Tomography/Computed tomography\n\nPositron emission tomography with computed tomography (PET/CT) is a whole-body scan often performed for staging esophageal cancer. PET is performed in conjunction with CT, because CT provides an attenuation map that is specific to the individual patient. The CT can either be done as low-dose noncontrast, which adds little diagnostic value, or as a dedicated CT with intravenous and oral contrast. The benefit of a low-dose noncontrast CT is its low dose, which is preferred if there is low suspicion for disease or if the patient has had a recent diagnostic CT. However, when a diagnostic contrast-enhanced CT is performed along with PET, any abnormality identified on the PET can be cross-correlated on CT, which improves diagnostic confidence.\n\nMost esophageal cancers are fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) avid; however, due to poor spatial resolution, T stage cannot be assessed on PET. For the same reason, early cancers may not be detectable on either CT or PET/CT.\n\nPET/CT may be limited in the detection of locoregional nodal involvement, as FDG uptake within the primary mass may be difficult to differentiate from the surrounding nodes. Another drawback to PET/CT is there may not be FDG uptake in micrometastases. The main role of PET/CT is to detect extra regional nodal metastasis and visceral metastasis, and it has been proven to be superior to CT alone. Studies show that the use of PET/CT was associated with a stage migration in up to 40% of patients when compared with staging using only CT ( Fig. 5.11 ). PET/CT is also increasingly used in therapy response assessment in patients receiving neoadjuvant chemoradiation therapy, and for restaging in patients with suspected recurrent disease.\n\nA medical scan with five panels labeled A to E displays anatomical structures. Panel A shows a coronal scan with arrows that point to key regions, while the other panels focus on organs. Panel A presents a coronal view of the body with arrows that point to different anatomical structures. Panel B zooms in on a specific region that shows one anatomical detail indicated by an arrow. Panel C displays a cross sectional scan of the body that displays internal organs, with an arrow that indicates a particular area. Panel D provides another focused view of the body, with an arrow that indicates a region of interest. Panel E displays a fused scan with anatomical details and marked key regions. The arrangement of the panels allows for a comprehensive examination of the internal structures.\n\nFig. 5.11\n\n### Magnetic Resonance Imaging\n\nCurrently, the role of magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) in esophageal imaging is limited due to lower spatial resolution and susceptibility to artifacts from motion and gas. With evolution of newer sequences and techniques, there is renewed interest in the role of MRI, and its role in staging of esophageal cancer, the diagnosis of MDs, and assessment of postoperative complications are being actively investigated.\n\nMRI can be used for postoperative fundoplication assessment as it is the only modality that allows direct visualization of the wrap and assessment of postoperative reflux. Although this should not replace manometric or endoscopic studies, it remains a noninvasive method for diagnosis of reflux and is concordant with pH manometry in 82% of patients.\n\n## Structural Esophageal Disorders\n\n### Outpouchings\n\n#### Diverticula\n\nEsophageal diverticula can be divided into pulsion diverticulum or traction diverticulum. Pulsion diverticula are pseudodiverticula, which do not contain a muscular layer and are made up only of the mucosa and submucosa layer. Traction diverticulum are true diverticula, which contain all layers of the esophagus.\n\n## Pulsion Diverticulum\n\nZenker diverticulum is mucosal herniation through Killian dehiscence between the horizontal and oblique components of the cricopharyngeus. This is best seen on a lateral cervical esophagram as a gas and fluid-filled rounded outpouching, extending posterior to the esophagus at the level of C5/C6 ( Fig. 5.12A ).\n\nFour radiographs of different views of a medical issue with arrows to identify areas of interest. The four radiographs are arranged in a horizontal layout. Panel A displays a lateral view with an arrow that indicates a prominent structure. Panel B depicts a frontal view that displays a different anatomical feature with an arrow. Panel C presents a cross sectional view, with an arrow that points to a notable area of concern. Panel D contains a faint view of the surrounding anatomy, with an arrow that directs attention to another significant feature.\n\nFig. 5.12\n\nKillian-Jamieson diverticulum herniates through the lateral aspect of the cervical esophagus below the cricopharyngeus muscle. As it herniates laterally, this is best seen on the AP cervical esophagram as a gas and fluid-filled rounded outpouching, more commonly on the left ( Fig. 5.12B ).\n\nEpiphrenic diverticulum occurs in the distal esophagus, just above the LES, more frequently on the right posterolateral wall ( Fig. 5.12C ). They are less frequent than traction diverticula, and are often associated with achalasia, hiatal hernia, esophageal stricture, or web.\n\n## Traction Diverticulum\n\nThe underlying cause is traction or fibrosis in periesophageal tissues causing a diverticulum usually from endemic tuberculosis or granulomatous inflammation. This affects the mid-esophagus adjacent to involved mediastinal nodes and is best seen on the thoracic oblique esophagrams as a triangular outpouching. As they are true diverticula, they tend to empty when the esophagus is collapsed ( Fig. 5.12D ).\n\n### Impressions\n\nIntrinsic and extrinsic masses often result in an impression on the barium column on an esophagogram.\n\nIntrinsic impressions can arise from the mucosa or submucosa. Mucosal lesions create an acute angle relative to the adjacent wall and may have irregular margins, whereas submucosal lesions create an obtuse margin with the adjacent wall (\u223c90 degrees) and usually have smooth margins. Extrinsic lesions have a larger obtuse angle with the wall than submucosal lesions with an epicenter outside the esophagus.\n\n### Intrinsic Impressions\n\n#### Rings and Webs\n\nEsophageal rings and webs are thin shelf-like mucosal structures that can cause partial occlusion of the esophageal lumen.\n\nEsophageal webs are noncircumferential membranes that protrude into the anterior aspect of the cervical esophagus ( Fig. 5.13 ). Etiology is often unclear but thought to have a variety of causes, including Zenker diverticulum, heterotopic gastric mucosa, laryngeal carcinoma, or skin conditions, such as epidermolysis bullosa, pemphigus, or psoriasis. When associated with iron-deficiency anemia and dysphagia, this forms the triad of Plummer-Vinson syndrome.\n\nA radiographic photo of a narrow space between two structures, indicated by arrows. #REF!\n\nFig. 5.13\n\nEsophageal rings are circumferential membranes that protrude into the distal esophagus. These include the A ring, which normally forms the superior portion of the LES; the B ring, which normally forms the inferior portion of the LES; and the C ring, which is found in the most distal part of the esophagus and formed by the impression of the diaphragmatic crura. The most common of the rings to be associated with esophageal abnormality is the B ring, which has a prevalence of 0.2% to 14%. Clinically significant narrowing at the B ring, termed a Schatzki ring, can occur with inflammatory reaction to gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD). When luminal diameter at the level of Schatzki ring is less than 13 mm, this can result in symptoms, including dysphagia or \u2018food getting stuck\u2019. If B ring is seen on esophagram and at least 2 cm above the diaphragm, the diagnosis of sliding hiatal hernia can be made with confidence.\n\n#### Strictures\n\nStrictures are identified as segments of luminal narrowing and nondistensibility on esophagograms. Short-segment strictures can be seen with peptic strictures, Barrett\u2019s strictures, or medication-induced esophagitis. These usually have smooth inner margins and are found in typical locations depending on the cause. Nodular inner margins and shouldering raise concern for malignancy.\n\nLong-segment strictures can be seen post radiotherapy ( Fig. 5.14 ), long-term nasogastric placement, or caustic ingestion. Eosinophilic esophagitis is sometimes considered a long-segment stricture; however, some authors describe it as a small caliber esophagus. Multiple strictures are uncommon; however, they can be seen with graft-versus-host disease, epidermolysis bullosa, pemphigoid, or caustic ingestion.\n\nThree radiographic photos labeled A, B, and C show vascular structure. The three radiographic photos display a catheter in the thoracic region. Soft tissue contrast is evident in each view, with arrows that indicate the catheter''s path. Scene A depicts the catheter vertically, B presents a slightly shifted view, and C depicts the catheter''s endpoint. The background reveals subtle details of lung structure and soft tissue between the catheter and the surrounding anatomical structures.\n\nFig. 5.14\n\n### Extrinsic Impression\n\n#### Cricopharyngeal Bar\n\nThis is the prominent appearance of the cricopharyngeal muscle, best seen on a lateral cervical esophagram as a smooth indentation of the posterior wall at the level of C5/C6 ( Fig. 5.13 ). Although thought to mainly be an incidental finding, they can be associated with Zenker diverticulum or reflux disease.\n\nCricopharyngeal bar may be seen transiently in patients with cricopharyngeal spasm or associated with reflux. Bars may also be seen as a persistent indentation associated with fibrosis or severe spasm and may rarely require surgical intervention.\n\n#### Varices\n\nEsophageal varices can be classified by etiology or by anatomic location.\n\nWhen classified by etiology, they can either be uphill or downhill varices. Uphill varices are related to portal hypertension and increased upward venous flow via dilated esophageal varices to the superior vena cava. These affect the distal esophagus. Downhill varices are less common and are associated with superior vena cava obstruction. The downhill flow is via esophageal collaterals to the portal vein and inferior vena cava. These affect the proximal to mid-esophagus.\n\nWhen classified by anatomic location, they can either be esophageal ( Fig. 5.15A ), which are within the esophageal wall and project directly into the lumen, or paraesophageal varices, which are located beyond the adventitial surface of the esophagus ( Fig. 5.15B ). Often, esophageal varices is used as an umbrella term for both esophageal and paraesophageal varices; however, paraesophageal varices outside the lumen of the esophagus do not cause upper gastrointestinal bleeding and are not visible on endoscopy.\n\nA group of three medical photos with anatomical details with arrows directed toward the points of interest. Photo A is an axial computed tomographic scan of the abdomen that depicts the kidneys. Photo B is another axial computed tomographic scan of the abdomen that depicts anatomical structures. Photo C shows the abdomen or pelvis in the radiograph with an arrow that points to abnormal findings. The photos depict diagnostic scans that evaluate a patient''s condition.\n\nFig. 5.15\n\nAll types of esophageal varices can be identified on portal venous phase CT as well-defined tubular structures, which enhance to the same degree as adjacent veins. On esophagram, these appear as serpiginous filling defects in the esophagus on the mucosal relief views ( Fig. 5.15C ). These change in size and shape with respiration, peristalsis, and Valsalva maneuvers. They are not visualized on distended views of the esophagus. If they remain fixed in nature, these may represent either thrombosed/treated varices or varicoid esophageal carcinoma.\n\n#### Aberrant Anatomy\n\nAberrant anatomy can result in characteristic extrinsic compressions on the esophagus. The normal impressions discussed earlier including the aortic arch and left main bronchus all result in anterolateral impressions. Any posterior esophageal impression on esophagram is abnormal.\n\n## Aberrant Right Subclavian Artery (Arteria Lusoria)\n\nAn aberrant right subclavian artery arises from the aortic arch distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery rather than from the brachiocephalic trunk. To reach the right arm, it crosses the midline coursing posterior to the esophagus causing an oblique extrinsic impression on the posterior upper esophagus ( Fig. 5.16 ). If there is compression of the esophagus, patients may present with dysphagia, termed dysphagia lusoria.\n\nFour computed tomographic scans with a highlighted area of interest. The computed tomographic scans include four labeled photos, A and B are frontal radiographs that represent the trachea and bronchi with arrows pointed to notable features. C is a lateral chest radiograph emphasized on the heart''s silhouette. D is a transverse computed tomographic scan revealing the heart''s position and surrounding structures, marked with arrows for clarity. All scans emphasize different anatomical details relevant to chest assessment.\n\nFig. 5.16\n\n## Double Aortic Arch\n\nThe left and right aortic arch surround and compress the trachea anteriorly and the esophagus posteriorly. On esophagram, the posterior esophageal impression can be identified. Tracheal impressions are not seen, and on esophagogram, this is difficult to differentiate from aberrant right subclavian artery. This usually presents in young patients soon after birth and is the most common symptomatic vascular ring.\n\n## Anomalous Origin of the Left Pulmonary Artery (Pulmonary Sling)\n\nThis occurs when the left pulmonary artery arises from the right pulmonary artery rather than from the pulmonary trunk. To reach the left lung, it crosses the midline coursing between the trachea and esophagus causing an anterior esophageal impression.\n\n## Aortic Coarctation\n\nSmooth indentation of the posterior wall of the upper esophagus at the expected location of the aortic arch with a reverse 3 contour abnormality is identified in aortic coarctation. This corresponds to the shape of the aorta, with prestenotic dilation of the aorta, indentation at the coarctation site, and poststenotic dilation of the descending aorta.\n\n### Hiatal Hernia\n\nHiatal hernias (HHs) are most commonly classified radiographically:\n\n  - 1.\n\tType 1, sliding HH, where the gastroesophageal junction migrates through the diaphragmatic hiatus along with gastric cardia, with remainder of the stomach infradiaphragmatic. These can be large, but the fundus is always located below the level of the gastroesophageal junction.\n  - 2.\n\tType 2 paraesophageal hernia, where the gastroesophageal junction remains in its normal location, but the gastric fundus migrates through the diaphragmatic hiatus adjacent to the esophagus.\n  - 3.\n\tType 3 paraesophageal hernia is a combination of type 1 and 2, where both the gastroesophageal junction and gastric fundus migrate through the diaphragmatic hiatus. Type 3 paraesophageal hernias are differentiated from type I by the location of the fundus above the gastroesophageal junction.\n  - 4.\n\tType 4 paraesophageal hernias are defined by structures other than the stomach (or in addition to) migrating through the diaphragmatic hiatus (i.e., omentum, pancreas, transverse colon).\n\nType 1 HHs are the most common, making up 95% of HHs ; however, they are often difficult to diagnose. This is due to the normal physiologic mobility of the esophagus through the diaphragmatic hernia. In addition, the majority of craniocaudal movement of the esophagus through the hiatus occurs when the esophageal lumen is closed, which will be occult on esophagrams, as they require contrast in an open lumen for assessment.\n\nRadiologically, due to esophageal motion, there must be at least 2 cm of separation between the B ring and the diaphragm to make the diagnosis of sliding HH ( Fig. 5.17 ). Less than 2 cm is considered physiologic. However, it is only seen radiologically in 15% of patients, and specific maneuvers may be required to adequately visualize the B ring. In the absence of visualization of the B ring, the diagnosis can also be made if gastric rugae are seen above the diaphragm.\n\nTwo computed tomographic scans to compare structures measuring greater than 2 centimeters, with arrows that indicate measurements. #REF!\n\nFig. 5.17\n\nIf HH is seen on esophagram, there are several pertinent findings that should be mentioned in the report. It is essential for the radiologist to measure the length of the esophagus ( Fig. 5.18 ). A shortened esophagus may be caused by reflux, and if there is suspicion for a short esophagus, this allows preoperative planning for esophageal lengthening procedures. Size and reducibility of the HH and the precise location of the gastroesophageal junction in relation to the diaphragmatic hiatus should be mentioned. Importantly, paraesophageal hernia characteristics should be specifically defined.\n\nTwo radiographs of the esophagus and stomach, with measurements noted. Part A depicts the length of the esophagus marked with twenty one point thirty one centimeters and an arrow pointed to an undefined structure behind it. Part B, the stomach and bowel have ballooned like outpouchings with arrows identified with areas of interest that appear to be pushing out the side of the stomach. Both A and B are traditional medical diagnostic radiographs that are plain with the bones appearing relative to the surrounding tissues.\n\nFig. 5.18\n\nCT may have a role in assessing paraesophageal hernias as they are at increased risk for gastric volvulus and other complications, especially if a type 4 hernia is suspected.\n\n### Laryngeal Aspiration and Penetration\n\nThis is formally assessed by the speech pathologists with VFSS but can be seen on lateral cervical esophagram. Penetration is defined as passage of material into the larynx but not through the vocal folds ( Fig. 5.2 ), whereas aspiration is the passage of materials below the vocal cords.\n\n## Inflammation and Injury of the Esophagus\n\n### Esophagitis\n\nEsophagitis or inflammation of the esophagus is caused by numerous conditions, which can often be determined by the distribution of esophagitis and clinical symptoms. Endoscopy is the modality of choice although they are occasionally identified on other imaging modalities.\n\nOn CT, esophagitis manifests as esophageal thickening of greater than 5 mm and a targetoid appearance of the mucosa ; however, CT lacks the ability to further differentiate, but it is useful in identification of extraesophageal manifestations of the underlying disease if any.\n\nReflux esophagitis often involves the mid- to distal esophagus. On esophagram, reflux esophagitis demonstrates fold thickening or as subtle nodular or granular changes of ulceration ( Fig. 5.6B ). When chronic, peptic strictures can form a stepladder appearance in the distal esophagus due to fixed transverse folds from concomitant longitudinal scarring and shortening of the distal esophagus ( Fig. 5.6B ).\n\nChronic reflux can be complicated by Barrett\u2019s esophagus, which is columnar metaplasia in the lower esophagus and may be identified as a reticular (fine web-like) pattern on esophagogram ( Fig. 5.19 ). A Barrett\u2019s stricture occurs in the mid-esophagus, in contrast to a peptic stricture, which is usually in the distal esophagus. The stricture occurs above the area of metaplasia, as the metaplastic tissue is acid resistant and therefore not affected by gastric secretions. Endoscopy is more sensitive for detection of Barrett\u2019s esophagus, which is considered a precursor to esophageal adenocarcinoma.\n\nThree radiographs of vascular conditions with arrows pointed to anatomical features. The radiographs of vascular structures A, B, and C are arranged horizontally. Part A depicts a long, slender vessel with an arrow that indicates a site of interest. Part B depicts a similar vessel but with a more pronounced constriction, also marked by an arrow. Part C features the broadest view that highlights a branch structure with an arrow that indicates a critical junction. The scans have high contrast that emphasizes the vascular details.\n\nFig. 5.19\n\nInfectious esophagitis can occur throughout the esophagus with a preponderance in the upper to mid-esophagus. The appearance may be dominated by the presence of either plaques or ulcers. Plaques appear as an absence of contrast, whereas ulcers will have pooling of contrast that projects beyond the esophageal lumen. Candida esophagitis, much like candida elsewhere, presents with raised mucosal plaques, usually in the upper to mid-esophagus. When severe, or in immunocompromised patients, fulminant candida esophagitis can present with shaggy esophagus with innumerable plaques, pseudomembranes, and ulcerations, which trap barium. This should be distinguished from glycogen acanthosis, which can be radiologically identical to candida esophagitis with smooth well-defined plaque-like mucosal lesions throughout the esophagus. Glycogen acanthosis usually has rounded plaques compared with the linear plaques of candida, which can help in differentiation. Importantly, the patient demographic is different, with candida occurring in immunocompromised patients with odynophagia and glycogen acanthosis occurring in immunocompetent elderly asymptomatic patients.\n\nHerpes esophagitis, caused by herpes simplex virus 1, presents with small punched out ulcers typically in the upper to mid-esophagus ( Fig. 5.20A ). CMV and HIV esophagitis present with giant ulcers greater than 1 cm and are impossible to distinguish radiologically.\n\nThree radiographs of the esophagus of herpes and eosinophilic esophagitis. The radiographs are displayed side by side, each of which depicts an esophagram that showcases the esophagus''s structure. Arrows point to areas of interest, such as ulcerations in part A that represent herpes esophagitis, which is narrowed in part B, and rings or strictures in part C that indicate eosinophilic esophagitis. The radiographs highlight variations in esophageal morphology.\n\nFig. 5.20\n\nMedication esophagitis occurs with tetracycline, doxycycline, aspirin, and alendronate and causes erosions at sites of esophageal narrowing, at the level of aortic arch or left main bronchus.\n\nEosinophilic esophagitis can manifest in several ways, including a small-caliber esophagus of less than 2 cm or a ringed esophagus ( Fig. 5.20B and C ).\n\n### Caustic Injury\n\nThe main determinants of extent of injury after a caustic ingestion depend on the pH and physical form of the ingested material, amount ingested, and length of time of tissue contact. Solid caustic material will cause injuries to the mouth and pharynx, whereas liquid material will cause injuries to the esophagus and stomach.\n\nAlkaline material tends to cause liquefactive necrosis, which penetrates deeper layers causing esophageal perforation and ongoing injuries outside the esophagus until the material is neutralized by tissue fluids. Acidic material causes superficial coagulation necrosis with formation of eschar, which limits the depth of penetration and injury.\n\nEarly endoscopy is usually performed within 24 to 48 hours of caustic ingestion; however, it is unable to exclude extraesophageal complications. Studies have shown that contrast-enhanced CT is superior to endoscopy in detecting transmural injuries after caustic ingestion and in predicting stricture formation. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nThe 2019 World Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) guidelines on esophageal caustic injuries state that emergency endoscopy should be performed if CT is unavailable, if contrast-enhanced CT is contraindicated, or inconclusive. The role of emergency endoscopy is therefore limited to situations where CT cannot be performed.\n\nImmediate complications include esophagitis, perforation, and esophago-respiratory or esophago-pleural fistula, which are both rare. Subacute complications include empyema and mediastinitis. Chronic complications include strictures, diverticulum, or carcinoma. Esophagograms are sometimes needed to assess the length of a chronic caustic stricture, especially if the stricture cannot be negotiated with an endoscope. Squamous cell carcinoma is the most common subtype of carcinoma that develops post caustic injury.\n\n### Esophageal Foreign Body\n\nImpaction of a foreign body usually occurs at the level of the hypopharynx or at the sites of physiologic esophageal narrowing. In the pediatric population, it is often prudent to start with a chest radiograph to assess the presence, location, and nature of the foreign body and to assess for signs of perforation. Performing lateral and posterior-anterior radiograph increases sensitivity for detection and can help differentiate between tracheobronchial and esophageal foreign body. Some commonly ingested items are nonradiopaque, making them more difficult to detect. These include fish bones, chicken bones to a variable degree, wood, plastic, and thin metal objects, such as beverage pull tabs.\n\nIf there are concerns regarding perforation, a CT is indicated. If the foreign body is small and the patient presents immediately, often a noncontrast CT is preferred to a contrast-enhanced CT as small vessels can be mistaken for fish bones. However, if there is a delayed presentation, a contrast-enhanced CT is preferred to exclude complication, such as perforation, pressure necrosis, or abscess.\n\nWorkup to exclude an underlying disease should be performed, as up to 25% of patients have an underlying esophageal disorder. This includes esophageal stricture, hiatal hernia, esophageal web, Schatzki ring, or eosinophilic esophagitis.\n\n### Esophageal Injury/Perforation\n\nEsophageal injuries can be divided anatomically into mucosal, submucosal, and transmural injuries ( Fig. 5.21 ). Esophageal contrast studies (either fluoroscopy or CT) are necessary to confirm the diagnosis and locate the injury.\n\nThree anatomical photos of a lateral chest radiograph, a computed tomographic scan of the thorax, and a frontal chest radiograph are all indicators of esophageal pathology. The anatomical photos are labeled A, B, and C. Photo A is a lateral radiograph of the thoracic spine, with three arrows that indicate abnormalities in the vertebrae. Photo B is a cross sectional computed tomographic scan of the chest that showcases the heart and major vessels, with arrows highlighting specific structures. Photo C is a frontal thorax radiography, with one arrow pointing to an area of interest in the lungs. The scans are presented on a dark background for contrast.\n\nFig. 5.21\n\nMallory-Weiss tears occur due to violent projection of gastric contents against the lower third esophagus, which results in mucosal and submucosal injury. As these tears are not full-thickness perforations, imaging findings are often occult.\n\nNontraumatic perforation, also known as Boerhaave syndrome, most often associated with vomiting usually occur in the lower third of esophagus at the left lateral border. This is a transmural injury and extravasation of contrast can be seen on esophagram and CT with complications, such as extraluminal gas, mediastinitis, focal wall defect, or pleural effusion.\n\nTraumatic perforations are mostly iatrogenic. When occurring post endoscopy, common sites of perforation are at the sites of physiologic narrowing.\n\nThe 2019 WSES guidelines on esophageal perforation suggest contrast-enhanced CT, and CT esophagography as the imaging examination of choice to assess the perforation and potential complications. Endoscopy is useful particularly when a stent to cover the perforation or a clip for treatment is indicated.\n\nImaging findings include retropharyngeal or posterior mediastinal gas, pleural effusion more commonly left sided, and extravasation of oral contrast into the mediastinum. Delayed complications include mediastinitis or mediastinal abscess.\n\n### Esophageal Trauma\n\nIsolated esophageal trauma is rare and usually occurs in conjunction with injuries to the heart, spinal cord, or airway. Mortality with penetrating esophageal trauma is high because of the associated injuries, with most deaths occurring within 24 hours.\n\nContrast-enhanced CT and CT esophagram can help identify associated injuries and confirm the location of esophageal perforation and its complications.\n\n## Esophageal Motility Disorders\n\nContrast imaging studies complement esophageal manometry examinations in a variety of ways. Normal esophageal peristalsis propels food from the cervical to the abdominal esophagus via primary and secondary contractions in characteristic radiographic patterns. Primary contractions are the initial swallow-induced waves that propel food through the esophagus, whereas secondary contractions evoked by esophageal distention help move any remaining boluses unmoved by primary contractions. Tertiary contractions, also known as ineffective peristalsis, are nonpropulsive, transient, and intermittent waves, inconstant in location. Despite the various available classifications, MDs can be broadly categorized as primary and secondary disorders, with the secondary MDs often associated with systemic diseases ( Table 5.2 ).\n\nTable 5.2\n\nPrimary and Secondary Esophageal Motility Disorders\n\n<table><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Disorder</th><th scope=\"col\" align=\"\">Features</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align=\"\" colspan=\"2\">Major</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\" colspan=\"2\">Disorders of Esophagogastric Junction Outflow</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Achalasia esophagus types 1, 2, and 3</td><td align=\"\">Impaired relaxation of the lower esophageal sphincter and no peristalsis</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Esophagogastric junction outflow obstruction</td><td align=\"\">Impaired relaxation of the lower esophageal sphincter and normal peristalsis</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\" colspan=\"2\">Disorders of Peristalsis</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Distal esophageal spasm</td><td align=\"\">Normal relaxation of the lower esophageal sphincter and reduced latency of distal esophageal contraction</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Hypercontractility of the esophagus</td><td align=\"\">Also called nutcracker or jackhammer esophagus; normal relaxation of the lower esophageal sphincter with high-amplitude peristaltic contractions</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\" colspan=\"2\">Minor</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\" colspan=\"2\">Disorders of Peristalsis</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Ineffective esophageal peristalsis</td><td align=\"\">Low-amplitude esophageal contractions or fragmented esophageal peristalsis</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\" colspan=\"2\">Secondary Esophageal Motility Disorders</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Absent contractility<br>Connective tissue disorders<br>Scleroderma esophagus</td><td align=\"\">Low to absent pressure of lower esophageal sphincter; absence of esophageal contractions and peristalsis in smooth muscle of the esophagus</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Myasthenia gravis</td><td align=\"\">Low pressure of upper esophageal sphincter and esophageal muscle fatigue with repetitive swallowing</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Dermatomyositis</td><td align=\"\">Low pressure of upper esophageal sphincter and esophageal muscle fatigue with repetitive swallowing</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Diabetes mellitus</td><td align=\"\">Low-amplitude, multipeaked esophageal contractions and low pressure of the lower esophageal sphincter</td></tr><tr><td align=\"\">Secondary achalasia esophagus</td><td align=\"\">Associated with neoplastic infiltration of lower esophageal sphincter or Chagas disease</td></tr></tbody></table>\n\n### Motor Disorders of the Esophageal Striated Muscle\n\nThe MDs related to the striated muscle, cervical esophagus, are most often neuromuscular conditions that also affect the oropharynx (e.g., dermatomyositis and myasthenia gravis) ( Table 5.2 ). Uncommonly, both striated and smooth muscles (thoracic esophagus) of the esophagus are affected concomitantly. These disorders include mixed connective tissue disease and amyloid deposition.\n\n### Motor Disorders of the Esophageal Smooth Muscle\n\nThe clinical diagnosis of MDs consists of both manometric and clinical findings, with the Chicago classification version 4.0 providing the main diagnostic criteria and algorithmic approach to the diagnosis.\n\nEsophageal dysmotility may manifest with nonspecific symptoms, including dysphagia, often to both liquids and solids, chest pain, regurgitation, and heartburn, particularly in patients with achalasia.\n\nRadiologic assessment of MDs using esophagram can suggest the diagnosis, identify structural lesions, and aid in selecting the patients who might benefit from further evaluation by manometry. However, the overall sensitivity of barium esophagram for MDs ranges from 56%\u201369% to up to 89% when patients with nutcracker esophagus and nonspecific MDs are excluded. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Moreover, addition of the marshmallow or 13-mm barium tablet to the esophagogram protocol along with TBE at 1, 2, and 5 minutes can improve diagnostic sensitivity for MD and treatment response in disorders of esophagogastric outlet obstruction.\n\n### Primary Motility Disorders\n\nPrimary or idiopathic esophageal MDs are much more common than secondary esophageal MDs, with their pathogenesis remaining poorly understood. However, their diagnosis is important as new therapeutic agents emerge.\n\n#### Achalasia\n\nAchalasia is an uncommon disease of the esophagus affecting 0.2 to 0.6 per 100,000 people per year. According to the Chicago classification version 4.0, achalasia falls under the disorders of the esophagogastric junction outflow ( Table 5.2 ), which are characterized on manometry by abnormally high LES resting pressure and absent peristalsis in the distal two-thirds of the esophagus caused by degeneration of intramural myenteric plexus neurons. At esophagram, achalasia typically demonstrates a dilated esophagus containing an air-fluid level and food debris. The distal esophagus demonstrates a bird-beak deformity, caused by the high tone of the LES and aperistalsis in the mid- and distal esophagus ( Fig. 5.22 ). Not uncommonly, an epiphrenic diverticula in the distal esophagus can occur as a result of the elevated intraluminal pressure distally. In longstanding untreated cases of achalasia, the esophagus becomes markedly dilated and redundant, with the distal esophagus assuming a sigmoid configuration. Addition of TBE to the protocol can help identify patients who will benefit from treatment and objectively assess response to therapy in a simple and cost-effective manner. This is important as patients with achalasia have an increased risk of developing esophageal squamous cell carcinoma.\n\nThree radiographs of esophageal abnormalities. #REF!\n\nFig. 5.22\n\nBased on esophageal contractility and pressurization patterns, achalasia has been divided into three types, with the contractility and pressurization increasing from type 1 to type 3 ( Fig. 5.22 ). Type I achalasia demonstrates absence of esophageal peristalsis and a marked increased LES tone with varying degrees of esophageal body dilation. Type II achalasia (the most common type) shows periods of simultaneous panesophageal pressurization due to contraction of the muscles of the distal esophagus with intermittent LES relaxation. Type III achalasia has vigorous premature or spastic distal esophageal contractions with or without periods of panesophageal pressurization, having been recently postulated to be associated with the use of opioids. These different types of achalasia have different prognostic outcomes, with type 2 having the best response to medical and surgical treatment, and type 3 the worst response.\n\nSecondary achalasia (\u201cpseudoachalasia\u201d) may appear similar to achalasia on esophagram, but it is caused by an infiltrative malignancy at the gastroesophageal junction (most common), a paraneoplastic syndrome, or rarely Chagas disease. Differentiation from true achalasia is crucial given their distinct management and prognosis. Secondary achalasia should be suspected in older patients with reported rapid onset of symptoms including weight loss. In the esophagogram, it often presents with a longer and slightly irregular narrowed LES segment with mild or no proximal esophageal dilation ( Fig. 5.23 ). If secondary achalasia is suspected, endoscopy and staging contrast-enhanced CT of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis is usually performed.\n\nTwo radiographic illustrations of the esophagus. #REF!\n\nFig. 5.23\n\nChagas disease is caused by the tropical protozoan *Trypanosoma cruzi* , which is endemic to South and Central America. Cardiac muscle and smooth muscle of the gastrointestinal tract are often involved. The radiographic appearance is similar to achalasia and therefore a strong clinical suspicion is required for the diagnosis.\n\n#### Esophagogastric Junction Outflow Obstruction\n\nEsophagogastric junction outflow obstruction (EGJOO) refers to a combination of primary and secondary disorders characterized manometrically by impaired relaxation of the LES and normal peristalsis. The vast majority of cases of EGJOO are related to benign conditions, such as peptic strictures, large HH, eosinophilic esophagitis, tight Nissen fundoplication, or less commonly to opioid use, and subtle cancers. However, an unknown subset of these patients has a variant of achalasia. The diagnosis is based on high-resolution manometry and supporting evidence of obstructive physiology from TBE or functional lumen imaging probe (FLIP). Barium esophagram may help identify a structural cause (i.e., stricture or malignancy) as the cause of symptoms.\n\n#### Distal Esophageal Spasm\n\nDistal esophageal spasm (DES) is related to impaired inhibitory innervation, leading to reduced latency of the distal esophageal contractions. Patients with DES commonly present with intermittent dysphagia to solid and liquids, and chest pain. The diagnosis requires both clinically relevant symptoms and a conclusive manometric assessment showing simultaneous premature esophageal contractions in at least 20% of the swallows, and normal LES relaxation. Findings at barium esophagram are nonspecific. However, barium esophagram can be a very helpful supportive diagnostic test in this group of patients by demonstrating diffuse nonperistaltic contractions, which result in a rosary bead or corkscrew appearance of the distal esophagus. Tertiary contractions are often identified in normal patients and in those with MDs and should not be interpreted as indicative of DES unless confirmed by manometry. On CT, patients with DES can present with marked circumferential esophageal wall thickening (>5.5 mm), more severe in the lower esophagus than in the upper esophagus ( Fig. 5.24 ).\n\nA radiograph of the esophageal condition with arrows pointed at the areas of concern. #REF!\n\nFig. 5.24\n\n#### Hypercontractile Esophagus\n\nHypercontractile esophagus (HE), also known as nutcracker or jackhammer esophagus, is an uncommon disorder presumed to be caused by excessive cholinergic stimulation, leading to greater-than-normal amplitude of the distal esophageal contractions that are peristaltic. Diagnosis requires both relevant symptoms, most often dysphagia and noncardiac chest pain, and a conclusive manometric diagnosis. HE can sometimes be associated with EGJOO and other causes of mechanical obstruction, including GERD, obstructing HH, eosinophilic esophagitis, and gastric laparoscopic bands. Opioid use association has also been reported.\n\nRadiological diagnostic assessment of this disorder is limited and nonspecific, as most barium esophagram findings are often normal. However, BE can be helpful at ruling out possible underlying mechanical obstruction. TBE can be particularly important in patients with HE who fail pharmacotherapy, as it provides an objective assessment of the esophageal emptying, as well as the level of barium retention and obstruction at the LES.\n\n#### Ineffective Esophageal Peristalsis\n\nPrimary and secondary causes of ineffective esophageal peristalsis (IEP) are manometrically defined as low pressure of the LES and low-amplitude propulsive esophageal contractions, with more than 70% ineffective swallows or at least 50% failed peristalsis. Patients often present with dysphagia or heartburn. IEP occurs as a primary motor dysfunction in 50% of patients with GERD. This disorder can also be encountered in other conditions, such as Barrett\u2019s esophagus, diabetes with neuropathy, amyloidosis, acute ethanol ingestion, chronic alcoholism with neuropathy, adenocarcinoma, eosinophilic esophagitis, endoscopic submucosal dissection, regurgitation, chronic cough, and rheumatic disease. The findings at barium esophagram are often nonspecific and include delayed transit of barium through the esophagus with failure of the peristaltic wave in the most distal esophagus, and free reflux of barium from the stomach to esophagus. Barium esophagram with marshmallow can also be helpful at clarifying potential relationship between impaired bolus transit and symptoms.\n\n### Secondary Motility Disorders (e.g., Scleroderma)\n\nSecondary esophageal MDs are systemic diseases that secondarily affect the esophagus. Except for some diseases, the radiographic appearance is often nonspecific. Scleroderma is one of the most important secondary MDs to affect the esophagus. Scleroderma is an autoimmune connective tissue disorder of unknown etiology, classified as a disorder of peristalsis ( Table 5.2 ) according to the Chicago classification version 4.0, under the subgroup of absent contractility or \u201cscleroderma-like esophagus\u201d given its higher prevalence in patients with connective tissue disease. Manometrically, scleroderma is defined by absent peristalsis and impaired function of the LES, as a result of the underlying atrophy and fibrosis of the smooth muscle in the lower two-thirds of the esophagus. These patients commonly display severe reflux disease and eventually GERD complications, such as esophagitis, stricture, and cancer ( Fig. 5.25B ). At barium esophagram, these patients often have impaired or absent esophageal peristalsis, esophageal dilation, stasis, and in due course esophageal injury secondary to GERD. Severe GERD if left untreated eventually leads to distal esophageal scarring characterized radiologically by esophageal shortening, HH, and distal esophageal stricture with tapered margins and proximal esophageal dilation. However, in advanced cases, it may be difficult to distinguish it from achalasia because of the similar radiographic findings ( Fig. 5.25A ). Moreover, patients with scleroderma are also at increased risk of developing infectious esophagitis (most commonly candidiasis) due to stasis, and also Barrett\u2019s esophagus and carcinoma due to chronic GERD.\n\nTwo radiographs of anatomical features with highlighted areas through arrows. #REF!\n\nFig. 5.25\n\nPatients with diabetes mellitus can have mild dysphagia and increased risk of GERD due to the neuropathic involvement. Radiological testing is nonspecific.\n\n#### Postsurgical Dysmotility\n\nPostoperative dysphagia can occur as a complication of bariatric surgery, known as postobesity surgery esophageal dysfunction (POSED), or after antireflux Nissen fundoplication.\n\nPostobesity surgery MDs, including achalasia, EGJOO, DES, HE, and IEP, have been described in a significant number of patients. However, a unique achalasia-like pattern, known as POSED, can also occur in a minority of these patients. POSED is characterized by aperistalsis or tertiary contractions of the esophagus, normal relaxation of the gastroesophageal junction, and increased gastric pressure. When suspected, further investigation of the gastric pouch and anastomosis should be performed to exclude obstruction.\n\nEsophageal dysmotility can be found in up to 7% of patients after Nissen fundoplication with the majority having nonspecific motility abnormalities, followed by achalasia and DES. Barium esophagram is recommended in these cases to evaluate esophageal emptying.\n\n## Postoperative Esophagus\n\n### Techniques of Postoperative Esophageal Imaging\n\nPostoperative esophageal imaging is often required as a component of postprocedural care in patients undergoing certain esophageal interventions, with exact protocols varying between institutions. The role of postoperative imaging includes documentation of baseline anatomy, assessment of the effectiveness of the intervention, and detection of complications. In the early postoperative period (<4 weeks), the most common complications include leak, obstruction, conduit ischemia, and stasis. In the late postoperative period (>4 weeks), complications include gastroesophageal reflux, aspiration, stricture, and cancer recurrence.\n\n### Imaging Modalities\n\nChest x-ray is an easily accessible and inexpensive imaging modality, which plays an important role in the early postoperative period following esophageal surgery. Chest radiograph can readily demonstrate common thoracic complications, including pneumonia, pneumothorax, pleural effusion, or pulmonary edema. New or progressing pleural effusion, pneumomediastinum, and mediastinal widening on chest radiograph may raise suspicion of an esophageal leak prompting further investigation.\n\nFluoroscopic esophagram is the primary imaging modality for evaluation of the postoperative esophagus, particularly for the identification of postoperative leak and may be a part of the standard postprocedural care for some interventions. Timing is dependent on the type of surgery, institutional preference, and level of clinical suspicion for a postoperative complication. Spot control radiographs are obtained before administration of oral contrast to demonstrate the location of surgical material. Real-time screening is viewed by the performing radiologist and is repeated in at least two projections, which may include AP, left oblique, right oblique, and lateral. In the early postoperative period, these examinations can be challenging due to reduced patient mobility requiring the study to be performed with the patient semi-recumbent or in a sitting position, although an upright position is preferred if possible.\n\nCT is a valuable imaging modality following esophageal surgery. CT esophagography is relatively sensitive and highly specific for the detection of anastomotic leak. It allows for rapid diagnosis and is always available and can be performed any time of the day, as it does not need direct radiologist supervision, unlike esophagrams. Additionally, CT esophagram can be performed in patients who are intubated and cannot tolerate standing or semi-recumbent positioning for barium esophagograms. CT can provide accurate assessment of collection size if present and demonstrate extraesophageal abnormalities. CT also provides more anatomical information to aid planning if surgical or image-guided intervention is required.\n\nProtocols vary but typically entail a precontrast acquisition to identify any existing radiopaque material followed by ingestion of oral contrast on table with repeat imaging with or without intravenous contrast. Intravenous contrast is helpful if other abnormalities are suspected, such as pulmonary embolus or empyema; however, it is not necessary to solely determine the presence of leak. The choice of oral contrast varies by institution. Enteric contrast may be administered by a nasogastric tube placed above the level of the cricopharyngeal sphincter if the patient is unable to swallow. Advances in dual energy CT enable generation of virtual unenhanced images, which may obviate the necessity for dedicated precontrast acquisition thereby decreasing radiation dose.\n\n### Types of Oral Contrast\n\nThere are two types of oral contrast agent that may be used in the fluoroscopic esophagram: barium sulfate or water-soluble contrast. The choice of contrast depends on the institutional preference and the duration of time postsurgery. Water-soluble contrast is preferred in the early postoperative period as leakage of barium carries a risk of mediastinitis. Persistent barium may also result in artefact on subsequent CT, whereas water-soluble contrast is more likely to be reabsorbed.\n\nIf there is a suspicion of high aspiration risk, high-osmolar water-soluble contrast such as diatrizoate meglumine (Gastrografin) is contraindicated due an increased risk of pulmonary edema and the study should be performed with a low-osmolar water-soluble agent such as iohexol (Omnipaque). If no leak is shown on initial screening with water-soluble contrast, some centers recommend immediately repeating the study with thin barium as there is some evidence that due to its higher density and greater adherence barium is more sensitive for the detection of small leaks. Evaluation for late complications (>4 weeks) is also typically performed using barium.\n\n### Postoperative Findings\n\n#### Cricopharyngeal Myotomy\n\nFlexible endoscopic cricopharyngeal myotomy and septotomy is used to treat symptomatic Zenker diverticula. Postprocedural imaging, to exclude perforation and allow commencement of oral feeding, is usually performed with fluoroscopic esophagram initially utilizing a water-soluble contrast agent, then repeated with barium if no leak is seen initially. Alternatively, CT esophagram pre and post oral administration of low osmolar water soluble contrast has been advocated as an alternative to fluoroscopy and can demonstrate the presence of extraluminal air as additional evidence of perforation.\n\n#### Cardiomyotomy\n\nLaparoscopic cardiomyotomy, often combined with partial fundoplication to prevent gastroesophageal reflux, is a surgical technique for management of achalasia. As with other postoperative esophagrams, the study should at least initially be performed with water-soluble contrast. Esophagram following cardiomyotomy should demonstrate passage of contrast through the gastroesophageal junction and evidence of the fundoplication. Ballooning of the esophagus through the myotomy defect may be seen and is a normal finding. Findings suggestive of leak should be differentiated from a pseudoleak reflecting contrast within the fundoplication wrap.\n\n### Per-Oral Endoscopic Myotomy (POEM)\n\nPer-oral endoscopic myotomy (POEM) is a relatively new minimally invasive procedure for treatment of achalasia in which an enterotomy is made in the mucosa of the mid-esophagus with submucosal dissection to the gastroesophageal junction. Myotomy is performed to release the circular muscle fibers and to close the tunnel with endoscopic clips. Routine esophagram to exclude postprocedural leak is typically performed on postoperative day 0 or 1 although there is some evidence to suggest that performing selective rather than routine postprocedural esophagram only when clinically indicated may be safe and feasible. Intratunnel contained leak at the enterotomy site is the most common complication ( Fig. 5.26 ). Clinically significant mediastinal leaks are extremely rare. Pneumomediastinum, pneumoperitoneum, and gastric pneumatosis are not uncommon due to the use of carbon dioxide insufflation but should resolve within 10 to 14 days. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Delayed passage of oral contrast may be seen on the postprocedural esophagram but does not predict symptomatic or physiologic outcomes in patients being treated for achalasia at 1-year follow-up.\n\nA radiograph of an esophageal hernia. #REF!\n\nFig. 5.26\n\n### Antireflux Procedures\n\nFundoplication is commonly performed for intractable GERD, complications of reflux disease, and HHs. In the early postoperative period, the primary role of imaging is to identify leaks and to identify postsurgical anatomy. Later, imaging is performed in patients who develop symptoms to identify complications, such as abnormal tightness of the wrap and early herniation. The expected postoperative appearance demonstrates a smoothly marginated \u201cpseudomass\u201d at the gastroesophageal junction reflecting the gastric fundoplication through which the esophageal lumen passes. The fundoplication should be entirely subdiaphragmatic, without HH. Mild narrowing of the esophageal lumen at the level of the fundal wrap is expected. A very narrow lumen, proximal dilation, delayed esophageal clearance, or retrograde passage of contrast may suggest the wrap is too tight (\u201ctight Nissen\u201d) although esophageal obstruction in the early postoperative period is most commonly a self-resolving finding reflecting edema of the fundoplication wrap. Alternatively, recurrent GERD symptoms and complications can occur if the wrap is too loose, the wrap is disrupted, or the wrap slips distally to surround the stomach. Herniation of the stomach or wrap above the diaphragm can also occur.\n\n### Esophagectomy\n\nA variety of esophagectomy techniques exist and the expected postoperative imaging appearances vary depending on the type of interposition graft used, either gastric, colonic, or jejunal ( Fig. 5.27 ). Anastomotic leak is the major complication following esophageal resection and is associated with higher rates of strictures, prolonged hospital stay, and increased mortality. A multicenter retrospective review suggests that severe esophageal anastomotic leaks in the setting of esophageal cancer are also associated with poorer oncologic outcomes with decreased disease-free survival and higher rates of overall and locoregional recurrence.\n\nA radiograph of a fluid filled structure with arrows pointed at an outgrowth. #REF!\n\nFig. 5.27\n\nEarly postoperative leaks occurring in the first 3 days tend to be due to technical failure and later leaks between days 3 and 7 due to ischemia. Leaks most commonly occur at the anastomosis and can occur at any staple line. They are more common in the cervical esophagus due to the higher degree of tension and risk of ischemia.\n\nA normal postoperative esophagram should demonstrate patency at the anastomosis, the esophageal hiatus, and the pylorus with absence of hold up ( Fig. 5.28 ).\n\nA radiograph of a vascular structure with contrast material. #REF!\n\nFig. 5.28\n\nFluoroscopic esophagram is highly specific but has relatively low sensitivity for detection of anastomotic leaks, with reported sensitivity ranging from 33% to 52%. Thus, a negative study does not exclude the presence of an anastomotic leak and further investigation with another modality (such as CT and/or endoscopy) or a repeat esophagram should be performed if there is a high level of clinical suspicion. In view of this, there is controversy in the literature regarding the utility of routine esophagram following esophagectomy.\n\nAt esophagram, leaks are identified as the presence of extraluminal oral contrast ( Fig. 5.29 ). If identified, patients may proceed to CT to quantify the size of an associated collection. Obstruction may occur in the early postoperative phase due to edema. Stricture is seen as a segment of persistent luminal narrowing.\n\nTwo chest radiographs indicate the catheter movement inside the lungs, with marked areas of interest. #REF!\n\nFig. 5.29\n\nAt CT, demonstration of extraluminal contrast or discontinuity of the conduit wall is diagnostic of leak. The presence of gas locules adjacent to the anastomosis is a concerning but nondiagnostic finding, which can be normal in the early postoperative period; however, it is more specific with increasing time postsurgery. Mediastinal fluid collection, mediastinal air, and fistula have been shown to be associated with the presence of anastomotic leak.\n\nLate complications of esophageal resection may include stricture ( Fig. 5.27 ) or GERD, both of which can be assessed with fluoroscopic esophagram.\n\n## Esophageal Neoplasms\n\nCarcinoma, including squamous cell carcinoma and adenocarcinoma, are the most common histological subtypes of esophageal cancer.\n\nMalignant esophageal neoplasms may be diagnosed at routine endoscopy or at surveillance for known Barrett\u2019s esophagus. When symptomatic, patients usually present with dysphagia. Benign esophageal neoplasms may present with dysphagia but are also commonly discovered as incidental clinical or radiological findings.\n\nThe National Comprehensive Cancer Network guidelines recommend contrast-enhanced CT of the chest and abdomen as the initial imaging modality in the workup of patients with endoscopically diagnosed esophageal cancer. FDG-PET should be performed if there is no evidence of metastatic disease and endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) if there is no evidence of unresectable metastatic disease.\n\n### Carcinoma\n\nDespite modern advances in curative treatment, esophageal carcinoma has a poor prognosis with 5-year survival rate ranging from 5% to 30%. Squamous cell carcinoma and adenocarcinoma are indistinguishable on imaging although a specific subtype may be suspected on the basis of location. Adenocarcinoma tends to occur in the distal esophagus within regions of Barrett\u2019s esophagus. In comparison, squamous cell carcinoma is typically seen in the upper two-thirds of the esophagus and is associated with smoking and alcohol consumption.\n\n### Radiologic Features\n\nEsophageal cancer may be difficult or impossible to diagnose radiographically, unless there is asymmetric thickening or frank invasion. Unlike EUS, CT cannot delineate the layers of the esophageal wall and therefore cannot accurately stage the lower T stages (T1\u2013T3); however, it can visualize invasion of adjacent structures (T4). The primary role of imaging is staging, particularly the identification of nodal and distant metastases. Accurate locoregional staging is critical to determine the most appropriate management approach and usually comprises a complementary multimodality combination of CT, FDG-PET/CT, and EUS. Fluoroscopic barium swallow (esophagram) may also play a role in diagnosis in specific indications including assessment of length of involvement if endoscope cannot be negotiated through the malignant stricture.\n\n### Radiological Staging of Esophageal Cancer\n\nThe eighth edition of the American Joint Committee on Cancer (AJCC) staging system is the most commonly used system for staging esophageal and gastroesophageal junction cancers.\n\nTo classify tumor location, the esophagus is divided into the cervical esophagus and thoracic esophagus, and the thoracic esophagus further divided into upper, mid, and lower thirds. The tumor location is defined by distance of its epicenter from the incisors. Gastroesophageal junction tumors with epicenter within 2 cm of the gastric cardia are staged as esophageal cancers.\n\nTumor stage is determined by the depth of invasion within the esophageal wall. T1 disease is confined to the lamina propria, muscularis mucosa, or submucosa, T2 disease involves the muscularis propria, T3 disease invades the adventitia, and T4 disease invades adjacent structures ( Figs. 5.30 and 5.31 ).\n\nThree photos where one is a computed tomographic scan, and two are ultrasounds of anatomical details with highlighted features. The photo contains three sets of visuals where one computed tomography panel and two ultrasounds. Panel A is a computed tomographic scan that displays a cross sectional view with notable anatomical structures where an arrow indicates a region of interest. Panel B is an ultrasound that features a circular area with a textured pattern, indicated by three arrows pointing to specific features within. Panel C is an ultrasound that depicts a similar circular area with a more precise depiction of interior structures; a single arrow marks another area of interest.\n\nFig. 5.30\n\nA computed tomography of a highlighted area with an arrow pointed at a specific region. #REF!\n\nFig. 5.31\n\nRegional lymph nodes are defined as any periesophageal lymph node from the upper esophageal sphincter to the celiac axis, with nodes outside this region defined as distant metastases. Cervical and upper esophageal tumors typically drain cranially to cervical lymph nodes, whereas mid to lower tumors drain caudally. Skip disease to distant nodal stations, bypassing regional nodal stations, may be seen in up to 20% of resected tumors.\n\n#### Fluoroscopic Esophagram\n\nFluoroscopic esophagrams, also referred to as barium esophagrams, have little role in the staging of esophageal malignancy; however, it may contribute to the initial diagnosis if malignancy is incidentally identified in patients with dysphagia. Suspicious findings on esophagram must be correlated with endoscopy and biopsy for histological confirmation.\n\nAt fluoroscopy, esophageal carcinoma may present as a polypoid mass, ulcerating lesion, stricture, or with a scirrhous appearance ( Fig. 5.32 ). Typical findings of a malignant stricture include short-segment eccentric luminal narrowing with mucosal irregularity, luminal narrowing, proximal shouldering, and abrupt transition with the normal esophagus ( Figs. 5.31 and 5.33 ). In contrast, benign strictures present with a circumferential luminal narrowing, a smooth contour, and gradual tapering. Rarely, esophageal cancer may demonstrate an appearance similar to esophageal varices, termed \u201cvaricoid,\u201d reflecting tumor spread within the submucosa via vascular and lymphatic channels ( Fig. 5.32 B and C ).\n\nFive radiographs of various stages of contrast flow in the gastrointestinal tract. The radiographic photos labeled A to E are arranged horizontally. Each photo depicts vascular structures with varying levels of contrast enhancement. Arrows indicate specific points of interest in photos A, C, D, and E, where changes in the vascular pattern or potential abnormalities may be identified.\n\nFig. 5.32\n\nThree radiographs of anatomical structures with arrows pointed at specific areas of interest. The radiographs are marked A, B, and C. Part A is a monochromatic radiographic view with an arrow marking a significant area of interest, displaying dense tissue contrast. Part B presents a high resolution Computed tomographic scan with a diamond shaped structure and an arrow indicating another focal point, characterized by varying grayscale tones. Part C is a Positron Emission Transmission scan providing a coronal view, where the arrow indicates a metabolic hotspot, revealing a warm palette of colors indicating differing intensity levels.\n\nFig. 5.33\n\nMalignancies of the lower esophagus near the gastroesophageal junction may cause luminal narrowing with proximal dilation and delayed transit of contrast, a presentation described as pseudoachalasia.\n\nTracheoesophageal fistulas can be well assessed with fluoroscopic esophagram and if present indicates T4 disease. Fluoroscopic esophagram utilizing a water-soluble contrast agent also has a role in the setting of suspected esophageal perforation.\n\n#### Computed Tomography\n\nMost institutions perform CT for esophageal cancer with oral and intravenous contrast but do not utilize a specific esophageal protocol.\n\nWhile changes suggestive of esophageal neoplasm may be found on CT, CT alone is insensitive for the diagnosis of primary esophageal malignancy. Furthermore, CT cannot reliably distinguish between T1 and T2 tumors. Its primary role is in excluding the presence of T4 disease, potentially unresectable disease as well as nodal and distant metastases.\n\nWhen visible on CT, early-stage esophageal cancer may be seen as circumferential or asymmetric esophageal wall thickening. Normal wall thickness of esophagus on CT is 3 mm, but there is considerable variation and identification of definitive wall thickening is challenging on CT. Any wall thickening >5 mm is generally considered abnormal but not specific for malignancy. Presence of periesophageal fat infiltration indicates a T3 tumor. Demonstration of frank invasion of adjacent structures, such as the presence of a tracheoesophageal fistula or bronchial obstruction, is diagnostic of T4 disease. Findings that raise suspicion for T4 disease include loss of fat plane between the tumor and adjacent organ, displacement or indentation of adjacent structures such as the pulmonary veins, trachea, or bronchus, the presence of pleural or pericardial thickening and effusion, and greater than 90 degrees contact between the tumor and the aorta.\n\nCT can identify suspicious lymph nodes but has limited diagnostic performance for the detection of nodal metastases. Suspicious lymph nodes are defined as measuring >10 mm in short axis; however, CT cannot detect metastases in subcentimeter lymph nodes and false positives may occur in inflammatory or infectious conditions.\n\nCT has a primary role in detecting distant metastases, most commonly to the liver, lungs, and bone.\n\n#### Endoscopic Ultrasound\n\nEUS is superior to cross-sectional imaging for the locoregional staging of esophageal cancer due to its higher resolution. At EUS, the layers of the esophageal wall can be delineated as concentric rings of differing echogenicity. Reported overall accuracy is variable in the literature, ranging from to 71% to 92% and tends to improve with increasing T stage. Differentiation of T1a from T1b disease is important as invasion of the submucosa is associated with an increased risk of lymph node metastases and usually necessitates esophagectomy; however, there are mixed conclusions in the literature as to the accuracy of EUS for staging of superficial cancers with estimates ranging from 48% to 85%.\n\nEUS is accurate for assessment of locoregional nodal disease, with reported accuracy up to 80%, and can be combined with fine-needle aspiration for pathological confirmation. At EUS, findings suggestive of a malignant lymph node include short-axis diameter >10 mm, rounded shape, homogenous and hypoechoic echogenicity, and well-demarcated borders ( Fig. 5.30 ). A limitation of EUS is its operator dependence.\n\n#### MRI\n\nWhile the role of MRI in staging of esophageal cancer is an area of active and ongoing research, currently MRI has no role in the routine imaging workup of esophageal cancer.\n\nMRI is a promising technique for the staging of esophageal cancers. EUS is considered the standard of care in determining T stage, particularly for early-stage malignancies; however, MRI may have a role where upper endoscopy is limited by esophageal stenosis. There is good correlation between the degree of esophageal wall infiltration and pathologic T staging, with a pooled sensitivity of 92% and specificity of 67% when differentiating T0 from T1, and a sensitivity and specificity of 86% when differentiating T2 and below from T3 and above. MRI has similar sensitivity and a higher specificity than EUS when detecting locoregional nodes ; however, unlike EUS, direct sampling of nodes or the primary malignancy is not possible. There is a potential role for MRI in restaging after neoadjuvant therapy using the diffusion sequences, which is important as studies have shown that EUS does not retain its usefulness as a restaging modality after neoadjuvant therapy.\n\n#### PET\n\nFDG-PET/CT is recommended for staging of esophageal cancers if metastatic disease has not been demonstrated on CT. In detection of metastatic disease, FDG-PET/CT is more sensitive than CT alone. FDG-PET/CT has minimal role in determination of T stage as it cannot accurately assess the depth of tumor invasion. False positives may also occur in the setting of esophageal inflammation. FDG-PET has a role in the diagnosis of nodal metastatic disease but has low sensitivity with limitations including limited detection of nodal micrometastases and obscuration of lymph nodes adjacent to the lesion by metabolic activity of the primary tumor. Nonneoplastic conditions, such as infection or sarcoidosis, may also result in false positives ( Fig. 5.34 ).\n\nSeven representations of the radiological photos of an esophagus with cancer. The group of seven radiological photos of a patient''s esophagus with esophageal adenosquamous carcinoma. Depiction from left to right and top to bottom are part A with a barium swallow photo and a demonstration of an irregular stricture in the distal esophagus. Part B is a computed tomography of the circumferential bulge of the esophageal wall. Part C is an endoscopic view that reveals an ulcerated mass in the distal esophagus. Part D is a positron emission tomography that represents increased Fluorodeoxyglucose uptake in the distal esophagus. Part E is an endoscopic ultrasound of a hypoechoic mass invasion through the esophageal wall. Part F is a microscopic view of the tumor of malignant squamous cells. Part G is a microscopic view of the tumor of malignant glandular cells.\n\nFig. 5.34\n\n### Imaging in Assessing Response to Treatment and Surveillance\n\nWhile exact protocols vary between sites, it is recommended that patients undergoing preoperative chemoradiotherapy undergo CT scan and/or PET/CT prior to surgery. Interval distant metastases have been reported in up to 26% of patients at restaging after neoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy and identification of these patients is critical to avoid futile surgery. A study by Findlay et al. showed that FDG-PET/CT was more sensitive than CT in detecting interval progression following neoadjuvant therapy but insufficient in isolation, with 10% of patients having unsuspected incurable disease at time of surgery. A meta-analysis by Kroese et al. found that FDG-PET/CT detected interval metastases in 8% of patients following preoperative chemoradiotherapy, with a false positive rate of 5% indicating a need for histologic confirmation ( Fig. 5.35 ).\n\nSix medical photos of radiology of the esophagus and its cancers. The six medical photos of the esophagus and hernia compare the baseline scans and follow up scans of a patient. The baseline scan consists of an outline of a normal esophagus, computed tomography of a hiatal hernia indicated by an arrow, and magnetic resonance images, with arrows pointed at a hiatal hernia in each. The follow up scans consist of the same medical photos and display mild tumor signs indicated by arrows.\n\nFig. 5.35\n\nEsophageal cancer has a high incidence (45%) of posttherapeutic recurrence, usually occurring in the first 2 years with a median time to recurrence of 11 months. Distant recurrence, usually in the liver or lungs, is most common and less frequently locoregional. While there is no standardized protocol, most institutions utilize a combination of CT and endoscopy for detection of recurrent disease with the frequency and duration of follow-up guided by T stage and institutional practice. PET/CT has also been shown to be highly sensitive and moderately specific for the detection of recurrent esophageal cancer in patients treated with curative intent.\n\n## Other Esophageal Malignancies\n\nSquamous cell and adenocarcinoma account for more than 90% of esophageal cancers, with other types of malignancy being rare.\n\nEsophageal gastrointestinal stromal tumors (GISTs) are mesenchymal tumors that account for 1% to 3% of GISTs and resemble GISTs elsewhere in the body appearing as submucosal mass lesion, usually with heterogeneous enhancement and varying degrees of cystic change.\n\nOther, extremely rare esophageal malignancies include lymphoma, melanoma, and leiomyosarcoma. Minor salivary gland neoplasms, including adenoid cystic carcinoma and mucoepidermoid carcinoma, may also rarely occur in the esophagus. Metastatic disease to the esophagus is extremely uncommon, but it can occur in melanoma, lung, and breast cancer.\n\n### Benign Esophageal Neoplasms\n\nLeiomyomas are benign smooth muscles tumors and the most common benign esophageal neoplasm. Small leiomyomas may be asymptomatic and detected incidentally. Large lesions may present with dysphagia or chest pain. On esophagram, leiomyomas typically present as submucosal lesions usually in the mid- to distal esophagus. In contradistinction to mucosal lesions, submucosal masses tend to form obtuse margins with the esophageal wall, protruding into the lumen with an intact overlying mucosa ( Fig. 5.36A ). On CT, leiomyomas appear as well-circumscribed lesions with homogenous low or isoattenuation and smooth margins. The presence of calcification is highly suggestive of leiomyoma although it can occur in GIST ( Fig. 5.36B ). Small GISTs may appear homogenous and indistinguishable from leiomyomas; however, the latter is far more common.\n\nA radiograph and a computed tomography with arrows indicate a narrowness in a duct. #REF!\n\nFig. 5.36\n\nFibrovascular polyps are uncommon benign, slow-growing, pedunculated lesions of the esophagus that originate in the submucosa but present as intraluminal masses on imaging ( Fig. 5.37 ). They occur in the upper esophagus, may be mobile due to their pedunculated nature. When symptomatic, patients may present with dysphagia, respiratory symptoms, or regurgitation. On CT, macroscopic fat may be demonstrated within the polyp.\n\nTwo radiographs of esophagrams with arrows pointed to anatomical structures. #REF!\n\nFig. 5.37\n\n## Future Directions\n\nEvolving understanding of molecular biology and genomics is allowing clinical care to rapidly shift towards a more personalized medicine, with imaging playing an important role in this transition. The increasing synergy between molecular biology and conventional anatomic imaging is propelling diagnostic imaging to become more specific and sensitive. Improved techniques, such as dual energy CT <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> and photon counting CT, are emerging as new potential noninvasive diagnostic tools for the evaluation of the esophagus, particularly in cancer staging. In parallel, progressive advances in pixel-level analysis and artificial intelligence are also permitting new quantitative imaging features to be extracted mathematically in the field of radiomics, allowing new biomarkers, classifications, risks, and prognostic stratifications to be defined. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n## References\n\n1.: Zaheer A., Raman S.P.: Diagnostic Imaging: Gastrointestinal . 4th ed. 2021 . Elsevier ,\n\nView In Article\n\n2.: Levine M.S., Rubesin S.E.: Diseases of the esophagus: a pattern approach . Abdom Radiol (NY) 2017; 42 (9): pp. 2199-2218.\n\nView In Article\n\n3.: Dane B., Doshi A., Khan A., Megibow A.: Utility of water siphon maneuver for eliciting gastroesophageal reflux during barium esophagography: correlation with histologic findings . AJR Am J Roentgenol 2018; 211 (2): pp. 335-339.\n\nView In Article\n\n4.: Neyaz Z., Gupta M., Ghoshal U.C.: How to perform and int