ing', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'Esophageal Imaging', 'Barium Esophagram', 'Computed Tomography', 'Positron Emission Tomography', 'Magnetic Resonance Imaging', 'Motility Disorders', 'Esophageal Imaging / Barium Esophagram', 'Esophageal Imaging / Computed Tomography', 'Esophageal Imaging / Positron Emission Tomography'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '5', '44-75', 2, 83, FALSE, TRUE),
('Esophageal Symptoms and Selection of Diagnostic Tests', 'shackelford-9th-ed-6-esophageal-symptoms-and-selection-of-diagnostic-tests', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Esophageal Symptoms and Selection of Diagnostic Tests\n\nAndres R. Latorre-Rodriguez; Sumeet K. Mittal; Ross M. Bremner\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 6, 76-88\n\n## Introduction\n\nA surgeon evaluating a patient before a possible esophageal operation must spend sufficient time in conversation with that patient to ensure a clear understanding of their symptoms. Such dialogue illuminates not only potential causes of the symptoms but, more importantly, whether a given surgical procedure can resolve them. The spectrum of symptoms in esophageal diseases is wide, ranging from common typical symptoms (e.g., heartburn, regurgitation, and dysphagia) to atypical symptoms (e.g., cough, voice changes, chest pain, and globus sensation). Esophageal symptoms are often vague, which should prompt further questioning of the patient. Surgeons should also be familiar with the concept of *functional heartburn* so that surgery is not performed for patients who would not benefit from surgical intervention.\n\nThe tests used to evaluate symptoms should be selected in accordance with the suspected underlying pathology. Functional testing is critical when a functional operation is planned, but in the present era of cost containment, exhaustive testing is not always necessary. Nonetheless, shortcuts should be avoided, as most functional testing adds meaningful information to the assessment of a patient\u2019s pathology. Surgery performed for the incorrect indication can be disastrous, particularly because the esophagus is a relatively unforgiving organ and reoperative surgery is challenging. The most common cause of failure of antireflux surgery is poor patient selection ; therefore, thoughtful analysis of presenting symptoms and a complete workup to identify the cause of these symptoms are necessary before the surgeon advises a surgical procedure for a functional esophageal disorder. Surgeons should be aware of the possibility of malignancy in patients who experience dysphagia, as dysphagia is the most common presenting symptom associated with esophageal cancer.\n\n## Origin Of Esophageal Sensation\n\nSensory nerve fibers in the esophagus are present in both the muscle and mucosa and are carried in the vagus nerve and spinal nerves. The vagus nerve afferents have been described as tension-sensitive fibers with a low threshold for response. They are thought to contribute to physiologic reflexes. The spinal afferents likely provide a nociceptor function and convey noxious intensity of various stimuli. Stimuli that excite these afferents include distention and exposure to acid. The afferent nerves have been classified as muscle-tension-sensitive, mucosal mechano/chemosensitive, and tension/mucosal receptors; however, most afferent fibers respond to both mechanical and chemical stimuli. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Acid excites primary sensory neurons in the esophagus by activating two proton-gated channels: transient receptor potential vanilloid-1 (TRPV1) and acid-sensing ion channels. The latter is thought to mediate heartburn in nonerosive reflux disease (NERD). The activation of the TRPV1 channel by acid can initiate neurogenic inflammation and the release of proinflammatory substances from the surrounding cellular matrix, with a resulting increase in noxious stimuli. Visceral hypersensitivity in patients with NERD appears to involve neurogenic inflammation with an increase in both release of substance P and expression of neurokinin 1 receptor, which in turn activates TRPV1 and protease-activated receptor 2.\n\nSeveral tests have historically been used to understand esophageal symptomatology, including acid infusion (i.e., the Bernstein test) and balloon distention. These proved to be useful for understanding the stimulus\u2013symptom axis of the esophagus, but they are seldom used in today\u2019s clinical practice. The sensory neurons from the heart and esophagus converge on the dorsal horns of the spinal cord, which likely explains the overlap of pain from either organ and often prompts suspicion of myocardial infarction in patients with severe esophageal spastic syndromes. Sex differences in esophageal symptom perception has also been described, with men having both a lower tolerance to acid perfusion and greater sensitivity to balloon distention after acid sensitization. Hyperalgesia (i.e., the heightened perception of painful stimuli) appears to occur over a greater anatomical region in women.\n\nSensory hypersensitivity includes both hyperalgesia and allodynia (i.e., the perception of pain from non-painful stimuli) and can be caused by exposure to acid, among other things. *Functional heartburn* describes the symptom of retrosternal burning that occurs without objective evidence of abnormal exposure of the esophagus to gastric contents. Early studies that characterized symptom perception in patients after balloon distention showed highly variable patient responses. Stimulus localization was poor, and perception of the distention as pain, nausea, or heartburn was also quite variable. These findings underscore the need for complete testing in patients presenting with various esophageal symptoms, especially when surgery is being considered as a treatment option.\n\n## Symptoms\n\nGastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) is the most commonly diagnosed digestive disorder among Americans with a prevalence between 20% and 40%; it is responsible for most presenting esophageal symptoms. GERD symptoms are classified as typical or atypical. Typical symptoms of GERD include heartburn and regurgitation (some authors include dysphagia); atypical symptoms include noncardiac chest pain, chronic cough and asthma, hoarseness and dental caries, nausea and vomiting, and globus sensation. A global consensus group defined GERD as troublesome symptoms or complications that result from reflux of gastric contents into the esophagus. Moreover, GERD has been further classified into three distinct phenotypes based on the endoscopic and histopathological findings: NERD, erosive esophagitis, and Barrett\u2019s esophagus. Patients with NERD comprise up to 70% of patients who experience reflux symptoms. Erosive disease and esophageal stricture may be related to the concentration of the refluxed acid as well as the duration of exposure.\n\n### Typical Symptoms of GERD\n\n#### Heartburn\n\nThe most common esophageal symptom of GERD is heartburn, usually resulting from reflux of acidic gastric contents into the esophagus. Acid irritates the esophageal mucosa, stimulating nociceptors and causing heartburn. The relationship between acid exposure and heartburn is complex, as evidenced by the variable response to acid suppression therapy (especially in patients with NERD). Up to 60% of the Western population experience heartburn at least once every year, and 20% to 30% have weekly symptoms. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Heartburn is usually described as retrosternal burning that ascends from the epigastrium toward the throat. The classic billboard advertisements for proton pump inhibitors (PPIs)\u2014featuring a patient with a grimace and a balled-up hand held to the chest\u2014is an apt representation of the sensation.\n\nMany patients describe heartburn that is aggravated by eating spicy or fatty meals, drinking citrus juice, or consuming chocolate, alcohol, or coffee. It is frequently associated with regurgitation, which is exacerbated by postural changes, such as bending down to tie one\u2019s shoelace. Heartburn is usually relieved by antacids or antisecretory medications, and the availability of over-the-counter PPIs and antisecretory medications have led to widespread use of these remedies. Frequently, patients are completely dependent on these medications, and withdrawal of PPIs results in a rapid return of heartburn. It is therefore important to ask the patient about their use of these medications and what symptoms they experience when the medication is withheld. Nocturnal heartburn appears to be an especially serious symptom, as noted by a Gallup poll conducted by the American Gastroenterological Association ( Box 6.1 ).\n\nBox 6.1\n\nNighttime Heartburn Is an Underappreciated Clinical Problem\n\n  - \u2022\n\t50 million Americans have nighttime heartburn at least once per week\n  - \u2022\n\t45% of heartburn sufferers report that current remedies do not relieve all of their symptoms\n  - \u2022\n\t63% report that heartburn affects their ability to sleep and impacts their work the next day\n  - \u2022\n\t72% are taking prescription medications\n  - \u2022\n\t80% of heartburn sufferers had nocturnal symptoms\u201465% both day and night\n\nThe most appropriate objective measurement of refluxed gastric acid as a cause of patient symptoms is the 24-hour pH monitoring test. The 24-hour catheter-based pH monitoring test has been well studied and documented by Johnson and DeMeester, and their composite score helps distinguish normal acid exposure from abnormal levels, as described in Table 6.1 . Capsule-based acid detection has become the most frequently used pH monitoring method as it is more easily tolerated by the patient than a transnasal catheter (both methods are described below).\n\nTable 6.1\n\nNormal Values of Six Components of the 24-Hour Record for 50 Healthy Volunteers\n\n| | Mean | 95th Percentile |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Total time pH < 4 (%) | 1.51 | 4.45 |\n| Upright time pH < 4 (%) | 2.34 | 8.42 |\n| Supine time pH < 4 (%) | 0.63 | 3.45 |\n| Number of episodes | 19.00 | 46.90 |\n| Number of episodes \u2265 5 minutes | 0.84 | 3.45 |\n| Longest episode | 6.74 | 19.80 |\n\n#### Functional Heartburn\n\n*Functional heartburn* , which is a concept developed further since the 2000s, refers to the manifestation of \u201cheartburn\u201d in a patient with no objective evidence of pathological reflux. Galmiche et al. have defined the diagnostic criteria of functional heartburn, which requires a negative impedance study to exclude patients experiencing symptoms with either weak-acid or alkaline reflux. Similarly, functional chest pain is presumed to be of esophageal origin but has a negative workup on routine testing. A study of pH impedance testing in 2015 showed that 30% of PPI-refractory patients experience functional heartburn ; thus, a lack of response to adequate PPI therapy is another relevant starting point for considering a functional heartburn diagnosis. These patients may have altered visceral hypersensitivity as their condition frequently overlaps with other functional abnormalities and various psychiatric disorders. In patients with functional heartburn, antireflux surgery outcomes are often poor, which drives home the importance of pH testing (and perhaps impedance testing) before antireflux surgery is considered. Treatment for functional heartburn usually includes antidepressants (i.e., selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors, tricyclic antidepressants, or histamine-2 receptor antagonists), which are thought to have a neuromodulatory role in hypersensitivity disorders. Moreover, antacid therapy including PPIs has no utility for functional heartburn management unless proven GERD overlaps with functional heartburn. Currently, a diagnosis of overlapping GERD and functional heartburn is made using Rome IV criteria when heartburn persists despite a maximal PPI dose in patients with GERD, and pH impedance testing while on PPI therapy has shown physiological distal acid exposure without associated symptoms of reflux.\n\nThe functional heartburn category of patients again reaffirms the sometimes-vague presentation of esophageal pathologies and certainly adds weight to the argument that GERD must be objectively diagnosed with pH or pH impedance testing before surgery is considered in the absence of another indication for surgery such as paraesophageal hernia.\n\n#### Regurgitation\n\n*Regurgitation* is the effortless return of gastric contents or recently ingested food or liquid into the back of the throat or mouth, and it is often exacerbated by postural changes. This symptom is most frequently accompanied by heartburn, but it may occur in isolation in patients on adequate acid-suppression therapy (i.e., PPIs). A significant decrease in refluxate pH, a high volume of proximal refluxate, and delayed esophageal clearance increase the probability that a patient will experience heartburn and regurgitation.\n\nRegurgitation occurring at night is especially significant, as it may result in silent aspiration and lung damage. Delayed gastric emptying may exacerbate regurgitation.\n\n#### Dysphagia\n\nDysphagia may be either oropharyngeal or esophageal in origin. Oropharyngeal dysphagia may result from mechanical, obstructive, functional, or neurological causes. Esophageal dysphagia usually results from a mechanical obstruction or poor bolus transport (i.e., hypomotility or uncoordinated, spastic contractions). Patients can frequently identify the general area in which dysphagia is occurring, but this is not always reliable. Dysphagia is often referred to as an \u201calarm\u201d or \u201cred flag\u201d symptom, as it is usually the primary presenting symptom of esophageal cancer. It is common, however, and can accompany GERD with or without stricture or several other benign disorders. Symptom duration and rapidity of progression often offer clues regarding the pathology. Rapid progression of dysphagia that inhibits swallowing solids first and ultimately impedes swallowing of liquids over weeks or months forebodes a malignant process, whereas a slow progression over years suggests an underlying motility disorder such as achalasia. Patients often initially compensate for solid food dysphagia by avoiding dense solid foods (e.g., steak, chicken), chewing food very well, or eating only soft food.\n\nIf dysphagia is accompanied by a prominent history of heartburn, the surgeon should consider peptic stricture, but patients with achalasia sometimes experience \u201cheartburn,\u201d and reflux disease is the culprit of most esophageal carcinomas in Western countries. Potential causes of esophageal dysphagia are listed in Box 6.2 .\n\nBox 6.2\n\nPotential Causes of Dysphagia\n\n  - \u2022\n\tCancer\n  - \u2022\n\tCongenital webs\n  - \u2022\n\tCongenital aberrant subclavian artery (i.e., dysphagia lusoria)\n  - \u2022\n\tSchatzki ring\n  - \u2022\n\tBenign stricture\n  - \u2022\n\t\tPeptic\n  - \u2022\n\t\tEosinophilic esophagitis\n  - \u2022\n\t\tPill-induced or caustic-induced\n  - \u2022\n\tMotility abnormalities\n  - \u2022\n\t\tAchalasia\n  - \u2022\n\t\tDiffuse esophageal spasm\n  - \u2022\n\t\tHypertensive lower esophageal sphincter\n  - \u2022\n\t\tMuscular A-ring\n  - \u2022\n\t\tHypomotility of the esophagus\n  - \u2022\n\tDiverticula\n  - \u2022\n\t\tZenker\u2019s diverticulum\n  - \u2022\n\t\tMid-esophageal traction diverticulum\n  - \u2022\n\t\tPulsion diverticulum associated with spastic motor disorders\n\nGenerally speaking, dysphagia should prompt a structural investigation such as endoscopy or dedicated barium esophagram.\n\nEndoscopy is both diagnostic and therapeutic, as it can facilitate biopsy and provide an opportunity to dilate a Schatzki ring or stricture, whereas barium esophagram is the least invasive, can provide evidence of narrowing from stricture or malignancy, and offers some information on the propulsive capability of the esophagus. When done correctly, this test can identify spastic motor disorders, diverticula, achalasia, and strictures (benign or malignant). In 2022, Razia et al. demonstrated that a longer bolus transit time in prone position on barium esophagram is associated with abnormal peristalsis and patient-reported dysphagia. Barium studies performed with liquids and foods of various consistencies or with a 14- to 15-mm barium tablet provide additional information (further described below). More subtle motility abnormalities often require manometry for diagnosis, which is necessary before surgery for a manometric disorder is considered.\n\n### Atypical Symptoms of GERD\n\n#### Noncardiac Chest Pain\n\nOne of the more difficult GERD symptoms to diagnose and treat is noncardiac chest pain. It is frequently of esophageal origin, and although it may be on the spectrum of GERD or a motility disorder, surgeons should approach this symptom with caution. Sensory neurons from both the heart and esophagus converge on the dorsal horns of the spinal cord, so myocardial infarction is often suspected in patients with severe esophageal spastic syndromes. Unfortunately, the fear of missing a myocardial infarction in patients presenting with chest pain can result in significant patient workup and expense. As many as 150,000 of the 500,000 coronary angiograms performed annually in the United States are performed for functional esophageal disorders. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nManometry is generally required to confirm suspicion of a motor disorder, but it is not always diagnostic. Although not widely available and rarely used in clinical practice, 24-hour manometry (often combined with 24-hour pH monitoring) is useful in diagnosing these patients. Fass et al. reported that pH testing was predictive of a therapeutic response to omeprazole in patients with severe reflux and noncardiac chest pain. In patients with acute chest pain, a chest X-ray and/or upper gastrointestinal (GI) endoscopy in select cases (e.g., patients who present with chest pain and GI symptoms) should be performed after excluding a cardiac origin as some cases of chest pain have been associated with the lodgment of foreign bodies in the esophageal body and pharynx.\n\n#### Chronic Cough and Asthma\n\nReflux as a cause of chronic cough is a challenge to diagnose. Silent aspiration is presumed to inflame and irritate the airway. Alexander et al. observed a higher prevalence of GERD symptoms and esophageal exposure to acid in patients with asthma. Schnatz et al. also noted a high proportion (78%) of positive pH tests in patients with chronic cough or asthma. Increased esophageal exposure to gastric contents in these patients is probably both a cause and an effect. Severe coughing with wheezing increases intraabdominal pressure, driving gastric contents into the relatively negative-pressure environment of the chest, and esophageal acidification can result in a reflexive bronchospastic response ( Fig. 6.1 ). Furthermore, as discussed later, chronic aspiration contributes to ongoing cough and progressive parenchymal fibrosis via non-alloimmune mechanisms. Evidence of pharyngeal reflux on pH testing helps identify patients with respiratory symptoms who may benefit from an antireflux operation.\n\nTwo graphs A and B, show the potential of hydrogen levels and pressure marks around the lower esophageal sphincter. Graphs A and B consist of multiple line graphs. The topmost graph shows the potential hydrogen channel with a drop that indicates reflux. The bottom three graphs are pressure channels at different heights, 15 centimeters, 10 centimeters, and 5 centimeters above the lower esophageal sphincter. Distinct spikes on the pressure graphs, annotated with arrows, indicate coughs and esophageal contractions.\n\nFig. 6.1\n\n#### Hoarseness and Dental Caries\n\nReflux of gastric contents to the laryngeal aditus or the mouth is called laryngopharyngeal reflux (LPR), which has been associated with laryngeal symptoms and dental caries. In the workup of patients thought to have significant reflux, catheters with two or more probes have been used to assess reflux in the more proximal esophagus or even the pharynx. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Furthermore, the addition of impedance catheter monitoring has shown that reflux in the pharynx is more frequent than previously thought, even when measured with pH monitoring. Kawamura et al. have shown that gaseous reflux with weak acidity is more common in patients with reflux-related laryngeal lesions.\n\nIn 2018, the heartburn, asthma, and BMI extraesophageal reflux (HAs-BEER) bedside model was developed to guide the evaluation and treatment of patients with persistent extraesophageal symptoms following an 8-week course of maximal PPI dose. Other diagnostic modalities for LPR such as laryngoscopy and upper GI endoscopy present poor sensitivity and specificity with significant interobserver discrepancies. Again, objective testing with pH or pH impedance is needed to diagnose proximal reflux as a possible cause of LPR. Nasopharyngeal pH testing may help provide objective evidence of LPR, but its accuracy has been questioned.\n\n#### Nausea and Vomiting\n\nAlthough nausea and vomiting may accompany other foregut symptoms, such as heartburn and regurgitation, they should alert the surgeon to proceed with caution when considering an antireflux procedure. Early satiety and bloating may indicate delayed gastric emptying or gastroparesis, especially in patients with diabetes. Severe preoperative nausea and vomiting should be a relative contraindication to antireflux surgery, as most antireflux operations inhibit the ability to vomit, and postoperative heaving may disrupt the fundoplication or result in recurrent herniation. Similarly, patients with concomitant symptoms of irritable bowel syndrome, post-cholecystectomy patients, or patients with other prominent bowel symptoms such as diarrhea should be treated conservatively if possible.\n\n#### Abdominal Bloating\n\nAbdominal bloating is the personal perception of gas buildup in the upper abdomen, often accompanied by heightened intraabdominal pressure, and is reportedly the third most common symptom among patients with GERD. It has been postulated that physiologic or pathologic gastric distension stimulates transient lower esophageal sphincter relaxation, leading to increased reflux events and subsequent aerophagia. Aerophagia creates a positive feedback loop in which gastric distension from swallowed air again stimulates transient lower esophageal sphincter relaxation. This bloating contributes to the diminished overall well-being of patients with GERD <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> ; however, to date, there is no objective method to measure and monitor abdominal bloating in patients with GERD in the outpatient setting; the evaluation of its severity is limited to subjective assessment via quality-of-life questionnaires such as the GERD health-related quality of life (GERD-HRQL) or the patient assessment of upper gastrointestinal symptom severity index (PAGI-SYM).\n\n#### Globus Sensation\n\nThe sensation of a lump or fullness in the back of the throat or having a foreign sensation in the cervical esophageal region is called *globus sensation* . This symptom was recognized 2500 years ago by Hippocrates, and in the 19th century, it was referred to as \u201cglobus hystericus\u201d due to its frequent appearance in individuals with psychological disorders. Although the sensation is generally associated with benign disorders, it is still extremely irritating to most patients. It usually presents in the fifth and sixth decades of life, and up to 46% of healthy individuals experience this sensation at some point in their lives. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Globus sensation has a significant association with GERD, and some have suggested a trial of high-dose PPIs for 3\u20136 months before further workup. It may require a more prolonged and intensive trial of PPIs than is required for typical heartburn.\n\nObjective pH testing may reveal abnormal esophageal acid exposure in many patients with globus sensation, but pH impedance studies may be more sensitive, as some patients have symptoms associated with weak acid reflux. Patients who respond to PPIs only partially or not at all should not expect good outcomes after antireflux surgery, and antireflux surgery should not be considered as a treatment for globus sensation alone. If the disorder is associated with other symptoms, such as dysphagia or weight loss, an immediate workup should be performed to rule out malignancy. The origin of the globus sensation is poorly understood, but if it is persistent, local causes such as abnormal upper esophageal sphincter function, esophageal motor disorders, or local laryngopharyngeal causes should be considered. The association of this symptom with psychological factors is not well documented, but more than 90% of patients report symptom exacerbation during periods of high emotional intensity.\n\nSimilar to functional chest pain or heartburn, idiopathic globus sensation (formerly called functional globus sensation) arises from non-mechanical or unobservable functional conditions. To confirm the diagnosis of idiopathic globus sensation, upper GI endoscopy, high-resolution manometry (HRM), and pH monitoring are used to rule out underlying abnormalities. In these cases, management is mainly reassurance and the use of neuromodulators in some cases; however, it is worth noting that idiopathic globus sensation is generally a benign condition that has an overall good prognosis without significant long-term consequences.\n\n## Relevant Testing Before Considering Antireflux Surgery\n\nIt is important to understand the underlying physiologic defect associated with the presenting symptoms before recommending antireflux surgery. Long-term symptom relief depends on sound patient selection and avoidance of intraoperative complications. An operation performed for the wrong diagnosis will likely yield a poor outcome, and reoperations are less successful than initial procedures. Patients with spastic motor disorders and achalasia may present with heartburn ; clearly, performing an antireflux procedure in these patients or patients with functional heartburn would produce undesirable outcomes.\n\nAlthough a defective lower esophageal sphincter is the most common underlying pathology of GERD, other defects may lead to increased exposure to acid within the esophagus. Xerostomia results in increased esophageal exposure to refluxed acid because it diminishes the bicarbonate buffering associated with swallowed saliva. Likewise, hypomotility of the esophagus interferes with the clearance mechanism of the esophagus of refluxed gastric contents, thereby prolonging esophageal acid exposure. Delayed gastric emptying may result in increased gastric volumes of both reflux of gastric contents and regurgitation of partly digested food. Duodenogastric reflux may result from a gastroduodenal pathology or previous surgical procedure (which may restrict available options for a future surgical procedure). For all of these reasons, a thorough history is the cornerstone of understanding the underlying pathology and guiding future surgical interventions. Further diagnostic testing is usually needed before a surgical procedure is offered.\n\n### pH Monitoring\n\nProlonged ambulatory intraesophageal pH testing allows for objective documentation of abnormal esophageal exposure to refluxed acid, providing a link between reflux events and presenting symptoms. The 24-hour pH monitoring test is the most widely used method for the study of suspected GERD and provides details on the extent of esophageal acid exposure ( Table 6.1 ). A pH monitoring test may be performed with either a 24-hour transnasal probe or with a small wireless capsule (Bravo capsule; Medtronic, Dublin, Ireland) that is affixed to the esophageal mucosa 6 cm above the gastric rugal folds and transmits pH data via a radiotelemetry device ( Figs. 6.2 and 6.3 ). Both catheter- and capsule-based technologies are valid and reproducible, <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> although the capsule allows for prolonged recordings (up to 48, 72, or 96 hours). Prolonged monitoring may add additional diagnostic information and provide a greater database for correlation of symptoms. In contrast, the catheter system allows for a proximal and distal pH sensor, which may help identify patients with LPR and increase understanding of the effect of reflux on chronic cough or aspiration symptoms. A 24-hour pH monitoring study also facilitates characterization of the reflux\u2014for example, whether it occurs predominantly in the postprandial period, the duration of reflux episodes (thereby indicating esophageal insensitivity or poor clearance), and the time of day during which it usually occurs.\n\nA diagram along with the dimensions of the Bravo hydrogen probe capsule and its components like the potential of the hydrogen probe, a transmitter, a battery, and a reference electrode. The diagram features two distinct parts. Part 1 shows the internal structure of the probe and reference electrode on the proximal end of the capsule, the transmitter in the center, followed by the battery. Part 2 illustrates the probe''s dimensions. The well has a depth of four millimeters by four millimeters, the probe has a length of twenty six millimeters, a width of six point three millimeters, and a height of five point five millimeters. The diagram emphasizes the dimensions and positions of components.\n\nFig. 6.2\n\nAn interior view of a tubular metallic capsule inside the esophagus for a medical endoscopic examination. #REF!\n\nFig. 6.3\n\nBefore antireflux surgery can be safely considered, it is important to document abnormal esophageal exposure to gastric contents. The pH catheter or Bravo capsule can provide objective evidence of acid exposure, but patients must cease taking PPI medications for at least 1 week before the test is performed. Many patients cannot tolerate the cessation of their PPIs, and some may \u201ccheat\u201d during the absence period, which may explain a negative test in an otherwise symptomatic patient. H2 blockers can be used up to 48 hours before the test; thereafter, only over-the-counter antacids are appropriate up until the time of the study. Understanding a patient\u2019s symptoms without PPIs is important, as severe heartburn after withholding PPIs is in itself a reasonably reliable diagnostic test. As a corollary, if a patient\u2019s symptoms do not significantly change when PPIs are withheld, the surgeon should exercise caution when considering surgical treatment\u2014functional heartburn may be the more accurate diagnosis.\n\nA pH monitoring test may not be necessary for a patient with an obviously defective lower esophageal sphincter (as seen on manometry) or with obvious esophagitis (as seen on endoscopy). However, mild esophagitis has poor interobserver agreement, and esophagitis may result from pill injury or infection; the American College of Gastroenterology currently recommends performing pH monitoring before surgery in all patients with NERD and those with Los Angeles grade A or B esophagitis. Moreover, pH testing may have utility for confirming reflux in patients with GERD or NERD who are unresponsive to PPIs. In patients experiencing both reflux and regurgitation, endoscopic ulcerative esophagitis is 97% specific for GERD. A pH monitoring test may be unnecessary if the patient has a very large paraesophageal hernia and surgery is primarily directed at this defect, especially as an antireflux procedure usually accompanies repair of the paraesophageal hernia, regardless of whether the patient experienced heartburn preoperatively.\n\nAntireflux surgery performed in patients with normal 24-hour pH test results is associated with significantly worse outcomes than when it is performed in patients with abnormal results; therefore, routine pH testing is recommended before antireflux surgery. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> As a corollary, 24-hour pH monitoring or pH impedance testing is very useful in selecting those patients with functional heartburn or with visceral hyperesthesia for whom surgery may prove ineffective.\n\n### Impedance Testing\n\nMultichannel intraluminal impedance and pH (MII-pH) testing relies on the change in resistance to an electrical current when a bolus, liquid, or gas passes between the metallic rings on a catheter. When the esophagus is empty, the electrical current is conducted by the ions on the mucosa. Liquids with more ions increase conductivity and decrease resistance, which can be measured and recorded in much the same way acid is measured in 24-hour pH monitoring. By measuring impedance at many sites along a catheter, the direction of the bolus movement can be determined: a swallow of liquid will be antegrade, whereas a reflux episode will be retrograde.\n\nThe benefit of this type of testing is that the fluid bolus (i.e., refluxate) can be measured regardless of its acidity. By combining pH monitoring with impedance testing, all types of reflux can be measured. This allows practitioners to determine acid episodes, weak-acid episodes, and non-acid episodes and correlate symptoms to each type. Although most patients undergoing antireflux surgery will have a positive acid pH test, a subgroup of patients with weakly acidic or non-acidic reflux who may benefit from surgery has been described. Impedance testing may also have value in identifying the cause of chronic cough in patients with normal pH studies.\n\nMII-pH testing was introduced in 2005 and has since been the subject of evaluation in surgical practice. In 2023, Zhu et al. reported that a mean nocturnal baseline impedance lower than 2.14 k\u2126 in MII-pH testing may predict an adequate response to standard antireflux therapy in patients with negative pH tests. MII-pH testing definitely has the potential to add substantially more information, although the testing requires a transnasal catheter for at least 24 hours.\n\n### Manometry\n\nManometry provides information on the tone and coordination of the upper and lower esophageal sphincters and the propulsive function of the esophageal body. It allows for the identification of motility disorders and provides information that may preclude some surgical approaches. The main indications and contraindications of HRM are summarized in Table 6.2 .\n\nTable 6.2\n\nCommon Indications and Contraindications for High-Resolution Manometry\n\nUsed with permission from Masuda T, Latorre A, Mittal SK. *The Beginners\u2019 Guide for Analyzing High-Resolution Manometry based on Chicago Classification version 4.0 \u00a92023* \\- Norton Thoracic Institute, St. Joseph\u2019s Hospital and Medical Center.\n\n| Indications | Contraindications |\n| --- | --- |\n| - \u2022 \tAssessment of non-obstructive dysphagia - \u2022 \tConfirmation of diagnosis of achalasia - \u2022 \tNoncardiac chest pain with normal EGD - \u2022 \tPreoperative evaluation for ARS candidates - \u2022 \tPostoperative evaluation for ARS and achalasia management - \u2022 \tEvaluation of esophageal motility disorders (including cases secondary to systemic diseases) | - \u2022 \tIntraluminal obstruction - \u2022 \tNostril/oropharyngeal structural alteration - \u2022 \tHigh risk of aspiration - \u2022 \tSignificant abnormal coagulation disorders - \u2022 \tPatients unable to follow instructions - \u2022 \tChronic anticoagulation \u2217 - \u2022 \tIntolerance to the catheter \u2217 |\n\n*ARS,* Antireflux surgery; *EGD,* esophagogastroduodenoscopy.\n\nMost legacy water-perfused manometry systems have been replaced with HRM that uses sensitive, solid-state pressure transducers, which allows for a more precise evaluation of esophageal motility disorders. A new classification system\u2014the Chicago Classification System\u2014has been proposed to capture this new level of precision. This hierarchical classification system was updated to version 4.0 in 2021 and uses the integration of esophageal pressure topography from HRM to classify the esophageal manometric disorders in two main groups: (1) esophagogastric junction (EGJ) outflow disorders (i.e., achalasia and EGJ outflow obstruction) and (2) peristalsis disorders (i.e., absent contractility, ineffective esophageal motility, distal esophageal spasm, and hypercontractile esophagus). This system has already facilitated clarification of achalasia subtypes I, II, and III, and implications of therapy and potential surgical outcomes for each subtype have been delineated. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Moreover, additional supportive assessments during esophageal manometry including provocative maneuvers such as multiple rapid swallows or the rapid drink challenge have been included and recommended; these maneuvers allow the contractile reserve of the esophagus to be determined; however, their significance and predictive value from the surgical point of view remain unclear.\n\nThe success of the Nissen fundoplication in patients with hypomotility of the esophageal body has been the subject of much debate. Some studies have shown that motility of the esophageal body may improve slightly in some patients after fundoplication. Although it is likely true that mildly depressed contraction amplitudes do not significantly impact postoperative dysphagia in expert hands, severely depressed contractions and the so-called aperistaltic esophagus (as seen in connective tissue disorders) will likely result in poor esophageal clearance after a 360-degree fundoplication. In 2021, Addo et al. demonstrated that patients with impaired motility (ineffective esophageal motility) as well as those with normal motility benefit from laparoscopic antireflux surgery for GERD; as expected, the mean baseline DeMeester score was significantly worse in patients with ineffective esophageal motility than in those with normal motility (38.6 vs. 24.0, *P* \\=.023); however, reflux reduction (80.6% vs. 72.4%), satisfaction (80% vs. 77.9%), and postoperative complications were comparable between the groups. Manometric evaluation of the esophagus is an objective way to provide a clear evaluation of the esophageal pressure profiles that guide a surgeon performing functional surgery. HRM may identify abnormalities that contraindicate surgery and may help a surgeon to counsel patients and manage expectations of surgical outcomes.\n\nOther esophageal disorders such as achalasia, distal esophageal spasm, or hypercontractile esophagus may present with heartburn-like discomfort. In a large retrospective study of 1081 patients referred for antireflux surgery, 1 in 14 had abnormalities on HRM that were considered absolute or relative contraindications for antireflux surgery. The researchers further noted that almost 25% of patients would have undergone antireflux surgery without clear evidence of GERD had pH monitoring and manometry not been performed during the workup. Of the 1081 patients, 2.5% had abnormalities on the achalasia spectrum. An antireflux operation in this context would have a poor outcome and likely require a second, corrective operation. In patients for whom manometry is impossible (e.g., the patient refuses or the catheter cannot be passed through the nose), a partial fundoplication should be performed to minimize the risk of postoperative dysphagia. In this situation, a well-performed barium study may provide some insight into peristaltic function.\n\n### Impedance Manometry\n\nThe recent addition of impedance to esophageal manometry may provide further information on esophageal clearance in real time, but the role this technology plays in surgical planning is presently unclear. This modality may help evaluate the propulsive efficiency of the esophagus for different bolus consistencies and different body positions. This method may be useful to evaluate esophageal function both before and after fundoplication in the future.\n\n### Barium Esophagram\n\nContinuous digital or video barium esophagram can identify structural abnormalities and provide functional information about the esophagus. If a patient is unable to tolerate a manometric study, a barium esophagram study can offer insight into the peristaltic activity of the esophagus, especially if the test is done with both solids and liquids. A barium esophagram can also help identify the nature and position of a hiatal hernia. Interestingly, the standard barium esophagram performed in many institutions today has changed little over the 30 years it has been in use. Effervescent crystals are still used to provide information on mucosal relief and prone oblique views are still used, even when achalasia is suspected. Some specialized centers have modified the barium study to better understand functional esophageal disorders, as is well described elsewhere in this book.\n\nPerhaps the most important aspect of performing a barium esophagram is effective communication between the surgeon and the radiologist regarding the patient\u2019s symptoms and suspected diagnoses. The study can be modified to concentrate on mucosal relief (for patients with ulcerative esophagitis, infections, or early tumors), propulsive action (recumbent swallows with different barium consistencies), emptying of the esophagus in the upright position in patients with achalasia, <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> or the evaluation of strictures. Certain provocative maneuvers, such as leg raising or the Valsalva maneuver while the patient is supine can elicit reflux, which although not a sensitive test, is usually quite specific for GERD. The radiologist should have some understanding of the concepts of deglutitive inhibition (i.e., rapid swallowing followed only by a terminal peristaltic wave) and the refractory period of the esophagus, as swallows closer together than 20 seconds may have poorer quality propulsive function. Overall, a barium study\u2014when performed correctly\u2014is a wonderful screening tool for patients with esophageal symptoms.\n\n### Endoscopy\n\nEndoscopy is considered a critical preoperative study before recommending antireflux surgery and can also provide necessary biopsy material in patients with Barrett\u2019s esophagus, suspected malignancy, or eosinophilic esophagitis. Endoscopy can identify esophagitis, strictures, hiatal hernia, Barrett\u2019s esophagus, or malignancy and provide a qualitative look at the function of the lower esophageal sphincter. This analysis has been well described by Hill et al.\n\nEndoscopy facilitates the categorization of esophagitis; the most commonly used scale is the Los Angeles classification system ( Table 6.3 ). Endoscopy also allows for the diagnosis of Barrett\u2019s esophagus via biopsy, as the presence of high-grade dysplasia or intramucosal carcinoma in a segment of the esophagus with Barrett\u2019s esophagus may alter the surgeon\u2019s approach. In such circumstances, further studies may be indicated, and ablation or resection may be the first course of action. The length of a Barrett\u2019s segment, the size of a hiatal hernia, the presence of esophagitis or stricture, and the ease of eructation in the retroflexed position on insufflation should all be noted. Patients with Barrett\u2019s esophagus should undergo biopsies at four quadrants every 1\u20132 cm and should be placed on a surveillance program regardless of whether they undergo fundoplication.\n\nTable 6.3\n\nThe Los Angeles Classification of Esophagitis\n\nReprinted from Sami SS, Ragunath K. The Los Angeles classification of gastroesophageal reflux disease (2013). Video Journal and Encyclopedia of GI Endoscopy. Used with permission under Creative Commons license CC BY-NC-ND 4.0.\n\n| Grade A | One (or more) mucosal break no longer than 5 mm that does not extend between the tops of two mucosal folds |\n| --- | --- |\n| Grade B | One (or more) mucosal break more than 5 mm long that does not extend between the tops of two mucosal folds |\n| Grade C | One (or more) mucosal break that is continuous between the tops of two or more mucosal folds but which involves less than 75% of the circumference |\n| Grade D | One (or more) mucosal break which involves at least 75% of the esophageal circumference |\n\n### Gastric Emptying Studies\n\nFor patients with prominent symptoms of nausea, vomiting, postprandial fullness, or bloating, an evaluation of gastric emptying should be considered. A bezoar visible after an overnight fast is usually a good indication of delayed gastric emptying, but the best objective study is a scintigraphic radionuclide study using both solids and liquids. Unfortunately, the methods and normal values vary significantly between centers, and the results are not always reliable. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> A consensus report in 2018 suggests using a standardized meal of radiolabeled low-fat egg whites with imaging up to 4 hours after the meal. A Nissen fundoplication may improve gastric emptying, but significantly delayed gastric emptying should alert the surgeon to the need for other procedures such as pyloric injection of botulinum toxin type A, pyloroplasty, or a Roux-en-Y procedure.\n\n## Relevant Preoperative Testing For Specific Indications\n\n### Preoperative Testing for Barrett\u2019s Esophagus\n\nBarrett\u2019s esophagus can only be diagnosed by endoscopy with confirmation of intestinal metaplasia by biopsy. The finding of goblet cells intermingled in a columnar lining of the tubular esophagus is pathognomonic of Barrett\u2019s esophagus. The disease is considered to be a metaplastic response to severe GERD, and its clinical significance is the premalignant potential of the unstable epithelium. The definition has changed slightly over the years, but a biopsy is required for confirmation.\n\nThe finding of Barrett\u2019s esophagus has significance outside its potential for malignancy, as patients with Barrett\u2019s esophagus often have associated esophageal hypomotility and generally have severely abnormal esophageal exposure to both refluxed acid and duodenal contents. Patients with Barrett\u2019s esophagus may also have a shorter-than-normal esophagus, which may have implications for a planned surgical procedure. Cutting-edge technologies using molecular markers and genetic profiling of common mutations (of TP53, CDKN2A, etc.) to assess the risk of Barrett\u2019s progression have been introduced over the last 10 years. Despite the cost of these tests and their limited distribution, it seems that their use improves the prediction of progression over clinical variables alone. Thus, they may become routine preoperative tests for Barrett\u2019s esophagus.\n\n### Preoperative Testing for Giant Hernias or Large Paraesophageal Hernias\n\nThe aging population coupled with the ubiquitous use of PPIs for heartburn control (often decades in duration) has led to an epidemic of large paraesophageal hernias (the common term for type III hiatal hernias) or the so-called intrathoracic stomach. Presumably, heartburn has been adequately controlled in these patients, but the hernia has progressively enlarged to the point that the hernia itself is responsible for the presenting symptoms. These symptoms may include chest discomfort, postprandial fullness or discomfort, dyspnea, dysphagia, or anemia. Dysphagia may be related to the accordion-like shortening of the esophagus, from the external pressure of the paraesophageal stomach pressing on the esophagus or a coexisting motility disorder. Chest discomfort and bloating may be related to distention of the intrathoracic stomach and the slow emptying of this compartment. Dyspnea as a symptom is poorly understood but is usually improved after surgical intervention. Not infrequently, patients with giant hernias or large paraesophageal hernias describe only a remote history of heartburn, but it is either no longer an issue or is easily controlled with PPIs.\n\nLarge hernias occasionally present acutely with torsion, which usually mandates immediate surgical intervention (although decompression and de-torsion with endoscopy have been described). Severe abdominal and chest pain is usually attributed to ischemia of the herniated stomach, and patients with these presenting symptoms often progress rapidly to being critically ill with hemodynamic instability.\n\nFor the most part, patient symptoms progress slowly and an outpatient workup can be performed. This workup should include barium studies, endoscopy, and manometry. As the indication for surgery is the large hernia itself, and the surgical repair of the hernia is usually accompanied by some sort of fundoplication, pH studies are likely unnecessary. Barium studies will show the size and position of the hernia and, if performed with a 13-mm barium tablet, will reveal any delay during passage through the esophagus. Endoscopy will identify Barrett\u2019s esophagus, dysplasia, Cameron ulcers in the stomach, and the hernia type and size. Manometry will identify any marked motility abnormalities\u2014especially important, as the incidence of spastic motor disorders increases in the older population.\n\n### Preoperative Testing for Myotomy for Achalasia or Diverticula\n\nThe diagnosis of spastic motor disorders and achalasia depends on a well-performed manometric study, and manometry is critical before surgery is considered for these disorders. Barium studies usually show areas of corkscrewing or the tapered bird-beak appearance of the distal esophagus associated with achalasia; timed barium esophagram with liquid barium or use of a barium tablet provide more conclusive information. Endoscopy is recommended to rule out pseudoachalasia, in which the motility disorder of the esophagus is secondary to an infiltrating process (usually adenocarcinoma) at the gastroesophageal junction. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Chagas disease may give a similar picture.\n\nBarium esophagram and a manometric study can indicate how far the myotomy should extend, especially in patients with a diverticulum that is situated more than a few centimeters above the gastroesophageal junction. Manometry can also help counsel patients with different variants of achalasia (i.e., EGJ outflow obstruction with spastic features) regarding expected outcomes. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n### Preoperative Testing for End-Stage Lung Disease and Transplantation\n\nThe effect of GERD in patients with end-stage lung disease and in patients who have undergone lung transplantation has historically been underestimated. A high proportion of patients with end-stage lung disease have pathologic GERD, and it has been suggested that silent aspiration contributes to pulmonary injury in many of these patients. Similarly, the chronic cough associated with many end-stage lung diseases is thought to promote reflux as it increases intraabdominal and trans-sphincteric pressure ( Fig. 6.1 ). Over the last 2 decades, multiple studies have demonstrated that GERD a significant adverse contributor to the development of bronchiolitis obliterans syndrome after lung transplantation. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Davis et al. have shown that 73% of patients who have undergone lung transplantation have GERD (diagnosed by pH monitoring). This may be due to the significant number of patients with unrecognized GERD before transplantation, vagal damage at the time of surgery, or reflux-promoting side effects of postoperative immunosuppressive medications. Nonetheless, Davis et al. have shown that fundoplication in lung transplant recipients with GERD is associated with significantly improved lung function, particularly if the fundoplication is performed before bronchiolitis obliterans syndrome reaches advanced stages. Others have suggested that performing a fundoplication early is beneficial, whereas performing it later after transplant allows the initiation of chronic rejection and may be associated with worse long-term outcomes. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Many patients with progressive deterioration in lung function and the diagnosis of pulmonary fibrosis referred for transplantation have experienced stabilization of their pulmonary disease after fundoplication.\n\nIt is now the standard of care to have a solid understanding of a patient\u2019s reflux history before considering lung transplantation, and in many centers, all patients considered for lung transplantation undergo manometry, video esophagram, and 24-hour pH testing to assess for GERD. Patients with severe reflux and a non-prohibitive surgical risk will undergo fundoplication before transplantation. Antireflux surgery in the early posttransplant period is considered for patients who cannot undergo surgery before transplantation or who develop GERD after transplantation.\n\nIn this complex group of patients, pH monitoring can provide tremendous insight into the significance of GERD and help to direct therapy. A mere symptom assessment is completely inadequate when evaluating patients slated to undergo lung transplantation, and pH or pH impedance testing is required to identify patients who may be at risk of aspiration as a result of GERD. Soresi et al. found that almost 60% of lung transplant recipients suffered from GERD. Similarly, Tamhankar et al. showed that PPIs only affect the pH of the refluxate\u2014not the occurrence or frequency of the reflux episodes. As such, it may be prudent to have all transplant patients undergo at least 24-hr pH or MII-pH testing after transplantation, especially as patients with abnormal proximal esophageal reflux are more likely to be readmitted to the hospital. This group of patients should be treated aggressively (i.e., early antireflux surgery) to protect the implanted allograft, especially in the face of immunosuppression.\n\nThe problematic effects of reflux in patients who have undergone lung transplantation are complex. Clearly, aspiration occurs more frequently than previously thought, as bile acids and activated pepsin have been found in bronchoalveolar lavage fluid, and thorough pre- and post-transplant testing is indicated. pH impedance studies are diagnostic, but manometry is also important, as abnormalities in peristalsis or function of the lower esophageal sphincter may occur in up to 66% of patients and may contribute to poor esophageal clearance of refluxed fluid. Endoscopy is important, as Barrett\u2019s esophagus may be more prevalent in the lung transplant population. Pre-transplant antireflux surgery should be considered in patients with GERD if the patient can tolerate such a procedure as the patient can recover when they are not taking steroids or other immunosuppressive post-transplant medications. If antireflux surgery cannot be performed before transplantation, it should be considered soon after to protect the transplanted organ. In 2023, Razia et al. demonstrated that patients with GERD who underwent fundoplication after lung transplantation presented with better pulmonary function and longer graft-dysfunction-free survival than those with a DeMeester score \u226530 who were medically treated. Furthermore, patients who underwent early fundoplication (<6 months after transplant) had better overall survival than those who underwent late fundoplication. It is clear that by the time the organ shows evidence of decline (i.e., decreased forced expiratory volume in the first second \\[FEV1\\]), it may be too late to prevent the progression of organ dysfunction.\n\n### Preoperative Testing for Reoperation After Failure of Previous Antireflux Surgery\n\nA very detailed patient history is critical when evaluating a patient who has undergone an antireflux procedure that has presumably failed. It is useful to review any preoperative studies carried out before the initial operation if the results of those studies are available. An attempt should be made to prioritize the patient\u2019s symptoms to understand the nature of the failure ( Box 6.3 ). When considering a reoperation, it is crucial to perform all necessary testing to optimize the outcome because the second and third procedures are usually less successful than the initial procedure, especially if dysphagia is a prominent symptom.\n\nBox 6.3\n\nQuestions To Ask Your Patient Before Redo Surgery\n\n  - \u2022\n\tWhat were your symptoms before your first operation?\n  - \u2022\n\tWhat tests did you undergo before your first operation?\n  - \u2022\n\tDid you have a hiatal hernia or a paraesophageal hernia? If so, did your surgeon use mesh to repair the hernia?\n  - \u2022\n\tHow long were you in the hospital?\n  - \u2022\n\tDid you have any side effects from the operation?\n  - \u2022\n\tDid your symptoms improve or resolve after your first operation?\n  - \u2022\n\tWhat are your main symptoms currently?\n  - \u2022\n\tWhen did these symptoms start? Are they progressively getting worse?\n  - \u2022\n\tDid anything precipitate the onset of these symptoms?\n  - \u2022\n\tWere any of these present before your initial operation?\n  - \u2022\n\tPlease describe any symptoms of dysphagia, heartburn, regurgitation, bloating, nausea, or early satiety in detail.\n\nDespite the lack of consensus on the interpretation of lower esophageal sphincter parameters after fundoplication, manometry is particularly important, as it will provide the surgeon with useful information about the motor function of the esophagus, as it may differ from its status before the first operation. Juhasz et al. have suggested endoscopic terminology for uniformly classifying post-fundoplication changes, and Hoshino et al. have described the manometric features related to each endoscopic finding. A gastric emptying study is also important, particularly if bloating and early satiety are prominent symptoms. Operative options include takedown of the previous wrap, redo fundoplication, possible pyloroplasty, or gastric diversion such as Roux-en-Y esophagoenterostomy or gastroenterostomy, all of which are discussed in greater detail later in this book.\n\n### Preoperative Testing for Esophageal Cancer\n\nThe presenting symptom of esophageal cancer is, invariably, some degree of dysphagia. Depending on the severity of the dysphagia, the patient may also have experienced some degree of weight loss. Unfortunately, dysphagia usually has an insidious beginning, and patients often adapt, sometimes for months, as the symptoms progress before scheduling an appointment with a physician\u2014particularly troubling, as dysphagia usually occurs late in the course of esophageal cancer. It only occurs when more than 60% of the circumference of the esophagus is involved or when the diameter of the lumen has decreased to less than 12 mm. Other symptoms, such as chest pain or hematemesis, are less common and are usually accompanied by dysphagia. If the tumor invades the tracheobronchial tree, symptoms such as cough, strider, hemoptysis, and pneumonia may be present. Distant metastases may produce symptoms of bone pain, neurological symptoms, or jaundice. Dysphagia has been called an \u201calarm\u201d symptom for this reason, and although there are many benign causes (e.g., GERD, motility disorders, and esophageal stricture), the physician should take this symptom seriously.\n\nThe workup of a patient with suspected cancer involves obtaining a tissue biopsy and diagnosis and performing staging procedures to plan treatment. A barium study may show narrowing or an apple-core-like stricture in the esophagus, but endoscopy will facilitate biopsy and (together with an endoscopic ultrasound including fine-needle aspiration) can provide information on the extent of the cancer and possible lymph node involvement. Additionally, techniques for endoscopy including chromoendoscopy, narrow-band image endoscopy, confocal laser endomicroscopy and endocytoscopy, volumetric laser endomicroscopy, and light-induced fluorescence spectroscopy, among others, have been reported to improve the diagnostic sensitivity. Bronchoscopy may be useful, especially in patients with respiratory symptoms, to rule out tracheobronchial invasion and should always be done early in the workup of patients with upper or mid-esophageal lesions. Positron emission tomography and computed tomography are critical in identifying the stage of the disease.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nComplete physiologic testing and a thorough understanding of a patient\u2019s symptoms are necessary before surgery can be recommended to patients with symptoms suggesting a functional esophageal disorder. Surgeons should understand the value and limitations of the various modalities of esophageal testing (e.g., pH impedance testing and manometry studies), as the information gleaned from these tests can direct therapeutic intervention. It is also crucial to note that symptoms alone should not be the sole deciding factor for recommending surgical procedures. Patients who experience dysphagia should be taken seriously and should undergo a complete workup, as dysphagia is the most common presenting symptom of esophageal cancer.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Campos G.M., Peters J.H., DeMeester T.R., et al.: Multivariate analysis of factors predicting outcome after laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication . J Gastrointest Surg 1999; 3 (3): pp. 292-300.\n\nView In Article\n\n2.: Wei M.T., Friedland S.: Early esophageal cancer: what the gastroenterologist needs to know . Gastroenterol Clin North Am 2021; 50 (4): pp. 791-808.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: Drewes A.M., Schipper K.P., Dimcevski G., et al.: Multimodal assessment of pain in the esophagus: a new experimental model . Am J Physiol Gastrointest Liver Physiol 2002; 283 (1): pp. G95-103.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Drewes A.M., Schipper K.P., Dimcevski G., et al.: Multi-modal induction and assessment of allodynia and hyperalgesia in the human oesophagus . Eur J Pain 2003; 7 (6): pp. 539-549.\n\nView In Article\n\n5.: Bulsiewicz W.J., Shaheen N.J., Hansen M.B., Pruitt A., Orlando R.C.: Effect of amiloride on experimental acid-induced hea