late(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n\n\nNeed help? Chat with AI Buddy!\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[5. Radiology of the Esophagus: Barium, Computed Tomography Scan, Positron Emission Tomography Scan, Magnetic Resonance Imaging - ClinicalKey|5. Radiology of the Esophagus: Barium, Computed Tomography Scan, Positron Emission Tomography Scan, Magnetic Resonance Imaging]]\n**Next:** [[7. Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux - ClinicalKey|7. Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "6. Esophageal Symptoms and Selection of Diagnostic Tests - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Esophageal Symptoms and Selection of Diagnostic Tests', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'GERD Symptoms', 'Diagnostic Evaluation', 'Preoperative Testing', 'Antireflux Surgery', 'Gastric Emptying Studies', 'GERD Symptoms / Diagnostic Evaluation', 'GERD Symptoms / Preoperative Testing', 'GERD Symptoms / Antireflux Surgery', 'GERD Symptoms / Gastric Emptying Studies'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '6', '76-88', 2, 62, FALSE, TRUE),
('Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux', 'shackelford-9th-ed-7-pathophysiology-of-gastroesophageal-reflux', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux\n\nChristy M. Dunst; Parakrama Chandrasoma\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 7, 89-102\n\n## Introduction\n\nGastroesophageal reflux is defined as the escape of gastric juice into the esophagus across the reflux barrier. The primary components of the reflux barrier include the lower esophageal sphincter (LES), the gastroesophageal flap valve (GEFV), and the crural diaphragm (CD) ( Fig. 7.1 ). Secondary components include the esophageal stripping mechanism through intact peristalsis and normal gastric emptying to prevent backflow across the barrier. The reflux barrier is stabilized at the level of the esophageal hiatus of the diaphragm during respiration by the phrenoesophageal ligament and the tubular integrity of the LES. A certain amount of reflux across the barrier is normal and swiftly cleared from the esophagus with reflexive esophageal peristalsis. This type of reflux event occurs as the stomach vents excess gas across the gastroesophageal junction (GEJ) and is imperceptible in healthy individuals. More dramatic distention of stomach with gas or solid contents, such as after a large meal, may cause more significant reflux events that are perceived as occasional heartburn. If the reflux barrier permanently weakens and loses its functional integrity, symptomatic troublesome reflux events increase in severity and frequency and the term gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) applies.\n\nA diagram of the lower esophageal sphincter that represents internal and external muscles, diaphragm, stomach, and related structures. The diagram illustrates the anatomical section of the lower esophageal sphincter. It includes the internal and external muscles, the longitudinal and circular muscle layers, and the diaphragm. Labels indicate the phrenoesophageal ligament, squamocolumnar junction, and the stomach. The diagram highlights the sling fibers and different diaphragm parts like the costal and crural parts.\n\nFig. 7.1\n\nExposure of the squamous cell lining of the esophagus to acidic gastric juice results in inflammation, often visible as erosive esophagitis. Two scenarios have been proposed regarding the natural history of GERD. The first is that GERD is a categorical disorder, and the patient can be categorized as having either nonerosive reflux disease (NERD) or erosive reflux disease (ERD) and patients remain in their diagnosed category. The second is that GERD is a spectrum disorder with NERD at one end of the spectrum and intestinal metaplasia and esophageal adenocarcinoma at the other end, with the ability of the disease to progress through the spectrum over time. Current clinical evidence appears to support the spectrum concept with studies showing progression of patients from their initial category to a more advanced category. The role in the reflux spectrum of each of the primary components of the barrier has been extensively studied over decades. It is now clear that the function of the reflux barrier is dependent on the combined interplay of each component. However, there does appear to be a sequence of anatomic and functional derangements that help us understand the pathophysiology of GERD starting with the loss of function of the low esophageal sphincter.\n\n## The Lower Esophageal Sphincter (LES)\n\nThe LES creates a measurable force located in the distal end of the esophagus where it straddles the diaphragm. Anatomically the LES boundaries are unmarked, and its exact location can only be determined by using a pressure-sensitive manometry catheter, which measures the distal esophageal high-pressure zone comprised of pressure contributions of the CD and LES ( Fig. 7.2 ). When the components of the reflux barrier are intact, the distal esophageal high-pressure zone, and specifically the tubular LES, acts as a beautifully designed barrier that prevents reflux of gastric contents into the esophagus. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The resting pressure is normally greater than 15 mmHg, exceeding the baseline luminal pressure in the esophagus (normally around \u22125 mmHg) proximally, and the baseline luminal pressure in the stomach (normally around +5 mmHg) distally. The distal esophageal high-pressure zone effectively prevents reflux along the natural pressure gradient that exists from the stomach into the esophagus ( Figs. 7.3 and 7.4 ).\n\nA high resolution manometry of esophageal pressure in three swallows. The high-resolution manometry traces the esophageal pressure during three swallows. The horizontal axis represents time. The vertical axis represents pressure in millimeters of mercury. There are three prominent pressure peaks depicting the esophageal contractions during swallowing. At the bottom is a high-pressure zone representing the lower esophageal sphincter.\n\nFig. 7.2\n\nA diagram displays the pressure changes in the thorax and abdomen that depict a shortened lower esophageal sphincter and the absence of lower esophageal sphincter pressure in the distal esophagus. The diagram illustrates the pressure dynamics in the thorax and abdomen with changes in the lower esophageal sphincter. It shows the lower esophageal sphincter with a pressure of 15 to 20 millimeters of mercury, which indicates a shortened lower esophageal sphincter. The area labeled No lower esophageal sphincter pressure in the distal esophagus represents a lack of pressure in that region. There is also a reference to Chronic Lower Esophageal in the distal esophagus. The pressure changes are highlighted with labels for both the thorax and abdomen at positive 5 millimeters of mercury.\n\nFig. 7.3\n\nA diagram of the esophagus, stomach, and a shortened lower esophageal sphincter. The diagram depicts the transverse section of the esophagus and stomach. The esophagus runs vertically and transitions into the horizontally oriented stomach at the lower section. Arrows and labels indicate key elements, which include the Esophagus, the Shortened lower esophageal sphincter taken up into gastric contour, the Exposed squamous epithelium, and the Stomach that is overdistended by a heavy meal.\n\nFig. 7.4\n\nEarly studies correlated the relationship between the LES and escape of gastric acid into the esophagus measured by pH testing. The results of these studies indicated there were three characteristics of the force, or LES, that worked together to provide a barrier to challenges of increased intragastric and intraabdominal pressure ( Fig. 7.5A ). One of these characteristics was the position of the LES. A portion of the LES length is normally exposed to the positive intraabdominal pressure environment and is commonly referred to as the abdominal length of the LES. During periods of increased intraabdominal pressure, the resistance of the LES could easily be overcome if the challenge of intraabdominal pressure was unable to be applied equally to the abdominal esophagus (i.e., synonymous with abdominal length of LES) and stomach. In situations in which the length of the abdominal esophagus has become permanently inadequate, the abdominal esophagus cannot collapse in response to challenges of intraabdominal pressure. This is called permanent failure of the LES ( Fig. 7.5B ), and with the encouragement from the negative intrathoracic pressure, results in persistent reflux of gastric juice into the esophagus with minimal abdominal pressure challenges.\n\nA set of three graphs that represent the pressure profiles and failure types of the lower esophageal sphincter. The set of three graphs A, B, and C, compare lower esophageal sphincter pressure profiles. The horizontal axis denotes lower esophageal sphincter length ranging from 0 to 5 leftward. Graph A depicts a normal lower esophageal sphincter that displays abdominal and overall length. Abdominal length lies within the overall length. Graph B depicts the permanent failure of the lower esophageal sphincter and notes a destroyed portion in the initial phase. Graph C shows the dynamic failure of the lower esophageal sphincter with gastric distention shortening continuously from the gastric baseline. All graphs include millimeters of mercury reference marks and gastric baselines, with the horizontal axis indicating lower esophageal sphincter length in centimeters. Intraluminal pressure equals 3 millimeters of mercury and remains constant in all three. Graphs A, B, and C are enclosed within a visual border.\n\nFig. 7.5\n\nThe remaining two characteristics of the LES, overall length of the LES and the LES pressure, also provide a barrier to reflux. They function together and depend on each other to provide resistance to flow of gastric juice from the stomach into the esophagus unrelated to intraabdominal pressure challenges. Critical to this function is the relationship between the LES overall length and the LES pressure. The shorter the overall length, the higher the pressure must be for the LES to maintain competency against challenges of intragastric pressure above intraabdominal pressure ( Fig. 7.6 ). Consequently, a normal LES pressure can be nullified by a short overall LES length, and a normal overall LES length can be nullified by a low LES pressure. The fundamental principle is that the overall length of the LES, like the LES abdominal length, is important to the function of the LES as a barrier.\n\nA graph that depicts the relationship between lower esophageal sphincter length and pressure indicates the competent and incompetent zones. The graph traces a declining trajectory with the lower esophageal sphincter length in centimeters on the horizontal axis and the pressure in millimeters of mercury on the vertical axis. The incompetent region lies below the trajectory is the incompetent region, while the other region is competent.\n\nFig. 7.6\n\nIf esophageal manometry done at rest in the recumbent position and after an overnight fast shows the LES to have an abnormally low pressure, a short overall length, or a minimal length exposed to the abdominal pressure environment, it is called a permanent failure of the LES, and unhampered reflux of the gastric contents into the esophagus occurs ( Fig. 7.5B ). The existence of a permanently failed LES is identified by one or more inadequate components which when compared with normal subjects, display values that are less than the 2.5 percentile for each parameter. Fig. 7.7 is a schema of the LES components showing their median normal values with the 5th and 95th percentile values and their point of failure.\n\nA diagram of a normal lower esophageal sphincter measurement for stomach anatomy. The diagram depicts the tubular lower esophageal sphincter ranging from 0 to units next to the hemispherical stomach. It includes statistical data as a median abdominal length of 2.2 centimeters with fifth and ninety fifth percentiles of 1 centimeter and 4 centimeters, respectively, alongside points of failure with an overall length of 3 point 6 centimeters with corresponding percentiles of 2 point 6 centimeters, 5 point 4 centimeters, and a point of failure and the respiratory inversion point indicating lower esophageal sphincter pressure values, including a median of 13 point 8 millimeters of mercury and percentiles.\n\nFig. 7.7\n\n## Early Reflux and Transient Lower Esophageal Relaxations\n\nThe LES normally remains closed with two exceptions: during a swallow, when an induced relaxation of the force occurs to allow a bolus of food to enter the stomach, or during a belch, when the force is disrupted to allow gas to be vented from a distended stomach. The common denominator for virtually all episodes of gastroesophageal reflux is the disappearance of the force required to contain fluid in the stomach. When this occurs, resistance to the flow of gastric juice from an environment of higher pressure\u2014the stomach\u2014to an environment of lower pressure\u2014the esophagus\u2014is lost. In early disease the loss of the force is a transient event. In advanced disease, the loss or deficiency of the force is permanent.\n\nTransient lower esophageal sphincter relaxations (tLESRs) were first described as an etiology of reflux events by Dr. Jerry Dodds in 1982. He observed transient relaxations of a manometrically normal LES that were unrelated to a swallow but were stimulated by gastric distention or nonpressurized gastric dilation. The term he used to describe these events was \u201ctransient LES relaxations\u201d (tLESRs). There are two proposed explanations for the occurrence of tLESRs. The first is, tLESRs are due to a neuromediated reflex initiated by pressurized gastric distention or nonpressurized dilation from gastric adaptive relaxation induced by a meal. It was hypothesized that these conditions stimulate stretch receptors in the gastric fundus, which in turn stimulate vagal afferent nerve fibers that relay the input from the receptors to the medulla. Medullary nuclei then orchestrate the efferent limb of the reflex via the vagal and phrenic nerves to elicit a tLESR, CD inhibition, and distal esophageal shortening. This explanation suggests that the basic etiology of GERD is a neuromuscular abnormality.\n\nThe second proposal is, tLESRs are due to transient shortening of the LES length due to it being taken up into the stomach during episodes of pressurized gastric distention or nonpressurized dilation from gastric adaptive relaxation. Normally, in the fasting state and resting recumbent position, the median overall length of the LES is 3.6 cm. With gastric distention or dilation, the length of the LES shortens as the effaced portion is taken up by the expanding fundus. When gastric distention or dilation is excessive, the length of the LES shortens to its point of failure of 2 cm or less. At this length the corresponding pressure of the LES can no longer maintain closure, the LES opens, and gastroesophageal reflux occurs. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> This occurs predominately during the postprandial period and is called \u201cdynamic failure of the LES\u201d in that when the gastric distention or dilation is relieved the LES returns to its normal initial length.\n\n## Effacement and Loss of the Lower Esophageal Sphincter\n\nUnderstanding the concept of LES effacement is crucial to comprehending the pathophysiology of GERD. Shortening of the overall length of the LES occurs naturally with gastric filling because the distal end of the LES is \u201ctaken up\u201d by the expanding fundus. This is analogous to the shortening of the neck of a balloon as it is inflated. During the process the distal portion of the neck of the balloon becomes part of the expanded body of the balloon. The process is called effacement and occurs with gastric distention ( Fig. 7.8 ). With voluminous gastric distention, the overall length of the LES shortens to a point at which the existing LES pressure is unable to maintain its closure and belching and/or reflux occurs. Consequently, the patient\u2019s gastric distention is relieved, effacement retreats, and competency of the reflux barrier is restored. This is called dynamic failure of the LES because it is reversible after the distention is relieved ( Fig. 7.5C ). If the length of the LES becomes permanently short ( Fig. 7.5B ), then further shortening caused by normal amounts of gastric distention with meals will readily result in postprandial reflux and gastroesophageal reflux becomes an ever-constant clinical problem.\n\nA diagram shows the stomach expansion that leads to the thinning of the lower esophageal sphincter which leads to the lower part of the esophagus being pulled into the upper part of the stomach. #REF!\n\nFig. 7.8\n\nNot all effacement events result in the reflux of gastric juice into the esophagus. During most effacement events, only the distal end of the LES with its squamous epithelial covering is taken up by the fundus and exposed to gastric juice while the proximal squamous epithelium remains protected. During a meal, there is a pocket of strong acid that collects at the height of the food column just under the GEJ ( Fig. 7.4 ). Inflammation and ulceration occur in the effaced portion of the squamous epithelium exposed to gastric juice. If the inflammation continues due to repetitive episodes of effacement, it can result in permanent damage limiting its ability to respond to intraabdominal pressure challenges and allowing unhampered reflux into the esophagus. The last component of the LES to go is pressure. The loss in pressure is due to injury of the underlying muscle by inflammatory by-products generated from the inflamed squamous epithelium.\n\nThe phenomenon of effacement of the distal end of the LES can be demonstrated at endoscopy. Endoscopic characterizations of the GEFV demonstrate how exposure of the esophageal squamous lining to gastric juice occurs with anatomic breakdown of the reflux barrier (see Chapter 3 ). In a person with normal endoscopy, the squamocolumnar junction (SCJ) is in line with the GEJ. In retroflex view, when the stomach is insufflated with air, the SCJ moves downward and becomes visible ( Fig. 7.9 ). When the same thing happens during a heavy meal, the distal squamous epithelium is in the stomach, below the pH transition point.\n\nTwo endoscopic photos of current and original squamocolumnar junction positions under normal light and narrow band image technique. Photo A shows the current lower esophageal sphincter with a clear view of its position. Photo B presents the changes in the lower esophageal sphincter that highlight the shortened lower esophageal sphincter in comparison to the original length. The colored marks outline the regions of interest, and arrows point to the current lower esophageal sphincter, the shortened lower esophageal sphincter, and other relevant anatomical details.\n\nFig. 7.9\n\nSince LES damage starts because of pressure and effacement from below, it follows that LES damage begins at its distal end and progresses upward. Robertson et al. showed that early LES shortening produced by a heavy meal in asymptomatic volunteers was entirely in the abdominal segment and did not affect the thoracic portion of the LES. When all three components are abnormal, the LES is completely destroyed and will require reconstruction. Figs. 7.10 and 7.11 show that the damage to the LES parallels the severity of esophageal mucosal injury and corroborates a link between damage to the LES, acid exposure, and mucosal injury. Importantly, the precise measurement of the LES length has been lost with the transition of clinical practice from water perfused manometry catheters to high-resolution systems that are better at measuring pressures but less accurate evaluating length.\n\nA stacked bar graph compares the permanent and dynamic failure of the lower esophageal sphincter in various groups. The stacked bar graph with five groups on the horizontal axis represents different patient categories that include Volunteers, Gastroesophageal reflux disease with no complication, Gastroesophageal reflux disease with esophagitis, Gastroesophageal reflux disease with strictures, and Gastroesophageal reflux disease with Barrett''s esophagus. Each category has two bars stacked vertically, a bar for dynamic failure of the lower esophageal sphincter, and another bar for permanent failure. The graph spans from 0 percent to 100 percent on the vertical axis, with exact failure rates labeled above each bar that is 2 divided by 50, 26 divided by 92, 43 divided by 66, 17 divided by 19, and 26 divided by 28. Notes at the bottom indicate statistical significance comparisons.\n\nFig. 7.10\n\nA scatterplot of the potential of hydrogen scores of gastroesophageal reflux disease patients with lower esophageal sphincter conditions is focused on common abnormalities. The scatterplot has the horizontal axis divided into four categories, namely, Normal lower esophageal sphincter, Dynamic lower esophageal sphincter failure, and Permanent lower esophageal sphincter failure. The vertical axis labeled the potential of hydrogen score that ranges from 0 to 75 and data points highlight individual potential of hydrogen scores for normal subjects, equal to 50, and gastroesophageal reflux disease subjects with typical lower esophageal sphincter components, where n equals 406, and those with failed or varying lower esophageal sphincter components. A horizontal line at 15 indicates a threshold.\n\nFig. 7.11\n\n## Histopathological Consequences of Exposure of the Esophagus to Gastric Juice\n\nIncreased esophageal exposure to gastric juice can cause injury to the esophageal epithelium. Injury is manifested on endoscopy by linear or interlacing ulceration and repair by stricture and/or metaplasia of the squamous epithelium to cardiac epithelium. As described, these changes can begin in the earliest stages of sphincter effacement where the SCJ is repeatedly exposed to the gastric environment. The prevalence and severity of injury are not only related to a failure of the barrier but also to the composition of the refluxed gastric juice. Mucosal injury is the highest when the refluxed gastric juice is a mixture of gastric acid and duodenal bile ( Fig. 7.12 ).\n\nA simple bar graph of the prevalence of mucosal injury by reflux type that includes no reflux, gastric acid reflux, and gastroduodenal reflux. The simple bar graph shows three types of gastric juice reflux composition on the horizontal axis. The vertical axis represents the percentage of mucosal injury prevalence, which ranges from 0 percent to 100 percent. The first bar, labeled Controls with no reflux, is minimal, indicating a low prevalence of 5 percent. The second bar, labeled Gastroesophageal reflux disease with gastric acid reflux, reaches approximately 57 percent. The third bar, labeled Gastroesophageal reflux disease with gastroduodenal reflux, has the highest prevalence at 93 percent.\n\nFig. 7.12\n\nUnderstanding the etiology of the pathologic changes within the reflux barrier has been challenging due to the absence of dependable anatomic, endoscopic, or histologic landmarks regarding the position of the LES and the fact the LES cannot be recognized either during endoscopy, at surgery, or on gross examination of surgical specimens. However, through understanding the concept of effacement and tLESRs, it is easy to surmise that the extreme distal aspect of the squamous-lined esophagus is most vulnerable to changes from chronic exposure to gastric juice. It is here that the earliest changes can be seen at the histologic level.\n\nThere are only three basic epithelial types that occur from the proximal end of the esophagus to the pyloric antrum. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> These are (1) stratified squamous epithelium, which is limited to the esophagus in the human and is *always* present; (2) gastric oxyntic mucosa, which is limited to the proximal stomach and not found in the esophagus, and is *always* present ( Fig. 7.13 ); and (3) metaplastic columnar epithelia, which are *always* derived from chronic exposure of esophageal squamous epithelium to gastric juice and are *not always* present. When present, however, metaplastic columnar epithelia are *always* interposed between the distal limit of esophageal squamous epithelium and the proximal limit of gastric oxyntic epithelium ( Fig. 7.14 ).\n\nA photo of a finger like projection of the stained cells viewed under a microscope. #REF!\n\nFig. 7.13\n\nA set of three anatomical diagrams labeled A, B, and C illustrates the progression of gastroesophageal reflux disease and its effects on the squamocolumnar junction and gastric oxyntic epithelium. Diagram A represents the normal state, where squamous epithelium transitions directly to gastric oxyntic epithelium. Diagram B shows the development of intestinal metaplasia in the dilated distal esophagus due to L E S damage. Diagram C illustrates the final phase, where severe L E S dysfunction leads to visible columnar lined esophagus due to extensive acid reflux.\n\nFig. 7.14\n\nMetaplastic columnar epithelium is cardiac epithelium. It consists of three histologic variants ( Fig. 7.15 ): (1) pure cardiac epithelium composed of only mucous cells; (2) cardiac epithelium with parietal cells admixed with mucous cells in the glands (oxyntocardiac epithelium); and (3) cardiac epithelium with goblet cells, which define intestinal metaplasia. The prevalence of these three columnar epithelial types is variable. Intestinal epithelium is the least common and oxyntocardiac epithelium the most prevalent.\n\nA histological view of the dilated distal esophagus reveals three types of metaplastic columnar epithelium. The histological view shows the proximal region with intestinal metaplasia, the middle has cardiac epithelium and oxyntocardiac epithelium lies on the left. Submucosal gland ducts are surrounded by the connective tissues surrounded by the nerves and blood vessels.\n\nFig. 7.15\n\nThe four columnar epithelial types (i.e., three metaplastic and gastric oxyntic epithelium) can be precisely defined by simple histologic criteria based on the presence or absence of mucous cells, parietal cells, and goblet cells. The definition of the epithelial type is applied to every unit of the epithelium, which is defined as a single foveolar-gland complex. Multiple epithelial types can therefore be present in a small area. In the absence of intestinal metaplasia, the pathologist often reports the nonspecific term \u201cjunctional epithelium\u201d or generally \u201ccardiac epithelium.\u201d\n\nIn the absence of squamoepithelial injury, the position of the SCJ and GEJ is concordant ( Fig. 7.16 ). As squamoepithelial injury occurs, metaplastic cardiac epithelium forms, and a new SCJ emerges, separated from the GEJ, and lying further cephalad in the LES. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In other words, the SCJ migrates cephalad in patients with exposure to gastric juice. Exposure of the normal SCJ to gastric juice is so prevalent with normal effacement and tLESRs that benign metaplasia is seen in nearly all adults but importantly the extent of the cephalad migration correlates with the severity of disease. Intestinal metaplasia, associated with the most severe alterations in the reflux barrier, represents the extreme of this migration.\n\nTwo histological sections depict tissue samples. Panel A displays a section with visible layers, while panel B presents a more detailed view of the tissue with distinct structures. The two histological sections are labeled A and B. Panel A shows a section of tissue with visible layers that include the surface epithelium and underlying structures. Panel B provides a closer, more detailed view of the tissue with distinct features such as the deeper tissue layers, cellular structure, and any potential abnormalities. Both sections appear stained in a typical manner for histological examination that reveals the organization and structure of the sample for further analysis.\n\nFig. 7.16\n\nThe early literature regarded intestinal metaplasia a congenital disorder, and not until 1959 had sufficient clinical evidence accumulated to suggest that it was an acquired abnormality caused by exposure to gastric juice. The acquired etiology was confirmed experimentally in the landmark report of Bremner et al. in 1970. Hayward in 1961 brought attention to the GEJ and SCJ zone by stating that the lower 1 to 2 cm of the esophagus is normally lined by a mucus-secreting columnar epithelium that has the ability to resist acid-peptic digestion. He argued that this epithelium prevents squamous epithelial digestion by providing a buffer between it and the acid-pepsin producing oxyntic mucosa of the fundus. Although Hayward\u2019s description placed this columnar mucosa in the lower esophagus, it has over time, without any logical or scientific basis, come to be regarded as the cardiac zone of the stomach and was termed cardiac mucosa. Hayward\u2019s thoughts persisted until 1976, when it was recognized that three different types of glandular epithelium could line the lower esophagus with visible columnar lining : oxyntocardiac mucosa containing chief and parietal cells; cardiac mucosa containing mucous cells and no chief and parietal cells; and intestinalized cardiac mucosa with a villiform surface, mucous glands, alcian blue\u2013staining goblet cells, and no parietal or chief cells. When present, the intestinalized cardiac mucosa is always most proximal (at the level of the SCJ) and the oxyntocardiac mucosa most distal, with cardiac mucosa interposed between them. Thus the traditional view that the anatomic gastric cardia is lined by cardiac mucosa is questioned. Rather, cardiac mucosa appears to be a metaplastic mucosa that occurs as a sequel to repeated exposure to gastric juice from LES effacement. This process likely represents a change in the direction of differentiation of the germinal cells of the squamous epithelium toward metaplastic cardiac epithelium. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Exposure of the effaced squamous epithelium to acidic gastric juice results in inflammatory damage and the formation of squamous epithelial islands separated by newly formed metaplastic cardiac epithelium. In nearly all circumstances, metaplastic cardiac mucosa, when present, shows inflammatory and reactive changes referred to as carditis. Biopsies of this area, commonly imprecisely referred to as the cardia, will demonstrate the presence of esophageal specific submucosal glands. From there the benign biopsy can further be characterized as cardiac mucosa, oxyntocardiac mucosa, or intestinal metaplasia but will not be normal gastric oxyntic mucosa of the stomach ( Fig. 7.17 ).\n\nA photo of intricate biological tissue under a microscope. #REF!\n\nFig. 7.17\n\nAlthough rare, this inflamed metaplastic cardiac mucosa is the only mucosal type that progresses to intestinal metaplasia. When this occurs, the metaplastic cardiac mucous cells develop acid rather than neutral mucin and take on a positive stain with alcian blue. Subsequently, well-formed goblet cells appear. Once intestinalized, the metaplastic cardia mucosa seems to have an increased ability to withstand damage by refluxed gastric juice, because biopsy shows little or no inflammation. The development of intestinal metaplasia within metaplastic cardiac mucosa is considered a detrimental change because this mucosa can progress to dysplasia and adenocarcinoma. In contrast, intestinal metaplasia does not occur within metaplastic cardiac mucosa that has undergone oxyntic mucosal transformation (i.e., oxyntocardiac epithelium) because of exposure to gastric juice. Oxyntic transformation of metaplastic cardiac mucosa appears to protect against the development of intestinal metaplasia and is a beneficial change.\n\n## Hiatal Hernia and Reflux\n\nThe definition of hiatal hernia is the cephalad migration of the GEJ above the hiatus leading to a separation between the CD and the LES ( Fig. 7.18 ). Small separations are common and not by themselves a defining clinical pathology. However, the presence of a hiatal hernia has been associated with the progression of mild esophagitis to severe esophagitis. As the hernia develops, the proximal portion of the LES is exposed to the negative pressure environment of the chest and loses the pressure contribution of the CD. As a result, compliance of the LES is substantially higher in hiatal hernias of at least 1 cm as measured by hydrostatic pressure. These alterations together reduce the ability of the LES to remain closed. At a certain point, the combination of a weakened LES and the emergence of a hiatal hernia reaches a threshold where pathologic reflux is more likely. The reflux threshold of LES herniation depends upon the inherent integrity of the LES within the hernia. In other words, an otherwise competent LES can tolerate small migrations whereas an already failing LES has less reserve and may become symptomatic earlier. If the forces creating the hernia persist, the phrenoesophageal ligaments eventually become more lax, the esophageal hiatus enlarges, and the opportunity for larger hernias to develop emerges. As hernias enlarge, the LES becomes completely decoupled from the diaphragm removing any barrier contribution of the crura on the GEJ. In GERD, the cephalad migration of the GEJ seen in hiatal hernia development occurs in concert with the loss of the tubular structure of the LES.\n\nA diagram depicts the human digestive system and a diaphragm. The gastroesophageal junction has moved above the diaphragm. #REF!\n\nFig. 7.18\n\n## Loss of the Normal Anatomy of the GEFV and the Dilated Distal Esophagus\n\nFrom a gross anatomy standpoint, the insertion of the esophagus occurs along the lesser curvature with a complex transition from circular esophageal muscles to junctional sling fibers. The sling fibers along with contributions of the left crus create the angle of His and provide a valvular anatomic structure to the normal GEJ. This asymmetrical orientation places the GEJ typically at least 1 cm below the external landmark at the angle of His. This creates a structural fold internally on the greater curvature side of the junction. The GEFV is the term used to denote the appearance of this anatomy as seen on endoscopy. Endoscopic grading systems for the GEFV can be reviewed in Chapter 3 . Destruction of the structure of the GEFV correlates with the severity of reflux in a graded fashion similar to progressive damage of the LES and hiatal hernias. A normal GEFV looks perfectly snug around the endoscope and the fold covers the distal tubular esophagus containing a competent LES. The process of effacement and reflux weakens the tissues of the GEFV. As the LES becomes progressively more damaged, the appearance of the fold is lost and the GEFV no longer holds the endoscope instead appearing patulous exposing the esophageal mucosa to the retroflexed vantage point. Most often, this gaping valve is associated with the presence a hiatal hernia although not always.\n\nA largely unappreciated normal function of the LES is to maintain the tubular shape of the abdominal esophagus and likely the structural integrity of the GEFV. The high resting pressure of the LES continually opposes the dilatory tendency of the positive (around +5 mmHg) intraluminal pressure of the abdominal esophagus and holds the valve in place. When the LES is damaged, the protection provided by the tonic contraction of the LES is lost. The dilatory positive intraluminal pressure will be accentuated during meals when the stomach distends and the intragastric pressure increases. The distal abdominal esophagus that has lost LES pressure will therefore dilate to form the dilated distal esophagus ( Fig. 7.3 ). Normally, in a person with a completely intact LES, the entire abdominal esophagus is tubular, lined by squamous epithelium to its end (the GEJ) where it transitions to gastric oxyntic epithelium. There is no metaplastic columnar epithelium (i.e., cardiac epithelium). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> With LES damage, the tubular abdominal esophagus shortens, the damaged esophagus dilates and takes up the gastric contour and becomes part of the reservoir, and the angle of His becomes more obtuse. This can be seen endoscopically as loss of the GEFV structure. Mucosal rugal folds, which are a feature of all reservoir organs, may develop in this dilated distal esophagus. This \u201cgastricization\u201d of the abdominal esophagus that has lost LES tone occurs at a manometric, endoscopic, and gross anatomic level. Therefore, the abnormal state where the LES is damaged is defined by the presence of a dilated distal esophagus. The length of the dilated distal esophagus, as measured by histology, has a strong correlation with the cellular changes associated with GERD. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The dilated distal esophagus has a variable length that is equal to the amount of shortening of the LES due to damage. The visible end of the tubular esophagus is now proximal to the true GEJ by the length of the dilated distal esophagus.\n\nThe presence of a dilated distal esophagus, especially in the setting of a hiatal hernia, can make defining the true GEJ quite difficult endoscopically. The most widely used definition of the GEJ is the proximal limit of rugal folds. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> This is a reasonably precise endoscopic landmark and can usually be seen in gross specimens in normal subjects. The basis of the definition is the opinion of experts. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Despite its universal acceptance, there is no evidence that it accurately represents the GEJ. On the contrary, the area distal to the endoscopic GEJ may very well be esophageal tissue in many people ( Fig. 7.19A and B ). The changes in columnar metaplasia confirming the presence of dilated distal esophagus have been eloquently demonstrated in autopsy studies. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> When visible columnar metaplasia is present, the dilated distal esophagus is measured from the endoscopic GEJ (end of tubular esophagus or proximal limit of rugal folds) to the proximal limit of gastric oxyntic epithelium ( Fig. 7.20 ) Therefore, the correct definition of the true GEJ is the proximal limit of gastric oxyntic epithelium. This never changes its position relative to the stomach. In the person with LES damage, whether symptoms or GERD are present or not, the true GEJ is separated from the endoscopic GEJ by cardiac epithelium (with and without parietal and/or goblet cells; see Fig. 7.14 ). The dilated distal esophagus can therefore be precisely measured by examining the mucosa distal to the endoscopic GEJ through extensive biopsies. Newer technologies such as optical confocal laser endomicroscopy, which provides the ability to obtain histologic images, may be useful to evaluate for the presence of a dilated distal esophagus in real time during endoscopy.\n\nTwo anatomical features with panel A, display the unmarked specimen and panel B, highlight specific areas with colored lines and dots for analysis. The anatomical views of the specimen are labeled A and B. Panel A presents the specimen without any marks, while panel B highlights specific regions with colored lines and dots. The colored lines in panel B outline different anatomical areas of interest, possibly to emphasize sections for further analysis. The specimen appears to be from the digestive tract, and the marks are used to focus on particular sections for study or diagnostic purposes. The lower part of both panels includes a metric scale for reference.\n\nFig. 7.19\n\nAn illustration of esophagectomy specimens from eight patients. The illustration represents the specimen with esophageal cancer that developed from Barrett''s esophagus. The specimens have a wider lower half and a narrow upper half. Equally spaced divisions next to the specimen are labeled 5 centimeters. The wider half of the specimen includes red and black regions forming an upper meniscus with black vertical lines. The upper halves include green and grey regions that vary in all specimens.\n\nFig. 7.20\n\n## Clinical Severity of Disease\n\nGERD is a progressive phenomenon that originates, on a pathophysiologic level, well before symptoms are present. When looked at from the perspective of LES damage, progression is inexorable from the onset of LES damage to the endpoint defined as the end of life, or some intervention that stops the progression, such as an antireflux procedure. To date, medical therapy has not been demonstrated to alter this process despite their remarkable effectiveness at ameliorating symptoms and healing esophagitis.\n\nIn general, the greater the barrier damage, the greater is the severity of reflux. Kahrilas et al. beautifully demonstrated LES length a critical determinant of the severity of reflux by comparing three groups with increasing severity of GERD: patients who had no symptoms of GERD (\u201cnormal\u201d), patients with GERD without a hiatal hernia, and patients with GERD who had a hiatal hernia. The baseline LES length in the fasting state was progressively less in normal persons compared to those with nonhernia GERD and hernia GERD. This correlated with an increase in baseline reflux as measured by a pH test. The investigators then infused air into the stomach at 15 mL/min, causing progressive gastric distention. This caused an additional shortening of the LES from baseline in all three groups as distention increased. The additional temporary shortening of the LES was similar in the three groups, suggesting that gastric overdistention caused LES exposure to gastric contents in a linear manner. During the temporary shortening of the LES with gastric distention, the number of reflux episodes and total acid exposure in the esophagus increased significantly and most prominently in the hernia-GERD group. This showed that a damaged LES with a shorter baseline length was more susceptible to failure when exposed to gastric distention including otherwise asymptomatic persons.\n\nTo further understand the effects of mechanical factors in the progression of GERD under proton pump inhibitor (PPI) therapy, Dr. Tom DeMeester studied the existence of mechanical abnormalities in the spectrum of GERD. This included factors such as anatomic distortion of the hiatal anatomy by a hiatal hernia, abnormalities of the LES, and the effects of LES incompetency on esophageal exposure to acid and bile. Fifty symptomatic consecutive patients were identified for each of the four stages of GERD from the preoperative records of those who had a laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication performed by us. The stages were (1) NERD; (2) mild ERD, defined as \u201chealable esophagitis\u201d with PPI therapy; (3) severe ERD, defined as \u201cdifficult to heal esophagitis\u201d that persisted despite PPI therapy; and (4) Barrett\u2019s esophagus (BE). All patients\u2019 records contained a detailed preoperative clinical questionnaire, and all underwent a preoperative upper gastrointestinal endoscopy, esophageal manometry, and distal esophageal pH monitoring. Patients who had received PPI therapy prior to their initial endoscopy were excluded from the NERD group. BE was diagnosed by the presence of microscopic intestinal metaplasia on biopsy of an endoscopic visible columnar-lined esophagus of any length. The final studied population consisted of 39 patients with NERD, 42 with mild ERD (i.e., healable esophagitis), 35 with severe ERD (i.e., difficult to heal esophagitis), and 44 with BE. The significant anatomic and physiologic differences between the patient groups are shown in Fig. 7.21 . The difference between the patient groups \u201chealable esophagitis\u201d and the \u201cdifficult to heal esophagitis\u201d was the status of their LES. Preoperative mechanical factors (i.e., altered hiatal anatomy, LES resting pressure, and LES lengths) were significantly more impaired in patients with \u201cdifficult to heal esophagitis\u201d and intestinal metaplasia compared with those with \u201chealable esophagitis\u201d and NERD. Esophageal acid and bile exposure also was worse in the more severe GERD stages with the most severe in patients with BE. The composite pH score, which includes all the acid reflux measures in a weighted calculation of reflux severity, discriminated most clearly between the different GERD stages. The findings link the extent and severity of endoscopic mucosal injury with the extent and severity of mechanical abnormalities at the gastroesophageal barrier. Furthermore, they suggest that progression of GERD in a patient on PPI therapy commonly requires a concomitant reduction in LES length and pressure and altered hiatal anatomy. These findings are similar to other studies of regression analysis, which show that the status of the LES and size of the hiatal hernia are dominant determinants of esophagitis and its severity. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Taken together, the aforementioned studies show most importantly the following: (1) the treatment of GERD with PPIs does not prevent progression of disease; (2) the stages of GERD severity correlate well with the altered mechanical features of the gastroesophageal reflux barrier; (3) damage to the LES is associated with altered hiatal anatomy, increased esophageal exposure to refluxed acid and bile; and (4) PPI therapy does not protect against continuing LES damage. These findings encourage the concept that to stop the progression of GERD requires (1) early recognition of the symptoms and signs of progressive disease, (2) manometric assessment of the LES, (3) measurements of esophageal acid exposure, (4) endoscopic examination of the esophagus, and, if indicated, (5) early surgical intervention to correct the LES abnormalities. To do so requires an understanding of the pathophysiology and the histopathology of GERD.\n\nA flowchart of the progression of esophageal disease over time. The flowchart presents the esophageal conditions. It details various factors affecting esophageal health, each accompanied by marked P-values that indicate statistical significance, defective lower esophageal sphincter, acid exposure with P less than point 05, bile exposure, and hiatal hernia. The chart flows from normal subjects to categories which include non-erosive reflux disease, no injury, healable esophagitis, Difficulty in healing esophagitis, and Barrett''s esophagus. A horizontal arrow at the bottom indicates a time range of 2 to 20 years. Visual elements include bold text for key terms and circled P-values to emphasize statistical findings.\n\nFig. 7.21\n\n## Conclusion\n\nAs clinicians, we depend upon objective assessments of the reflux barrier components to determine treatment strategies. As surgeons, understanding which component is failing and to what degree may impact operative strategies and decision making. Some people will progress from early effacement of the LES and occasional heartburn to permanent loss of the structural integrity of the reflux barrier. This is associated with breakdown of each component to varying degrees. To some extent there is redundancy in the barrier system such that a breakdown of one component alone does not necessarily result in complete failure. For example, many people are known to have small incidentally diagnosed hiatal hernias without troublesome reflux symptoms. Further, almost half of the patients with confirmed abnormal esophageal acid exposure by 24-hour esophageal pH monitoring have a normal LES on a motility study. Therefore, a single unified explanation for the progression of disease does not exist. However, many studies have shown that disease severity is associated with increasing number of dysfunctional barrier components. Still for most people with GERD, it is generally postulated that repeated increased intraabdominal pressure leads to chronic LES effacement and loss of LES function, widening of the esophageal hiatus, with elongation of the phrenoesophageal ligaments with ultimate cephalad progression of the GEJ into the mediastinum. Increased abdominal pressure can be due to postprandial gastric distention but also by other mechanisms such as weight gain, repeated vomiting, and repetitive heaving lifting. Whatever the cause or sequence of events, disruptions in the strength and alignment of the components weaken the function of the barrier. Importantly, an unknown number of people will undergo the histopathological changes associated with effacement without any measurable symptoms at all. Understanding this process has the potential to have a large impact on our understanding of GEJ cancer.\n\n## Acknowledgments\n\nThe authors would like to acknowledge with deep respect and gratitude the contributions of Dr. Tom DeMeester to the field of GERD and specifically to this chapter.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Agrawal A., Castell D.O.: GERD is chronic but not progressive . J Clin Gastroenterol 2006; 40: pp. 374-375.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n2.: Pace F., Bianchi Porro G.: Gastroesophageal reflux disease: a typical spectrum disease (a new conceptual framework is not needed) . Am J Gastroenterol 2004; 99: pp. 946-949.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: Labenz J., Nocon M., Lind T., et al.: Prospective follow-up data from the ProGERD study suggest that GERD is not a categorial disease . Am J Gastroenterol 2006; 101: pp. 2457-2462.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Bonavina L., Evander A., DeMeester T.R., et al.: Length of the distal esophageal sphincter and competency of the cardia . Am J Surg 1986; 151: pp. 25-34.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference90007-3)\n\n5.: Zaninotto G., DeMeester T.R., Schwizer W., Johansson K.E., Cheng S.C.: The lower esophageal sphincter in health and disease . Am J Surg 1988; 155: pp. 104-111.\n\nView In Article\n\n6.: DeMeester T.R., Johnson L.F., Joseph G.J., Toscano M.S., Hall A.W., Skinner D.B.: Patterns of gastroesophageal reflux in health and disease . Ann Surg 1976; 184: pp. 459-470.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n7.: DeMeester T.R., Wernly J.A., Bryant G.H., Little A.G., Skinner D.B.: Clinical and in vitro analysis of determinants of gastroesophageal competence . Am J Surg 1979; 137: pp. 39-46.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference90008-4)\n\n8.: Johnson L.F., Lin Y.C., Hong S.K.: Gastroesophageal dynamics during immersion in water to the neck . J Appl Physiol 1975; 38: pp. 449-454.\n\nView In Article\n\n9.: Pellegrini C.A., DeMeester T.R., Skinner D.B.: Response of the 