-21.8c-.3%200-.6-.3-.6-.6V7zm28.8%200c0-.4.2-.6.5-.6h5.2c.3%200%20.6.2.6.6v30.5c0%20.3%200%20.4.3.4H151c.3%200%20.5.2.5.5V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.5.6h-20.8c-.3%200-.517-.3-.5-.6V7zm47.7%2036.7c-.4%200-.6-.2-.8-.5l-7.3-12.7-7.4%2012.7c-.2.3-.4.5-.8.5h-5.8c-.3%200-.5-.3-.3-.7L166%2024.3%20156%207.1c-.2-.4%200-.7.3-.7h5.8c.4%200%20.6.1.8.5l6.5%2011.3h.1L176%206.9c.2-.4.5-.5.9-.5h5.7c.4%200%20.5.3.3.7l-10%2017.2L183.7%2043c.2.4%200%20.7-.3.7h-5.8zM192.015%2019c-.2%200-.338-.004-.3-.2V8.4h-3.3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n\n\nNeed help? Chat with AI Buddy!\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[6. Esophageal Symptoms and Selection of Diagnostic Tests - ClinicalKey|6. Esophageal Symptoms and Selection of Diagnostic Tests]]\n**Next:** [[8. Acid-Suppression Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and the Therapeutic Gap - ClinicalKey|8. Acid-Suppression Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and the Therapeutic Gap]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "7. Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'GERD Pathophysiology', 'Lower Esophageal Sphincter', 'Transient LES Relaxations', 'Hiatal Hernia', 'Histopathology', 'GERD Pathophysiology / Lower Esophageal Sphincter', 'GERD Pathophysiology / Transient LES Relaxations', 'GERD Pathophysiology / Hiatal Hernia', 'GERD Pathophysiology / Histopathology'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '7', '89-102', 2, 46, FALSE, TRUE),
('Acid-Suppression Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and the Therapeutic Gap', 'shackelford-9th-ed-8-acid-suppression-therapy-for-gastroesophageal-reflux-disease-and-the-therapeuti', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Acid-Suppression Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and the Therapeutic Gap\n\nParakrama Chandrasoma; Christy M. Dunst\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 8, 103-110\n\n## Acknowledgments\n\nThe authors would like to acknowledge with deep respect and gratitude the contributions of Dr. Tom DeMeester to the field of GERD and specifically to this chapter.\n\n## Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease Therapeutic Gap\n\nGastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) is the most common foregut disease in the world and accounts for approximately 75% of all esophageal pathology. The majority of affected patients have mild disease and are successfully managed with lifestyle modifications and acid suppression medication, most commonly with proton pump inhibitors (PPIs). However, up to 50% of patients with reflux symptoms do not achieve a satisfactory response to PPI therapy due to persistent symptoms of heartburn, regurgitation, and associated negative effects on quality of life. The safety and efficacy of antireflux surgery is well documented, but its reputation is tarnished by side effects. Therefore, only a small fraction of unsatisfied patients ever receives escalation of treatment to surgery. This combination of factors creates a substantial therapeutic gap in the treatment of patients with GERD ( Fig. 8.1 ).\n\nAn illustration shows the correlation between the severity of symptoms and patient dissatisfaction with proton pump inhibitor therapy for gastroesophageal reflux disease. The illustration depicts a triangular region divided into three sections for symptom severity, dissatisfaction, and treatment options for patients with esophageal and hernia conditions. The triangle base denotes the severity of symptoms and dissatisfaction rising from low to high rightward. The largest section on the left indicates patients satisfied with proton pump inhibitor therapy with lower symptom severity and dissatisfaction. The middle section represents gastroesophageal reflux disease patients with persistent symptoms with higher symptom severity and dissatisfaction despite proton pump inhibitor use with the therapy gap. The smallest section on the right denotes high dissatisfaction among reflux disease patients who elected to receive antireflux surgery despite proton pump inhibitor use.\n\nFig. 8.1\n\n## Who Is in the Gap?\n\nThe unifying characteristic among individuals in the gap is that they are people with GERD symptoms who are unsatisfied with medical treatment. The exact composition of clinical scenarios within the gap is largely unknown. An easy conclusion is that to close the gap, we need to increase access to surgery. However, it is unlikely that all individuals in the gap are suitable surgical candidates based on symptoms alone. GERD is often defined as a condition that develops when the reflux of stomach contents into the esophagus causes troublesome symptoms such as heartburn and/or regurgitation. However, symptoms alone are fairly inaccurate to conclude that pathologic GERD is actually the underlying etiology. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> There is not always a clear correlation between reflux symptoms and objective evidence of the disease as patients may have typical reflux symptoms in the absence of endoscopic esophagitis or have endoscopic esophagitis in the absence of typical reflux symptoms <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> ( Fig. 8.2 ). Despite the unreliability of symptoms to define the disease, objective testing with ambulatory pH monitoring is infrequently done when patients first present with symptoms because PPIs are effective for the majority of patients who have early GERD. Therefore, most patients receive empiric acid-suppressive treatment with PPIs with the sole objective of symptom control. A positive empiric test of PPI therapy is commonly used to confirm the symptom-based diagnosis of GERD. The common treatment algorithm for GERD ( Fig. 8.3 ) can be described as reactive with many patients not receiving further evaluation such as endoscopy until \u201ctroublesome\u201d symptoms develop. As a result, the therapeutic gap is likely a mix of patients that are incompletely evaluated for disease severity and could be offered surgery, those who are misdiagnosed, and those who have subthreshold and/or functional heartburn.\n\nA pair of bar graphs display two scores for two groups based on their responses to a gastroesophageal reflux disease questionnaire. The bar graphs compare the brief symptom index score and the patient reported outcome measurement system global quality of life score for two treatment groups based on the acid exposure time and self reported assessments. The first bar graph shows the brief symptom index scores for the gastroesophageal reflux disease questionnaire, which are less than 8, and the gastroesophageal reflux disease questionnaire, which are greater than or equal to 8, subgroups. The lower acid exposure and self reports show comparable index score differences, while for higher acid exposures the index scores are almost the same. The second bar graph shows the patient reported outcome measurement system global quality of life scores, gastroesophageal reflux disease questionnaire less than 8, and gastroesophageal reflux disease questionnaire greater than or equal to 8 subgroups. In both the bar graphs, the difference in index score for lower acid exposure and self reports remains the same as for the higher acid exposures the index scores. The scores for questionnaire scores of less than 8 remain lower than the index scores for questionnaire scores higher than or equal to 8 in both bar graphs.\n\nFig. 8.2\n\nA flowchart depicts diagnostic pathways for a person with no gastroesophageal reflux disease symptoms with potential diagnoses of early cancer or dysplasia. The flowchart presents decision pathways for Barrett''s esophagus diagnosis in individuals without gastroesophageal reflux disease symptoms. It features rectangular process boxes and diamond decision points with arrows that indicate progression. Key points include undetected Barrett, symptomatic gastroesophageal reflux disease, proton pump inhibitor therapy, controlled, dose escalation, failure to control, and outcomes, which indicate risk percentages for advanced cancer is 90 percent, and dysplasia or early cancer, which is 10 percent. The layout is hierarchical, effectively guiding the viewer through clinical decision-making steps.\n\nFig. 8.3\n\n### Patients With Functional Heartburn in the Gap\n\nDespite the high percentage of patients who report persistent symptoms with medical therapy, expert gastroenterologists and surgeons recognize that failure to respond to PPI does not simply indicate undermedication and may instead alert to alternative diagnoses. Psychological symptoms by themselves do not differentiate between true refractory GERD and what is referred to as \u201cfunctional heartburn.\u201d Functional heartburn is the term used to describe patients who have typical GERD symptoms but negative objective testing. A recent study investigated PPI-refractory heartburn and found that only 21% were truly refractory when compliance was monitored and objective testing was used. Over the past 20 years, much effort has gone into understanding the complexities of GERD symptomatology beyond the strict definition of abnormal esophageal acid exposure. The concept of GERD phenotypes aims to incorporate the impact of visceral and central hypersensitivity, hypervigilance, and anxiety into the evaluation of patients with GERD symptoms but who are not improved with PPI therapy. Anxiety and hypervigilance are known to augment the central response to esophageal stimulation to both normal acid exposure events and esophageal distention. Our understanding of the pathophysiology of GERD as a complex syndrome with a broad range of underlying etiologies continues to grow with dedicated research. It is apparent that simply controlling acid, either medically or surgically, may not be the answer for all patients with GERD symptoms. The percentage of the gap that is occupied by functional disorders is unknown, but escalating acid control either medically or surgically is unlikely to be the answer.\n\n### Surgical Candidates in the Gap\n\nAn abundance of peer reviewed research has definitively demonstrated that laparoscopic fundoplication is an effective treatment for GERD. To achieve the excellent published results with antireflux surgery, the criteria for surgical therapy has been narrowly defined. Dozens of studies have demonstrated that, specifically, an abnormal pH test is the best predictor of a successful outcome with antireflux surgery. Therefore, definitive objective evidence of abnormal esophageal acid exposure is required to confirm the presence of disease prior to offering antireflux surgery. In addition, regurgitation dominant GERD has been shown to have a reduced response to PPI therapy and is particularly suited for surgical correction if abnormal acid exposure off antisecretory medication is confirmed. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nLevel 1 evidence comparing PPI with fundoplication has shown that although reflux control was superior for the surgical group, PPI was associated with significantly fewer side effects like dysphagia, bloating, and flatulence. For this reason, it is generally accepted that a trial of PPI is prudent before making a decision to escalate reflux control to surgery to avoid unnecessary side effects. However, in practice, most clinicians fail to discuss surgical alternatives even with their unsatisfied patients, which limits patients\u2019 access to consider all treatment modalities. Instead, in the absence of a complete response to a trial of PPIs, it is recommended that the dose of PPIs be doubled. If this does not lead to symptom resolution, finally a 24-hour esophageal pH monitoring study or endoscopy may be performed. If these studies are abnormal, it has historically been recommended that the PPI dose be further increased or an alternative PPI prescribed. As quality surgery has improved and concerns about PPI are evolving, major gastroenterology societies have updated recommendations for PPI therapy including dose deescalation and guidelines for surgical referral that have slowly begun to disseminate throughout the medical community. However, in the meantime, many patients in the gap are likely in this scenario of dose escalation and failure of the treating clinician to recognize progressive disease that could be amenable to surgical correction.\n\n### Patients With Subthreshold GERD in the Gap or Visceral Hypersensitivity?\n\nThe spectrum of GERD severity ranges from isolated mild symptoms to the development of significant concurrent anatomic consequences. Historically, the \u201cdisease\u201d is quantified by objective esophageal acid exposure testing. This is accomplished by placing a pH monitor 5 cm above the manometric upper border of the lower esophageal sphincter (LES) or 6 cm above the gastroesophageal junction on endoscopy. The decision to measure the pH in this precise location above the reflux barrier was not determined by any biologic or clinical thresholds but instead selected based on technical limitations of the emerging technology at the time. Normal values were established defining abnormal as acid exposure as levels falling outside the 95th percentile of individuals. This narrow window makes the diagnostic test highly specific, by design, but disregards the potential clinical impact of reflux events between the pH sensor and the reflux barrier. To date, the quantification of acid exposure as currently measured has not been shown to be a useful tool to differentiate between normal pH range GERD phenotypes. It is conceivable that high-frequency reflux events in this unmonitored zone could very well be quite symptomatic and could respond well to antireflux therapy. In some instances, a subthreshold number of acid reflux events will strongly correlate with symptoms on objective testing. Currently, we define these patients as having visceral or esophageal hypersensitivity. Hypersensitivity is generated at both the mucosal level, with increased mucosal permeability, <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> and centrally with enhanced pain transmission and perception. Medical therapy such as selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors and others have been shown to improve symptoms in these patients.\n\nTraditionally these patients are not offered antireflux surgery because the abnormal pH test has been shown to be the most reliable predictor of a favorable outcome to surgical intervention. We accept and support this restrictive prerequisite for surgery because the worst mistake is operating on someone with minor symptoms or symptoms amenable to lifestyle changes and giving them side effects without a perceivable improvement in their day-to-day quality of life. In 2018, the criteria for abnormal acid exposure have been elevated from 4% to 6% as measured with prolonged pH testing. The consensus acknowledges a gray zone of reflux between 4% and 6%, but this is still based on measurements taken 5\u20136 cm above the barrier. Unsurprisingly, tightening the criteria for surgery may result in a higher percentage of satisfied surgical patients by ruling out a few more false positives, but it may also potentially increase the gap.\n\nMuch more work needs to be done to identify patients who are below the traditional pH threshold of our current testing but who may be better served with surgical alternatives due to true symptomatic medically refractory reflux in the distal esophagus. Advanced diagnostics may be helpful in identifying this group of patients with subthreshold GERD. Mucosal impedance technology is an endoscopic test that measures the epithelial conductivity of the squamous cell lining of the esophagus without the same technical constraints found in a standard pH exposure test. The integrity of the squamous mucosa is impaired to varying degrees by inflammation, which results in edema and dilated intracellular spaces that can be measured using impedance as a surrogate. Results have been correlated with histological features found on biopsy both in the proximal and distal esophagus as well as to PPI response. The technology shows promise to differentiate between reflux-related symptoms and other etiologies. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Early appearance of columnar-lined esophageal metaplasia has also been proposed as an early marker of reflux damage (see Chapter 7 ). Presently, differentiating between potential subthreshold GERD and visceral hypersensitivity has not been extensively studied. Patients with these scenarios are generally not considered for surgery, but further research may identify a subgroup for which a low-risk mechanical adjunct to medical management may be useful.\n\n## Consequences of Reliance on PPI Response to Guide Therapy\n\nThe presence of such a large therapeutic gap suggests that many patients with GERD symptoms are incompletely or incorrectly managed. Many patients on lifelong PPI therapy are under the assumption that their current therapy is the best that can be offered and that nothing more can or needs to be done. This leads them to \u201clive with it\u201d and GERD becomes an ignored entry on the medical record problem list. Beyond troubling symptoms, the gravest consequence of GERD is the development of esophageal cancer. Fortunately, progression to erosive disease occurs in only 13% of patients over 5 years. Unfortunately, progression to visible columnar metaplasia, or Barrett\u2019s esophagus (BE), the premalignant lesion for adenocarcinoma of the esophagus, occurs in 10% of patients over 5 years. It is estimated that more than 113 million PPI prescriptions are filled globally each year, yet we continue to see this pattern. This has led to concerns that PPI therapy does not directly address the underlying cause of the disease. A 10% progression to BE every 5 years is therefore an enormous problem. While the development of increasingly effective acid-reducing drugs has brought symptomatic relief to millions of people, relying on symptom control alone allows us to ignore the greatest increase of a specific cancer type in the history of medicine. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nMultiple studies demonstrate the progression of disease while on PPI. The best available scientific prospective study of long-term outcomes associated with treating symptomatic GERD with acid-suppressive medical therapy is the Pro-GERD study. A total of 6215 patients aged >18 years old with the primary symptom of heartburn were enrolled into this prospective multicenter open cohort study in Europe. The study was largely conducted under the auspices of Astra-Zeneca, makers of esomeprazole, which makes any result that suggests a negative effect of PPI therapy highly credible. It is important to note that patients with BE were excluded. The study consisted of an initial endoscopy, followed by 4 to 8 weeks of PPI therapy, and subsequently maintenance therapy. A follow-up endoscopy was performed at 2 and 5 years. Progression to biopsy-proven BE during the 5 years of therapy was observed in 5.9% of patients with nonerosive reflux disease (NERD), 12.1% of patients with mild erosive disease (LA grade A/B), and 19.7% of patients with severe erosive disease (LA grade C/D). Overall, 10% of patients progressed to BE during the 5-year follow-up period. This study clearly showed that disease progression occurred in a proportion of patients while receiving PPI therapy and established that, although regular and consistent PPI therapy can improve symptoms and heal erosive esophagitis, it does not stop progression to BE. When one considers that 20% to 40% of the population have symptomatic GERD, 10% translates to an absolute number that easily explains why GERD-induced adenocarcinoma has increased sevenfold since the 1980s. Patients in the gap are at risk for disease progression if the medical community fails to recognize this crucial pattern.\n\n## How to Address the GAP?\n\nSo far in this chapter, we have discussed the composition of the gap and the various reasons why gap patients might be underserved. Next, we will discuss how we might be able to shrink the gap.\n\n### Improved Medical Therapy\n\nAlthough PPI medications are extremely powerful, they cause an incomplete elevation in pH leading to fluctuations throughout a range of pH values depending on dosing schedule and interaction of the reflux gastric juice, duodenal juice, and saliva at the squamocolumnar interface ( Fig. 8.4 ). This inconsistency may be part of the underlying mechanism for incomplete PPI response. Elevating the pH of gastric juice has known effects ( Table 8.1 ). Under normal physiologic conditions, the pKa of bile acids allows them to be absorbed across the mucosal border of the terminal ileum but in the acidic stomach, bile acids precipitate and have minimal effect. The amount of bile acids in the stomach varies by individual. Alkalinization of gastric juice with PPIs clearly improves acid-related GERD symptoms and heals esophagitis, but it also changes the exposure to potentially toxic bile acids. When nondissociated, nonpolar bile-acid molecules reflux into the esophagus, they can enter the mucosal cells where they can impair mitochondrial function, become cytotoxic, and function as co-mutagens or likely direct mutagens. If soluble bile acids are to remain innocuous in a patient with chronic reflux managed by acid suppression therapy, they must remain completely ionized. This requires that a gastric pH of 6 to 7 be maintained 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, while the patient is on acid suppression therapy. This is not only impractical but probably impossible without very high doses of medication or new medications. A new class of medications known as small molecule potassium-competitive acid blockers (P-CABs) is now available. Both PPIs and P-CABs work on the gastric hydrogen-potassium-ATPase pump in the stomach. PPIs need to access active pumps to bind (therefore, patients are advised to take it before meals), but P-CABs can bind anytime. Early data suggests a more potent and durable acid suppression profile with P-CABs, but it is unknown whether it will be sufficiently high to stabilize bile acids and their potential toxic effects. P-CABs may improve patient compliance by eliminating the restrictive dosing schedule around meals, which may translate into improved therapeutic benefits and treatment satisfaction, thereby closing the gap.\n\nA graph represents the chemical system''s relationship between the potential of hydrogen and ionic species. The graph depicts the potential of hydrogen levels from 0 to 8 on the horizontal axis and the percentage of ionization on the vertical axis from 0 to 100 percent. The graph is divided into three sections, the insoluble or precipitate formation on the left, the danger zone in the center, and the ionized and unable to enter the cell on the right. The curve is stable till p H level 2 and lies in the insoluble section. It rises as the percentage ionization increases for a higher p H value of 6. The curve is again stable for 100 percent of ionization with salt formations with Hydrogen and Carboxylate ions. A formula states, that the p H equals 4.3 added to the logarithm of StartFraction Salt concentration over Acid concentration EndFraction.\n\nFig. 8.4\n\nTable 8.1\n\nImpact of Gastric Juice pH\n\n| Gastric pH | Effect |\n| --- | --- |\n| <2 | Normal, precipitated bile salts |\n| 3\u20135 | Stimulation of phenotypic mucosal differentiation toward intestinalization |\n| \\>4 | Heartburn and regurgitation symptoms diminish |\n| \\>4.5 | Bacteria normally present in the mouth begin to grow in the stomach |\n| \\>5 | Bile acids deconjugate to release more noxious free bile acid <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> |\n| 3\u20136 | Bile acids become soluble, and a portion dissociates into their ionized salt and free H <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">+ </sup> while the remainder persists as a lipophilic, nonionized acid |\n| \\>7 | More than 90% of bile acid becomes soluble and completely ionized |\n\n### Quality Control on Antireflux Surgery\n\nTreating GERD medically is relatively straightforward. There is little consequence to starting a patient on acid-suppressive medications for GERD symptoms and it works most of the time. However, all surgeries have the potential for serious complications. Even as serious perioperative complications are exceedingly rare with antireflux surgery, there is essentially no risk of bleeding, infection, or death from PPIs. Couple that with a relatively high rate of functional side effects such as dysphagia, bloating, and flatulence, it is no wonder hesitancy toward surgery exists. In contrast to empiric medical therapy, GERD surgery is complex on both the diagnostic and technical side. When done poorly, the outcomes can be severely debilitating including daily troublesome new symptoms, but at worst, poor surgery can lead to major life-changing surgical resection. To achieve the published results, antireflux surgery requires an expert in GERD management. A good surgeon not only is an expert technician, but also recognizes which patients are likely to have a good surgical outcome and those who are better off with conservative management. Unfortunately, there are no current quality metrics or standard qualifications required to perform antireflux surgery aside from general surgery board certification and hospital privileges. This has led to some disastrous results leaving patients with permanent, debilitating digestive dysfunction. Poor surgical outcomes can certainly occur in expert hands as well. However, a review of >75,000 antireflux surgeries in the United States demonstrated that morbidity, length of hospital stay, and overall cost is lower at high-volume centers defined as more than 25 operations annually. However, investigations of long-term functional outcomes as a measure of quality are lacking. Major surgical societies recognize this issue and have focused efforts to improve training, certification requirements, and develop improved quality metrics going forward.\n\n### Innovative Surgical Alternatives\n\nWhen done meticulously, antireflux surgery is extraordinarily successful for uncomplicated GERD, leading to high rates of patient satisfaction. The current paradigm, which recommends antireflux surgery only for individuals with the most advanced disease, leads to poorer outcomes due to the underlying baseline esophagogastric function. However, to have a favorable risk-to-benefit ratio for surgery on patients with less complicated disease, new techniques need to be developed that address the reflux barrier before substantial anatomic or functional derangements have developed. Ideally, such measures would prevent further disease progression while preserving function and associated quality-of-life metrics.\n\nOver more than a decade, minimally invasive outpatient barrier augmentation procedures have been developed. Examples include the implantation of a collar of magnetic beads around the inferior border of the LES to prevent its effacement into the stomach, neuromodulation of the LES through electrical stimulation to increase LES resting pressure, and incisionless partial fundoplication performed using a flexible endoscope introduced into the stomach through the mouth. Clinical studies have shown the efficacy of LES augmentation and transoral fundoplication in eliminating reflux symptoms and healing esophagitis in patients with GERD suffering from an incomplete response to PPI therapy. These procedures appear to minimize the side effects associated with traditional fundoplication and are appropriate for early surgical treatment of patients with progressive disease. Treatment algorithms are being proposed for use of these traditional fundoplication alternatives to treat symptoms and prevent GERD progression that emphasize the use of early endoscopy with biopsy of the squamocolumnar junction, manometry of the LES, and esophageal pH monitoring to assess patients with the likelihood of progression. Further details of these therapies are discussed elsewhere in the textbook.\n\n### Multidisciplinary Collaboration\n\nAs our understanding of the pathogenesis of GERD symptomatology grows, it becomes clear that the GERD spectrum consists of a wide variety of underlying etiologies and therefore treatment options. Triadafilopoulos and colleagues have termed this emerging concept as mixed esophageal disease (MED) recognizing the complexity of both diagnosis and treatment. As newer technologies emerge aimed at decreasing side effects of a traditional fundoplication, a multimodality approach is likely to emerge with a role for concurrent medical and mechanical therapies. Improving our management of patients with GERD requires early use of endoscopy and pH testing in patients with a partial or a deteriorating response to PPI therapy or with a rigid dependency on PPI therapy. Importantly, the risk of progressive disease with otherwise successful medical therapy must be recognized. It is incumbent on both gastroenterologists and surgeons dedicated to understanding and treating GERD to work together to close the therapeutic gap.\n\n### Improved Patient and Clinician Education\n\nAntireflux surgery is extremely successful at both stopping reflux and improving quality of life. Reported satisfaction with antireflux surgery remains >90% in multiple publications. A majority of patients do not experience detrimental long-term side effects. When compared with long-term PPI, patients who had a fundoplication experienced a 6% higher rate of dysphagia, 12% higher rate of bloating, and 17% higher rate of flatulence. However, when 500 patients were asked if they regretted the surgery or felt the side effects were troublesome, >90% said no. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nUnfortunately, the frequency and severity of side effects from surgery have been largely exaggerated for a few reasons. First, indiscriminate performance of antireflux procedures by nonexperts, particularly in the early laparoscopic era, resulted in less-than-optimal results. Historically, these patients were often managed long-term by gastroenterologists or primary care providers. More recently, loud voices of dissatisfied patients have been amplified on social media. These factors have created an understandable negative bias against antireflux surgery that is hard to overcome. Consequently, even expert surgeons have become more selective and unrealistically hope for a zero side-effect rate. This dynamic has created a situation where patients generally must be quite miserable with their disease, having tried every conceivable conservative measure before being offered a surgical option. Once they have been sufficiently exhausted by their efforts to control the disease including taking medication multiple times per day, trying to manage disrupted sleep by sleeping upright, eliminating their favorite foods, or eliminating lifestyle activities that bring them joy. When they reach that point, surgeons know they will achieve a high benefit from having surgery, even if it comes with a few minor side effects.\n\nA concerted effort needs to focus on improving GERD management from diagnosis to treatment, including surgery, system wide to improve quality of care and reestablish community trust. The true risks of side effects need to be widely available to patients and providers. Surgeons performing antireflux surgery need to have specific training and experience to ensure the best outcomes. Outcome measures should be collected and available for full disclosure so that patients can make informed decisions regarding the potential escalation of care.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe therapeutic gap seen in GERD represents a complex group of patients who are unsatisfied with PPI therapy alone for their symptoms. The gap likely represents a mix of patients that are incompletely evaluated for disease severity and could be offered surgery, those who are misdiagnosed, and those who have subthreshold and/or functional heartburn. Greater understanding of the various GERD phenotypes as well as new therapies, both medical and surgical, are required to improve care and close the gap.\n\n## References\n\n1.: DeMeester T.R., Stein H.J.: Surgical treatment of gastroesophageal reflux disease . In Castell D.O. (eds): The Esophagus . 1992. Little, Brown , Boston pp. 579-626.\n\nView In Article\n\n2.: Tutuian R., Castell D.O.: Management of gastroesophageal reflux disease . Am J Med Sci 2003; 326 (5): pp. 309-318.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: Becher A., El-Serag H.: Systematic review: the association between symptomatic response to proton pump inhibitors and health-related quality of life in patients with gastro-oesophageal reflux disease . Aliment Pharmacol Ther 2011; 34 (6): pp. 618-627.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Delshad S.D., Almario C.V., Chey W.D., Spiegel B.M.R.: Prevalence of gastroesophageal reflux disease and proton pump inhibitor-refractory symptoms . Gastroenterology 2020; 158 (5): pp. 1250-1261.e2.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n5.: El-Serag H., Becher A., Jones R.: Systematic review: persistent reflux symptoms on proton pump inhibitor therapy in primary care and community studies . Aliment Pharmacol Ther 2010; 32 (6): pp. 720-737.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n6.: Kahrilas P.J., Boeckxstaens G., Smout A.J.: Management of the patient with incomplete respon