indow)\n  - Accessibility (opens in a new window)\n\nWe use cookies to help provide and enhance our service and tailor content. By continuing you agree to the .\n\nAll content on this site: Copyright \u00a9 2025 Elsevier Inc. or its licensors and contributors. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies. For all open access content, the relevant licensing terms apply.\n\n RELX''%20d=''M20.7%2023.4c11%200%2024.2-2.6%2024.2-13.1C44.9%202.8%2037.2%200%2030.3%200%2019.6%200%200%206%200%2027c0%2010.5%208%2016.6%2020.8%2016.6%2013.5%200%2023.2-8.8%2026.2-20.5C39.1%2036.7%2029%2041%2021%2041%2010.7%2041%206.8%2033.4%206.8%2027%205.869%2013.417%2016.685%201.91%2030.3%202c6.1%200%209.7%204%209.7%208.3%200%2011.9-17.2%2011.5-25%2011.5h-3.8l-1.6%201.8c3.6.5%208.5%201.5%2014%204.2%2011.1%205.6%2021.7%2020.6%2035.6%2020.6%205%200%206.4-1.6%207.4-3-6.9%204.4-18.3-3.1-24.5-9-5-4.8-9.6-10.2-21.4-13.1''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23e9711c''/%3e%3cpath%20clip-path=''url(%23b)''%20d=''M89.3%2043.6c-.5%200-.7-.2-.8-.6l-7-14.5h-6.1c-.2%200-.3.1-.3.3V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.6.6h-5.1c-.4%200-.6-.3-.6-.6V7c0-.4.2-.6.6-.6h13.9c6.6%200%2011.5%204.6%2011.5%2011.1%200%205-2.7%208.7-6.9%2010.3L95.5%2043c.2.3%200%20.7-.4.7h-5.8zm-.7-26.2c0-3.2-2.2-5.3-5.5-5.3h-7.7c-.2%200-.3.1-.3.4v9.9c0%20.2%200%20.3.3.3H83c3.3%200%205.5-2%205.5-5.3M101%206.9c0-.4.3-.6.6-.6h21.8c.4%200%20.6.2.6.6v4.7c0%20.3-.2.5-.6.5h-15.8c-.2%200-.3.1-.3.4v9c0%20.3.1.4.3.4h12.7c.4%200%20.6.2.6.5v4.7c0%20.4-.2.6-.6.6h-12.7c-.2%200-.3%200-.3.3v9.4c0%20.3.1.4.3.4h15.8c.4%200%20.6.2.6.5V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.6.6h-21.8c-.3%200-.6-.3-.6-.6V7zm28.8%200c0-.4.2-.6.5-.6h5.2c.3%200%20.6.2.6.6v30.5c0%20.3%200%20.4.3.4H151c.3%200%20.5.2.5.5V43c0%20.3-.2.6-.5.6h-20.8c-.3%200-.517-.3-.5-.6V7zm47.7%2036.7c-.4%200-.6-.2-.8-.5l-7.3-12.7-7.4%2012.7c-.2.3-.4.5-.8.5h-5.8c-.3%200-.5-.3-.3-.7L166%2024.3%20156%207.1c-.2-.4%200-.7.3-.7h5.8c.4%200%20.6.1.8.5l6.5%2011.3h.1L176%206.9c.2-.4.5-.5.9-.5h5.7c.4%200%20.5.3.3.7l-10%2017.2L183.7%2043c.2.4%200%20.7-.3.7h-5.8zM192.015%2019c-.2%200-.338-.004-.3-.2V8.4h-3.3s-.356-.175-.2-.3V6.5l.2-.1h8.8l.2.1v1.6c0%20.2-.1.2-.2.2h-3.2l-.1.1v10.4l-.2.2h-1.8zm7.5-12.5l.2-.1h1.6l.3.1%203.4%207.8%203.4-7.8.3-.1h1.6l.1.1v12.3l-.1.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.25-.006-.2-.2v-7.7l-2.7%206c0%20.1-.1.2-.3.2h-1c-.2%200-.3%200-.4-.3l-2.6-6v7.8l-.2.2h-1.6c-.1%200-.2%200-.2-.2z''%20transform=''translate(0%20-.008)''%20fill=''%23666''/%3e%3c/svg%3e) (opens in a new window)\n\n\n\nNeed help? Chat with AI Buddy!\n\n---\n\n> [!navigation] Section Links\n> [[Esophagus/README|Back to Esophagus Capsule]] \u00b7 [[Home|Vault Home]]\n\n**Previous:** [[7. Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux - ClinicalKey|7. Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux]]\n**Next:** [[9. Fundoplication for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease - ClinicalKey|9. Fundoplication for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease]]", "version": "1.0", "source_file": "8. Acid-Suppression Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and the Therapeutic Gap - ClinicalKey.md"}'::jsonb, 'Book Chapter', 'surgery', 'esophagus', 'Esophagus', 'Acid-Suppression Therapy for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease and the Therapeutic Gap', ARRAY['Shackelford 9th Ed', 'GERD Management', 'Therapeutic Gap', 'Proton Pump Inhibitors', 'Antireflux Surgery', 'Patient Education', 'GERD Management / Therapeutic Gap', 'GERD Management / Proton Pump Inhibitors', 'GERD Management / Antireflux Surgery', 'GERD Management / Patient Education'], 'textbook', 'Shackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract', '9th', '8', '103-110', 2, 37, FALSE, TRUE),
('Fundoplication for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease', 'shackelford-9th-ed-9-fundoplication-for-gastroesophageal-reflux-disease', 'chapter', '{"markdown": "Book Chapter\n\n# Fundoplication for Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease\n\nJustin L. Hsu; Maggie M. Hodges\n\nShackelford''s Surgery of the Alimentary Tract, 9, 111-128\n\n## Background\n\nGastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) persists as the most common disorder of the esophagus and gastroesophageal junction, developing from deterioration of the intrinsic antireflux barrier of the lower esophagus. The lower esophageal antireflux barrier is composed of the crural diaphragm, the lower esophageal sphincter and its sling fibers, and the gastroesophageal flap valve, and failure of the components of the antireflux barrier results in pathologic esophageal reflux of gastric contents. The lower esophageal antireflux barrier is not impenetrable; transient reflux events occur physiologically. However, the criteria for defining GERD set forth by the Montreal classification is \u201cwhen the reflux of stomach contents causes troublesome symptoms and/or complications,\u201d with troublesome defined as either mild symptoms occurring 2 or more days per week, or moderate/severe symptoms occurring more than 1 day per week. While difficult to quantify, the prevalence of GERD has been observed to be increasing, and the proportion of the population experiencing GERD symptoms weekly or more has been estimated to be between 2.5% and 7.9% in Asia, up to 30% in Western countries, and up to 30.9% in the United States. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nLongstanding GERD increases the risk of erosive esophagitis, esophageal stricture, Barrett\u2019s esophagus, and progression to esophageal cancer, while also placing patients at an increased risk of hospital admission related to GERD symptoms and sequelae of persistent disease, as well as impaired health-related quality of life and lost work productivity. While lifestyle modifications such as smoking cessation, weight loss, avoidance of dietary triggers, and sleeping with the head of the bed elevated may provide relief for some patients, it is estimated that 86% of US adults evaluated by their primary care physician for GERD are already on either a proton pump inhibitor (PPI) or histamine H <sub>2 </sub> receptor antagonist (H <sub>2 </sub> RA). Gastric acid production in patients with GERD is most often normal; however, medical therapy for the treatment of GERD has centered on acid suppression using PPIs and H <sub>2 </sub> RAs to neutralize the erosive and inflammatory gastric refluxate in order to reduce symptoms and esophageal inflammation, with additional therapies including alginates, surface acting compounds, and the newer potassium competitive acid blockers. However, medical therapy must be continued indefinitely, and an increasing body of research has called into question the safety of long-term PPI use. Furthermore, these medical therapies do not address nonacid reflux and bile reflux, which have been associated with the development of esophageal squamous cell carcinoma and esophageal adenocarcinoma. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nIn contrast, antireflux surgery provides durable, symptomatic relief of GERD by re-establishing the competency of the antireflux barrier. The complete (Nissen) fundoplication has undergone several modifications since it was first performed to protect a gastroesophageal anastomosis in 1937, and while the complete posterior or Nissen fundoplication remains the current gold standard operative treatment for GERD, partial (Toupet and Dor) fundoplications have gained in popularity due to what is perceived as a more favorable side-effect profile, with reduced rates of dysphagia and gas bloat after partial fundoplication compared to complete fundoplication. Fundoplications aim to recreate the antireflux barrier by restoring the esophageal approximation of the crural diaphragm and recreating a gastroesophageal flap valve around 2 to 3 cm of intraabdominal esophagus. This chapter discusses the indications for antireflux surgery, the recommended preoperative evaluation and postoperative management, and the technical aspects of both laparoscopic and open complete (Nissen) and partial (Toupet and Dor) fundoplication for the treatment of GERD.\n\n## Preoperative Evaluation\n\nOther conditions, both esophageal and extraesophageal, can masquerade as GERD; therefore, proper patient selection prior to fundoplication is essential for a successful outcome for both the patient and the surgeon. A thorough history and physical examination, as well as appropriate testing (see Chapter 2 , Chapter 3 , Chapter 4 , Chapter 5 , Chapter 6 ), should be completed to establish a diagnosis of GERD and eliminate other potential causes of symptoms. Patients should be queried regarding classic GERD symptoms, including heartburn, regurgitation, and dysphagia. Detailing the frequency, timing, and description of reflux (bitter or bland), associated reflux-related symptoms, the relationship to meals, symptom exacerbation in the supine or upright position, and difficulty swallowing (noting whether dysphagia is worse with solids or liquids) is key. The response to and the duration of medical therapy are also recorded, as this information has prognostic significance following fundoplication.\n\nPatients may present with atypical symptoms such as chronic cough, globus sensation, asthma, pulmonary disease, odynophagia, hoarseness, and postnasal drip. These patients should undergo thorough evaluation, including a chest radiograph, electrocardiogram, and, if indicated, cardiac stress testing, pulmonary function tests, and otolaryngology evaluation, in addition to the standard diagnostic evaluation for gastroesophageal reflux. Patients with atypical symptoms and those who fail to respond to medical therapy may show less improvement in symptoms after fundoplication than those with typical GERD symptoms. Box 9.1 includes a list of classic typical and atypical GERD symptoms.\n\nBox 9.1\n\nTypical and Atypical GERD Symptoms\n\n  - **Typical Symptoms**\n  - Heartburn\n  - Regurgitation (sour or bitter)\n  - Dysphagia\n  - **Atypical Symptoms**\n  - Noncardiac chest pain, palpitations\n  - Cough, wheezing, dyspnea\n  - Nasal congestion\n  - Throat pain or burning\n  - Hoarseness\n  - Globus sensation\n  - Dental erosions\n\nAll patients undergoing preoperative evaluation to determine their candidacy for antireflux surgery should undergo an esophagogastroduodenoscopy to evaluate for evidence of reflux-related pathology, and to define the anatomy of the esophagus and hiatus to guide surgical decision making. High-resolution manometry (HRM) is considered the gold standard esophageal motility study for ruling out aperistalsis and for identifying patients who may benefit from a tailored approach in order to minimize the risk of dysphagia following fundoplication. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> A tailored approach to fundoplication advocates balancing the patient\u2019s presenting symptoms, the severity and sequelae of the patient\u2019s GERD, and the patient\u2019s esophageal motility in the decision regarding the type of fundoplication to pursue. HRM also provides documentation of baseline esophageal motility to help guide decision making in the event a patient develops postoperative dysphagia.\n\nEsophageal pH testing (by either catheter or wireless pH probe) is considered the gold standard for the diagnosis of GERD and is essential in the preoperative evaluation of patients with nonerosive reflux disease, extraesophageal, or atypical symptoms, and those who do not respond to PPI therapy. Patients with typical reflux symptoms and evidence of Los Angeles grade C or D esophagitis, Barrett\u2019s esophagus >2 cm in length, or peptic stricture do not routinely need a pH study to prove the diagnosis of GERD prior to consideration of antireflux surgery. While it is estimated that over 54% of patients with GERD are refractory to PPI therapy, only 32% of patients referred for evaluation of PPI-refractory GERD were found to have true, reflux-related, PPI-refractory GERD, with the remaining cohort either improving on an optimized PPI regimen (17.3%), having functional heartburn (40.9%), or having non-GERD\u2013related esophageal disorders (9.5%). <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In this context, it is unsurprising that in a multivariate analysis of factors predicting a good response to antireflux surgery, the best outcomes (98% good to excellent results) occurred in patients who had symptom relief with PPIs, typical GERD symptoms, and a positive 24-hour pH study. In patients unable to tolerate the traditional transnasal 24-hour pH probe, or in whom the initial 24-hour pH test was negative with ongoing high clinical suspicion of GERD, a wireless pH probe can be used to assess distal esophageal acid exposure over 48 to 96 hours, detecting GERD with increased sensitivity.\n\nMultichannel intraluminal impedance (MII) testing may also provide useful information in the evaluation of GERD. MII can detect intraesophageal bolus movement of liquid or gas, regardless of pH, by measuring the electrical resistance (impedance) of the esophageal contents. By determining the temporal sequence of impedance events, one can establish the directional flow of gas and liquid within the esophagus (i.e., distal flow: swallow; proximal flow: reflux event or belch). Combined analysis of this data with data from a standard pH probe allows correlation of both acid and nonacid refluxate with patient symptomatology. While up to 48 reflux events within 24 hours is considered physiologic, MII may facilitate identification of patients whose symptoms are due to a pathologic degree of nonacid reflux; however, the role of this technology in determining which patients will best respond to either medical management or antireflux surgery is yet to be defined. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n## Indications for Surgery\n\nDespite widespread advancement in the medical and endoscopic management of GERD, fundoplication remains the \u201cgold standard\u201d surgical therapy for GERD. Yet, while fundoplication sets the benchmark for the surgical management of GERD, not all patients with GERD warrant surgical intervention. In patients with uncomplicated GERD satisfied with the symptom control afforded by medical therapy, patients can be advised to continue their medical therapy and pursuit of lifestyle modifications (including weight loss, when applicable). However, it is estimated that up to 54.1% of patients with GERD are resistant to antisecretory therapy. Patients with lifestyle limiting GERD unresponsive to medical therapy and lifestyle modifications, those who prefer to avoid lifelong acid-suppression therapy, and those with evidence of complicated GERD (Barrett\u2019s esophagus, refractory esophagitis, stricture) should be considered as candidates for antireflux surgery. While these patients should be considered as surgical candidates, even evidence of complicated GERD does not mandate surgical intervention. If surveillance of Barrett\u2019s esophagus demonstrates stable or improved disease, subsequent endoscopy demonstrates healing of the esophagitis, or 24-hour pH probe demonstrates normal esophageal acid exposure on medications, the patient and surgeon should participate in a shared decision-making process weighing the constellation of symptoms, disease severity, and individual surgical risks to decide whether surgery is the appropriate path forward. However, it should be noted that elimination of excessive reflux is difficult to achieve in patients with complicated GERD, as Barrett\u2019s esophagus, esophagitis, and strictures are markers of disease severity, and diligent consideration should be given to antireflux surgery for these patients.\n\nIn patients presenting with an esophageal stricture, it is recommended to pursue preoperative endoscopic dilation of the stricture to a goal of at least 16 mm (48 Fr) to minimize the compounded effect of postoperative edema and early postoperative dysmotility on anticipated postoperative dysphagia. Furthermore, patients with peptic esophageal stricture meet diagnostic criteria for severe GERD and warrant consideration of Nissen fundoplication should their esophageal motility be adequate, with recommended use of an approximately 56-Fr bougie to calibrate the Nissen fundoplication. Further esophageal dilation can be performed at the time of fundoplication, with up to 10-mm increase from the last preoperative dilation having been shown to be well tolerated in prior studies. Severe esophageal strictures that do not improve with endoscopic dilation may require esophageal resection.\n\nPrior to fundoplication, patients with Barrett\u2019s esophagus should be current on their endoscopic screening for evaluation of the presence of dysplasia or progression to esophageal adenocarcinoma. Barrett\u2019s esophagus with low-grade dysplasia should be treated with high-dose PPI therapy for 3 months, and thereafter undergo repeat biopsy to evaluate for progression of dysplasia. If low-grade dysplasia persists, the patient may undergo close endoscopic surveillance or eradication therapy (a combination of radiofrequency ablation, endoscopic submucosal dissection, and endoscopic mucosal resection) to reduce the risk of progression. Patients with high-grade dysplasia or esophageal adenocarcinoma should undergo esophageal eradication therapy or esophageal resection, where appropriate. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> However, patients successfully treated for dysplastic Barrett\u2019s esophagus may be considered for fundoplication, as studies suggest patients who are able to achieve complete remission of their dysplasia or metaplasia by endoscopic eradication therapy show reduced recurrence of disease after Nissen fundoplication compared to patients maintained on PPI therapy. Furthermore, patients with persistent Barrett\u2019s esophagus have an increased likelihood of entirely clearing their Barrett\u2019s esophagus after fundoplication. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nGERD has been associated with chronic lung injury and progressive impairment in lung function in patients with interstitial pulmonary fibrosis. The potential role fundoplication may play in slowing the decline of lung function for these patients remains an area of ongoing research. However, uncontrolled GERD and resulting microaspirations (both acid and nonacid) are known to be risk factors for the development of chronic lung allograft dysfunction and associated with the development of bronchiolitis obliterans following lung transplant, and laparoscopic antireflux surgery either before or after transplant should be considered for this patient population. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nDespite the success of fundoplication in the management of GERD, fundoplication may not be the most appropriate antireflux surgery for all patient populations. Morbidly obese patients (body mass index >35 kg/m <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">2 </sup> ), especially those with multiple medical comorbidities, may benefit from Roux-en-Y gastric bypass as an antireflux surgery, as these patients are at a higher risk of developing a disrupted fundoplication or recurrent hiatal hernia than nonobese controls, with an increased risk of recurrent reflux after fundoplication. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Emerging evidence now suggests that Roux-en-Y gastric bypass may be appropriate in patients with lower BMI as well. Additionally, patients with history of prior foregut surgery should be evaluated thoroughly and approached cautiously. Typically, previous Roux-en-Y gastric bypass, sleeve gastrectomy, or vertical banded gastroplasty are contraindications to attempting fundoplication, as the fundus has been disrupted by these prior surgeries.\n\nOnce a patient has been identified as an appropriate candidate for antireflux surgery, consideration should then be given as to whether they are best served by a partial fundoplication or a complete fundoplication. Traditional teaching and long-term data continue to support the complete posterior fundoplication as a durable treatment for GERD, with patient satisfaction approaching and exceeding 90% at long-term follow-up in multiple studies. However, long-term studies also suggest that the complete posterior fundoplication may convey a higher risk of dysphagia and gas bloat than partial fundoplication. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> In particular, patients with baseline esophageal dysmotility, preoperative dysphagia, and gas bloat may be at a greater risk of persistent dysphagia and gas bloat following Nissen fundoplication. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Patients with severe GERD (Barrett\u2019s esophagus >2 cm in length, esophageal stricture, Los Angeles grade C or D esophagitis, or a DeMeester score >50 on 24-hour pH testing) may benefit from complete posterior fundoplication due to an increased risk of failure with partial fundoplication. Conversely, partial fundoplication could be considered for patients with significant preoperative dysphagia and bloating, ineffective esophageal motility on preoperative HRM, or history of dysphagia after prior Nissen fundoplication.\n\nBalancing the severity of a patient\u2019s GERD, their baseline esophageal motility, their presenting symptoms, their personal surgical history, and surgeon experience allows selection of a fundoplication to optimize the surgical outcome for the patient and the surgeon, as the body of literature evaluating the evolution of complete and partial fundoplication and their optimal applications continues to evolve. This chapter will describe the steps common to both complete (Nissen) and partial (Toupet and Dor) fundoplication while also detailing the nuances of the anterior-posterior versus greater curve\u2013to\u2013greater curve approach to a complete posterior fundoplication, as well as the technique of the partial posterior (Toupet) and partial anterior (Dor) fundoplication.\n\n## Common Principles\n\nDiligent adherence to basic surgical principles underscores the key principles of performing a laparoscopic fundoplication. Combining these basic surgical principles with a clear understanding of the functional goals of the hiatal reconstruction and the chosen fundoplication will optimize outcomes for the patient and the surgeon. The basic surgical principles and key steps to performing a fundoplication (laparoscopic and open) are described in Box 9.2 . When comparing open and laparoscopic fundoplication, multiple randomized studies support equivalent symptomatic control of GERD and functional outcomes while also noting significantly decreased length of stay, decreased risk of wound-related complications, decreased risk of in-hospital morbidity, and decreased time to return to work observed in patients undergoing laparoscopic fundoplication compared to open fundoplication. Despite remaining the gold standard for the surgical management of GERD, a laparoscopic fundoplication may not be feasible for all patients due to either the patient\u2019s prior surgical history or the surgeon\u2019s experience with advanced laparoscopy. As such, it is important to understand the guiding principles common to both laparoscopic and open approaches, as well as the distinct nuances of each approach.\n\nBox 9.2\n\nPrinciples of Fundoplication\n\n  - **Patient Positioning**\n  - \u2022\n\t\tPadding of bony prominences and prevention of pressure injuries\n  - \u2022\n\t\tNeutral positioning of shoulders, hips, and back to prevent musculoskeletal discomfort and peripheral nerve injuries\n  - \u2022\n\t\tAppropriate bed height and monitor placement to optimize surgeon ergonomics\n  - **Safe Entry into the Abdomen**\n  - **Exposure**\n  - \u2022\n\t\tReverse Trendelenburg positioning\n  - \u2022\n\t\tSelf-retaining retractor to elevate the left lobe of the liver and visualize the hiatus\n  - **Circumferential Division of the Phrenoesophageal Ligament**\n  - \u2022\n\t\tAvoid esophageal injury\n  - \u2022\n\t\tLimit direct manipulation of the esophagus\n  - **Circumferential Mediastinal Mobilization of the Esophagus**\n  - \u2022\n\t\tIdentify and preserve the vagus nerves\n  - \u2022\n\t\tMobilization of the esophagus to attain 3 cm of intraabdominal esophagus without caudal traction\n  - \u2022\n\t\tEsophageal lengthening procedure if unable to attain adequate intraabdominal esophageal length\n  - \u2022\n\t\tConsider use of intraoperative endoscopy to confirm location of the gastroesophageal junction\n  - **Complete Mobilization of the Gastric Fundus**\n  - \u2022\n\t\tDivision of the short gastric vessels\n  - \u2022\n\t\tDivision of posterior attachments to the pancreas\n  - \u2022\n\t\tPreservation of the gastroepiploic arcade when possible\n  - **Closure of Hiatal Defect**\n  - \u2022\n\t\tReapproximate the diaphragmatic crura using permanent suture\n  - \u2022\n\t\tReinforce the diaphragmatic crura with mesh, when indicated\n  - \u2022\n\t\tUse of adjuncts (i.e., pleurotomy, diaphragm relaxing incision) when indicated\n  - **Creation of a Fundoplication**\n  - \u2022\n\t\t2 to 3 cm in length\n  - \u2022\n\t\tTension free\n  - \u2022\n\t\tAround the distal esophagus only\n  - \u2022\n\t\tSecured to the esophagus\n\n### Laparoscopic Fundoplication\n\n#### Positioning and Port Placement\n\nPrior to induction of general anesthesia, patients should have pneumatic sequential compression devices applied and they should also receive appropriate antibiotic prophylaxis prior to incision. Although not routine, a Foley catheter may be placed at the discretion of the surgeon or if indicated by patient history. The patient can be placed either supine or split leg, on an antislip foam pad or vacuum beanbag mattress to prevent patient migration during intraoperative repositioning. A footboard can also be helpful. There are several described configurations of surgical team and port positioning ( Fig. 9.1 ). In this chapter, we will describe the configuration depicted in Fig. 9.1A ; however, we encourage each surgeon to use the configuration that they find affords the best exposure with the most ideal operative ergonomics given the available assistance in the operating room.\n\nA surgical setup layout of an operating room. The surgical setup layout consists of three diagrams labeled A, B, and C, that depict the positions of surgical instruments and surgical team members around the patient. The surgeon is positioned close to the lower torso of the patient in diagram A facing the monitor behind the patient''s head position. The camera focuses on the abdomen region. The surgical left hand and right hand ports are next to the liver and below the chest. The assistants and scrubs stand on the patient''s left and right sides providing engaged or observational assistance. The assistant monitor is placed on the upper right of the upper torso. The surgeon stands on the patient''s right in diagram B facing the monitor on the upper left above the patient''s upper torso. The camera focuses on the abdomen region. The liver, surgical left hand, and right hand ports remain the same. The assistants and scrubs stand on the patient''s left and close to the lower torso assisting the surgeon. The assistant monitor lies above the patient''s head position. The surgeon stands on the patient''s left in diagram C facing the monitor on the upper right of the upper torso. The camera focuses on the abdomen region. The surgical left hand and right hand ports operate below the liver position. The assistant and scrub stand on the patient''s right with the scrub closer to the lower torso of the patient and the assist location is below the left chest. The assistant monitor lies on the upper left above the upper torso.\n\nFig. 9.1\n\nThe surgeon stands between the patient\u2019s legs, with the surgeon\u2019s monitor positioned over the patient\u2019s head, at a height that allows clear viewing without straining the surgeon\u2019s neck to view. The first assistant stands to the patient\u2019s left, with the scrub technician standing to the patient\u2019s right. Entry to the abdomen can be achieved using the surgeon\u2019s technique of choice. These authors prefer Veress needle insertion at either Palmer\u2019s point or via the left paramedian incision where the camera port is planned. In patients with prior abdominal surgical history, an open cut-down approach is a safe alternative.\n\nFive ports are placed to facilitate laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication (one or two 10- to 12-mm ports, and three or four 5-mm ports, Fig. 9.1 ), with additional ports placed if needed. The camera port is placed approximately 10 to 12 cm below the xiphoid and 2 to 3 cm to the left of the umbilicus; a 12-mm port is depicted in Fig. 9.1 to facilitate a 10-mm laparoscope, although a 5-mm laparoscope may also be used. Either a 30-degree or a 45-degree laparoscope is used to optimize visualization of the hiatus. The patient is positioned in steep reverse Trendelenburg, and the second port is placed along the left costal margin, approximately 10 cm from the xiphoid process, for the surgeon\u2019s right hand (SR in Fig. 9.1A ). The 12-mm port allows easy passage of an SH or V20 size needle for intracorporeal suturing. The third port is the assistant\u2019s right-hand port (5 mm), which is placed midway between the camera port and surgeon\u2019s right-hand port, along the anterior axillary line at least 5 cm caudal to the surgeon\u2019s right hand. The fourth port placed is a 5-mm port along the right costal margin approximately 15 cm from the xiphoid, thereby allowing introduction of the articulating liver retractor to elevate the left lateral lobe of the liver anteriorly and superiorly. Alternatively, a Nathanson liver retractor can be introduced inferior to the xiphoid. The liver is retracted adequately when both the right crus and the caudate lobe of the liver are visible through the gastrohepatic ligament. The liver retractor is then stabilized with an instrument holder attached to the operating room table. The final port (5 mm) is placed along the inferior edge of the liver (after the liver is retracted) to the right of the patient\u2019s midline and in line with the 12-mm dissecting port, allowing triangulation of the surgeon\u2019s left hand with the hiatus, without risking injury to the left lobe of the liver or interference from the falciform ligament.\n\n#### Exposure\n\nThe assistant uses an atraumatic grasper to firmly hold the phrenoesophageal or anterior gastric fat pad just inferior to the gastroesophageal junction, retracting the stomach caudally and laterally toward the patient\u2019s left flank. The surgeon uses an atraumatic grasper in their left hand, with an advanced energy device (ultrasonic scalpel or advanced bipolar device) in their right hand. The gastrohepatic ligament should be placed on tension using this maneuver, and the pars flacida should be divided using the advanced energy device ( Fig. 9.2A ). The gastrohepatic ligament may contain both the hepatic branch of the anterior vagus, and an aberrant left hepatic artery in up to 17% of patients. Attempts can be made to preserve these structures, but doing so may limit access to the right crus; furthermore, clinically significant liver ischemia is rare and mostly limited to division of a replaced left hepatic artery. The gastrohepatic ligament is then divided along the lesser curve cephalad, exposing the apex of the right crus.\n\nA set of four surgical photos of progress in a procedure with instruments and tissue. Photo A represents the identification of the ligaments with the surgical instruments. Photo B depicts the dissection of tissue lining close to the deep muscle layer. Photo C shows the deeper dissection, revealing blood vessels. Photo D captures continued dissection, exposing deeper ligaments. The procedures are carried out with precision using specialized surgical instruments.\n\nFig. 9.2\n\n#### Division of the Phrenoesophageal Ligament\n\nThe peritoneum medial to the edge of the right crus is incised, and the esophagus is gently dissected away from the right crus ( Fig. 9.2B ). Using the atraumatic grasper, the right crus is retracted anteriorly and laterally, away from the esophagus, thereby placing the phrenoesophageal ligament on tension. The surgeon\u2019s right hand is used to bluntly sweep the esophagus away from the phrenoesophageal ligament, which is then divided using the energy device. This dissection continues clockwise to the apex of the hiatus. This dissection is facilitated by keeping the phrenoesophageal ligament on tension, which can be accomplished by the assistant changing the direction of retraction on the anterior gastric fat pad to directly oppose the direction of retraction of the crus by the surgeon\u2019s left hand. When the apex of the hiatus has been reached, the dissection is continued down the left crus, being cautious to sweep the esophagus away from the backside of the phrenoesophageal ligament. It is important to be intentional in the effort to identify and preserve the anterior vagus nerve as it courses along the esophagus in this location, as it lies in close association with the left crus ( Fig. 9.2C ). The dissection is continued down the medial border of the left crus until the dissection is limited by the angle of His and the gastric fundus. Attention is then returned to the initial site of dissection at the medial border of the right crus. The medial border of the right crus is again retracted laterally, with commensurate adjustments to retraction of the anterior gastric fat pad to maintain exposure and tension on the remaining phrenoesophageal ligament. The dissection continues posteriorly and caudally until the crural decussation is identified, taking care to identify and protect the posterior vagus nerve by keeping it elevated with the esophagus ( Fig. 9.2D ). Once the crural decussation is identified, the plane between the left crus and fundus is bluntly developed until the prior plane of dissection of the left crus is joined. The esophagus can then be retracted using either an atraumatic grasper placed through this retroesophageal window (with caution to avoid injury to the gastric fundus or spleen), or a 0.25-inch-wide, 4-inch-long Penrose drain passed around the distal esophagus and secured with an Endoloop. The posterior vagus should be included within the Penrose to avoid inadvertent injury during mediastinal dissection. Outward retraction of the esophagus enables identification and protection of the posterior vagus nerve while also facilitating division of the remaining posterior phrenoesophageal ligament, thereby freeing the esophagus from the crus. Circumferential division of the phrenoesophageal ligament is confirmed on inspection, and attention is then turned toward mobilization of the gastric fundus.\n\n#### Complete Mobilization of the Gastric Fundus\n\nThe stomach is oriented anatomically, and the greater curve is examined. The watershed point where the gastroepiploic arcade terminates and the short gastric arteries begin is identified ( Fig. 9.3A ). If feasible, the gastroepiploic arcade should be preserved given the potential that the patient develops esophageal cancer, thereby requiring esophagectomy with creation of a gastric conduit dependent on the gastroepiploic artery. The anterolateral edge of the fundus is grasped at this watershed location and retracted anteriorly and to the patient\u2019s right, while the gastrocolic omentum opposite this point is gently grasped and retracted anteriorly and to the patient\u2019s left. The advanced energy device is used to enter the lesser sac at this location, approximately 5 to 10 mm away from the greater curve of the stomach. The fundus and omentum are manipulated to enable a clear visualization of the course of the greater curve to avoid injury to the greater curve of the stomach ( Fig. 9.3B ). If injury to the stomach is suspected, an imbricating suture should be placed. The short gastric arteries are sequentially divided until the superior pole of the spleen is reached. Poor visualization of the superior pole of the spleen, a bulky omentum, and adhesions between the fundus and either the spleen or the retroperitoneum can make complete fundus mobilization challenging; several strategies to improve the ease of this dissection are detailed in Box 9.3 . The base of the left crus should be visible after complete mobilization of the fundus ( Fig. 9.3D ), and the fundus and proximal stomach should be fully mobile after completing division of the phrenoesophageal ligament, as described in the previous step.\n\nFour laparoscopic surgery photos of gastric anatomy with labeled structures. The laparoscopic surgery photos consist of endoscopic views marked A to D. Photo A depicts forceps manipulating tissue near short gastric arteries and the gastroepiploic arcade, labeled with arrows. Photo B captures tissue being grasped by surgical instruments. The lower Photos, C and D, depict different surgical maneuvers. Photo D depicts an arrow pointing to the left crus. The lighting creates shadows, emphasizing depth within the surgical field.\n\nFig. 9.3\n\nBox 9.3\n\nOptimizing Mobilization of the Fundus\n\n  - 1.\n\tImprove exposure of the superior pole of spleen: The surgeon\u2019s left hand optimizes anterior and medial retraction on the anterosuperior tip of the fundus ( Fig. 9.3C ), while the assistant retracts the posterior wall of the fundus posteriorly and away from the tip of the spleen. The tip of the spleen forms the third point of retraction to facilitate exposure of this area; however, the retraction should be gentle to avoid avulsion of short gastric vessels.\n  - 2.\n\tManaging the difficult omentum: If a mobile or bulky greater omentum obscures the superior pole of the spleen, it should be retracted inferiorly and laterally by either:\n  - a.\n\t\tIncreasing the degree of reverse Trendelenburg.\n  - b.\n\t\tIntroducing an additional port and grasper in the left flank to allow either an additional hand for retraction or for introducing a fan retractor for added assistance.\n  - c.\n\t\tPlacing a broad-based, figure-of-eight \u201creefing\u201d suture in the greater omentum and retracting the omentum through the left lateral port with the two long ends of this suture.\n  - 3.\n\tWhen the fundus and spleen or retroperitoneum are densely adherent: Identify the junction between the fundus and spleen and address it one layer at a time. Begin by incising the visceral peritoneal reflection, then divide any underlying short gastric vessels using the advanced energy device. Finally, divide the retroperitoneal gastrophrenic tissues. Dividing any retrogastric adhesions as well as the pancreaticogastric peritoneal fold and the posterior gastric artery is necessary to fully mobilize the fundus. The base of the left crus should be visible after complete mobilization of the fundus.\n\n#### Circumferential Mediastinal Mobilization of the Esophagus\n\nThe distal esophagus is again retracted caudally and toward the patient\u2019s left, using either the previously placed Penrose or the atraumatic grasper, as previously described. Circumferential mediastinal mobilization of the esophagus is initiated bluntly. Using the atraumatic grasper, the right crus is retracted laterally, and the surgeon\u2019s right hand sweeps the esophagus medially ( Fig. 9.4A ). Caudal traction on the esophagus facilitates identification and preservation of the vagus nerves during mediastinal mobilization. This blunt mediastinal mobilization should be continued clockwise around the esophagus, with care to identify perforating vessels, which should be coagulated and divided using the advanced energy device, and with attention to and avoidance of nearby mediastinal structures. The esophagus should be mobilized from the mediastinum to facilitate 3 cm of intraabdominal esophagus without tension ( Fig. 9.4B ).\n\nA set of four photos of a surgical procedure performed on an internal organ. The series of four photos of an endoscopic montage of groin dissection. Photo A represents the initial dissection with the surgical instrument visible. Photo B depicts a more profound view that depicts muscle structure with the instrument not visible. Photo C depicts a closer angle that depicts the left nodes. Photo D depicts the incision completed that depicts the angle of H i s and left crus.\n\nFig. 9.4\n\nAfter complete mediastinal mobilization is achieved, the location of the gastroesophageal junction should be evaluated to rule out the presence of a foreshortened esophagus. The presence of Barrett\u2019s esophagus, severe esophagitis, stricture, a large hiatal hernia, or previous surgery increase the risk of a foreshortened esophagus, which necessitates additional mobilization or an esophageal lengthening procedure (i.e., a Collis gastroplasty). It is estimated that up to 20% of surgical failures after fundoplication may be due to a failure to recognize and address a foreshortened esophagus at the time of fundoplication. There are several ways to assess the gastroesophageal junction intraoperatively; however, intraoperative endoscopy (with the Penrose loosened and the esophagus off tension) enables accurate assessment of the gastroesophageal junction prior to fundoplication, as well as a final assessment of both the hiatal closure and fundoplication at the completion of surgery.\n\nThe final step to confirm an adequate mediastinal and fundus mobilization is performance of the \u201cshoeshine\u201d maneuver ( Fig. 9.4C ). A grasper in the surgeon\u2019s left hand is passed behind the esophagus and the fundus is grasped either 3 cm from the gastroesophageal junction (if performing a \u201cgreater curve\u2013to\u2013greater curve\u201d complete posterior fundoplication or a partial posterior fundoplication) or 6 cm from the gastroesophageal junction on the mid-posterior wall of the fundus (if performing an \u201canterior-posterior\u201d complete posterior fundoplication). The surgeon\u2019s right hand then grasps either a point about 6 to 7 cm further along the distal greater curve (if performing a \u201cgreater curve\u2013to\u2013greater curve\u201d complete posterior fundoplication or a partial posterior fundoplication) or 6 cm from the gastroesophageal junction on the mid-anterior wall of the fundus (if performing an \u201canterior-posterior\u201d complete posterior fundoplication). The surgeon\u2019s left and right hands are elevated toward the diaphragm and directed in opposite directions to place the fundus on tension. In concert, both hands are moved first to one side and then to the other, back and forth, maintaining the fundus on tension and confirming that there is no redundant tissue posteriorly, nor any residual fundus attachments that will cause tension or twisting of the final wrap. After the successful \u201cshoeshine\u201d maneuver, the fundus is released. The gastroesophageal junction should remain in the abdomen, and the fundus should remain posterior to the esophagus. Retraction of the gastroesophageal junction into the hiatus ( Fig. 9.4D ) suggests either inadequate mediastinal dissection or the presence of a foreshortened esophagus that necessitates an esophageal lengthening procedure (for details on performing an esophageal lengthening procedure, see Chapter 24 ). Retraction of the fundus from behind the esophagus suggests residual posterior fundus attachments that should be divided to prevent traction on the final fundoplication.\n\n#### Closure of the Hiatal Defect\n\nThe crural closure is initiated by retracting the esophagus anteriorly and laterally to expose the hiatus from the right of the esophagus. Nonabsorbable heavy sutures should be used to close the crura. We favor the use of interrupted nonabsorbable 0-Ethibond placed 8 to 10 mm apart and 8 to 10 mm back from the crural edge ( Fig. 9.5A ). The sutures should be slightly staggered within the anterior-posterior plane of the crura to avoid splitting the crura along the same bundle of muscular fibers. The peritoneum overlying the crura should be incorporated into the crural repair; if the peritoneum has been stripped from the crura during the dissection of the phrenoesophageal ligament, consideration can be given to using pledgets or an absorbable mesh to reinforce the crural closure ( Fig. 9.5B ). The crura should be closed to gently approximate (but not impinge upon) the walls of the empty esophagus ( Fig. 9.5C ). If using a bougie to calibrate the fundoplication, the final crural closure suture should be left unsecured until after the fundoplication is complete to avoid dilating the newly approximated hiatal closure.\n\nA set of four surgical photos of nonabsorbable sutures closing the crural incision. The set of four surgical photos is marked A to D. Photo A depicts stitching the incision with surgical instruments. Photo B depicts the wrapping of the aneurysm in a bloody, dark textile graft with markers. Photo C displays dark blood clots with swollen and exposed tissue. Photo D depicts an incision in the diaphragm layer to relax the crural closer.\n\nFig. 9.5\n\nAttention should be paid to the tension required to close the crura, as excessive tension may predispose to recurrence of a hiatal hernia. Tension on the crural closure can be redistributed by use of pledgeted sutures made of felt, Teflon felt, or absorbable or nonabsorbable mesh. Should there be significant tension on the crural closure (as seen in Fig. 9.5D ), the combination of a pleurotomy and diaphragm relaxing incision has been demonstrated to decrease tension on the crural closure by 56.1%; this is discussed more extensively in Chapter 24 .\n\n### Open Fundoplication\n\nOpen fundoplication may be indicated based on the surgeon\u2019s lack of experience with advanced laparoscopy, due to the patient\u2019s history of prior upper abdominal surgeries, or due to complications encountered during laparoscopic fundoplication that are addressed best by an open approach. The steps of an open fundoplication are similar to those of the laparoscopic approach; however, exposure and visualization of the hiatus via an open approach may be more difficult to achieve. Due to the significant similarities between the open and laparoscopic approaches, the sections below focus on notable differences between the two approaches.\n\n#### Positioning and Exposure\n\nThe patient is positioned supine, with arms abducted, and the abdomen is entered via an upper midline incision. If protuberant, the xyphoid is excised to facilitate adequate exposure of the hiatus. If the left lateral lobe of the liver is noted to be enlarged, the coronal ligament is divided to facilitate mobilization. A self-retaining retractor is placed to facilitate retraction of the liver and visualization of the hiatus; this typically requires placement of a retractor to elevate the most posterior aspect of the left lateral lobe of the liver in order to expose the hiatus. When the diaphragm is seen to run vertically from the incision directly posterior to the hiatus, optimal exposure has been achieved and the surgeon can next direct their attention to division of the gastrohepatic ligament. Similar to the laparoscopic exposure of the right crus, the gastrohepatic ligament is incised and divided, extending superiorly to where it abuts the apex of the right crus. When an aberrant left hepatic artery or hepatic branch of the vagus are seen, they are preserved when feasible.\n\n#### Division of the Phrenoesophageal Ligament\n\nThe lesser curve is retracted inferolaterally and the right crus is exposed. Blunt dissection separates the right crus from the esophagus, and the phrenoesophageal ligament can be bluntly separated from the esophagus and divided using electrocautery or an advanced energy device, using a finger to protect the underlying esophagus. This dissection can be continued over the anterior esophagus toward the left crus, being sure to sweep the anterior vagus away from the phrenoesophageal ligament before dividing the ligament near the junction with the left crus.\n\nWith similar inferolateral retraction on the lesser curve, blunt dissection at the base of the right crus is used to develop a retroesophageal tunnel, through which a Penrose drain is placed to facilitate esophageal retraction, being sure to include the posterior vagus nerve. Retraction of the esophagus toward the patient\u2019s right lower quadrant facilitates exposure of the left crus, enabling complete division of any remaining phrenoesophageal ligament.\n\n#### Mediastinal Mobilization\n\nWith gentle retraction on the Penrose, blunt dissection along the esophagus can accomplish the majority of the necessary mediastinal mobilization, being sure to protect the vagus nerves. Perforating vessels should be identified and divided using the advanced energy device, especially posterior and lateral to the esophagus.\n\n#### Mobilization of the Gastric Fundus\n\nThe watershed area between the termination of the gastroepiploic and the beginning of the short gastric arteries is identified. The lesser sac is entered here, with every effort made to preserve the gastroepiploic arcade, and the short gastric arteries are sequentially divided using either clamps and suture ligation or by using the advanced energy device. Any residual loose attachments between the fundus and diaphragm are divided. Retrogastric adhesions are divided, and the pancreaticogastric peritoneal fold and posterior gastric artery are divided using the advanced energy device, enabling complete mobilization of the gastric fundus.\n\n#### Crural Repair\n\nCrural closure is performed as described previously, with the same attention to reducing the tension on the crural closure. If pleurotomy is required to facilitate crural closure during an open fundoplication, consideration should be given to draining the mediastinum and/or the pleura given the risks of resulting pneumothorax.\n\n## Creation of the Fundoplication\n\n### Complete Posterior Fundoplication (Nissen Fundoplication)\n\nThe eponymous Nissen fundoplication was first described by Rudolf Nissen in 1937 after follow-up revealed that buttressing an esophagogastric anastomosis with the wrapped fundus resulted in decreased gastroesophageal reflux and healing of esophagitis. This technique has been further refined and defined over the course of the intervening decades and was translated into the realm of laparoscopy by Dallemagne et al. and Geagea in 1991. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> While any 360-degree or \u201ccomplete\u201d fundoplication is often referred to as a \u201cNissen,\u201d there are a variety of methods used to create a complete fundoplication, with the most common two methods being the \u201canterior-posterior\u201d (AP) wrap ( Fig. 9.6A ) and the \u201cgreater curvature\u201d (GC) wrap ( Fig. 9.6B ).\n\nTwo diagrams of complete Nissen fundoplication techniques feature the anterior posterior and greater curvature. The diagrams with the steps involved in the two types of fundoplication surgery procedures to treat gastroesophageal reflux disease. The first diagram represents the Anterior-Posterior Complete Fundoplication, with the steps involved in wrapping the upper part of the stomach around the lower end of the esophagus. The second diagram depicts the Greater Curvature Complete Fundoplication, illustrating a different method of wrapping the stomach around the esophagus.\n\nFig. 9.6\n\n#### Anterior-Posterior Wrap\n\nThe AP wrap is based on the original description of the Nissen fundoplication, which described an invagination of the distal esophagus into the anterior and posterior walls of the gastric fundus, leaving the greater curve in its normal anatomic position (as shown in Fig. 9.6A ). Please see Video 9.1 . A 2-0 silk marking suture is placed in the posterior fundus midway between the greater curve and lesser curve, 6 cm distal to the angle of His ( Fig. 9.7A ). The stomach is then oriented anatomically, with the esophagus off tension and the Penrose liberally loosened to minimize the risk of esophageal injury during bougie placement, and a 56-Fr or 60-Fr bougie is placed by the anesthesiologist, to allow calibration of the complete fundoplication. After the bougie has been atraumatically placed and oriented along the lesser curve, an atraumatic grasper is passed behind the esophagus to grasp the previously placed marking suture. This suture is used to pull the posterior fundus through the retroesophageal window ( Fig. 9.7B ). A commensurate spot 6 cm distal to the angle of His on the mid-anterior wall of the fundus is grasped, and a shoeshine maneuver is performed to confirm lack of redundancy to the fundus and lack of tethering of the fundus, or twisting of the gastroesophageal junction, as discussed previously ( Fig. 9.7C ). The posterior fundus becomes the right leaflet of the fundoplication, and the anterior fundus becomes the left leaflet of the fundoplication ( Fig. 9.6A ). These leaflets are secured to the esophagus at the 9-10 o\u2019clock position on the esophagus, in line with the lesser curve and preserving the anatomic location of the greater curve and the angle of His ( Fig. 9.7D ).\n\nA group of surgical photos of the methods with anatomical identification and tools in a procedure that involves the posterior fundus. The four photos capture endoscopic surgical views of the anterior posterior wrap procedure. Photo A depicts the posterior fundus, with a marking suture placed 6 cm inferior to the angle of H I s. Photo B shows the marking suture being pulled through the retroesophageal window, initiating the shoeshine maneuver. Photo C shows grasping the marking stitch on the posterior fundus and the corresponding point on the anterior fundus. Photo D shows the leaflets of the anterior posterior wrap coming together in line with the lesser curve, with the first stitch of the AP wrap performed using a Pledget securing the anterior wall of the esophagus to both leaflets of the wrap.\n\nFig. 9.7\n\nThe number and type of sutures used to secure the wrap varies significantly based on surgeon preference; however, it is recommended that a permanent suture be used, most often a woven synthetic 0 or 2-0 suture. Similarly, there is wide variation in the use of pledgets to reinforce the fundoplication sutures, as well as wide variation in the number of sutures used to secure the fundoplication (ranging from two to four). The first suture is a horizontal mattress suture incorporating both leaflets of the fundoplication, and the esophagus, with each pass. The second suture is a simple interrupted suture placed 1 cm above the prior horizontal mattress; incorporation of the esophagus with this stitch is based on surgeon preference. The final suture is a simple interrupted suture 1 cm inferior to the first suture to secure the left and right leaflets of the fundoplication, creating a 1.5- to 2-cm, secure, \u201cfloppy\u201d fundoplication around the distal esophagus ( Fig. 9.7E ).\n\n#### Greater Curvature Wrap\n\nShown in Video 9.2 , the GC wrap is initiated after safe placement of the 56-Fr or 60-Fr bougie along the lesser curve with the stomach oriented anatomically. An atraumatic grasper is then directed posterior to the esophagus to grasp the superior fundus at a location 3 cm from the gastroesophageal junction and pull the proximal fundus posterior to the esophagus ( Fig. 9.8A ). The surgeon\u2019s right hand then grasps a location along the greater curve approximately 8 to 9 cm distal from their left hand. A shoeshine maneuver is then performed to again confirm adequate mobilization of the fundus and to visualize the symmetry of the proposed wrap, as described earlier ( Fig. 9.8B ). It is important to confirm stabilization of the gastroesophageal junction during this maneuver to avoid twisting of the gastroesophageal junction with the final wrap. The leaflets of the fundoplication are then secured to the anterior wall of the esophagus using between two and four permanent sutures, taking seromuscular bites to create a 1.5- to 2-cm-long \u201cfloppy\u201d fundoplication around the distal esophagus ( Fig. 9.8C ). The ideal complete posterior fundoplication should be snug enough to prevent both recurrent reflux and herniation of any redundant fundus through the wrap while also being loose enough to prevent dysphagia, with an endoscopic appearance of 2 cm fundoplication and a Hill grade I valve on retroflexion ( Fig. 9.8D ).\n\nA series of surgical photos that demonstrates an anatomical procedure. The series depicts four steps in a surgical procedure that involves tissue manipulation, stitching, and an endoscopic view of the body. Steps include handling tissue with surgical instruments, securing a surgical knot, and a view inside a bodily opening of wrinkled interior walls.\n\nFig. 9.8\n\n### Partial Posterior Fundoplication (Toupet)\n\nAndr\u00e9 Toupet first described the posterior partial fundoplication in 1963 as a means to minimize the postoperative dysphagia observed after complete posterior fundoplication. Although the method of Toupet fundoplication has changed somewhat since its first introduction, the posterior partial fundoplication continues to be utilized as an alternative to the complete (Nissen) fundoplication. A partial posterior fundoplication may be preferred due to a surgeon\u2019s preference, concern that a patient\u2019s preoperative esophageal motility may place them at a higher risk of postoperative dysphagia after complete fundoplication, and in an effort to minimize the symptoms of gas bloat reported after complete fundoplication. While initially described as a posterior 180-degree fundoplication without hiatal closure, the partial posterior fundoplication is currently considered to be any posterior fundoplication that is less than 360 degrees, with a posterior 270-degree fundoplication being the most commonly utilized variant, and hiatal closure considered to be an integral part of re-establishing the lower esophageal antireflux barrier.\n\nAfter complete mediastinal mobilization and mobilization of the gastric fundus, the partial posterior fundoplication can be completed. Use of a bougie to calibrate this partial posterior fundoplication is a choice of surgeon preference, with anywhere from a 46-Fr to 60-Fr bougie described by several authors. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> The use of sutures to pexy the fundus to either the crural pillars and/or the posterior crural closure is recommended to reinforce the wrap placement since it will not be sutured to itself as in a full Nissen. As shown in Video 9.3 , the first step is performance of the shoeshine maneuver as described earlier, ensuring that the fundus is freely mobile, without redundancy, and the gastroesophageal junction is oriented anatomically, without twisting ( Fig. 9.9A ). If performing a gastropexy, the surgeon\u2019s left hand grasps the fundus 3 cm from the gastroesophageal junction, and the first suture secures this right leaflet of the fundus to the apex of the right crus ( Fig. 9.9B ). The distal greater curve is then elevated and secured at the apex of the left crus ( Fig. 9.9C ). The fundoplication sutures are then performed, securing the right leaflet of the fundus to the anterior esophagus at the 10 o\u2019clock position and the left leaflet of the fundus to the anterior esophagus between the 12 o\u2019clock and 2 o\u2019clock position. This is accomplished using two to three interrupted nonabsorbable sutures on either side, taking seromuscular bites of the underlying esophagus, and being sure to avoid entrapment of the anterior vagus nerve in these fundoplication sutures. A modified partial posterior (Toupet) fundoplication without the use of gastropexy sutures is depicted in Video 9.4 . The final partial posterior fundoplication should be 2 to 3 cm in length, lay within the abdomen without tension, and should appear symmetric and without twisting ( Fig. 9.9D ).\n\nA set of photos of the closing of an incision with sutures. The photos are marked A, B, C, and D. Part A features a clamped organ with surgical tools. Part B depicts additional manipulation with a bolster. Part C reveals an incision. Part D depicts the surgical site closed with dark sutures.\n\nFig. 9.9\n\n### Partial Anterior Fundoplication (Dor)\n\nWhile more commonly used after Heller cardiomyotomy for achalasia, a partial anterior fundoplication (Dor) is another alternative to the complete fundoplication that may be useful in patients with ineffective esophageal motility, or in patients whose gastric anatomy is not conducive to performing an adequate complete or posterior partial fundoplication. After mediastinal mobilization of an adequate length of intraabdominal esophagus (ideally 4\u20135 cm) and crural closure, the appropriate segment of fundus for the anterior fundoplication is chosen. To identify the appropriate segment of fundus, the assistant retracts the gastroesophageal fat pad caudally, while the surgeon rotates the cephalad, anterior fundus over the distal esophagus, adjusting the fundus as needed until the fundus sits naturally and loosely across the anterior hiatus ( Fig. 9.10A ). Unlike the techniques described previously, an anterior partial fundoplication does not require division of the short gastric vessels, unless they are found to be tethering the fundus. The proximal fundus may be secured to the left crus based on surgeon preference ( Fig. 9.10B , shown after cardiomyotomy). Two coronal sutures anchor the fundus to the apex of the hiatus at the 11 o\u2019clock and 1\u20132 o\u2019clock position ( Fig. 9.10B ). Subsequent sutures proceed inferiorly to anchor the fundus to both the right lateral esophagus and right crus (similar to Fig. 9.10C , shown anchoring the fundus to the edge of the myotomy). Traditionally, a suture also attaches the fundus to the 7\u20138 o\u2019clock position of the esophagus and the right crus at the level of the crural closure, creating a 180-degree fundoplication (and being sure to avoid incorporating the posterior vagus in the closure).\n\nA set of four surgical photos of various stages in a medical procedure being performed on internal organs. The photos marked A to D consist of endoscopic views. Photo A reveals a closer of the stomach tissue being incised with surgical instruments exposing the blood vessels. In photo B, the connective tissue is dissected and secured with sutures, set against a backdrop of deep red visceral tissue. Photo C depicts blood vessels. Photo D highlights sutures closing an incision with remaining free stomach tissue.\n\nFig. 9.10\n\n## Intraoperative Endoscopy\n\nWhile not necessary to perform the steps of a fundoplication as described earlier, intraoperative endoscopy is a useful adjunct to (1) confirm the location of the gastroesophageal junction when there is concern about adequacy of intraabdominal esophageal length, (2) to evaluate the esophagus for injury either from mediastinal mobilization or for the presence of inadvertent full thickness sutures, and (3) to evaluate the adequacy and symmetry of the final fundoplication ( Box 9.4 ).\n\nBox 9.4\n\nEndoscopic Characteristics of an Adequate Fundoplication\n\n  - 1.\n\tLack of evidence of esophageal injury or full-thickness suture material\n  - 2.\n\tEasy passage of the endoscope through both the crural closure and fundoplication\n  - 3.\n\tRetroflexed view with evidence of a gastroesophageal flap valve snug against the endoscope (Hill grade I)\n  - 4.\n\tA straight, well-oriented gastroesophageal junction, without twisting of the new lower esophageal antireflux valve\n  - 5.\n\tLocation of the gastroesophageal junction at the bottom of the fundoplication (and neither within the stomach nor above the fundoplication)\n\n## Intraoperative Considerations\n\nIntraoperative complications include esophageal and gastric perforations, splenic injury, bleeding, injury to surrounding structures (aorta, inferior vena cava, pericardium), and missed visceral injury. The rate of complications remains low after laparoscopic fundoplication, with the risk of esophageal perforation and gastric perforation remaining less than 1% in most case series. However, when these do occur, they are associated with significant morbidity and mortality when unrecognized. When recognized, these perforations should be primarily repaired and buttressed with an omental flap or the intended fundoplication. Esophageal injury requiring repair may be reason to delay progression to a solid diet, and consideration can be given to performing a contrasted swallow study postoperatively prior to initiating a diet; however, this management remains surgeon dependent.\n\nPleurotomy during mediastinal dissection can lead to capnothorax. Capnothorax is generally well tolerated due to the rapid reabsorption of CO <sub>2 </sub> by the pleura; however, when a pleural injury is detected, the hole should first be made larger to avoid one-way valve physiology with development of a tension capnothorax, and the anesthesiology team should be notified to monitor for respiratory or hemodynamic compromise. A contralateral pleurotomy may be required to equilibrate the intrathoracic pressure and avoid further tension physiology. Any residual capnothorax can be evacuated by means of mediastinal drainage and application of positive pressure ventilation after the crura has been closed. A chest tube is rarely required. Routine chest radiography is not required unless the patient has evidence of ongoing cardiopulmonary compromise, which would suggest parenchymal lung injury as opposed to a simple pleurotomy.\n\nSplenic injury can occur during division of the short gastric arteries, due to traction on the gastrosplenic omentum or due to unrecognized penetrating injury. These injuries can result in either infarction or bleeding. Infarction may rarely lead to increased pain or postoperative fever, but it rarely requires further intervention and is most commonly limited to the upper pole of the spleen. Conversely, splenic bleeding may necessitate conversion to laparotomy and urgent splenectomy (0.5%\u20131.0%).\n\nInjury to hollow viscera may be incurred in the process of instrument exchanges or due to unintended electrocautery burns due to incomplete insulation of instruments or arcing of current from instruments to tissue. These injuries can be associated with significant morbidity and mortality and care should be taken during all laparoscopic procedures to minimize this risk; tissue should be handled gently, instruments should be introduced with care, all instruments should be examined prior to use to ensure the insulation is intact, electrosurgical cords should not be bundled with laparoscopic camera or light source cords, and the surgeon should be aware of unintentional contact between tissue and instruments that may occur outside of the field of view. The abdomen should be surveyed prior to completion of the case to allow identification of potential unrecognized sources of bleeding or tissue injury that should be addressed.\n\n## Postoperative Assessment and Management\n\nPostoperative management after fundoplication is variable and dependent on surgeon preference. Generally, a nasogastric tube is unnecessary after laparoscopic fundoplication. Antiemetics should be used liberally and even scheduled when necessary to prevent postoperative retching, which is a described risk factor for early hernia recurrence and wrap disruption. Patients can be monitored on a general surgical floor postoperatively, with advancement to a clear liquid diet as soon as their mental status and respiratory status allows. Diet can usually be advanced to full liquids quickly after surgery, and patients are typically discharged on liquid or crushed oral analgesia on postoperative day 1 to 2, with instructions to progress in a slow, staged manner from full liquids to a soft mechanical diet over the course of the first 6 weeks postoperatively. Patients should be instructed to avoid dry breads, dry meats, and raw vegetables, which can become impacted in the swollen distal esophagus and may require endoscopic retrieval if they do not pass on their own. Medications should be liquid or crushed when possible to facilitate passage through the swollen hiatus and gastroesophageal junction postoperatively. We routinely follow-up patients at 1 month postoperatively. If there is concern for early recurrence of heartburn related symptoms or dysphagia beyond that expected in the early postoperative period, a barium swallow can be used to evaluate whether the fundoplication is intact and whether the wrap allows sufficient passage of contrast. Postoperative dysphagia often can be managed with a watchful waiting approach; however, severe dysphagia with inability to tolerate secretions necessitates urgent endoscopy to assess for food impaction, reherniation, or further pathology. Persistent, severe dysphagia precluding per oral intake may necessitate return to the operating room with consideration of revision.\n\n## Postoperative Outcomes\n\nShort- and long-term outcomes after fundoplication for GERD remain excellent. With some variation amongst techniques, long-term outcomes after laparoscopic fundoplication demonstrate significant improvement in quality-of-life scores related to heartburn, with the majority of patients remaining free of symptoms and not requiring use of antacid medications on long-term follow-up. Systematic reviews of existing randomized control trials suggest that at up to 5 years post-Nissen fundoplication, 78% of patients remain free of any pathologic esophageal acid exposure, with comparable results (82%) observed among patients post-Toupet fundoplication. Furthermore, patient satisfaction remains high long term, with over 90% of patients satisfied with their surgical outcome after Nissen fundoplication 15 to 20 years after surgery. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\nHowever, there are slight variations in outcomes between fundoplication techniques. Available meta-analyses would suggest no significant difference in postoperative heartburn, the risk of abnormal lower esophageal acid exposure on 24-hour pH monitoring, esophagitis, regurgitation, recurrence of heartburn symptoms, or resumption of antireflux medications when comparing the complete posterior versus partial posterior fundoplication. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> However, there was a significant difference in the prevalence of reoperation, with an increased risk of requiring reoperation following complete posterior fundoplication in one meta-analysis. When comparing the prevalence of postoperative dysphagia in this same meta-analysis, complete posterior fundoplication was found to have a greater risk of postoperative dysphagia when compared to partial posterior fundoplication in studies with a follow-up of less than 36 months, as was shown in prior meta-analyses. This difference disappeared in the two studies that had follow-up greater than 36 months, similar to the results of prior retrospective case series. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> Partial posterior fundoplication was also associated with a significantly lower risk of reported postoperative gas bloat and inability to belch, when compared to complete posterior fundoplication. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup> When comparing 15- to 20-year outcomes between laparoscopic complete posterior fundoplication and laparoscopic partial anterior fundoplication, similar patterns emerge, with high rates of satisfaction after both complete posterior (90.2%) and partial anterior (86.8%), and with further investigation demonstrating improved heartburn symptom scores after complete posterior fundoplication but increased dysphagia symptom scores when compared to partial anterior fundoplication. In this long-term follow-up of patients undergoing either partial anterior or complete posterior fundoplication, 9% of patients undergoing complete posterior fundoplication were converted to partial anterior fundoplication for dysphagia, and 11% of patients initially undergoing partial anterior fundoplication were converted to complete posterior fundoplication for recurrent reflux.\n\nFundoplication failure has been described as being due to one of several patterns: (1) slippage or misplacement of the initial fundoplication, (2) disruption of the fundoplication, (3) herniation of the fundoplication, (4) an overly competent fundoplication due to the wrap being too tight or too long, (5) twisting of the fundoplication, and (6) the \u201ctwo-compartment stomach.\u201d These failures may require reoperation depending on the patient\u2019s symptoms and functional evaluation. Although reoperative fundoplication is technically challenging and carries an increased risk of conversion to open procedure and injury to the stomach or esophagus, it can be accomplished safely and effectively by the experienced surgeon. <sup class=\"u-ckc-superscript\">, </sup>\n\n## Conclusion\n\nGERD persists as the most common disorder of the esophagus and gastroesophageal junction, with longstanding GERD increasing the risk of erosive esophagitis, esophageal stricture, Barrett\u2019s esophagus, and progression to esophageal cancer, as well as decreased quality of life. Antireflux surgery is a safe and effective method of re-establishing the competency of the antireflux barrier in patients who have persistent symptoms despite maximizing medical therapy, in patients who wish to avoid lifelong medical therapy, and in patients with evidence of complicated or severe GERD. While the complete posterior (Nissen) fundoplication remains the current gold standard operative treatment for GERD, the partial posterior (Toupet) fundoplication and partial anterior (Dor) fundoplication provide alternative methods of re-establishing the antireflux barrier for patients with poor esophageal motility or severe preoperative dysphagia and bloating. An in-depth understanding of GERD pathophysiology, a thorough preoperative diagnostic evaluation, appropriate patient selection, and familiarity with the variety of antireflux procedures available are essential requirements for the surgeon to optimize patient outcomes following antireflux surgery.\n\n## Acknowledgments\n\nThe authors would like to thank the Foundation for Surgical Innovation and Education (FSIE) for the use of their educational videos as well as their ongoing dedication to surgical education at all levels.\n\n## References\n\n1.: Nguyen N.T., Thosani N.C., Canto M.I., et al.: The American Foregut Society white paper on the endoscopic classification of esophagogastric junction integrity . Foregut J Am Foregut Soc 2022; 2 (4): pp. 339-348.\n\nView In Article\n\n2.: Vakil N., van Zanten S.V., Kahrilas P., Dent J., Jones R., Global Consensus Group : The Montreal definition and classification of gastroesophageal reflux disease: a global evidence-based consensus . Am J Gastroenterol 2006; 101 (8): pp. 1900-1943.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n3.: El-Serag H.B., Sweet S., Winchester C.C., Dent J.: Update on the epidemiology of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease: a systematic review . Gut 2014; 63 (6): pp. 871-880.\n\nView In Article|Cross Reference\n\n4.: Delshad S.D., Almario C.V., Chey W.D., Spiegel B.M.R.: Prevalence of gastroesophageal reflux disease and proton pump inhibitor-refractory symptoms . Gastroenterology 2020; 158 (5)